u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT     06-22 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS CRUSH YANKEES, 11-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Hideki Irabu should take some solace in the fact
that he went nearly three months of this season without being
routed. But when he absorbed the inevitable beating on Sunday
night, it was a rather spectacular event.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians blasted five home runs, four of more than
400 feet, and pounded the Yankees, 11-0, the most one-sided defeat
this season of the team with the game's best winning percentage
(.735). It was the Yankees' worst loss in a shutout since a 12-0
pasting by the California Angels on Aug. 27, 1988. The Indians'
Bartolo Colon allowed three hits in eight innings, striking out 10.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu lasted three innings, his shortest outing of the season,
allowing five runs that pushed his earned run average to 2.19 from
1.68. If this was, indeed, an All-Star Game audition for Irabu
(6-3), throwing in front of Cleveland and American League Manager
Mike Hargrove, Irabu did not exactly distinguish himself.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Yankees did, a truth reflected in their body
language. Chuck Knoblauch, pinned in a minor slump, shaking his
head in disgust after grounding into a doubleplay. Derek Jeter
smashing his glove against the ground after botching a would-be
double-play grounder. Paul O'Neill angrily waving his arm at an
ESPN cameraman to aim his lens at something other than the sullen
Yankees in their dugout. They figure to be in a collective foul
mood Monday, when they open a week in which they will play four
games against the Atlanta Braves and three against the Mets at Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was consistent in his first 11 starts, never permitting
more than three runs, never giving up more than one home run, and
he was armed with extra reason to beat the Indians, besides the
possibility of nailing down a spot on the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   After Cleveland knocked him around a bit last year, David
Justice, the Indians outfielder, sniffed that he did not understand
the hype, that Irabu was not anything special. One person in the
Yankees' organization predicted that if Irabu had the chance,
Justice might find a fastball planted in his ribs on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   It would not have been a bad night to get hit by Irabu: He
simply did not have a good fastball, a pitch he relies on. Irabu
cut short his pregame warm-up; when he walked in, Colon was still
throwing in the Indians' bullpen, even though Colon had to take the
mound first. Irabu's fastball, typically 93 to 95 miles an hour,
was usually clocked from 86 to 88 mph on Sunday night, and only a
few times did he break 90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians swung at and missed just one of Irabu's first 39
pitches. He was ripe for the picking, and oh, did they ever hit him
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Cleveland's Manny Ramirez engaged his teammate
Jim Thome in a contest of strength in batting practice, and they
took turns crushing moon shots all over the stands at Jacobs Field
_ fine preparation for Ramirez's at-bat in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu threw a fastball on a 3-2 count, Ramirez swung and the
sound he made while making contact probably sickened every pitcher
within earshot. Chad Curtis, playing center field for the Yankees,
raced back to the fence in right-center, launched himself above the
wall, glove extended _ and the ball carried over his head by a good
30 or 40 feet, landing some 15 or 20 rows into the stands.
Estimated distance: 421 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu tried three straight fastballs against the next batter,
Mark Whiten, who fouled off the first two and made that same awful
sound on the third. Curtis raced back directly to the center field
fence, braced himself for a monumental leap _ and didn't bother.
The ball carried over his head by 20 feet or so, landing halfway
between the pitcher's mound and the plate in the Cleveland bullpen.
Estimated distance: 419 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Two runners were on base with one out in the third inning _
including Justice, who was walked twice by Irabu _ when Ramirez
strolled to the plate and picked out a fastball. Whock. Curtis
raced back directly to the center field fence, braced himself,
leaped _ and the ball dropped just over the wall. Estimated
distance: 401 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu threw 70 pitches in the first three innings and the
Yankees were losing, 5-0, and it was a good time to give Irabu the
rest of the night off and let him get on with his life; he didn't
have it.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes relieved in the bottom of the fourth, and the
first batter for Cleveland was Travis Fryman. A fastball, a hard
swing. The beastly sound. Curtis began racing back to the wall, and
stopped, looking up. Fryman's monster drive crash-landed behind the
decorative row of trees in right-center, a 439-foot shot, and
Cleveland finished with 2,058 feet in home runs when Shawon Dunston
hit a sub-400 foot homer in the eighth inning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0004EDT &QL; 
