<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON MAKES IT OFFICIAL: HE WON'T COACH BULLS NEXT SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Jackson has officially informed the Chicago Bulls that he
will step down as head coach, the first step in what could become
the dismantling of the National Basketball Association's reigning
dynasty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During Jackson's nine-year tenure as coach of the Bulls, the
team gained unprecedented global popularity and dominated the NBA,
winning six championships in the last eight seasons. Chicago won
its sixth title with a Game 6 victory over the Utah Jazz last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had feuded in recent seasons with the team's owner,
Jerry Reinsdorf, and general manager, Jerry Krause, and his shaky
status with the Bulls had been linked to the futures of their
superstars, Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen, who can both become
free agents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson's agent, Todd Musberger, said on Sunday night that
Jackson had met privately with each of the players and that their
decisions regarding whether to stay with the team next season would
be made independently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been such a great run,'' Musberger said. ``Phil has
been such a great ambassador for the game and for Chicago. I hope
that when Chicago wakes up to the news after mourning just a little
bit, they will step back and feel great pride in his
accomplishments and all the entertainment he provided. He won with
grace and dignity and Phil goes out that way, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Messages left for Krause and Jordan on Sunday night were not
returned. Jackson could not be reached for comment. In the days
following the Bulls' conquest of the Jazz, Jackson spoke of an end
to the team's championship run, and Pippen insisted that he would
not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Phil never wants to feel responsible for keeping
somebody out of the game,'' Musberger said. ``He has had a series
of private conversations with the players, and all of the
principals, Michael, Scottie, Dennis Rodman, will make their
decisions on an individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on this past season, they all understood that there may
come a time when each might have to make an individual decision
that took them in a course that varied from other guys. Nothing
that Phil has done is being done in an effort to force anybody else
to do something, and the same is true of the players' decisions.
They are going to do what is best for them and they fully support
Phil in doing what is best for himself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Musberger said that Jackson met with Reinsdorf and Krause last
week and that Reinsdorf offered Jackson an opening to return. But
the offer came after an often acrimonious relationship had
deteriorated to the point that Jackson felt comfortable in walking
away from the best team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds for the decision were sown a year ago, when similar
speculation ended with Jackson accepting an offer to return for one
more year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you really have to do is go back a year ago and realize
that we were met with opening remarks from the Bulls that if they
did a deal with Phil for the '97-'98 season, that it would be the
last deal that they would do and would be for one year,'' Musberger
said. ``We took their word for it and never expected any other
outcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
