<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-MISHAPS-2-takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP ACCUSES THEME PARK OF `DANGEROUS' SECURITY PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By SHERRY JOE DAVIS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; VALENCIA, Calif. _ Church administrator Tim Mossholder got the
ride of his life at Magic Mountain recently. But it wasn't the ride
he paid for _ and he hopes he never has to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Mossholder, his wife and their three young children were among
more than 1,400 members of the Southern California Foursquare
Churches who were at the theme park 25 miles north of downtown Los
Angeles last month when 60 sheriff's deputies and a helicopter were
called in to quell an unruly crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The parishioners said that rowdy teens swept through the roller
coaster park May 30, fighting, trampling visitors, smoking
marijuana and cutting into lines for rides.
</P>
<P>
   In a six-page letter last week to park officials, Mossholder
said security was ``woefully and dangerously inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tense environment. It was a violent environment,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Mountain officials deny the incident was as violent as it
appeared to Mossholder and insist they have adequate security to
deal with problems.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is one of a series that have forced park officials
to re-evaluate and increase security measures in and around the
260-acre park in recent years. In April, a 15-year-old Fontana,
Calif., youth was fatally shot. Five years ago, hundreds of teens
rioted after being denied admittance to a rap concert in the park,
causing more than 40 injuries and thousands of dollars in damage to
local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the park safe for visitors _ while maintaining an open
atmosphere of fun _ is an ongoing concern for park officials, say
the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department and area leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Mountain sends its security guards to anti-gang
conferences, and park managers meet regularly with sheriff's
officials to review security policies. Later this month, for
instance, both sides will review their handling of the May 30
incident, said Lt. Carl Deeley of the Santa Clarita Valley
sheriff's station.
</P>
<P>
   There is some progress to show for their efforts. During the
past two years, crimes have dropped in the park. From June 1996 to
May 1997, there were 76 serious crimes, compared to 62 serious
crimes for the same period the following year. Serious crimes
include homicide, aggravated assault and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Deeley, who oversaw the emergency response during the May 30
incident, said the park is one of the safest around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do an excellent job,'' said Deeley, a 20-year veteran of
security operations throughout the country. ``Magic Mountain is the
best I've seen in the way they enforce the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Theme park consultant Dennis Speigel said Magic Mountain's
troubles are a result of its teen-age clientele and location in a
culturally diverse metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic Mountain does almost 3million people or more a year.
You're going to get a couple of bad apples,'' said Speigel,
president of Cincinnati-based International Theme Park Services.
``You get these types of problems in bigger, cosmopolitan
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   He said amusement parks are not immune to the problems facing
larger society.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids bring guns to schools and shoot students and
teachers in a very structured environment, I can see why it happens
in theme parks,'' Speigel said.
</P>
<P>
   Park problems tend to occur on crowded days, said Jan Heidt,
mayor of neighboring Santa Clarita, who tried to persuade Magic
Mountain to carry anti-gang messages on its in-house television
system after the April 1993 melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the circumstances are always the same, and the No. 1
factor is that the park is overcrowded,'' Heidt said. ``I don't
think their public relations can stand any more of these incidents,
particularly with summer coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Park spokesman Andy Gallardo said while the park had an unusual
number of visitors May 30, security guards were able to control the
crowd. Deeley said there may have been as many as 30,000 people at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies arrested 11 people and helped move out visitors,
shutting down the park about an hour before its usual closing time.
</P>
<P>
   Security efforts have been beefed up since the incident. The
park has doubled its security staff, employed law enforcement
officials to help screen crowds for potentially troublesome
visitors, added lights and security towers in the parking lot and
increased the number of closed-circuit televisions in and around
the park.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they have apologized and offered to refund the
church group's discounted $20 tickets. But they say the incident
never reached the level of violence described by Mossholder and
other church members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
