<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGIC-MISHAPS-2nd-add     06-22 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-MISHAPS-2nd-add-LADN </SLUG>
 
VALENCIA, Calif.: other church members. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ``He had a very unpleasant experience in our park, and we'e
extremely sorry for that,'' Gallardo said. ``But if any of these
accusations are true, someone would have gone to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Southern California Foursquare Churches
have a different view.
</P>
<P>
   Mendy DeMoss, a youth leader with Trinity Church in Burbank,
said she and fellow parishioners were swept into a mob of
teen-agers shouting gang affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were terrified and running,'' said DeMoss, who had two
teen-age girls with her. ``I put my arms around them and told them
everything was going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMoss said the park was so crowded that it reminded her of the
congestion immediately following a Los Angeles Dodgers game. She
said she saw no security guards until she and the girls reached the
park's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were unprepared for the situation,'' DeMoss said. ``I
thought someone was going to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth pastor Louie Reed, who brought 30 to 40 teen-agers from
the Monterey Park Christian Center, said he will not return to
Magic Mountain. He said security guards were hard to find, so busy
were they pursuing rowdy teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did see security trying to find some of them, but it was too
much, and they were overloaded,'' Reed said. ``We're not going
back. I can't ensure their safety. What I saw was not good and was
dangerous. It was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gallardo said the park did respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption that security officers did not do anything
about (complaints of fights) is ludicrous,'' he said. ``We turn
away people everyday, and we will not hesitate to throw people out.
That all goes down to our zero-tolerance policy for misbehavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Mossholder said park officials are spinning the day's events to
put Magic Mountain in the best light. He said church members will
avoid the park until officials can guarantee visitors' safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officially, they have not yet acknowledged that anything
happened in the park,'' Mossholder said. ``Their official statement
is woefully lacking and misinterpreting the facts of the day. It
was atypical. It was not a typical day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
