<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BURN-MUTINY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTINY'S MASTERY OF BURN CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Injuries are piling up, the minor-league roster is
being plucked almost weekly, and the offense has been, well,
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even the worst team in Major League Soccer is landing
punches on the Dallas Burn.
</P>
<P>
   Short two of its own stars because of the World Cup, Tampa Bay
(4-12) has earned half of its season victories against Dallas (8-7)
after last night's listless 1-0 victory at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The paceless contest played on an oven-hot field saw neither
team truly assert itself until Tampa Bay's Steve Ralston found
former SMU player Alan Prampin for the 50th-minute game winner.
Prampin slammed in Ralston's rolling cross along the left endline.
</P>
<P>
   In the 55th minute, forward Dante Washington (severe ankle
sprain) became the eighth Burn starter to be sidelined recently
because of injury or yellow-card accumulation. Tampa Bay's Chris
Houser ran over Washington's ankle on a collision that sent both
out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Heat-related cramps and fatigue slowed the action on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like a blow dryer out there,'' Prampin said. ``It took
a toll on both teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Washington left Damian as the Burn's only playmaker,
and the Tampa Bay defense collapsed on him each time down the
field. The Burn's best scoring try came, though, before Washington
went down.
</P>
<P>
   In the 43rd minute, Damian's corner kick found Ted Eck from 12
yards out. Lying face-up over the goal line, defender Jan
Eriksson's right foot blocked Eck's header by an inch.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Damian's five attempts missed wide or high, and the
fifth was saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had guys who could barely stand up out there,'' Burn coach
Dave Dir said. ``We only had the same 11 guys we had in Chicago \Ra
1-0 loss\S. We gave everything we had, but to be honest, it wasn't
very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay was without Frankie Hejduk and Roy Wegerle, both of
whom are at the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been taking a lot of hits, but I don't think the Grim
Reaper's here yet,'' said Dir, whose team has lost five of seven
matches. ``We're gonna find out who has character on this team, and
whoever doesn't will have to go. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Burn, it was a lineup that shouldn't have been. Reserve
forward Mickey Trotman was making his first MLS start, and defender
Richard Farrer was forced back into action prematurely with a groin
pull.
</P>
<P>
   In for Washington was Juan Sastoque, an MLS Project-40
developmental program player. Burn farmhand Chad Brown, summoned
this weekend from New Orleans of the A-League, logged 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an ugly game,'' Dir said. ``Injuries aren't why we
lost. It's not an excuse, just a fact. \RTampa\S didn't play any
better. They beat us down the field once.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks with MLS about replacing marquee Burn midfielder Alain
Sutter (hip sprain) are ongoing. Sutter's 10-game absence has taken
a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys we've got injured, we might not get back,''
Dir said. ``This is the team that has to play better, or they're
not going to win a lot of games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
