<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLPHONE-SUIT-LADN     06-22 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELL PHONE USER SUES OVER DISCONNECTION DURING CARJACKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- When Marcia Spielholz realized that her BMW was
about to be carjacked, she reached for the only weapon she had: her
cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   All she wanted was a 911 operator.
</P>
<P>
   All she got was a staccato ``beep-beep-beep'' indicating that
her call was not connecting. Over and over.
</P>
<P>
   With no one to head off the bandits at the pass, Spielholz was
cornered south of Beverly Hills, approached by two men. One of them
shot her in the face.
</P>
<P>
   She survived the 1994 incident and has filed three lawsuits
against L.A. Cellular.
</P>
<P>
   Spielholz contends that in the interest of larger profits,
cell-phone service providers allow dangerous gaps in service that
can cause unwanted disconnections, higher bills and _ in the most
extreme cases _ a busy signal when someone's life is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``She relied on the advertising that said a cellular phone would
protect her,'' Spielholz's attorney Mark Hiepler said. ``But these
phones are sold to make money, not save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   An L.A. Cellular spokesman denied Spielholz's allegations. He
said the phone company works as hard as it can to provide
uninterrupted service but is often challenged by the limitations of
radio-based communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dynamic system that's virtually impossible to
predict,'' said Steven Crosby, who is L.A. Cellular vice president
for external affairs. ``It's like watching the ocean _ you have
high tides, low tides and waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby maintains that the phone industry should not be held
liable for random attacks like the one on Spielholz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible situation, but we couldn't have prevented
those two thugs from following her,'' he said. ``A phone, a cop, a
suit of body armor _ sometimes nothing can stop terrible things
from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Speilholz, formerly an attorney with MGM, is recovering from her
14th reconstructive surgery and could not be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever was caught for the carjacking. One of Spielholz's
lawsuits is scheduled to return to Los Angeles Superior Court on
July 16. The court file, already in its third thick volume,
explains her urban nightmare in detail.
</P>
<P>
   After her car was bumped by a black Nissan on Dec. 4, 1994,
Spielholz claims she was chased for 10 to 12 minutes, dialing 911
frantically as she weaved through Beverlywood, just north of the
Santa Monica Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police Capt. John Trundle said in court declarations
that there was an airborne helicopter in the area that could have
made it to her car in less than two minutes if she had reached an
emergency dispatcher.
</P>
<P>
   But the call couldn't get through, because L.A. Cellular's
32,000 square miles of coverage in Southern California was less
like a blanket and more like Swiss cheese, Hiepler claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredibly, L.A. Cellular willfully and intentionally chose
not to disclose this life-threatening information to its own
customers, and potential new subscribers, out of a desire to
maximize profits,'' Hiepler said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Crosby and Steve Carlson, executive director of the
Cellular Carriers Association of America. Cellular phone companies
make a point in their advertising of saying that connections might
be interrupted anytime, anywhere for a variety of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the lawsuit is Spielholz's contention that the
phone companies could provide blanket coverage if they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Spielholz said cellular phone companies each set up separate
transmitters and might have saved her from injury if they worked
together to route emergency calls to the strongest transmitter
available.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson said the theory is flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a technological standpoint it absolutely doesn't work,''
Carlson said. ``With digital phones you have several companies with
completely different technologies. They just don't mix and match.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, which regulates the
cellular phone industry, has taken written arguments from both
sides and is currently looking into this ``strongest signal'' issue
for 911 calls. The agency will determine whether cellular telephone
companies should be required to pick up 911 calls regardless of
whether they come from one of their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Spielholz's personal injury lawsuit is set for trial in October,
but she doesn't plan to end her fight there.
</P>
<P>
   While she lobbies state and federal legislators for new laws to
protect cellular phone owners, Spielholz and her team of attorneys
filed a class-action lawsuit in February, claiming the gaps in
coverage are also taking a financial toll on cellular phone users.
</P>
<P>
   With cellular phone companies rounding up to the nearest minute,
even after a five-second call, they actually profit from
disconnections, Spielholz claims.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, L.A. Cellular attorneys claim the complaint
doesn't belong in state court and should be decided by Federal
Communications Commission officials instead.
</P>
<P>
   Spielholz's lawyer pledges to continue the fight no matter the
venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't in a canyon, she wasn't on a hill. She wasn't under
a building or out of their coverage area,'' Hiepler said. ``When
you're in the heart of the city you have a right to expect your
phone to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
