<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-U.S.OPEN-TEX     06-22 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANZEN'S 2ND CROWN SIMILIAR TO '93 TRIUMPH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some sequels lose their luster because they
stray too far from the original plot line. Not so in the case of
``Lee Janzen, U.S. Open Champion II''.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, who rallied from a five-stroke deficit in yesterday's
final round to hoist the Open trophy for the second time in five
years, leaned on elements at the Olympic Club that were crucial to
his 1993 triumph as well.
</P>
<P>
   He vanquished the same foil, Payne Stewart, and did so with a
timely chip-in and a fortunate encounter with a tree. Dig up the
script from Janzen's victory at Baltusrol Golf Club in Springfield,
N.J., and you'll also find a chip-in during crunch time. Not to
mention a flirtation with some thick branches that worked to
Janzen's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh plot twist yesterday proved to be a big one, however.
Instead of holding off Stewart down the stretch, as he did five
years ago, Janzen authored the third-largest comeback in Open
history.
</P>
<P>
   Down five strokes to start the round, Janzen immediately dug
himself a deeper hole with consecutive bogeys at Nos. 2 and 3. That
put Janzen seven strokes in arrears with 15 holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I didn't think I could win. But I had to suck
it up and go on. I knew if I gave up there, I'd be upset with
myself,'' said Janzen, who went on to record four birdies and 11
pars during a closing round of 68. ``So I kept plugging away and,
somehow, I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart helped open the door by backsliding with a five-bogey,
one-birdie round. A wire-to-wire leader through 54 holes, Stewart
coughed up the lead for the first time in the tournament with a
bogey from the rough at No. 13, then squared matters again with a
15-foot birdie putt at No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   With the players tied, Janzen headed to the 17th tee box, where
he had taken a bogey and two double bogeys in the first three
rounds. This time, Janzen found the fairway and salvaged par.
Moments later, Stewart pushed a 7-iron approach from the 16th
fairway into a greenside bunker and took bogey.
</P>
<P>
   When Janzen parred No. 18 to finish the tournament at even-par
(280), he held a one-stroke lead as Stewart played the final hole.
Given one last chance to force a playoff, Stewart's 20-foot birdie
putt slid left at the last moment and Janzen had become the 18th
player in history to win multiple Open titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I bring out the best in Lee Janzen,'' said Stewart,
who lost by two strokes in the 1993 Open. ``There was nobody in
contention who shot under par in the final round except for him. He
deserves to be the champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen got his first inkling that the tournament could be
heading in his direction when his tee shot at No. 5 stuck in a
tree. Told by spectators of his fate, Janzen made a U-turn toward
the tee box and hit his third shot. Before he could get there, a
gust of wind nudged his ball out of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Given a chance to play his original tee shot, Janzen hacked out
of the deep rough and airmailed the par-4 green with his third
shot. But he discovered his ball sitting up in the rough and
chipped in for par from 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart called it ``an all-world par ... maybe the greatest par
in the history of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen thought of something else. In the final round at
Baltusrol in 1993, he had survived an errant shot that somehow
skittered through the branches of a tall tree and salvaged par on
the 10th hole. He had also chipped in for birdie at No. 16 to break
a deadlock with Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking, `Payne Stewart, a chip-in and a ball in
the tree. Where have I seen this before?' '' said Janzen, who went
on to repeat the Baltusrol outcome by draining three birdie putts
from six feet (No. 7), eight feet (No. 11) and five feet (No. 13).
Combined with a 20-footer at No. 4, they proved to be enough to
bring Janzen back from 4-over to even-par within a 10-hole stretch.
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be more than Stewart could handle. The only
player with an under-par total through 54 holes, Stewart remained
in red numbers until his drive at No. 12 rolled into a sand-filled
divot in the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy deliberation, Stewart hit a 9-iron into a
green-front bunker and was told by U.S. Golf Association rules
official Tom Meeks that he had taken too long to play his shot and
would be assessed a one-stroke penalty if a similar delay occurred
during his round. The news, said Stewart, ``did not sit well'' and
he responded on the next hole by knocking a 5-iron over the green
at the par-3 13th hole, setting up the bogey that gave Janzen his
first lead of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen took care of matters thereafter. He hit his final 10
fairways and his last eight greens in regulation to seal the
victory. And he cried during his acceptance speech, just like at
Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream of mine to win the U.S. Open the first time,''
Janzen said. ``Since then, not a day has gone by that I didn't
dream about winning it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the sequel is complete, with a familiar final scene: Janzen
over Stewart. Just like in Baltusrol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
