<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CAN'T SEEM TO MAKE DECISIVE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What the heck. The Mariners were never a spring kinda
team anyway.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting they are capable of fall ball, either. They
are, however, 1-0 this summer.
</P>
<P>
   As the old baseball sage, Chairman Mao, once observed, the
journey back from a thousand losses begins with a single step.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's step was the winning of a series. The 10-5 victory gave
them a 2-1 weekend conquest of the Oakland A's. In recent years,
taking a series from the A's at the Kingdome would have been a rank
disappointment, like allowing Peter McNeeley to lay a glove on the
champ.
</P>
<P>
   These days, of course, the Mariners are hanging from the ropes,
squinting through swollen eyes hoping to spot the difference
between the ref and the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners connected Sunday. They also have lost a lot of
blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have redefined rock bottom,'' said Alex Rodriguez, ``by
underachieving so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner shortstop had just completed a 4-for-5 afternoon and
stole his 18th base, so you can tell momentary success died not
obscure the enormity of the task.
</P>
<P>
   Two small things take fresh measure of the plight of the Rock
Bottoms:
</P>
<P>
   With seven wins, including Sunday's resolute effort following
injury, Billy Swift is the starting staff's leading winner.
</P>
<P>
   And to replace a third baseman who leaks more than either George
Karl or Ken Starr, the Mariners' only viable option was to call up
a 34-year-old journeyman minor leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   No disrespect to Rico Rossy, who filled in well Sunday in his
first start at third replacing Russ Davis, but the guy has 236
major league at-bats in a 13-year pro baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rossy call-up is, apparently, the only kind of move the
Mariners are able or willing to make. Bad as the season has been _
Sunday was the 12th win in the last 38 games _ it is the inability
to do anything substantive to stop the free fall that is most
annoying to Mariner fans.
</P>
<P>
   Beset by age, injuries, heavy contracts, a ravaged upper farm
system, an ownership-imposed salary cap, the Randy Johnson mess and
below-average years for numerous players, the Mariners have nowhere
to go for help. A handful of untouchables on a roster with a
preponderance of unloadables is the worst possible fix to be in for
a team with big expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Even a Johnson trade near next month's trading deadline will by
then bring only prospects instead of the immediate help that would
have come in a trade last month or last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it is like to break the emergency glass and find no
fire alarm behind it, Lou Piniella smiled wanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to talk about that,'' said the Mariner
manager, more resignation than rancor in his voice. After many
years as an employee of George Steinbrenner as well as Marge
Schott, Piniella is far too adroit in the matter of house politics
to spill for publication his view of the Mariner paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite this turgid state of affairs, more than 115,000 fans
forsook the weekend's atmospheric glories to come inside and watch
the Mariners twist in the wind against one of baseball's most
unglamorous teams. Say what you will, Seattle fans no longer know a
bad team when they see one. The Mariners are off more than 150,000
from last year's record attendance pace, the American League's
second-biggest drop behind the Chicago White Sox, but have played
badly enough to have lost half a million, particularly given the
absence of substantive change.
</P>
<P>
   They have become the baseball equivalent of Baylor football _
about two touchdowns behind Texas _ but most of the fans have hung
in. They don't even boo much when the bullpen stirs.
</P>
<P>
   Has somebody decaffeinated the local coffee? Or have the
season's results been so dispiriting that the the Kingdome has
become a giant Prozac pill?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as Rodriguez suggests, the fans are aware of something
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the law of averages,'' he said. ``We have too many good
players for this. If everybody in the clubhouse stays on an even
keel, things can turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, our problems aren't from a lack of intensity. In
fact, it may be too much intensity. Everybody's trying so hard, it
creates its own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   One guy with few problems is the oft-injured Swift, a
36-year-old spring-training pickup who in his last six starts has a
5-1 record with an ERA under 2.00. Blasted out of his last start by
a comebacker that nearly went through his upper chest, Swift
betrayed no ill effects, but remained a little bewildered by his
status as ace by default.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for me,'' he said, ``but not so good for the rest of
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would have said if he were told in spring training
that by Father's Day Swift would have been his big winner, Piniella
said, ``I would have begged to disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Piniella has done his begging elsewhere, to no good
end. Absent outside help, beating the Irans of baseball is one way
to get reintroduced to the law of averages.
</P>
<P>
   A major-league team cannot ride long the twin Clydesdales of
Billy Swift and Rico Rossy.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
