r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-OPEN-SPI &LR;      06-22 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-OPEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANZEN CAPTURES U.S. OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the final scores were posted Sunday at The
Olympic Club, all the red leaderboard numbers had been tossed
aside. The 98th U.S. Open turned into Men in Black, the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Victory went to a par-shooter, a boyish-looking guy actually
dressed conservatively in blue and gray, a player who has done this
before.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen withstood the test of something alien to most golfers
_ four-inch rough mixed with ultimate pressure. When a week of
nonstop pars and bogeys was over, he had beaten three-round leader
Payne Stewart by a stroke to claim his second U.S. Open title in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen didn't so much tame the Open, this time played across the
street from the Pacific Ocean, as ride it out like a wild wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Olympic Club really won,'' Stewart said. ``Only
one person was even-par for the tournament. I think this club stood
up to the challenge of the Open championship.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Janzen. It wasn't a Billy Casper comeback, but the
Minnesota native earned his eighth PGA Tour victory, and first in
three years, by rallying from seven strokes off the pace over the
final 15 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a 2-under 68, Janzen was one of just six players to
break par Sunday, and the only one in contention. Still, this Tony
Robbins TV pitchman and disciple had his comfort zone shaken
slightly when he bogeyed two of his first three holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I could win, but after I got a birdie on four I
felt much better,'' he said, getting emotional in the trophy
presentation. ``Somehow I did it. There hasn't been a day gone by
that I haven't thought about winning it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pocketing a check for $535,000 and finishing with a 280 total,
the 33-year-old Janzen became the 15th different victor in the past
15 majors, as well as the 18th player to win the U.S. Open more
than once. His career earnings now total $6,241,113.
</P>
<P>
   On a stuffy, overcast day in the Bay Area, Janzen used a little
magic, but mostly undying resilience. He stuck a ball in a tree on
the fifth hole, was ready to concede to a two-stroke penalty and
watched as a gust of wind shook it free. He chipped in from the
greenside rough. Instead of a double bogey and maybe certain
defeat, he parred. Mother Nature should get a cut of his winnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how good that felt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen caught and passed a struggling Stewart on the backside
with birdies at 11 and 13, settled into a momentary tie with the
man in the knickers and prevailed by parring his final five holes.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a scoreboard watcher, Janzen purposely shielded his
eyes from all the posted black numbers over the final six holes,
determined to keep his focus. Walking off the 18th, he finally
found out where he stood. The crowd erupted with a roar as the
greenside scoreboard flipped over, indicating that Stewart had
dropped a shot on 16.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Stewart had a 20-foot birdie putt on the 18th to
tie and force a Monday playoff, but it narrowly missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice choke,'' a fan yelled after the shot curled to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, however, didn't flinch or even glance in his
detractor's direction. He remained outwardly philosophical rather
than downcast sitting in a crowded room full of reporters,
readdressing his failure and 1-over 281 effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to change my life,'' he said. ``I'm
disappointed I didn't win, but I didn't play well enough to win.
Life goes on. I hit six fairways, Lee Janzen hit 12. I hit nine
greens, Lee Janzen hit 14. Bingo. That's why I didn't win the golf
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, winner of the 1991 U.S. Open and 1989 PGA Championship
but a very average player since, had been terrific over the first
three rounds at the Olympic. But all he could do was hang on until
the 12th. Then a sand-filled divot put a big hole in his game.
</P>
<P>
   He launched a tee shot down the middle, only to have it stop in
a repaired divot. Most players have asked that their fairway divots
remain untouched, with the sand and fertilizer mixture used as fill
actually serving as mini bunkers. Or that they receive a free drop
from the broken ground.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart sent his second shot into a true bunker right of the
green and he bogeyed. His outright lead was gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Janzen also outdueled Stewart in the final round to win
the U.S. Open at Baltusrol Golf Club in Springfield, N.J. There
were other similarities in his victories. Both offered clutch
chip-ins and miracle plays involving trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where have I heard this before?'' Janzen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I bring the best out of Lee Janzen,'' said Stewart,
who as runner-up accepted a check for $315,000.
</P>
<P>
   No one else was within three strokes of the top two finishers.
Bob Tway shot a final-round 73 and finished in third at 4-over 284,
good for $201,730.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, considered the best player never to win a major,
played in the final group with Stewart but couldn't get going in
the final round, slicing his first shot into the trees. Lehman shot
a final-round 75 and a 6-over 206 total.
</P>
<P>
   He now has finished tied for sixth, third, tied for second and
third in the past four U.S. Opens, shooting over par in each of his
Sunday rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum never got going in our group,'' Lehman said. ``It
was uncomfortable. I'm really disappointed because I know I was
right there knocking at the door again.''
</P>
<P>
   On Father's Day, Janzen ended a four-year victory drought. He
had started to question when his next win might come. He had had
the luxury of winning eight tournaments over a four-year span, then
nothing. He had grown impatient, especially after blowing the
Players Championship this year and the Greater Vancouver Open in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   As he gripped the silver trophy tightly, with his wife and young
son nearby, all the doubts about his game had disappeared as
quickly as the red numbers on the Olympic scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the trophy that I wanted to win more than any other
trophy, for the second time is just ... it's too much,'' he said.
``To win the U.S. Open twice, you can't do anything better than
that, as far as I'm concerned. That's the best I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
