<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-22 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS RALLY TO BURY OAKLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Stop the presses. Phone Beijing, or at least the Elias
Sports Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in front of a Fathers Day crowd of 37,665, the Mariners
ended a streak that was beginning to threaten the longevity of the
Kennewick Man. They recorded a come-from-behind victory, 10-5 over
the Oakland A's, something they hadn't done since May 12 in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that this year?'' joked reserve infielder Jeff Huson.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it wasn't a rally from a five-run deficit. It came after
Seattle trailed 3-2 in the fifth inning. But it was the Mariners'
first comeback win in 38 games, or since the one day this year they
have been over .500.
</P>
<P>
   In this go-figure season, it made sense that a fellow named Rico
Rossy was the ignition that led to eight unanswered Mariner runs,
bringing them their first series victory after six consecutive
failures in June.
</P>
<P>
   That's Rico Rossy, who is not a California varietal, but a
34-year-old utility infielder who hadn't played in a big-league
ballpark since 1993. Called up from Tacoma and inserted into the
troublesome third base spot, Rossy homered to left to tie the game
at 3-3 in the fifth, and soon the M's were cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Rossy probably shouldn't get too comfortable _ Huson says the
sprained finger that kept him from starting is almost healthy _ but
then, Rossy is used to that.
</P>
<P>
   Signed originally by Baltimore in 1985, he spent time in seven
minor-league cities before finally making it to Atlanta in 1991. He
got a single at-bat with the Braves and struck out.
</P>
<P>
   He was traded to Kansas City before the '92 season and had 235
at-bats in two seasons, hitting a combined .216. Power is not his
calling card; he had three major league homers before his shot
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of time and opportunity,'' Rossy said.
``Don't throw it away, don't waste it. I'm not going to get another
one, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his 56 games in Tacoma, 51 were starts at shortstop, but
Rossy has spent some time at third. He hit .409 in spring training
for the M's this year but fell victim to Huson's versatility and
experience and was sent out.
</P>
<P>
   But with Russ Davis fighting fielding problems and Huson's
finger injured last week in Anaheim, the Mariners called up Rossy
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always think of ways they could use me up there in a
certain fashion, but it doesn't happen,'' Rossy said. ``If I was
going to go through a whole year down there again, then turn 35
(next February), it would be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It must have been tough, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play winter ball every year,'' said the native Puerto Rican.
``That has a lot to do with staying in the game. If I'd been one of
the guys who goes to another job in the offseason, I might have
said, `Don't go back.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most veteran guys on a veteran team, Rossy still was
struck by the moment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured after 12 or 13 years of playing this game, I wasn't
going to get butterflies,'' he said. ``But everybody gets them.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Edgar Martinez hit the Mariners' 119th homer of
the season and Alex Rodriguez had four hits, it was left to one of
the other club old-timers, Billy Swift, to swatch together the
pitching victory.
</P>
<P>
   After a start in Anaheim truncated by a line drive off his
chest, Swift didn't have quite the devilish sinker he usually
throws _ only five of the 19 outs he recorded came on groundouts _
but he was resourceful enough to last for 111 pitches and earn his
club-leading seventh victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a lot of breaking balls, changeups, cut fastballs,''
Swift said. ``My control (four walks and a hit batter) was the only
thing that bothered me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just gets it done,'' catcher Dan Wilson said..
</P>
<P>
   The most pivotal pitch Swift threw all day, however, was a
sinker. Ahead 2-1 in the third, Swift was in major trouble after
Rodriguez failed to glove a liner for an error, allowing the A's to
load the bases with one out and ex-Mariner Mike Blowers at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   At a point when Blowers could have broken the game open, he
tapped a sinker back to the mound, and Swift started a 1-2-3 double
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big turnaround,'' Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, M's fans can't yet project anything like
that. Monday night, Seattle returns to interleague play with four
straight against the sizzling San Diego Padres, first two of which
are at the Kingdome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
