<HEADLINE>
PERISHO'S OUTINGS LIKELY TO FORCE RANGERS HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Rangers expect second baseman Mark
McLemore to be reinstated from the 15-day disabled list today.
</P>
<P>
   That will require a roster move.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Matt Perisho likely simplified the Rangers'
impending decision.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho, whom the organization recalled Tuesday from Triple-A
Oklahoma, failed to complete the third inning for the second time
in as many starts during last night's 10-7 loss to the Angels at
Edison International Field of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Rangers 2 1/2 games back of the American
League West-leading Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates declined to discuss the impending
move until meeting this morning with general manager Doug Melvin,
but Perisho's days appear numbered. Perisho, who surrendered 10
runs (nine earned) on 10 hits and five walks in 2 2/3 innings,
likely will be optioned to Triple-A Oklahoma today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the situation with my brutality on the mound the past
week,'' Perisho said, ``I would think the move is rather obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates plans to start right-hander Todd Van Poppel on Thursday
against the Arizona Diamondbacks in Phoenix and expects injured
left-hander Darren Oliver to rejoin the rotation and start Friday
against the Giants in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves only the bullpen as an alternative for Perisho, and
the organization views the 23-year-old pitcher better served by
pitching in the RedHawks' rotation than being utilized in long
relief by the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho helped put the Rangers at a 10-run disadvantage during
his 87-pitch appearance, and the Angels sent 21 men to the plate
during the second and third innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really baffled by what happened,'' said Perisho, whose
earned-run average rose from 23.14 to 27.00. ``The preparation was
there. The attitude was there. The commitment to the pitches was
there. I just didn't get the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Al Levine did.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, who threw 50 pitches Saturday during three innings of
relief, gave the Rangers 3 1/3 scoreless innings yesterday and an
opportunity to chip away at the Angels' lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the ballgame planning not to use Levine,'' Oates
said. ``I asked Boz \Rpitching coach Dick Bosman\S to call and see
if Levine could give us anything. He got up and said he could give
us a couple of innings. Little did I know he would give us 3 1/3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not fair to him. I don't want to do that to him. I
appreciate a pitcher's arm. It's the only way he has to make a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine's performance this season and the continual struggle by
the rotation, though, might merit a start for the right-hander
sometime in the future, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that during the ballgame, and I had plenty of
time to think,'' Oates said. ``I like Al where he is. We've talked
about how important that long man is and how he can help you in
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it might not be as farfetched as you thought with
what I'm seeing. Today? No. Tomorrow? Probably not. Two weeks from
now? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine threw 69 pitches during a 4 2/3-inning appearance Tuesday
during the Rangers' 9-7 defeat to Oakland at The Ballpark in
Arlington, and at least one Rangers teammate suggested the
possibility of starting to Levine within the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been thrown at me before,'' Levine said. ``If it happens,
fine. If it doesn't, I'm happy where I'm at. I'll take the ball
whenever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
