<HEADLINE>
US SOCCER QUEST COME TO ABRUPT END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LYON, France _ They never saw themselves going out this way.
Not with a whistle blowing and scarlet-clad Iranians leaping off
the bench and hugging and kissing and weeping and thanking the
heavens. Not with one match left to play. Not two-and-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years,'' midfielder Cobi Jones said Sunday night after a
2-1 loss to Iran knocked the US soccer team out of the World Cup
before most of the world even knew it was here. ``And it's over in
a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans knew they had no chance of winning this
quadrennial kickball tournament. The London oddsmakers had them at
150-1, down with the rest of the ``minnows.'' Their own federation
president said before they even crossed the Atlantic that it was
unrealistic to expect the US to make it to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   But two-and-out? Never. ``We figured we could get a point
against Germany,'' midfielder Tab Ramos was saying, as his
blazer-clad mates filed past him, tight-lipped and red-eyed, to the
bus. ``We figured we could get three points against Iran. Then we'd
play Yugoslavia and see what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when less was expected, the Yanks had
overachieved. They had made it to the second round and lost by one
goal to eventual champion Brazil. The draw was tougher this time
and they were playing overseas and yet ...
</P>
<P>
   They never thought they would lose Sunday night. Iran had not
been to a World Cup in 20 years. The sport had gone moribund there
for nearly a decade after the Islamic revolution and during the war
with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians had needed a miracle even to qualify. They had been
through three coaches since November. They had lost by six goals
last month to Rome's club team, which was only supposed to be a
sparring partner. They did not expect to win a match here. All the
Iranians hoped for was to lose with honor. ``If we die,'' coach
Jalal Talebi said, after they'd lost their opener to Yugoslavia,
``we die standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Americans ever thought it would be easy. They knew
how much beating Uncle Sam meant back in Tehran. They knew the
Iranians would play themselves into the ground. But the Americans
thought that if they loaded their lineup with attackers and kept
coming, coming, coming, they would win.
</P>
<P>
   So they came with guns blazing. They controlled the ball for 34
minutes, 20 of them in the attacking zone. They took 27 shots.
Brian McBride hit the crossbar. Claudio Reyna hit the right post.
David Regis hit the left post. Frankie Hejduk nearly blew a hole
through the keeper's gut from sawed-off shotgun range. Nothing. Not
until 87 of the 90 minutes had ticked down and Iran was already up
by two goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how we didn't win that game,'' Ramos said, shaking
his head. ``I don't remember a game with so many chances and
scoring just one goal. The ball just didn't want to go in the back
of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for lack of audacity, or lack of sweat. ``We did what
we set out to do,'' coach Steve Sampson said. ``Attack and get
behind them. We played to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It came down, the Iranians agreed, to the bounce of the ball.
``You deserved to be a winner, too,'' coach Jalal Talebi graciously
told Sampson. ``But at the end of the day there can be only one
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans never dreamed it would not be them. Even though
they had struggled to qualify for the tournament, they had
developed a reputation for winning the important match _ or at
least not losing it. They had played down a man for much of a
qualifying match against Mexico in Mexico City's foul thin air and
managed a scoreless draw. They had beaten the Canadians by three
goals in Vancouver to get here. They figured they could win Sunday
night, even if the ball wasn't bouncing for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams know how to win at this level,'' defender Marcelo
Balboa was saying. ``And we're a good team, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   They are still not good enough to get a result, even after three
consecutive trips to the World Cup. Getting a result is a soccer
term for extracting exactly what you need out of a match. Three
points, one point, or zero points with only one goal allowed. The
countries that win World Cups _ the Brazils, the Germanys, the
Italys, the Argentinas _ know how to get a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game where if Germany was down, 1-0, they
win, 2-1,'' mused playmaker Reyna. Indeed, the Germans were down,
2-0, to Yugoslavia Sunday afternoon with 16 minutes to play in the
broiling heat with an aging team at Lens. They managed a 2-2 draw.
They got a result.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, down, 1-0, lost, 2-1. So they'll fly to Nantes
Monday and sit around a seaside hotel for three days and wait to
play a match that will mean something in Belgrade but nothing in
Boston. They've canceled next weekend's just-in-case hotel
reservations in Montpellier and Toulouse. Come Friday, they'll put
on their blue blazers and neckties and fly home to a country that
will be watching baseball and Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be 16 countries leaving here next week and we'll be
one of them,'' striker Roy Wegerle was saying, as Iranian drums
banged and cymbals clanged outside the Stade Gerland. ``No
disaster. It's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
