<HEADLINE>
JANZEN SHUTS OPEN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They saluted Jack Fleck, Billy Casper, and Scott
Simpson as somewhat unlikely winners of the US Open at The Olympic
Club, now they have a picture of Lee Janzen to hang on the
clubhouse wall. He didn't beat Ben Hogan, Arnold Palmer, or Tom
Watson as did his predecessors, but he seized the opportunity
Sunday to shoot a round for the history books and dash Payne
Stewart's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   It started off looking like a runaway, a romp by Stewart to his
second US Open championship. After three holes Sunday, Stewart's
lead was five shots and it seemed it would be a day void of
excitement. Then reality started to sink in and Janzen became a
tiger.
</P>
<P>
   After Stewart registered his first bogey at the fourth hole and
slid a putt past the cup on No. 7 for a second bogey and a
front-nine 37, the door was open. Janzen overcame two early bogeys
that left him seven shots astern and played the final 15 holes 4
under par to win his second US Open on a level par tour of
73-66-73-68_280. Isn't even what Watson predicted would win it
before the flag went up?
</P>
<P>
   Whether The Olympic Club setup was too severe, it certainly
demanded precision and a few bounces. Janzen got them when he
seemed to require them to remain in the hunt. Stewart played the
final 15 holes 4 over for a 74_281 finish. Bob Tway (73_284) ended
up third and Nick Price (73_285) was fourth. Paul Azinger went out
early and made eight birdies to shoot 65_289, while British Open
champion Justin Leonard carded just five birdies in four rounds,
finishing 14 over.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament came down to the 18th hole and Janzen was already
safely in the clubhouse. ``It was a dream to win another US Open,''
said Janzen, who added this triumph to his one at Baltusrol in
1993. ``There hasn't been a day that's gone by when I haven't
thought about winning it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart looked at the statistics and saw he had hit six
fairways, Janzen 12. Stewart hit nine greens, Janzen 14. ``That's
why I didn't win,'' said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen began his move when he sank a treacherous right-to-left
putt from 20 feet with a 2-foot break on the fourth. He birdied the
seventh (sand wedge, 6 feet), then the 11th when his ball bounded
left off a hill and he holed an 8-foot putt. When he made another
right-to-left putt for birdie on the par-3 13th (5-iron, 5 feet) ,
he was there. Stewart's problems became compounded on the par-4
12th when his tee shot landed in a sand divot in the middle of the
fairway and he took two putts from 10 feet for a bogey. Stewart has
campaigned with the PGA Tour and United States Golf Association on
this issue, stating divots should be considered ground under
repair. That's where Janzen, three groups in front, overhauled him.
After making a birdie on the 14th (9-iron, 15 feet), Stewart
bogeyed out of a bunker on the par-5 16th. Stewart's second shot on
the 18th left him above the hole with a scary downhill putt. He had
to sink it to force a playoff and he saw it go past the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He led the tournament the whole way, and he slept on the lead
every night,'' said Janzen. ``I know how hard that is. He's got
some courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was a realist. ``I didn't go out and do what I had to do
to win the golf tournament,'' he said. Janzen's round was saved
when he hit his tee shot into the trees to the right of the No. 5
fairway. He couldn't find it but as he was walking back to the tee
to hit a provisional, the wind picked up the ball fell out of a
tree. ``I was thinking double bogey,'' Janzen said, ``and I chipped
in for par.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bogeys in Janzen's round were on the second hole, when
he flew an 8-iron second shot over the green and required two putts
from 25 feet, and the par-3 third, when his 5-iron bounded over a
bunker and he wound up sinking a 3-footer for a four. Then he
played the next 15 holes superbly and sat around watching the
television monitors. Stewart's putt on the 18th had to go in but
nobody in the final 15 groups had made a birdie on the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about winning when I teed off,'' said
Janzen, ``and when I bogeyed two and three I just thought about
hitting good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's slide after leading for three days left him limp, but
in praise of The Olympic Club, where Hogan, Palmer, and Watson also
saw their dreams go by the boards. ``The golf course won,'' said
Stewart. ``Only one player in the whole field shot even par. I
thought the golf course lived up to its reputation. I kept trying.
I didn't quit, but I didn't play well enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
