<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-IRAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US GETS KICKED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Iran remained composed in the highly charged
atmosphere of Stade Gerland, withstanding the pressure of a
must-win situation against an aggressive US team, to eliminate the
Americans, 2-1, Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians were superior technically, allowing them to use a
counterattacking strategy that paid off after early forays by the
United States failed.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid Estili scored first with a 40th-minute header and Mehdi
Mahdavikia converted a breakaway in the 84th minute as Iran gained
its biggest victory ever, and not only because this was the
country's first World Cup finals win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're elated,'' said Mahdavikia, a 20-year-old striker for
Pirouzi, Iran's most popular club. ``In the locker room we were all
crying. When I scored, I thought about my people. I think in Tehran
at the moment the people are in the streets, as they were during
our final qualification match.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which suffered its earliest World Cup finals
elimination since 1934, changed formations and tactics after an
opening 2-0 defeat against Germany. Coach Steve Sampson went to a
3-5-2 alignment, adding more experience and offensive orientation,
and the move nearly worked.
</P>
<P>
   But though the US hit the crossbar once and the post twice, Iran
had three other clear chances, including a controversial one by
Asian player of the year Khodadad Azizi in the 21st minute. Azizi,
one of three Germany-based Iranian professionals, broke past Thomas
Dooley and appeared to be fouled by goalkeeper Kasey Keller on the
edge of the penalty area. Keller could have been ejected and Azizi
awarded a penalty kick, but Swiss referee Urs Meier allowed play to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   This was a well-played game, wide open, with both teams eager to
go at the goal. After a pregame exchange of gifts and a group
photo, there was little excessively rough play or professional
fouling, except by the US' David Regis.
</P>
<P>
   There were spirited political protests against the Iranian
government in the stands, despite a FIFA directive against such
manifestations. But Iran, the last team to qualify for France '98,
exhibited the poise necessary to counter a hard-charging team such
as the US.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dominated the game most of the time,'' Iran coach Jalal
Talebi said of the US. ``Technically and tactically, they had it
over us. I congratulate Mr. Sampson; he deserves to be a winner. We
had fewer chances but we scored the goals and you did not, and that
is the only reason we won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very sensitive game and we knew they would be
playing hard and coming for the win. There was a lot of pressure on
our players and we were so excited. There were many things in the
media which made this match big and it was a little difficult to
get our nerve and play as well as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran, which will meet Germany in its final first-round game in
Montpellier Thursday, moved smoothly from defense into attack on
its first goal. Javad Zarincheh advanced from a deep position while
Ali Daei held possession. Zarincheh played a combination with Karim
Bagheri, then sent a soft cross to Estili, who was unmarked 15
yards from goal. Estili, who had played for Talebi in Singapore and
with Bahman in Iran, leaped to head into the far left corner of the
net in the 40th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The goal concluded the simplest of maneuvers. Zarincheh played a
short pass to Bagheri, then curled away from the goal, and defender
Dooley, toward the corner flag. Bagheri returned the pass
perfectly, and Zarincheh it chipped back toward the penalty arc. US
players, including Claudio Reyna, were drawn toward the end line by
Zarincheh's maneuver and caught flatfooted as Estili advanced.
Keller dove to his right but had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   The US had threatened, aggressive attacking from the start with
two forwards _ Brian McBride and Roy Wegerle _ plus Frankie Hejduk
and Cobi Jones on the wings, and the Tab Ramos-Reyna combination in
midfield. Joe-Max Moore added an attacking mentality in defensive
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   McBride nearly made the move pay off early as he headed a Ramos
free kick off the bar in the third minute.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna benefited from the changes, especially from Ramos's
playmaking, but failed to provide much substance, at least until he
slotted a shot off the right post in the 37th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we set out to do from the beginning, which was to
attack and get behind them,'' said Sampson, who could be coaching
the US for the last time when it meets Yugoslavia in Nantes
Thursday. ``We played to win and we took risks in order to get the
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The US played more patiently at the start of the second half,
using slow buildups to set up McBride as a target man and moving
Dooley into midfield. Preki entered in the 12th minute, with Ernie
Stewart, and quickly disconcerted the Iran defense. Reyna had a
close-in shot headed away by Khakpour and was wide with a scissors
kick. Dooley moved in for two headers near the goal area.
</P>
<P>
   Regis volleyed a Preki pass off the left post in the 28th
minute. And Iran soon began making changes. Azizi, carried off on a
stretcher after a hard tackle by Regis midway through the half, was
replaced by Ali Reza Mansourian.
</P>
<P>
   Iran struggled without its midfield leader and withdrew further
into a defensive shell, hoping to counter with Daei. The strategy
paid off as Abedzadeh blocked a Hejduk point-blank shot in the 34th
minute of the second half. Two minutes later, Daei held off Eddie
Pope, then laid off to Mahdavikia, who dribbled from the halfway
line, until Keller committed. Mahdavikia slotted the shot past
Keller's left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Daei nearly gave Iran a three-goal edge when he powered through
the gambling US defense and shot off Keller's hand, then had his
follow cleared off the line.
</P>
<P>
   The US went into all-out attack, and Preki sent a corner across
the goal mouth for McBride to head. Substitute Naim Saadavi stopped
the shot on the goal but could not clear it and Meier signaled the
score, then added three minutes of injury time. But the US could
not capitalize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
