r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7TH INNING IS `BACKBREAKER' FOR OAKLAND 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Don't expect the A's to be very wowed by the Giants as
the two Bay Area teams square off over the next four days, first in
Oakland and then across the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have nearly the talent we have,'' former Giant
Kevin Mitchell said Sunday. ``They've got guys on that team I
haven't even heard of. But they've got a better record than we do.
I give Dusty (Baker) a lot of credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's (33-40) dropped two of three this weekend in Seattle,
losing 10-5 to the Mariners Sunday, but finished up their road trip
3-3 and have won six of their past 10. The Giants (44-32) have lost
eight of 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area says now we have a little rivalry going, so I'm
quite sure we'll be up for beating them, like they'll be trying to
get back on track,'' the A's Rickey Henderson said. ``But it's not
like it will be something extra, like the World Series. It won't do
a thing for bragging rights. If we beat them, that's probably more
satisfying for us, because they're in the race and we're trying to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The players downplay the rivalry, but there's no denying the
games at the Coliseum the next two nights will have more
electricity than most games in Oakland this year. Large crowds give
games a different feel, especially when it comes to crowd-pleasing
antics such as those Henderson unleashed Sunday in the first.
</P>
<P>
   He led off the game with a walk and then stole second. Catcher
Dan Wilson's throw skipped into center field, so Henderson scooted
down to third, reaching the bag just as Ken Griffey Jr.'s throw
arrived. The ball hit Henderson's shoulder and bounced away, giving
Henderson time to race toward home plate, despite being winded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a classic Rickey Run,'' Henderson said. ``I didn't
want them to throw the ball around like that. It's the way to go,
running like that to try to make something happen. But when the
ball hit me in the shoulder, I was tired already. Ron Washington
said `Go!' I said, `Go?' One more base, I wouldn't have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   It mostly went downhill for the A's after that. Starter Mike
Oquist (4-4) gave up two runs in the second, but the A's came back
with single runs in the fourth and fifth to take a 3-2 lead. Then
Oquist got wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   He started the fifth by leaving a pitch up to No. 9 hitter Rico
Rossy, and that led to a solo shot to tie the game. Later in the
inning, after a couple of singles and a Griffey sacrifice fly,
Oquist left another pitch up, this time to Edgar Martinez, and
after a two-run homer it was 6-3 Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two outings, I just haven't thrown the ball well,''
Oquist said. ``I was throwing well until the fifth. It was just two
pitches: They were right down the middle, belt high. They're going
to get hit. I don't know if it's my concentration level or not.
I'll get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's had thoughts of getting the game back, given the
wretched state of the Seattle bullpen, but two Jason Giambi
throwing errors in the seventh helped unleash another four-run
rally. T.J. Mathews' leadoff walk didn't help much either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate we had the one bad inning defensively,''
Giambi said. ``It kind of put a damper on a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   So even when the A's scored twice in the eighth, getting a
run-scoring double from Miguel Tejada and an RBI single from Ryan
Christenson, it was hopeless. That A's lost out on a chance to
finish the trip with a winning record, building on their strong
start in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seventh was the back-breaker,'' manager Art Howe said.
``That's the one that took us out of the game. But we played .500
on the road trip. That's what you shoot for. It's a step in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
