<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SURVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION TO CONDUCT TOBACCO SURVEY ON YOUTH SMOKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a mammoth anti-smoking bill rebuffed in the
Senate, the Clinton administration is seeking to raise public
indignation against tobacco companies by publicizing which ones are
the most successful in marketing their brands to underage smokers,
an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the White House would announce on Monday that
the Department of Health and Human Services will conduct an annual
survey of smokers to determine the most popular cigarette brands
among youths ages 12 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   The survey will be conducted as part of the annual National
Household Survey on Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan, which was first reported in Monday's Washington
Post, was the administration's first new initiative on smoking
since the Senate failed to muster enough votes last week to halt
debate on the comprehensive anti-smoking bill the administration
favored.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of the bill left the administration scrambling to
find ways to revive Clinton's campaign to reduce smoking,
especially among children under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's failure in the Senate was in large measure attributed
to a multimillion-dollar advertising blitz conducted by the tobacco
companies that generated public pressure on the Senate not to
support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's new plan had been one of the provisions of
the failed anti-smoking bill. The bill, however, would have imposed
significant financial penalties on cigarette companies that failed
to reduce their sales to young smokers by 30 percent over five
years, and 60 percent over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the administration is hoping that the publicity
surrounding the survey will create enough public pressure to force
lawmakers to reconsider a new anti-smoking measure.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
