r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-22 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLERY SHARES LEHMAN'S PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The allure of the U.S. Open, as articulated by
Paul Azinger, is that ``it's the peoples' tournament,'' embracing
the top professionals and any Tom, Dick or Harry who catches fire
during the qualifying process.
</P>
<P>
   The most egalitarian of golf's four majors had a clear-cut
peoples' choice during Sunday's final round at the Olympic Club's
Lake Course. Anybody grinding for that next paycheck, next
promotion, next sale or next break couldn't help but align himself
with Tom Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous gallery that gathered around the first hole shortly
after high noon was firmly behind Lehman, trying to push him over
the top by the sheer force of its cheers of ``Go, Tom,'' or ``This
is your year, Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman felt the fans' passion, and by the end of the day they
would share his pain. You'd think after four straight years of
losing a U.S. Open on the last day, Lehman and his legions of fans
would be desensitized to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But, no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for the fans,'' Lehman said. ``I feel like they
were really pulling for me and I didn't give them what they
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Lehman didn't have the lead stuffed in his pocket like
a dollar bill on the final day this time, and then lose it
somewhere over the last few holes. This time victory eluded him
like a George Washington swept up in the wind. Lehman gave it chase
but every time he lunged for it, another gust got there first and
it flitted further from his grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman bogeyed the first hole and the ninth and couldn't birdie
any in between on his way to a 5-over-par 75 that left him tied for
fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I lost it,'' Lehman said. ``I just didn't win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Payne Stewart, who began the day with a four-shot
advantage over Lehman and Bob Tway. He extended his lead to seven
after three holes but scrambled thereafter and bogeyed three of the
final seven holes to create an opening that a fast-closing Lee
Janzen (68) barely slid through.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen won his second U.S. Open championship while sitting in
the clubhouse when Stewart's bid for a birdie and a playoff slid
inches past the cup on the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   You could say Lehman also lost this tournament by inches.
Because even though he finished six strokes behind Janzen and five
in back of Stewart, it likely would have shaped up as a different
day altogether if not for an 18-inch putt Lehman botched for par on
the first hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was an inexplicable gaffe on the easiest par-5 on the course.
And for Lehman, who was nervous to begin with, the three putt _
only the third he made all week _ was like adding hyper to his
tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``You step up to the first tee, you're nervous, let's face it,''
Lehman said. ``And when you miss a putt like that, it unsettles you
even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman stayed outwardly calm and it looked like the tide might
turn when, on the par-4 fourth hole, Lehman one-putted for a par
while Stewart was two-putting for a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   But that was as good as it would get on a day when Lehman didn't
seem at one with his putter, taking 32 strokes with his flat stick
or four more than he needed while fashioning his third-round 68.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that Lehman couldn't get his drives and tee shots
to stay on the sloped fairways that the sun had baked until were as
hard as the crust on week-old sourdough bread. He missed seven
fairways and then, to add ire to irritation, hit only 10 greens in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed to hit just enough bad shots to struggle all day,''
Lehman said. ``I never got any momentum going from the very first
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Every golfer has days like that. Janzen had one, himself, in
late March when he took a lead into the final round of the Players'
Championship in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla., and shot his way out of
contention with a seven-over-par 79.
</P>
<P>
   After he accepted the championship chalice on the 18th green
Sunday, Janzen, in a voice cracking with emotion, said the wins,
when they come, erase all the bad shots and bad rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can say that,'' Lehman said, smiling weakly, standing well
up the hill from the hoopla on 18, ``when he has won (the U.S.
Open) twice.''
</P>
<P>
   From Lehman's vantage point, he can focus on his four
consecutive final-round U.S. Open disappointments or zero in on the
memories of the last U.S. Open he played here, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was an assistant pro at Wood Ranch at the time, after
having failed in his first, second, third and fourth attempts to
keep his PGA Tour playing privileges.
</P>
<P>
   That was one British Open championship, two Ryder Cups and a few
million dollars ago.
</P>
<P>
   So it didn't sound at all like one man's self-delusion when
Lehman said, before heading home to Scottsdale, Ariz., ``I'll get
it right. I usually find a way to get it right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0128EDT &QL; 
