</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS CAN'T SCORE A WIN AGAINST BROWN 
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Let the record show that at 2:54 in the
afternoon, on the 21st day of June in the year 1998 A.D., in the
city of St. Francis, the Giants finally scored a run at home
against pitcher Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton crossed the plate on a Barry Bonds groundout to
end a 32-inning goose-egg streak against the gangly right-hander,
but it was not nearly enough. Then again, in seven games against
the Padres over the past 10 days, nothing the Giants did was
enough.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego won six of the seven, taking Sunday's series finale at
3Com Park 5-1 on a bad day for Orel Hershiser. The Padres left no
doubt who rules the National League West as they left town with a
51/2-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   When the games against San Diego began, the Giants to a man said
they could not use Jeff Kent's injury as an excuse, that they had
to keep plugging and find a way to win. After the Padres left town
with three wins in four games, the Giants were forced to admit that
they were severely handicapped without Kent, their cleanup hitter,
and J.T. Snow, their regular first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's pretty obvious,'' catcher Brent Mayne said.
``But that's baseball. What are you going to do? At this point,
you've got to think (the Padres) are a better team. They came in
and beat us up pretty good. But they're healthy. They've got all
their guns. The thing we've got to do is keep battling until we can
get the machine going again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to panic or get weird about this. There is
more than half the season to go. Who knows? Maybe next time we face
them they'll be down a man.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't come until September 7-9, when the Giants travel to
San Diego for their last three meetings of the season. Manager
Dusty Baker and Co. know that between now and then they must shave
some or all of their 51/2-game shortfall. The Giants already have
bridged a 61/2-game deficit this season. The question is, can they
do it again? Even a good thoroughbred rarely closes twice in the
same race.
</P>
<P>
   Baker thought the question was silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we have a week left in the season,'' he said.
``We're still due for a couple more good streaks and a couple more
bad streaks. Last year, we were six games up or so at the break and
the Dodgers caught us, and we passed them gain. The race isn't over
today. The race isn't over until October 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played better than us,'' Baker said. ``Maybe with the
situation we're in, they're a better team now. That's the key word:
now. We're without a couple of big horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Clydesdales or miniature ponies, it doesn't matter. If they don
a Giants' uniform, they have no chance against Brown, who missed
his sixth complete-game victory against San Francisco by one
batter. Nevertheless, he scattered seven hits, walked one, struck
out nine and improved to 6-0 with a 0.58 lifetime ERA against the
Giants. At 3Com, he is 4-0 with a 0.25 ERA and a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an explanation for it,'' Brown said. ``I don't
know if it's timing, or if I'm just lucky enough to have good stuff
when I face them. But as long as we're doing well I don't care.
That's not the kind of thing you want to analyze.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, already leading 1-0, scored three runs off Hershiser
in the third inning on a walk to Quilvio Veras, a Steve Finley
triple past a diving Charlie Hayes at first, an identical smash by
Tony Gwynn for a double and a two-out infield single by catcher
Carlos Hernandez. Hershiser did not return for the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-0 lead is tantamount to running up the score when Brown
faces the Giants, especially with their makeshift lineup. The
Padres, however, made it clear that they played well enough to win
no matter who was missing from the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you suffer anytime one of your key players is out. It
sure takes something away,'' Brown said. ``But we've had players
out too. Cammy (Ken Caminiti) has been hurt a lot, and Tony (Gwynn)
has been down with his leg. That's the case with any team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key over the course of the season is who gets over
injuries the best,'' he said, ``who steps in for them and who makes
it through the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it's advantage Padres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
