<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DEFEAT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The tip of Jason Dickson's right index finger was a
concern to Angels manager Terry Collins before Sunday's game
between the Angels and Texas Rangers. Dickson has a crack in the
bone of the finger, but Collins' fears proved unfounded as the
Angels pitcher retired the first 11 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone should have been worried about his pitcher, it was
Rangers manager Johnny Oates, who threw former Angel Matt Perisho
and his 23.14 ERA in a matchup of the AL West's top two teams.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho was battered for 10 runs in 22/3 innings as the Angels
beat the Rangers 10-7 before 32,914 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson got help from three Angels relievers, including Troy
Percival, who earned his league-leading 23rd save.
</P>
<P>
   The win moved the Angels 2{ games ahead of the Rangers, their
biggest division lead since a three-game edge over the Mariners on
Sept. 17, 1995. All it took was winning 18 of 21 games, which the
Angels have done, starting with a victory over the Twins on May 31.
Most recently, the Angels have completed a 10-game stretch against
the Mariners and Rangers, going 8-2 and taking over first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just playing to our capabilities,'' Percival said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely showed we're a team to contend with,'' Dickson
said. ``We've come out and won the close games and also pounded 'em
into the ground. It sends a message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We said going into the first of seven against Texas that these
were very big,'' Collins said. ``Our guys have played absolutely
great baseball. Every guy has a piece of it. You can't win with two
or three guys. We've gotten something from everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Dickson's contribution was the most notable, but not
unexpected considering the way all the starters have pitched
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson suffered a nondisplaced fracture of his right index
finger last Wednesday while swinging at bat during pitchers'
batting practice. But the injury wasn't serious enough to keep him
from getting his seventh victory in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson (8-4) gave up four runs and seven hits in six innings.
He struck out six and walked only one. But he isn't about to allow
himself to feel too good about things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start to think, `Yeah, I'm throwing the way I want to,'
the game steps up and bites you in the butt,'' Dickson said. ``You
have to stick to the basics. Sometimes it helps to keep things
really simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Dickson's performance Sunday was made easier thanks
to Perisho's troubles. The Angels scored five runs in both the
second and third innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Darin Erstad's three-run double got the Angels on
the scoreboard. Perisho made things tougher on himself by walking
three in the inning, including Tim Salmon with the bases loaded to
force in a run.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Perisho gave up four hits, hit a batter and walked
two more. The second walk _ to Damon Mashore _ forced in a run and
forced Oates to finally take Perisho out of the game. After
allowing 10 runs (nine earned) and 10 hits in 22/3 innings
Perisho's ERA rose from 23.14 to 28.80.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, made things ``scary,'' scoring three times
in the fourth and once in the fifth off Dickson. They added two
more runs off reliever Mike Holtz to cut their deficit to 10-6 in
the seventh, and scored another in the ninth to make it 10-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their offense, it should be scary,'' Collins said.
``They've scored a lot of runs all season. There's no reason to
think you're going to hold 'em down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
