<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SNIPER' GUNS DOWN DAAL, DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Where did it come from?
</P>
<P>
   Was it from the grassy knoll beyond the center-field fence? Was
it from Big Mac Land in the corner of the upper deck? Was it from
the top of the Gateway Arch?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows where the sniper was perched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sniper'' was how Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter
referred to what happened in the sixth inning on Sunday, when his
starting pitcher, left-hander Omar Daal, went down as if he'd been
shot while running from first to third on a double by Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   On a sweltering first day of summer, it was believed to be only
a case of the cramps in both legs, but it was contagious. The
cramps seemed to spread to the arms of relievers Russ Springer and
Clint Sodowsky, who couldn't preserve a lead, as the St. Louis
Cardinals rallied to defeat Arizona, 5-4, at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory signaled a three-game sweep for the Cardinals and
enabled them to climb above the .500 mark at 37-36. Arizona, which
fell to 25-50, moves on to Arlington, Texas, to begin a two-game
interleague series with the Texas Rangers tonight.
</P>
<P>
   With a 4-1 lead _ the result of four runs in the top of the
sixth _ Springer replaced Daal in the bottom of the inning. He
walked John Mabry, the leadoff man, and allowed him to go to second
on a wild pitch. Tucson Rincon High product Tom Pagnozzi then drove
Mabry home with a one-out single.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Springer retired the first two batters, but gave
up a single to Mark McGwire that was hit sharply past third baseman
Matt Williams into left field. Brian Jordan, tied for second with
Chicago's Mark Grace in the National League batting race entering
the game, then hit a two-run homer to tie it at 4. It was Jordan's
second homer of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Sodowsky entered the game in the eighth and gave up a base hit
to veteran third baseman Gary Gaetti. David Howard replaced Gaetti
as a pinch runner and was sacrificed to second by Pagnozzi.
</P>
<P>
   Sodowsky walked pinch-hitter Ray Lankford, and after Willie
McGee's grounder to Travis Lee at first moved the runners up,
Sodowsky walked Royce Clayton. Delino DeShields stepped to the
plate, and Sodowsky uncorked a wild pitch, allowing Howard to score
what proved to be the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed closer Jeff Brantley took the mound in the ninth
and got the Diamondbacks in order. The third out was Lee, on a pop
to DeShields at second, which served as a bit of revenge for
Brantley, who gave up a game-winning homer to Lee when the teams
played at Bank One Ballpark last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Lee homered off Curtis King to lead off the sixth for
Arizona and tie the game at 1. It was his team-leading 14th of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams singled, Jay Bell walked with one out and Karim
Garcia drove in Williams with an opposite-field single to left.
Gaetti snared a line drive by Damian Miller for the second out and
Daal walked to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Brady Raggio replaced King and Fox hit a rocket
toward the base of the fence, scoring Bell and Garcia easily. It
appeared Daal might have a chance to score, too, but a few feet
before reaching third, both legs apparently cramped up and he went
down. Raggio then got Devon White on a grounder to short to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough break. Omar was pitching well,'' Showalter
said. ``Our relievers gave up some hits, and the bases on balls
compounded the problem. We've gone through some good points, where
our starters scuffled and the relievers did well, and now it's
going the other way. We can't seem to put anything together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's disappointing. But you can either wallow around in
it or keep grinding, which is what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor said Springer made some
good pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire just muscled it past Matty and Jordan . . . he's been
hitting everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Sodowsky, Connor said, is overthrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes out of himself a little bit,'' Connor said. ``He's
got good enough stuff. He just needs to let it take over, trust it
in the strike zone. We keep telling him that. It has worked
sometimes, and other times, you have this type of situation.
Hopefully, he can develop some more consistency.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
