<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, RED SOX MASTER DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ For all the pleasure he took in the
restored splendor of his own performance, there was a sorrow that
tugged at Pedro Martinez's heart with every pitch he made during
Sunday's 3-1 Red Sox win over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   As he felt the magic and the power coursing through his own
right arm while allowing Tampa Bay just one hit in eight innings _
Miguel Cairo hit a hanging curve-ball for a run-scoring triple in
the fifth _ Martinez could not help but think of the damaged right
arm of his older brother, Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being the ace of the Dodgers' staff, Ramon Martinez is
an idol, inspiration, and spiritual adviser to his younger brother.
So imagine the dread Pedro Martinez felt when his brother called
him this weekend to tell him that he had decided to undergo
season-ending surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why every time I go out there and go through one
inning,'' Martinez said, ``I pray to God to keep me healthy for the
next inning, for the next pitch, and I pray for my brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother came to my mind out there. Every pitch you throw,
it's up to God. One pitch, and you could be through.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first fastball he threw while warming up in the bullpen
Sunday, Martinez knew that the afternoon had a chance to take on an
uncommon aura. He had spent part of the morning napping on the
clubhouse couch, having mistakenly arrived earlier than needed. But
whatever dreams he may have had on the sofa were eclipsed when he
took the mound.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out Quinton McCracken, the first batter he faced,
overpowering him with fastballs. He ended the first inning by
striking out Wade Boggs, who rarely whiffs, with a vicious fastball
that dived over Boggs's shoetops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he was so calm, so under control, reminded me of the
way he was when he threw nine perfect innings against San Diego,''
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said, recalling Martinez's 1995
flirtation with perfection that ended when Bip Roberts led off the
10th with a double. ``By the second inning, I knew we had something
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven Devil Rays paraded back and forth, from dugout to home
plate, before Boggs drew a walk with two outs in the fourth, the
first Tampa Bay base runner. The next batter, Fred McGriff, looked
pitiful, striking out on changeups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those changeups were unfair,'' catcher Scott Hatteberg said.
``He had the kind of stuff today, I'm glad I was catching.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sorrento, who hit two home runs in the four-game series,
drew a full-count walk to open the fifth, after barely fouling off
the previous pitch. Martinez struck out Mike DiFelice, one of his
six strikeouts on the afternoon, to bring up Cairo, a 24-year-old
Venezuelan.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who threw almost exclusively fastballs and changeups,
got ahead of Cairo 0-and-2, the second strike a breaking ball. He
tried throwing another curve past the Devil Rays infielder, but
Cairo launched a drive into the left-center-field gap, out of reach
of left fielder Troy O'Leary, for the triple that scored Sorrento
with Tampa Bay's only run.
</P>
<P>
   ``One mistake, one hanging curveball, and I gave up a base
hit,'' Martinez said. ``Sometimes one mistake is all it takes to
win or lose a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Red Sox had scored all the runs Martinez would need
off Devil Rays pitcher Jason Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, the Red Sox loaded the bases when Mo Vaughn and
O'Leary singled and John Valentin was hit by a pitch. Hatteberg
popped out, but rookie Lou Merloni hit a two-run double off the end
of his bat, which broke on impact, the ball carrying past third
baseman Boggs into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to give Pedro a lead,'' said Merloni. ``If
it's nothing-nothing in the seventh, sometimes a team thinks it can
steal one off him.''
</P>
<P>
   With Nomar Garciaparra hitting a solo home run in the third,
there would be no larceny on this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Cy Young Award winner,'' Boggs said. ``That says it
all. A 97 mile-an-hour fastball, an 82 mile-an-hour changeup.
That's a pretty big disparity in pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in his last inning, Martinez was still hitting the radar
gun at 94 and 95 m.p.h., according to Kerrigan. Even so, manager
Jimy Williams, mindful that Martinez had thrown 121 pitches on top
of the 140 he threw in his last start, lifted him for closer Tom
Gordon, who gave up a one-out single to Dave Martinez in the ninth,
then retired Boggs and McGriff for his third save of the series,
fourth in five games, and 23d of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had no quarrel with being lifted. Nor did he lament the
loss of a no-hitter, which he has never thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there too many times _ seventh inning, sixth inning,
ninth inning _ and never gotten it, for me to be disappointed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as he would later add, he felt blessed just to be able
to pitch. If only Ramon could say the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
