<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9823 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CASSTEVENS-US-IRA     06-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CASSTEVENS-US-IRAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS WINNERS, BUT NOT ON THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ So, what do you say to an Iranian wearing face
paint and a green Harpo Marx wig, who is bouncing up and down and
blowing a toy whistle in your ear?
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations. See you in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   We keep hearing that the day will come when the United States
will win the World Cup. But that won't happen in four years or
eight years, and if we keep taking backward steps like the one we
took Sunday night under the lights of Stade Gerland, it is a good
bet the Cardinals will win the Super Bowl before Americans are
declared the global champions of kickball.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed it, Tehran newspapers have the story. It's
banner-headline news.
</P>
<P>
   ``IRAN 2, SATAN 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Shut out by Germany, the U.S. needed to beat Iran to avoid
first-round elimination. Five hours before the match, at a lavish
reception, U.S. Soccer Federation president Alan Rothenberg stood
on the terrace of the four-star Ville Florentine Hotel that
overlooks the red-tiled roofs of this charming city, the
third-largest in France. Rothenberg appeared upbeat. He sounded
confident.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. had been no match for the Germans. But the Iranians
aren't in the same class. Iran was the last of 32 teams to qualify
for the World Cup. Jalil Talebi is the team's fourth coach in seven
months, breaking the record of managerial impatience formerly held
by George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   One of the party guests swirled his glass of Beaujolais and
posed a small-talk question. So, Alan, what do you want to see
tonight? The U.S. was starting five different players, half the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see us kick their (. . .)!'' Rothenberg bellowed.
Everyone laughed, including the host, who added, ``A Holland-South
Korea result'' _ Holland won, 5-0 _ ``would be acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   How about a one-goal win? Or a face-saving tie?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't happen. The U.S. couldn't find the net, and it was there,
right in front of our lads, so open-mouthed at times it appeared to
be yawning. Our guys came out shooting. Brian McBride fired a
header three minutes into the match. The ball bounced off the
crossbar. Claudio Reyna took a turn. A ricochet off the post. David
Regis shot. Dang. Off the post again.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the French National police, who frisked each of the
44,000 spectators entering the stadium, had discovered what little
luck the American team had, and confiscated it.
</P>
<P>
   In all, four shots struck iron, and bounced away. It was like
watching Kevin Butler, in a slump, trying to make field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trailed, 2-0, before McBride scored America's first
World Cup goal. It came after almost three hours of trying.
</P>
<P>
   Outscored, 4-1, in two losses, America has done little to earn
the respect it seeks in the soccer world. But its appearance here _
the U.S. still has a game left on Thursday against Yugoslavia _ has
not been a complete waste of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have been good ambassadors. Before the game, they
exchanged gifts with the Iranians. The teams broke with tradition
and posed for a group picture, the players in white and red all
smiles, arm in arm, like a snapshot of college fraternity brothers.
</P>
<P>
   American and Iranian fans also celebrated the sport, together,
treating one another better than some Arizona State and UA fans do.
</P>
<P>
   This score will fade from memory, hopefully. But I won't forget
those around me in Section A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you, please?'' the woman, an Iranian, asked politely in
halting English, offering her camera. As I looked into the
viewfinder, she positioned herself between two strangers from a
country far away and far different from her own. One sported a red,
white and blue Mad Hatter's hat. The other wore the Stars and
Stripes like a shawl. Before clicking the shutter, I didn't have to
ask them to smile. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
