<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9824 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON     06-22 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANZEN PUTS IT TOGETHER 
BY C.W. NEVIUS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Well, that's it. If you don't understand the
crushing pressure of the stretch run at the U.S. Open now, I am
afraid we are going to have to revoke your viewing privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen and Payne Stewart staggered down the clipped green
fairways of the Olympic Club Sunday afternoon, looking like two men
holding their breath. They came stylishly out of every shot to an
elegant follow-through, but if you looked closer you could see they
were squinting so hard that they appeared to be playing in a
sandstorm.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, they stood on the 18th green for the trophy
ceremony, each fighting back tears, and you'd have been hard
pressed to tell which one was the winner. For the record it was
Janzen _ again.
</P>
<P>
   He'd beaten Stewart five years ago for the Open title at
Baltusrol, and he did it again Sunday, holding his game together,
getting a couple of nice little breaks and managing to concentrate
when nearly everyone around him was springing tiny, disastrous
leaks in their swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to suck it up,'' said Janzen, who bogeyed the third
hole to go to five strokes behind the leader. ``I just knew that if
I gave up, I would be really upset with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Janzen's voice trailed off, and he had to go through
another spell of staring at his shoes and blinking hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' he mumbled. ``I can't help myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all right. Because you don't win the Open, you survive it,
and then you look around to see where you are. You raise the club
high above your head, let it flash down at the ball and then you
hope to God that something good happens when the ball hits the
earth again.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees. We struggle to explain how things can
go wrong in the thatch and greasy greens, but Olin Browne, who
limped home in 15 over par and then staged a mini-victory dance on
the 18th green, may have put it as well as anyone Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever try to light one of those big white-headed kitchen
matches with your thumbnail?'' asked Browne. ``Pretty cool when you
do it, right? But sooner or later you are going to get a piece of
phosphorus under your fingernail and it is going to burn the crap
out of you. That's a good analogy for the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   When we look back at this one, a pretty good case could be made
that Stewart, who lost by a single stroke, saw the big silver cup
slip away when he hit a drive to the exact center of the 12th
fairway and discovered that he was stuck in the world's tiniest
sand trap.
</P>
<P>
   In a world-class bad hop, Stewart's ball had come to rest in a
divot, which the USGA has ruled should be filled with sand every
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this before,'' said Stewart. ``If they are going to
come out and try to repair something, that's ground under repair. I
think you should get a drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, and a lot of people thought the 17th hole was unplayable as
a par 4 and that the 18th green was unputtable when the pin was
placed at the top of the Olympic Club ski jump.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had trouble shoveling it out of the sand, put the ball
in another, honest-to-goodness, sand trap, got it out, missed a
putt and suddenly he was a stroke behind Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   What are you going to do? That's the Open. And, the members will
be telling you proudly for the next 10 years or so, that's the
Olympic Club's Lake Course.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come right down to it,'' said Stewart, ``it was the
Olympic Club that really won. There was one person at even par for
the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, frankly admits he couldn't stand the tension. He says he
quit looking at the leader board down the stretch because watching
too many players would have cluttered his mind to the breaking
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing the golf part is easy,'' he said, ``because we have
done it so many times. When I got to 11 and I knew I had a chance
to win, I just kept telling myself `This is the U.S. Open. It only
takes one shot. Lose focus on one shot and you could lose.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, we can say that Janzen won because of a steady,
gutty effort, a couple of kinks in Stewart's swing and at least two
sensational breaks. On 11, the ball hit the deep, terrible rough
but magically hopped back out to safety. And better yet, on the
fifth hole, Janzen's ball disappeared into a tree, sat up there for
a minute, then fell down to where he could play it. There's no
accounting for it.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something else to the Open, that always seems to
find a way to come true. There's almost always a lovely symmetry to
the conclusion, a nice little wrap-up that saves this sometimes
stuffy game from terminal snootiness.
</P>
<P>
   As Janzen spoke at the post-tournament press conference, his
wife, Beverly, and son, Connor, sat at his feet. Janzen struggled a
little after his first Open win, and there were lots of
explantions, from a change in golf clubs to a new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But as he said on Friday in a low-key press conference, he
thinks the real reason was the birth of Connor, soon after the
Open. The whole family was trying to travel the tour together, and
they weren't getting much sleep. Janzen didn't win, but he doesn't
hesitate when asked about his biggest thrills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being a father,'' he said. ``I can't think of anything
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And, when a reporter asked how old his son was, Lee and Beverly
exchanged a look, remembering where they were five years ago in a
U.S. Open champion's press conference and all the things that have
happened since.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's almost 5,'' Janzen said, and by then he almost had the
blinking completely under control.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
