<HEADER>
A9825 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BICKLEY-USOPEN-AZ     06-22 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BICKLEY-USOPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CLUB REAL WINNER IN THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a line you'd never expect to see in the 1998 players'
guide, written by the U.S. Golf Association and focusing on the man
in knickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``... he became known on tour for wearing his plus-2s and a
habit of choking in the closing stages of a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   At Payne Stewart's request, the line will be deleted in all
forthcoming editions. But there is a difference between a man's
biography and his reputation, and the latter is never so forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Resist the temptation.
</P>
<P>
   You can look at the scorecard and see that Stewart gave away
four shots on Sunday. He bogeyed three of the final seven holes. He
joined Ben Hogan, Arnold Palmer and Tom Watson, a dubious foursome
that has blown Sunday leads at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   Choking. There is no uglier word in competition. But this was no
Greg Norman. This was no hideous meltdown. And as much as Sunday's
crab-stagger will be perceived as Stewart swallowing a grapefruit,
that's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointed? Yeah, I'm disappointed,'' Stewart said. ``But
I'm going to hold my head up. I played good this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Stewart did nothing different on the final seven holes
than he did all week. He simply ran out of breaks, and it was never
more evident than a wonderful tee shot that somehow landed in a
place more beach than divot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first fairway I hit in a while,'' Stewart said. ``And sure
enough, I was in a bunker, a sand divot on No. 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Next hole, another bogey sprouted when his approach landed in
the deep rough, complicated by a clump right behind his ball. The
only moment resembling a gag was an awful putt he yanked on No. 16,
one that cost him a playoff. But that was prefaced by a birdie on
No. 14, followed by a courageous effort on the final hole in which
the ball squirted away as if allergic to the cup.
</P>
<P>
   No, Stewart didn't choke. Lee Janzen won. Sometimes it's that
simple. If anything, be thankful that some competitive drama
finally emerged from an event that plodded along for three days.
And more than anything, remember what this tournament was all
about.
</P>
<P>
   The real history occurred earlier in the day, when Casey Martin
motored up the 18th fairway, stepped out of his cart and received a
standing ovation. He shot a 72 on Sunday, finishing 11 over par in
his first major. Once a pariah, he is thawing the frozen hearts of
his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Well, most of them. On his way to the interview area, Martin
crossed paths with Jack Nicklaus, a legend who likened golf carts
to the bubonic plague. Martin said hello, testing the waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed uncomfortable,'' Martin said. ``But he was gracious.
He said `Hi' and went on his way.''
</P>
<P>
   How nice.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Martin's tee time was so late that his cart needed
headlights. On Saturday, his dying leg hurt so much that he cut off
interviews in midstream. On Sunday, he missed his goal, failing to
qualify for the Masters. But he finished in 23rd place, 20 slots
higher than Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering where he was 10 months ago _ he could barely walk
from room to room _ it's such a victory,'' said his mother,
Melinda. ``It's so heartwarming, seeing all the strife we had to go
through. The cart was a non-issue, and all I heard was cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Martin prevailed like no other in man the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt our tour could've kept this from going to the courts,
could've stopped the whole process,'' Stewart said. ``Because the
game is bigger than that. Let him play.''
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, let Stewart off the hook. He dominated
for three days before the course found him, as it did everybody.
But even when his lead disappeared, he kept fighting, scratching,
hoping. Until he found a reality shared by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the golf course won,'' Stewart said. ``I'd say the
golf course lived up to its reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some will say the same about Stewart. Sorry. In the end, he was
simply prisoner to fate. And a piece of real estate destined for
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bickley can be reached at 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
