<HEADER>
A9826 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VICTORY FORGED BY WILLPOWER 
BY TIM KEOWN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After finishing the 13th hole, Lee Janzen
started walking the Olympic Club fairways like General Patton. His
eyes were fixed straight ahead, and his head never moved. He didn't
look like he was playing a round of golf; he looked like he was on
his way to make an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   You knew right then Janzen was on his way to his second U.S.
Open championship. You knew it because winning was the only thought
he allowed to invade his consciousness. He wasn't just approaching
his ball, he was stalking it, treating it as if he were afraid it
might get away.
</P>
<P>
   You also knew Janzen would win for another reason: After three
days of blissful good fortune, events were beginning to conspire
against Payne Stewart. As Janzen approached the 15th green, the
manual scoreboard changed Stewart's score to even par for the
tournament and 3-over for the day. This brought Janzen into a tie
for the lead, and it tripped several reactions.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd around the 15th went crazy. Steve Stricker, Janzen's
playing partner, looked up at the board, laughed, then dropped his
head in exaggerated amazement.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Stricker saw all of this coming, too.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen's reaction was straight out of ``Rio Lobo'': He marched
toward his ball and looked straight ahead. To him, the scoreboard
didn't exist. Stewart didn't exist. His world consisted of his ball
and the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 13th hole, I decided I wasn't going to look at the
board _ no matter what,'' Janzen said. ``The last thing I wanted to
do was look up at the board and see that I had a lead. I didn't
want to get it in my mind that I had to protect a lead. I just
wanted to play every hole the way I'd been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen finished the tournament at even par, and he beat Stewart
by one stroke. To get an idea of the kind of charge he put on over
the final 15 holes, consider this: After the first three holes, he
was seven strokes behind Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Being seven strokes behind with 15 to play is like being down
four runs in the bottom of the ninth with one out and nobody on
base. Seven strokes is a lot to make up, in part because it takes a
joint effort: Janzen had to get it together, and Stewart had to
come apart like a cheap shoe.
</P>
<P>
   As Janzen approached the fourth tee, the U.S. Open looked like a
done deal. Stewart was bouncing his way through the course,
knickers billowing in the wind, and everybody else was trying to
make enough shots to finish with dignity. The fans following
Stewart and Tom Lehman were actively rooting for Lehman, for no
other reason than to coax some drama out of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After the first three rounds, rooting for Stewart was the
equivalent of rooting for Microsoft: It only felt good if you had a
stake in it.
</P>
<P>
   And although he would never admit it, there's a good chance
Stewart _ in the pre-dawn quiet of his own head _ started Sunday
morning with a look at his closest challengers and a confident nod.
</P>
<P>
   With a four-stroke lead, Stewart couldn't have looked at the
group consisting of Lehman, Bob Tway and Janzen with anything
approaching fear. Nick Price might have sent a little shiver
through him, but the others don't have a strong recent history of
late challenges or final-round heroics. To a man, the others are
known for what they used to do, or how well they finish second.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen tore Stewart's heart out at the '93 Open, when he chipped
in a wondrous shot to win by a stroke at Baltusrol. He hadn't
approached those exploits since. He hadn't attended a trophy
presentation of any kind in three years. His round of 66 on Friday
seemed likely to be his shining achievement for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after falling seven down after the first three holes.
</P>
<P>
   And even more especially after his tee shot on the fifth hole.
</P>
<P>
   After a birdie on No. 4, Janzen hit a ball nobody could find. He
couldn't find it, his caddie couldn't find it, the course marshals
couldn't find it. It was Saturday morning at Lodi Muni _ everyone
looking for a lost ball. Finally, a fan with binoculars found it
lodged in a cypress tree. Janzen dutifully walked back toward the
tee, holding a new ball and absolutely zero hope, when a gust of
wind blew the ball out of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   There is good fortune, and then there is finding a winning
Powerball ticket in a Laundromat. Instead of teeing off with a
one-stroke penalty for a lost ball _ in effect, Janzen's second tee
shot would have been his third shot at a par-4 hole _ he got to
take his second shot from the rough. He ended up chipping in from
behind the green to save par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at a ball struck in a tree, where I would have
been lucky to make double (bogey) to somehow making par,'' Janzen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen accepted his trophy with tears running down his face. His
family _ several generations, it appeared _ stood off to the side,
and there wasn't a dry eye among them. Janzen was humble and
disbelieving, presenting the opposite image from the one he showed
on the course.
</P>
<P>
   The stoicism crumbled, replaced by a cry-fluttered voice and a
few failed deep breaths. ``I recall I was the same way last time,''
Janzen said. ``Can't help myself.''
</P>
<P>
   His reaction was something of a surprise _ maybe the only one of
the afternoon. If you looked closely, you could see the rest of it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
