<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBALABOR_REPUBLIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SUMMER OF DISCONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For two years, the Suns have been aiming toward this summer,
laying plans to put the final pieces of a championship contender
together through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why the club probably won't be involved in
Wednesday's draft, unless there's a trade.
</P>
<P>
   But after the draft, the Suns and 28 other NBA teams could be
sitting idle through a long, hot summer of labor negotiations
centered on free agency, character issues and how the league and
players will split up a revenue pie fattened during the Michael
Jordan era.
</P>
<P>
   It could mean the Suns' blueprint for the future will collect
dust.
</P>
<P>
   The league's owners have indicated their intention to lock out
their players on July 1, stopping all transactions and virtually
shutting down league business until a new collective bargaining
agreement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The first indication that an impasse might be avoided surfaced
late last week after USA Basketball, which is closely aligned with
the NBA, announced that a team of league players selected to
represent the United States at the World Championships in Athens,
next month would be replaced by college or Continental Basketball
Association players.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Players Association, the union that
represents NBA players, has asked the league for a no-strike,
no-lockout agreement that would allow league business to continue
while negotiations go on this summer. That would allow NBA players
to remain on the World Championships team. However, league sources
said it is unlikely that any player transactions would be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Another negotiating session, which might provide some answers,
is scheduled for today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, owners and players appear to be dug in and willing to
lose regular-season games for the first time in league history
because of a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference during the NBA Finals, Commissioner David
Stern made it clear that owners are prepared to lock the players
out right into the season if necessary. Asked how many owners were
willing to interrupt the season, Stern answered:
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't comment directly on that, other than to say that
the owners voted, 27-2, to open up the collective bargaining
agreement. And I think that speaks pretty articulately to the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the fight all about?
</P>
<P>
   It's fairly simple on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when the players and owners reached a six-year
collective bargaining agreement, the owners agreed to give the
players no more than 52 percent of total revenues from the league.
They had hoped it would be closer to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement included a clause that would allow the owners to
reopen the agreement if the players' cut of revenues went above 52
percent. According to the owners, players received 57 percent from
last season _ more than a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   So the owners propose eliminating exceptions to the league's
salary cap, creating a so-called ``hard cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Under such a plan, each team would have a limit on how much it
could pay players, with few if any exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The most important and expensive of these exceptions is the
so-called ``Larry Bird exception.''
</P>
<P>
   It allows a team to pay its own free agent as much as the player
and team agree upon, without regard to the salary cap, if that
player has been with the same team for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   It's been expensive for owners, but it also has paid benefits.
Because of the Bird exception, many of the league's best players
have remained with the same club throughout their careers. Michael
Jordan has never played for a team other than the Chicago Bulls.
Larry Bird spent his entire playing career with the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter in the long run if all we have is a sport
that's running large losses, raising ticket prices and generally
viewed as not a very good citizen over time,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The owners contend that as many as a dozen NBA teams lost money
last season. The players don't believe it, and there is
disagreement over just what total revenues entail.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is rookie salaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the last agreement, a three-year rookie salary scale was
implemented to provide more money for proven veterans and bring
down astronomical salaries for players new to the league.
</P>
<P>
   The owners don't like the system because the have-nots are
either developing players for the better, higher grossing clubs, or
they must pay far more than they can afford to keep the players.
</P>
<P>
   Owners want a rookie scale of up to six years, or perhaps a form
of restricted free agency until a player has been in the league for
a given number of years. Players and agents have indicated they
might be willing to compromise, but only if the Bird exception
stays.
</P>
<P>
   The final point of contention is ``character issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Some owners, such as Utah's Larry Miller, have indicated this is
more important than any of the financial issues. They're troubled
by an already shaky league image tainted further by the Latrell
Sprewell coach-strangling incident and numerous charges related to
marijuana _ a drug that is not banned under the current collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   It could all add up to a very long summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
