<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9828 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-US.OPEN-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANZEN OVERCOMES PAYNE 
BY PAT SULLIVAN
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Olympic Club finally got its man Sunday. No
more quibbling, please, about the ``wrong'' golfer winning the U.S.
Open again, not when his credentials read: ``two-time U.S. Open
champion Lee Janzen.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, 33, who won the 1993 U.S. Open but had been winless on
tour since 1995, used steel-trap thinking as well as the clubs in
his golf bag to shoot a 2-under-par 68 to finish at exactly
even-par, 280, and beat Payne Stewart by a stroke in a rematch of
their final-round duel in '93 at Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final five holes, after Janzen had pulled to within a
stroke of the lead, he had the discipline to keep his eyes off the
leaderboard and his mind on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to know how I stood,'' he said. ``I was going to
play my game the rest of the way in. I didn't want to think if I
got lucky and got ahead. I didn't want to play safe. I just wanted
to hit good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   With 25,000 watching, he had the golf game to finish
par-par-par-par-par, and isn't that what the U.S. Open is about? At
one particular hole, the annoying, sloping, 468-yard, par-4 17th _
the hole members play as a par-5, and Janzen had played in 5-over
par the previous three rounds _ he pulled off a pure Lee Janzen
performance.
</P>
<P>
   In '93, his long-iron play was critical to his victory. This
time it was, too. He pulled a 3-iron from his bag and rifled a
200-yard shot on a straight line, grabbing the tournament _ and the
front of the green _ by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Janzen was seven strokes off the lead after a bogey
at No.3, but he never wavered in his strong thinking, not when his
ball found the rough, not when he had some luck, like his
``member-bounce'' approach shots to No.11 and No.13 and his 4-wood
tee shot obligingly falling out of a tree after several minutes on
No.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't count myself out, but I wasn't thinking about
winning, either,'' Janzen said of that early stretch of holes.
</P>
<P>
   After he won, he said, ``I feel complete satisfaction. I went
out and played my absolute best in the championship I love most.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, 33, from Orlando, Fla., has had a solid if unflashy
career as a tour pro. In nine years, he has now won eight times.
But it is the two U.S. Opens and the 1995 International and 1995
Players Championship, both on tough courses, that stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because I won a U.S. Open on a very difficult course,
you just get in your mind that you can play tough courses,'' he
said. ``After that I felt more comfortable on tough courses. The
Players Championship is incredibly hard conditions. Winged Foot
last year (PGA Championship) was very tough, and I had a good
tournament (tie for fourth). It only gets better as time goes by.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like Hogan had to sweat out Fleck's finish in 1955, Janzen
had to sit and watch Stewart's. Janzen waited in the locker room,
his wife, Beverly, close by. Stewart had a 20-foot putt from above
the cup at the 18th to reforge a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could barely stand to watch,'' Janzen said. ``If he makes
it, we're playing off. If he misses it, I've won the tournament.
I'm watching it roll down there. I thought, three or four feet from
the hole, it was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's putt curved left just short of the cup. When it did,
Beverly gave Janzen a long hug and a quick kiss. Then he went out
to the 18th green for a tearful acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a day that has gone by that I haven't
thought about winning the U.S. Open again,'' Janzen said. ``This
erases all the bad Sundays, all the missed cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Stewart, he said, ``I know how hard it is to sleep on
that lead. He's not going to take home the trophy, but he deserves
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who had led the tournament since Thursday, was
matter-of-fact in defeat. ``First off, you've got to give Lee
Janzen all the credit. He's in the third-to-last group and shoots a
68. ... He deserves to be the champion today.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what it all boils down to, I think, is that the Olympic
Club really won, because there was one person even-par for the
tournament. So I think this golf course stood up to the test of
holding an Open Championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was the better-known player starting Sunday's final
round with a four-stroke lead, but he also was no Ben Hogan, Arnold
Palmer or Tom Watson, the threesome of famous runners-up in the
Olympic Opens of 1955, 1966 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the third-round leaders teed off in early
afternoon, Masters champion Mark O'Meara, a friend and neighbor of
Stewart's in Florida, completed a round of 1-under 69. ``Yes! I
broke par. Yes! With a double (bogey) on 17,'' he said after coming
of the 18th green to complete a tournament that went 70-76-78-69 _
293, good for a tie for 32nd.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, a five-time winner at Pebble Beach who broke through
for his first major victory this year at Augusta, said he left
Stewart a note of encouragement Sunday morning. ``After the second
round my wife saw him and said, `Let's keep the majors in Orlando.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Even (par) or 1-under should be good enough for Payne today,''
O'Meara predicted.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been, with breathing room, except for one thing:
Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart never settled into a rhythm. His opening drive
sailed into the gallery on the right side of the first fairway,
and, for starters, he had to forget about making birdie at the
tournament's easiest hole.
</P>
<P>
   At the 609-yard 16th, Stewart drove through the fairway and into
the rough, found a bunker with his third shot and made his fifth
bogey of the round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I scrambled pretty well today,'' Stewart said. ``But I didn't
play good enough to win today, and I got beat by an outstanding
golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
