<HEADLINE>
A NATURAL FINISH    
 WIND-AIDED SHOT NETS JANZEN OPEN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There was no reason to believe that Lee Janzen
would win another U.S. Open, especially the 98th version.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen opened this national championship with a 3-over 73 on
Thursday and matched that score in Saturday's third round. Even
though he did get to 66 in between, the guy couldn't make it past
the 17th hole, where he had made a bogey and two doubles during
those three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't enough, Janzen began Sunday's final 18 holes
with bogeys at Nos. 2 and 3, tumbling 7 shots off the pace. Even
the mild-mannered Floridan knew it didn't look good.
</P>
<P>
   But the Olympic Club is golf's version of ``The Twilight Zone,''
and Payne Stewart, who led through the first three rounds of the
Open, was visited by the ghost of Rod Serling late Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ben Hogan, Arnold Palmer and Tom Watson, who had carried
leads into the final round of the Open here, Stewart ended up going
from winner to runner-up in the blink of an eye.
</P>
<P>
   History will show that Janzen's 2-under 68 on a relatively calm
day earned him a 1-shot victory over Stewart, who never got it
going on his way to a 74. But the real story, the eerie truth, is
that this U.S. Open swung on two most unlikely of shots.
</P>
<P>
   The first came early in Janzen's round, when he hit an errant
drive into the trees at the fifth hole. The ball didn't come down,
and Janzen was on his way back to the tee to take a penalty and hit
his third shot when . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``A gust of wind came up and blew it out of the tree,'' Janzen
said, smiling at the recollection. ``I really thought I was going
to make double (bogey) there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he made par by chipping in from 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The second strange occurrence befell Stewart after he pummeled
his drive down the 12th fairway. The ball settled in a sand-filled
divot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first fairway I had it in in a while, and sure
enough, I'm deep in the divot. Smack dab in the middle of the
sand,'' said Stewart, who pushed his second shot into a bunker and
made bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Take those breaks out of it, and Stewart might have broken the
fourth-round jinx that has cursed this Open course since 1955. But
Janzen was the only player in the field to equal par, as his 280
total earned him $535,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Complete satisfaction,'' was the way Janzen described his
second victory in the Open, which joins the title he captured in
1993 at Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played my absolute best in the tournament that means the
most to me. It's just too much.''
</P>
<P>
   If the eerie conclusion was not enough, there also was the deja
vu factor: Janzen beat Stewart in '93.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about it earlier, but late in the round, I
thought, `Payne Stewart, ball in the tree, chip-in. Where have I
heard this before?' '' said Janzen, who broke a three-year drought
for his eighth victory.
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to a shot he hit between the trees at the 10th
hole at Baltusrol, where he made another impossible par before
chipping in at the 16th hole to beat Stewart by 2 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is, (the Olympic Club) lived up to its
reputation,'' said Stewart, who almost forced a playoff on the
final hole when his 18-foot birdie putt from above the cup just
died left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one guy managed to shoot par, and Lee gets all the
credit. I didn't play well enough to win, and I got beat by an
outstanding round of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   There were others who also came up short, like Bob Tway, whose
73 got him to third place, 4 shots off the pace, and Nick Price,
who also shot 73 but finished 5 strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest disappointment was Tom Lehman, who was
playing in the final group of the Open for the fourth straight
year. The Scottsdale pro didn't have a birdie on his way to a 75
that pushed him back into a tie for fifth place, 6 back.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also some winners who didn't get to hold the
coveted silver cup.
</P>
<P>
   They included U.S. Amateur sensation Matt Kuchar (74, 9 over),
who celebrated his 20th birthday by earning his way into next
year's national championship. The top 15 finishers and ties earn
Open exemptions, and Kuchar finished in a tie for 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin, who rode his way into Open history this week, also
played well. He closed with a 72 that left him 11 over and in tie
for 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen also made history by becoming the 18th player to win two
or more national championships. His comeback from 5 shots down
entering the final round was the biggest rebound since Johnny
Miller rallied from 6 strokes off the pace to win the 1973 Open at
Oakmont Country Club in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (winning Open No. 2) elevates what I've done to a
whole new level,'' said Janzen, 33, who caught and passed Stewart
with four birdies and a crucial par save at the 17th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Even his peers are starting to understand Janzen's impact on the
Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is becoming a U.S. Open specialist,'' Price said of
Janzen's ability to hit tight fairways, withstand the pressure and,
of course, play par golf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
