<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-STING-MERCURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE'S FINAL SHOT SERVES MERCURY THEIR FIRST LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As quick as Coach Cheryl Miller was to take blame for the
Mercury's first loss of the season, her players offered absolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost because we let them back into the game,'' said guard
Bridget Pettis, not because Miller failed to call a full timeout
during the final 30 seconds of a 72-71 Charlotte victory Sunday at
America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Miller pleaded poor clock management in a rapid-fire finish _
``It was going too fast to breathe,'' said Toni Foster, then on the
bench _ after a Mercury 20-second timeout at the 36.1-second mark.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie point guard Christy Smith scored her only points on an
almost uncontested layup with 24.7 left to put the Sting ahead,
70-69, for the first time since 4-3. Instead of taking a timeout to
set up a final shot, the Mercury raced upcourt and scored on a
Pettis layup at the 14-second mark.
</P>
<P>
   That left Charlotte (4-1) enough time to set up rookie Tracy
Reid for a 16-footer that the two-time All-America from North
Carolina buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a position like that before,'' said Reid,
who bumped her short pro career scoring high to 21 points. ``It was
exciting that my teammates had confidence enough in me at the end
to take the last shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The final two seconds slipped away without Phoenix (3-1)
responding. Charlotte won for the first time in three tries here
and took a 3-2 series lead over the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take full responsibility,'' Miller said. ``I cost our team a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   She took the rap before her players in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a crowded room with an elephant and nobody's
talking about the elephant, you might as well address it.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran Mercury, just 2-of-13 from the three-point line,
know better. With a game-high 11-point lead, less than 6:30
remaining and a crowd of 13,503 screaming for the kill, more is
responsible for the loss than a timeout not called before a
successful possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are taking the blame for that game,'' said Michele
Timms, who admitted to letting Smith ``walk to the basket'' for her
bucket instead of at least forcing the former Arkansas star to
convert from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a five-minute patch where they scored on every
transition. And you have to give credit to Charlotte. They're by
far the best of any team we've played so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicky Bullett hit two of four free throws and a 13-foot jumper
and Reid two free throws in the Sting rally from 66-55 down, but
the shots that truly set up the closing seconds were three-pointers
by 6-foot-2 Andrea Congreaves at 2:27 and 42.1.
</P>
<P>
   The second of those closed the gap to 69-68 and rewarded
Charlotte for its perseverance with a genuine chance to steal the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Congreaves scored 12 points in a season-high 23 minutes because
of a lineup shuffle to cover an early first-half injury to center
Rhonda Mapp (torn tendon/left foot).
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix power forward Toni Foster missed the final 6:53 after
suffering a right hand sprain.
</P>
<P>
   At 66-65, Phoenix executed well enough on both ends to put its
leading scorer, Jennifer Gillom, on the foul line for three
consecutive possessions. But Gillom made just half of her six
tries, which Congreaves erased with her second three-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Houston (5-0) is next at 7 p.m. Wednesday.
The battle of unbeatens angle is gone, but the game is important if
the Mercury is to keep pace with its new Western Conference rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can cry about this for about 24 hours, then we have to let
go and start focusing on Houston,'' Timms said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
