<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9831 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-LADN     06-22 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN WALKS OVER U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Claudio Reyna didn't know what to do. So he stood there for a
moment, watching the mayhem around him, then knelt on the turf at
Stade Gerland, disbelieving all he saw.
</P>
<P>
   What had started so promisingly ended in the cruelest manner
imaginable, the United States' World Cup dream slipping away in a
stunning 2-1 loss to Iran, and much of the credit --- or blame, as
it were --- rested on Reyna's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   For so long the future of American soccer, Reyna turned out to
be a dud when it most mattered, and that --- as much as anything
else --- proved the Yanks' undoing in France.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't horrendous Sunday night, when the United States became
the fifth squad eliminated from second-round consideration, but his
lax defending wasresponsible for the only goal in the match that
mattered, and his supposed prowess in orchestrating an attack never
materialized, neither in the 2-0 loss a week ago to Germany nor in
this clash, the one the Americans had been expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   There were myriad reasons that they didn't, including the old
standard, the one dealing with finishing chances. Despite owning
huge portions of play, despite creating at least a half-dozen
outstanding opportunities, Sampson's Army put just one goal away, a
Brian McBride header in the waning minutes that halved the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   It was too little and far too late, although the U.S. continued
to hammer away at the Iranian goal until Swiss referee Urs Meier
finally ended it after nearly 31/2 minutes of injury time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last four years is gone in a week,'' noted Cobi Jones.
``That's difficult to take.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely disappointing,'' said goalkeeper Kasey Keller.
``We played so well, we hit post like five times or whatever it
was. It just wasn't going to happen for us today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' best shots ripped into the woodwork, three of
them --- ``It was like the post had a magnet in it,'' quipped
McBride --- but that's not good enough, and the end result, to the
delight of the largely Iranian audience, was the most devastating
loss the United States has suffered in the sport since coming of
age in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson, the U.S. coach, doesn't agree. He lauded his
team's play, spoke of the progress the Yanks have made and are
still making, and made certain everyone knew how proud he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very proud, and very disappointed at the same time,''
he said. ``I will never be happy with a loss, but I was very happy
with the effort and the style with which we approached the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It had begun pleasantly enough, with handshakes and flowers and
both sides --- the Americans and Iranians, supposed mortal enemies
--- getting together for an integrated team photo. But there seemed
an air of desperation to the U.S. lineup: Sampson made five changes
from the Germany match, sending forward Eric Wynalda and
midfielders Ernie Stewart, Chad Deering, Brian Maisonneuve and Mike
Burns to the bench. He dropped his 3-6-1 formation for a more
offensive 3-5-2, with McBride and Roy Wegerle as forwards, Tab
Ramos in Stewart's spot, Frankie Hejduk in Burns', and Joe-Max
Moore playing behind Ramos and Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   It led to a strong start, with McBride hitting the crossbar with
a header just three minutes in. Once Iran got its bearings, the
match was played primarily between the boxes, with winger Mehdi
Mahdavikia's dominance on the right side the key element to the
clash.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was the Americans who should have surged ahead, if not
on McBride's shot, then on a 25-yard blast from Reyna that slammed
against the base of the right post in the 33rd minute. Instead, it
was the Iranians who took charge, just four minutes before the
half, when Reyna left Hamid Esteli alone in the box.
</P>
<P>
   The play developed on the right, with Mahdavikia --- hemmed in
by Moore and Jones --- sending the forward to Javad Zarincheh,
whose cross found Esteli about nine yards out. His looping header
to the left side of the net left Keller no chance.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, until at least midway through the second
half, the Americans offered little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our patience (after the goal),'' said Reyna, who
blamed miscommunication on the poor marking of Esteli. ``We had the
speed to get behind them, and we couldn't do it. Mentally we lost
it. We lost control of the game, and we lost the calm we had before
the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Reyna's fault. He's responsible for picking this team
up, for guiding it through the tough spots and picking apart
opposing defenses. And while he continues to show promise, as he
has since his early teens, he's not fulfilled that promise, not
yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' attack returned not because of his work, but
because, desperate as the minutes ticked away, they finally threw
all they had into going forward. It led to some fine chances --- a
David Regis volley hit a crossbar, and Iranian goalkeeper Ahmad
Abedzadeh made a point-blank stop of Hejduk --- then exacted a
heavy price. Mahdavikia took advantage of space in U.S. territory,
racing in to latch onto an Ali Daei through ball and bear down on
Keller in the 84th minute. His shot glanced off Keller's fingertips
en route to the lower-right corner.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, Daei nearly made it 3-0 --- Keller stopped
one shot, and Regis knocked another off the goal line --- before
McBride's goal a minute after that.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Yanks joined Saudi Arabia, South Korea, Jamaica and
Japan on the boat home with one match, Thursday against Yugoslavia,
still to go. Whether that game will bring an end to Sampson's reign
remains to be seen. He was asked afterward if he intended to
resign, given his team's failure in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step down? Voluntarily?'' he replied. ``You've got to be
kidding. I couldn't have done anything better tonight. Our team was
prepared well, the team played well. They just couldn't finish
their chances. There's nothing --- not one thing --- that I
would've done differently.''
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't have, for instance, brought on Wynalda, the
Americans' all-time scoring leader, when a goal was sorely needed.
Several players questioned that decision --- ``You need someone to
score goals, and he's somebody who can score them for you,'' Keller
said --- but Wynalda was mum.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians, whose celebrations Reyna had watched when the
final whistle blew, weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the greatest game we've ever played,'' said
Mahdavikia. ``Our people were expecting us to win this game, and we
gave it to them. I'm sure they're very happy. I'm sure they're
celebrating. I wish you could go to Teheran and see what's
happening over there right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
