<HEADER>
A9839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEYRITZ-BO     06-22 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEYRITZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ GETS HIS WISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Jim Leyritz is out as the Red Sox'
righthanded designated hitter, former Dodger Billy Ashley is in,
and three members of the San Diego Padres, none of whom are at the
top of anybody's wish list, are headed East as a result of the
trade finalized Sunday by Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz and a minor league outfielder, Ethan Faggett, were
traded to the Padres for two pitchers, middle reliever Carlos Reyes
and relief prospect Dario Veras, both righthanders, and
switch-hitting minor league catcher Mandy Romero.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, who was the only Red Sox position player with a World
Series ring, said Sunday night he thinks the club may come to
regret the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not show up now,'' Leyritz said, ``but somewhere down
the line, they're going to miss me being there. When it comes down
to crunch time, hopefully those kids will come through for them. I
know I would have. I've been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of their catchers goes down, who's going to catch for
them? Billy Ashley? Mandy Romero?''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7-inch Ashley, a prodigious power hitter in the minor
leagues who failed several trials of varying lengths with the
Dodgers, was batting .297 with 10 home runs and 45 RBIs in 50 games
with Triple A Pawtucket. Ashley, 27, is expected to be in uniform
for Monday night's game with the Phillies at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes, whose arrival date is not yet known, will join the big
league club, while Veras and Romero will go to Pawtucket. When
Reyes arrives, the Red Sox almost certainly will send rookie Brian
Barkley back to Pawtucket, leaving Ron Mahay as the only lefty in
the Red Sox bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Ashley is a young slugger with outstanding power, the
kind of light-tower power fans like to see at Fenway Park,''
Duquette said. ``Billy Ashley is a competent major league player,
and we now have 25 guys going in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked Leyritz's bat on our ballclub, but we also like the
other combination of younger players we have in Ashley, Veras,
Reyes, and Mandy Romero.''
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy at his limited role with the club, Leyritz had asked to
be traded after Duquette refused to pick up his $1.9 million
contract option for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading Leyritz,'' Duquette said, ``reinforces the team
concept and commitment every player makes to the other players on
the roster ... To have good chemistry, everybody has to make a
sacrifice to be a part of the team ... Jim Leyritz was not
satisfied with his role on this team. We thought it best for the
ballclub, with the season it has going, to make a change that
allows him to pursue his goals with another ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, who drove home to Fort Lauderdale after Sunday's game
and plans to join the Padres in time for their game Monday night in
Seattle, vigorously took exception to Duquette's implication that
he was not a team player. Manager Jimy Williams told him Sunday,
Leyritz said, that he didn't want to lose him, as did veterans Mo
Vaughn, John Valentin, and Jim Corsi in the last several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you personally that Jimy Williams spoke to me this
afternoon and said, `I didn't want the trade to be done, I really
don't want to lose you. I know you how feel but I didn't want to
lose you,''' Leyritz said. ``John Valentin told me that he hated me
when he played against me and didn't think he'd like to play with
me, but that I was a great guy and didn't want me to leave. Until
the last three days, I never knew how much these guys liked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz charged that the trade would never have happened if
Duquette had honored the pledge he made to Leyritz last November,
when he acquired the 34-year-old veteran and outfielder Damon
Buford from the Texas Rangers for pitchers Aaron Sele and Mark
Brandenburg and catcher Bill Haselman.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Leyritz said, Duquette told him that the Red Sox
planned to use him to catch between 80 and 90 games, as well as use
him as a righthanded DH and to give occasional breathers to
Valentin at third and Vaughn at first. But Leyritz was told at the
end of spring training that he would not be in the catching mix,
was behind the plate for just one game this season, and never
played another position in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dan can look somebody in the face _ and I know he can,
because he lies right through people _ and say that he traded Aaron
Sele for a close-to-$2 million catcher/utilityman who would never
play in the field for two months, then he's a bigger man than me,''
Leyritz said. ``Also a huge liar.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't trade Aaron Sele and Bill Haselman for a platoon
outfielder (Buford) and a platoon DH. That doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is Dan made a commitment to me that he didn't
communicate to his manager. And now he's trying to smear me. I
think Dan knows he made a mistake. Whether he's willing to admit
it, I don't know. If I were in his position, I wouldn't admit it,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said Sunday night, ``in fairness to Leyritz,'' that he
had expectations of a more expanded role until rookie Jason Varitek
wrested the catching job away from him in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   While several Sox players privately questioned the wisdom of
giving up a veteran righthanded bat when the team is already short
in that area, Duquette claimed that Ashley can fill Leyritz's role,
citing Ashley's slugging percentage and on-base average against
lefthanded pitchers that virtually mirror Leyritz's.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, who did not play Sunday, batted .287 in 52 games with
the Red Sox. With eight home runs, he was tied for fourth on the
club with Valentin, and he drove in 24 runs. He became an instant
fan favorite on the team's first weekend at home, when he hit three
home runs in two days against the Mariners, including a game-tying
homer in the bottom of the ninth, then eight days later hit a home
run in the bottom of the ninth to tie a game against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He finished April with a .346 average and five home runs, but
hit just three homer thereafter, the last on May 28. After a
three-hit game in Kansas City May 8, Leyritz batted just .215 in
his last 23 games and drove in just nine runs as his playing time
dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, meanwhile, has been the team's hottest hitter in
June, batting .400 (16 for 40) in 13 games, including Sunday's 0
for 5.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz said he would have accepted his reduced role if Duquette
had picked up his option. ``Pick up the option, call it a wash,''
Leyritz said. ``But they didn't even consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was traded to the Padres, who are in first place in
the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was I traded for?'' Leyritz said. ``Ask Dan Duquette this:
Is he trying to win a World Series, or is he trying to win in the
future?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
