<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9844 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-USFANS-BOS &LR;      06-22 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS NOT AN ISSUE FOR US FANS 
</HEADLINE>
 FANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Hostage situations, Great Satans, fatwahs, and
negative stereotypes were forgotten when hundreds of Iranian and US
supporters converged in what became a spontaneous celebration in
Place Bellecour in the city's center just after noon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There was little antagonism between the groups, mostly friendly
bantering. One American with his face painted red, white, and blue
and holding the flags of both countries, posed for pictures with
equally exuberant Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   Afsaneh, a 33-year-old architect who would not divulge her last
name, displayed a handmade, heart-shaped sign with stars and
stripes on one half and Iran's green, white, and red on the other.
Afsaneh said she resided in the US and England after leaving Iran
in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Iran and the people of the US are not against
each other,'' she said. ``This war was between the politicians.
Iranian people don't hate Americans and, from living in the US, I
found that nobody in America hates Iranians. The people of the two
countries should love each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Iranians were ex-patriates, like Afsaneh. Some
sympathized with the National Council of Resistance of Iran, which
complained that the French government denied visas to prominent
exiles such as Moslem Eskandra Filabi, a super heavyweight wrestler
who competed in the Olympic Games, or Bahram Mavedat and Hassan
Nayeb-Agha, members of Iran's team in the 1978 World Cup in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The National Council of Resistance of Iran planned to protest
against the Iranian government by supplying the traditional ``lion
and sun'' flag instead of a flag with the symbol for Allah.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of factions, Royalists, Islamists, others, but
today we are supporting Iran together,'' said Hamid, 38, a
financial analyst residing in Chartres. ``We are here for the
sport, to support the team and not the regime. But choosing the
flag could divide Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the game is a tie, because otherwise the regime could
use it to justify what they have done. A tie means that freedom and
democracy win. The US and Iran are drawing closer together
economically. The current regime realizes that the fanaticism
cannot work over a long period. Things must change in Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Stade Gerland, there was a large group of Americans,
attracted by a brew pub. Members of Sam's Army, the US supporters
group, have set up headquarters at Ninkasi, named after the
Somalian goddess of beer, according to owner Christophe Fargier.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the images of Iranians have held up,'' said Jason
Wharton, a soccer coach from Abilene, Texas. ``We were told the
Iranians were crazy, bloodthirsty people. But when they played
Yugoslavia they showed they were great sportsmen, always helping up
the other team. I think they should win the FIFA Fair Play award
for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US is going to do well in this game. This is a lucky day
for the US. We were lucky Germany came back to tie Yugoslavia.
America is a lucky country and good things happen to us. I've
always thought that if America was ever going to win the World Cup,
we would have to get lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's 2-1 loss eliminated the US from Cup contention,
Wharton may have a different opinion of his country's luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
