<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCLAUGHLIN LEARNING ON JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Sometimes the other players on the New
England Revolution call him Tom or Tommy. At other times, he's
referred to by his last name, McLaughlin. And then there are the
occasions when teammates hail him simply by calling out the name of
the college from which he recently graduated, Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McLaughlin is a rare Major League Soccer player, the only
Harvard graduate in the league. The forward was Ivy League player
of the year last season.
</P>
<P>
   Though teammates don't ask him much about Ivy soccer, said
McLaughlin, ``there's always a mystique about Harvard, though.
Really, it's not all that different than some other colleges _ the
difference is that Harvard gets more hype than others as the best
institution. It was a great feeling picking up my diploma from the
place, though.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, an economics major, graduated cum laude on the
strength of his performance in the final two exams of his college
career.
</P>
<P>
   More recently came another examination, this on the field for
the Revolution against Columbus May 22. It was the first game in
which he dressed, and McLaughlin played 22 minutes. He remembers
everything about that game _ from being told by coach Thomas Rongen
to warm up to go in the game, to being told by the coach to move
the ball forward and become the Revolution's No. 3 offensive
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the words, definitely not,'' McLaughlin
said. ``He told me to make things happen. He told me to push the
ball forward. As I recall, I did want to have a shot early, but I
wasn't quite sure what game I'd get in.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin played well and even scored a goal _ or so he
thought. The ball went in after McLaughlin redirected a corner
kick, but McLaughlin was whistled for a foul for obstructing the
Columbus goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were watching the game footage before a practice,
Coach Rongen showed the play and he said that home teams aren't
supposed to get calls like that, not have them go against them at
least,'' said McLaughlin, who despite having a goal called back
still showed a videotape of the play to his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a case of the officials trying to protect the
goalkeeper. I was shielding the goalkeeper, something I like to do,
and when the ball came in, it hit my shin and went in. It seemed
the goalie was pulling me down from behind as I was facing Jesse
(Van Sawn), who put the corner kick into play. I tried to hit it
with my foot, but I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Had McLaughlin's goal counted, it would have cut Columbus's 2-0
lead in half. Instead, it was just another near miss in a difficult
season for the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin has found the pace of play in MLS to be far quicker
than the college game. ``The ball is on one side of the field and
the next thing you know it's on the other, so you have to be able
to anticipate play,'' he said. ``And the game is a lot more
physical than college ball, where I was a physical player. In that
game against Columbus, I was tossed around by one guy. There's so
much bumping and pushing, I don't know what a foul is anymore. So
I'm trying to adapt to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The kid from Harvard is still learning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
