<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-STEWART-BO     06-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAND WAS KICKED ON STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-STEWART-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Olympic Club is on the edge of the Pacific
Ocean's line of low clouds and fog and the result is this part of
The City alternates between too warm or too chilly. By the minute.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that when Payne Stewart stepped to the 10th tee Sunday
afternoon, the weather _ which had been too warm _ suddenly turned
chilly. And perhaps it was only a coincidence that on that hole,
Stewart looked at the leaderboard ``and that was the first time I
took notice of what was happening,'' and Stewart saw that his golf
fortunes suddenly were chilly, too, while that guy a few holes away
_ Lee Janzen _ was warm.
</P>
<P>
   The weather and Stewart kept getting chillier, even though
Stewart was able to scramble for pars on both the 10th and 11th.
This was no way to win a US Open _ backing into it _ and Stewart
had meandered around the front nine, surrendering two strokes to
par, and soon he would pay the price for dallying.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart hit a solid drive down the right side of the 12th hole
``and I was walking down the fairway and I saw it was in a sand
divot.'' Hmmm ... more than a few earlier Stewart drives of this
Open had landed off course ``and I had gotten good lies in the
rough but now I had a bad lie in the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was here that the US Open title, which Stewart seemingly
was attempting to coddle rather than seize, slipped from his grasp.
Different courses attempt to repair fairway divots in various ways,
and the United States Golf Association does it by filling the
divots with sand. But the problem, said Stewart, ``is you don't
know how deep the sand is in the divot.''
</P>
<P>
   So Stewart was in a quandary. His ball had landed ``in three or
four'' sand divots at various stops on the PGA Tour this year, but
now the Open was riding on how he would handle this latest strange
twist of irony, his ball landing cleanly on the fairway but resting
on sand. ``I told myself,'' said Stewart, ```Well, it's a divot.
You have to deal with it. You have to take the good with the
bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart reached for a club, thought some more, and went with a
9-iron in place of his original choice, a pitching wedge. He
clearly was unsure of what to do. His swing _ a half-go with that
9-iron _ looked weak and the result was even weaker, a plop of the
ball into the bunker guarding the right front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, USGA rules official Tom Meeks informed Stewart that
his play had been too slow, and ``Meeks said to me, `You just got a
bad time,''' said Stewart, which is a warning for slow play.
Stewart asked Meeks what would happen if he got another bad time,
and ``He told me it'd be a one-stroke penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this, including Stewart missing a 7-footer for par after
blasting out of the bunker, ``sat well with me,'' he said. ``Here I
am, trying to figure out what to do with this sand divot, and what
kind of shot to play, and after I played it into the bunker, he
gives me the bad time.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise then that Stewart's next shot, a 5-iron off the tee
to the 186-yard 13th hole, seemed perfectly stroked ``but it rolled
through the green and into the back rough.'' Stewart's adrenaline
was flowing at the divot on 12, Meeks's warning, and how suddenly
the five-stroke lead he once enjoyed had vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also bogeyed the 13th and even a birdie on 14 could not
slow the momentum of this Open slipping away. He found a front
bunker on the 609-yard 16th, taking another bogey, and even an
impressive par on the monstrous 468-yard par-4 17th gave no hint
that Stewart was capable of making up the one shot that would
enable him to tie Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's second shot on the final hole left him 25 feet above
the cup. The putt may have seemed makeable on television but not to
any who had been around the 18th green all day. ``Nobody's made
this putt,'' said one fan. ``They've all been left,'' said another.
``I know, I've been here 11 hours.'' Stewart's putt, while firm,
was also left and never threatened the cup.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Payne Stewart said he was sure he would sleep well
last night, just as he was sure that The Olympic Club itself ``won
this Open, since only one golfer out there was able to equal par.''
Late afternoon was coming. The Pacific air now seemed very chilly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
