<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9859 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LOUDONCLASSIC-BOS     06-22 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOUDON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YATES LAST ONE STANDING AT NHIS 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Aaron Yates couldn't believe his eyes. Or his
luck.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Honda rider Ben Bostrom and Suzuki rider Mat
Mladin make a broken-field runaway in the first nine laps of
Sunday's American Motorcycle Association Superbike Tour race, Yates
survived a battle of attrition among the leaders by winning the
39-lap featured event of the 75th Loudon Classic at New Hampshire
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In winning his first Superbike Tour event of the season, and his
first since a victory at Sears Point Raceway two years ago, Yates
capped a calamitous weekend that saw Miguel Duhamel, the AMA
Superbike series points leader, suffer a season-ending double
compound fracture of his left femur during Friday's qualifying
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys who went out in front, they sure made it
easy,'' said Yates, 24, of Milledgeville, Ga., who pocketed a
$10,500 check for the Superbike triumph and finished runner-up to
Doug Chandler in the Pro Honda Oils 600cc Supersport race Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   After he rode his Suzuki for the first nine laps in fourth
place, Yates capitalized on a ruinous turn of events sparked when
Bostrom wiped out on a sweeping, uphill curve in Turn 6 to drop out
of the lead on Lap 9. Bostrom picked up his Honda from the gravelly
runoff area, dusted it off, and reentered the fray to finish
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what initiated it,'' Yates said, when asked about
Bostrom's wipeout. ``But it looked like he was in front of Mat and
must have lost the throttle or something. He stood it up and kind
of went straight off in the middle of the turn into the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   One lap later, Mladin surrendered the lead he had inherited from
Bostrom to runner-up Jamie Hacking when his Suzuki seized. Mladin
rolled it to a stop at the top of the hill just past Turn 8, got
off, and flung it to the ground in disgust. He finished last and
departed the track without comment.
</P>
<P>
   So when Bostrom crashed and fell back to 18th, and Mladin
declared no mas and dropped out along with Thomas Kipp, who crashed
in Turn 2 while running in third place on the same lap Mladin
parked it, Yates realized it was time to stop spectating and start
riding hard.
</P>
<P>
   He did precisely that and wrested the lead from Hacking on Lap
11 to lead the final 29 laps. On each go-round, ``I counted down
the laps and counted up the money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ben had his little thing there, I kind of figured he was
pushing pretty hard there,'' said Yates. ``And then when I saw Mat
coast off the ace, I was like, `Wow, thanks a lot.' They really
handed it to me. I just thought they made it a good day for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian Anthony Gobert had a similar feeling when he came
around for the final lap and was startled by the sight of Chandler,
who had been running third at the time, picking his bike up off the
grassy runoff area near Turn 1. Gobert, as a result, wound up third
and pulled within two points (251-249) of Chandler, who departed
NHIS after a tumultuous weekend as the new Superbike Tour points
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Miguel going out, that opens it up quite a bit because he
was dominating the last couple of races,'' said Yates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'd say this weekend's been ... pretty different.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as far as Aaron Yates was concerned, it was pretty
fortuitous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 0159EDT &QL; 
