<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FIRE RUSSELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Bill Russell, who became the Los Angeles Dodgers'
manager after the 42-year run of Walter Alston and Tom Lasorda, is
out after less than two seasons, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, 49, was fired Sunday after the Dodgers suffered another
loss to the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field, ending 32 years as a
player, coach and manager with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Russell becomes the first Dodgers manager to lose his job since
Charlie Dressen in 1954. He is the first to be fired during the
season since Leo Durocher in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Under Russell this season, the Dodgers struggled, going 36-38
after many projected they would win the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   They were involved in a blockbuster trade on May 15 that sent
catcher Mike Piazza to Florida and sustained several critical
injuries, including top pitcher Ramon Martinez, who is lost for the
season with a torn muscle in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell's firing, which had been rumored since spring
training, happened as the team flew home from a disappointing 2-4
road trip. It included a two-game sweep by the division-leading San
Diego Padres, who lead the Dodgers by 12{ games, the club's largest
deficit in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Russell was in the final season of a two-year $700,000 contract.
Lasorda's name has surfaced as a candidate to replace Russell, but
he denied that Sunday night from his home in Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   Russell took over the club on July 29, 1996, when Lasorda
stepped down with a heart condition. The Dodgers made the playoffs
as a wild card team, but lost in three games to the Atlanta Braves.
The Dodgers have not had a post-season victory since 1988, when
they won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers missed the playoffs last season despite a
late-season charge against division champion San Francisco. Russell
was criticized for several tactical errors during a September
series with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He also was viewed as a bad fit after the team was sold last
March from the conservative O'Malley family to Rupert Murdoch's
flamboyant Fox Group.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who joined the organization in 1966, was built more in
the low-key mold of Alston, who managed the club from 1955-76. But
his first manager in the minor leagues was Lasorda, who helped him
make the transition from the outfield to shortstop, where he played
for 18 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The two were close through Lasorda's 20 years as manager,
together winning four pennants and a World Series. But the
relationship became strained when Russell took over as manager.
</P>
<P>
   The players had become tired of Lasorda's over-the-top style and
welcomed Russell's approach. Russell, however, was not allowed to
choose his own coaching staff, which is common in managerial
changes.
</P>
<P>
   And with pending sale to Fox clouding off-season acquisitions,
Russell also was not given the top relief pitcher that was lacking
during the final months of last season. O'Malley, who sold the team
for $311million, wanted to keep the payroll as trim as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a strong showing in spring training, the Dodgers
continued to underachieve under new management, and a shake-up was
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The firing is believed to be another step in an overhaul of the
organization by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The trade of Piazza and third baseman Todd Zeile for outfielder
Gary Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, catcher Charles Johnson and
outfielder Jim Eisenreich was staggering for fans who watched
Piazza have the best five seasons by a catcher in major league
history.
</P>
<P>
   But it also raised the team's payroll from $47million to
$58million. Piazza was seeking a seven-year, $105million contract
and was eligible for free agency at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations stalled in April. Fox feared Piazza would leave
without compensation and made the trade. Since the May 15 trade,
the Dodgers are 15-16 entering a four-game stretch with the Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
