<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODERBUND-BID-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEARNING COMPANY MAKES BID FOR BRODERBUND 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FOST  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
The Learning Co. made a $419 million bid yesterday to acquire
Novato-based Broderbund Software, sources said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Broderbund's board of directors met yesterday to decide whether
to accept the offer, the sources said. The board's decision was not
known last night, and spokespeople for both companies refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the deal would create a software powerhouse.
Broderbund is one of the pioneers of educational multimedia
software, and its computer games Myst and Riven are among the
best-selling titles of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co., based in Cambridge, Mass., has roots in
Fremont, and it maintains an office there. It is locked in a fierce
battle with Cendant Corp. for dominance in the educational software
market, and it has voraciously acquired smaller software firms,
including Novato-based Mindscape in March and San Francisco-based
PF.Magic in May. Earlier this month, it acquired Sofsource, a
publisher of educational and test software, for about $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   The price of $20 a share is 21 percent above Broderbund's Friday
closing price of $16.50. The Learning Co. stock closed at $25
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the deal is expected to close by August 31.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund strongly hinted last week that it was up for sale.
Rumors that Hasbro was considering buying the company sent
Broderbund's stock up 30 percent over two weeks, and Broderbund
announced that it had hired Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to
``explore strategic alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Broderbund also announced that its earnings for the
third quarter would fall short of analysts' expectations. It
forecast a loss of 12 to 15 cents per share, or $2.5 million to
$3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since last September, Broderbund has eliminated 135 positions,
all in the Bay Area. It currently employs 1,100 people, 320 of whom
are in Novato.
</P>
<P>
   Although sources said no immediate layoffs would be announced,
many of Broderbund's products overlap with The Learning Co.'s
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund's The Print Shop competes with Mindscape's
Printmaster, and the two companies also have competing genealogy
products.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Rodoni, Broderbund group vice president who oversaw the
education, productivity and genealogy business units, would leave
the company, according to sources. Rodoni, who joined Broderbund
when it acquired Banner Blue of Fremont, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Broderbund's educational titles, including the popular
Carmen Sandiego series and its Living Books division's Dr. Seuss
software, make it a logical choice for a merger with The Learning
Co., according to John Girton of Larkspur-based Girton Capital
Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education-wise, there's a nice fit,'' Girton said.
</P>
<P>
   When The Learning Co. acquired Mindscape, company President
Kevin O'Leary declared, ``Our strategy is to be the No. 1 consumer
software company, period.'' With that acquisition, The Learning Co.
became No. 2 in number of software packages sold through stores,
second only to Cendant.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co. _ which employs about 260 workers in Fremont
and Redwood City _ faltered last year, laying off about 50
employees and paring back its product line. Since that time, the
firm has trimmed its debt and gone on a buying binge. In 1997, The
Learning Co. recorded a loss of $475,000 on sales of $392.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund lost $13 million on sales of $192 million last year.
Girton said the company should register close to $300 million in
sales this year, and he noted that it holds $137 million in cash
and short-term investments, which would be substantial assets for a
debt-heavy company like The Learning Co.
</P>
<P>
   Once a high-flyer, Broderbund has struggled in recent years as
the consumer software market grew increasingly cutthroat. During a
period of furious consolidation, Broderbund was the last well-known
maker of consumer software to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co., then based in Fremont, was bought by
Massachusetts-based Softkey in 1995, and the combined company took
the name of the acquired firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
