<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GAMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKE-UP FOLLOWS ANOTHER DODGERS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Dodgers' voyage of the damned ended Sunday with the
club throwing manager Bill Russell and general manager Fred Claire
off the plane at 35,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Russell became the first Dodgers manager fired during the season
since Leo Durocher in 1948, just hours after the team's road trip
ended with an 11-6 loss to the Colorado Rockies. Glenn Hoffman, the
manager at Triple-A Albuquerque, will replace Russell on an interim
basis. Claire, the team's GM since 1987, will be replaced by Tom
Lasorda, also on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who became a club vice president in July 1996 when
retiring as manager after 20 years, was with the Dodgers Class-A
team in Yakima, Wash. on Saturday night. He was scheduled to fly to
Boston on Sunday but returned home after learning of the death of
close friend and former Dodgers general manager Al Campanis.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda drove to Dodger Stadium late Sunday night and was
offered the interim GM's job by former owner Peter O'Malley and new
team president Bob Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's last game, played in front of 48,186 at Coors Field,
dropped the Dodgers 12{ games behind first-place San Diego and
reflected the kind of spell they have been under all season.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that included the loss of shortstop Jose Vizcaino,
whose seriously sprained right ankle made him the sixth front-line
member of the club to be injured this season. Eric Karros hit two
more homers and Chan Ho Park pitched the worst game of his young
career.
</P>
<P>
   Park (5-5), the Dodgers top pitcher a year ago, allowed 10 runs
in just 51/3 innings, including a three-run homer and two-run
single by Dante Bichette. In his last two starts, Park is 0-2 and
has given up 10 runs in 111/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I can say, he was terrible,'' the usually
placid pitching coach Goose Gregson said. ``From the first inning
on he did not make the pitches he needed to make. He was not
throwing hard. He has never really faced adversity before now, but
he's facing it now and he's not doing well at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Park acknowledged he pitched timidly, trying not to walk batters
instead of challenging them with his 95 mph fastball. Sunday he was
rarely clocked at 90.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad day,'' Park said. ``And it was not a good
day to have one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers already had third baseman Bobby Bonilla in the
hospital, where he is being treated for an intestinal infection. He
was placed on the 15-day disabled list Saturday and will remain
here overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Vizcaino, who was holding together an infield of
third baseman Paul Konerko and second baseman Juan Castro in the
absence of Bonilla and Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   He singled to left with one out in the third but turned his
ankle attempting to steal second. He was carried off on a golf
cart. Vizcaino was taken to the same hospital as Bonilla. Trainer
Charlie Strasser, who remained overnight in Denver, visited Bonilla
while Vizcaino was being examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole scene was just too weird,'' Strasser said. ``I don't
think I've ever seen anything quite like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his 21 years with the organization, it is unlikely
Strasser has seen many worse-looking ankles than Vizcaino's. The
doctors said he will be out three to five days, but Vizcaino said,
``It's going to be a long time. That is the most pain I have ever
felt.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bright spots were the two homers by Eric Karros had in
left-hander Bobby Jones' (2-2) first career complete game. Karros,
often critical of the softball atmosphere here, had four homers and
13 RBI in the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't sound like he likes Coors Field,'' Rockies manager
Don Baylor said. ``But it sure likes him.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros was too preoccupied with his faltering team to care very
much about the homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the last two games after winning the first two,'' he
said. ``That isn't the way it is supposed to work. It must be very
hard for Billy to put up with this with all the other stuff that is
going on. I feel for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
