 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2457 - JUNE 22, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. OUT OF JAIL, CHINA'S WEI JINGSHENG HAS A TOUGH AGENDA By
Philip Caputo, from The New York Times Magazine
</P>
<P>
   HIs arrival in the United States raised hopes that he would
unify the Chinese dissidents and press the case for human rights.
Now, as President Clinton heads for China, Wei Jingsheng, while
still revered, is finding out what a tough agenda that is. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------2. CLINTON'S APPOINTMENT WITH BEIJING IS A
MISTAKE By Robert Kagan &AMP; William Kristol, from The New York Times
Op-Eds
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has argued that once the U.S. stopped
challenging China's human-rights record and withdrew the threat of
economic sanctions, China would ease repression at home. In fact,
the Chinese government has responded by exiling a couple of
prominent dissidents and arresting many others - in sum, by
maintaining one of the world's most repressive regimes. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------3. PRISONER IN KOSOVO By Peter Lippman, from
The Progressive
</P>
<P>
   In March, Peter Lippman became a prisoner in Kosovo, along with
a group of activists from Peaceworkers, a California-based
organization that monitors human-rights abuses and promotes
nonviolent conflict resolution. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------4. REVIVE THE DRIVE AGAINST NUCLEAR WEAPONS
NOW By David Andrews &AMP; Lena Hjelm-Wallen - an Op-Ed from The
International Herald Tribune After a decade of great promise in the
field of nuclear disarmament and nonproliferation, the specter of
nuclear weapons is again at the center of attention. The nuclear
disarmament process now urgently needs a new and forceful impetus. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------5. HONG KONG'S YEAR ONE UNDER BEIJING'S THUMB
from Der Spiegel Magazine (English translation)
</P>
<P>
   In subtle and insidious ways, the Beijing overseers are changing
the face of what was one of the world's most dynamic capitalist
economies. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------6. WHAT'S DOING IN ASPEN By James Brooke,
from The New York Times Way to Go
</P>
<P>
   Coloradans sometimes feel they need a visa to visit Aspen. But
behind the intimidating buzz of celebrities and high prices, Aspen
is a magical town where the beauty of the Elk Mountains combines
with an ever more stimulating cultural life. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------7. ALGERIAN SECURITY SERVICES MAY HAVE BEEN
INVOLVED IN THE TIBEHIRINE TRAGEDY By Henri Tincq from Le Monde
</P>
<P>
   In May 1996, seven French trappist monks were murdered in
Algeria, two months later, the bishop of Oran, Mgr. Pierre
Claverie, died in a bomb attack. New and disturbing evidence
suggests that the Armed Islamic Group, blamed at the time for the
killings, may not have been solely responsible. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------8. CRUISE CENTRAL By Everett Potter from the
New York Times Way to Go It's full steam ahead in the cruise
business. While some industry pundits point to the film `` Titanic
`` as an ironic booster of sales, that's open to debate. But
icebergs or not, the fact is that travel agents and cruise-only
agents report record bookings, sold-out sailings and inquiries many
months in advance of embarkation.
</P>
</TEXT>
