<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 21, moved Saturday in the `a' category and are
repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-ASIA-REVIEW _ No one then could imagine the kind of crisis
Asia faces today: economic meltdown. And if you listen closely to
the oratory of Washington before the most important foreign trip of
Bill Clinton's presidency, to China, things sound very different.
On Tuesday Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin took to the podium of
the White House to declare that ``China has been an island of
stability in Asia'' _ a savvy, responsible player in the global
effort to tamp out the economic firestorm that started in Asia a
year ago. And Japan? The view from Washington these days is that it
is spreading the bubonic plague of the markets _ wild instability _
and yet refuses to clean up its act. By David E. Sanger. WITH
GRAPHIC. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-REVIEW _ These days, it seems people are trying to be
all they can and must be at the office, as the workplace has become
an increasingly popular but elusive spot to look for meaning and
fulfillment in life. It's fine to take the road less traveled, as
long as it means finding a less-congested route to get to the
office earlier. By Adam Bryant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-DEATH-REVIEW _ Eight months have passed since the Princess
of Wales died in what the French authorities have called a
straightforward car crash. But their flat assertions that it was
merely an accident have only encouraged theorists, who are still
busily inventing wacky stories. By Sarah Lyall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ENTOURAGE-REVIEW _ The horde accompanying President
Clinton to China this week will number more than 1,000 people. The
presidential entourage and its paraphernalia fill four passenger
planes and several large C-141 military transports. But why? By
John Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL-REVIEW _ A rush is on to exploit what could prove to
be the world's richest oil bonanza. The Caspian is a
California-size body of saltwater _ the world's largest landlocked
body of water _ that may sit on as much as 200 billion barrels and
16 percent of the Earth's potential oil reserves. Even at today's
low prices, that could add up to $3 trillion in oil. But it is it a
sea or a lake? The answer will determine what countries can exploit
the reserves. By Elaine Sciolino. WITH GRAPHIC MAP. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-PHONES-REVIEW _ The dream of an African renaissance is
all the rage these days on the continent, but without better
telecommunications it will be as hard to spread wealth and
democracy as it would have been for Florence and Chartres to spread
Renaissance culture without the old Roman roads. Only about 1 in
300 people in sub-Saharan Africa has a phone, making the financial
opportunities huge. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-WATCHDOG-REVIEW _ Midway through a news story about Steven
Brill's arrival as the newest major-domo in the booming industry of
media criticism, Howard Kurtz, a respected practitioner himself for
The Washington Post, suddenly found it necessary to open
parentheses confessionally in noting: ``The founder of Brill's
Content (to which this reporter is to be an occasional contributor)
could not be reached for comment.'' It was a moment of comic relief
badly needed by the Fourth Estate, run ragged these past five
months in its coverage of the allegations of sex and mendacity at
the Clinton White House. Here was the media watchdog watch turning
into a shimmering house of mirrors, with one watchdog sniffing out
the latest watchdog while properly noting the crisscross of
commercial interests at work in all the watching. By Francis X.
Clines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COP-SUICIDE-REVIEW _ It happens dozens of times each year during
jittery hostage dramas and routine traffic stops: desperate people
lure police officers into shooting them in a phenomenon that has
come to be known in law-enforcement circles as suicide by cop.
There are no hard statistics showing the frequency of such
incidents, but experts estimate that up to 10 percent of the
roughly 600 fatal police shootings that occur in an average year
are caused by people actively seeking to die. By Alan Feuer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-REVIEW _ Republicans can usually win when they can
position themselves as the guardians of low taxes and small
government. By the same token, Democrats have the advantage when
they can frame an issue as one involving the protection of
children. The tobacco bill, the most ambitious measure before
Congress this year, lay across that political fault line. By David
E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-REVIEW (Washington) _ Is China friend or foe? And
should it or should it not benefit from U.S. technology? The United
States is pulled both ways. A llok at how Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, a
conservative Republican from a southern California district with
lots of high-technology industry, has changed his position.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ How big is golf? It is 24-hour
cable-TV-channel big. To put the very existence of the Golf Channel
into perspective, consider that there is no Football Channel, no
Basketball Channel, no Baseball Channel. The Golf Channel says
something uniquely profound about our culture. Here, on the
occasion of the U.S. Open, the first day of summer and Father's
Day, are gleanings from a single day's programming.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
</TEXT>
