<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Violating a journalistic trust
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, June 24, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been in this business more than 47 years and have never
lied in print. I've made mistakes, plenty of them, but I've never
lied. Neither have most of the people in this business of the daily
printed word.
</P>
<P>
   Have all the direct quotes I've used over the years been exact?
No. Have they all been in context? Yes. Sometimes I couldn't read
part of my scribbly notes but I made certain I got the gist of the
direct quote. Sometimes I paraphrased, leaving out the quote marks,
but at other times, when I knew the quote was close to being
totally accurate, I put them within the quote marks.
</P>
<P>
   Have all the people I've written about and quoted been real
people? How could there be any other way? I couldn't conceive of
inventing a person for a news story or column, unless it was
identified in print as a hypothetical person.
</P>
<P>
   Over all these years, I've misspelled names and places, and
gotten dates wrong, even matched the wrong person with an event.
And made some bad decisions. But never intentionally. Neither have
any of the people I've worked with.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes to mind because of Patricia Smith, the Boston
Globe columnist and Pulitzer Prize finalist, who was exposed
recently as fabricating quotes, people and events, and forced to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Her journalistic lies reinforce the stereotype of newspaper
reporters who often are criticized of ``writing that just to sell
newspapers.'' Reporters can be accused of writing to look good, but
to sell newspapers? Other than the folks in the financial news
department, newspaper reporters have no idea of economics.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other field, the reputation of the newspaper person is
evaluated by its weakest link. Politics are rated by the bad
politicians, and thus newspaper people are rated by the few liars
and plagiarists.
</P>
<P>
   During my tenure as a newsroom executive, I ran into some
strange people in this business. I once had a reporter who believed
anything was quotable, as long as it was said by someone. He never
made up the quotes or people, just allowed their reckless
statements to get into his story without concern whether or not the
allegation was legitimate. We parted ways.
</P>
<P>
   One of the claims against Smith, whose saccharic mea culpa was
printed in the Boston Globe and other newspapers, was that she
reviewed an Elton John concert in 1986 for the Chicago Sun-Times
without ever attending the concert. That rang a bell with me.
</P>
<P>
   There was once a TV editor at our newspaper, well before I
became an executive there, who reviewed a new TV show most harshly.
When the managing editor, who saw the show _ and liked it _ called
him in to debate the acrid reviews, it was discovered that the
writer's TV set was on the fritz and he never saw the show he
condemned, contending that he knew anyway that it would be bad.
</P>
<P>
   There was a new TV editor quicker than you could say Red
Skelton.
</P>
<P>
   All of us in the business have to be careful of what we say, and
who we say said it. It can come back to haunt us as it did Patricia
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In a column that she wrote for the Boston Globe as recently as
April of this year, Ms. Smith excoriated Stephen Fagan, the father
who raised his daughters after lying to them that their mother had
died.
</P>
<P>
   Her column began: ``So we've established that Stephen Fagan _ he
of the forehead hugging hair, Palm Beach preening, and makeshift
social status _ is the most pathological of pathological liars.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have been, at least until it was discovered that Ms.
Smith, herself, has been at this lying game since at least 1986 and
made up quotes and people in at least four columns this year. That
she writes only two a week gives her a high percentage of lying.
</P>
<P>
   I hope she now turns to writing novels; she's well-suited for
it.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
