<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORT TAKES: Crying for Big Tobacco
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What we didn't know until the last few weeks, when Big Tobacco
started spending $40 million to instruct us, was that any effort to
put some bounds around the holocaust of smoking was just another
big-government tax-and-spend dodge. That is now Republican policy,
and it played well in the polls. What dummies we are.
</P>
<P>
   Parents used to tell their kids that smoking would stunt their
growth _ almost everything stunted your growth in those days. It
was a fuddy-duddy sort of thing to say, but it turned out to be
pretty much right.
</P>
<P>
   We know a lot of things now about smoking. Smoking can make you
sick. Smoking can kill you in highly unpleasant ways. Smoking is as
addictive as hard drugs. Smoking can track you down in the womb.
Smoking in the 20th century has manufactured premature death for
millions.
</P>
<P>
   My father was a cigar smoker. Used to walk around with an unlit
cigar in his mouth when he couldn't light up. The house reeked of
smoke. He wondered why he had an asthmatic kid. He died of cancer.
My wife's grandfather was a chain smoker, and proud of it. Died of
lung cancer. They tried to slip a pack of his beloved Lucky Strikes
in his pocket when they buried him. The rabbi wouldn't let them.
Something told him it wasn't right. Family lore does not record if
he elaborated.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
