<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: On taxes and tobacco, GOP plays with fire
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, those wacky congressional Republicans. Aren't they having
fun? Don't you wish you could be one?
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans vote to do away with the entire, complete,
whole federal tax system of the United States of America in just
five short years, and the same day Senate Republicans, as a public
health service, prove that tobacco really, really is addictive.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of the tax system is a gesture in search of a
point. Building on the 1995 triumph when they closed down the
government, House Republicans now are playing chicken with the idea
of eliminating the United States altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The majority complains the current system is hideously complex
and causes H&AMP;R Block and other social ills. Well, yes, but that's
because Congress keeps voting in little quirks to pay off favored
interests. Both parties are guilty, though over the years
Republicans have been especially creative in legislating dodges for
their business clienteles.
</P>
<P>
   In sunsetting the system, the House in effect is pleading to be
saved from itself. Congress doesn't have a clue about what to put
in the system's place, but the hard-core ideologues who ramrod the
House these days are arguing for either a flat tax or a national
sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   It really doesn't matter which. By ending the progressive income
tax that asks more of our big financial winners than of the
workaday, either would stick it to middle-income earners. To any
degree this whimsy can be taken seriously, what it's really up to
is eliminating the little loopholes in favor of a single huge one
that would make the well-off better off.
</P>
<P>
   Jolly as all that was, the Senate's tobacco dance was even more
entertaining. GOP majorities bloated the legislation with
irrelevant amendments, then their leadership killed the bill
because _ because it had been bloated with irrelevant amendments!
Thus did the tobacco lobby's kept senators avoid an honest vote.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause figures senators who voted tobacco's way averaged
$20,761 in tobacco money over the past six years, four times more
than others. And tobacco gave $16.7 million to the parties, 80
percent of it to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Awesomely, big tobacco, which has lied to us for decades, gulled
the public again, this time with TV ads claiming the legislation
was just a tax bill meant to fund more big government, and targeted
at lower-income folks to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The tax hike on cigarettes would indeed have hit the
under-$30,000 crowd heaviest, but that's where smokers are
concentrated, especially price-sensitive young smokers. And for
every 10 percent increase in prices, there's a 5 percent decline in
smokers, so the levy would have disproportionately benefited the
same group. If the industry really cared about those folks,
wouldn't it stop selling them poison?
</P>
<P>
   And those awful new federal programs? They were mainly to help
tobacco farmers move to new crops, to do independent research and
to pay for smoking illnesses _ in short, to mop up after big
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   So, the industry ducks regulation and snakes out of a legal
obligation to cut youth smoking. And their congressional playthings
will continue to be well-greased for fun. Let the good times roll.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
