<HEADER>
A0082 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-AMISH-$ADV27-0622-     06-22 1772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-AMISH-$ADV27-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEVELOPMENT THREATENS AMISH WAY OF LIFE
 &HT;    For release Saturday, June 27.
 &HT;    Photos for this story are available from the Nerw York Times
News Service.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HOLLAND, Pa. _ Eli's grandfather reckons that the Amish are
like other folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the best environment for the Plain People is the
farm,'' he explained, standing in a well-ordered woodshop near
fertile fields that his family has cultivated for six generations.
``So just like you will save and bend over backwards to send your
children to college, we will save and bend over backwards to help
our sons and daughters buy a farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Eli's grandfather _ who does not want to be
identified further because of church strictures _ and the 36,000
other Plain Sect disciples in picturesque Lancaster County is that
developers are encroaching on farmland they have tended since
William Penn welcomed their persecuted forebears nearly three
centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster is the fastest-growing county in Pennsylvania as
families move in from Philadelphia and other East Coast cities.
Instant neighborhoods have sprung up on what were once rolling
dairy pastures and carefully plowed fields of produce, corn and
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, recent years have brought bumper crops of tourists.
Motels and theme parks are now as commonplace as barns and silos,
and tour buses outnumber Amish buggies on the crowded roadways.
Land prices have skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 40 years, the county has lost more than 103,000
acres of farmland to development _ an average of about seven acres
per day. The loss is especially dramatic considering that the farms
are among the most productive in the nation and are typically less
than 100 acres in size.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of local preservationists, the World Monument Fund
last year named Lancaster County one of the world's 100 most
endangered historic sites, along with the Taj Mahal, the ruins of
Pompeii and other threatened global treasures.
</P>
<P>
   With a lifestyle historically rooted in agriculture, the Amish
are at a cultural crossroads. Four decades ago, 95 percent of the
county's Plain Sect populace worked on farms, compared to about 50
percent nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   The Plain People have adapted economically _ finding outside
jobs and nurturing their own enterprises _ but the changes are
threatening their simple and spiritual way of life, warned
Randy-Michael Testa, a Dartmouth College professor and author of
``After the Fire: The Destruction of the Lancaster County Amish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: How far can a people bend until something
snaps?'' asked Testa. Now bearded Amish men in black trousers and
straw hats and women in long dresses and white bonnets watch warily
as suburban sprawl paves over much of the good earth between
Paradise and Bird-in-Hand and Intercourse and other colorfully
named villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more and more commercial development, it creates a
conflict, if I may say so, for land use,'' said Eli's grandfather,
who believes it would be sinful to call attention to himself and,
like most Amish, does not want to be photographed or publicly
identified. ``But the commercial developers are able to pay more
for the land. That takes it out of agriculture, which doesn't suit
me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   When Amish settlers arrived in this lush valley in the early
1700s, they found a place to heed the Biblical words: ``Be ye a
people set apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 130,000 or so Old Order Amish in North America, about
20,000 live in Lancaster County. The sect and setting were
popularized in the 1985 movie ``Witness,'' starring Harrison Ford.
The county is also home to 16,000 Old Order Mennonites _ spiritual
cousins who share many of the same beliefs but are less rigorous in
their separation.
</P>
<P>
   In the 17th Century, the Amish and Mennonites were persecuted in
Europe because they were Anabaptists _ believers in voluntary adult
baptism. The Old Order sects are known as the ``Plain Folk,''
adverse to ostentation and committed to their faith, family and
community.
</P>
<P>
   The Amish are famous for their pacifism, simplicity, plain garb
and curiously selective rejection of modern technology. For
instance, they will not hook into the local electric utility _
maintaining independence from government _ but do use generators to
produce their own electric power. They won't allow phones in their
houses _ fearful of the disruption of family time _ but do have
phones in outside sheds.
</P>
<P>
   They don't buy cars and rely on horse-drawn buggies for getting
about the county, but they will ride in cars owned by outsiders,
whom the Amish call ``English.'' They farm with horse-drawn plows
and harvesters rather than with tractors and combines. Their
children can ride scooters, but not bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Amish children still attend one-room schoolhouses, with their
formal educations ending with the eighth grade at age 14. The
adults pay income and property taxes but neither contribute to nor
collect from Social Security. They don't serve in the military or
in public office. They don't participate in federal farm programs.
And they don't demonstrate against rezonings of land use or lobby
for government protection of agricultural acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their belief is very clear on this. They are not going to tell
the rest of society what to do,'' said Herman Bontrager, a local
insurance executive and leader in the preservationist movement.
``It is very important to them to maintain integrity and honesty in
their beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, local preservationists explained, the Amish would
move to other rural regions or adopt non-farm occupations rather
than engage in any sort of organized public policy ``fight'' to
save the county's farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They live their faith more than speak it,'' Bontrager said.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   From the shade of her backyard trellis, Eliza can see the nearby
farmhouse where she was born and the furrowed field where her
father grew tobacco before his death, and where her nephews now
tend this traditional cash crop. She works in a mini-mart in nearby
Ronks and thereby ``knows both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What keeps me here is a respect of the religion. It keeps you
down to earth more. You don't get swept up in the fast pace. You
appreciate what you have more. You know the blessing of the rain as
well as of the sunshine,'' she explained. ``I believe there is one
God and each of us has to find our own way to reach Him.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly outspoken for an Amish woman, she does not equate
this inner peace with willing acceptance of commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the Amish culture is going to survive somewhere,'' she
said. ``But we are blessed with good soil here and it is just not
right to pave over this land.''
</P>
<P>
   But asphalt parking lots already cover much of Lancaster County.
For many Amish families, an agrarian lifestyle is no longer an
option. Indeed, outside jobs are plentiful and ``some have found it
mighty nice to work 'til 5 o'clock and have evenings off. Farmers
work from sun 'til sun and then some,'' said Eli's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Some Amish families have yielded to the temptation of inflated
land prices and have sold out and bought farms in neighboring
counties or Kentucky, Indiana or Ohio. Others make quilts,
furniture or crafts for the tourists. Industrious and notoriously
frugal, some Amish businessmen have prospered and made theological
decisions that the Plain Life does not preclude use of cell phones
or pagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to be very optimistic about their ability to adapt
and handle pressures from the outside world,'' said Conrad Kanagy,
a sociology professor at nearby Elizabethtown College. ``Many Amish
families have essentially moved from farm to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   But the changes bring complications.
</P>
<P>
   In enforcing federal child labor laws, for instance, the Labor
Department has fined some Amish sawmills and furniture shops for
employing teen-agers in what otsiders regard as hazardous jobs. In
earlier times, these youngsters would have gone to work on their
family farms after finishing their schooling at the age of 14.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes Magazine recently reported that some Amish businesses
have become so profitable that the sect has a snowbird community of
vacation homes in Pinecraft, Fla., where wealthy Plain People
escape the cold of Lancaster County winters. Amish elders worry
about such compromises of the Ordnung _ rules of living _ that even
bans zippers as excessive conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the farm is the best place to raise a family,'' said
Eli's grandfather. Through barnyard chores, children learn
responsibility at an early age. It is the daily duty of 9-year-old
Eli, for instance, to care for calves. Extended families stay
together, building additions to farmhouses as offspring marry.
Sunday meetings are held in parlors and barns, since the Amish have
no churches.
</P>
<P>
   If Lancaster County's farmland is not preserved, the traditional
Amish way of life will fade away, predicts Testa, the Dartmouth
professor who has lived with the Plain People for his academic
studies.
</P>
<P>
   He cited an Amish parable to describe the dangers of gradual
change. ``If you drop a frog in a pot of boiling water, it will hop
out,'' he said. ``But if you put it in comfortable water and
gradually raise the temperature, the frog will stay until it is
cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Fred Daum still lives in the Lancaster County house were he was
born in 1930. During his boyhood, he would see more buggies than
cars pass by on New Holland Pike. Now, fearful for the future of
his Amish neighbors, he is an organizer for LAND, the Lancaster
Alliance for New Directions, one of several preservationist groups.
</P>
<P>
   The conservationists have generated considerable sentiment
against haphazard sprawl. They have tried to establish Urban Growth
Boundaries outside of which development would be banned, but some
communities in the county have spurned this concept. The county's
Agricultural Preserve Board provides tax protection against rising
property assessments for farmers who promise never to develop their
land. The preservationists have managed to stave off a state
transportation department plan to build a four-lane highway through
the farmland, but feasibility studies on the project continue.
</P>
<P>
   Divine providence brought the Amish to Lancaster County, wedding
some of the world's best farmers to some of its most fertile soil,
Daum explained. ``They belong here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
