<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0120 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MEDIA-WATCHDOG-REVI     06-22 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEDIA-WATCHDOG-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20.) 
 WATCHING WATCHDOGS WATCHING WATCHDOGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, June (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Midway through a news story about Steven Brill's
arrival as the newest major-domo in the booming industry of media
criticism, Howard Kurtz, a respected practitioner himself for The
Washington Post, suddenly found it necessary to open parentheses
confessionally in noting: ``The founder of Brill's Content (to
which this reporter is to be an occasional contributor) could not
be reached for comment.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment of comic relief badly needed by the Fourth
Estate, run ragged these past five months in its coverage of the
allegations of sex and mendacity at the Clinton White House. Here
was the media watchdog watch turning into a shimmering house of
mirrors, with one watchdog sniffing out the latest watchdog while
properly noting the crisscross of commercial interests at work in
all the watching.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural edition of Content magazine (``the independent
voice of the information age''), Brill, a masterly self-promoter,
managed to unnerve the media with his own reporting and caustic
criticism of the print and television performance thus far on the
still murky story of President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky, the
former White House intern now flirting with indictment.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a mad competitive tumble of rumor and scoop, leak
and spin that, apart from any search for truth, has been selling
newspapers sensationally and plunging television news into
round-the-clock frenzies of redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   For his debut, Brill succeeded in getting an exclusive interview
with Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel in charge of the
Lewinsky investigation whose style seems part Garbo, part Javert.
Brill fashioned not so much a bombshell as an enormous cream pie
smeared in the face of the Washington press corps. ``Corrupted to
its core,'' he charged in depicting the media as enablers of a
freewheeling prosecutor and ``headlining whatever he leaks out _
instead of remaining professionally suspicious of him and his
power.''
</P>
<P>
   In his indictment, Brill dared to denounce a few reporters by
name as ``lapdogs'' and ``stenographers'' fawning for biased scoops
engineered by Starr's office. Brill's timing was fortuitous, for,
as so often happens, there was no real news this week in the
Lewinsky story. The traditional fallback in this situation is for
the media to fill space by writing a story about the sort of job it
has been doing on the big story. But Brill arrived with rabid
keenness, his teeth bared for his own kind, nipping at a pack that
instantly turned yowlingly back at him.
</P>
<P>
   Treacheries were decried. Lawsuits were threatened by bloodied
reporters. Headlines were tinged with shock, shock! as Starr openly
confirmed that, for all the anti-leak strictures, he most certainly
did dispatch agents to operate amid the jostling, murmuring crowds
of anonymous sources who work the mean media streets of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Brill soon was vetted by deflated investigative journalists.
Legitimate questions were honed: How could Brill not bother to
tape-record the Starr interview as an event certain to be subjected
to enormous second-guessing and back-biting? How could he not
bother to disclose that he donated $2,000 to Clinton's re-election?
How dare he criticize press methods when, some reporters charged,
their own comments to him in the self-serving world of
``background'' interviewing became warped in translation or even
shifted like chess pieces onto the record as attributed quotes?
What did he call this stuff? Journalism?
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which was least scathed in the Brill version of
the Clinton/Lewinsky media saga, gloated as the Diogenes Watch
morphed cannibalistically into Les Liaisons Dangereuses. News
addicts not already numbed by the growing specialty of
media-watchdogging-cum-hotdogging could pay the $3.95 and read
Brill's full 25,000-word jeremiad, providing they had the stamina
of a doctoral candidate. This oeuvre was followed by a 19-page
single-spaced rebuttal from the presumably very busy Starr in which
the prosecutor charged that Brill's critique ``borders on the
libelous.''
</P>
<P>
   (Thus far, Brill, as principled as any ink-stained wretch, has
yielded only one apology _ for mistaking the ground rules and some,
uh, content of an interview _ once he had learned that the
complaining reporter had furtively tape-recorded the interview.)
</P>
<P>
   The conduct of Lewinsky and the president, whatever it really
had been at the White House, was turned for one brief welcome
moment into a sidebar. They stood by as mute as those accused of
heresy, alchemy and witchcraft in medieval inquisitions used to
wait on learned debates about holy methods. Anyone singed by the
relentless months of blowtorch coverage had to leer at the sweet
turnabout as media fur smouldered.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, media critics have been finding fault since the
invention of the printing press, and maybe since life itself was
first lifted out of context for retelling at prehistoric campfires.
``Newspapers are unable, seemingly, to discriminate between a
bicycle accident and the collapse of civilization,'' George Bernard
Shaw, one of the best of the critics, decreed a century before
Lewinsky became the apple of the press corps' eye.
</P>
<P>
   Let's stipulate, as the phrase goes among the wads of lawyers
now so richly, so leakily involved in the criminal investigation of
Clinton and Lewinsky, that the true story lies somewhere between a
bike accident and doomsday. The devil is in the details, still to
be unearthed by all manner of reporters as the watchdogs watch.
</P>
<P>
   Who is watching Brill? He anticipated the question, appointing
Bill Kovach, a respected newsman and curator of the Nieman
Foundation for Journalism at Harvard, to be an independent monitor,
and take aim at Content from within.
</P>
<P>
   But Brill's excoriating debut has prodded volunteer watchdogs to
the fore, all the way down the ranks to Matt Drudge, the Walter
Winchell wannabe on the Internet. He is often dismissed as a
grating cybergossip but he still lays proud claim to first sparking
the Lewinsky story's explosion in the nation's media. The
mischievous Drudge knows how to filch reporters' story leads and
how to get under the skin of media elitists who imagine the
business should somehow have firm standards.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking Brill's many television appearances in the requisite
huckstering of this latest media watchdog enterprise, Drudge
offered Brill free advice: ``Feed the hungry machine slowly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1030EDT &QL; 
