A0185 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN22-COX     06-22 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guess who went to dinner with big tobacco?
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you tried to contact your GOP senator the evening
before the Senate's key vote on comprehensive tobacco legislation,
you might have found him out for early cocktails and dinner. One of
the year's biggest fundraisers for the Republican National
Committee and its Senate and House campaign committees was staged
at the Washington Convention Center, courtesy of big tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   You weren't invited. And you didn't have much voice in the way
your senator voted.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't match tobacco money. No one can.
</P>
<P>
   The night-before gala wasn't for giving lil' ol' $5,000 limited-
by-law contributions to individual GOP senators. It was to raise
$10 million in so-called soft money. Republican senators attended
in droves. And the next day they deliverd pro-industry votes as
expected. Tobacco is the top soft-money donor to the GOP, and has
been for the past three years. Phillip Morris alone has given
approximately $275,000 to various Republican political campaign
committees since the first of January.
</P>
<P>
   The get-along, go-along crowd of GOP senators who went from
being wined and dined to caving in on a crucial public health issue
will rationalize with their leadership that what's needed is a
narrower bill on tobacco, one that won't ``increase taxes.'' A vote
to increase taxes is a powerful election-year TV spot. Everybody
know that. The political pitfall on the tobacco issue is that the
American people don't really view increasing the cost of cigarettes
as increasing their taxes. According to a recent Gallup poll, 60
percent support raising the cost of tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   The people, hopefully, will see through much of the double-talk
on a matter GOP leaders have wrongly allowed to become partisan.
For example, the party that calls for personal responsibility for
welfare mothers doesn't demand such for folks who smoke themselves
to death. The party that wants to cut health care costs doesn't
isn't interested in curtailing the nation's greatest single health
care expense. The party that hates solving things through the
courts cares not about tobacco lawsuits that will go on endlessly.
The party that believes government policies can change personal
behavior doesn't want to bully people who smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Given the GOP's blatant sell-out to the tobacco industry, it's
an amazing thing that the legislation the industry so hates is
sponsored by a Republican. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) deserves a
place in ``Profiles in Courage'' next to John Quincy Adams who also
fought his party-- the most politically treacherous fight of all. A
Vietnam war veteran, true to a conservative social agenda ( he is
pro-life), loyal to the presidential campaign of Bob Dole when
other party faithful deserted, McCain has stood firmly against the
deceit of the tobacco industry without name-calling or blaming his
fellow Republicans. The same is true of his measured response to
GOP leaders' opposition to his campaign finance reform bill, one
related to this very issue and one tobacco lobbyists helped kill.
Not many know of McCain's quiet decision several years ago not to
accept any more tobacco money. It was after the discovery of
documents that show the industry purposefully targeted its
cigarette marketing to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from one man's courage and a party sell-out, there's
something else voters ought to note: A dozen Republicans mustered
the courage to support the tobacco bill -- check to see if your
senator was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
