A0186 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN21-CO     06-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cut them slack, and kids go adrift
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Now that school is out, my mom's hassling me about everything
I want to do,'' the teenager wearing a middle school T-shirt
complained to her girlfriend as they stood in line next to me in
the crowded outer lobby of the multiplex movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' her companion replied, rolling her eyes heavenward
to express adolescent contempt and annoyance. ``My parents are the
same way. Like we got into it last night about what I want to do
this summer. I mean, I almost lost it. I told them they got to cut
me some slack or ... ''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't hear the rest of the conversation as the two girls
rushed away to get into line at a ticket window just opening up.
Thus, I was left behind to reflect on the familiar phrase this
generation invokes like a sacred mantra: Cut me some slack.
</P>
<P>
   As it's used by today's youth, the message to adults is:
``Whatever your expectations or standards for me, adjust them to
accommodate what I want to do the way I want to do it or risk a
volatile explosion. I reserve the right to determine what's best
for me. And (most insulting of all to the older generation) you
have earned no right to tell me what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After I left the theater, I continued to think about the
teenagers' overheard conversation and the struggle of wills going
on in many families where parents are striving to guide their
children safely toward adulthood. These parents are probably
frustrated and exhausted. Clearly, many teenagers are frustrated
and angry. This volatile mix of emotions, if unrelieved by healing
communication between parents and children, portends serious
trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In Toni Morrison's novel (ITALS) Paradise, (UNITALS) she tells
of a time when ``give me some slack'' was the younger generation's
slogan, replacing respect for elders, fear of God or concern for
expressing his will.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the all-black town of Ruby, Okla., during the '70s, this
novel tells the story of perilous times when the divisive tensions
throughout the rural community were fueled by ``what nobody talked
about: young people in trouble or acting out behind every door.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger generation of the town's most stable families
thought their elders' ways of doing things too slow, weak and
ineffective, and, unlike previous generations, these youths had no
reluctance to say so. Hence ``the sass, the pout, the outright
defiance'' became likely responses whenever the older generation
tried to proscribe conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been better for everyone if the young people had
spoken softly, acknowledged their upbringing as they presented
their views. But they didn't want to discuss; they wanted to
instruct,'' Ms. Morrison writes. That observation definitely
applies to many of today's youth.
</P>
<P>
   In Ruby, young people no longer routinely acknowledged that the
older generation had wisdom the younger generation needed in order
to survive. Nor did the new generation feel any need to obey their
elders as an act of gratitude for the nurturing community provided.
Newly formed in more technological times and ignorant of the
hardships of the past, these youths felt sufficient unto
themselves, fully able to cope without standards except those of
their own making.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, though Ms. Morrison tells the mythic story of another era
and the dilemma of a new generation seeking to define its identity
and sense of purpose, the disconnect between adults and youths that
she describes mirrors the widening chasm between children and
adults in modern society where the sass, the pout and outright
defiance of our youth varies only in degrees of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the challenge to bridge the communication gap between
children and adults is more daunting than ever, but parents must
not abdicate their responsibility to gain momentary respite from
the struggle. Better that they risk occasional explosions of
adolescent wrath and work through it than cut the reins of
authority too loose. Slack reins provide children enough rope to
hang themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
