<HEADER>
A0200 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARFIELD-MONTH22-COX     06-22 0250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARFIELD-MONTH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Birthday bash for special cat held at International Museum of
Cartoon Art
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ It wasn't your average 20th birthday bash.
But Garfield isn't your average cat.
</P>
<P>
   The International Museum of Cartoon Art hosted a party and book
signing recently to kick off a two-month celebration in honor of
Garfield, the fleshy, fatigued feline that cartoonist Jim Davis
brought into the world in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a corn-fed, Indiana cat,'' Davis said, ``It's a great and
humbling thrill and a real honor to be here. This is a real mecca
for cartooning.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was joined by a 6-foot, walking and wise-cracking
Garfield, who arrived blind-folded in a city library's Bookmobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most exciting thing I've ever seen,'' said Eric
Jorge, who said he is 8-3/4 years old. Jorge, of Palm Beach
Gardens, said he's ``definitely'' going to be a cartoonist when he
grows up. Or maybe a baseball player, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Davis gave fans every reason to expect 20 more years of
Garfield, Odie, his slow-witted canine companion, and Jon, the two
animals' hapless human handler. And he gave a preview of what's in
store for Garfield's future: A Garfield theme park will open
outside of Indianapolis in 1999 _ complete with four roller
coasters, a designated nap area and, of course, ``the best lasagna
in the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0201 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLERS-REJECTED22-CO     06-22 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLERS-REJECTED22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Juveniles in Jonesboro shooting may land in San Marcos detention
facility
 &HT;    By Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A San Marcos center for troubled youths has decided it
will not accept two Arkansas boys accused of killing five people in
a school shooting, even if an Arkansas judge recommends they be
placed there.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Andrew Golden, 12, and Mitchell Johnson, 13, were
accused of opening fire into a crowd of middle school teachers and
students, killing five and injuring 10 in what quickly became known
as the Jonesboro massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Last week (week of June 15 - 21), Arkansas officials toured the
Brown Schools Inc. facility in San Marcos as they looked for
alternative places to keep the boys if they are found guilty.
Concerns about the boys' safety in Arkansas' Division of Youth
Services program prompted the search. Officials would not comment
on whether other facilities were being considered.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decision about where the boys might be sent is
still in the initial stages _ they have not yet been before a judge
_ the Brown School has already declined to house and treat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have carefully considered the impact on our facility, our
neighbors and the kids whom we currently serve and believe it is in
the best interest of all to decline the opportunity to treat these
children,'' said John Harcourt, chief executive officer of the
Brown Schools, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas Judge Ralph Wilson Jr. was contacted by Brown School
officials Friday and notified of the center's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Walden, the prosecuting attorney in the case, said the
youngsters are undergoing psychological evaluations, and until
those are complete, it is premature to discuss the kinds of
facility where they could be placed. Bill Sadler of the Arkansas
State Police said discussing anything about the case or its
possibilities is ``completely inappropriate,'' since the boys do
not even have a hearing date set.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's visit did direct attention to the Brown Schools,
and that attention is what led the center to announce the decision
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the tremendous amount of media attention that
surfaced after the Brown Schools was considered as a treatment
option for the children has significantly compromised our ability
to accept these children into our program,'' Harcourt said.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown Schools, privately owned facilities founded in 1940 by
Bert Brown, treat children with behavioral and psychological
problems. There are 15 campuses in six states and Puerto Rico, all
licensed through the Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory
Services as residential child-care facilities. The San Marcos
center is the oldest and best known.
</P>
<P>
   While the schools are known for their ability to treat children
with problems, they are not correctional facilities, said Donna
Burtanger, vice president of marketing and communications for the
Brown Schools. Although individual buildings are secured, Burtanger
said, the 110-acre campus in San Marcos is not fenced in.
</P>
<P>
   Security became a problem at one Brown School campus earlier
this year. Twice residents of the Brown Schools Rehabilitation
Center on Dittmar Road in South Austin walked off the grounds and
had run-ins with Austin police.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a 19-year-old mental patient was accused of trying
to attack officers with a crowbar at a fast-food restaurant. He was
shot in the stomach. A week later, a 14-year-old boy left the
campus and pointed a BB gun at police officers, investigators said.
Police officers fired at the boy, but he was not hit.
</P>
<P>
   After those incidents, Brown Schools executive Jim Dalzell said
security was being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a policy of carefully watching our patients, and if
that policy was followed, then we will have to look at what we have
to do in terms of our whole system to reduce the risk of this
happening again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
