<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHAT-SHOES?22-COX     06-22 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-SHOES?22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lost souls find new soles
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Come Friday (June 19) on 13th Street and
nobody knows anything. The shoes are gone. Took a hike.
</P>
<P>
   The streets in Coleman Park are hot, lawns dead if there was a
lawn to begin with. No irrigation. Rubbish is piled high in the
streets, in yards. Nobody on the streets except young men on the
corners. Some wear beepers.
</P>
<P>
   One young kid with several gold teeth and white cotton shorts
worn low over plaid underwear is standing on the corner in front of
Sam's grocery. He's wearing new Nikes _ so new you can almost smell
the box. The laces are untied, in the dirt, but so white, so clean
they or the shoes or both are quite obviously new.
</P>
<P>
   Know anything about all the stolen shoes? he's asked.
</P>
<P>
   What shoes, he says. It's a statement, not a question.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,400 pairs of shoes that disappeared from the street right
there yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gimme $1,000 and I'll tell you, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Are those shoes new, he's asked?
</P>
<P>
   He looks down at his feet. What shoes? he says.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday (June 18), a truck driver parked his rig carrying more
than 5,000 pairs of Nikes, Reeboks and Bass shoes on 13th near
Tamarind Avenue, one of the poorest neighborhoods of West Palm
Beach. The driver went off to find sex and dope. He came back and a
crowd had broken into the truck and stolen more than 3,400 pairs of
the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   At $80 to $100 a pair, that's $300,000 retail.
</P>
<P>
   But the police and some people in the neighborhood see the shoe
episode as an opportunity, not a crime. They feel it would be
``stupid'' to try to get the shoes back.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of those kids there, this was probably their first
pair of new shoes,'' West Palm Beach officer Chip Woods said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is reminiscent of the Brinks truck that capsized in
January 1997 in the Overtown section of Miami. Only $300 of more
than $800,000 in spilled money was returned.
</P>
<P>
   Miami police had warned passersby they would be arrested for
picking up so much as a quarter, but residents of Overtown laughed.
And kept the money. But one little boy returned 85 cents and was
given a good citizenship award. Honesty paid, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, no little kids are on 13th, no families. There are no
cafes, no water fountains, no ice cream wagons. Here and there down
an alley someone goes over a fence, disappears. A few feet flash
with bright new shoes, but the owners don't know anything.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody says the same thing about the stolen shoes: What
shoes. Or, I don't know nothing.
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable, says Donald Gibson III. He's the director
of the non-profit Community Resource Center. A native of the
neighborhood, he's come back to Coleman Park after 15 years of
doing community mental health work in San Francisco. He wants to
rebuild Coleman Park, those hot and dirty streets between Douglas
and Tamarind avenues north of Palm Beach Lakes Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure they're going to bend down and grab those shoes,'' he
says. ``People in Palm Beach or Wellington would do the same thing.
But here, these people are poor, exploited, red-lined out of their
homes and businesses. They're going to keep those shoes. They got
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the police _ who said they wouldn't be expending any shoe
leather on the case _ make the right decision?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever broke the lock on that truck is a hero to the people
around here,'' Gibson says. ``Nobody's going to turn him in. The
police made a prudent decision to walk away from this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the shoes is wrong, sure,'' Gibson allows. ``But it's
gonna happen. A lot of people, they're not going to take those
shoes. There's a lot of pride here. Black people are proud. But
there's a lot of poverty, too. So, others, they're going to take
the shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson points up the street, toward Sam's. ``That store,'' he
says, ``used to be black-owned. Now, an Arab owns it. It smells,
the prices are high and the Arab doesn't live in the neighborhood.
That's the problem here. Money goes out but doesn't come in. Go
talk to the Arab.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arab turns out to be Jewish. Art Yahoda, 39, Tel Aviv
expatriate and owner of Sam's for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   He's never been held up, he says, but half his vendors won't
deliver merchandise or produce. He has to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today a beer truck comes,'' Yahoda says. `` While the driver
is wheeling in five cases, somebody grabs two cases of Guinness
Stout from the truck. You can't leave anything lying around. It
won't be there long.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Bennett just came in to the neighborhood, by way of
Camden, N.J. She lives on the second floor of an apartment house
with her daughter and 12-year-old grandson, Ahmad. She was working
when the shoe heist took place right in front of her apartment
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong to take the shoes,'' she says. ``If my grandson
came home with those shoes, I'd haul him myself to the police
station. I understand why people who need them would take the
shoes, but most of those shoes are long gone, sold or being sold.
That's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad, the grandson, nods. Helen Bennett tells him to stay off
the streets. He nods again. His shoes are old.
</P>
<P>
   Down on the street three women are loading a bunch of kids into
a big station wagon. They're going to the beach. What do they know
about the shoes?
</P>
<P>
   Each says the same thing: ``What shoes?''
</P>
<P>
   A West Palm Beach police car comes up the street. Two cops
inside. They're hot.
</P>
<P>
   What's new on yesterday's shoe heist?
</P>
<P>
   ``What shoes?'' they ask in unison.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't even heard about the shoes, they say. When did it
happen, where, they ask.
</P>
<P>
   Three thousand pairs of shoes. Gone. Nobody knows nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
