<SLUG> BC-POOL-ICE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ice for the pool
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ Tony Tarallo was sick of climbing into a
94-degree pool every day. ``It was, like, not refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   So he ordered 1,200 pounds of ice for $200, helped push the
300-pound blocks one by one into the deep end, then climbed in
himself.
</P>
<P>
   While he and family friend Mike Flanagancq used one slab as a
mini-bar, the kids used the others as floats.
</P>
<P>
   Ice-truck driver Scott Jensen declined an invite and stood by,
sweating. ``I'd rather sit in the air conditioning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarallo, who owns a Stuart restaurant, completed his
10,000-gallon pool three weeks ago. This was an experiment, he said
as the water temperature fell to 90 degrees. It might become a
weekly event.
</P>
<P>
   He and Flanagan hoisted one rapidly melting block onto the lip
of the man-made waterfall that flows into the pool, then floated
under it. ``Being a kid, you know?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Cassidy, owner of Cassidy's Stuart Icecq, said this was the
first such request of the company this year. Others have simply
asked to crawl into their giant ice boxes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also have dry ice,'' he said, watching the fun. ``That's 110
below zero. I'd love to experiment with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
