<HEADER>
A0210 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LELAND-RETURNS22-COX     06-22 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LELAND-RETURNS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leland returns to Florida after lung transplant
 &HT;    By Christine Evans
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Maybe you weren't at the airport
Saturday (June 20), so you did not see a little squirt of a guy get
off the Midway flight from Raleigh, N.C., and you did not see all
the kids crowd around to give him hugs, or the big banner stretched
across the concourse to welcome him home, or the outrageous way the
little guy lifted up his shirt _ with the TV camera rolling! _ to
show off his scars, two big, curvy red lines stretching like smiles
across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Smallest Gym Teacher came home Saturday. And he
could breathe.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped off the plane in West Palm Beach with his wife,
Melissa, a heavy backpack that he carried himself, and, underneath
those smiling scars, a new set of lungs. That work.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' Leland Herring told his friends and students and
colleagues from Wellington Christian School. ``I have only one
thing to say: This is a miracle. I mean, really! Your prayers made
it happen. Because when I went up to North Carolina, I didn't know,
to be honest with you, if I'd ever be coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   His doctors didn't know, either. The Herrings moved to Durham,
N.C., the day before Thanksgiving to be close to Duke University
Medical Center and the transplant team that hoped to save Leland's
life, if only they could get their hands on a decent set of lungs.
Leland has cystic fibrosis, and his own lungs were good for perhaps
another six months. If that.
</P>
<P>
   Just as doctors were getting worried, really worried, somewhere
in the Midwest a teenager died, and that teenager had a good set of
lungs and a blood type that matched. On April 26, Leland got his
transplant, which greatly increases the chance he will live another
five years, or more.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, he was back in his Durham apartment _ and that
afternoon, in typical fashion, he showed up at the gym to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so appreciative,'' he said, his hands shaking a bit as he
made his speech from an airport chair, thanking everybody who had
cheered him up _ and on _ during the seven-month wait. ``This
donor, whoever he is, allowed me my first really good deep breath
of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   Now The World's Smallest Gym Teacher, as all the kids call him
(he's 5-foot-4 and 112 on a good day) has big plans. First, he will
fly to Illinois to be best man in a dear friend's wedding _ he
wasn't sure he would live to see that day. Then he will return to
Duke for a check-up _ the doctors are amazed by his progress. And
then, well, this is the really remarkable thing:
</P>
<P>
   He plans to go back to work this fall as The World's Smallest
Gym Teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no reason to stop,'' he said, ``My motto is, `Just keep
going.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is a gutsy motto, and he imparted it to his students at
Wellington Christian, where for three years he taught track and
basketball, never mind that he can't run a quarter mile himself.
Chris Tellexcq, 10 years old and next year a sixth-grader, recalled
how he and his teammates dedicated a track meet to Leland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend and I tied for first, and we held hands across the
finish line to honor Mr. Herring.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Kurnitskycq, 11, said she and her friend Jamie were
struggling to complete the mile run and the 50-yard dash for the
Presidential Physical Fitness Award _ ``and Mr. Herring, he was so
encouraging, he made us keep going until we got presidential.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior pastor at Wellington Church, Tim Christensoncq, said
he will never forget the day Melissa Herring showed his
congregation a video of Leland sitting on a bench outside his
Durham apartment before the transplant. For the first time, church
members saw Leland clearly suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just sitting there, but he looked like he had just run
a marathon,'' the pastor said. ``He just could not breathe. His
lungs were working at about 19 percent of their capacity, and he
was just heaving. That video catalyzed us. We had a prayer meeting
right after.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Leland are just skyrockets, they burn fast and
they burn bright. None of us really have any idea how long we're
going to live, and he's such a poignant example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a sports star, which he does not resemble, or a rock star,
which by a leap of imagination he might, Leland Herring came home
to a hero's welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Giggling teenage girls remarked that his cheeks looked a bit
chubbier. A grandmotherly type complimented his ``beautiful'' skin
tone. And the music teacher at Wellington Christian inquired
whether he could give Leland a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' someone said, ``Just don't squeeze too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And from the crowd, Brett Bowers, 11, emerged to tell one more
anecdote about his favorite teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives out Mr. Herring's Bonus Points,'' Brett said. ``One
time, we had to do the mile, and a bunch of kids were saying, `We
can't do it!' And I said, `Yes, we can! We can do it!' And Mr.
Herring said, `Brett Bower, 20 extra bonus points!'
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing he wanted to teach us is, `Never say can't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
