A0211 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEASONAL-WORKERS22-CO     06-22 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASONAL-WORKERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer helpers look past parks
 &HT;    By Kelly Daniel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Blue skies, rippling lakes and smiling swimmers are all
it used to take to get summer workers for Travis County, Texas,
parks. Now nothing but a stream of green cash does the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Fast food jobs, retail stores, beauty salons _ just about
anything, really _ paid more. The college-aged workers who usually
snapped up Travis County's 45 seasonal parks jobs instead man
drive-through windows. Halfway through spring, the parks department
lacked 32 seasonal workers, thanks in part to the Austin-area's 2.3
percent unemployment rate in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had a problem hiring,'' said Donna Holt, human
resources coordinator for Travis County Transportation and Natural
Resources. ``This year...we can't get anybody out there at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in recent memory, Travis County raised
seasonal workers' pay to attract applicants, increasing wages to $7
an hour from $6.08 an hour _ still lower than the $7.50 an hour
some retail jobs pay.The parks department started doing telephone
interviews and quickened its hiring process, but is still 10
workers short of its usual number for this time of year. The pay
raise helped, bringing in 22 people since it took effect last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage means some park visitors wait in line longer to pay
their entrance fees. For a lucky few, who hit the right park on the
right day, it means no one is available to take their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get in free,'' said Charles Bergh, parks division
director. Not always, though, because park rangers and other
supervisors have collected fees _ not normally part of their duties
_ at the county's 18 parks.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal workers pick up litter, keep an eye on boaters,
swimmers, picnickers and divers to make sure everyone follows park
rules, collect fees and hand out information pamphlets to visitors.
They work at a different park almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty low-stress job,'' said Shelly Sheppard, who left
a beauty salon job for a Travis County parks booth nearly two weeks
ago. ``The pay was decent.''
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos also has a seasonal worker shortage, but with
lifeguards, who earn between $6.30 to $7.08 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Pool managers and other supervisors are climbing into the
lifeguard stands because of a shortage of lifeguards, said Christi
Schmidt, city recreation manager. Besides nearby water parks,
better-paying fast food jobs and other employers, ``We've got the
outlet mall and they can maybe work at the outlet mall and make a
little more money,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   The state parks department and Round Rock city parks haven't had
as much trouble filling their positions. The state jobs typically
attract teachers looking for summer work and Round Rock only has
nine jobs to fill, officials for both said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis County still has more work than people and ``You share
everybody else's weight,'' said Pam Sliva, 35, a seasonal worker
since December. But new employees are clocking in.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Masters is one of them, donning the park uniform of white
knit shirt and green shorts for the first time last week. She spent
her second day on the job at Mansfield Dam Park, helping Sliva and
Sheppard collect fees and patrol the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making more at my other job, but this is a seasonal job so
that's to be expected,'' said Masters, who has worked in a hotel
two years while finishing her zoology degree at University of
Texas. ``But I make $7 an hour _ it's fairly good for the
responsibilities. It's not like it's a tough job, as far as I can
tell from one day. I love the scenery. I love being out on the
lake.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's one extra perk for Masters, who's used to handling
grumpy hotel guests' complaints. ``The people are pretty much happy
because they're coming out to the lake,'' she said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
