<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax's Business Commentary: Shift in job attitudes
would brighten South's future
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In a downtown hotel in Louisville, Ky., last week
(week of June 15 - 21), Southerners who had gathered for a ``Future
of the South'' convention got a taste of the region's present-day
problems: Overwhelmed waitresses raced around the hotel restaurant
trying to serve far too many customers; guests carried up their own
luggage; hallway carpets went unswept.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Louisville's 2.7 percent unemployment rate has made
it tough for the hotel to hire an adequate number of workers. Real
estate ads featured lots of beautiful new homes, and the airport
was busy. It would seem any Kentuckian with a bit of ambition could
make a decent living in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   But while the state's largest city is booming, thousands of
Kentuckians continue to live in poor, rural areas where they hang
on to dirty, difficult mining jobs. The Louisville Courier-Journal
recently completed a series of stories that revealed about 10
percent of miners still get black lung disease, caused by the
inhalation of thick coal dust.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that disease should not still exist. Mine operators
are required to send the federal government samples of the dust
levels in their mines to prove they are complying with tough
regulations. But the newspaper's reporter found that dust tests
routinely are being distorted to show the mine air is clean.
</P>
<P>
   Who would do such a terrible thing? Who would fake test results
so that workers would breathe in dangerous dust?
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the miners themselves are usually the cause of the
cheating. They turn off the testing machines or put their shirts
over them so that dust can't get into the intake valves.
</P>
<P>
   The miners fear that if their employers are forced to meet
federal dust standards, they won't be able to operate profitably.
The workers don't want to lose their jobs, so they are willing to
cheat, even if that means committing suicide by black lung.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps during the 1930s, when the nation's unemployment rate
was 25 percent, making such a choice might have made sense. But
today, miners don't have to pick between lung disease and
joblessness. Employers in Louisville, Lexington and other vibrant
cities are begging for workers.
</P>
<P>
   A hard-working miner ought to be able to learn to operate a
construction crane or a bulldozer. All over the South, tree-cutting
companies are desperately seeking strong workers who can help clear
debris from this spring's big storms. Trucking companies are
looking for drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities abound, yet coal miners would rather choke on coal
dust than change their location or occupation. Why? Finding the
answer to that question is vital to the South's economic future.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, sponsored by the Southern Growth Policies
Board, the blue ribbon panel of governors and other top leaders
from the region pounded home the message that the South will not
continue to prosper unless more workers learn the skills needed in
our high-tech, global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the South, employers are suffering from a lack of
workers, yet pockets of unemployment and underemployment persist
because so many people resist change.
</P>
<P>
   So we end up with these absurdities: In urban areas, many young
men would rather sell drugs and risk getting shot than learn to
repair cars. In coal-mining counties, men would rather breathe
filthy air than learn to operate construction equipment. In rural
areas, women would rather cut up poultry than enroll in nursing
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Getting people to break out of their familiar roles will require
the commitment of all community leaders. Educators, ministers,
union officials, politicians, employers and other leaders have to
deliver a tough, clear message: Today's economy is booming, but it
will reward only those people willing to change their old haunts
and habits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
