<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reviews of new grill books
 &HT;    By American-Statesman staff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ `Sizzlers' By Monda Rosenberg McClelland &AMP; Stewart
Inc., $16 Pages:143 Color photos:43 Illustrations: None Recipes:200
+ Thoroughness: Offers designer versions of meat, seafood and
veggie grill mainstays and throws in entries like Jalapeno-Yogurt
Sauce, Warm Tomato &AMP; Feta Salad and Warm Fruit Dessert Pizza. Ease
of Understanding:Short words, uncomplicated recipes and each
section includes tips for beginners. Helpfulness:Not only does
``Sizzlers'' assume you have no previous BBQ knowledge, it doesn't
even assume you have a grill. There are more than 70 indoor
adaptations User friendly:Handily organized with large type and
color-coded margin tabs. Looks like a cookbook designed by
Entertainment Weekly. Value: Perfect for novice cooks or grilling
in a hurry. Comments:''Sizzlers'' is a stress-free introduction to
Grilling 101. Emphasis on short cooking times and simple
instructions may shortchange some traditional recipes . _ James
Hibberd is an American-Statesman staffer who has grilled since Boy
Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   `The Complete Indoor/Outdoor Grill' By Donna Rodnitzky Prima,
$18 Pages:386 Color photos: None Illustrations: Few black and white
sketches Recipes:175 Thoroughness: Covers poultry, beef, lamb,
pork, seafood and fruits and vegetables. Many varieties of
marinades offered. Ease of understanding:Introduc- tion has lots of
useful tips, which are good for beginners. Helpfulness:Directions
are easy to follow. Value: Good. Comments:Not the most attractive
cookbook, with no photos and few illustrations, but useful and
practical. Easy for grilling novices to comprehend. _Michele
Santos, an American-Statesman lifestyle writer, has bought her
first home and grill.
</P>
<P>
   `All Fired Up' By Margaret Howard Firefly, $25 Pages: 224 Color
photos: More than 50 Recipes: More than 125. Thoroughness:
Reasonable, although beginners might be lost. Helpfulness:In terms
of sparking the imagination, very. Applicable to today's
lifestyle:Painfully so, with lots of Asian and Pacific Island
flavors. User friendly: Fits nicely in a see-through plastic
cookbook holder. What else do you need? Value: You pay a lot for
the pictures. Comments:If you're ready to move beyond the basics,
this is for you. Duck breasts with mango orange sauce and wild duck
crepes sound complicated enough to make you want to stick your head
in the oven? There are plenty of variations on burgers (beef,
poultry, vegetarian). But the target audience for this one who'll
take a crack at shrimp-stuffed fish fillets with coconut sauce. _
Patrick Beach is an American-Statesman lifestyle writer who loves
to play with fire.
</P>
<P>
   `Born to Grill' By Cheryl and Bill Jamison Harvard Common Press,
$28 Pages:500 olor photos:None Illustrations:Some pen and ink
sketches ecipes:300 Thoroughness: Almost exhaustively so. Ease of
understanding:Compares grilling to golf, uses words like ``wimpy
results.'' Even cooks operating on one burner should be able to
handle it. Helpfulness: If you burn stuff after reading this book,
you're hopeless or absent-minded. Quit playing with fire.
Applicable to today's lifestyles: Yes, but some of the recipes are
probably too involved for weeknight cooking. User friendly:
Frequent technique tips, well-marked. Separate discussions on
cooking pizzas on grill, skewering foods, ketchup. Value: Worth the
money. Comments:With no color photos, this book is not flashy. Buy
it to read for a vast amount of info. Recipes may be more upscale
than some backyard burger cooks are accustomed to, but these
award-winning authors are serious cooks. Taste before you pass
judgment. _ Kitty Crider, American-Statesman food editor, has both
gas and charcoal grills in active use on her patio.
</P>
<P>
   `The Firehouse Grilling Cookbook' By Joseph T. Bonanno Jr.
Broadway Books, $23 Pages:228 Color photos: None Illustrations:None
Recipes:150 Thoroughness:Covers meat, poultry, fish _ along with
rubs, marinades and side dishes. Ease of understanding: Won't
intimidate a novice. elpfulness: Has all the basics pplicable to
today's lifestyles:Balances old favorites, new trends. User
friendly: Well-written, straightforward directions; good index.
Value:Worth the money. Comments: The book is well-organized, with
many contributions from firefighters around the country. And, as
you might expect, a long list of safety tips for grilling with
fire. _ Dale Rice, American-Statesman restaurant critic whose
garage-sale grill turns out great steaks, chops and salmon.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
