<HEADER>
A0216 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILLERS21-COX     06-22 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLERS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grilling the grillmasters about new book
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Cheryl and Bill Jamison of Santa Fe, those fire
fanatics whose cookbooks have copped a couple of James Beard
awards, breezed into Austin last week to talk of things of meat and
heat, especially their latest work, ``Born to Grill'' (Harvard
Common Press, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   Now, Central Texans don't cotton to outsiders telling us how to
play with fire under an open sky. But who among us has had 15
grills on our patio at once?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Jamisons are not total outsiders. Bill, whose
family is from Buda and Sprinkle, was the education director of the
Texas Commission of Arts and Humanities in Austin from 1973 to
1975, and Cheryl lived in Dallas awhile.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of ``Smoke &AMP; Spice,'' ``Sublime Smoke,'' ``The
Border Cookbook,'' ``Texas Home Cooking'' and the ``Rancho de
Chimayo Cookbook,'' both love good food.
</P>
<P>
   They are good sports, too, agreeing to let us grill the
grillmasters. Q: Do you still have 15 grills ? A: We are down to
six, but we predominantly use four: an indoor Viking gas grill, an
outdoor Weber kettle grill, a Hasty-Bake charcoal grill and a
Tuscan grill that fits inside a wood-burning fireplace. Q: What are
your favorite foods cooked on the grill? A: Bill: shrimp (out of
the shell), tuna steak and corn on the cob (out of the husk).
Cheryl: pork chops, porterhouse steaks, asparagus (angled so it
does not fall through the grill.) Q: What is grilling? A: It's high
heat, dry cooking, directly over the fire. But contemporary grills
are so versatile and easy to use that they've led us to neglect
real grilling.
</P>
<P>
   Too often these days we think we're grilling just because we're
using a grill, while much of the time we are actually cooking the
food in quite a different way _ roasting, baking, frying _ and
losing much of the grill flavor that brought us to the back yard
originally. (Our recipes state a preference fos when you turn the
fish, re-oil the grate. If grilling covered, sear both sides of the
fish first on high heat uncovered for 2 minutes; finish the cooking
with the cover on over medium heat for 4 to 5 minutes, turning once
midway.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the steaks immediately, halved for four diners, with
dollops of the horseradish cream.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4. For a summer supper, pair the tuna with new potatoes
and string beans, dressed with vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing goes with grilled meat like corn on the cob. We used to
grill the old favorite in the way that's generally recommended,
soaking the ear in water and cooking it with the husk on. We
realized finally that the traditional method actually steams and
roasts the corn, instead of grilling it, producing a good result
but little true grill taste. Now we remove the husk and silk before
cooking, exposing the kernels directly to the heat, which sizzles
surface juices and concentrates the corn flavor. To keep it classic
and elemental, we add no seasoning except salt and butter,
preferably a premium version of the latter. Simply Superb Corn on
the Cob
</P>
<P>
   6 ears of corn, husked and silk removed
</P>
<P>
   Butter, preferably an unsalted premium butter such as Plugra,
melted
</P>
<P>
   Salt or All-'Round Rub
</P>
<P>
   Finely minced fresh parsley or cilantro, optional, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Fire up the grill, bringing the temperature to medium (4 to 5
seconds with the hand test).
</P>
<P>
   Brush the corn lightly with butter. Grill the corn uncovered on
medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes, turning on all sides to cook
evenly and brushing with more butter after about 10 minutes. If
grilling covered, cook for 18 to 22 minutes, turning once midway
and brushing with butter. The cooking time is longer than
technically necessary to cook the corn, but helps concentrate the
juices a bit, giving the corn a more intense taste and crisper
texture.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the corn again with butter, sprinkle it with salt or dry
rub, and serve hot. If you can't resist the urge to add a little
something extra, scatter on a bit of parsley or cilantro for color.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   All-'Round Rub: Mix 6 tablespoons paprika, 2 tablespoons each of
coarse-ground black pepper and coarse salt, 1 tablespoon chili
powder, 2 teaspoons packed brown sugar, optional pinch or two of
cayenne. Save this fruit fantasy for a special party, a birthday,
Father's Day, the Fourth of July, or just the next available
Saturday. Warming the bananas on the grill mellows their taste and
softens their texture, making them as meltingly luscious as the ice
cream and the toffee candy sauce. Grilled Banana Split with
Chocolate-Toffee Melt 1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   6 medium bananas
</P>
<P>
   Three 1.4-ounce Heath Bars or 4 to 5 ounces chocolate-covered
toffee, chopped into chunks
</P>
<P>
   6 large scoops each of two kinds of ice cream, such as vanilla,
butter pecan, praline, chocolate or banana
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Toasted almonds, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Fire up the grill, bringing the temperature to medium (4 to 5
seconds with the hand test).
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar and half-and-half in a heavy medium saucepan.
Bring the mixture to a full rolling boil, stirring occasionally.
Stir in the butter and remove from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Just before grilling, slice the bananas, still in their skins,
lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the bananas cut-side down to a well-oiled grate. Grill
the bananas uncovered over medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes. Turn the
bananas skin-side down, brush their cut surface with a few
teaspoons of the sugar-half-and-half mixture, and grill them for 2
to 3 additional minutes, until soft and lightly colored.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the bananas from the skins. If you own long banana split
dishes, leave the banana halves whole and place two of them in each
dish. If not, cut the bananas into bite-size chunks and divide them
among individual serving dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Return the sugar/half-and-half mixture to medium-low heat and
stir in the toffee chunks. Cook briefly until the chocolate and
toffee have partially melted (leaving some chunkiness) and stir
well. Top each dish of banana with one scoop of each ice cream and
some of the chocolate-toffee melt. Add whipped cream, top with
almonds, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 gargantuan servings.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider is the food editor for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
