<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0219 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-LIGHT-$ADV21-     06-22 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-LIGHT-$ADV21-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIGHT COMES WHEN LIFE UPSETS OUR EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELAVAN, Ill. _ By the time we got to church, the early morning
wind and rain had bullied its way through fields of my uncle's
knee-high corn and pushed into town, unplugging electrical power in
the whole building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The preacher said the lights went out in the middle of the 8
a.m. service in the chapel, so they lit a few candles and carried
on. (As far as I know, Christian worship has never actually
required electricity.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the 9:30 service there still was no power, so we sat in the
sanctuary in a kind of sacred twilight, two small candles on the
altar offering the only light not strained through stained glass
windows. The effect was altogether remarkable and engaging. And I
gave thanks for an unexpected reminder that our alleged necessities
often are no more than conveniences that insulate and distract us
from reality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning aspect of the dimly lit sanctuary was the
depth of color that almost sang to us from the large round window
above the altar. The occluded outside light made the window's blues
especially profound in their richness, and I tried to remember ever
seeing that window on any of the several times I came to this
church as a boy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was the day in 1953 when we gathered here to bid Godspeed
to my grandmother _ dead of cancer at barely 65. But my only vivid
memory from that sad day is watching my other grandmother _ herself
already 71 _ pat the neatly folded hands of Grandma Tammeus as we
passed by her open casket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that as an 8-year-old boy it struck me as an odd and
even gross thing for the living to touch the dead. But today that
gesture seems to me to have been a loving and fearless act from a
spontaneously gracious woman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I cannot, however, bring to mind the lovely stained glass window
from that day or even from the day seven years later when we
collected here again to eulogize Grandpa Tammeus after his heart
ran out of beats. The reason, I'm sure, is that on those and other
occasions the electric lights in the sanctuary provided light
pollution, dimming the window's thick colors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm no Luddite. In fact, I am attached to much of the technology
that makes the way most of us live possible. So do not hear my
praise of church services without electricity as naive advocacy of
some long-gone time of supposed innocence. Rather, what I mean to
praise are interruptions of our increasingly unexamined
expectations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who live in cities and suburbs expect, at night, to
hear auto traffic and neighborhood dogs and even low-flying
aircraft as we slide away to sleep. I certainly do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the central Illinois farm house of my aunt and uncle is
surrounded not by a grid of busy streets but by nothing more than
fields of noiselessly growing corn and soybeans. The silence at
night is breathtaking. Indeed, when I lie in bed and draw breath I
hear nothing but the rhythmic seesawing of air in an out of me.
It's almost eerie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the windows are open and I listen long enough I may,
eventually, hear a cricket, say, but the overwhelming sensation is
immersion in gentle but insistent waves of silence, like shimmering
heat rising from corn fields on a torrid day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a reminder to me that not everyone lives _ or needs to live
_ at my normal pace or decibel level. There are alternatives. And
my strong, healthy, still-farming uncle in his mid-70s may be proof
that such an alternative life can have benefits we ignore at our
own peril. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At church, with the power gone, the organ was out of commission.
Because of this interruption in our expectations, we listened to _
and sang along with _ a lively piano. I love organ music (my oldest
sister is a Juilliard pipe organ graduate, so I better), but
there's something refreshingly direct and simple about a happily
percussive piano in a church sanctuary, and I was glad for the
change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On all counts, in fact, I was glad on this trip to have insights
break in through overturned expectations. I just hope I can
remember to look for them in other times and places. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
