<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-NEUTRINO-$ADV     06-22 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-NEUTRINO-$ADV22-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET ENOUGH NOTHING IN ONE PLACE AND YOU MAY HAVE SOMETHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years I've wanted to write a column about nothing. My theory
is that the less a column is about the less an editor can find to
challenge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've never quite gotten around to doing a column about nothing _
no matter what some of my more annoyed readers claim _ but today I
will get close by writing about almost nothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scientific name for almost nothing is neutrinos. How close
to nothing is this subatomic particle? Well, until earlier this
month it was thought to have no mass at all, thus resembling Bill
Clinton's foreign policy. In addition, it is unimaginably small and
so neutral in terms of electrical charge that trillions of them
pass through our bodies each day undetected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They may not be as small as the Ken Starr Fan Club, but they're
teeny. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For amounting to almost nothing, neutrinos certainly dealt the
scientific world a hefty blow upside the head a few weeks ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who have been trying to capture and study neutrinos
announced that neutrinos actually have mass. Indeed, there are so
many neutrinos in the cosmos that their mass may account for all
the so-called ``missing mass'' in the universe. And that's a
bunch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And this conclusion doesn't come from just one geek in a
basement lab. No, a team of more than 120 scientists from American,
European and Japanese research institutions has been working on
this project. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listen to what physicist John G. Learned (a wonderful name for a
scientist) of the University of Hawaii said about the finding of
the research team on which he served: ``It could prove to be the
key to the Holy Grail of physics, a unified theory of
everything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may find the naivete of what I'm about to tell you amazing,
especially if you have come to appreciate and even be comfortable
with all the ambiguity, complexity and chaos in the world, but ever
since Albert Einstein, scientists have been seeking this theory of
everything. It would be a single set of equations to explain all
the foundational forces of the world, from gravity to
electromagnetism to the strong and weak interactive forces inside
atoms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The famous physicist Stephen Hawking even claimed once _ in a
burst of arrogant and ridiculous hyperbole _ that once we find this
grand unified theory of everything we will ``know the mind of
God.'' Well, no. The most we might know then is an inventory of
utensils in God's tool box. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As scientists conduct this quixotic search for the grand theory
of everything, they have devoted more than two years to using a
fantastic array of equipment just to study the itsy-bitsy
neutrino. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to call attention to the size of their efforts, they
named themselves the Super-Kamiokande group. They buried a
50,000-ton tank of purified water deep underground in a zinc mine
owned by the Kamioka Mining and Smelting Company in Japan, about
150 miles northwest of Tokyo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There they set up intricate and expensive devices to detect the
astonishingly faint flashes of light given off when neutrinos
interact with the water in the tank. From their measurements they
determined that neutrinos have mass. If you expect me to explain
the math and science behind this conclusion you have been sadly
misled into thinking I'm capable of such a feat. I can't even
explain why my car often starts when I turn the key. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For decades scientists have been wondering where all the mass in
the universe is that their equations tell them exist. They call
this missing mass ``dark matter.'' The mass of neutrinos, it turns
out, may be some or most of the dark matter for which they've been
hunting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which surprised me. My theory has been that dark matter is made
up mostly of members of Ken Starr's Fan Club. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
