<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, June 22, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-FRAUD (San Antonio) _ The state of Texas and the
company that administers Medicaid in Texas have failed to collect
hundreds of millions of dollars over the past decade, according to
a whistle-blower lawsuit filed by a former lawyer for the Texas
Department of Health. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ICE-STORM-AFTERMATH (Plattsburgh, N.Y.) _ The four-inch-thick
ice that encased several counties in northern New York in January
has long since melted, but the havoc it wreaked is far from
forgotten. Nearly six months after the storm, many farmers are
still struggling to put their lives back together. By ELIZABETH
BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-X-FILES-WHO'S-WHO (San Francisco) _ These ``X-Files''
freaks are scary people. They are such a collection of geeks and
nerds, wallowing in the minutiae of a television show that their
presence may almost be enough to keep you from checking out a movie
that has you curious. Here's a look at who's who in the
``X-Files.'' By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-X-FILES (Undated) _ What has gone unreported in the hype for
``The X-Files'' feature film is that a great TV show is now forever
altered. Can fans of the TV show live with the fact that basic
tenets will change when ``The X-Files'' returns in the fall? By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-WAR (Undated) _ Horst Faas, who edited _ along with
Tim Page _ the recently published ``Requiem,'' a book of
photographs from Vietnam and Indochina taken by men and women
killed in action, shakes his head over the response to ``Requiem,''
from city to city. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-MEASURE (Undated) _ Describing their meeting at
Appomattox, author Jeff Shaara describes Grant's order to silence
Union celebrations _ ``They do not need to be told they are beaten,
they do not need us to tell them we have won.'' By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-PROFILE-SHAARA (Undated) _ Michael Shaara, who died of
heart disease in 1988 at the age of 59, never saw his novel ``The
Killer Angels,'' become a popular success. His son is the author of
a new Civil War novel ``The Last Full Measure.'' By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   PHIL-COLLINS (Houston) _ Take a look at him now. Phil Collins,
the venerable 47-year-old pop icon, is trying to reinvent himself _
and his music. And not everybody is happy. By ANDY SUMMA.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-JEALOUSY (Undated) _ Writer-director Noah Baumbach
was praised for his first film, ``Kicking and Screaming,'' about a
bunch of guys who graduate from college but can't seem to take the
next step. With ``Mr. Jealousy,'' Baumbach has taken the next step
and made a terribly good film. By BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MULAN (Undated) _ ``Mulan,'' Disney's 36th animated
full-length feature, is based on a popular Chinese legend about a
young woman named Mulan who disguises herself as a man in order to
take her aging father's place in the Army. By BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-CASINOS (Kinder, La.) _ For thousands of gamblers from
cities around Texas, a bus ride to the casino is the low and short
road to the Vegas-style action. And it's virtually a vacation
jackpot. The casinos subsidize the bus trips for players and often
throw in a free meal and complimentary drinks. By JOHN MacCORMACK
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STORM-DOORS (Albany, N.Y.) _ In recent years, the appearance of
storm doors has caught up with the look of exterior doors. New
models feature wood and foam cores, solid brass hardware,
full-view, beveled glass panels, brass inlays, etched or stained
glass. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-GARDEN (Undated) _ Water. A welcomed, cooling thought
these hot, dry days. There is a water garden for every person, for
every budget. And it doesn't have to be expensive. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-JANZEN (San Francisco) _ Lee Janzen sat down and
dandled the U.S. Open trophy on his right knee, as though it were
his son, Connor, or in a more playful mood, his wife, Beverly. He
had completed one of the most remarkable comebacks in major
tournament history, turning a seven-shot deficit to Payne Stewart
into a one-stroke win at the Olympic Club. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-STEWART (San Francisco) _ Paye Stewart tipped his very
distinctive cap to Sunday's two winners. Lee Janzen had the U.S.
Open trophy all to himself, but he shared Stewart's respect for San
Francisco's most famous golf course. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (Redding, Calif.) _ Redding is at the center of
a 60-mile radius that is the capital for outdoor recreation. The
region provides outstanding fishing, hiking, boating, hunting,
biking, rafting, mountain climbing, camping, backpacking and
recreational travel. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Bishop Alvaro Ramazzini was
stunned when fellow Bishop Juan Gerardi was beaten to death just
two days after he'd presented a major report on human rights
violations in Guatemala. The killing shows that the death, deceit,
corruption and cover-up that characterized Guatemala's 36-year
civil war did not disappear with the 1996 peace accord. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Mark and Dayle Gruder lost their
home to a tornado. Their insurance policy calls for full
replacement value of the house, but the company wants to knock off
15 percent for depreciation. The precise figure they'll get to
rebuild is still under negotiation. The tornado lasted only a few
eyeblinks, but the Gruders have no idea this nightmare will end for
them. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   CLACK-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ The storm of racial hate that swept
across the life of James Byrd Jr. in Jasper, Texas, can never be
expunged from the nation's consciousness. But in the aftermath of
Byrd's death, hope is seen as Jasper's residents _ black, white and
brown _ reach out to one another. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ This is the 160th anniversary
of Congregation Beth Emeth and the year has been marked with
observances and salutations by its congregants and public figures
from the president on down. The event has religious and secular
significance. By HARRY ROSENFELD
</P>
