<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ What we didn't know until the last few
weeks, when Big Tobacco started spending $40 million to instruct
us, was that any effort to put some bounds around the holocaust of
smoking was just another big government tax-and-spend dodge. What
dummies we are. Brief insights from the editor-in-chief of Cox
Newspapers. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Miners fear that if their
employers are forced to meet federal dust standards, they won't be
able to operate profitably. The workers don't want to lose their
jobs, so they are willing to cheat on dust tests. But today, miners
don't have to pick between lung disease and joblessness. (Geewax,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (k, f)
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ I've been thinking about the struggle of
wills going on in many families where parents are striving to guide
their children safely toward adulthood. These parents are probably
frustrated and exhausted. Clearly, many teenagers are frustrated
and angry. This volatile mix of emotions, if unrelieved by healing
communication between parents and children, portends serious
trouble ahead. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ If you tried to contact your GOP
senator the evening before the Senate's key vote on comprehensive
tobacco legislation, you might have found him out for early
cocktails and dinner. One of the year's biggest fundraisers for the
Republican National Committee and its Senate and House campaign
committees was staged at the Washington Convention Center, courtesy
of big tobacco. (Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ If it has wheels that go
around and it's painted red, you can bet it's in our village this
weekend. It's Gibsonburg's year to host the Northwestern Ohio
Volunteer Fireman's Annual Convention and I dare you to find anyone
who can pronounce all of that after nine o'clock tonight. (Schuett,
Cox News Service) MOVED.
