<P>
   TEENJOBS _ ATLANTA _ With the labor market tight, teenagers are
getting special inducements to go to work. But the jobs aren't any
better. We troll the scene to reel in 10 or so vignettes: Boat
Girl, the Two Angelas, Young Businessman, Mr. Career Move (goes
from Wendy's to Mrs. Winners for an extra 25 cents an hour), Donut
Boys, Princess Diana and more. (Harrison, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   LELAND-RETURNS _ Maybe you weren't at the airport Saturday (June
20), so you did not see a little squirt of a guy get off the Midway
flight from Raleigh, N.C., and you did not see all the kids crowd
around to give him hugs. The World's Smallest Gym Teacher came home
Saturday. And he could breathe. Leland Herring said: ``I have only
one thing to say: This is a miracle.'' (Evans, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SEASONAL-WORKERS _ AUSTIN _ The college-aged workers who usually
snapped up the Travis County, Texas, 45 seasonal parks jobs instead
man drive-through windows. Halfway through spring, the parks
department lacked 32 seasonal workers, thanks in part to the
Austin-area's 2.3 percent unemployment rate in May. (Daniel, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT-SHOES? _ WEST PALM BEACH _ One young kid is standing on the
corner in front of Sam's grocery, Coleman Park, Florida. He's
wearing new Nikes _ so new you can almost smell the box. The laces
are untied, in the dirt, but so white, so clean they or the shoes
or both are quite obviously new. Know anything about all the stolen
shoes? he's asked. What shoes, he says. It's a statement, not a
question. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POOL-ICE _ STUART, Fla. _ Tony Tarallocq was sick of climbing
into a 94-degree pool every day. ``It was, like, not refreshing.''
So he ordered 1,200 pounds of ice for $200, helped push the
300-pound blocks one by one into the deep end, then climbed in
himself. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (d category)
</P>
<P>
   GRILLERS _ AUSTIN _ Cheryl and Bill Jamison of Santa Fe, those
fire fanatics whose cookbooks have copped a couple of James Beard
awards, breezed into Austin last week to talk of things of meat and
heat, especially their latest work, ``Born to Grill'' (Harvard
Common Press, $27.95). Now, Central Texans don't cotton to
outsiders telling us how to play with fire under an open sky. But
who among us has had 15 grills on our patio at once? (Recipes
follow.) (Crider, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GRILLBOOKS _ AUSTIN _ Austin American-Statesman staff reviews
books about outdoor grilling. (Staff, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
