<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX     06-22 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Small town parade means . . . port-a-johns a-plenty
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. If it has wheels that go around and it's
painted red, you can bet it's in our village this weekend. It's
Gibsonburg's
</P>
<P>
   year to host the Northwestern Ohio Volunteer Fireman's Annual
Convention and I dare you to find anyone who can pronounce all of
that after nine
</P>
<P>
   o'clock tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The welcoming banner went up last week, strung between the
appliance store and the insurance office, and streets have been
swept to
</P>
<P>
   within an inch of their bricks. For days, volunteers have been
weeding and planting flowers uptown. Company's coming.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, aluminum recycling bins hit the corners and flatbeds
loaded with portable outhouses came rolling into town. One confused
</P>
<P>
   driver looked like he was going to drop the whole load in my
front yard. We talked, and he moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I asked my sister-in-law what she imagined folks did
before roll-away toilets were invented. ``Went in the bushes, I
guess,'' was her
</P>
<P>
   unconcerned response. She always thinks it's a little odd when I
wonder about stuff like that, but just think about it. Six thousand
people (the
</P>
<P>
   estimated parade-day attendance, and three times the population
of our village) with the urge - where would they go? And even if
there had been
</P>
<P>
   public restrooms available, could a little sewage plant have
handled all of those flushes?
</P>
<P>
   On my front porch, just two blocks west of the one-block
business district, I'm kind of in the thick of things which is
great for parades
</P>
<P>
   and waving at neighbors, but a little dicey when 83 companies,
complete with fire engines (state-of-the-art and antique), rescue
trucks,
</P>
<P>
   campers, golf carts, dogs, daughters, and mothers-in-law, hit
the village streets. Our shady sidewalks are awash in unfamiliar
faces out
</P>
<P>
   for a stroll and a look-see.
</P>
<P>
   This morning I pedaled my bike uptown for some last-minute
shopping and a quick glimpse of the big doin's. The grocery store
was
</P>
<P>
   full, the bakery was jammed, and the restaurant was so confused
they'd gone to a limited menu (just like at home - eat what's on
your plate and
</P>
<P>
   don't complain).
</P>
<P>
   On the ride back, I noted a sign warning revelers: No drinking
beyond this point. Uh huh. Sure, I'm thinking, and if frogs had
</P>
<P>
   wings.... But, if the edict holds, that means hilarity will stop
a block short of my house and I'll be spared some of the racket of
the impromptu
</P>
<P>
   Friday night whoop-de-do where merrymakers pile on firetrucks
and circle the blocks with sirens blasting and horns blaring,
turning our sleepy
</P>
<P>
   village into Hearing-Loss City.
</P>
<P>
   A vintage beauty of a truck with a rocking chair strapped to the
front bumper just rolled by hauling a wagon loaded with firewood
behind
</P>
<P>
   it. Figure that one out.
</P>
<P>
   In a little while, on the high school lawn, firefighters will
get together and turn the hoses on one another - well not exactly.
Opposing
</P>
<P>
   teams will be spraying water at a 15-pound ball on a cable, and
whoever drives the ball into the other team's territory, wins.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon the judges will be electing a convention queen.
Our representative is a pretty little girl I taught 8th-grade
English.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be 18 high school marching bands, and our 1918 Model T
fire truck (the village's first not powered by horses) will lead
the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, friends will wander over and pull up a rocker to watch.
We'll have some refreshments and just kick back to enjoy the
goings-on.
</P>
<P>
   We'll probably be thinking how lucky we are to have a front row
seat on a shady porch for the festivities. I know I will.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, I'll be feeling twice-blessed for not having to
visit one of those moveable outhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
