<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASSMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS NOT LIABLE FOR TEACHER MISDEEDS THEY DON'T KNOW ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ School districts cannot be held responsible when a
teacher sexually harasses or abuses a student if the school
authorities were not informed of the misconduct, the Supreme Court
ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 ruling means that in order to collect monetary damages,
a student must prove that school officials knew of the teacher's
misconduct and chose to ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Congress speaks directly on the subject, we will not
hold a school district liable in damages ... for a teacher's sexual
harassment of a student absent actual notice and deliberate
indifference,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   She noted, however, that the ruling will not affect any right
that a harassed student has to recover monetary damages from a
guilty teacher, or against a school district under some state laws.
But such state cases have proved virtually futile.
</P>
<P>
   Although refusing to hold school districts liable, O'Connor
acknowledged that ``harassment unfortunately is an all too common
aspect of the educational experience ... and that a student suffers
extraordinary harm when subjected to sexual harassment and abuse by
a teacher, and that the teacher's conduct is reprehensible and
undermines the basic purposes of the educational system.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling killed a sexual-harassment lawsuit against a
Texas public school district over a teacher's sexual relationship
with a ninth-grade student.
</P>
<P>
   Because the decision focused exclusively on a school setting
involving teachers and students, it does not apply to on-the-job
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices are expected to say more on that subject in
employment in a pair of decisions to be announced before the court
ends its 1997-98 term this week or next.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the justices are considering whether employers
should be held financially responsible for a supervisor's sexual
misconduct when the victim complained to another supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   In the other pending case, the question is whether a company is
responsible if one of its supervisors harassed a woman and
threatened to make her job difficult unless she succumbed to his
advances but never carried out the threat. She alleged that even
though she received a promotion, she felt compelled to resign
because of a hostile work environment.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's case, Frank Waldrop was 52 and a social studies
teacher at a Lago Vista, Texas, high school when in 1993 police
found him naked in the woods with a 15-year-old student, Alida Star
Gebser.
</P>
<P>
   According to a lawsuit that Gebser and her mother later filed
against the Lago Vista school district near Austin, the sexual
relationship had lasted for about six months. Gebser, now a college
student, apparently told no one about the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in October 1992, parents or guardians of at least two
other girls had complained about what they called inappropriate
comments Waldrop made to their daughters. He met with the parents
and said he had meant no offense. The school principal admonished
Waldrop and considered the matter resolved, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   After the police discovered Waldrop and Gebser having sex in the
woods, Waldrop was fired and stripped of his teaching certificate.
He eventually pleaded no contest to a charge of attempted sexual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge threw out Gebser's lawsuit against the school
district, however, after noting a lack of evidence that any
administrative official knew about the sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the
dismissal of the suit, rejecting arguments that school districts
should be held responsible whenever a teacher sexually harasses a
student.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Supreme Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor's majority opinion were Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the four, Stevens attacked the majority decision,
saying: ``As a matter of policy, the court ranks protection of the
school's district's purse above the protection of immature high
school students that those rules would provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens also said the decision ``thwarts the purposes of Title
IX'' of a 1972 law denying federal aid to schools that allow
discrimination against girls in sports and other school activities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Supreme Court ruled that under the 1972 law
sexually harassed students may collect monetary damages from their
schools and school officials. But it did not say what standard
should be used for imposing liability on a school district for the
intentional acts of one of its teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In their arguments before the court, lawyers for the Lago Vista
school district said it would be unfair to make employers legally
responsible when they don't know that the harassment is taking
place.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Gebser contended that a school district should
provide adequate procedures to prevent, discover and eradicate
sexual harassment. School districts that fail to create a safe
environment, they said, should be held financially liable,
regardless of whether they knew about sexual harassment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
