<HEADLINE>
STORM DOORS ADD PROTECTION AND STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New thermal door technology has reduced the need
for the old storm door, which plainly provided extra protection to
conventional doors from wind, rain and debris.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past several years, the appearance of storm doors
has caught up with the look of exterior doors. While most of us are
familiar with the low-end white aluminum storm door, new models
feature wood and foam cores, solid brass hardware, full-view,
beveled glass panels, brass inlays, etched or stained glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solid wood core makes the door sturdy,'' said Mary Ann
Holler, marketing communications manager for Larson Doors in South
Dakota. ``They are also weather-stripped and don't rattle. The
baked-on enamel finish gives an elegant look to the sheet aluminum
that covers the wood core. In the last five years, the hardware has
been upgraded to brass levers and locks to accent the front
entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Holler said the heavier storm door still adds another barrier to
the front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you open your front door, you're not exposed to the
person on the other side,'' Holler said. ``Many of the new storm
door models also come with a keyed deadbolt lock.''
</P>
<P>
   Storm doors also double as screen doors in summer, by switching
the glass panel to the companion screen panel. Some storm doors
feature a triple-track system to hold both the screen and glass
panel.
</P>
<P>
   A good storm door begins at approximately $100 and goes up to
$250, and high-end models can reach $500 or more.
</P>
<P>
   With the higher-end models, there is often more glass, affording
a better view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large glass panels are beautiful, allowing you to see the
front door,'' Holler said. ``But you might want to consider a kick
panel for the lower half if you have a medium- to large-size dog.
This way, they won't get the glass all muddy or streaked or dent
the screen insert in warm weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers include muntins, or dividers, to give the
door a Colonial flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new wood-core storm doors come in colors to
coordinate with your primary front door or shutters, and some
suppliers offer a warranty that's good for as long as you own your
door.
</P>
<P>
   Storm doors generally carry instructions for the
do-it-yourselfer. Some companies may offer a discounted
installation fee with the sale. But if you purchased a storm door
and need it professionally installed, plan on paying another $190
to $230.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
