<HEADLINE>
TROUBLES IN THE PATH OF A TORNADO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MECHANICVILLE, N.Y. _ Imagine for just a moment that you're
coming off gall bladder surgery, recuperating at home. Imagine that
you hear a tornado warning on the radio. Imagine that you dive for
your basement.
</P>
<P>
   Then imagine that in just a few moments everything you own is
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   You've just imagined that you're Dayle Gruder. She and her
husband, Mark, are New York state workers. Until three weeks ago,
they lived in a three-year-old house atop Ferdinand's Hill in
Mechanicville, an Albany suburb. Then that towering twister roared
through. In only a minute or so, it inflicted about $145 million in
damage to 186 homes and dozens of businesses. Miraculously, it
killed no one. But this thing tore up more than real estate. It
also tore up lives _ among them, the lives of Mark and Dayle
Gruder.
</P>
<P>
   When the Gruders emerged from the rubble of their home, they
were thrilled to be alive and unhurt. But their house was a
shambles. Their cars were scrap metal. The rain drenched down on
them as they surveyed the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks now, the Gruders have been cheered by the
selfless support they've received from neighbors and people
involved in the rescue effort. But they've also had a look, close
up and personal, at the limitations of human institutions in
dealing with disasters like this. The sheer scope of this
catastrophe has meant that many tornado victims, like refugees in
war-torn Europe a half century ago, have essentially been on their
own as they struggle to dig out and rebuild and resume normal
lives.
</P>
<P>
   After the tornado ripped through, rescue workers hustled the
Gruders and other victims off the hill. Strange, jagged lightning
was shooting horizontally through the rain. The storm had ripped
off gas meters, creating vast leaks. A single lightning strike on
that high ground could have been murderous.
</P>
<P>
   In just the clothes they were wearing _ with no money, credit
cards or identification _ they made their way down the hill and to
the home of friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even have toothbrushes,'' Dayle Gruder told me.
``They were very kind to us. They fed us. They bought us
toothbrushes ... The next day, we had to go to a firehouse. They
would bus us back up to the house. I had to have my painkillers. I
was in agony ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Only two people could go to each house. I wasn't allowed to
reach, stretch, pull or pick up anything. So, we had a friend come
up to help, and they would not let the three of us go ...
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I was left behind in the firehouse ... the scanner was
going in the firehouse, and I'm sitting there by myself. And I hear
an officer on the scanner saying, `Oh, my God, there's a huge crowd
getting off. They let them all off the bus at once. We can't
control the crowd. The only thing we can do is shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, nobody got shot. Eventually, the Gruders got a $12,000
advance from their insurance company _ an out-of-state check that
took a week to clear. They found a furnished apartment and rented a
car.
</P>
<P>
   Their insurance policy calls for full replacement value of the
house, but the insurance company wants to knock off 15 percent for
depreciation. The precise figure they'll get to rebuild is still
under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado lasted only a few eyeblinks, but the Gruders have no
idea this nightmare will end for them. Dayle Gruder says that when
the new house is built and furnished, she'll videotape everything,
inside and out, and secure the tape and all the family papers in a
bank safe deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   And pray that no tornado hits that bank.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
