r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GUATEMALA, A BISHOP IS MARTYRED BUT HIS RESEARCH SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Like millions of Guatemalans, Roman Catholic
Bishop Alvaro Ramazzini was stunned when fellow Bishop Juan Gerardi
was beaten to death just two days after he'd presented a major
report on human rights violations in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected this,'' Ramazzini said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the killing, however, nothing that has happened _ or not
happened _ has surprised Ramazzini. The death, deceit, corruption
and cover-up that characterized Guatemala's 36-year civil war did
not disappear with the 1996 signing of a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, personally, feel this crime (Gerardi's murder) will never
be cleared up,'' Ramazzini said earlier this month during a visit
to San Francisco. ``There is no political will to resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   A low-profile, auxiliary bishop with an inner-city parish in
Guatemala City, Gerardi was attacked about 10 p.m. April 26 near
his garage. The assailant used a concrete block to smash his head
from behind, then dragged the 75-year-old priest into the garage
and obliterated his face with more beating.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop's wallet and ring were not taken.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of Guatemala's Archdiocesan Human Rights Office,
Gerardi launched a massive research project in 1995 to document
cases of human rights violations that occurred during the long and
bloody civil war. More than 6,500 eyewitness testimonies were
included in the report, which named and detailed the deaths of some
55,000 Guatemalan victims.
</P>
<P>
   Entitled ``Guatemala, Nunca Mas'' (``never again''), the report
blamed 80 percent of the 200,000 civil war deaths and
``disappearances'' on the Guatemalan military and paramilitary
groups that were backed by wealthy landowners. (Two percent of
landowners control 67 percent of arable land in Guatemala.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite wait-and-see stances by most authorities, including the
U.S. ambassador, there is no doubt in the minds of Gerardi's
colleagues and most Guatemalan people that the bishop was killed
because of the human rights report.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many powerful people in Guatemala who did not want
the report to come out and who do not want the peace process to
continue,'' Ramazzini said. ``This shows if they're capable of
killing a bishop, they're certainly willing to kill anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   A current disinformation campaign against the slain priest _ an
implication that perhaps he was a homosexual and his death a result
_ disgusts Ramazzini but, again, does not surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claims are entirely false,'' he said, shaking his head.
``We interpret them as an intent to manipulate the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Such accusations are akin to charges that, because the Catholic
Church is committed to social justice and human dignity, it is a
front for Communist activity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the killing of Gerardi and an investigation that
Ramazzini says has been inept, at best, the report now has a life
of its own. International human rights groups like the San
Francisco-based SHARE Foundation already are raising money to
publish a million copies of the four-volume report and to draw
worldwide attention to the bishop's death.
</P>
<P>
   SHARE spearheads a campaign to place a two-page ad, signed by
hundreds of U.S. religious and lay leaders, in the National
Catholic Reporter. Among other declarations, the ad calls ``upon
the United States government to press for a full, impartial
investigation'' into Gerardi's death and to declassify U.S.
government information about Guatemala's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bishop Ramazzini: ``If we want to do a spiritual, internal
cleansing, we must bring all violations to light. Guatemalan
society has to face what we have lived. There cannot be a true
reconciliation until the guilty confess their sins, and the victims
can then have an opportunity to forgive them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
