<SLUG> BC-X-FILES-WHO'S-WHO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLOCKING SOME MYSTERIES FOR `X-FILES' NEOPHYTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Let's face it, these ``X-Files'' freaks are
scary people. They are such a collection of geeks and nerds,
wallowing in the minutiae of a television show that their presence
may almost be enough to keep you from checking out a movie that has
you curious.
</P>
<P>
   These ``X-Philes'' communicate in code, know the titles of all
the episodes, and have those encyclopedias so they can tell you
that Owen Lee Jarvis was hired by Susan Kryder to do yard work
after her husband was institutionalized and Jarvis must defend her
son Kevin against the Forces of Darkness in ``Revelations.''
</P>
<P>
   (I borrowed one called ``X-Files Confidential,'' published by
Little, Brown _ Jarvis is killed by Millennium Man and after he
dies his body smells like flowers.)
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to give anyone the heebie-jeebies. But why be
intimidated by some cult? This ``X-Files'' insider stuff is
actually pretty simple. Knowledge of a few key characters and
symbols from the television show is enough to enhance your
enjoyment of the movie while still allowing you to have a complete
life. And no matter what anyone tells you, it's all make believe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agents Fox Mulder and Dana Scully: We'll start real simple
here. Mulder is the guy and Scully is the girl. They are FBI
agents, working on the X files, which deal with unexplained
phenomena. The files were burned up in the last TV episode. Mulder
and Scully want to go to bed but haven't so far. Mulder went to
Oxford and reads a lot of porn and watches adult videos. He
believes in UFOs. Scully has a medical degree, is an expert in
forensics and thinks science can explain everything. She's into
cleaning her gun. On to the esoterica.
</P>
<P>
   _ 10-13: Creator Chis Carter's birthday, it is also the last
four digits of Scully's cell phone number. It's bound to turn up
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cigarette Smoking Man: Also known as Cancer Man, this dude
with the perpetual smoke aflame is part of a group of mystery men,
known as The Syndicate, who are plotting with aliens to take over
the world. Other Syndicate members include the Well-Manicured Man;
a German named Strughold who dabbles in eugenics; and the ageless
Dick Clark, part of the first alien-human crossbreeding experiment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Black Oil: The black oil virus carries the alien life form and
kills ordinary humans who don't have a little alien in them.
Members of the Syndicate also have developed a vaccine so they
don't get killed with everyone else, but chances are they won't
share it, even if you ask nicely.
</P>
<P>
   _ Corn and Bees: These are quick and easy carriers of the virus
and will likely make an appearance in the movie. Choice of these
vehicles for spreading the disease shows how stupid the aliens
really are, because if they really wanted to reach everyone, all
they would have to do is put the virus in boxes of Kraft Macaroni
and Cheese. They would own the world within a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lone Gunmen: Computer hackers who are heavy conspiracy
theorists and help Scully and Mulder whenever possible. They also
appear on the show so hard-core ``X-Philes'' have someone to
identify with. Dweeb City.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mulder's Relatives: His dad worked with Cigarette Man at the
beginning of the alien conspiracy back in '48 or whenever but
bailed out. Mulder's sister was abducted by aliens. Just another
dysfunctional American family.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scully's Crucifix: A little cross worn on a chain around her
neck meant to symbolize a guy from a couple thousand years ago who
could walk on water, was killed and came back to life after a few
days. Man, this sci-fi stuff can get out of hand. OK, save the
letters: The crucifix represents Scully's faith in God as opposed
to Mulder's seeming lack of same. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's lots more, like Mulder and Scully's boss Skinner,
who used to be Cigarette Man's stooge but now seems to be a
straight shooter, or the black helicopters, which symbolize the
shadow government. But this is more than enough. Just remember,
it's supposed to be fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
