<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-EDUCATION-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSENSUS GROWS FOR NEW APPROACHES TO EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen carefully, and you just might hear the walls of an
American monolith _ public education _ starting to crack.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, a national commission on educational
excellence released ``A Nation at Risk,'' a report that said our
schools were ``being eroded by a rising tide of mediocrity that
threatens our very future as a nation and a people.'' Now, the
system is being challenged _ from Milwaukee to San Antonio, from
Maine to California _ by radical reforms that are rapidly making
new alternatives a norm. The message to many school systems seems
clear: ``Change with us or prepare to die by attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the kids are dying,'' says Howard Fuller, the former
superintendent of the Milwaukee public schools, and a strong
advocate of vouchers _ one of the most controversial funding tools
of change _ for low-income students. ``They are dying in reality,
and they are dying academically.''
</P>
<P>
   Such stark talk has begun to mute the long-heard argument that
any challenge to public education threatens the base of democracy
and that programs such as vouchers, which allow parents to take
funds that would be used to teach their children and seek
educational alternatives they like better, are pernicious policies
that help a few students at a high cost and leave many more
wallowing in a system stripped of funding.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levine, president of Teacher's College at Columbia
University, last week came out _ reluctantly, he said _ in support
of vouchers to help the poorest students in the nation's worst
schools that show no signs of improving. In Chicago, if a major
internal reform effort now underway proves ineffective, officials
may implement a voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   A rapidly growing alternative to vouchers is the charter school
movement, under which communities can create new schools with fewer
of the strictures of the traditional ones. In 1992, there was one
charter school in the country. In September, there will be more
than 900. In Massachusetts, 25 charter schools are open, and 25
more are awaiting approval.
</P>
<P>
   While vouchers have not been proposed in Boston, charter schools
have been spreading like wildfire here and elsewhere in the nation.
And each will take money that would have otherwise gone to the
established public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are not only turning to charter schools as a salvation,
educators are as well. Susan Jamback spent 15 years as a teacher
and seven as a principal and thought about speaking out against
charter schools when New Hampshire was debating whether to permit
them.
</P>
<P>
   School reform in and of itself, of course, is nothing new.
Throughout this century, ``sweeping'' reforms have been instituted
through regulation and edicts from governors, state legislators, or
local boards. But such reforms nearly always took place within the
existing system and, if not with its blessing, at least with its
qualified support.
</P>
<P>
   What often is happening now, however, is change from the bottom
up _ individuals so dissatisfied with the system as it is that they
are striking out to start new schools, or desperately trying to get
vouchers that enable the poor (the only ones who heretofore had no
choice) to have options beyond rickety neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vouchers are a way for poor parents to affect the system,''
says Fuller. ``To be frank about it, choice has never been an
issue, it has just been a a matter of who had the choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a new world,'' says Paul Peterson, a professor of
government at Harvard's Kennedy School and director of the program
on education policy and governance. ``How fast this will move is
another question. It may take 50 years for the system to
fundamentally change. It is a very large system, and there are a
lot of vested interests fighting to keep the staus quo. But once
civil rights leaders are on board, then it will all be over with.''
</P>
<P>
   When people talk of vested interests, layered bureaucracies,
they often mean teachers unions, which adamantly oppose vouchers.
But Sandra Feldman, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, says her group is not obstructionist and that teachers'
unions are a strong partner for reform in cities from Boston to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes we have been an obstacle to vouchers,'' says Feldman.
``Vouchers are not reform, they are giving up on the public school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   That some critics have suggested giving up on public education
is a remarkable development, and frightening evidence of profound
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment to the education of the public, and the use of
government funds to pay for it, is as sacred a commitment as you
can get in this country,'' says Paul T. Hill, a University of
Washington education researcher, and coauthor of ``Reinventing
Public Education.''
</P>
<P>
   That commitment, coupled with an entrenched bureaucracy and
polling data that show many Americans concerned with educational
quality in schools other than their own, has traditionally left the
system unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing fast, for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, poor children frequently ended up in vocational
programs, trained to work in factories. If they dropped out of
school, that drew little response. But in a world where blue-collar
jobs are disappearing, a higher level of education is essential to
succeed, says Fuller, now an education professor at Marquette
University and director of the Institute for the Transformation of
Learning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
