<HEADER>
A0365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP VICTORY ON TOBACCO COULD BECOME ASHES IN THE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Democrats needed an issue that would enhance their
chances of winning back control of the US House in November, the
Republicans last week may have handed it to them on a silver ash
tray.
</P>
<P>
   After the GOP Senate leadership orchestrated the defeat of the
massive tobacco bill, key Senate Democrats immediately laid this
defeat at the feet of the GOP leadership and their partner, the
huge tobacco lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats can now claim that the GOP and the tobacco lobby
worked closely together to kill a bill that protects their own
self-interests at the expense of the interests of millions of
school children who might have benefited from the educational and
preventive aspects of the antismoking legislation.
</P>
<P>
   As some Democrats said afterward, the GOP's successful strategy
to kill the tobacco bill was a ``defining moment'' for both
Republicans and Democrats in terms of which party truly has the
best interests of families and children at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic senators pointed out in a joint press
conference after the vote that the GOP leadership and key tobacco
lobbyists are popping champagne corks in celebration. But the
Democrats might also have cause for celebration in the fact that
the GOP now has given them an election issue that they can use.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties are fighting to win over public opinion
on this issue. The Republicans are saying that they killed, not an
effective antismoking bill, but a big tax bill that would have done
more harm than good to the American taxpayer. They did not mention
the fact that the bill included a major tax cut, which Sen. John
McCain, Republican of Arizona and a sponsor of the bill, pointed
out after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, including President Bill Clinton, are saying that
the GOP killed one of the most important bills ever crafted.
Clinton said of the bill, ``It may not be dead tomorrow. And it's
not dead over the long run because the public health need is great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never quit on anything this important in my life, and I
don't intend to stop now,'' he added, further warning the GOP that
it cannot assume that it's ``safe to walk away from the biggest
public health obligation that this country has today.''
</P>
<P>
   US Senator Edward M. Kennedy looked toward November when he said
``No power on earth _ not even the Republican leadership of the
Senate working in an unholy alliance with Big Tobacco _ can stop an
idea whose time has come. It may be that the final vote on this
legislation will occur on election day.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason why the Republicans killed the bill, as a few
Democrats pointed out, was to protect some GOP Senate members and,
if the bill had been sent to the lower chamber, some House members
who may have seen their vote against the bill used against them by
the electorate in their respective districts.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP is hoping to counter the Democrats portrayal of their
alliance with the tobacco lobby by announcing that the House would
file an antismoking bill that would be focused more directly on
teenage smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But, as House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, Democrat of
Missouri, suggested, that bill will likely be little more than a
piece of paper containing words such as: ``Don't Smoke.'' In other
words, any such bill that House Speaker Newt Gingrich offers would
be far more satisfying to the tobacco lobby than to parents who
want to keep cigarettes out of their children's mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Gingirch and other members of the House GOP leadership will try
to file antismoking legislation that would give the appearance of
sincerity, but the Democrats have already warned the electorate
that the real purpose will remain the same: to prevent any real
legislation that will hurt big tobacco and its GOP friends in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while the GOP charged that the defeated tobacco bill
would have been too expensive for the industry, the tobacco
industry saw no problem in spending more than $50 million to run a
national ad campaign aimed at defeating the bill. And, based on
some reports, the industry is preparing to launch another ad
campaign aimed at keeping any true antismoking legislation from
getting passed this year.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the ad campaign, along with GOP efforts, to
prevent passage of such legislation, may backfire.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic strategists will have to effectively counter what
is expected to be a massive and expensive campaign blitz by big
tobacco in the coming months. Although Democrats will not have the
funds to launch a counter-campaign as expensive as the tobacco
lobby's, they will have one thing on their side that can cut
through any campaign built on a foundation of deception and ongoing
greed _ the truth.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats continue their almost daily, factual
explanations of why the GOP killed this legislation, the electorate
will clearly see who is more truthful.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans who lost elections after spending millions on
campaigns this year found out, for example, that no amount of money
can disguise the true intentions of an ad campaign, whether it's
about a candidate or a tobacco bill. And the electorate will know
what party supports truth in packaging.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans fear and the Democrats hope, the voters in
November will know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-EDUCATION-2ND &LR;      06-22 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-EDUCATION-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of Learning.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even before ``A Nation at Risk,'' vast sums were pumped into
fixing the system, particularly in urban schools. More has been
funneled in since, often with little to show for it in better
learning and higher test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Consider figures from Eric Hanushek, an economist at the
University of Rochester who for 30 years has studied educational
policy and performance in schools. He says that between 1970 and
1997, spending adjusted for inflation on a per pupil basis rose by
91 percent and is now at a national average of $6,564 per pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that it has bought us much in terms of
overall improvement or much improvement in terms of distribution,''
says Hanushek. ``There was some black-white improvement in the
'80s, but that seems to have stopped and may even be widening in
the '90s. And the narrowing of those attending college has
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill says that rising frustration is being fed by what he calls
``the politics of hope. A new superintendent comes and says things
will change, but they lose the push or are discredited, or the
proposals are never bold enough to make a difference in the long
run. The result, especially among African-American parents and
leaders, is the sense that the system is not going to fix itself.
That is why there is as much support in the legislature for charter
schools, and business people are willing to fund vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Financier Theodore J. Forstmann, a senior partner at an
investment firm, and John Walton, an heir to the Wal-Mart fortune,
this month committed $100 million to poor students in five cities:
New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, Jersey City, and Washington, D.C.
They hope that money will be matched by other business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the program, Forstmann said public schools had
become stagnant monopolies and needed competition to change.
</P>
<P>
   While the $100 million donation is the single largest ever for
vouchers, the most comprehensive private funding outlay for
vouchers will get underway later this year when $50 million will be
used to give every student in the Edgewood School District, a
predominantly poor and Hispanic district in San Antonio, vouchers
for a seat in another public school district or in a private
school. One state senator said the program ``declares war on public
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Peterson will monitor students who leave Edgewood,
those who stay, as well as students in three control districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find no results, and if a series of studies come in like
that, it will slow the voucher process way down,'' says Peterson.
``But there are some signs from Milwaukee that are positive.''
</P>
<P>
   While vouchers have not been proposed in Boston, charter schools
have been spreading like wildfire here and elsewhere in the nation.
And each will take money that would have otherwise gone to the
established public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are not only turning to charter schools as a salvation;
educators are as well. Susan Jamback spent 15 years as a teacher
and seven as a principal and thought about speaking out against
charter schools when New Hampshire was debating whether to permit
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought schools could be changed from within, but I was
still in denial,'' says Jamback, now principal of the Chelmsford
Public Charter School. ``After many years of minor successes and
major frustrations, I finally decided it was a lost cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I now get to hire everyone. I always had a small group of
teachers I could work with, but never a whole school. I had to
spend too much time cajoling, training, defending, pushing, and the
payoff was not worth the time spent. Now, everyone can move,
comparatively, at lightning speed. I can hire people who are
trained or philosphically aligned and there are no more `Why are we
doing this' questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Educational issues are not the only player in the emerging
drama. Emotional ones are, too. Emotions run high over the
Milwaukee voucher program, as well as one in Cleveland, because
they are publicly funded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take the amount of money spent on vouchers and put in
an all-day kindergarten program for every child,'' says Feldman.
And it is not simply money. There is a finite number of spaces in
private schools _ which educate about 10 percent of the nation's
students. With vouchers, many will be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Even privately funded voucher programs can meet with resistance.
Two years ago, the mayor of Jersey City, N.J., presented a plan to
give some students tax-funded vouchers to attend private schools.
When the state blocked the plan, a local Pepsi distributor offered
to pick up some of the costs. The National Education Association
local organized a boycott, and the company changed its mind.
</P>
<P>
   That voucher programs would take money out of the system to help
a few and leave the majority behind is something even some
reformers find unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sympathetic to the notion if you pull kids out of the
system, it gives them a chance to succeed, but you can't make the
argument that you want to save 100 kids by giving them vouchers and
then abandon the 4,000 left behind,'' says US Senator John Kerry,
the Massachusetts Democrat who last week broke from his party's
tradition of backing teachers' views by calling for the abolition
of seniority that serves to protect teachers who have become burned
out or are ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry says he called for the end of tenure because of what he
has seen in 14 years in Washington. ``I watched the discussions of
education reform. I watched George Bush, and I have heard (Bill)
Clinton talk about it. But our kids still can't read, schools are
falling apart, and bureaucracies in many places are layered and
impenetrable.''
</P>
<P>
   While many public schools work well, Kerry said he could not
``sit here and watch another class of kids graduate'' from schools
that are dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for vouchers improved this month when Wisconsin's
highest court turned aside concerns over the separation of church
and state and ruled that Milwaukee could extend its voucher
program, which serves 1,500 poor students, beyond private schools
to religious ones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
