<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GAMBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN IN CONGRESS FOR GAMBLING OPPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is preparing to act on an array of
legislation that could dramatically alter the nation's booming
casino industry, as an antigambling coalition led by key
Republicans fights GOP leaders to eliminate tax breaks for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the antigambling movement will be tested in the
coming weeks. Congress is ready to consider proposals that would
kill a $3 billion annual tax break for gambling losses, make it
more difficult to build new Indian casinos, and prohibit gambling
on US-based Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Donald Trumps of this world are profiting handsomely from
this business,'' said Representative Patrick Kennedy, a Rhode
Island Democrat, referring to casino owners like the New York real
estate mogul.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trumps of the world _ including his counterparts in Las
Vegas _ are concerned that as Congress turns its attention away
from tobacco, gambling could be the next target.
</P>
<P>
   The antigambling movement is led by a group of religious
conservatives, notably the influential James Dobson of Focus on the
Family. Dobson is working with Republicans such as Senators Dan R.
Coats of Indiana and John Ashcroft of Missouri to enact bills
intended to slow the explosive growth of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the gambling industry has mobilized a massive
lobbying and fund-raising drive to influence the outcome of the
legislation. The industry quadrupled its political contributions in
1996 and hired former Republican Party chairman Frank Fahrenkopf as
its chief lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Fahrenkopf is the head of the American Gaming Association, which
represents most major commercial casinos but not the tribal
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Fahrenkopf said he became concerned that
there were no strings attached to the money that casinos were
contributing to campaigns. He instituted a requirement that
candidates listen to the lobbyists' message before getting the
donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were leaving Las Vegas without knowing a thing about our
industry,'' said Fahrenkopf, referring to candidates who came to
the gambling mecca for quick fund-raising trips. ``I said they have
to give us an hour and a half of time before a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress have been happy to comply. Many
congressional leaders, including House minority leader Richard A.
Gephardt of Missouri and Senate majority leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi, visited Las Vegas recently and returned with large
campaign donations. All told, gambling interests delivered nearly
$4 million in unregulated ``soft money'' to the political parties
during the 1996 campaign and are on track to give a similar amount
this election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos are hoping to see the payoff. They appear to be placing
their biggest bet on Lott, who last week helped kill tobacco
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, casino construction has exploded in
Lott's state, making Mississippi the third-largest source of casino
revenues, after Nevada and New Jersey, according to industry
officials. Lott flew aboard a jet owned by Mirage Resorts owner
Stephen A. Wynn to attend one of the fund-raisers put on by
Nevada's gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent has been very helpful,'' said Senator Richard H. Bryan,
a Nevada Democrat who has led the way in protecting the casino
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Lott prevented a vote on a proposal to
eliminate the $3 billion deduction for gambling losses. Under
current tax law, gamblers can deduct losses from their winnings,
reducing their tax bills substantially. But Lott agreed to allow
backers to try attaching it to a different bill, perhaps as soon as
July.
</P>
<P>
   If Lott hopes to save the gambling deduction as he defeated the
tobacco bill, he could be in for a surprise. Some of his key
tobacco allies, including Ashcroft, have parted company when it
comes to gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would not be a tax hike,'' Ashcroft said about his
support for eliminating gambling loss deductions. ``This is the
elimination of a subsidy for something that is not a productive
enterprise.'' Ashcroft said a backlash against the growth of the
gambling industry in the last decade will lead to public support
for killing the subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Indian leaders, meanwhile, are concerned about a Senate effort
to limit their ability to establish new casinos. Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt has proposed that his department be able to mediate
between a tribe and a governor when a state will not negotiate in
good faith on a tribal casino. Senate leaders have blocked
Babbitt's request for this authority, ``basically making it
possible for a state to just stall everything, and we have no
recourse,'' said Babbitt spokesman Michael Gauldin.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group of California tribes that have been unable to
come to terms with Governor Pete Wilson came to Washington to lobby
Congress and the administration for the right to establish gambling
operations. Two tribes have hired Lanny Davis, who until earlier
this year was President Clinton's special counsel on the
campaign-finance investigation. Davis helped arrange delivery of a
letter from the tribes to Clinton. He also sat in on a meeting
between the tribes and members of Congress, as well as a session
with Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes are also lobbying heavily for a measure introduced
last week by Rhode Island's Kennedy. Kennedy, the founder of the
congressional Native American Caucus, wants the Narragansett tribe
in his state to have the right to build a bingo hall.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy's support for the bill turned into a demonstration
of the power of antigambling forces. Rhode Island's two senators,
its second House member, and the governor quickly blasted Kennedy's
proposal and vowed to kill it. Kennedy, who has received more
campaign contributions from gambling interests than all but three
House members, acknowledges that the bill faces an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   Many Rhode Island political leaders point to a 1978 agreement to
provide 1,800 acres to the tribe in exchange for the state's
keeping jurisdiction over the land. In 1994, Rhode Island voters
rejected a referendum that would have allowed the tribe to build a
casino. Then in 1996, Senator John Chafee, a Rhode Island
Republican, backed legislation that bars the tribe from operating a
gambling enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, arguing that Chafee's measure violates the tribe's
rights, is backing a bill that would repeal it. Chafee said
Kennedy's measure ``allows bureaucrats in Washington to make the
decision to expand gambling in our state, something we know our
citizens and voters oppose.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Kennedy said he personally opposes gambling.
But he said the Narragansett tribe, as a federally recognized
sovereign nation, should be allowed to operate a bingo hall that
would help lower the tribe's high unemployment rate. Moreover, he
noted that Rhode Island already profits from gambling revenues from
dog tracks, keno, and slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hypocritical for the leadership of Rhode Island to
say they are for denying the Narragansetts the very same revenues
that the state profits handsomely from,'' said Kennedy, whose
district does not include the tribal land.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy received $24,000 from gambling interests in this
election cycle as of June 1, according to the nonpartisan Center
for Responsive Politics. The three House members who received more
were Nevada's representatives _ Republicans John Ensign and Jim
Gibbons _ and Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Casino lobbyists, meanwhile, are urging Congress to ban Internet
gambling on the grounds that it is unregulated. But the lobbyists
acknowledge that casinos have another reason for opposing on-line
gaming. ``Competition, sure,'' said Roger Stone, a lobbyist for
Trump.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether Congress will act on any of these
issues before receiving a report from the Gambling Impact Study
Commission, which was established in 1996 and is not slated to
deliver a report until 1999. The commission includes casino
operators and casino critics such as Dobson, raising doubt whether
the panel can agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
