<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-VENICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL WE ALWAYS HAVE A VENICE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The city known as ``La Serenissima'' has had a Jewish ghetto
since 1516, when the Venetian government set aside land for Jews
exiled from other countries. The word ``ghetto,'' in fact, comes
from the Italian word for metal casting: The site of the ghetto had
previously been home to a foundry.
</P>
<P>
   By 1650 there were 5,000 Jews in Venice. Now there are fewer
than 500, and only 20 or so live in the ghetto, where there are,
however, still five synagogues. The German Synagogue, dating from
1528, is the oldest, occupying the top floor of an apartment
building: No one could live above God, and there wasn't enough
space in the ghetto for a free-standing synagogue. The German
Synagogue's leaky roof has damaged its precious frescoes; the angle
of its floor makes the Leaning Tower of Pisa seem straight. Its
upkeep, and that of its sister synagogues, are a crushing
responsibility for the tiny Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Save Venice. Prompted by the cataclysmic floods of 1966, a
small group of concerned Bostonians led by Wellesley College art
historian John McAndrew and his wife, Betty, started the first of
the two dozen private international committees that work to rescue
Venice from the ravages of weather, time, and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Save Venice grew from a volunteer group raising
a few thousand dollars a year to a professionally run charity with
an annual budget hovering around $1 million and a New York branch
that is an altogether larger and more glamorous affair than its
older sister in Boston. The organization has learned sophisticated
marketing. There's even a new Venice Collection of home
furnishings, launched at Bloomingdale's this past winter. A
percentage of sales from the Venetian-inspired bed linens, lamps,
tableware, and furniture goes to the Save Venice cause.
</P>
<P>
   Save Venice's woman on the scene is Melissa Conn, a vivacious
young American art historian who works out of the organization's
office on the Grand Canal, just across from the Accademia, that
treasure-trove of Tintorettos, Titians, and Bellinis. Conn recently
led me through the city's baffling maze, to the Venice beyond the
pigeon-infested St. Mark's Square, where daytripping tourists begin
and end their visits, to the Venice of the dark, meandering
canal-side streets that John Singer Sargent loved to paint.
</P>
<P>
   She showed me some of Save Venice's completed projects and some
for the future. We saw the thundering equestrian statue of Orazio
Baglioni, the commander of the Venetian army who died defending the
city in 1617. Once gray with filth, the statue has now been
restored, its original gilding gleaming once again against the
darkness of the church of SS. Giovanni e Paolo. We saw a young
restorer, Toto Bergamo, cleaning marble reliefs in the church of S.
Francesco della Vigna, which is in a neighborhood too poor to
afford the work on its own. Using poultices and toothbrushes,
Bergamo will labor for the better part of a year to remove
centuries of soot left from candles. We saw the Scuola Grande di
San Marco, one of the greatest examples of early Renaissance
architecture in Europe, which currently has weeds growing out of
cracks in the marble facade and clunky glass and iron screens that
protect the exterior marble reliefs from soccer balls flying over
from the adjacent square. Venice is not an outdoor museum: People
live _ and play _ here.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration costs vary as widely as Save Venice's projects, from
the $5,000 the Boston chapter's Young Friends raised to restore
``Il Gobbo di Rialto,'' the much-loved 16th-century statue of a
hunchback that supports the pulpit where new laws were proclaimed,
to the $4 million that the organization as a whole raised to bring
Santa Maria dei Mira-coli back to glory. The Miracoli _ recently
and triumphantly reopened after a decade-long effort _ is Save
Venice's biggest project to date, and the only Italian church ever
completely restored, inside and out, in a single continuous
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Save Venice operates in one of the world's most surreal cities.
It's a place that holds a special fascination for Bostonians, in
part because Venice's Palazzo Barbaro, home to several generations
of the expatriate branch of Boston's Curtis clan, was the
inspiration for the museum that Isabella Stewart Gardner built on
the Fenway. Gardner was a guest at the Curtises' palazzo. So were
Sargent and Claude Monet, two of Boston's best-loved painters. So
was Henry James, who used it as a setting for ``The Wings of the
Dove.'' I was invited to sip peach juice with the current Curtis in
residence, Patricia, whose great-grandparents had bought the place
in 1872. Patricia Curtis, who grew up in Europe and has never been
to Boston, lives in splendor _ but worries about the endless upkeep
of a 15th-century palace that includes a library filled with gilded
furniture and leather-bound books, under a curved ceiling that is a
riot of plasterwork and frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Conn worries, too, and not only about the projects Save
Venice tackles. Over those she has some control. But there's the
huge issue of the future of the city itself. ``We could have a huge
onslaught of bus after bus in the year 2000, which the Pope has
declared a pilgrimage year,'' Conn says.
</P>
<P>
   One Italian minister fought for holding a millennial world's
fair, Expo 2000, in Venice. Preservationists fought back, arguing
that the influx of visitors would irreparably damage the city's
fragile fabric. They won _ the battle, not the war.
</P>
<P>
   Venice's champions are always coming up with schemes to control
tourism. One is to charge an entrance fee to the city itself,
treating it like a Colonial Williamsburg or a Disney theme park.
Venice hasn't gone out of its way to be accessible to tourists in
the past. Churches filled with art treasures used to have hours
that were erratic at best, at the whims of poorly paid caretakers
who tended to close them for three-hour lunches. Recently, many
churches have agreed to stay open from 10 to 5 _ and also to charge
admission of about $2.
</P>
<P>
   With the dwindling of their congregations, the churches are
acting more like museums. As for museums themselves, Venice's
greatest, the Accademia, which is stuffed with Tintorettos,
Veroneses, and Bellinis, used to be open only in the mornings. Now,
it's not only open in the afternoons, but until 10 most nights.
This means more tourists, mostly daytrippers coming by bus, since
there is no available land in the city to build more hotels. It
means more tourist money. It also means more wear and tear on frail
buildings. And that means more demands for help from Save Venice.
</P>
<P>
   While that help is urgently needed, the private committees can't
come across as high-handed foreigners. Save Venice works under the
supervision of Italian government agencies, and also under the
watchful eye of UNESCO. And it works discreetly. Except in the very
few cases when a project has been undertaken as a memorial to
someone, there are no plaques on Save Venice restorations.
</P>
<P>
   One of those exceptions is the current restoration of a painting
that has long been a mystery, the huge ``Supper at Emmaus'' in the
Church of San Salvador. Save Venice took on the project in memory
of Sydney Freedberg, the Boston-born art historian who became a
legend in his field during three decades of teaching at Harvard,
who was a leader in Save Venice, and who died last year. Authorship
of the painting has long been debated; some scholars argued that it
was a Giovanni Bellini. During its current cleaning, though,
restorers not only discovered a date of 1513 under the filth, they
also decided the painting was definitely by Carpaccio. The world of
Renaissance art is abuzz with this news. Freedberg, a super-sleuth
in attributing art, would have enjoyed sharing in this discovery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
