<HEADLINE>
BOB AND MARGARET ARRIVE, OH SO POLITELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BOB AND MARGARET 
Created by: David Fine and Alison Snowden 
On: Comedy Central 
Time: Mondays at 10:30 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bob &AMP; Margaret,'' the new animated series on Comedy Central,
is about as far from ``South Park'' as biscuits and tea are from
cheesy poofs. This droll slice of British life is the polite new
townhouse on TV's block of ``cartoons for adults,'' which already
includes ``King of the Hill,'' ``Dr. Katz: Professional
Therapist,'' ``Daria,'' and, of course, ``The Simpsons.'' It's a
slight but charming domestic comedy, one that milks affectionate
humor out of the quiet eccentricities of its ordinary middle-aged
characters, a London dentist and his podiatrist wife.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-episode series, on Comedy Central Monday nights at 10:30,
is based on the 1995 Oscar-winning short film ``Bob's Birthday.''
The creation of husband-and-wife team David Fine and Alison
Snowden, it covers familiar relationship territory with an
appealing modesty _ sort of like a marriage sitcom on the order of
``Mad About You'' but with a muted, laugh-track-free veneer. The
main characters don't display the edginess and directness so common
in American TV comedy, which may be why they have been designed
with long pink faces, round red noses, and hair like blobs of
soft-serve ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the kitcheny coziness of ``Bob &AMP; Margaret'' are the
couple's two very hungry dogs, who have a habit of stealing scenes
as they joyously beg, steal, lick, and sneak any morsel of human
food left unattended for a single moment. Bob doesn't especially
like the pooches, working their tails into a happy frenzy by saying
in an excited voice, ``Do you want to go to the vet and be put to
sleep?'' Margaret, on the other hand, is protective of her brood,
unaware that she's under heavy surveillance from the dogs during
her snack. One of the subtleties of ``Bob &AMP; Margaret'' is that
while the couple lead a reserved existence, their dogs flamboyantly
pursue their own appetites.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent source of the comedy on the show comes from pitting
the low-key, ambivalent Bob and Margaret against more aggressive
and predatory people. Tonight, Bob's practice is threatened when a
glitzy young dentist opens up shop across the street. Bob's
patients and his secretary are seduced by the new guy and pay him a
visit, and even Margaret, who has chipped her tooth on some dog
food, ends up in his shiny chair. In the third episode, which airs
July 6, Bob and Margaret go on a health kick and find themselves in
a game of badminton with a pushy and cheating woman, who finally
whacks her boyfriend unconscious with her racket. Compared to this
unbearable couple, Bob and Margaret's social awkwardness looks
almost lovable.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, an animated series can offer its producers respite
from high star salaries. But animated shows also come with creative
advantages, as they are sometimes able to evoke more of human
nature than comedies featuring real actors. ``Dr. Katz:
Professional Therapist,'' which begins its fifth season tonight at
10 on Comedy Central, is one of the most enjoyable of them. It toys
masterfully with the line between comedy and psychosis, as
well-known comedians show up in animated form to undergo a session
with the good doctor. They deliver what resembles comedy routines,
but in the context of therapy, the routines sound quite different _
usually fairly bonkers. Tonight, cigarette-smoking man Denis Leary
shows up as a father who goes into a few scary tirades about the
stress of raising children. On ``Dr. Katz,'' the squiggly
characters pulsate with the sort of anxiety that Bob and Margaret
work hard to keep at bay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0384 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-VENICE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     06-22 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-VENICE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... this discovery.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After its restoration, ``Supper at Emmaus'' will return to its
original position in the Contarini Chapel in San Salvador. Keeping
paintings and sculpture in the churches and palazzi for which they
were designed, in their original architectural settings, is part of
Save Venice's mission. That also means the art isn't pampered as it
is in a climate-controlled museum with state-of-the-art security.
But this is art that has _ or at least had _ a different meaning
and function than ``museum'' art. It's startling to see holes
circling the face of a madonna who is the central figure in an
altarpiece. The holes are for nails, to hang crowns and jewelry on
the painting in celebration of the Virgin's feast days. To the
celebrants, this madonna is part of a religious rite, not art for
art's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Most Save Venice projects have involved Roman Catholic churches,
because that's where most of the art is. But now Save Venice is
helping to save the Jewish ghetto. To many, ``Venice'' plus
``Jewish'' equals Shakespeare's Shylock, the greedy moneylender of
``The Merchant of Venice.'' Shakespeare's treatment of Shylock as
the ``other'' is actually helpful in understanding the sense of a
separate reality in Venice's ghetto. On the interior of its brick
wall is a series of powerful contemporary bronze reliefs by
Lithuanian artist Arbit Blatas, commemorating the Holocaust; the
wall is topped with barbed wire, to suggest the Nazi death camps.
Laundry lines stretch across the windows of the low- &QC; 
ceilinged apartments squashed under the German Synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venice is already strange,'' says Sandro Romanelli, the former
president of the Jewish Community, a position that's a holdover
from the days when the ghetto had its own internal government.
``You get to the ghetto and it's even stranger.'' Consider, for
instance, the Christian-style bas-reliefs of biblical stories in
the French synagogue. Because of the Jewish prohibition on graven
images, the stories are told without any people. The Red Sea parts
_ but Moses is nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Romanelli thinks big. He plans to convert a large home for the
elderly, which is increasingly underpopulated as the number of Jews
in the ghetto declines, into a major cultural center. He also plans
to see the German synagogue restored. At the moment, the marble
floor of its oval-shaped central room tilts so dramatically that
were you on skates, you'd roll downhill. Venetian floors and walls
typically tilt at alarming angles; one reason is that canal
dredging, a periodic necessity, causes foundations to shift. ``My
living room is like this, too,'' says Conn. ``When I wash the
floor, the water slides to one end.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 15th century, Nicolo di Pietro's 1408 painting
of the Madonna and Child had acquired a reputation for causing
miracles. So many Venetians made votive donations to it that there
was finally enough money to build a church around the painting. The
Church of the Miracoli, designed by the Lombardo family of
architects and sculptors and dedicated in 1488, is long, slim, and
vessel-like, as if it were about to float down the canal that
borders it. The Miracoli is clad, inside and out, in richly veined
marbles, in the colors of honey and champagne, rubies and emeralds.
But by the 20th century, the hues both delicate and dramatic were
muted by filth. And 19th-century restorers had made matters worse,
by putting cement between the marble and the brick core, which
attracted and held water, with its corroding salts. In the Save
Venice restoration, the marbles were removed, soaked in deionized
water to remove the salts, and reattached to the brick with metal
hooks that allow air to circulate. Metal hooks had been used in the
first place. ``A lot of what we do,'' says Conn, ``is correcting
19th-century restoration. The original is often better.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Miracoli glistens in the sun, the effect amplified by
its reflection in the canal. It looks more like an oversize jewel
casket or reliquary than a mere building. How to keep the Miracoli
sparkling is now the challenge. Pigeons, and their acid-laden
droppings, are an eternal problem. The Miracoli now sports hundreds
of ``pigeon spikes.'' Metal needles protruding from flat surfaces
to prevent pigeon-landings, they're virtually invisible, much less
conspicuous than the netting that is the usual alternative. And in
the canal beside the Miracoli, the poles that held up the
scaffolding during the restoration have intentionally been left in
place, to prevent gondoliers from pushing off the marble walls.
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet corner of the island of the Lido, with St. Mark's
Square a distant backdrop, is the Jewish cemetery, on a tract of
land the Venetian government ceded to the Jewish community in 1386.
The thousands buried here over the centuries have not been left to
rest in peace. Their tombstones were unceremoniously uprooted and
tossed aside during periods of war, foreign occupation, and road
building. The carved images on those stones are a surprising mix of
faces, feathers, crowns, masks, putti. All manner of images, both
Jewish and Christian, make an appearance, the iconography often
determined by the Jew's country of origin rather than the
proscriptions of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Great writers including Goethe and Shelley made pilgrimages to
this cemetery, whose mournful wildness perfectly suited the
temperament of Romantic-era writers. In 1834, the French author
George Sand threw a famous temper tantrum here, documented by poet
Alfred de Musset, who wrote that Sand ran ``jumping from tomb to
tomb,'' an indication that the stones were lying flat on the ground
rather than upright. Many of them still are.
</P>
<P>
   For most of this century, the cemetery has been neglected,
choked by spontaneous vegetation, including bamboo that grows in
the areas most in need of draining, the carving on the toppled
stones worn down by puddles left after rains. For the past 20
years, Cesare Vivante, a prominent member of Venice's Jewish
community, has worked to convince the world that the cemetery
urgently needs, and deserves, restoration. Thanks to Save Venice,
plus help from other charitable and government sources, his dream
is finally coming true. The restoration of the cemetery has an
estimated $400,000 price tag: Save Venice is contributing $60,000.
Even with the other contributions, though, there is still about
$80,000 left to raise.
</P>
<P>
   In a sunny spot in the adjacent ``new cemetery,'' where Jews
have been buried since the 18th century, Aldo Izzo, the former
Italian naval officer now in charge of maintaining both Jewish
cemeteries, has set up a ``lapidarium'' _ a hospital for
tombstones, where they wait their turn to be cleaned, consolidated,
and conserved, which costs around $1,100 per stone. Several
restored stones now stand proudly upright again, their carving
legible once more.
</P>
<P>
   All burial grounds are an issue in Venice. Space is so tight in
the city's main cemetery that the deceased get to stay underground
for only a few token years before being dug up and packed into
slots in cemetery walls. Foreigners buried in Venice are more
fortunate. Distinguished citizens of the world including
Stravinsky, Diaghilev, and Ezra Pound are permanently interred in a
separate foreigners' cemetery. John and Betty McAndrew are buried
there, too. And every November on All Saints' Day, Melissa Conn
lays flowers on their graves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
