<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FREEDOMLAND-BOS &LR;      06-22 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FREEDOMLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CINEMATIC STORY IN BLACK AND WHIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FREEDOMLAND 
By Richard Price. Broadway Books. 548 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As cinematic as artillery against a night sky, ``Freedomland''
is a big, blustery novel with a story at its center just as
incendiary. Set over the course of five summer days in the projects
of a black community near Newark, it crackles with a visual realism
and dialogue so pitch-perfect you can almost see the credits
rolling in a darkened theater. No big shocker there: Richard Price
is one of the few highly regarded American novelists to work
Hollywood and actually appear to like the place. Long appreciated
for the flinty, inner-city truths of such novels as ``The
Wanderers'' and ``Clockers,'' he's also been lauded for the
tough-boy screenplays (among them ``The Color of Money''). His
style is half dialogue coach, half urban anthropologist. Emile Zola
and Tom Wolfe are the guys on his literary corner, and what he
lacks in psychological depth or literary interiors, he provides in
sweep and street-smart authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   That savvy affection for veritas took Price to the headlines, to
the 1994 catastrophe of Susan Smith and her missing children in
South Carolina, for the subject matter of ``Freedomland'': A white
mother whose fabricated story about a black carjacker masks her own
role in her son's disappearance. Price must have figured that
incident for all it was worth, seeing within it the elements of
tragedy, betrayal, psychopathic hubris, a race card played and then
sullied beyond repair. By transplanting the rough outlines of the
Smith saga to a housing project in the urban Northeast, he has
brought a horrific tale into his own intimate milieu. The result is
a near-hallucinatory novel, replete with the palpable details of
24-hour police work, tabloid journalism, murderous summer nights,
and, worst of all, a mother whose mind seems to be breaking page by
page.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Martin is 32, a teaching aide in the Dempsy, N.J.,
projects who lives in the neighboring white working-class community
of Gannon. When the novel opens, she's stumbling through Dempsy at
9 p.m., her hands bloodied, oblivious to everything around her. At
the hospital emergency room, she tells her story through a haze of
shock and denial: Her car was stolen by a young black man, she
insists; she was thrown clear and injured; her 4-year-old son,
Cody, was in the back seat. Witness to this fractured testimony is
Lorenzo Council, a 47-year-old black detective for whom Dempsy's
day-to-day heartbreaks are a personal mission. He's arrogant,
gregarious, and compellingly human, a man with his own personal
turmoil who wants to save everybody else worth saving, or at least
give them a chance. Lorenzo quit drinking several years ago; since
then, he's had to rely on hope and his own volition to do his
consistently impossible job. And now he's got a white woman
unraveling on him, by turns copping to the minor sins of motherhood
or trying to escape into the netherworld of her CD headphones.
Whatever evil Brenda Martin may have committed, she hardly seems
capable now of anything more demanding than monstrous incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   The other onlooker to this unwinding drama is Jesse Haus, a
young stringer for the Dempsy Register who has ``converted
journalism into a track and field event.'' Pumped up and ruthlessly
single-minded, Jesse lives for the deadline and the story for all
the usual vicarious reasons: If she can break the lock on Brenda's
precarious psyche, she'll gain access to a place most people
wouldn't go on a million-dollar dare. With Lorenzo propping up
Brenda in order to interrogate her, and Jesse offering the woman a
fake-benign protection from the rest of the media frenzy, the two
form a kind of ravaged contract both to guard and to break their
suspect-victim. Jesse wants an exclusive; Lorenzo wants to find a
child _ &UR;  &LR; or, barring that, solve a murder.
</P>
<P>
   That we suspect from the outset the fate of Cody Martin doesn't
really rob ``Freedomland'' of its punch. Instead, that knowledge
lends the novel a merciless inevitability, propelling it toward
Brenda's dissolution and the town of Dempsy's enraged comprehension
of her acts. Initially a barricade is set up in the projects to
isolate suspects, then a bogus arrest is made. Calling her rewrite
man every few hours, Jesse is becoming dangerously frenzied; nobody
has slept, and Lorenzo's so stooped over from asthma that the
reader can barely breathe. By the time a save-the-children group
shows up to accelerate the search, leading Brenda through the
grounds of an abandoned mental institition, the tension in
``Freedomland'' is so exquisitely rendered that any revelation _
even one of ineradicable darkness _ would come as a relief.
</P>
<P>
   You can feel the imprint of celluloid all over Price's novel:
That's the unstoppable power of it, and it's also responsible for
the book's limitations. This is a screen treatment set to text,
with brilliant depictions of Dempsy's residents, with crosscutting
that dances flawlessly from one dramatic cameo to the next. The
racial and class anxieties between the projects and the police,
between Dempsy and Gannon, are handled with depth and insight; it
is also refreshing to read a novel (particularly one written by a
white man) where you have to work to figure out a character's race,
rather than simply assuming he or she is white. But Price is so
agile (and fanatically detailed) at setting up scenes that the
shots themselves begin to feel endlessly repetitious: the first
third of the novel, for instance, takes place over a mere seven
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda herself, the sorrow-ridden antagonist who has almost
caused an entire city to burn, is delivered to us externally,
through Price's use of gesture and language. We begin to understand
her frailty and the horrendous consequences of her amorphous sense
of self through painstaking images _ Brenda disappearing into the
soulful world of her headphones, listening to her ``hit parade of
lamentation,'' Brenda chopping off her hair or writing Cody's name
across eight pages of a composition book. These are action clues so
exactingly creepy they render this broken woman with surprising
gravitas: We might not be able to bear what she may have done, but
we know with wrenching certainty who she is.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse's tough-girl reporter is hardly envisioned with such
complexity. She waffles between over-identification with her
subject and callous disregard; no reporter, no matter how
sentimental or ambitious, was ever so guilty of both traits
simultaneously. It's also hard to imagine that a cop would hand
over his chief suspect to a reporter for safe-keeping for hours on
end, regardless of how much Lorenzo and Jesse begrudgingly trust
each other. What does come through with intricate credibility is
the bizarre, shipwreck intimacy among all these players _ the
obsessional reality of a world constructed and shared over the loss
of a child.
</P>
<P>
   If Brenda Martin is the maelstrom of despair in ``Freedomland,''
Price has also given us the more far-reaching tragedy of Dempsy's
agonies _ the barricades nobody can see, built by racism and
poverty and still standing long after Brenda is gone. Poised for
trouble, hellbent on protecting Dempsy's residents from their own
fury, Lorenzo explains his devotion to a neighborhood activist: ``I
just want to keep people safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Safe,'' his old friend counters, in what is possibly the
grimmest exchange in the book. ``Safe for what?''
</P>
<P>
   With its chillingly accurate dialogue, its comprehension of a
personal calamity and the mile-wide fallout, ``Freedomland''
manages to be outraged and tender at once. And the novel has a
moral center as certainly as Lorenzo has a calling. Hollywood may
have counseled Richard Price on how to see, but it surely hasn't
told him how to feel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Caldwell is chief book critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
