<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S TV PLANS FOR CLINTON IRK US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton prepares for this week's
summit in China, his advisers have been stung by threats from the
Beijing government not to broadcast his speeches live to an
audience of more than 1 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``technical difficulties,'' Chinese authorities have told
a White House advance team that it will be nearly impossible to
show several toasts and speeches live with simultaneous
translation.
</P>
<P>
   The US officials say the Chinese are making excuses. Taped,
delayed broadcasts will give President Jiang Zemin's government
time to edit Clinton's speeches, toning down or deleting any calls
for democratic openings and improvements in human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that it's a technical problem _ I mean, they
have television,'' said Stanley Roth, the assistant secretary of
state for Asian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The advance teams are still working on the final details of
several prickly topics, including Chinese sales of nuclear
technology to Pakistan and Iran, wording about the ballooning US
trade deficit with China, and sales of high-tech equipment to
Beijing. But for days, Jiang's representatives have been
intransigent on the subject of television coverage of the nine-day,
five-city visit, according to officials in the White House and the
State Department. Clinton is to arrive in China on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When they were assured anonymity, several of the officials
expressed irritation at the recent rounds of negotiations with the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you might expect, the Chinese are completely paranoid and
neurotic about this,'' said an official familiar with the
discussions in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The official added that the National Security Council, which
advises Clinton on foreign policy, has decided that soon after
arriving Clinton must make an unmistakable call for a democratic
opening in China. ``Sometimes when you're paranoid, there's a good
reason,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, the Chinese are well aware that the Chinese
know Clinton will couch any criticisms in the soft phrases of
diplomacy. ``Clinton will keep his message subtle ... he's not
going to make a frontal assault on their system. He's not going to
say, `Your leaders are a bunch of Leninist thugs.'''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Clinton will make about 15 public speeches during the
visit. The White House was initially interested in a ``town
meeting'' at Beijing University or another site, but that has been
scaled down to be a talk to students.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Americans, Chinese officials are planning to
broadcast excerpts from Clinton's remarks at the forum with
students at Beijing University and at other venues.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's government has not formally announced its decision about
broadcasting, and the US negotiators are reluctant to talk publicly
because they hope for last-minute concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese Embassy in Washington did not return calls asking
for a comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are especially irked because in February 1989,
China had the know-how to broadcast a live nationwide speech by
President George Bush. It was the first time a foreign leader's
remarks had been shown live in China. Bush was given a spot in
prime time, just before broadcast of immensely popular Donald Duck
and Mickey Mouse cartoons in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials estimated that the 15-minute broadcast reached
an audience of 400 million people or more. Bush, who had lived in
Beijing, was seen as a friend of China. He and his secretary of
state, James A. Baker III, avoided public comments about human
rights during their two-day stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased that we had negotiated a way for Bush to talk
directly to the Chinese people,'' said Winston Lord, who served as
US ambassador to China at the time. ``As I recall, that didn't
require a lot of heavy lifting'' on the part of US negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was a different era. The crackdown on
demonstrators at Tiananmen Square was four months away and the
controversy over China's contributions to American polical
campaigns had not started.
</P>
<P>
   By airing Clinton's remarks unedited, the Chinese would be
returning a courtesy, administration officials said. When Jiang
spoke at the White House, Harvard University and other sites at a
summit last fall, his speeches were broadcast to Americans,
sometimes on C-Span and sometimes on other channels.
</P>
<P>
   To Jiang's advisers, though, that was exactly the problem. They
were smarting when Clinton used a memorable phrase to reprimand
Jiang at a White House exchange, broadcast live: ``You are on the
wrong side of history,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
