<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !! ``Dream for an Insomniac''  Slight but sunnily diverting romance
played out among the staff and regulars in a family-owned
coffeehouse in San Francisco. MacKenzie Astin, Ione Skye, and
Jennifer Aniston keep the cappuccino foaming. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
--- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``Hav Plenty''  &LR; Christopher Scott Cherot wants so badly for you
to like his first film, a lightweight comedy about the vagaries of
attraction, that that you almost feel sorry when it just doesn't
work. Even a standout performance by Tammi Jones, as a pushy
Francophile, can't pull this out of the fire. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! 1/2 ``High Art''  &LR; Invigorating, risk-taking film about SoHo
types trying to figure out how much of themselves to parcel out to
get what they want. Ally Sheedy is haunting, delivering the career
re-entry performance of the year as a talented but fragile
self-exiled photographer attracted to an ambitious careerist. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! 1/2 ``Mulan''  &LR; Disney, back in top form with a fresh treatment
of a Chinese legend about a girl who disguises herself as a male
soldier, empowering herself and saving her country. Although closer
to Disney formula than to Chinese culture, its theme of women's
self-determination will strike a universally popular chord.
``Mulan'' is Disney's best since `The Lion King.'' (G)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FU)!! 1/2 ``The Opposite of Sex''  &LR; This study of familial and
sexual dysfunction is rudely funny in its first half, draggy in its
second. But it's a wonderful showcase for Christina Ricci as an
icepick-tongued teenager, using scorching one-liners as weapons as
she invades the space of her gay brother, drolly played by Martin
Donovan. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 &UR; ``Testamento''  &LR; Lush, beautiful filmmaking. It's about the
life and loves of a wealthy Cape Verdean businessman (played with
panache by Nelson Xavier) and the effect his death has on several
townspeople, especially the young woman named sole heir to his
fortune. (Unrated) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;   &UR; ``The X-Files: Fight the Future''  &LR; Typically, this
eagerly-awaited film, an offshoot of the hit television show, poses
twice as many questions as it answers. Still, the film, scripted by
series creator Chris Carter, succeeds in offering thrills for
longtime fans and newcomers as FBI agents Mulder and Scully get
knee-deep in all sorts of nasty covert doings. (PG-13) (Renee
Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
