<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0402 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MERCADO-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-22 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MERCADO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... personally invovled.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He thought briefly about singing, but he couldn't sing. Then he
thought of becoming a musician, but he didn't play an instrument.
Not deterred, he said, he tried to figure out what his strength
was, and how he could put that strength to work in the music world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was numbers. I was always very good at math,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mercado got together with some friends and started a social
club, appointing himself president. They began to organize
``waistline parties'' _ dances in basements of neighborhood
apartment buildings with live bands, where admission fees were
based on the size of the woman's waist. (The bigger the waist, the
more it cost.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Raffi was the one who stood at the door and did all the
measuring,'' recounted Jose ``Tuffy'' Sanchez, who helped organize
the dances and now works as RMM office manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have five bands going, and the place would sell out,''
Mercado said. ``I mean sell out. People would be waiting in line
around the block all night long.'' The shows averaged 1,500 in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of money,'' Sanchez said. ``There was a real
void in entertainment for Puerto Ricans, and we filled it. That's
what Raffi has always done, see. He pays attention. When there's a
void, he steps in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercado and Sanchez soon opened the 3 &AMP; 1 nightclub in Brooklyn,
hoping to expand their concert parties. According to Mercado and
Sanchez, people came by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Mercado was in his early 20s, newly married to a
young Puerto Rican woman named Dolores, and their first child,
Debra, had made her appearance in the world. Another, Damaris, was
soon on the way. (Dolores passed away eight years ago; Mercado has
not re-married and has two adult children, Ralph III and Melissa,
by another woman.)
</P>
<P>
   Mercado worked as a delivery man for United Parcel Service
during this time, but his mother said that he told her he could not
envision himself punching a time clock for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, he took a job booking a nightclub called Cheetah, where
he discovered a little-known band called the Fania All-Stars. The
band, featuring pianist Eddie Palmieri, bassist Ray Baretto, and
singer Hector Lavoe, went on to become the trailblazers of the New
York salsa sound. (Salsa originated in New York City as a hybrid of
Cuban rhythms, big band orchestration, and American harmonies.)
</P>
<P>
   One year later, Mercado established his first company, Ralph
Mercado Management Inc., or RMM. Though his current company still
bears the same name, in the early days Mercado focused exclusively
on representing artists. He became known around New York for his
punctuality, organization, and ability to get artists paid well, a
rarity in those days.
</P>
<P>
   Tito Puente recalled those early days in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone took advantage of Latin musicians back then,'' he
said. ``As a promoter, Raffi was different. He respected us. ...
He's very efficient, very businesslike, and he's a man with ethics.
That was hard to find in a manager back then. Everybody who was
anybody went with Raffi.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Mercado was the invisible conductor
behind the careers of dozens of Latin music's top artists,
including most of the nation's best-known Latin jazz artists, such
as Palmieri, pianist Hilton Ruiz, trumpeter Charlie Sepulveda,
flutist Nestor Torres, and percussionist Giovanni Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1987, Mercado said, he found himself increasingly
frustrated by the way major record labels in the United States
treated Latin musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to getting major record labels to sign these
artists, forget it,'' Mercado said. ``They didn't think there was a
Latin market. Or if they did, they didn't understand how to treat
the artists.''
</P>
<P>
   So he started his own label, signing recording contracts with
many of the artists he had represented, but also branching out in
search of newer, younger, and glossier talent, a move that rattled
some of his longtime associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the people what they want,'' Mercado said.
``It doesn't mean today's music is worse. It's just very, very
different. In the old days, bands and musicians were where it was
at. Now it's singers, singers, singers.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the new voices he discovered was Harlem-born salsa singer
Marc Anthony, who recently starred alongside Ruben Blades in Paul
Simon's Broadway musical, ``The Cape-man.'' Anthony also will
perform _ in English _ the theme music for Disney's upcoming
``Zorro'' feature film.
</P>
<P>
   RMM's newest roster additions include Michael Stuart, a
photogenic young Puerto Rican salsa singer, and Corrine, his female
counterpart. On the merengue front, RMM is banking on Manuel and
Grupo Mania; in salsa, it's hoping for big sales with new bachata
singer Henry Rosario.
</P>
<P>
   RMM also has begun to venture into the world of Rock en Espanol
and Latin House/Rap, with groups such as Limi-T XXI, Tres X, and
Vivanativa. But Mercado said he is most excited about Raul Paz, a
young Cuban singer he found performing at a nightclub in Paris.
With his romance-novel-hero looks and rich, versatile tenor voice,
Paz is the artist RMM will promote most heavily in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Money also is being poured into a new ``Fobidden Cuba'' series,
aimed at the Anglo audience currently buying Cuban recordings in
record numbers, and into RMM's new film division, RMM Filmworks.
Last year, RMM released its first film, a documentary on the
evolution of salsa, ``Yo Soy del Son a la Salsa,'' directed by
Cuban-born director Rigoberto Lopez. Mercado said that he has plans
for a feature film this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing in all kinds of directions,'' said Mercado.
``This is only the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no class you can take to learn to run a business like
RMM. There is no college that will teach you what we know.''
Pointing to his heart, he concluded, ``It's got to come from
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
