<HEADLINE>
BLOSSOMING OF BLOOMSDAY IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Ah, Bloomsday. Or is it Bloomsweek?
</P>
<P>
   Bloomsday is a Dublin tradition, celebrated by a dedicated group
of literature lovers who dress up as characters from James Joyce's
epic novel, ``Ulysses,'' which recounts in minute detail a day in
the life _ June 16, 1904 _ of the protagonist, Leopold Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd dressed in Edwardian period costume gathers for
breakfast in the seaside village of Sandycove, then saunters up to
the James Joyce Center in the Martello tower. Joyce lived briefly
in the tower. The crowd then retraces Bloom's steps up the
Sandymount Strand and around the city.
</P>
<P>
   There are many readings. And Bloomsday would not be complete
without the obligatory lunch at Davy Byrne's pub.
</P>
<P>
   With each passing year, however, Bloomsday gets bigger, if not
necessarily better. This year marked the biggest-ever celebration,
with a worldwide Internet reading.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Dublin, Bloomsday has blossomed into Bloomsweek, a
six-day festival complete with corporate sponsors. More coffee mugs
and T-shirts bearing Joyce's image are sold than copies of his
confusing, brilliant book. At the end of it all, one might be
forgiven for assuming that Joyce's masterpiece was underwritten by
the Guinness Co.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a half century after this quaint tradition began, some
Dubliners, and especially some of Ireland's literary giants, are
beginning to ask, is it still quaint, or has it become just another
tourist attraction sullied by crass commercialism?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The celebration of Bloomsday is traced to 1954, when a group of
writers led by Patrick Kavanagh and Flann O'Brien used horse-drawn
carriages to retrace Bloom's steps. It was, truth be told, a
glorified pub crawl, even if the intentions were sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Cronin, the poet and biographer who took part in that
initial pilgrimage, says the early celebrations were noble
commemorations held to honor a great Irish writer who lived in
exile in Paris and whose works were banned in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But Cronin, whose book ``Dead as Doornails'' chronicles the
hard-drinking Dublin literary scene that ended with Brendan Behan's
death in 1964, is among a growing list of writers who believe
Bloomsday is blooming out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Heaney, the Nobel laureate who has a house on Sandymount
Strand, says Joyce would not like Bloomsday. But Heaney is wary of
those who would censor the celebrations. As he told the Sunday
Times, Heaney said it is important to draw a distinction between
Joyce the citizen and Joyce the writer: The former belongs to
everyone, the latter to those who have read and appreciate his
work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A very unscientific survey of the families and children enjoying
the Bloomsday celebrations in Peoples' Park in Dun Laoghaire found
that few _ actually, none _ had read Ulysses. But the children
loved the period costumes, the singer, and the antique cars.
</P>
<P>
   David Norris is Ireland's first, and only, openly gay
politician. He is also the driving force behind what has become
Bloomsweek. A Joycean scholar, he is unapologetic about getting
Joyce to the masses, and is scornful of what he considers the elite
who dismiss Bloomsday as having become too common.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Trinity College graduates dinner in London, Norris
had a bunch of stuffed shirts laughing at Joycean quips. He says
humanizing Joyce gets many people who never read Joyce, and even
those who did so out of obligation, to go back and discover this
remarkable artist.
</P>
<P>
   But what about those who say Bloomsday has become tawdry?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all old farts,'' Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Cullen is chief of the Globe's Dublin bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
