<HEADLINE>
TOUCH-SCREENS HELP YOU BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER B. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As marketing pitches go, it might sound more alarming than
alluring, but BankBoston can promise you an electrifying experience
if you use their newest automated teller machines _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the bank, which operates New England's
largest network of ATMs, has joined dozens of other financial
institutions in installing touch-screen computer systems. These
allow people to choose the amount of cash they want to take out or
select other transactions by touching the glass computer screen
directly, instead of using a keypad.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-dozen basic types of touch-screen computer
technologies are in use today. BankBoston, which has switched over
about 400 of its 1,507 ATM locations to touch screens, uses a
unique ``capacitive'' technology made by a Methuen, Mass. company,
MicroTouch Systems Inc., in which the ATM customer draws
electricity from the screen to enter numbers and transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get nervous. It's less electricity than you would get from
picking up a tiny AAA battery, and you are putting yourself at no
risk if you go get $50 when it's raining. But it does mean you have
to take your gloves off, or the machine will not respond.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the system, which runs about $35,000 per
machine, are four wires that feed from each corner into an
invisible conductive mesh under the screen. When your finger makes
contact with the glass, within less than 1/100th of a second it
will draw slightly more electricity from the corner closest to
where you are touching, and progressively less from the corners
farther away. In effect, your fingertip is acting as a
``capacitor,'' something that draws electric current.
</P>
<P>
   By sensing how much electricity is being drawn from each corner,
the ATM's computer figures out where you are touching. It
correlates that to what is being shown on the screen, the way a
computer determines where a mouse click is aimed on a screen.
</P>
<P>
   Then it registers that you have touched the number 5, or
``transfer from checking to savings,'' or whatever other option is
being displayed. It also makes a beep and causes the relevant icon
to flash to show you it sensed you made contact.
</P>
<P>
   One big appeal of the system is that it allows ATMs to handle a
much larger range of transactions than the standard four
transaction keys. It also reduces the number of screens you need to
flip through to get to the transaction you want. That's because
instead of showing only three possible transactions at a time, plus
a button to summon the next three, it could display a dozen or more
possible transactions on a single screen.
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction for the bank is that the machines _ which on
average are used by more than 200 people a day _ are less prone to
breakdowns. ``Our field service personnel are big fans of things
without moving parts,'' says Stephen R. DeMay, a BankBoston product
manager at its Waltham consumer banking headquarters. ``Anything
that can break down, will.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, touch-screen ATMs could be used to sell a wide
range of products, such as MBTA bus and subway passes, prepaid
telephone calling cards, or concert tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Or a bank could let you use ATMs to pay utility bills or get
current stock quotes (a service CitiBank has made available at some
machines in Manhattan). Many BankBoston ATMs already offer postage
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The network will evolve to offer different things at different
places,'' says Randy Gearhart, BankBoston's director of global
consumer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Other types of touch-screen systems are in use at such places as
tourist information kiosks, museums, and restaurant cashier desks,
including:
</P>
<P>
   _Acoustic and infrared systems that project waves over or
through the surface of the screen in two directions. When your
finger breaks a wave by touching the screen, the computer
calculates where your finger is and correlates it to what the
screen shows. One drawback, according to MicroTouch marketing
manager Alice D. Moran, is that these systems can often register
``false touches'' or get confused by water droplets or cleaning
solvent residue on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   _Resistive systems in which, put most simply, your finger or a
pen-like device completes a circuit on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   _Strain gauge systems in which the screen is mounted on what are
essentially very sensitive springs. Your finger's pressure actually
pushes the screen inward, and the strain gauge calculates from the
tilt where you are touching.
</P>
<P>
   One feature of the BankBoston machines is a ``privacy screen''
that makes the screen unreadable to someone standing outside a
60-degree arc fromto the center of the screen. This feature is
designed to thwart snoopers from figuring out your secret ATM
number, or reading your massive reserve credit balance you owe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
