<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODE TO OLD MAN ON THE MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANTRY, Ireland _ Each day, the old man moves across his small
piece of the island, looking west toward the child who gives him
strength. Her name is Katie Driscoll. She is 13, the old gent's
great-niece, and she lives in Arlington, Mass., where she wrote
this past school year about what Danny O'Driscoll, 85, means to
her. Here, on Father's Day, is a portion of that essay:
</P>
<P>
   ``On Muntivera peninsula in Southwest Ireland stands a rugged,
wind-battered mountain, steeply rising in waves of rock-ribbed
ridges and bog-filled hollows. It is a harsh, wild hill smothered
in tangles of heather and gorse, wildflowers and ivy, and scattered
with surprise waterfalls. Etched into this hill is a farm that
gazes into the deep rippling waters of Bantry Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It includes a stone, slate-roofed farmhouse, an open-walled
barn where kittens frolic through fresh hay in search of mice, and
a stone shed where calves are raised. It is here you see
85-year-old Daniel O'Driscoll herding sheep up the mountain with
his faithful dog, Teddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny, my great-uncle, grew up on this farm with three
brothers and two sisters, the oldest being my grandfather. His
brothers and sisters immigrated to England and America to find work
and raise their families. Danny and his younger brother, Christy,
worked the farm together until Christy's death in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the beginning of a controversy within the family that
continues today. Some felt Danny should be in the rest home in
nearby Clonakilty; ``He'll die on the mountain,'' they say. At 85
years, he is completely stooped over, in danger of falling
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to die on the mountain than in Clonakilty,'' insists
Danny. He has refused to leave his farm. Instead, my family has
joined him for one month each summer to keep his way of life going.
Caring for our elderly uncle has come to be supporting a way of
life that reaches far into the past, even beyond his 85 years. My
uncle didn't change with the times; he has steadfastly kept to the
old and ancient ways about the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, Danny leads us through an overgrown,
rainforest-like path of ferns, leaves, and sub-tropical growth
until we reach a field thick with fresh-cut hay. Danny brings out
the hand-crafted rakes and hand-forged pitchforks, tools for the
art of making `caulks' of hay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend the entire day beneath the beating summer sun, raking
and turning the hay, gathering it and pitching it into high piles
with Danny demonstrating how to transform a pile of loose hay into
a tight, waterproof haystack, perfectly proportioned. On most
farms, machines are used to gather, bale, and stack hay, but on
Danny's farm we do all the work by hand. He insists on the old
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny expects us to do the work right and when truly
frustrated with our unknowing ways, he exclaims, `Will o' God! Have
ye not a spark o' sense?' We all have come to enjoy Danny's lively
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mountain is alive with stories from the past, and Danny
weaves the age-old expressions and stories into every task we share
with him. Neighbors also stop by, telling news and stories with
sharp bits of wit and wisdom, building on tales from past
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experiences with Danny O'Driscoll relate to having respect
for the old, and the thoughts and feelings of people who are old.
How we treat the elderly is an important concern. What is best for
the aging seems to be different for each person. What they think is
best for their lives might be what they should do, although they
might make a poor decision for their body's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is more important: What the old want or what the old
need? Maybe ``dying on the mountain'' is what one needs if the
mountain is where the memories, stories, and life are; if a
mountain is where one chooses to find peace, then let it be.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Muntivera peninsula, there is a farm, a symbol of beauty, a
place where the lush green countryside stretches into the sparkle
of the sea. On this farm lives the stooped and aged Daniel
O'Driscoll, whose body is weakening but whose soul is alive, living
where he belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where he was yesterday; walking slowly through the
mist, waiting for a big part of his life, a 13-year-old, to return
from America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
