<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES RADIATION MAKE FOOD DANGEROUS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By USHA LEE MCFARLING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The government says radiating food can't hurt you, but does
it kill the vitamins in the food? What is the point of radiating
food if it destroys nutritional value?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Radiation has been applied to some foods to kill bacteria and
lengthen shelf life for years. Since the 1960's, the Food and Drug
Administration has approved the irradiation of wheat, spices, and
tea.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In 1984, the FDA allowed the irradiation of meat, poultry,
fruits, and vegetables as well. Astronauts have eaten irradiated
food since 1972, and at least 40 countries, both developed and
developing, allow the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In irradiation, food is placed in large aluminum containers and
exposed to gamma radiation as the food moves through a chamber on a
conveyor belt. The process kills bacterial cells that can cause
disease or decomposition of food.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials say the technology is safe, does not unduly alter
food's nutritional value, and is necessary to stem the estimated
6,000 to 9,000 deaths caused in this country each year by
food-borne illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistics show you hands-down that the biggest problem
people face is microbiological,'' says James Tillotson, the
director of the Food Policy Institute at Tufts University.
``Whoever thought a child could die from a glass of apple juice?''
he said, a reference to a recent case in which fresh juice was
contaminated by a virulent strain of E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Much bacteria cannot be effectively washed off because it gets
into tiny crevices in some foods, such as raspberries, says
Tillotson. Some imported fruits carry harmful bacteria because
human feces is used as fertilizer in some countries. Irradiation
can also kill bacteria that can grow if meat is handled improperly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some proponents compare irradiation to a car air bag: an extra
precaution against carelessness or an accident. But opponents have
several concerns, including the impact on nutritional value of
food.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that irradiation reduces vitamin content,
particularly of vitamins A, C, E, and B complex, says Michael
Colby, executive director of Food and Water, a Vermont-based
organization that is leading efforts to stop food irradiation.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents, including Tillotson, say irradiation removes
only a small amount of vitamins, and more are removed during
canning, cooking or freezing. Many nutritionists say the small
nutritional loss is not critical in a country as well nourished as
ours. Colby responds that people will still have to cook, freeze,
and process irradiated food _ and so will end up with even less
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   He and others also have safety concerns. The FDA claims numerous
animal studies show that the process is safe, but some scientists
look at the same data and conclude that irradiation is not safe.
Still others say that they are not for or against irradiation _
they just want more conclusive studies done before the technology
becomes widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Irradiation, adds Colby, should not be a substitute for clean
processing and handling of the nation's food supply: ``It allows
processors to continue the filth and contamination.''
</P>
<P>
   The process does not make a food radioactive, but it may
introduce ``radiolytic compounds.'' These chemicals, says Colby,
are relatively new compounds and have not yet been proved safe. In
addition, accidents at food irradiation plants could expose workers
or the environment to radiation, he says.
</P>
<P>
   While opponents and proponents debate the scientific and safety
issues, consumers may ultimately decide the shelf life of food
irradiation. A CBS News poll last year found 73 percent of
Americans oppose irradiation, but supermarket anecdotes suggest
otherwise. A grocer, interviewed in a November 1997 Technology
Review article, said that when both irradiated and non-irradiated
chicken was offered to consumers, they bought whichever was
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   In another test, irradiated strawberries outsold similarly
priced non-irradiated berries _ probably because irradiation killed
mold on berries and made them look better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1355EDT &QL; 
