<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0429 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMAS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE FORGOT THE MOST IMPORTANT RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACK THOMAS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was midmorning last Thursday when computers
throughout the Globe city room blinked with a message that an
urgent staff meeting had been scheduled for noon by the editor,
Matthew V. Storin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's it about?'' asked a feature writer now so distressed by
events that ensued that he insists his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' I answered. ``I can't go, because I'm writing
on deadline, but when the meeting's over, let me know what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What I was writing was a column that asked why Americans have so
little confidence in journalists. I got the answer soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes before noon, Storin stopped by. ``You'd better
come to this meeting,'' he said grimly.
</P>
<P>
   When news was broken to the staff that Patricia Smith had been
asked to resign for having fabricated people and quotations in her
metro column, there were audible sighs and murmurings of ``oh,
no,'' and then the silence and sadness that come with a death in
the family.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Smith's resignation, telephone calls and e-mail
to the ombudsman's office ran 3 to 1 sympathetic to Smith and
critical of the Globe. One response was particularly bizarre. In
reaction to Smith's column of apology Friday, a woman from
Dorchester called to say that it was so poignant and so well
written that it ought to be nominated for a Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Friday, members of the Globe staff struggled to make
sense of the realization that for all her skills at writing, what
Smith had done was to take the language she claims to love and
twisted it to manipulate readers and make a mockery of the least
complex and most fundamental standard of writing _ telling the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed, sad, and unable to explain why Smith had come to
violate that trust, many people at the Globe were depressed. The
question on many minds was posed by Robert A. Jordan, president of
the union that represents writers and editors: ``Why would someone
with such skill and talent and passion need to go beyond the
boundaries of journalistic ethics to make an impact when she could
have made with the same if not greater impact within the
boundaries?''
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, but many of the columnists, reporters, and editors
who demand daily that other people answer questions in the midst of
crisis were unwilling in their own crisis to speak for the record
about Patricia Smith and her struggle with truth.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was afraid, though. Viola Osgood, an
African-American woman from Dorchester who is retired as a writer
of editorials for the Globe, had the courage to say what others
would only whisper:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Globe should have asked for Patricia Smith's
resignation. I think the Globe should have fired her.''
</P>
<P>
   I agree.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, charges resurfaced that in years past, another
columnist, Mike Barnicle, had fabricated characters and quotations.
To avert any question of a double standard, the Globe acted swiftly
and prudently in announcing that Barnicle's columns, too, would be
scrutinized again.
</P>
<P>
   As Storin explained to the staff on Thursday, all three metro
columnists _ Smith, Barnicle, and Eileen McNamara _ had been
notified two years ago that their columns would henceforth be
examined vigorously for fabrications. It's startling, and
disappointing, too, that any editor feels compelled to remind
columnists that they are not allowed to write falsely, that they
are obliged to write the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith's column of apology was written with her
customary flair, she continued to compromise the truth. Making up
an entire column of fictitious people and fictitious quotations is
not, as she would have us believe, slamming home a point.
</P>
<P>
   It's lying.
</P>
<P>
   And for all her professed love of the language, when she writes:
``I will survive this, knowing that the heart of my columns was
honest and heartfelt,'' the question remains, were they honest, or
were they deceitful?
</P>
<P>
   That is why many people, black and white, are angry for reasons
articulated by Viola Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the first black women to work at the Globe full
time,'' says Osgood. ``I was `the girl,' and `honey' and `dear.'
And I was given `soft' stories along with two other black women,
Carmen Fields and Gayle Pollard, until we rebelled and got to do
the same stories as everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in as black woman and walked out as respected
journalists who did the job as well as anyone else, black or white,
male or female. We worked hard to leave a legacy where black women
like Patricia Smith would be trusted to do the job without regard
to sex or color.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Patricia Smith has prostituted that, and I'm angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she did is unforgivable. I worked 24 years at the Globe,
and it never occurred to me that anybody would make up quotes. And
Patricia Smith's column of so-called apology was an insult to
blacks in journalism who worked so that she would have the status.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what did she do? She forgot the most important rule in
journalism _ tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Thomas is the Globe ombudsman. His conclusions and
opinions are his own. His e-mail address: ombud(AT)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
