<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSAN TRACY'S BIG WEEK AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Tracy is about to have one of those weeks people in
politics dream about, and for the best of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   She deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the inadequately sung sleepers in the campaign to succeed
Joe Kennedy in Congress, Tracy is about to be plucked from the
large pack and tapped on the shoulder by no less than the National
Women's Political Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   And then, from another, equally important direction, she is
about to be tapped on the other shoulder by Local 26 of the Hotel
and Restaurant Workers. For those who follow this business, Local
26 is one of Boston's major sources not just of the validation that
comes from significant endorsements, but of the field workers and
phone banks that can transform shoestring, grass-roots campaigns
into machines. This sudden surge of support, moreover, just happens
to come as she prepares to hold a very important fund-raiser
downtown this week.
</P>
<P>
   For those who detest conventional wisdom and who think Kennedy's
departure presents an ideal opportunity to pass the torch and get
fresh energy and ideas, Tracy comes from central casting.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom type-casts this campaign into nothing
more than a contest of names and resumes. But Tracy's bottom-up
effort has the potential to severely undercut the twin pillars of
that assumption.
</P>
<P>
   The solid labor support for this community activist and former
state legislator is no knock on Ray Flynn. The former Boston mayor
from outside the district has always been there for working people.
But as Local 26's president, Janice Loux, put it after meeting with
the crowded field, it is the future that's on the union's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about the issues labor cares about,'' she
said, turning to the candidate the union supported for the
Legislature when she first ran in 1990. ``Susan Tracy is especially
important in her determination to protect pensions, and we don't
have any doubt about her record in putting together the coalitions
that get things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is more about the person. Susan is the hometown girl
in this thing; she lines up perfectly with the identity of our
union. It isn't often you seek this mixture of a genuine
identification with working people along with an ability to get
things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the fact that Tracy is getting blessed by the women's
movement she has always supported is no knock on the campaign's
other ``name,'' Marjorie Clapprood. Before she went into the talk
show business, there was never a moment _ in the Legislature or
running with John Silber statewide in 1990 _ when she wasn't in the
thick of things. Again, however, this is about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan Tracy is very seasoned, but she also has the energy of
youth,'' said Pat Dear of the Women's Political Caucus. ``Because
of who she is and what she's done, she is instinctively able to see
people not as voters but as constitutents and as neighbors. Coming
up through the ranks really gives you a special ability to make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot to say of a 38-year-old who worked her way through
Boston College after Catholic school, ran Flynn's homeless
operation, and represented the city both before the Legislature and
later in it. But as she took me around the sprawling district last
week and then at a candidates' night in Dorchester, that was what
everyone who knows her wanted to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has two wonderful qualities that are rare in
combination,'' said Tim Garvin over at the Y he runs in Boston's
Brighton district. ``Nobody can get from Point A to Point B better,
but she also knows the people who are affected. She simply gets
it.''
</P>
<P>
   We were talking welfare reform. Tracy knows there are miles to
go at the national level before this can work over time. She also
knows that nine of the 36 kids at the Y that day for afternoon day
care are on vouchers under the state's absurdly Draconian rules;
and that those vouchers expire this fall. As we talked, she fumed
at the inattention given affordable housing issue during the '90s.
But she could also point out buildings where federal subsidies are
about to expire, putting low-income tenants at great risk.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy is also happy to talk Social Security reform, about which
her mind is open to the new ideas in Washington. But she gets truly
passionate about the widows who face special privation in both
pension and Social Security benefits, precisely because she knows
so many individually.
</P>
<P>
   She is not a soundbite artist. Tracy is a straight-ahead talker,
favoring verbs and direct objects over adjectives and adverbs. But
she knows people she doesn't know are going to hear about her
organizing success and look at her more closely to see what's
there. She needs to be ready for that.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, hers is not the only way to make a fresh start.
There are also candidates with business backgrounds who seek to
identify with the New Democrat, bipartisan twist in today's
congressional climate. And they deserve close attention, too. But
this week is Susan Tracy's. It's also a week for all those who
delight in showing how conventional wisdom has all the durability
of a sand castle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
