A0433 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      06-22 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GNMA FUND SEEMS BEST FOR CONSERVATIVE INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I will be 62 in July and will begin drawing Social Security
of $1,112 a month. I retired last year, and the Social Security
will combine with a pension of $1,500 a month and my wife's pension
and Social Security. We own our home and the bills we have are for
normal things we need and a few we don't. We are not desperate for
more income, but it would be convenient. I enclose a copy of the
statement on my 401(k) account, which remains with my former
employer. I would like to move it and then draw some income without
loss of principal. The 401(k) is invested through Vanguard, and I
would like to stay with them, although it could be moved elsewhere.
How should I handle these funds to get the maximum gains with the
least loss?
</P>
<P>
   W.M., Warren, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The statement shows that 97 percent of the 401(k) money is in
a Vanguard money market fund, with the other 3 percent in a common
stock, presumably that of your former employer. I often hesitate to
suggest much of a change when a person has a portfolio that's this
conservative, reasoning that if a person holds a huge percentage of
his or her savings in a money market fund, it's because they are
very, very conservative _ perhaps even are the kind of people who
would lose sleep over the prospect of losing money in the stock or
bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some people hold money market investments
simply because they didn't understand the confusing array of
offerings when they set up their account, and accordingly chose
what seemed simplest and safest.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously you could roll the account over into a Vanguard IRA
with similar investments and obtain your goal of an income stream
without loss of principal by simply withdrawing the actual
dividends from the money market shares. You could even sell the
common stock and put that money into the same fund.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to be a bit more aggressive, I make this
suggestion. Instead of the money market fund, why not roll the
account over into shares of Vanguard's GNMA fund _ a proven
above-average performer within its category, and a fund which you
can expect, over the long run, to yield about 1.5 percentage points
more than the money markets.
</P>
<P>
   The key words in that last sentence are ``over the long run,''
because there's no escaping the fact that Ginnie Mae funds can be
quite volatile in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   These funds own government-guaranteed mortgage securities, and
while Uncle Sam stands behind both interest and principal payments,
the value of these holdings _ like any fixed-income investment _
fluctuates inversely to interest rates. That's to say, when
interest rates rise, the value of these securities fall; when
interest rates fall, fixed-income securities rise in value.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the value of such funds also rises or falls when the
markets only speculate that interest rates will change. The
long-term record shows that these funds do poorly in about two of
every ten years, but that they also tend to make back the lost
ground fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a suggestion for a conservative strategy for a GNMA
position for one who is concerned about preserving capital. More
the funds to the GNMA, but direct that Vanguard send you monthly
checks representing only 5 percent of the value of your initial
investment. Since the GNMA fund is currently producing a yield of
6.5 percent, that means that you would be reinvesting about 23
percent of your yield. Over time those reinvestments should build
up a buffer sufficient to keep the principal value at a higher
level than your initial investment, even when those apparently
inevitable bad years come.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, once that buffer has reached the point that the account
is 10 to 15 percent larger than your initial investment, you could
decide you have enough padding, and at that point direct that the
entire yield from your position be sent to you monthly.
</P>
<P>
   At least on paper, if a fund yields 6.5 percent and you withdraw
only 5 percent, the principal should grow by 10 percent in a matter
of six years and one month; to achieve 15 percent principal growth
would require a little less than 8 1/2 years. Either way, once you
get to the target, you could then give yourself a thumping good
``raise,'' increasing your withdrawals by 43 percent if you set the
target for the buffer at 10 percent, and by nearly 50 percent if
you set the buffer at 15 percent. Either way, it's an attractive
way to build a little protection against future inflation into your
retirement budgeting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I find myself starting over as I recover from an unwanted
divorce after 25 years of marriage. I am a 48-year-old baby boomer
who has not prepared for my retirement years. I will be inheriting
about $50,000 and would like to know the best way to invest this
for my future. Last year I opened a $3,000 account in Vanguard
Windsor II, and IRA accounts of $1,000 each in Vanguard Index
Growth and Balanced Index. This year I am considering adding Janus
Worldwide fund to the IRA portfolio. Since most of my money will
not be in IRAs, would a tax-managed account be a good idea for me?
</P>
<P>
   T.J., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's true that Vanguard's tax-managed funds appear to work.
Last year, for example, the Vanguard Tax-Managed Growth and Income
fund produced a total return of 33.31 percent, and its
distributions for the year represented 1.34 percent of its yearend
net asset value. The Vanguard Index 500 fund, which holds a very
similar portfolio, produced a total return of 33.21 percent, and
its distributions represented 2.12 percent of yearend assets. The
only problem with these tax-managed funds is that there is a fairly
limited menu. Besides Growth and Income, there are balanced and
capital appreciation funds in the category _ and none of the
value-oriented type of funds I tend to favor in general and favor
now in particular.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is twofold: One is to reason that index funds
tend, by their nature, to make fairly moderate distributions;
theirs is basically a buy-and-hold strategy, and it leads to few
unpleasant surprises on tax day. So it seems to me that a taxable
account in Vanguard Index Value or Balanced Index might ultimately
be more attractive. (It's worth noting that the Tax-Managed
Balanced fund differs from Balanced Index in one important area,
which is that it normally has a target portfolio of 50 percent to
55 percent tax-free bonds, with the rest in cash and stock;
Balanced Index holds 60 percent stocks and 40 percent bonds, and
thus should be a better candidate as a long-term savings vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The second suggestion is that you consider putting all or some
of the inherited money in one of Vanguard's variable annuity
accounts. These offer tax deferral of all internal growth within
the accounts, which means you would face no tax liabilities at all
until you withdraw funds in retirement, and at that point you would
pay taxes only on the percentage of withdrawals representing the
internal growth. Since you don't seem to expect to be rolling in
cash during retirement, this might be an attractive prospect for
you, since you would probably be in a lower tax rate then than you
are now. Variable annuities are complicated instruments, offering a
mild form of insurance which enables them to offer the
tax-deferral.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't free _ you can expect the cost of the insurance to
reduce returns on these accounts by about one-half of 1 percentage
point annually, but for many people the tax advantages are
sufficient to far outweigh that drawback.
</P>
<P>
   An important final point about variable annuities is that they
work only as long-term investment vehicles, and you would pay a 10
percent tax penalty on earnings if you withdraw funds before age 59
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does one go about opening a Uniform Gifts to Minors
account, and how much do you need to open one?
</P>
<P>
   G.B., Boston
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's about the simplest thing in the world. You simply ask
the financial institution of your choice, whether it be a mutual
fund, a brokerage firm, or a bank, to establish the account,
supplying vital statistics and Social Security numbers for both the
beneficiary and yourself (or any other person you chose as
custodian). The minimum investment amount is up to the institution
_ the bank I called required only $10 to open a UGMA passbook
savings account. At other institutions such as mutual funds,
different minimum initial investment levels are established _
frequently at lower levels than for other accounts. At the Vanguard
mutual fund family, for example, the normal $3,000 minimum initial
investment level is reduced to $1,000 for such accounts. Other
mutual fund families have no minimums at all, although such funds
do typically levy a sales charge of some sort, either up front or
deferred or a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
