<SLUG> BC-STAGE-LONDON-SIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD WORK TO BE SEEN ACROSS THE THAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A theater junkie could make a satisfying trip to London
simply by crossing the Thames and hanging out where the Royal
National Theatre and Shakespeare's Globe are holding forth. The
National is riding a hot streak engineered by former artistic
director Richard Eyre and current AD Trevor Nunn. ``Closer,'' in
fact, is a National production that transferred to the West End.
Many of their productions are touring at America's regional
theaters _ ``An Enemy of the People'' in Los Angeles; Tennessee
Williams' ``Not About Nightingales'' at the Alley in Houston; and
one of their most intriguing plays, Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen,''
is coming to the Long Wharf Theatre in New Haven June 23 through
27.
</P>
<P>
   There are grumblings of a more commercial sensibility, but with
subsidies stagnant at best, Nunn has made it clear that future
productions like ``Oklahoma!'' have to pay the rent _ although if
``Oklahoma!'' is nearly as good as the National's ``Carousel,''
there won't be anything to apologize for.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, its three theaters along the Thames now offer a
delicious smorgasbord, with Christopher Hampton's lacerating
adaptation of ``An Enemy of the People'' with Ian McKellen
(reviewed last week) in the Olivier Theatre before transferring to
the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles; and ``Othello'' and ``The
London Cuckolds'' holding forth in the Lyttelton, where Fiona Shaw
is just opening in ``The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie.''
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Barry's new play, ``Our Lady of Sligo,'' wasn't on, as
they say, at the smaller Cottesloe while I was there, but Frayn's
``Copenhagen'' is certainly one of the meatier offerings in London.
In 1941 the German physicist Werner Heisenberg went to see his
colleague Niels Bohr in Copenhagen, then under German occupation.
Presumbably Heisenberg was there to find out if the Allies were
close to developing the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Frayn makes this the jumping-off point for a discussion of
quantum physics and the uncertainty principle and if that doesn't
sound like the most riveting of theatrical possibilities to you,
you're half right. This isn't a dressed-up theater of ideas like
Tom Stoppard's ``Arcadia.'' I spotted half a dozen people fighting
off, or giving in to, naptime during the first half. But all eyes
were open after intermission, when the implications of uncertainty
were becoming clearer. If Heisenberg had taken a simple yet daring
leap of faith, would the Germans have beaten the Allies to the
bomb? Had Heisenberg figured it out and censored himself to prevent
the Germans from winning the war? The only thing certain is that
Frayn has fashioned a very compelling play out of the uncertainty
of motivation, one that even someone as mathematically challenged
as myself could see is playing with, and mastering, philosophical
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road is the year-old Shakespeare's Globe, the project
that American Sam Wanamaker led to fruition. Designed in the style
of Shakespeare's theater, with a pit for groundlings, and benches
to keep the richer folk out of the sun and rain, the Globe is a
most enjoyable place to experience Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rylance, the theater's artistic director (and the American
Repertory Theatre's Hamlet), describes the ambience the place
achieves in his notes to the audience: ``Whether seated on a bench
or standing, Shakespeare kept his audience physically aware of
themselves. There is nowhere on the stage that an actor can be seen
by everyone in the theatre, Shakespeare must have wanted you to
look at each other sometimes while you listened. Shakespeare and
his fellows placed their thoughtful observations in an emotional
story, let yourself get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, one's appreciation is enhanced by leaving one's
seat (they're murder on the back anyway) and walking around the
pit, particularly in a comedy such as ``As You Like It,'' where the
actors barrel their way through the crowd onto the stage.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the most profound Shakespeare in the world and not
every actor is wonderful, but both ``As You Like It'' and ``The
Merchant of Venice'' show that accessibility is a most
Shakespearean virtue. The Globe shows that Shakespeare doesn't have
to be quantum physics. Not, as the National demonstrates, that
there's anything wrong with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-LONDON-BOS &LR;      06-22 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-LONDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WE HOPE THERE WILL ALWAYS BE AN ENGLISH TEHATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's difficult for an American theatergoer in London
not to be awed by the health of the British scene. There is, of
course, the choice _ it's easy to find a pair of plays almost every
day for the duration of one's stay. And the quantity matches the
quality, as is obvious from the Anglo-Irish domination of this
year's Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive aspect of British theater, though, is the
sense that it still matters, that it's still part of the national
dialogue for more than a tiny percentage of the people. A
production of Ibsen's ``An Enemy of the People'' is part of the
debate over Tony Blair's moving the Labour Party to the right.
Brits talk about the romantic implications of Patrick Marber's hot
West End play ``Closer'' alongside Helen Fielding's bestseller
``Bridget Jones's Diary.'' Young people flock to the reconstructed
Globe Theatre, where being a groundling is as cool as going to a
rock club. All right, almost as cool. And when British producers
look for star power, they lure a fine actor like Kevin Spacey into
doing ``The Iceman Cometh'' instead of a clown like Quentin
Tarantino into ``Wait Until Dark.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, easy to romanticize the English theater scene.
Government subsidies account for much of the healthier climate for
theater in England than in America, and Blair has made it obvious
that he's no friendlier to the arts than his Tory predecessors. As
ticket prices rise, the financial elitism of the audiences becomes
a self-fulfilling prophecy. Theater still matters to more people in
England than in America, but the percentage is dropping. And with
the recent boom in the British film industry, it's getting harder
to get long-term commitments from even second- or third-tier
actors.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the theatrical fabric is relatively bright and
more resistant to contemporary flames. At its core is a most
impressive historical through-line, where productions of
Shakespeare are vital to today's concerns and Marber, Harold
Pinter, and Tom Stoppard seem clearly part of the Shakespearean
tradition. There are as many people sniffling away at the end of
the Royal National Theatre's ``Othello,'' for example, as there are
at Marber's more contemporaneously resonant play.
</P>
<P>
   You could draw that historical through-line, in fact, from
``Othello'' through the same company's adaptation of Edward
Ravens-croft's Restoration play ``The London Cuckolds,'' to the
historical play about Harold Macmillan, ``A Letter of
Resignation,'' to revivals of Pinter and Peter Shaffer, to three
contemporary plays: ``Closer,'' ``Nabokov's Gloves,'' and Alan
Ayckbourn's latest, ``The Things We Do for Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayckbourn's title is meant to be ironic. While it conjures up
notions of sentiment and sacrifice, the play is really about vagary
and betrayal, in which a prig played by Jane Asher and a macho
Scotsman who have seemingly nothing in common except contempt for
each other betray her best friend/his fiancee for a stormy, violent
relationship with each other.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the light comedy in the bunch. ``Closer'' has even
more laughs, but Marber's wit, though somewhat glib, cuts like a
knife. You leave the theater feeling as if you've been scarred as
deeply as the four characters for whom love and sex seem like drugs
rather than emotions. Once they've achieved their peak highs, they
need a hit of something, or someone, else, even though their
betrayals leave lives in ruins. The same goes for Patrick Wise's
lawyer in ``Nabokov's Gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   In those rare instances where a monogamous relationship seems to
work, as in Pinter's ``The Lover'' _ part of a loving revival of
three of his works by the Donmar Warehouse _ it's only because the
couple have decided to pretend that they're carrying on affairs
with, as it turns out, each other's alter ego.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hugh Whitemore's dull historical play ``A Letter of
Resignation'' has a double entendre on the subject as the British
prime minister Harold Macmillan has to resign himself to his wife's
affair if he isn't to lose her.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is new, of course. The high-spirited Restoration
romp ``The London Cuckolds'' _ the National makes clear that
``Restoration'' and ``romp'' aren't a contradiction in terms _
makes clear that there's no putting a lid on libido. And if any
production of ``Othello'' these days seems like an O.J. Simpson
prequel, the National's is all the more creepy for Simon Russell
Beale's seductive sycophant of a Iago. Does Desdemona's innocent
flirtatiousness set him on his murderous way? The things that Iago
and Othello (an unsatisfyingly bombastic David Harewood) do for
love aren't terribly different than their contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   What all these decidedly unromantic plays add up to is a
restlessness with the spirit of the times. A revival of Shaffer's
'60s one-acter, ``Black Comedy,'' playing on a very funny double
bill with Stoppard's ``The Real Inspector Hound,'' reminds us that
bed-hopping reflected the miniskirted merriment of that decade, but
there's nothing funny about it in these plays _ even in Ayckbourn's
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Nabokov's Gloves'' the postmodern disdain for values is
represented in the attorney's indifference to his client's guilt or
innocence and in his determination to bed her, no matter what the
cost to his marriage or to his client's fragile psyche. His wife's
self-righteousness betrays a heavy-handedness on the part of the
playwright, Peter Moffat, but the ideas he's juggling are
nonetheless provocative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closer'' is the play where these issues come together most
satisfyingly and most disturbingly. Marber gets all the
contemporary nuances right _ the exoticism of a ``Something Wild''
romance; the phobias over commitment; even quasipornographic
Internet flirtation. Yet what's most striking is the yearning of
its youngest and seemingly least traditional character for a life
in which values like sacrifice matter.
</P>
<P>
   And for all of Marber's wonderfully sexy and droll dialogue _
his other impressive play, ``Dealer's Choice,'' is coming to
Gloucester Stage this summer _ there's a sense that the playwright
is also looking for a way out of the hedonistic dead end. Take, for
example, this scene between the younger woman, Alice, who confronts
Anna, her supposed friend, for stealing her man:
</P>
<P>
   ALICE: Why did you do this?
</P>
<P>
   ANNA (tough): I fell in love with him, Alice.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE (laughing): That's the most stupid expression in the
world. ``I fell in love.'' As if you had no choice. There's a
moment, there's always a moment; I can do this or I can resist it.
I don't know when your moment was but I bet there was one.
</P>
<P>
   ANNA: Yes, there was.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE: You didn't fall in love, you gave in to temptation. Don't
lie to me.
</P>
<P>
   Marber doesn't offer any easy ways out, though. Besides the
edge-of-the-seat dialogue, ``Closer'' is a tightly constructed play
in which the inevitability of circumstance catches the audience in
its grip as tightly as the tragedy in ``Othello.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' entertainingly skims the surface of
today's relationships, but ``Closer'' is closer to the bone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
