<HEADER>
A0441 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HIGH-ART-BOS &LR;      06-22 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HIGH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW SPARK OF `HIGH ART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``High Art'' is centered in New York's downtown art scene, a
singular world as notorious for its poseurs and pretensions as for
its sparks of daring creativity. Yet this film, written and
directed by newcomer Lisa Cholodenko, slips beneath the airy
galleries, perfectly chilled wines, and terminal hipness of that
arena to present its shadow self. Hers is a world where today's hip
darlings become tomorrow's punch lines, as talent and promise are
eroded by drugs and expectation. This film has less to do with high
art than the low spark of misspent lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something I was exposed to,'' said Cholodenko, who
wrote and directed the film, which opened Friday. ``I came to New
York in 1992, and ended up meeting a lot of people living in the
downtown art, photo, and film scene, and there were people like
that. There were a lot of people who sat around, dabbled (in
drugs), and lived in lofts. It's an atmosphere that I found very
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the film is Lucy Berliner, a Nan Goldin-type
photographer once renowned for gritty, provocative photos. But her
fame becomes shrouded in mystery after she disappears from the art
world and descends into druggy decadence with her German lover,
Greta, a former actress who spends most of her time nodding off in
a heroin haze. Their junkie-chic lives are interrupted by Syd, an
assistant editor at a tony photo magazine, who lives in the same
apartment building. Syd accidentally meets Lucy and is quickly
enthralled by her and the ruined romance of her world.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which won a screenwriting award at this year's
Sundance Film Festival, stars Radha Mitchell as Syd and Patricia
Clarkson as Greta, but the actress receiving the most attention is
Ally Sheedy as Lucy. The role is a stark departure for Sheedy, best
remembered as a card-carrying member of the so-called Brat Pack,
the cadre of young, photogenic actors who appeared in such popular
1980s films as ``The Breakfast Club'' and ``St. Elmo's Fire.'' It
was a fame Sheedy shared with Molly Ringwald, Anthony Michael Hall,
Judd Nelson, Emilio Estevez, Demi Moore, and Rob Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Sheedy broke from the Brats and appeared in ``WarGames'' with
Matthew Broderick, ``Short Circuit'' with Steve Guttenberg, and
``Only the Lonely'' with the late John Candy. But her career waned
as roles became scarce, and she battled drug problems and
unforgiving directors who refused to see beyond her good-girl
wholesomeness.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while many teenagers and 20-somethings in the 1980s were
plucking down their dollars to watch Sheedy and her Brat Pack
cohorts, Cholodenko was frequenting her local art house, which
never ran the suburban teen-angst films that made Sheedy famous.
Knowing little about Sheedy's past work, the filmmaker had no
trouble imagining her as a strung-out lesbian artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw those movies, so I really didn't really know who
she was,'' Cholodenko said. ``I knew in a really general way about
the Brat Pack, but for me it was really a blank slate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cholodenko, who worked as an assistant editor on such films as
Gus Van Sant's ``To Die For'' and John Singleton's ``Boyz N the
Hood'' before making her first feature, has been fascinated with
photography since she was a student at San Francisco State
University in the 1980s. She was particularly struck by the
personal artistic style of Goldin, Larry Clark (director of the
controversial film ``Kids''), and Jack Pierson. Their photos mostly
featured friends and acquaintances, often people on society's edge.
With graphic images of sex and drug use in black-and-white, their
work was both shocking and scintillating. By the time Cholodenko
moved to New York, that style had permeated popular culture from
music videos to fashion, culminating in ``heroic chic,'' with
models affecting the burned-out, dead-end look of junkies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was being used to sell everything from clothes to
cologne,'' she said. ``At the same time, work of Larry Clark was
being displayed in the Museum of Modern Art, so I knew I wanted to
explore that world of artists and drugs in a fictional story.''
</P>
<P>
   In her original story, Cholodenko focused on Syd's career
ambitions. At the magazine Frame, Syd has the title of assistant
editor, but she spends more time fetching coffee and pastries for
bosses than making major editorial decisions. Although she is at
first unaware of Lucy's fame, she is immediately moved by the work
she sees when she first visits Lucy's apartment. Prompted by her
bosses, Syd imagines getting her big break if she can persuade Lucy
to create new photographs for a special issue of the magazine. In
later drafts, Cholodenko toned down Syd's ``status-seeking'' to
create a character with more shades of gray, a woman torn between
the personal and professional sides of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on she was much more in the `All About Eve' camp,'' she
said, referring to the classic 1950 film with Anne Baxter as a
conniving young actress. ``But I wanted more complexity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in ``High Art'' there are no innocents. Syd has a
burgeoning romantic love for Lucy, but she is just as eager to use
Lucy for her own professional gain. Some may find the ambiguity of
the characters off-putting, and just as many are likely to be
unsettled by the film's conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, people want to be uplifted at the end of a
movie,'' said Dolly Hall, the film's producer. ``So it's incredibly
hard to not only get people to invest in a film, but to do see a
movie which is a big downer at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Cholodenko discussed changing the film's ending, but
decided only the original conclusion could be true to the story,
Cholodenko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it, and there were drafts when I tried to push
it in a different direction. But it just felt wrong,'' she said.
``The story needed to go in a certain direction, and anything less
I felt would really be a cop-out.''
</P>
<P>
   For her next film, Cholendenko is switching coasts. She is
developing a story about the music industry in Los Angeles, and
that film, like ``High Art,'' also will focus on the people behind
the glitter and glamour. But for now, she is still reveling in the
success of her first film, which was screened at last month's
Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was making the film, my only goal was to get through
this without feeling ashamed,'' she said. ``We made this film
without an agenda, we made it on our own terms, and that may never
happen for us again. That's what we want to enjoy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
