r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICE-STORM-AFTERMATH-H     06-22 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-STORM-AFTERMATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE THICK OF SUMMER, EFFECTS OF CRIPPLING ICE STORM LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. _ The four-inch-thick ice that encased six
upstate New York counties in January has long since melted, but the
havoc it wreaked is far from forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six months after the storm, power has been restored to
the 125,000 people who were without electricity, structural damage
has been repaired and the last of the downed tree limbs are being
collected and chipped.
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of problems remain.
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers, who are an integral part of the region's economy,
are still struggling to put their lives back together. The
distribution of millions of dollars in federal and state aid that
could assist the farmers is tangled in red tape. The majestic trees
that once graced the Adirondack Mountains have been broken and
stripped of branches, which has crippled the maple industry and may
hurt tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The region, which straddles the Canadian border to the North and
Lake Champlain on the east, is no stranger to nature's wrath. In
the last three years, floods and blizzards have pounded the area.
But the ice storm that began on Jan. 5, transforming Clinton,
Essex, Franklin, St. Lawrence, Jefferson and Lewis counties was
unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Five days of freezing rain followed by a snowstorm left
thousands of residents stranded in their homes without heat,
electricity and, in some cases, food. Nine people died during the
storm, most from carbon monoxide poisoning caused by generators or
space heaters operated in poorly ventilated rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The area's 1,400 dairy farmers suffered some of the most serious
losses, according to Donald LaPierre, executive director of the
Clinton County Farm Service Agency. Collectively, they dumped an
estimated $300,000 worth of milk that week, and some never
recovered from the financial setback. Already, more than 12 Clinton
County dairy farmers have sold their farms, LaPierre said.
</P>
<P>
   While homeowners have received more than $40 million in grants
and low-interest loans from the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, the farmers are still waiting for compensation for loss of
livestock and decreased productivity due to the storm. Although
many had insurance, their policies did not cover damage done by ice
or other natural disasters, which are typically excluded under an
``act of God'' clause.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of dollars have been allocated to assist farmers,
LaPierre said. Just this week, the New York Emergency Management
Office announced a $2.8 million program that will reimburse farmers
up to $5,000 for lost cows. But distribution of these funds has
been held up by bureaucratic hassles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are avenues we have to follow,'' said LaPierre, who is
still awaiting training on how to administer federal funds to
farmers and determine who is eligible to receive them. ``It's
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, farmers are waiting and some are simply giving
up on farming and selling off their land.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was the last straw for some small dairy farmers who
had already grown weary of farming's many demands and low financial
return, said Joseph Giroux, a Clinton County legislator who also
owns about 150 head of cattle on a farm in the town of Plattsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle before, and the struggle continues,'' Giroux
said. ``This caused some people to give up, is all.''
</P>
<P>
   The maple industry did not escape the ice storm either. Until
January, maple farmers were the second-largest producers of syrup
in the Northeast. This year, about 380,000 taps couldn't be set due
to storm damage, according to the New York Agriculture Statistics
Service.
</P>
<P>
   It could be years before trees fully recover, according to Lewis
Staats, a maple expert at Cornell University Cooperative Extension
in Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, many maple farmers may have been forced out of
business and it will be too late, said Earl Parker, who owns about
250 acres of sugar bush 10 miles north of Plattsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to give up and I don't want to cut these trees
until I'm sure they're not going to produce,'' said the 63-year-old
farmer, who was the North Country's largest producer of maple syrup
in the until the storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But several logging companies have already contacted me. I
said `no,' but I know some farmers who said `yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tree damage may also hurt the tourism industry. It remains to be
seen whether the millions who flock to the Adirondacks in the
summer stay away or leave early after glimpsing what some locals
have dubbed ``the uglification of the North Country.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's saving grace may be that the worst tree damage is
on trails between Lake Placid and Keene, which are not heavily
used, said Katy Odell, communications director at the Lake
Placid/Essex County Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The number of visitors may decline, however, come September and
October when fall foliage lovers, or ``leaf peepers,'' typically
travel. If they hear of the damage, these tourists may shun the
area in favor of Vermont or the Catskill Mountains, which could
cost millions in tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other effects of the ice storm on residents that
cannot be tallied or studied. The disaster left people feeling
fragile and vulnerable, feelings they won't soon shake off, said
Jeanie Roberts, executive director of the Clinton Northern Essex
Chapter of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least for the next few years, the broken trees will be
around us and we'll see the damage,'' Roberts said. ``We're more
acutely aware of the fact that this can happen here, not somewhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned a lesson that we'll remember for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
