<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BOCELLI-2TAKES-     06-22 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOCELLI-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOCELLI'S BLITZ 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time I heard Andrea Bocelli was last fall, a few weeks
after the September release of the Italian tenor's ``Romanza''
album on Philips. In an upscale restaurant, ``Romanza'' was the
soundtrack for lunch, and it wouldn't stay in the background. The
musicians I was interviewing couldn't stand the volume and
intensity of Bocelli's power ballads, found his passions
incompatible with their palates. So they asked if the music could
be turned down _ or off. The hostess was aghast. ``That record is
the reason people come here.'' So much for the chef ...
</P>
<P>
   Within the five years since the release of his first CD in Italy
in 1993, Bocelli has become one of the hottest stars in the record
business. Last year he sold 14 million CDs worldwide, coming in
second only to the Spice Girls. He made his first US appearance
last April, so he is not yet a household name here, although
``Romanza'' has been on the world music charts for months and
recently went platinum in this country. ``Aria,'' Bocelli's
recently released record of operatic music, immediately went to the
top of the classical charts. PBS made a substantial contribution to
Bocelli's popularity, as it did to the Three Tenors and Andre Rieu
before him, by repeatedly broadcasting his video, ``A Night in
Tuscany,'' during its December fund-raising period. Bocelli's first
US tour begins in Pittsburgh in July and brings him to Great Woods
Aug. 4; the seats in the pavilion are long gone, but some lawn
tickets remain. People Magazine discovered Bocelli last month and
told his fans that the unshaven tenor likes cologne (Opium and
Azzaro Pour Homme) which he wears ``for myself, not for other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   At 39 Bocelli is a late bloomer for a pop star, even for an
aspiring opera singer. He tells interviewers that from childhood he
always loved listening to opera, always enjoyed singing on family
occasions. A career in music, especially on the operatic stage,
seemed out of the question because he has been blind since a soccer
accident when he was 12 _ a fact unmentioned in his personal
publicity and a forbidden subject in interviews. In 1986, Bocelli
finished his law degree at the University of Pisa and spent a year
as a public defender, but he couldn't resist the lure of music. He
auditioned for former Met tenor Franco Corelli, who accepted him as
a pupil. To pay for the lessons, Bocelli took jobs in piano bars
(in addition to piano, he plays saxophone and flute). He was often
too self-conscious to sing, but when he did, he chose saloon songs
associated with Frank Sinatra and Charles Aznavour.
</P>
<P>
   His rise to celebrity was unexpected and swift. In 1992, the
Italian pop star Zucchero had a new song called ``Miserere'' that
he wanted to record with Luciano Pavarotti. To interest the
tenorissimo, he made a demo of the song, and the tenor he chose was
Bocelli. When Pavarotti heard the demo, he reportedly said, ``You
don't need me'' _ but went ahead and recorded the song anyway.
Pavarotti was unavailable to tour with Zucchero, but Bocelli was
ready and eager; audience response was tremendous and spontaneous,
and soon he had his own solo spot on Zucchero's show. Television
appearances during the annual San Remo festival and competition
made Bocelli a national star. In 1994, he recorded his first album
for the Sugar label in Italy. In 1995, ``Con Te Partiro'' (``Time
to Say Goodbye'') became an international hit, selling millions of
copies across Europe; a bilingual duet version with Sarah Brightman
was also a big success, especially in Germany _ Brightman first
heard Bocelli and the song in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   What is interesting about this story is that Bocelli became a
pop star almost by accident. Most of the great Italian tenors from
Enrico Caruso to Pavarotti have sung Neapolitan songs and pop
music. For this historical reason Bocelli went along with the game,
but he also hoped it would open the door to concerts and even
opera. In an interview in the May issue of Britain's Classic CD
magazine, Bocelli said, ``Pop was a very important medium. It was
the best way to get myself known to more people quickly and,
without the pop success, no one would have accepted me on the
classical side. There have been thousands of difficulties and
questions about me being able to do classical. A lot of people
brought up the problem that I wouldn't be able to see the
orchestral director and most people thought it would be impossible
for me to act on stage. These two points have been blown away,
because the facts speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Most crossover has been in the opposite direction _ not since
Grace Moore in the 1930s has a popular entertainer made a
successful career in opera, although Mary Martin toyed with the
idea. Michael Bolton recently made an operatic album, but he has
spent too many years putting his voice through the shredder. In
1993, Bocelli appeared onstage in the short role of Macduff in
Verdi's ``Macbeth'' in Pisa, and earlier this year he sang Rodolfo
in a production of Puccini's ``La Boheme'' in Sardinia that was
televised. The performance hasn't been commercially released on
video, but Bocelli fans have eagerly circulated copies of their
off-the-air tapes.
</P>
<P>
   It's an amazing performance, and people who watch it will cry
all the way through ``La Boheme'' for the first time in years.
Bocelli does not portray Rodolfo as a blind man; there's a lot of
horseplay and emotional embraces that unobtrusively guide the tenor
to where he needs to be, like the railing on the stairs. There are
some wonderful rehearsed effects, as when Bocelli lifts the
fainting Mimi in his arms and carries her over to the bed where she
will die. But many of the best touches seem spontanous, as when
Rodolfo steals a kiss from Mimi when she isn't looking, or when he
pulls his chair closer to her so he can listen more intently to her
aria. Overall Bocelli acts the part better than many a sighted
tenor. And although he is still figuring out how to pace himself
through a full performance, he sings it better than anyone since
the young Jose Carreras 25 years ago. Because his singing is so
pure, honest, and full of belief he makes everyone sing better too
_ this may be the performance of soprano Daniela Dessi's career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
