</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BOCELLI-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-22 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOCELLI-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Dessi's career.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are six Bocelli CDs, including a guest appearance (one
number) on a Deutsche Grammophon album, ``A Concert for the
World,'' and there is some duplication among them. ``Romanza,'' the
first CD with worldwide distribution, is actually a compilation of
the juciest power ballads from the first two albums on Sugar.
Philips has followed up with ``Aria'' and ``Viaggio Italiano''
(``Italian Voyage''), which was recorded, paradoxically, in Moscow.
This is a collection of five additional arias (including the
inevitable ``Nessun dorma''), Neapolitan songs, and ``sacred''
selections heard in arrangements that recall the high 1930s _ the
legendary Beniamino Gigli could have stepped into these
arrangements without a hitch, which is probably the point.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Pilavacchi, president of Philips Records, says, ``Andrea
Bocelli's voice touched me right from the very first minute I heard
it _ that's the reaction everyone has. I think he came to Philips
because it was his dream to make classical records and sing opera.
He will still make pop records, in fact he's making one now, but
most of his activity will be in the classical field. He's doing a
sacred album for us, and there will be a video to go along with
that, and we plan to record a complete `Boheme' with Myun-Wha Chung
conducting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bocceli's pop singing makes an immediate impression because of
the natural emotion in his voice and the sincerity of his
expression. But it doesn't wear well _ the music is
undistinguished, the orchestrations caloric, the electronics
wearing, the context so crassly commercial. Also Bocelli doesn't
vary his strategy enough. He does adjust his voice a bit, roughing
up and thinning out his middle range so that he doesn't sound
overbearing or pretentious. But structures nearly all his pop songs
the same way; they begin lightly and conversationally, then the
full voice kicks in for the big tune and the climaxes. Apart from
the deliberate casual roughness, Bocelli sings very straight _ he's
very careful not to put his voice through the shredder _ and from
the rhythmic point of view, pretty square.
</P>
<P>
   The opera singing is marked by the same natural emotion and
sincerity, and it is better. Pilavacchi says Bocelli prefers to
sing unmiked, as he has in his operatic performances and classical
concerts. The voice does not seem large; it is the quality that
counts. The range is extensive _ he has no fear of high C, knocking
off a string of them in Pavarotti's old show piece from Donizetti's
``La Fille du Regiment,'' and even ventures above that in an aria
from Bellini's ``I Puritani.'' For the most part, he shies away
from the dramatic repertoire, and the heaviest arias tend to
receive the least satisfactory performances.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly and automatically Bocelli has been compared to
Pavarotti, who paved the way. Pavarotti and the Other Two may not
have built a vast new audience for opera, as promised, but they
have certainly built a huge new public that wants more of the same,
and Bocelli is ready to supply it. To these ears, Bocelli and
Pavarotti don't sound or sing much alike. A better comparison is to
the Italian tenor idol of the generation before Pavarotti, Giuseppe
di Stefano. Bocelli does not boast the exceptional beauty of tone
that di Stefano enjoyed in his youth, but he shares his
predecessor's vivid diction and generous, authentic emotionality,
reinforced by a shared technical flaw. Both tenors have trouble
with managing the transitional notes between the upper middle voice
and the top tones, the so-called ``passaggio.'' Both Bocelli and di
Stefano sound raw and strained on these pitches, but this problem
does make them sound sincere, the way an untrained folksinger does.
Di Stefano's faulty technique and undisciplined lifestyle
foreshortened his career _ his great days were over by the time he
had reached Bocelli's current age. The only price Bocelli is
currently paying is in top tones that don't invariably carry the
full resonance of the rest of his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli is disarmingly modest about his vocalism. Repeatedly he
tells interviewers that the more he learns about singing, the more
he realizes he needs to know; he speaks with infinite respect of
his predecessors, whom he regards as his superiors. There are
things Bocelli hasn't mastered; not all of his ornamentation is
elegantly turned, for example. But Bocelli doesn't need to speak as
modestly as he does. He is an instinctive, natural musician who has
worked hard to learn what he needs to know about style. Whatever
his formula for pop songs, he doesn't sing all his arias the same
way. His most beautiful performance to date is ``Cielo e mar'' from
Ponchielli's ``La Gioconda,'' which he phrases poetically and with
many shades of dynamics; the performance is both intimate and
expansive. Mario Lanza, to make another obvious comparison, was a
more solid singer; Bocelli is more imaginative.
</P>
<P>
   The video ``A Night in Tuscany'' (Polygram) presents an
idealized portrait of Bocelli's life _ we see him riding a white
horse through woods and ocean surf; he plays chess in a bistro;
chats with his family, which maintains vineyards and olive groves
and bottles a Bocelli Chianti; he ripples through Liszt's
``Liebestraum'' at the piano. There are glimpses of his wife,
Enrica, whom he met in one of his piano bars, and their two small
sons. He says he likes to spend time with them at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The video doesn't add much to what comes over on the records
because it doesn't show Bocelli very often when he is actually
singing _ it repeatedly cuts away to the orchestra, or to his
partners in duet, opera soprano Nuccia Focile, pop stars Marta
Sanchez and Zucchero, and the unclassifiable Brightman, who looks a
little like Zucchero scrubbed up and poured into a gown. For
Pavarotti's enormous handkerchief, Bocelli substitutes long silk
scarves as a visual signature. Its to Bocelli's advantage that he's
never seen the regulation tenors strut and pose, so he can't
imitate them; he doesn't even gesture. His colleagues ``act,'' mug
for the camera. Bocelli doesn't, so you like him for that. He
simply stands there and sings, his bushy head slightly inclined to
the microphones, pouring his heart out. When something has gone
well, an irresistible smile lights up and you love him, but you
already loved him the minute he opened his mouth to sing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
