<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MERCADO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BERRY GORDY OF TROPICAL LATIN MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time when the term ``Latin music''
referred to music exported from Latin America. But in the past
decade, Latin music has become a lucrative American business.
</P>
<P>
   The Latino population in the United States grew from 14.6
million in 1980 to 22.4 million in 1990, an increase of 53 percent.
The United States is now the fifth-largest Spanish-speaking nation,
and Spanish speakers are the fastest-growing immigrant group here.
With the shifting demographics has come astounding growth in the
domestic Latin music industry.
</P>
<P>
   Exact figures are tough to determine. The Recording Industry
Association of America started tracking the genre only last year,
and Sound-scan, which monitors national record sales, collects data
only from major music retail chains. (Most Latin rec-ords still are
sold out of mom-and-pop stores.)
</P>
<P>
   But Billboard estimates annual growth in domestic Latin music
sales at more than 20 percent. The New York Times reported that
Radio City Music Hall now books Latin acts for 50 percent of its
shows. The most popular radio stations in at least two major cities
_ Los Angeles and Miami _ are in Spanish. Artists such as Boyz II
Men, Celine Dion, Madonna, and Toni Braxton recently have released
reverse crossover recordings, in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in the domestic Latin music market is obvious in the
bustling, spacious SoHo lobby of RMM Records and Video Corp. Gold
records line the walls; phones ring incessantly. The company made
more than $20 million last year, a 40 percent increase over the
year before, making it the world's most successful label for
tropical Latin music (Afro-Caribbean-based music such as salsa,
merengue, and bachata). Seven years ago, 80 percent of RMM sales
were generated in Latin America, but since 1994, the majority of
sales have been coming from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is changing,'' said RMM owner and president, Ralph
Mercado Jr. ``And the way I see it, we represent that change.''
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Brooklyn, Mercado, 56, is to salsa and
merengue what Berry Gordy was to soul and R&AMP;B. He also has been
called ``the new Emilio Estefan,'' a comparison that equates his
power with that of the Miami-based record company executive who
also is producer, manager, and husband of pop star Gloria Estefan.
In April, Billboard presented Mercado with its El Premio
lifetime-achievement trophy. A spokesperson said the award ``is
given to those Latino artists and music industry executives who
have helped expand Spanish-language genres beyond their Latino
followers.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Dominican dockworker and a Puerto Rican factory
worker, Mercado grew up hearing the music of his parents' homelands
in the hallways of his family's fifth-floor walk-up. His dad, he
said, taught him to dance the merengue as soon as he could walk.
</P>
<P>
   Now the owner of a five-bedroom luxury condominium towering 56
stories above Lincoln Center, Mercado has not forgotten his modest
roots. His speech is pure street Newyorican. He still finds his
acts by hanging out in clubs. He treats owners of mom and pop
stores the same way he treats Tower Records. He wears a pinky ring.
And, even though his office is surrounded by some of the finest
restaurants in the world, his mother, Manuela, 81, comes to the
office several times a week to cook him rice and beans.
</P>
<P>
   The category of Latin music is very diverse. The largest seller
under the Latin umbrella nationally is Mexican/regional, which
totals more than 50 percent of all sales. Most of these sales occur
in the southwestern states like Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Latin music accounts for 23 percent of all Latin music
sales nationally. The biggest market for tropical Latin music in
the world is the Northeast, with New York City as the top consumer
base. The second-biggest market is Puerto Rico; the third is
southeastern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Of the tropical market, Mercado's RMM accounts for 40 percent of
all sales. The remaining 60 percent is divided among various
labels, ranging from WEA Latino and Sony Latin to the independent
Caiman Rec-ords; no company has a larger share of the pie than RMM.
Five years ago, RMM ``could not even get into Sam Goody's
bathroom,'' said Vicente Iturbides, national director of sales and
marketing for RMM. Now, Sam Goody is RMM's biggest corporate
account.
</P>
<P>
   RMM's success comes thanks to a roster of more than 30 popular
artists, including the legendary Tito Puente and Celia Cruz, as
well as their modern counterparts Marc Anthony and India. Earlier
this year, Anthony, RMM's biggest seller, received Billboard's
tropical artist of the year award. Manny Manuel, the top-selling
merengue artist in Puerto Rico, records on RMM. Several artists who
were interviewed said they chose RMM because of the company's
``family atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Iturbides said that he has met nearly all of the presidents and
CEOs of tropical labels, and that ``none of them has the street
smarts, the savvy, and the gut instincts of Ralph Mercado, who grew
up on this music. He knows instinctively what the community
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercado's father, Ralph Sr., died when Mercado was 15 years old.
Mercado's mother worked for many years in a Brillo factory; she
also worked for the phone company. She still lives in the
fifth-floor walk-up where she raised her family, because she does
not want to move away from her friends. Mercado has offered to move
her many times, but she's not interested.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, Mercado went with some friends from the neighborhood to
the Palladium nightclub in Manhattan to hear his first live
concert: the Machito Orchestra. In an interview in his SoHo office,
he said that night changed his life forever. ``I was just
completely blown away. The energy, the colors, the sounds! I came
out of there knowing I had to be involved in this music somehow,
personally involved.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
