<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0454 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-JEALOUSY-     06-22 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-JEALOUSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAUMBACH SCORES AGAIN WITH `MR. JEALOUSY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noah Baumbach was praised for his first film, ``Kicking and
Screaming,'' about a bunch of guys who graduate from college but
can't seem to take the next step. With ``Mr. Jealousy,'' Baumbach
has taken the next step and made a terribly good film.
</P>
<P>
   His central figure is the well-meaning but emotionally confused
(and sadistically named) Lester Grimm, who is played
sympathetically by one of the most appealing young actors working
today, Eric Stoltz. Lester is kind of a loser for no good reason
except that he feels a little too sorry for himself to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   He's smart, but he just doesn't seem able to apply himself to
writing the fiction he knows he ought to be writing. He's sweet and
good looking, but he sabotages relationships by ruining them before
they can ruin themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When he meets Ramona (Annabella Sciorra), something clicks and
he seems to forget himself momentarily. Before he knows it, they
are a couple spending most of their free time together and edging
up to the moment when full commitment is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Just around then, Lester starts allowing his lifelong affliction
_ jealousy _ to poison his mind. Obsessed with Ramona's ex-lovers,
he focuses on one, a famed young writer named Dashiell (Chris
Eigeman), whose recent short story is a veiled description of his
affair with Ramona.
</P>
<P>
   Lester's perversity forces him to tail Dashiell and finally to
join Dashiell's therapy group, led by Dr. Poke (played by a
glum-looking Peter Bogdanovich). Lester isn't sure why he's doing
this. Is it to torture Dashiell in group for being a first-class
creep? Is it to learn about Ramona's taste in men? Or is it to
humiliate himself?
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Baumbach uses all of these motivations to come
up with some amusing, imaginative and charming situations. As
neurotically duplicitous as Lester must become to continue his
charade, he still remains likable, and this is problematic as he is
much more likable than Ramona, to whom duplicity comes more
naturally. In fact, it's a little tough to understand what Lester
sees in her. If Baumbach's movie has a flaw, it is that Ramona
seems a cardboard figure. Sciorra can't do much more with the
character than play her as a self-righteous runaround. She likes
flirting with ex-boyfriends, and she especially likes defending her
right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Stoltz, who is executive producer on the film, gives, as always,
an intelligent and bemused performance that keeps us rooting for
the otherwise maddening Lester. As Stoltz seems to know, Baumbach
is definitely a filmmaker to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
