<HEADER>
A0464 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MULAN-HNS     06-22 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MULAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MULAN': `YENTL' WITH A DIFFERENT LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mulan,'' Disney's 36th animated full-length feature, is based
on a popular Chinese legend about a young woman named Mulan who
disguises herself as a man in order to take her aging father's
place in the Army. She suits up and answers the emperor's call in
the fight against the invading Huns.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the movie is full of catchy songs by Matthew Wilder and
David Zippel, and there is the dazzling Disney palette of colors
and the studio's renowned suppleness with a cartoon image. But,
boy, it's hard not to keep thinking that this movie is basically
``Yentl'' with a nose job.
</P>
<P>
   Barbra Streisand played the I.B. Singer character who dressed as
a male in order to get the kind of Talmud education that was denied
females. Her studies brought her face to face with the man she
loved, a fellow Talmud scholar. Oh, the frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan, on the other hand, looking like an Asian version of the
perky Sandra Bullock, is in drag in order to fulfill her ailing
father's obligations to his country. All this nobility leads to a
meeting with the handsome young commander of her unit, Shang (voice
of B.D. Wong), with whom she falls in love. (Shang's singing voice
is Donny Osmond's.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Yentl'' had Streisand's wondrous voice, a few melodic notches
above Mulan's singing voice _ Lea Salonga. (Ming-Na Wen of ``The
Joy Luck Club'' provides the speaking voice of Mulan.) In its
favor, ``Mulan,'' however, can boast the talents of Eddie Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   He is the voice of Mushu, a tiny dragon who is the equivalent of
the Robin Williams genie in ``Aladdin.'' That is, Murphy gets to
riff to his heart's content on the theme of being a less than
frightening dragon, and thank goodness because he gives a rather
dull movie whatever life it's got.
</P>
<P>
   The pint-sized dragon is sent by Mulan's ancestor spirits to
help the poor girl live through her rash adventure. As with all
Disney animated features, ``Mulan'' is admirable for the sheer
vastness of the project. Artists, animators and technicians
numbering more than 700 were employed in the making of the movie.
And it took two directors, Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft, to pull it
all together. Not to mention that it boasts one of the first, if
not the first Asian female protagonist in an animated feature.
</P>
<P>
   The voice acting is good overall, including Soon-Tek Oh as
Mulan's father; Harvey Fierstein as Mulan's comrade Yao; and Miguel
Ferrer as the evil Hun, Shan-Yu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
