<HEADER>
A0514 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCROLLS-SON-OF-GOD-NY     06-22 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCROLLS-SON-OF-GOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SON OF GOD' IN THE DEAD SEA SCROLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By NEIL ALTMAN and DAVID CROWDER  
 c.1998 NEIL ALTMAN and DAVID CROWDER  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   ``He shall be hailed as son of God, and they shall call him the
son of the most high'' sounds like a passage from the New Testament
describing Jesus Christ, but it comes from a Dead Sea scroll that
scholars say was written a generation before Jesus was born.
</P>
<P>
   Written in Aramaic on a piece of leather about the size of a
business envelope, the Son of God text contains language almost
identical to the New Testament account of the angel Gabriel's words
to Mary in the book of Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars say the text bolsters an increasingly popular
theory that there was little original about the divine claims by
the carpenter from Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet overlooked for decades is evidence that the scholars are
wrong and that this little-known document -- along with other Dead
Sea Scrolls -- could not have been written until well after the
rise of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians and Jews, the implications are as important as
the Bible itself. Claiming that the Son of God text and other Dead
Sea Scrolls are ancient, scroll scholars have convinced publishers
of Christian Bibles to make hundreds of changes to some recent
editions of the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   But the Son of God text contains long-ignored Hebrew vowel marks
and words written in tiny letters, neither of which came into use
until centuries after 25 BC, the year that scroll scholars
speculate the Son of God text was written.
</P>
<P>
   And just as important as the physical evidence attesting to the
scroll's age are the ideas it contains and the way they are
expressed.
</P>
<P>
   Its verses describe the coming of a divine messiah who would be
the son of God -- terms that some rabbis and scholars say would
have been foreign and offensive to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that a Jew of that time didn't write this,''
said Rabbi Kenneth Weiss of El Paso, Texas. ``It's not a Jewish way
to refer to a messiah, and I don't believe a Jewish source would
ever use that phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after seeing a copy of the original Son of God text, Murray
Friedman, director of Feinstein Center for American-Jewish History
at Philadelphia's Temple University, could not believe it was found
among the Dead Sea Scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable!'' he said. ``If this is real ... Jesus has
been authenticated. If it's a BC document, it announces in strict,
clear-cut terms the arrival of the messiah. But if it's after, it's
worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Hershel Shanks, editor of Biblical Archaeological Review
magazine, has written a new book on the scrolls that comes within
shouting distance of Friedman's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the 'son of God,' a designation that is
strongly associated with Jesus as messiah in Christian theology is
referred to in a Dead Sea Scroll text called 4Q246,'' Shanks writes
in ``The Mystery and Meaning of the Dead Sea Scrolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Forced to speculate on how a supposedly pre-Christian text could
refer to the coming messiah as divine, Shanks says the Son of God
text suggests Jews had come to accept that idea in the generation
before Jesus was born.
</P>
<P>
   Shanks also tells of a second little-known Qumran fragment that
speaks of the sonship of the messiah -- theologically, another term
for deity.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent presence of that very loaded concept so intrigued
scholars in 1955 that they subjected that fragment to infrared
analysis just to be sure, and then said nothing more about the
results for almost 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Disagreeing with the views of established scroll scholars,
Milton Fisher, a professor of Old Testament at Philadelphia
Theological Seminary and former president of that institution, said
he does ``not think the Son of God text was written before the time
of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanoch Guy, professor of Hebrew and coordinator of Hebrew
Studies at Temple University in Philadelphia agreed that ``the
language is absolutely Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that this is a Christian text,'' he said of
the Son of God text.
</P>
<P>
   The Dead Sea Scrolls supposedly were written by a Jewish sect
over a period that began as early as 200 years before the birth of
Christ and ended early in the first century.
</P>
<P>
   About 68 AD, most scholars believe, the scrolls were stashed in
caves overlooking the Dead Sea where they remained undisturbed
until 1947 when an Arab shepherd boy stumbled upon them.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   But, even as Israel marks its 50th anniversary as a nation, many
questions remain about the origins of the scrolls. While the
scrolls are a national treasure to Israel and the basis for changes
in Christian Bibles, publishers of Jewish Bibles are reluctant to
go along, even though the scrolls are thought to be the oldest
existing copies of Jewish holy texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are really leaving the (Bible) as is,'' said
Helaine Denenberg, editorial assistant with the Jewish Publication
Society, North America's foremost publisher of Jewish Bibles.
Orthodox Jews are even more adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scrolls are not from mainstream Judaism, but from an
extremist sect,'' said Rabbi Yehoshua Kaganoff of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the existence of the Son of God text was known only
to a handful of scholars. But in the mid-1990s, the entire text was
published, revealing striking New Testament themes: The text reads
in part, ``One nation shall trample on another nation ... (Then)
his kingdom (shall be) an everlasting kingdom ... He shall judge
the earth in righteousness, and everyone shall have peace ... and
every nation will submit to Him.'' (EDITOR'S NOTE: Parentheses
represent reconstructed passages.)
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to portray the Son of God text as a
pre-Christian document, some scroll scholars theorize that it
referred to some figure who lived a century or more before the
birth of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence strongly suggests that the writer was aware of
New Testament theology, of Jesus and of the end of the world that
he described.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Neil Altman is a Philadelphia-based writer who specializes in
the Dead Sea Scrolls and religion. He has done graduate work at
Dropsie College for Hebrew and Cognate Learning, Conwell School of
Theology, and Temple University. He has a master's degree in Old
Testament from Wheaton Graduate School in Wheaton, Ill., and was an
American Studies Fellow at Eastern College.
</P>
<P>
   (David Crowder is an investigative reporter and former editorial
page editor for the El Paso Times.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
