A0543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-CASINOS-HNS     06-22 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-CASINOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOT MACHINES ARE JUST A BUS RIDE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINDER, La. _ It's 4 a.m. on a Wednesday and the nearly vacant
Grand Casino Coushatta is a slot-player's paradise, with just a
handful of gamblers wandering among 2,300 gleaming machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the slowest time of the week. In a couple of
hours, our regular morning players will start coming in,'' said a
host at the gaming house that can hold 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   The never-setting neon suns glow brightly overhead and the
casino pulses softly with an eerie blend of taped Muzak, beeping
machines and the occasional riveting cascade of coins into a metal
tray.
</P>
<P>
   And while idle blackjack and poker dealers stifle yawns,
janitors scrub rugs and men in blue jump suits rush around emptying
coins from machines, a hardy, dedicated few gamble on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won $2,250 one time, and $2,700 another time,'' said Felisa
Garza, 65, a San Antonio seamstress and a veteran of the gambling
graveyard shift.
</P>
<P>
   Garza spoke while tending a cigarette and steadily pumping
half-dollars into two 50-cent slots.
</P>
<P>
   Nine hours earlier, Garza and 32 others boarded a charter bus in
San Antonio. Many clutched pillows and tiny drink coolers for the
330-mile ride.
</P>
<P>
   With a second casino on the itinerary, it would be nearly 24
hours more before the gamblers are home in San Antonio, all weary,
some broke, but most ready to go again next week.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of players from cities around Texas, this is the
low and short road to the Vegas-style action.
</P>
<P>
   And for the Louisiana casinos that depend heavily on Texas
gamblers, the bus trade, humble though it might be, is essential.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos subsidize the Texas bus trips so players pay little
or nothing for the ride. The casinos also often throw in a free
meal and complimentary drinks.
</P>
<P>
   And, since everyone sleeps on the bus, there is no hotel bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't drink. I don't go to dances or movies. I don't do
nothing. This is like a day off for me, to go out. And even if you
don't win, it's a lot of fun,'' she said as the cherries and
diamonds whirl past.
</P>
<P>
   Even at this hour in early June, anything can happen to the
truly lucky, as a gleaming white sports car waiting nearby attests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win a car for 25 cents. Win a BMW Z-3 and $10,000 cash. Play
Super Grand Bonus,'' read the signs on the quarter machines.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case anyone forgets what this is all about,
photographs of smiling winners grasping giant fake checks decorate
the casino walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than Vegas. It's a better bus, better food and
they treat us like people,'' said Josie Ramirez, who has been going
twice a week to Louisiana for nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 65, and in Vegas, they don't have patience. It's more
relaxing here than any place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacinto Perales, 60, who operates a charter service in South
Texas, once hauled gamblers to Las Vegas, a 2,500-mile round trip.
But for the last five or six years, he has been running east.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly our customers are senior citizens and most of them are
regulars. Some go every week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people win. That's why they go with me. We go
at the right time of night and people know which machines pay.
You've got to know your machines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip begins at 7 p.m. on a Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours later, Perales flips on the inside bus lights and
gives the wakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning. We're in Kinder, Louisiana. We'll be at the
casino in about five minutes, so please start waking up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the bus pulls into the casino's vast parking lot, a Jeep
escort with a blinking yellow light attached swoops out and leads
the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Perales gives the customary briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be here until 8 a.m. and during our five-hour stay, you
cannot come back to the bus. You don't have to play but you do have
to remain inside the casino,'' he said, speaking much as a teacher
would to a busload of school kids.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
