<HEADER>
A0547 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-WINDOWS-SPI     06-22 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-WINDOWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 PACKS TV PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Any new product succeeds or fails based on what might
be called its bomb index, how much bang it gives for the buck. In
the case of Windows 98, the index should also include the length of
the fuse.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from antitrust issues, discussion about the
operating-system upgrade Microsoft Corp. will release Thursday has
focused on what it will deliver right away _ smoother operation,
more Internet features, more disk space, for example _ and whether
those things are worth about $90 at retail.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important over the long term are new features in Windows
98 that most consumers may not notice at first: software that turns
the personal computer into an intelligent, interactive television
and delivers mountains of news, entertainment and financial
information without tying up a telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   The reason these features may take awhile to ignite consumer
interest is that they require a television tuner card, an add-in
device still far from commonplace in the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   But hardware makers are pushing to make tuner cards an easy,
inexpensive option for consumers. Microsoft, by adding the software
to Windows today, is aiming to foster and profit from another
explosive business as the computer and the television come together
at last.
</P>
<P>
   Sound cards provide a good analogy, said Steve Guggenheimer, the
Microsoft product manager responsible for its digital television
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we added sound support into the operating system,
adding a sound card was pretty hard to to. Now you can't find a PC
without a sound card,'' Guggenheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we've added the fundamental building blocks for TV
reception, it will start to increase over time,'' he said. ``It's
another logical extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 includes new software called WebTV for Windows that,
in conjunction with a tuner card, turns the PC into a television
monitor and program guide. It lets the user make transactions or
find out more about a topic _ tools that are similar to, though
separate from, those in Microsoft's WebTV set-top products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just used the WebTV brand to represent the TV technologies
that have been added to the PC,'' Guggenheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 also includes a similar technology from Intel Corp.
called Intercast that combines images and data, an example of which
is NBC's coverage of the U.S. Open over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   Television viewers could follow the action on San Francisco's
Olympic Club golf course in the conventional way, but Intercast
viewers could click on graphics on their PC screens to study the
course hole by hole, find biographical data about the contestants
and learn more about the PGA tour.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovation packaged with Windows 98 is a
data-broadcasting service developed by a Phoenix company called
WavePhore.
</P>
<P>
   Called WaveTop, it distributes various types of news,
entertainment, financial and other data using a portion of the
television signal called the ``vertical blanking interval,'' the
horizontal black stripe that appears on a television screen when
the vertical-hold control goes haywire. Users view the information
in a browser, just as they would on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   WavePhore reaches 100 U.S. markets, about 85 percent of the
population, through a distribution deal with the Public
Broadcasting Service.
</P>
<P>
   It is similar in concept to the popular Pointcast service on the
Internet, but because the data is sent in a TV signal, it can be
updated constantly without tying up a telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   WaveTop transmits 170 megabytes of data every day _ 10 megabytes
an hour for 17 hours a day, general manager Sandy Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   WavePhore officially launched the service in April, but is
counting on a boost from Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's going to generate a tremendous awareness of
broadcasting data to your home PC,'' Goldman said. ``That's one of
the main objectives for us _ to hitch our wagon to Microsoft, to
help us educate the market. And second, by including our software
in (Windows 98), you don't have to look for it _ it's already
included.''
</P>
<P>
   As demand grows, a number of manufacturers are vying to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   ATI Technologies makes a product called the ``All-In-Wonder''
that combines TV-tuner and graphics adapter capabilities, and
replaces the computer's existing video card.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Hauppauge Computer Works and ixMicro, make
boards that work in conjunction with the existing video card.
</P>
<P>
   Prices vary, but have dropped substantially in the past couple
of years, said Mike Richmond, manager of broadcast products in
Intel's consumer products group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really a testament to the cost reduction that's very
common in our industry,'' Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
   A few computer makers have begun including TV tuners as standard
equipment, but it will be awhile before they become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers ``don't want to make a device standard until
they can get it for under $30,'' which typically means $75 to the
customer, said Scott Naylor, product manager at ixMicro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working to get the cost down low enough to where it can
be part of a standard machine,'' Naylor said. ``And we're also
working with them to do build-to-order options.''
</P>
<P>
   A tuner board is often a good option for someone buying a new
computer for a home office, he said. For $80 or so, it adds TV
features that would cost a few hundred dollars in a separate unit.
The same logic applies in college dorms, where computers are
common, but space and money are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Tuner boards are also popular with stock brokers, who use them
in desktop computers to monitor television news, and in Pacific Rim
countries, where tiny apartments make it difficult to install a
television and a computer monitor, said Rufus Connell, an analyst
with Frost &AMP; Sullivan in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, adding TV functions to the PC is not about
replacing the television, Microsoft's Guggenheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of putting the PC in the living room and
everyone in the family huddling around it to watch TV,'' he said.
``It's a matter of getting TV information in another area, when I'm
not close to a TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of television and computer technology won't
result in a single all-powerful device, he said. Instead, just the
opposite is likely to happen _ there will be new types of devices,
all with more intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking at a convergence of devices here but at a
convergence of technologies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we might see this moving forward is that devices will
get better and better at sharing information. . . I'm going to want
my information, my personal information, anywhere, at any time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0549 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-CASINOS-2ND     06-22 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-CASINOS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 KINDER, La.: x x x school kids.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Don't forget to take your ID with you. You need to prove you
are 21 when you win. And don't forget what time we leave or your
bus number. We leave at 8 a.m. and it's bus 007,'' he said, noting
the bus number several times and making his passengers repeat it
back to him.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after grabbing a free breakfast coupon and signing up
for a ``player card,'' the eager gamblers pour into the huge
illuminated casino, some not to be seen for five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are a few first-timers such as Teresa Perez of
Laredo, Texas, who is here with her sister. Hours later, Perez
recounted her initial reaction to the extravagant possibilities of
the Grand Casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so fascinated, I was looking all over the place. I liked
the sound of the machines when other players were winning. It was
so exciting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing the nickel machines. I was pushing all the
buttons. I was so excited, the lady came and said, `Are you OK?'
Just slow down,''' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   And, as her own modest stake ran low, Perez said she began
feeling highly conspicuous in the nearly empty game hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Who's looking at me?' I didn't want anyone to know
I had lost. I don't even spend a dollar on the lottery and here I
am spending $40 or $50. My money went so fast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m., right on schedule, the white bus is rolling again
through rural Louisiana, over two-lane blacktops through an
unfamiliar land of tall oaks and pines and amazingly green lawns.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop will be the Grand Casino Avoyelles, in Marksville,
two hours to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than two hours later, they were back at it,
working the slots at the Grand Casino Avoyelles, which _ like the
Grand Casino Coushatta in Kinder _ is on Indian land, where state
gambling laws do not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Neal, a hostess at the Grand Casino Avoyelles, explained
some of its gambler-friendly feature as she conducted a
walk-through of the jam-packed gaming floor.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the 1,700 slot machines, 40 gaming tables featuring
blackjack, roulette, craps, minibaccarat and various poker games,
the casino offers a full-service childcare center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have day care for the kids, from 6 weeks to 10 years of
age, and for those 11 and older, we have an arcade,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are issued a pager so they can be summoned should any
problems arise with their children or should the casino want to see
if they are still in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run random checks to make sure people don't just drop their
kids off here and then go shopping,'' Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Neal said the casino keeps track of how much individuals bet
through their ``player cards,'' which are inserted into card
readers on each machine as players move around the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Gamblers use the cards to accumulate free meals, hotel stays and
other perks, much like travelers get perquisites by accumulating
frequent-flier miles. But the real benefit is to the casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way we can know how much they are gambling,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m. Wednesday, the white bus was again on the road,
beginning the 440-mile trip back to San Antonio. There would be
only one stop, and most gamblers quickly settled in for some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't invite me back,'' said Estella Regalado, a
regular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost everything and just before we left, this lady came over
to where I was playing and put three quarters in and won $500,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As Perales made a fueling stop, the weary gamblers staggered out
to use the restroom, grab a bite and then crawl back on board.
Before he pulled out, Perales asked a final question.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of you would be interested in adding a third
casino?'' he asked, while cautioning that it would add at least
eight hours to the 30-hour trip.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was quick and decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 90 percent of the hands go up. I was surprised. I
thought everyone would want to go back home, but everyone wants to
gamble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ______ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Grand Casino Coushatta is located in Kinder, La. Call
318-738-7263 or 800-584-7266. The Web site is
www.grandcasinos.com/coushatta.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Casino Avoyelles is in Marksville, La. For information
call 800-946-1946.
</P>
</TEXT>
