<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-PAYNTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLUMN'S BASE RESTS ON RESPECT FOR READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ED NOTE: Susan Paynter is the Metro page columnist for the Seattle
P-I)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PAYNTER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Without credibility, all the vivid quotes, funny turns
of phrase and piercing insights a columnist can craft aren't worth
the paper they're written in.
</P>
<P>
   Credibility does not mean never making an honest mistake. Or
that everyone agrees with or likes you. But, without being
believed, you've got zip, nada, bubkes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, award-winning Boston Globe news columnist Patricia
Smith became the latest journalist to learn that lesson the hard
way. She must have known it all along, but somehow chose to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Smith won this year's American Society of Newspaper Editors'
Distinguished Writing Award for column writing. She was a finalist
in April for a Pulitzer Prize. And she resigned last week after an
internal investigation of her work revealed she had made up several
quotes and even fabricated a handful of people featured in her
acclaimed, twice-weekly column.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, her editors admitted her colorful copy seemed too
good to be true _ and apparently was.
</P>
<P>
   In last Friday's farewell, Smith's apology was predictable, just
better written than those preceding her in journalism's hall of
shame.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted her columns to jolt. To be talked about. She had set
her own expectations too high and spread herself too thin. So she
``tweaked'' her copy to achieve the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tweak'' is a pretty polite word for faking news and making up
sources. And while Smith's explanation was surely painful, it was
also spiked with self-pity. ``To those colleagues and readers who
salivated daily at the thought of my head on a platter, congrats,''
she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not the first to go this route. Another Pulitzer
Prize-winning reporter, Janet Cooke, resigned from The Washington
Post under similar circumstances in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   And just last month a series of fabrications caught up with
widely published free-lance reporter Stephen Glass. He admitted
making up people, events _ even a company _ in a report on cyber
crime printed in The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Justifiably, journalism is combing its conscience and checking
the batteries in the smoke-and-mirrors detector.
</P>
<P>
   That's good, because those who break the commandment ``Thou
shalt not defraud the reader'' don't only lose their own jobs. They
lose ground for all the reporters and editors who earn their keep
in column inches every day they go to press.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter's contract with the readers is unforgiving. It says
be accurate, be fair, and, if humanly possible, be first. Do it
against the clock amid noise and chaos and sometimes conflicting
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers may still blame you for bringing them bad news. But
you have a chance to inform and maybe even help them. And, although
the payoff may not come in the form of a nice fat paycheck, it's
there in personal access to the events and people worth knowing
about.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist's contract is not one bit less binding, but it can
be a lot more personal. Expectations are high.
</P>
<P>
   Your face, opinions, personality and sometimes even your
emotions stand in the public square. If you take on difficult and
touchy issues _ as Smith apparently did _ the reaction can be swift
and highly personal.
</P>
<P>
   Without a tender heart, a columnist touches no one. But it had
better be wrapped in a pretty tough hide.
</P>
<P>
   Even after decades in the newspaper business, anonymous reader
attacks can take my breath away.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the anger in the voice of one male caller stayed with
me after a column on moms juggling work with the raising of
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look in the mirror, Susan!'' the voice spat. ``You'll see
what's wrong with this country and its kids. It's selfish,
egotistical, money-grubbing mothers like you! If you can't live on
your husband's salary, you have no right to have a child!''
</P>
<P>
   As a columnist, I have had people write and call radio talk
shows to wish the worst pain, not only for me but for my family. A
few have wished I could still be ``aborted.''
</P>
<P>
   But columnists also hear the kind-est possible comments. And,
once in a while, someone writes to say, ``I don't always agree with
you, but this time you made me think about this in a new way.''
That's the best.
</P>
<P>
   Real life _ and the people who live it _ far outstrip fiction
any day. Their quotes and personas may not always fit neatly into a
column's preconceptions. But being surprised is more fun.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Paynter can be reached at 206-448-8392 or send e-mail to:
susanpaynter(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
