<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0609 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     06-22 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT I WISH SOMEONE HAD TOLD A YOUNGER ME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Greek historian Plutarch once said, ``Oh that men would
learn that the true speaker is he who speaks only when he has
something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   I think the wise ancient one had graduation ceremony speakers in
mind when he uttered those words.
</P>
<P>
   For I cannot remember one idea or suggestion made by any of the
speakers when I graduated from old St. Mary's Elementary School, or
old Laneri High School or even the University of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   True, those events occurred many years ago, but you would have
thought that at least one would have said something that would have
been meaningful enough to have stayed with me.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, I have no recollection of the names of the
speakers. I can only recall that the speaker at Notre Dame was a
well-decorated Army general.
</P>
<P>
   Being a graduation speaker is no easy calling. Most young folks
really don't give a darn what they have to say. The graduates want
to get their diplomas and get out of there to celebrate. Most of
their relatives are there to rejoice in their kin's achievement and
to breathe a sigh of relief that the ordeal is finished.
</P>
<P>
   All these thoughts became clear to me when I was asked to
address the graduating class at Fort Worth Academy a few weeks ago.
I considered it one of the most challenging speaking assignments I
have ever accepted (and I have accepted many during the last
decade).
</P>
<P>
   I searched for quite a long time, trying to determine what I
could say that might have some meaning to these eighth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't need to tell them that they faced many new challenges
as they advanced to a new chapter in their young lives. They
already knew that.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't need to tell them that we were counting on them to
improve this world of ours. They knew that _ at least they had
already been told that on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
   I finally decided that I would share with them five things I
wished someone had told me when I was preparing to leave elementary
school. Here are the five points I wished a graduation speaker had
convinced me were applicable to me, because I had to learn them the
hard way:
</P>
<P>
   1. It is OK for men and boys to cry.
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly 50 years for me to learn the freedom that comes
from shedding tears when I'm hurting, or when I'm rejoicing, or
when I'm deeply moved by an event.
</P>
<P>
   From the looks on the young men's faces that night at FW
Academy, I fear I was not very convincing. That's OK. They'll learn
if they are wise.
</P>
<P>
   2. You don't have to control everything.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of the most difficult things I have had to learn.
Somewhere along the line, I had been convinced that one should
always strive to be in control of every situation.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until I was in the depths of depression at age 48 that
a wise priest-counselor convinced me that I needed to let God take
control of my life _ that he could control circumstances that were
beyond my control during that terrible journey into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   When I finally took that momentous step, I stopped messing up so
many things in my life and the lives of those around me.
</P>
<P>
   3. It is OK to take risks when the objectives are important.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the world's great achievers are risk-takers who
experience an occasional failure, I told the graduates. Reaching
for happiness, striving for love, trying to be a success _ all
involve worthy risks. Those who evade risks encounter blandness.
</P>
<P>
   4. You don't have to be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Why, oh why, didn't someone convince me of that when I was on
the threshold of leaving elementary school? Oh, how much worry I
would have been spared had I been convinced of that.
</P>
<P>
   I was a perfectionist for many years. Yet perfection was often
beyond my capabilities and what was expected of me by others.
</P>
<P>
   When told by my father to rake up the leaves, I figured I had to
capture every leaf in the yard. My father would have been delighted
with the capture of 95 percent of the leaves. Not me! I would have
been down on myself had I not snared that last elusive leaf in the
yard.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wise professor at Notre Dame, Tom Stritch, who finally
convinced me that he and others simply were expecting my best, not
perfection, and that I needed to stop expecting more from myself
than God expected of me.
</P>
<P>
   What a relief that was, although I find myself occasionally
slipping back into that quest for perfection.
</P>
<P>
   5. Don't expect your friends to be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   When we expect friends to give more than they possibly can, we
are doomed to disappointment. This is such an important topic that
I will reserve further comment for another column.
</P>
<P>
   I concluded the talk by issuing a challenge to the students.
</P>
<P>
   I reminded them that they had reached this point in their lives
because of the dedication and hard work of many teachers.
</P>
<P>
   I asked each of them to determine which teacher at the academy
had had the greatest impact on their life and then to write that
teacher, thanking him or her for all they had done for them.
</P>
<P>
   I told the young people to give themselves an A if they
fulfilled the challenge within a week, a B if it took two weeks, a
C it they waited three weeks, a D if it took a month, and an F if
it took longer because I doubted if they would ever do it after a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after making the talk, I received a letter from
headmaster Charles Asche, who told me that the next day he saw
tears running down the faces of several teachers as they read
thank-you notes that they had found in their mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   That made my risking the challenge worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT &LR;      06-22 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING HEALTHY WITH FINS, FUR AND FEATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (JT)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You no doubt know of helpers of the canine persuasion, mostly
guide dogs and perhaps some hearing dogs. But have you ever heard
of therapy administered by a bunny or turtle, a horse or pig or,
believe it or not, a stingray?
</P>
<P>
   These animals, along with cats and dogs, are participating in
the treatment, care and emotional nourishment of seriously ill or
injured individuals, from young children with severe burns,
crippling birth defects or brain injuries to the sick elderly in
nursing homes. They are the stars of a documentary, ``Mary Tyler
Moore in Three Cats From Miami,'' to be broadcast at 8 p.m. Eastern
daylight time and Pacific daylight time on Sunday on HBO. The
documentary is co-presented by the Delta Society, a pioneer in
animal-assisted therapy through its Pet Partners Program.
</P>
<P>
   It shows Splash the stingray as he prompts Noah, a boy with
cerebral palsy, to rise from the wheelchair he is reluctant to
leave and walk up stairs to help feed Splash and receive a
thank-you kiss _ yes, a kiss from a stingray _ as well as a bit of
a bath in return.
</P>
<P>
   It shows Harley the swine _ who acts more like a dog than a pig
_ prompt Juanita, a severely brain-injured girl, to begin to tune
into her surroundings and attempt to talk.
</P>
<P>
   And it shows Frosty, a 1,300-pound horse, helping children like
Jordan, who has Down syndrome, improve his muscle tone to the point
where he can run, jump and play like other children, and John, who
was brain-injured and is stiff most of the time, learn to relax his
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the three cats, Buster, Flashback and Flame, who
bring joy, comfort and love to elderly patients in a Florida
nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Assistance animals, as they are called, have been helping ill,
injured and disabled people for many decades. The overwhelming
majority of the animals have been dogs. But in recent years the
popularity of pet therapy has burgeoned and the variety of
assistance animals has expanded to include monkeys, dolphins, birds
and fish. Many medical institutions and rehabilitation services,
including White Plains Hospital Center in Westchester County, N.Y.,
are now incorporating pet therapy into their more traditional
ministrations.
</P>
<P>
   How Pet Therapy Helps
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever had a pet that responds to talk or touch
knows the comfort and joy an animal can offer a human being. Pets
bring people out of themselves, help them forget their troubles and
enjoy the company of a living creature that rarely complains. Pets
lavish unconditional love, stimulate laughter, foster
responsibility and self-esteem and make their owners feel needed.
Pets can also minimize health risks in people who are not sick.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown, for example, that blood pressure declines
when people watch fish swimming about in a tank. Researchers in
Melbourne, Australia, recently found that pet owners overall have
lower blood pressures and cholesterol levels than people who do not
own pets. Those with birds or fish for pets were as well off as
those with dogs, so it was not the exercise associated with walking
a dog that was responsible for this finding.
</P>
<P>
   A study of 1,000 Medicare enrollees in a health maintenance
organization found that those with pets experienced less stress in
response to disturbing life events and paid fewer visits to
physicians than their counterparts without pets.
</P>
<P>
   Pets of all kinds also foster social interaction and reduce
isolation and loneliness, especially for those who are seriously
disabled or disfigured and might otherwise be avoided by strangers.
</P>
<P>
   And for the seriously ill or disabled, a pet can do much more.
Service dogs can be trained to perform nearly 100 different tasks,
including opening and closing doors, turning switches on and off,
pulling a person up from a sitting or lying position, assisting a
person in and out of a bath or pool, helping someone dress,
retrieving dropped or needed objects, pulling wheelchairs, helping
with shopping and carrying packages and even dragging a person to
safety in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Dr. Karen Allen, in the department of medicine at
State University of New York at Buffalo, and Dr. Jim Blascovich, at
the University of California at Santa Barbara, published the
results of a two-year study of the value of service dogs to people
with disabilities that required them to use a wheelchair. The 48
participants, half of whom were given service dogs, had severe
chronic conditions that required many hours of care each day. Those
with service dogs developed a higher level of self-esteem and
psychological well-being and were more involved in their community.
They were also more likely to work part-time and use public
transportation and they required less assistance. After one year,
the number of hours of paid assistance they needed had declined by
68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More Parts for Pets
</P>
<P>
   Pet therapists are constantly discovering new roles that pets
can play in aiding the ill and injured. At the Shriners Burn
Institute, for instance, a once-abandoned bunny named Dusty is
encouraging children who have been severely burned to learn to
touch again. In Florida, a loggerhead sea turtle named Mo, born
with a defective shell, helps to build self-esteem in Robert Smith,
a boy born without legs. Robert gets to do something no other child
does _ brush Mo's shell and rub his neck and flippers.
</P>
<P>
   And in Tacoma, Wash., inmates at a women's prison rescue and
train abandoned dogs to be assistance pets. One of the dogs,
Natasha, a Shepherd-Husky mix, goes to school with Stephanie, who
has neurological problems and uses a wheelchair. Natasha opens the
gate, pulls Stephanie's chair and accompanies her on the school bus
and into the classroom, to await the next task, like picking up a
dropped pencil.
</P>
<P>
   In cooperation with Pennsylvania Hospital, Independence Dogs
Inc. in Chadds Ford, Pa., trains dogs to assist Parkinson's disease
patients whose severe symptoms cannot be relieved by drugs alone.
The dogs are taught, for example, to tap a patient's foot with a
paw when the patient is suddenly unable to move, or ``freezes.''
The tap prompts the patient to move again. The dogs are trained to
walk beside the patient and provide support when balance is lost,
which has significantly reduced falls and fostered independence.
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of his canine assistant, Ivan, Russell Moore, a
Parkinson's patient who had been nearly house-bound because he fell
so often, became able to take long walks, go grocery shopping,
visit the mall and attend church.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1540EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
