<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICES WERE AMONG THE BEST IMPROVEMENTS AT PC EXPO SHOW  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN MANES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computers are about as fast as they are likely to get for a
while. Over the next year or so, the megahertz rating of top-of-the
line microprocessors will improve from today's 400 to just 500, a
gain so small as to be invisible with most programs.
</P>
<P>
   But as last week's PC Expo show made clear, computers and the
things that hook up to them are getting cheaper and cheaper. A
person who last looked at price tags a year ago will be astonished
at prices today. Thanks to a consumer-friendly confluence of
oversupply, competition, Asian financial woes and relentless
self-improvement among hardware makers, prices are plummeting in
just about every area of the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you might think prices on machines themselves cannot
drop further, there they go again. Prices should drop a bit more
before school starts and drop yet again before Christmas. That
means $600 computers with brand names you have heard of will be
commonplace before the end of the year, and no-name machines will
be even cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Bargains will be the rule all the way up and down the price
range. One example at the show at the Jacob K. Javits Convention
Center in New York was Sony's forthcoming VAIO E203, which will
include a DVD-ROM drive that can play movies on television sets as
well as the computer screen. It will also come with a new
300-megahertz Celeron processor, 48 megabytes of random access
memory, and a 6.4-gigabyte hard drive, all for a surprisingly low
$1,300. This machine is among the first in an expected trend to
replace the CD-ROM drive with a much more facile DVD unit on most
computers above the very bottom of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Computer prices typically do not include the monitor, but after
a long era of slowly declining prices, monitors are getting cheap
fast. A year ago, a typical brand-name ``17-inch'' display cost
more than $500; now you can get one for as little as $300, and
there are similar bargains in other sizes. For a small premium,
several makers are beginning to offer a line of what might be
termed ``stubbies,'' units whose shorter front-to-back dimensions
can free up a bit of desk space. Now that Windows 98 can handle
more than one monitor at a time, one strategy that can deliver a
great deal of screen area for the buck is to buy two or more
17-inchers. The biggest problem, once you get them to work, is
where to put them.
</P>
<P>
   If desk space is really at a premium, you can always buy an LCD
display, which typically resembles the screen from a normal laptop
machine stuck on a little pedestal; it may or may not include
speakers. Prices for these range widely, but a few small units have
been sighted at about $800. LCD screens can present problems with
some video cards, tend to cause problems at screen resolutions
other than the specific one they were designed for, cost more than
twice as much as equivalent tube-based models and vary widely in
quality. But the diagonal measurements of LCD screens are reported
accurately, unlike the inflated measurements of their tube-based
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Digital cameras, now made by electronics companies, computer
companies and even camera companies, were all over the show, and
they, too, keep getting better and cheaper. ``Megapixel'' cameras
that can produce decent 5-by-7-inch prints were rare, expensive
birds just a year ago. Now they cost about $800 and come with more
features than ever, and even a cursory inspection of several units
reveals significant differences in every aspect, from output
quality right down to the shape of the case. Though computers have
increasingly become functionally identical commodities, the
designers of digital cameras exercise great creativity to make sure
that no two seem remotely alike, which makes them hard to compare.
</P>
<P>
   Installing a network in one's home has long been attractive only
to the hardest-core of computer geeks, but in theory it can save
time and money by letting the whole family share things like
printers and scanners. Now that there are plenty of
multiple-computer households, some networking ideas about to arrive
on the market do not require festooning the walls and baseboards
with new wiring. The Intelogis Passport system sends its signals
along the A.C. power wires in your home at a rated speed of up to
350 kilobits per second, or about 10 times that of a typical modem;
two computers and a printer can be connected for less than $300.
The Symphony system from Proxim Inc. is designed to transmit its
bits over radio waves significantly faster over a range of up to
150 feet.
</P>
<P>
   For peripheral devices, the Universal Serial Bus, better known
as USB, is slowly gaining the momentum that was expected for it
thanks to software plumbing built into Windows 98. Several monitors
included USB hubs, which allow multiple devices to be plugged in at
once. USB computer speakers also appeared, promising cleaner audio
because they bypass the sound card and accept digital signals
directly, turning the bits into audio far from the festival of
electronic noise found inside most computers. The promise is
cleaner sound, but there are potential drawbacks, like just how the
device handles standard music CD's.
</P>
<P>
   Some ideas are just too good to be left alone. Not far from the
booth where Sony was showing its slim three-pound VAIO 505
notebook, Sharp Electronics Corp. displayed a forthcoming knockoff.
The Actius A100 Ultralite will come with a bigger screen, a bigger
hard drive, more memory and a bigger battery than Sony's $2,000
unit. It will also cost $500 more, but that still seems a good deal
for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, today's computers are becoming so cheap that they are
even being used to control more expensive things. Play Inc. showed
off Trinity, a big case of electronics that costs upward of $5,000
and amounts to a television control room in a box, complete with
the sort of jazzy fade, dissolve and loop-the-loop effects that
infect everything from commercials to the evening news. What
controls this cornucopia of chips? A plain-vanilla Windows computer
no more powerful than the one you bought for your kid last
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
