<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ALBRIGHT-OPED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGAGING CHINA IS NOT ENDORSING CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MADELEINE K. ALBRIGHT  
 c.1998 MSNBC and the Center for War, Peace and the News Media  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It is difficult to exaggerate the importance of China's place in
the world today, or of the role it is likely to play in the future.
</P>
<P>
   As President Bill Clinton has said, our relationship with China
``will in large measure help determine whether the new century is
one of peace, security and prosperity for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-fourth of the world's population lives in China. It
has the world's third-largest economy. It is a nuclear weapons
state, a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council and, after
the United States, the world's largest source of greenhouse gases.
China shares borders with 14 other nations _ more than any country
in the world _ and it has unresolved border disputes with four of
them.
</P>
<P>
   From maintaining stability on the Korean Peninsula to resolving
the economic problems of East Asia to addressing global warming,
China will play a key role in the international community.
</P>
<P>
   That role can be helpful or harmful, and it is the task of
American diplomacy to ensure that it is indeed helpful. The manner
in which we engage China will have an important bearing on whether
China becomes integrated as a constructive participant in
international institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to China presents an opportunity to continue
building a productive relationship with this vast country, one that
will benefit both of our peoples for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 26 years, six presidents have all striven to
achieve a proper balance in our relationship with China. But
engagement with China does not mean endorsement. To accomplish our
goals, we need a clear policy that firmly advances American
interests and values.
</P>
<P>
   We must assert our positions on issues ranging from
nonproliferation to intellectual property. We must voice our belief
in the universality of human rights. And we must make clear our
commitment to the peaceful resolution of the differences between
China and Taiwan. Clinton's policy of engagement with China meets
these needs.
</P>
<P>
   Our strategy is based on the premise that it is in our interest
to work toward the emergence of a great, stable, open and
nonaggressive China that embraces political pluralism and global
norms of conduct and that works with us to build a secure
international order, as well as peace and stability in the Asia
Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   Our policy has thus far achieved significant results. After
decades of rejecting such cooperation, since 1992, the People's
Republic of China has signed on to a variety of nonproliferation
regimes, including the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, the
Chemical Weapons Convention and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, when the five permanent members of the Security
Council met in Geneva to discuss nuclear tests in India and
Pakistan, China _ this month's coordinator for the permanent five _
oversaw efforts that led to a forceful expression of the
international community's determination to stabilize the situation
in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In Korea, where American and Chinese troops once battled, we are
now working together with China in the Four Party Talks aimed at
finally realizing a permanent peace on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   China has also released on medical parole to the United States
such prominent dissidents as Wei Jingsheng and Wang Dan, signed the
U.N. Covenant on Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights, and has
pledged to sign the U.N. Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
   However, many differences remain. We continue to push for more
progress on our nonproliferation, trade, human rights and energy
and environment agendas. Clinton's visit offers an opportunity to
energetically press for such progress. Meanwhile, we have seen
China move in the right direction, toward greater acceptance of
international norms.
</P>
<P>
   In our determination to address these challenges, we must not
ignore the achievements. And to make further progress, expand
cooperation and advance our national interests, we should continue
our engagement with the Chinese people and government through firm,
forceful and patient diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   On regional and global issues, in the areas of nonproliferation,
economic cooperation and even human rights _ where much more
progress is still needed _ the achievements are real, and our
policy is working.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Madeleine Albright is the U.S. secretary of state. She wrote
this article for ``The Challenge of China,'' a project of MSNBC and
New York University's Center for War, Peace and the Media.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
