<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE ANNIVERSARY PROMPTS CALL FOR BLESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is the 160th anniversary of Congregation
Beth Emeth and the year has been marked with observances and
salutations by its congregants and public figures from President
Clinton on down. The event has religious and secular significance.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Emeth (House of Truth) began life in 1838 as Beth El (House
of God), founded by Albanians who for years had practiced their
faith without the assistance of a rabbi. Their first rabbi was not
hired until eight years later, but he turned out to be a historic
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Mayer Wise, an immigrant from Germany, brought with him to
his first pulpit the ideas that were shaping the Reform movement in
his native land. Although at Beth El he was the spiritual leader of
a traditionally Orthodox congregation, he began to introduce
elements of Reform observance in Albany during his rabbinate from
1848 to 1851. After he left Albany in a dust of controversy, he
became the chief promulgator of Reform Judaism in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But celebrants this year were not heralding the anniversary of
Beth El, whereby hangs a story about three Jews shipwrecked on a
desert island who establish four synagogues. The joke only
exaggerates substantial reality. In Albany this tendency at schism
was demonstrated before Rabbi Wise arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   In 1841, a small group detached from Beth El to form their own
temple, Beth El Jacob, even though both followed the Orthodox
ritual, as then was commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   When Rabbi Wise showed up five years later and began to
integrate some Reform practices, which radically differed from
Orthodox ritual, there was dissent among the worshipers who had
remained with Beth El. In time, disagreements got so severe that a
public brawl took place, which required the intervention of the
Albany police. Afterward, the modernists headed off on their own,
establishing Anshe Emeth (People of Truth) as a Reform
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth Reform congregation in America and is the
basis for the distinction claimed today on behalf of Beth Emeth,
because the two congregations reunited in 1885, as Reform was in
ascendancy and while the Orthodox synagogue was losing so many
members it could no longer keep going. In coming together again,
their new name combined the Beth from the one with the Emeth from
the other.
</P>
<P>
   This rich history was recounted recently in a musical review at
the Albany temple.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the audience, it was easy to reflect on the good
fortune of being able to celebrate 160 years of continuity, having
survived the fractures, and having done so in a very special
country. It is a fundamental American myth, based on reality, that
this country welcomed newcomers of all nationalities and faiths,
which made it possible for a group of people, who would never be
more than a tiny minority, to live life according to their ethnic
and religious traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Many _ if not most _ of these immigrants, whether they came in
the 19th or 20th centuries, were more familiar with other
experiences. Instead of being able to live peacefully in one place
for more than decades upon decades, these people were more
accustomed to picking up their shattered belongings and fleeing
pogroms and persecutions from country to country, from place to
place, in search of a haven, however temporary it might turn out to
be in the end.
</P>
<P>
   In our time, such fearfulness reached epic dimensions. That's
why, as I sat there in temple, to see the kids and their parents
and their grandparents performing to everyone's delight, I was
reminded, even in that circumstance, of Kristallnacht, the night 60
years ago when the Nazis burned Germany's synagogues. The thought
struck about the vast difference between America and not only
Germany, but many other countries as well.
</P>
<P>
   These words are written aware that given the history of the
Jewish people, it is tempting fate to speak too loudly about good
fortune. There have been other times and other worlds in which the
Jews flourished only to be brought to utter despair. Ironically,
Germany before Hitler, although suffused with latent anti-Semitism,
was not inhospitable to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, during the reign of the Moors, Jews contributed
mightily to the general culture and to their own, for hundreds and
hundreds of years. When in the 15th century, the Christians
conquered Spain, the Jews were confronted with a choice that often
faced them: convert or be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   All these thoughts intermingle on the occasion of the 160th
anniversary of Beth Emeth, my temple. It is here that one of my
daughters was confirmed and another was married and where a
granddaughter was named. It is here where our family shares in the
joys and the griefs that mark the life of a congregation.
</P>
<P>
   On occasions of moment, Jews offer a particular prayer. Given
all that has been and the uncertainties of what might yet be, that
prayer fittingly acknowledges the 160th anniversary, blessing God,
``Who has kept us alive and sustained us and brought us to this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
