<HEADER>
A0629 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`LASTDAYS'-DIRECTOR-T     06-22 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`LASTDAYS'-DIRECTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIVE TALKING WITH THE DIRECTOR OF `LAST DAYS OF DISCO'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 46, ``Last Days of Disco'' director Whit Stillman still loves
the night life, he loves the boogie, and he doesn't think either
fits in well with thunking melons.
</P>
<P>
   As the title of his movie indicates, Stillman is fond of disco
music, but he says it has its place, and that place is in the
clubs. Not in commercials. Not on the radio. Not in any piped-in
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to go to clubs anymore; you can just go to
supermarkets,'' Stillman said during a Dallas stop, loquacious
despite (or maybe because of) a publicity-tour-induced lack of
sleep. ``I remember a lot of the songs that I hear on CD, and I
don't like 'em much. And then I hear them in an auditorium, where
people are dancing, and I think, `You know, this IS good. This DOES
work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``The Last Days of Disco'' is more about the days than
it is about the disco. It's set in the early '80s, before MTV and
AIDS became two of the decade's defining acronyms, as a group of
young men and women debate the merits of social groups vs.
``ferocious pairing off'' between rounds of dancing at a Studio
54-esque nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debate'' is a key word here; unlike in disco songs, the words
in the movie are more important than the music. As in Stillman's
other films, ``Metropolitan'' (1990) and ``Barcelona'' (1994), the
characters love to talk, and they're so witty and erudite that they
could be pre-millennial visitors from an Oscar Wilde or Noel Coward
piece.
</P>
<P>
   Like his characters, Stillman is an urbane New Yorker who likes
to talk, although after a day of interviews he's more prone to
tangents than the young, epigram-spouting people who populate his
movies. He says he was a little concerned about how ``Disco'' would
play outside New York, but that it tested well in screenings in
Houston and Austin.
</P>
<P>
   And Stillman has been spending more time in Austin recently,
serving on the advisory board of the Austin Heart of Film Festival,
a screenwriter-centered festival that runs in early October. He's
even considering a Texas project, one with deep personal roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great-great-grandfather was the founder of Brownsville,
Texas, and was one of the earliest Texans,'' Stillman said. ``The
historical museum in Brownsville's the Stillman House, and the
museum is the old house Charles Stillman had. The film is not
really about him, but it's that period and it's essentially the
part of the war that's not large-scale. It's not the Alamo, but
it's the Texas war of independence.''
</P>
<P>
   But just because Stillman is switching gears doesn't mean that
he believes his conversation-heavy style is running out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's the opposite,'' he said. ``For me, (''Disco'' is)
the culmination film. This is the film where I got to do everything
I wanted to do, use the music I wanted to use. We actually have
much less dialogue in the film than in the others. There are only
about four really big set-pieces, conversation scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when those conversation scenes include a dissection
of how well ``Lady and the Tramp'' works as a social comedy and a
brief discussion of the sexiness of Scrooge McDuck, it's apparent
that this isn't your run-of-the-mill summer one-liner comedy. But
Stillman believes that the movie's audience will find it, and that
it will complement rather than conflict with this season's other
disco movie, the upcoming ``54.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are similarities, they're in the youthful casts.
``Disco'' stars Chloe Sevigny (''Kids'') as Alice, a demure college
graduate who enters a boogie wonderland accompanied by her brash
roommate Charlotte (Kate Beckinsale of ``Cold Comfort Farm''). They
hook up with a young ad exec (Mackenzie Astin), a corporate lawyer
(Robert Sean Leonard), the club's manager (Stillman regular Chris
Eigeman) and a rookie prosecutor (Matt Keeslar) for nights of
dancing, drinking and talking.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the on-the-verge-of-a-breakthrough cast, Stillman
makes a comparison to a true disco-era movie _ the 1979 flop
``Thank God It's Friday'' _ although he makes it clear that he's
comparing the casts, not the films.
</P>
<P>
   `` `TGIF' had Debra Winger, Jeff Goldblum, all these great
people,'' he said. ``But I don't think it helps `TGIF.' Maybe the
hope would be that `Disco' would be like `St. Elmo's Fire,' that
launched that whole group of people, without the odium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Odium'' _ again, like his characters, Stillman gets the
erudite last word.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
