<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0633 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSTARICA-TRAVEL-1200     06-22 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-TRAVEL-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SON ALSO RISES ON COSTA RICAN FISHING TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by BC-COSTARICA-TRAVEL-TIPS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HADDAWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEPOS, Costa Rica _ I had never danced with a fish before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on, Dad!'' said my son, James. He strapped a rod-holder
around my waist, so the butt of the rod wouldn't dig into my
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep the slack out of the line!'' he reminded me as the
sailfish leaped into a pirouette. The fish was dancing, I was
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you doing all right, Dad?'' he asked after the boat rocked
a little and put me off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   The sweat was rolling into my eyes. He got a towel. He gave the
old man a sip of Fresca. ``Are you sure you're all right?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   He's 26, I'm 49, and we'd come to Costa Rica for a week of
guyness.
</P>
<P>
   It had been years since we'd had any real time together, ``mano
a mano.''
</P>
<P>
   For so long we'd been busy, on separate tracks,
career-searching, career-building; growing up, growing out. And I
was thinking, as I hung onto that fish for dear life, my son's hand
on my shoulder guiding, instructing _ man oh man, how times have
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, wasn't it, when I was wrestling with his diapers? He
was 2. I was getting more powder in his hair than where I'd aimed
it. Finally, I got the darn thing pinned and let him loose, and
with one step he walked out of it and then the dog got the diaper
and ran off with it, and there I was with this little nude dude
running after the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, wasn't it, when we were together on the jetty at Port
Aransas, a cane pole, a cork, fishing for piggy perch. He was 6. I
had my hand on his shoulder, counseling about patience, about
waiting for the full bite of the fish and not the nibble. And he
did, and he got one, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   And yesterday, too, when we were walking across a field
together, shotguns in hand, waiting for doves. He was 14. I had my
hand on his shoulder, counseling about patience, about hiding till
the last minute, waiting until they come in range, and then the
quick, perfect flow of the end of the gun with the bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on, Dad, I think that fish is wearing down.'' He had his
hand on my shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We flew into San Jose on a Sunday evening. We got the car the
next day and headed for the hills.
</P>
<P>
   James is a Spanish teacher. He'd spent three weeks in Costa Rica
the year before, so he knew his way around. He led the way.
</P>
<P>
   First thing was getting the right vehicle. It was a
four-wheel-drive Isuzu Trooper, pretty worn, but we thought it
would do. It looked tough.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I was introduced to what should be the state symbol of
Costa Rica, the ``huecos grandisimos.''
</P>
<P>
   No, those are not some rare bird. They are potholes, some as big
around and deep as bathtubs, some just rough ruts, and they are
everywhere. Driving among them makes everybody look like a drunk.
You go all over the road to avoid as many as you can. ``Ca-lunk,
ca-lunk,'' the jostling is as rude as a New York subway crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It took us four hours to get to Fortuna, in the central
mountains, where the famed Arenal volcano loomed.
</P>
<P>
   The highways were not always paved, never wider than a
farm-to-market road, always busy with livestock and pedestrians and
tractors.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape was lush. This was the green side of the country _
we'd be spending most of our time in the dry, Pacific side. Here
were fields of coffee plants, woods, pasture and cattle. Every
fence post had a canopy of leaves on it. The chopped trees
sprouted.
</P>
<P>
   Road signs were an afterthought, but James could get all the
directions he needed with the charm of his Spanish. Our wrong turns
didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Back in Austin, his home, James had gotten to know a gardener
named Rigo Arce. He was from Costa Rica, couldn't speak English;
James didn't have many people he could practice his Spanish with.
They talked up a storm on numerous visits.
</P>
<P>
   It happened that Rigo was from Fortuna and had a dozen brothers
and sisters and cousins there. He wrote a letter of introduction
for James. We brought it with us. It opened doors.
</P>
<P>
   One brother, Oliver, was a fishing guide, and he took us to Lake
Arenal. It was just like bass fishing in a Texas lake, in an area
something like the rugged hills around Possum Kingdom in North
Central Texas, but here we were in the shadow of a coughing,
smoking volcano. The fish were ``guapote,'' a wide, striped, dark
green bass cousin but with big teeth and a temperament to match. We
caught a half-dozen. Just as many broke free. ``''Gracias a dios!''
Thanks to God!'' Oliver said with each strike.
</P>
<P>
   James had wanted to see the Arenal, the volcano, at night, but a
veil of clouds had kept its red top hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, however, knew the secret. You had to come around to the
other side of it, to the dam, beyond the Tabacon resort, he said.
Then, at night, the clouds often lifted away and you could see the
red spout.
</P>
<P>
   We tried it. Out on the dam, on the side of the road, a family
had stopped for a sort of volcano picnic as they waited for the
darkness. We waited with them, sitting on the side of the road,
listening to the drumbeat of frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, high in the darkness, we saw an orange sputter, then a
glow, and then the glow broke up into red pieces _ molten rock
tumbling down the mountain. The fire was alive.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Oliver went with us from Fortuna to help us find the road to our
next stop, the Pacific coastal town of Tamarindo. He went halfway,
driving with us all morning, then took the bus back.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Costa Rican way of doing things. Somebody is good
to your brother back in the States? You have a friend for life in
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pura vida'' is a phrase you'll hear often here. The pure life.
The good life.
</P>
<P>
   It means other things, too _ ``how are you?'' ``OK,'' ``cool,''
``goodbye.'' ``Pura vida.'' Good people in a beautiful country
where friendship and helpfulness and friendliness are paramount.
The good life.
</P>
<P>
   When Christopher Columbus first wandered into the area in 1502,
the Indians offered him gifts of gold, and the Spanish explorers
began referring to the place as the ``rich coast,'' or Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniards thought they had an area rich in mineral wealth,
but that was not the case. Costa Rica was rich in other things.
</P>
<P>
   Mountains, rain forests, semiarid plains and stretches of
cropland; the Caribbean on one side, the Pacific on the other, all
of which could be called the Oregon coast of Central America, with
its true blue water crashing into rocks; and a climate that doesn't
stand still, if you don't. Because of the varied landscape, you can
get the tropics on one side of the mountains, West Texas on the
other and Colorado on top. This makes for a tiny country that is
one of the most bio-diverse in the world. It is home to 5 percent
of all the plant and animal species in the world. Rich, indeed.
``Pura vida.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Tamarindo is a resort town famed for its surfing. We spent two
days here.
</P>
<P>
   James was determined to catch a wave. He'd never surfed much
before. He was also determined that I learn, too. I tried.
</P>
<P>
   The board looked too big for me to handle, so we decided that
dear old Dad would start off small, on a boogie board, which is a
sawed-off, bantam-weight surfboard for the wave-disabled _ sort of
a surfboard with training wheels.
</P>
<P>
   At least I could carry it. After a time I snagged a wave or two,
in the shallows, skimming into shore on my stomach.
</P>
<P>
   James left me for the big water. He went out and worked at it,
and in an hour he was standing, bending, turning down the hills of
waves, and I was remembering the old days again.
</P>
<P>
   He was 4. He wanted those training wheels off his bike.
Unmechanical Dad was reluctant. How was I ever going to get them
back on if things didn't go well?
</P>
<P>
   He nagged. I took the little wheels off, and he got on. I held
him upright for a second and then gave him a push. He took off and
never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Dad did three waves on his boogie board and sat on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Our last stop was Quepos, seven hours south of Tamarindo, also
on the Pacific. It's where the best deep-sea fishing is.
</P>
<P>
   The roads were worse than ever, the ``huecos grandisimos''
unavoidable. We lunged and plunged, bumping and grinding, and the
dust was a chalky fog. Cars traveled with their headlights on.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, on a rare stretch of smooth pavement, a herd of goats
bounded across the highway two vehicles ahead of ours. A fruit
truck hit the brakes, a tour bus hit the fruit truck, pineapples
hit the ground and we missed the whole thing by inches. The goats
weren't even startled.
</P>
<P>
   Quepos (''Kay-pose)'' was an oasis. Not green _ the jungle
around it was often brown and crisp because of the dry spell _ but
at least the dust was gone. The ocean was blue and cool. The air
felt lush.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Librett runs an offshore charter outfit called On the
Fly. He's an American expatriate with a forward-thinking philosophy
on fishing. We'd made reservations months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sport'' is the key word. He uses fly rods (typically used in
trout streams) for catching sailfish _ weighing from 100 to 200
pounds. And he follows a catch-and-release system, taking extra
care when removing the hook and patting the worn-down fish back to
oxygen viability before sending it back to the deep. None of that
winching in of fish like a heavy-equipment operator and heading for
the taxidermist.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't get to use fly rods this time. The fish were slow to
surface and lacked enthusiasm for the baits. When you use a fly
rod, you've got to tease the fish close to the boat with a hookless
lure, then toss some real bait to them with the smaller rod.
</P>
<P>
   We did a lot of sitting that day. The fish showed up hourly or
so, and Marvin the deckhand was supposed to announce fish sightings
and give us directions on which of five baits it was hitting. But
each time Marvin just went nuts and started screaming in Spanish,
and we'd all lunge for the nearest rod.
</P>
<P>
   James caught a 40-pound dorado _ a blunt-headed, rainbow-colored
fish that is known as a mahi-mahi in other ports. We had several
near-misses with sailfish, then James got one hooked.
</P>
<P>
   He played it well. They danced together. His fish was a
ballerina. He got it in, we took a few quick pictures, and she was
on her way. The guide guessed 125 pounds, a nice fish.
</P>
<P>
   Then, toward noon, it was my turn.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I struggled a little longer with mine, although it wasn't as
big. It took out line again and again, thrashed on the surface,
dived, turned, danced. It was a solid thrill, one of those guy
things, touching the wild.
</P>
<P>
   My son stayed close beside me, guiding, encouraging, gently
showing the way. This was my first sailfish. He'd caught a bunch.
</P>
<P>
   At last I got my fish to the boat. Librett said it was too tired
to bring up for pictures. He had to get the hook out at once. In
seconds it was free and gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good job, Dad,'' James said. ``Good job.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
