<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILCOLLINS-HNS &LR;      06-22 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS LOSE PATIENCE WITH COLLINS, SHOW 

</HEADLINE>
 COLLINS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDY SUMMA 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Take a look at him now.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Collins, the venerable 47-year-old pop icon, is trying to
reinvent himself _ and his music. And not everybody is happy.
</P>
<P>
   Before an almost-sold-out crowd at the Cynthia Woods Mitchell
Pavilion in The Woodlands Thursday night, classic Genesis and Phil
Collins tracks were performed. And the talented British
drummer/singer was onstage. But Collins, an able drummer in his own
right, was only that for most of the night. He didn't sing until
the very end.
</P>
<P>
   The Phil Collins Big Band took the stage at 8:30 p.m. and
delivered efficient and often sophisticated big-band renditions of
the classic rocker's greatest hits. The orchestration was tight,
the band hit almost every note and the arrangements were sometimes
beautiful. The music that made Collins famous (``Invisible Touch,''
``That's All'') translated perfectly into big-band stylings.
</P>
<P>
   But many in the humid pavilion audience obviously came to hear
the wily Brit's voice trounce along with the music. By 9:30,
smattered, half-hearted boos and yelps of ``Sing!'' were heard
between songs, prompting the normally cool Collins to snap, ``Did
they run out of beer?''
</P>
<P>
   No, but many in the audience ran out of patience and began
leaving in droves. Apparently, their appreciation of big-band
music, Phil Collins-style anyway, had worn thin. But for those who
kept an open mind, the music was personal and well-received.
Collins' music was played in a different style, to be sure, but the
orchestral variations only added depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Invisible Touch,'' the fast-paced melody-driven Genesis
anthem, was a highlight of an easygoing jam session Thursday night.
The song built confidently and methodically, like a slow train to
nowhere. The well-paced song climaxed with a fantastically polished
Gerald Albright saxophone solo.
</P>
<P>
   The exuberant Albright caressed the high notes and bussed the
low ones as he wailed through a brilliant performance. His sultry
note-dancing through ``Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)''
was topped only by his breathtaking solo during ``In the Air
Tonight.'' He got a standing ovation for ``Against All Odds,'' but
his soulful play through ``Tonight'' was the high point of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Next, ``I Don't Care Anymore'' (Collins' ``Take This Job and
Shove It'' homage, perhaps) was performed with playful Pink Panther
undertones. After a forgetful ``Hold On, My Heart,'' the group
strutted through the rhumba-singed ``In the Air Tonight,'' with the
Albright solo stealing the show.
</P>
<P>
   The band segued into ``Georgia on My Mind,'' a bloated
solo-heavy opportunity for a restroom break, and then gave the
stage to Oleta Adams for a curiously long six-song set.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, a talented vocalist and powerful stage presence, did
everything right _ she sang with soul and gave a solid performance.
By the time she slinked onstage, however, many in the audience just
wanted Collins to step up to the mike.
</P>
<P>
   The show, the fourth stop on a 13-city summer tour, had been
advertised as ``instrumental,'' and Collins stayed true to its
definition. He finally did belt out a few numbers (Tony Bennett's
``The Way You Look Tonight''), and the dwindling audience took
notice. But after two hours of ornate orchestration and anxious
anticipation, the vocals lacked the overall impact many had hoped
for. Maybe the encore should have been his 1994 single ``We Wait
and We Wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phil Collins Big Band put on a great show. But the Phil
Collins moniker on the title may have been overemphasized.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
