<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-TRAVEL-TIPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPFUL HINTS IF YOU'RE GOING TO COSTA RICA
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies COSTA RICA-TRAVEL) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HADDAWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   General information: Costa Rican Tourist Board: (800) 343-6332.
</P>
<P>
   Getting in: You need a valid passport; visas aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out: Departure tax is about $17. People just outside the
airport will take care of you.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: There are about 50 car-rental agencies in Costa
Rica. We rented an Isuzu Trooper for $350 a week, unlimited
mileage, with $1,000 deposit refunded if you bring the car back in
one piece.
</P>
<P>
   Check your vehicle carefully before you take possession of it.
We didn't. The brake pads were worn down to the metal; the horn
didn't work, nor the heat gauge. The engine light came on and off
for no reason. We had a flat on our last day; the jack didn't fit
the car.
</P>
<P>
   Money: Colones are valued at about 255 to the dollar. To
exchange cash, U.S. bills must be in good shape, not worn or torn.
Take traveler's checks. Cash machines are hard to find in smaller
towns.
</P>
<P>
   Medical: This is a clean country. Although we generally used
bottled water, we weren't absolutely careful, and we had no
problems. Malaria pills are recommended. Check with your doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: ``Lonely Planet'' notes that there are more than
200 hotels in San Jose, but accommodations can be tight in the high
season, which is December to May. It suggests making reservations
three months in advance for Christmas and Easter, with rooms
prepaid.
</P>
<P>
   Only blocks from the airport is a Hampton Inn, just like the
ones at home. You can avoid the congestion of San Jose if all
you're interested in is a clean place to stay before or after a
trip into the hinterlands. (800) 426-7866. $65 double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at the Cabina Jireh in Fortuna. New construction, hot
showers, air conditioning. $69 for a double. 011-506-479-9004.
</P>
<P>
   We enjoyed the Hotel Tamarindo in Tamarindo. It's right on the
beach under a canopy of palms, but the rooms are a lot nicer in the
new addition across the street. Doubles $83-112. 011-506-653-0031.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of character at the Hotel California in Quepos. The walls
are painted with murals of Costa Rican national parks. The
architecture is Eurotech. Natural setting at the top of a hill,
with squirrel monkeys as neighbors. Beautiful pool. $60-100.
011-506-777-1234.
</P>
<P>
   Resorts: No, no, you don't have to rough it. Several resorts are
nestled in the hills between Quepos and Manuel Antonio. Hotel La
Mariposa offers 10 villas with big windows that look out on the
white sand beaches and tropical hills. Also ceiling fans, balconies
and bathrooms that incorporate tropical gardens. $220-$240 for a
double. 011-506-777-0355.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, on 42 acres among waterfalls, forests and sand beaches
is Tulemar Bungalows. Kayaks available for wave-running. $180 for a
bungalow that sleeps four. 011-506-777-0580.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely upscale is the Tabacon Lodge outside Fortuna, in the
shadow of the Arenal volcano. As part of the stay, you get free use
of the thermal springs at Tabacon Resort across the highway. Sit
under a warm waterfall or baste in one of the warm pools among
tropical gardens. Massages, swim-up bar, good view of the volcano
at night. Doubles $88-$100. 011-506-256-1500.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat: We never had a bad meal, but we had a few
mysterious ones. Lots of black beans, fried things. Go in one of
the open-air cafes where the natives hang out and ask for the
``plato tipico'' (blue-plate special) and see what you get.
</P>
<P>
   Try El Gran Escape in Quepos. We brought in our fish, and they
fixed it up nicely, some of it grilled, some fried.
011-506-777-0395.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing: Go fishing in Lake Arenal with Sunset Tours in Fortuna.
$250 for full day of fishing. 011-506-479-9415.
</P>
<P>
   A full day of offshore fishing with On the Fly in Quepos is
$600. That includes gear, bait, lunch, drinks. (800) 836-1235.
</P>
<P>
   Parks: Costa Rica is a natural wonder. Manuel Antonio National
Park, just outside Quepos, is stunning. Easy walking along sandy
footpaths. Monkeys and iguanas everywhere. Admission $6.
</P>
<P>
   Pick-up line (James swears this works): ``Tu tienes tantas
curvas, y yo sin frenas.'' (''You have so many curves, and I don't
have any brakes!'')
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
