<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
YIP-COLUMN
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUDENT LOAN RATES GOING DOWN SOON
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
By Pamela Yip &QL; 
Your money &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU ARE headed for college in the fall or spring, or your
child is, you should be in the heat of filling out applications for
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   There's good news, but timing is important.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that starting July 1, interest rates on federal
student loans drop dramatically to the lowest rates in 17 years.
The decline from about 8.25 percent to 7.46 percent on that date
reflects a change in the formula for calculating the rates.
</P>
<P>
   Currently the rate is based on the yield of the 91-day U.S.
Treasury bill, plus an additional 3.1 percentage points. On July 1,
the spread will drop to 2.3 percentage points. There's a 8.25
percent cap over the life of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Those will be one of the lowest student loan interest rates in
17 years. However, there's a catch.
</P>
<P>
   These rates apply only for Stafford loans, the most common
college loan program, taken out between July 1 and Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The rub is that private lenders making student loans don't like
the new system because they will be paid less by the federal
government for making the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, lenders are paid a 3.1 percentage-point spread above
the 91-day treasury bill yield, but that spread will fall to 2.8
percentage points in July.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders said that's not enough and some may be forced to pull
out of the student loan program if Congress doesn't find a
permanent solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now makes it more difficult for us to find a reasonable
return for the investment and risk that we take in making these
loans,'' said Jim Gathard, business executive for education loans
at NationsBank in Charlotte, N.C. ``It is very likely that some
lenders will find that they can no longer participate in the
program because the yield margin is so narrow today that they
wouldn't want to make the loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenders can't expect what the government pays them to go up
because of budget constraints, so the best they hope for is that
things won't be so up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The key to giving lenders some certainty is Congress'
re-authorization of the Higher Education Act, which would make
permanent the changes and the lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   The House has approved its version of the legislation and the
Senate is expected to take it up this week.
</P>
<P>
   Call your U.S. senator and urge him or her to support
re-authorization of the Higher Education Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress were to fail to pass the Higher Education
re-authorization, there would be a problem for loans on or after
Oct. 1, 1998,'' said John E. Dean, attorney for the Consumer
Bankers Association in Washington, D.C., a banking trade group.
</P>
<P>
   However, I don't expect Congress to commit political suicide by
doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody anticipates that happening,'' Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   The message for parents and students is don't panic. Loan money
isn't about to dry up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question whatsoever about the availability of
loans for students returning to school this fall,'' Dean said.
``Virtually all students who need loans are going to be able to
find them very easily.''
</P>
<P>
   However, don't dillydally about filling out financial aid
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders I talked to said they don't plan to pull out of the
student loan program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not anticipate major lender withdrawals,'' Dean said.
``It will cause a reassessment of participation by some smaller
lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger lenders will figure out a way to become more
efficient so they would be able to continue to make student loans,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we decided to stay in the program even with the
30-basis-point (0.3 percent) reduction,'' said Mary Polsley, senior
vice president of corporate relations in Bank One's Education
Finance Group. ``We're pretty dedicated to the student loan
program, and we feel we can make up the 30 basis points.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank also will remain in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to make loans because our customers have a
substantial need to find ways to finance higher education,''
Gathard said.
</P>
<P>
   But what's key to him is that Congress acts on a permanent
solution instead of a temporary fix so that lenders have a firm
guideline to work with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Temporary is the worst way for me,'' Gathard said. ``If I know
I have a fixed index and fixed spread for the next five, six years,
I can try to say let me see how I can work my budget so I can at
least know what my expectations are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
