<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LEPER-COLONY-ART-     06-22 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LEPER-COLONY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH HOME AND PRISON, LEPROSY CENTER TO CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (jt)  
 By SANDEEP JAUHAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARVILLE, La. _ Tucked away in a bend in the Mississippi River,
on a quiet two-lane country road, is a place where fever, fear and
hope have intersected for more than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosts occupy these grounds. Ghosts of people brought in
handcuffs to live out their days, under aliases, behind a
barbed-wire fence; of women denied their babies and, sometimes,
motherhood; of lovers who obeyed passion's demands by slipping
through a hole in the fence; and of nuns who loved people for whom
even the Bible has an unkind word, ``unclean.'''
</P>
<P>
   But this is a place of the living, too, and they are facing a
jolting change. This place, once called the Louisiana Leper Home,
but now commonly known as Carville, after the town whose physical
and psychological landscape it dominates, may soon close.
</P>
<P>
   A bill sponsored by Rep. Richard Baker, R-La., and signed into
law by President Clinton in November, will transfer control of the
site, the Gillis W. Long Hansen's Disease Center, from the U.S.
Public Health Service to the State of Louisiana, which plans to use
it for troubled young people.
</P>
<P>
   The few patients who still live here can accept a $33,000 annual
stipend and leave Carville for good, move to a long-term nursing
home in nearby Baton Rouge, where they will receive much of the
same care they received here, or remain in Carville with fewer
doctors and nurses and less intensive medical care. They will have
until Oct. 1 to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Most patients do not want Carville to change, and at least half
do not want to leave. Once their prison, Carville is now home.
``Some of the patients have never known any other life than this
place,'' said Rachel Pendleton, 63, who has been a patient here for
almost 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital has outlived much of its medical usefulness.
Most people are naturally immune to leprosy, and nowadays it can be
treated on an outpatient basis, thanks to the sulfone drug
treatments pioneered at Carville in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   The stigmas of the infection _ the rotting limbs from repeated
trauma to nerve-damaged extremities; the facial deformities; the
blindness _ are now largely prevented with aggressive multi-drug
therapy and orthopedic management. The number of patients at
Carville has dropped from about 400 at its height in the mid-1980s
to 134 today.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization has set the year 2000 as a goal
date for eradicating leprosy as a widespread public health problem.
It wants to see the number of cases in endemic areas like India and
the Philippines drop below 1 in 10,000. There are about 6,000
people with leprosy in the United States, but ``medically they're
cured,'' said Dr. Robert Jacobson, the director of Carville. As
long as they take their medication, their disease is in remission
and they are not infectious.
</P>
<P>
   But Carville has not vanished as quietly as it began, in 1894
when seven lepers were brought by coal barge to slave cabins on an
abandoned sugar plantation. Over the years, many people have argued
that the federal government has a moral obligation to keep the
place open. They say that a government that deprived people of
liberties and a chance to develop basic skills must not abandon
them.
</P>
<P>
   The millions of dollars spent each year to maintain Carville
made it an easy target for budget cutters. But Dr. John Duffy, a
former director and outspoken Carville critic, said that for years
Federal lawmakers were hesitant to take action. Duffy, who argues
that there is no longer a need for a place like Carville, said
public officials lacked ``the will or intestinal fortitude to
confront patients and employees who were living off the federal
largess.''
</P>
<P>
   For some patients, Carville cannot close soon enough. ``I really
want to get out of here and forget this place ever existed,'' Mrs.
Pendleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Leprosy was first diagnosed in Mrs. Pendleton at the age of 5,
when a numb spot developed on her leg, but she went untreated for 9
years. At the age of 14, she says, she was kidnapped by public
health officials and brought to Carville, which, she said, ``robbed
me of the best years of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another patient, Nancy Battista, 69, said she had ``mixed
emotions'' about the impending changes. Ms. Battista, who arranges
books in the Carville library with hands curving and rigid from
leprosy-related nerve damage, recently separated from her husband,
a former Carville patient who now lives in California. She plans to
take the annual stipend and move to San Francisco to live close to
her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Battista said she was lucky to have something most patients
did not have: family. But many of her Carville friends will
probably remain in what is the only home they have ever known. In
Carville, she found a far better place than she had known in her
native Philippines, where she was locked up at night in barracks,
not given medication and was fed a diet of soup and rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very bad memories there, very bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Carville, she said, ``we were taken care of, regardless,
whether rich or poor.
</P>
<P>
   In his tiny apartment, the walls covered with his oil paintings,
Johnny Harmon, a stooped 86-year-old with emphysema, remembers how
the doctors who diagnosed his leprosy in 1935 disclosed it to a
local newspaper, despite his pleas. A headline in the newspaper
reported, ``Local Health Official Discovers Case of Leprosy in
Highway department.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon believes patients are better off staying at Carville.
``If you get diagnosed in a small town, where they don't know
anything about the disease, they get scared to death and scare your
family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon met his wife, Anne, at Carville, where she was a patient,
and they settled in a small cottage there. ``My folks thought I was
crazy for marrying a girl with leprosy,'' Harmon said. ```Well,' I
told them, `I have leprosy, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Francis de Sayles Provancher, 81, a Daughter of Charity
here for 50 years, hopes she will die at Carville. ``The only thing
I want is to be buried at Carville with my patients.'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Francis has lived at Carville for all but seven years
since 1942, when she developed a lifelong passion for treating
leprosy. Fiercely devoted to her patients, she replies sharply when
asked about the Bible's admonitions against lepers: ``The Bible
should be rewritten. It was wrong on that count.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
