   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DISNEY (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush's first chore
if he runs for president in 2000 may be to persuade the Republican
Party's social conservatives to accept his little-known role in
helping to finance more than a dozen R-rated movies for the Walt
Disney Co. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT-DEATHS (Laredo, Texas) _ The U.S. Border Patrol beefs up
its rescue efforts along the border in South Texas, where at least
six illegal immigrants have died in the past week in a torrid heat
wave. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-ELECTION (Bogota, Colombia) _ A follow-up on Colombia's
presidential election Sunday, in which the conservative former
Mayor of Bogota, Andres Pastrana, was elected president. Pastrana
had accused the current leader, Ernesto Samper, of accepting drug
money. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   JERICHO-CASINO (Jericho, West Bank) _ With cash from private
international investors, Palestinians are about to turn the world's
oldest city into the Middle East's newest gambling destination, say
representatives of an Austrian-based casino company that has set up
shop in Jericho. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ House Republicans were shamelessly
grandstanding last week when they decided to eliminate the federal
income tax system in one fell swoop, without so much as suggesting
how to replace it. Do they really think voters will take such
fakery seriously? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you are headed for college in the fall
or spring, or your child is, you should be in the heat of filling
out applications for financial aid. By PAMELA YIP. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Pete Sampras has owned
the grass courts of Wimbledon for the past five years, winning four
titles and staking his claim as one of the greats of the game. But
questions abound this year as Sampras enters Wimbledon mired in one
of the worst slumps of his career. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Steffi Graf has
dominated Wimbledon for nearly the past decade, but she is only one
of the many intriguing contenders in this year's women's field. By
JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
</TEXT>
