<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, June, 23. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Hank Warnke (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUKE (Moscow) _ Ignoring American protests, Russia has
sold two nuclear power stations to India, Russian and India
officials said on Monday. The nuclear deal, which is worth more
than $2 billion to Russia's cash-strapped nuclear energy ministry,
is part of an broad array of civilian and military technology
Moscow is planning to sell despite India's decision to conduct five
nuclear tests, a decision that will almost certainly help India
break out of its diplomatic isolation. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FREEDOM (Shanghai) _ At a kitchen table strewn with glossy
fashion magazines, Lucy Lu sat with her boyfriend Tony Yao and
talked about what it is like to live together without being
married, an arrangement rarely allowed in China until recently.
More than being symbols of a sexual revolution, this young couple
signals a growing realm of personal freedom in China that allows
ordinary people to make choices about travel, work, study and love
with less government interference than at anytime since the
People's Republic was established nearly 50 years ago. By Seth
Faison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-REVENUE (London) _ The recent drop in oil prices, which
began in October and accelerated recently, has prompted several
oil-producing countries to trim spending in anticipation of less
revenue. In the last month, Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil
producer, has quietly borrowed some $2 billion from its banks to
help pay for public spending program as it prepares to reduce its
budget by at least 10 percent and raise fees on government services
_ all to offset the most serious fall in oil revenues in a decade.
By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS (Washington) _ A sharply divided Supreme Court set
a highly restrictive standard for determining when school districts
can be found liable under Federal law for a teacher's sexual
harassment of a student. A harassment victim can recover damages
from the school district only if a school official with the
authority to intervene actually knew of the teacher's misconduct
and, acting with ``deliberate indifference,'' failed to stop it,
the Court said in an opinion by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor. The
vote was 5 to 4. The decision came in a case from a school district
near Austin, Texas. By Linda Greenhouse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court struck for the first
time against the federal government's aggressive use of forfeiture,
ruling that a forfeiture intended as punishment is unconstitutional
if the amount seized is ``grossly disproportional'' to the gravity
of the offense. Applying that test in a sharply contested 5-4
ruling, the court went on to declare that the government could not
constitutionally seize $357,144 in undeclared cash that a Los
Angeles man and his family had attempted to bring in their luggage
on a flight to Cyprus to repay a family debt. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BORDER-TOWNS (El Paso, Texas) _ Four years after the North
American Free Trade Agreement lowered trade barriers, the cities
along Texas's long border with Mexico that had hoped to benefit are
instead struggling to become more than glorified truck stops as
they watch their manufacturing jobs go south by the thousands.
Almost everywhere else in the United States, the economy is booming
and the national unemployment rate is the lowest in nearly 30
years. But along the border unemployment persists at two and three
times the national rate, and incomes remain far below state and
national averages. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   FISH-LOGO (Republic, Mo.) _ Eight years ago, on a whim, Marilyn
Shexsnayder entered the contest to design a logo for her hometown.
She was a stockbroker, not an artist. But using her colored pencils
and her computer she drew an oustretched hand, a family of four in
silhouette, and, to portray the centrality of religion in this old
railroad town with more than 25 churches and about 8,000 people,
she sketched the simple fish that she had regarded from childhood
as a universal symbol of faith. She won the logo contest and $100
prize. Now, suddenly, the little fish is causing an awfully big
splash. Someone complained about the fish to the American Civil
Liberties Union, and in February the organization sent a letter
asking the mayor to delete the fish from the logo because the fish
was ``unmistakably identified with Christianity.'' By Laurie
Goodstein. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
