<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-JANZEN-HNS &LR;      06-22 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-JANZEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANZEN TOO BUSY WINNING TO GRIPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lee Janzen sat down and dandled the U.S. Open
trophy on his right knee, as though it were his son, Connor, or in
a more playful mood, his wife, Beverly.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it was an unconscious but loving gesture.
</P>
<P>
   It had been nearly an hour since he had completed one of the
most remarkable comebacks in major tournament history, turning a
seven-shot deficit to Payne Stewart into a one-stroke win at the
Olympic Club. And though he had pretty much emptied himself of his
rawer emotions, Janzen still could cloud up when he thought of what
he had done, where he had done it, and most of all, how.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I feel right now,'' he said, still tanning himself in the
glow of his final-round 68, ``is complete satisfaction, knowing
that I played my absolute best in the tournament I love the most.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't kidding about any of that, either. He stepped out of
the blow-dried pack in 1993 by winning the Open at Baltusrol,
coincidentally beating Stewart on the last day of that tournament
as well, then won the Players Championship in 1995 to move to the
short list of great-player candidates, then went three years
without winning anything but hugs from the family and a series of
sizable thanks-for-coming checks.
</P>
<P>
   Which is right where he, and everyone else in the field, thought
they would be when day dawned over the Olympic Club in San
Francisco. Stewart wasn't too far ahead, necessarily, but he was
playing too well to be run down, and especially after Janzen
bogeyed the second and third holes to fall the equivalent of two
holes behind even before Stewart had cleared his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I bogeyed 2 and 3, my only thought was honestly to hit
some good shots, play some good holes, and see if I couldn't
somehow get back into it,'' he said, making whistling in the
graveyard look optimistic by comparison. ``I wasn't thinking about
winning, but I wasn't counting myself out.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, why duplicate the efforts of the rest of the
golf-speaking world? They all knew that Stewart had this one packed
in dry ice and ready for shipping, because nobody in a position to
challenge had shown much gumption to actually do so.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, though, was an odd duck among the flock this week. While
most of the chorus was scatting away about the USGA, its rulebook
and for all we know, its catering, Janzen was standing foursquare
for fast greens, hard fairways, improbable roughs and thick trees
that take balls and never give them back.
</P>
<P>
   Well, most of the time, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The bogey on 3 set him back mentally, but had he known it would
be his last, he might have been a lot giddier about the way the day
was going to turn out. He birdied 4. He put a ball in a tree at 5,
walked for more than a minute toward the tree, then back toward the
tee box, when a gust of wind blew the ball out and into the rough,
which no matter how thick or high is still a better lie than a
branch 30 feet above ground.
</P>
<P>
   This reminded many observers of how Janzen beat Stewart at
Baltusrol in '93, by putting a shot between two trees to save a par
that looked hopeless. It reminded him of nothing but how much more
work there was to do.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied 7. He birdied 11. And then he birdied 13, and told
himself he no longer would watch the leaderboard to see how Stewart
was coming along. This was a departure for him, since like any
modern control freak, Janzen wants all the information in his hands
ahead of time. Now, though, he wanted the solitude _ just him, his
caddie and the club in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped looking when I was on the 13th green,'' he said. ``I
just made a point of not doing it after that. I didn't want to
think if I got the lead ... I didn't want to play it safe.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he didn't. There is no reason not to believe him, what
with the evidence there bouncing contentedly on his knee.
</P>
<P>
   For Stewart, well, he left town suspecting, if not out-and-out
knowing, that he would be remembered as the fourth member of an
Olympic Club quartet of failed favorites, with Ben Hogan, Arnold
Palmer and Tom Watson. Stewart said all the right things about
Janzen's winning, as you knew he would, and he spent a few minutes
passionately disputing the concept of the fairway sand divot, one
of which helped pull a bogey out of him at 12.
</P>
<P>
   The sand divot debate we will leave to The Golf Channel's
``Nothing Else On At This Hour Of The Night Theater.'' As for his
testimonial to Janzen, it bears repeating, because it explains how
the professionals will remember Janzen's performance for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the third-to-last group, and he shot 68,'' Stewart
said, resisting the temptation to add, ``right on my head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody in contention in the golf tournament that shot
under par today expect for Lee Janzen, so he deserves to be the
champion today.''
</P>
<P>
   And later: ``Let me just show you something right here. Now I
hit six fairways in regulation today, and Lee Janzen hit 12. I hit
nine greens in regulation, and Lee Janzen hit 14. Bingo. That's why
I didn't win the golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, just maybe, because for Janzen this had just a tinge
of a labor of love, rather than a sandbag fight with a bouncer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why I was emotional today?'' he said. ``Because it
says `United States Open' on it. This is the national championship,
and this is just the best one to win. I feel extremely lucky to be
playing golf for a living, and to win the U.S. Open here, well, you
can't do anything better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then someone asked him about the importance of Father's Day, and
having his father, Larry, as well as Connor and Beverly on hand,
and he waxed even more philosophical than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every day that I'm the luckiest guy going,'' he said.
``There's nothing better than being loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Which made a person wonder, if only trophies could talk ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
