<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARASS-HNS &LR;      06-22 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARASS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-HNS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  SCHOOL DISTRICT ISN'T LIABLE FOR TEACHER WHO MOLESTED STUDENT,
COURT RULES
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Note: If there is a question about identifying the victim, her
name was included in the case title and documentation with her
familiy's consent.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
By STEVE LASH &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Texas girl who was molested by her high school
teacher lost her lawsuit against the school district Monday when a
sharply divided Supreme Court ruled the district cannot be held
liable because the teacher's supervisors did not know of his
abhorrent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision, the court narrowly interpreted a 1972
federal law aimed at prohibiting sex discrimination in public
schools. That law, Title IX of the Education Amendments, permits
the federal government to restrict funds to schools that
discriminate, but gives students only a limited right to sue
because of harassment and discrimination, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   For a school board to be found liable, students must prove
someone with supervisory responsibility, such as a principal, knew
of and deliberately did nothing to prevent the harassment, the high
court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   No supervisors in the Lago Vista Independent School District
near Austin knew that teacher Frank Waldrop was molesting student
Alida Star Gebser, 15, until a police officer caught the teacher
and student having sex in January 1993, the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the high court rejected Gebser's argument that
schools should be held liable for abuse committed by teachers. The
justices also were unpersuaded by the federal government's
contention that districts should be held liable when they ``should
have known'' of a teacher's misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, the justices said Title IX is primarily a funding
statute that allows the federal government to restrict funds when
it can show that a school board displayed deliberate indifference
toward sexual discrimination in the classroom and on the playing
fields. Students who sue a school must prove that the board knew of
the harassment but chose to do nothing, the high court held.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one questions that a student suffers extraordinary harm
when subjected to sexual harassment and abuse by a teacher, and
that the teacher's conduct is reprehensible and undermines the
basic purposes of the educational system,'' Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor wrote in the court's majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue in this case, however, is whether the independent
misconduct of a teacher is attributable to the school district that
employs him under a specific federal statute designed primarily to
prevent recipients of federal financial assistance from using the
funds in a discriminatory manner,'' she added. ``Until Congress
speaks differently on the subject ... we will not hold a school
district liable in damages under Title IX for a teacher's sexual
harassment of a student absent actual notice and deliberate
indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia,
Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas joined O'Connor's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The harassment that gave rise to the Supreme Court case began in
the spring of 1992, Gebser's freshman year, when Waldrop kissed and
fondled the student after stopping by her home ostensibly to give
her a book. The pair had sex several times during the rest of the
school year and summer.
</P>
<P>
   The student never reported the behavior to school officials.
After the policeman arrested Waldrop, the school district fired him
and the Texas Education Agency revoked his teaching license.
</P>
<P>
   The girl and her mother sued the school board in November 1993,
but lost in both the U.S. District Court for Western Texas and the
5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. Both courts held, as the Supreme
Court did, that Title IX holds school boards liable only if they
knew of the harassment and failed to respond.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Justice John Paul Stevens said the school
district should be held liable for the behavior of its employee,
even if supervisors had no actual knowledge of what Waldrop was
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case presents a paradigmatic example of (an injury) that
was made possible, that was effected, and that was repeated over a
prolonged period because of the powerful influence that Waldrop had
over Gebser by reason of the authority that his employer, the
school district, had delegated to him,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a secondary school teacher, Waldrop exercised even greater
authority and control over his students than employers and
supervisors exercise over their employees,'' Stevens added. ``His
gross misuse of that authority allowed him to abuse his young
student's trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer joined Stevens' dissent.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate dissent, Ginsburg reiterated that school boards
should be held liable for teachers who molest students. However,
she added that a board could escape liability if it had a strong,
well-publicized policy prohibiting and redressing instances of
harassment. A school district with such a policy could not be held
liable for the harassment of a student who ``unreasonably failed to
avail herself'' of the district's procedures, Ginsburg wrote. She
was joined in dissent by Souter and Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Gebser's attorney, Terry L. Weldon of Austin, assailed the
Supreme Court's decision, which he said marks ``the end of the
road'' for his client's claim against the school board and rewards
schools that ignore their teachers' misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling ``will allow school districts to cultivate ignorance
of their teachers' wrongdoing and then to assert that ignorance as
a complete defense to any (Title IX) litigation,'' Weldon said.
``This unfairly places all the burden on students who are in most
cases immature and emotionally vulnerable to teachers who exploit
their position of trust and power.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lago Vista's attorney, Wallace B. Jefferson of San
Antonio, praised the high court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court properly refused to hold school districts
liable for the concealed criminal conduct of abusive employees,''
Jefferson said. ``Most school districts would be financially
devastated by jury verdicts holding them liable for sexual
harassment which they could not have prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
