<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Louise Woodward, the British nanny, now back home in England.
Gee, I wonder if any of those people who were cheering for her in
that pub will help her out now, maybe give her a babysitting job.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about brave new world. I don't know whether this is creepy
or science or what, but for the first time ever, a woman has given
birth on the Internet. She's fine, the baby's fine, the keyboard's
a mess.
</P>
<P>
   And, God bless him, 78-year-old Tony Randall became a father
again. His wife gave birth to their second child. Tony says he just
wants to live long enough to see his kids graduate preschool.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Jones is getting a nose job. Which I think is great. Now,
she'll finally be able to turn around in her trailer.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Whitney Houston and Bobby Brown announced they are
separating. Apparently, it's over career differences. I guess she
has one.
</P>
<P>
   Internet users can find more information about NBC and its
programming at www.NBC.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Bulls won their sixth NBA championship, Chicago
police had to arrest more than 400 people for overturning cars,
looting stores and throwing bottles. In fact, things were so bad,
police ran out of mace and had to spray people with Michael
Jordan's cologne.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been reported that Sylvester Stallone is considering
doing 'Rambo IV.' Producers say if they can't get Stallone, they're
going to use Koko, the sign language-speaking gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The makers of the Barbie doll announced that their sales this
year are going to be lower than expected. They said if things don't
improve, they'll have to introduce the 'I love you long time
Barbie.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Senate Majority leader Trent Lott compared
homosexuals to kleptomaniacs. Lott said he knows about
kleptomaniacs because he once had a roommate in college who stole
oral sex from him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This past Monday, 78-year-old Tony Randall and his wife had
their second child. Not surprisingly, they're naming the child
Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a recent interview, Luciano Pavarotti said that he's been
counseling Ginger Spice. Pavarotti said, 'Ginger is my favorite
spice next to the ones the Colonel uses.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``On singles cruises, passengers are taking part in a new
X-rated scavenger hunt where they have to search for underwear,
bras and lingerie. It's kind of like Easter at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Father's Day is coming up this Sunday which means that right
now Michael Jackson's kid is shopping for a tie that will fit a
turkey baster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After 60 years, the Navy has decided that sailors' bellbottoms
are outdated and undignified and they're getting rid of them. The
bad news is, they're replacing them with hot pants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night at the White House, President Clinton gave out a
prestigious architecture award. This year's winner was an Italian
architect who proposed mirrored ceilings in the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A New Jersey man was arrested for smuggling 1,800 fake Beanie
Babies. The disturbing part is, authorities found the 1,800 Beanie
Babies during a cavity search.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been reported that several Washington lobbyists have been
secretly supplying members of Congress with Viagra. And you can
tell because today Newt Gingrich started a meeting by pounding on
his desk and he wasn't using a gavel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists have isolated the gene for alcoholism. It was
trying to pick up the gene for homeliness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a recent survey, over half of New Jersey drivers say they
frequently experience rage or anger while they're driving. They
said the rage happens when they're driving down the street and they
realize they live in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wynonna Judd stopped singing the national anthem at a sporting
event the other day because she screwed up the words. Apparently,
Wynonna was distracted and sang, 'Oh, say can you see those hot
dogs; they look delicious.'''
</P>
<P>
   Internet users can find more information about NBC and its
programming at www.NBC.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I was hurrying toward Union Square during the rainy spell we had
a few weeks ago. My umbrella had collapsed in the wind and my hands
were full of packages.
</P>
<P>
   I was feeling rather sorry for myself when I saw a homeless man
lying on a sleeping bag on the side of the street and talking to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, all my self-pity was replaced by guilt. How could I
have felt sorry for myself? I continued to walk along, chastising
myself, and began to search my pockets for change. As I approached
him, I looked more closely and realized that he was not talking to
himself at all _ he was on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   _ HEATHER L. EISENMAN
</P>
<P>
   Sister Sheila Campbell is a native New Yorker but she had never
been to the Aquarium at Coney Island until a friend visited.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lovely day and the two were enjoying the indoor and
outdoor display of the sea lions, but Sister Sheila didn't want to
miss the shark feeding, whether it was indoors or out.
</P>
<P>
   She asked the attendant standing next to the indoor shark tank
where the sharks would be fed that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady, today we're taking them to Nathan's,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Vargas describes himself as a mature gentleman who has
never taken an interest in the pricey hair salons that cut, blow
and style. He goes to no-frills men's barbershops and opts for the
shortest cut possible. Recently, he came to the conclusion that his
hair style had limited appeal, that perhaps he was the only person
who appreciated it.
</P>
<P>
   This sad fact was made clear to him by an unusual experience
while he was sitting in his barber's chair. A little boy was in the
next chair and he was giving both his mother and the barber a hard
time.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, in desperation (Vargas' words), pointed to Vargas
and said in a threatening tone to her son, ``If you don't behave, I
will tell the barber to cut your hair just like his.''
</P>
<P>
   Things eventually settled down and the mother, realizing that
she might have offended Vargas, attempted an apology. ``I just
wanted to scare him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything! Six visiting sailors, out for a night on
the town, recently got on the subway at West 4th Street. They were
gazing around wide-eyed and clearly excited to be in the big city,
said a fellow passenger, Patricia Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   A panhandler entered the car and began his speech: ``Ladies and
gentlemen, sorry to disturb you, but has anyone here had to eat
government cheese day after day, every day?''
</P>
<P>
   Six arms in crisp white uniforms shot up, the other occupants of
the car burst into laughter and the panhandler beat a hasty
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   As Pauline Trigere was walking into the hotel where she usually
has her hair done, a young couple, obviously tourists and
accompanied by their luggage, were awaiting a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy Airport?'' the doorman asked them.
</P>
<P>
   The woman drew herself up indignantly _ no rube she. ``No,'' she
said. ``JFK.''
</P>
<P>
   A colleague's 2-year-old son was visiting him at the office. The
child sat at a nearby desk playing with a cup of pencils, and a
Mickey Mouse pencil caught his eye. He tried to draw with it but it
made no marks. It was unsharpened. ``What's wrong?'' he asked.
``Nothing comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been sharpened yet,'' his father replied.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's face looked blank for a moment but suddenly it lit up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to get new batteries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ SCOTT BANE
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Brick Swid was carefully preparing to negotiate the last
step as she went down the escalator at the Port Authority terminal.
A tall young man in blue jeans, directly ahead of her, turned
around and gently helped her off. No words were spoken and he
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Swid, who says she is a small older lady, was naturally
curious. She caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you do that?'' she asked. ``I wasn't in need of
assistance. I've traveled all over the world and no one has ever
needed to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen my mother in 12 years,'' he said. ``She lives
in the Philippines. I miss her terribly.''
</P>
<P>
   And once again, he walked away.
</P>
<P>
   We have taught our 2{-year-old son, Elliot, to be friendly with
the people who live in our apartment building, especially in the
lobby and in the elevators. Those we don't know he refers to as
``neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall, distinguished-looking, balding man stepped on the
elevator recently and Elliot immediately greeted him with ``Hello
neighbor,'' but then he added, ``What happened to your hair?''
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I almost choked. Not getting an answer, Elliot
turned to me and said clearly, ``Mom, what happened to that guy's
hair?'' There was no escape; our floor was still a way off. I was
just about to stammer something when the neighbor replied: ``I lost
my hair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot exclaimed: ``You lost your hair? Will you find it?''
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I held in our embarrassment and hysteria with
difficulty until we finally arrived at our floor. Getting off the
elevator, Elliot patted his own hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost his hair,'' he repeated in amazement and added,
perhaps to reassure us: ``I won't lose mine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ROXANNE BOK
</P>
<P>
   Maryanne M. Garbowsky was in the checkout line at a supermarket
the other day, just behind the counter waitress at her local deli.
Ms. Garbowsky greeted her.
</P>
<P>
   The waitress smiled in recognition. ``You're the large tea,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garbowsky, more than somewhat surprised, congratulated the
woman on her good memory and said she couldn't wait to relate the
encounter to the friend who usually accompanied her to the deli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you mean the turkey on rye,'' the waitress replied.
</P>
<P>
   They had finished lunch and Muriel Lilker's friend Ina Shivack,
who had walked to the nearby ladies' room, returned almost
immediately. She had no sooner told Mrs. Lilker that it was
occupied than she spotted another customer heading for the same
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on line,'' Mrs. Shivack called out, running after her. The
other woman kept on walking and Mrs. Shivack repeated that she was
on line.
</P>
<P>
   When they both reached the bathroom door, Mrs. Shivack explained
that she had been waiting to get in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' the other woman replied, ``I thought you were talking
about a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LITTER OF KITTENS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A three-year-old boy went with his dad to see a new litter of
kittens. On returning home, he breathlessly informed his mother,
`There were two boy kittens and two girl kittens.`
</P>
<P>
   `How did you know that?` his mother asked.
</P>
<P>
   `Daddy picked them up and looked underneath,` he replied. `I
think it's printed on the bottom.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRAVY LADLE --- Oldie but greatie &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An elderly priest invited a young rabbi over for dinner. During
the meal, the young rabbi couldn't help noticing how attractive and
shapely the housekeeper was. Over the course of the evening, he
began to wonder if there might be more between the elderly priest
and the housekeeper than met the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the young rabbi's thoughts, the elderly priest
volunteered, `I know what you must be thinking, but I assure you my
relationship with my housekeeper is purely professional.`
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, the housekeeper came to the elderly priest
and said, `Father, ever since your young rabi friend came to
dinner, I've been unable to find the beautiful sterling silver
gravy ladle. You don't suppose he took it, do you?`
</P>
<P>
   The priest said, `Well, I doubt it, but I'll write him a letter
just to be sure.` So he sat down and wrote:
</P>
<P>
   `Dear Rabbi:
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying that you DID take a sterling silver gravy ladle
from my house, and I'm not saying you DIDN`T take it. But the fact
remains that one has been missing ever since you were here.`
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, the elderly priest received a letter from
the young rabbi which read:
</P>
<P>
   `Dear Father:
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying that you DO sleep with your housekeeper, and I'm
not saying that you DON`T sleep with your housekeeper. But the fact
remains that if you were sleeping in your own bed, you would have
found the gravy ladle by now.`
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
