<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPREDICTABILITY AT THE OLYMPIC CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Payne Stewart tipped his very distinctive cap to
Sunday's two winners. Lee Janzen had the U.S. Open trophy all to
himself, but he shared Stewart's respect for San Francisco's most
famous golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Olympic Club really won,'' Stewart said, ``because
there was one person even-par for the tournament. So I think this
golf course stood up to the test of being an Open championship.''
</P>
<P>
   For three days, though, Stewart pulled a con. He led with ease
before Sunday's final round, four strokes ahead of anyone. He
defied the convention that at the Open, and especially at the
Olympic Club, there is no convention. He banished the craziness and
lived in the fairways. Very rarely did he let the bushy rough
obscure the cut of his knickers.
</P>
<P>
   He had us all going for a while there. Admit it. You were
fooled. The endless rains had finally ended. The fog kept a polite
distance. Stewart was cruising. In this naturally unruly city, on
this inherently rambunctious course, in this purposely confounding
event, there was a perceptible lull.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Sunday, and out went stability. Janzen continued the
hoax for a while, bogeying the second and third holes, playing
possum golf.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 5, he hit into a tree, lost his ball in the leaves. He
seemed truly a goner. But just as he was marching back to the tee,
ready to take a penalty shot, the wind kicked up, a little San
Francisco treat. The ball fell from the tree, and the game was on
at last.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five, when his ball fell out of the tree, you could see
his confidence,'' said Steve Stricker, Janzen's playing partner.
``He walked with a purpose, it looked like.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who led Janzen by seven strokes early in the final
round, started to falter. Janzen just kept charging. He finished
the day at 68, 2 under par for the round, even for the tournament.
He watched on a television monitor as Stewart missed a birdie putt
at 18 for a tie, and he sobbed.
</P>
<P>
   He bent over and kept crying, letting go of the composure that
had carried him to this point. He had conquered the Open, and now
it was getting him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest emotion right now?'' Janzen said at his news
conference. ``I would say complete satisfaction that I went out and
played my absolute best and then won in the one championship I love
more than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   His comeback was the third-best in U.S. Open history, but it
wasn't all that shocking. On Friday, he foreshadowed the whole
thing. Almost every other contender complained that day about the
pin placement on 18 for that round. The pitch of the green sent
balls rolling all over the place, wildly and unpredictably.
</P>
<P>
   Only two notable contestants made a case for stoicism on 18 that
day. The first was Jack Nicklaus, who sent a 40-foot birdie putt
curving to the left of the hole. It broke in, sneaking toward the
opening like a burglar and then rested on the lip of the hole,
teasing the gallery before it took an obedient dive into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Until Janzen put on his charge, that putt was the moment of the
tournament. It let Nicklaus make the cut and hang around for two
more days. And it sent a message, from the 58-year-old legend to
all the whiners, pampered by the usual PGA Tour courses: This hole
can be beaten. If you can't do it, that's your problem.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a player gripes about the course, Nicklaus said, it
means that he is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart complained. Janzen didn't. He and Nicklaus were the big
holdouts at the pity party. Janzen shot a 66 that day, a par on 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are professional golfers,'' he said. ``We should be tested
to the fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said: ``(The Open) is a test of wills, to find out who
overcomes adversity the best and who has the most patience.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that seemed immediately prophetic. Janzen swooned a bit
on Saturday. By shooting a 73, he erased the chance of becoming
Stewart's playing partner on the last day, which could have been
reprise of their head-to-head battle at Baltusrol in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen won that Open, and four months later, his only child,
Connor, was born. It was a big year. Today, Janzen's custom-made
golf balls have ``93'' printed on them.
</P>
<P>
   As a previous winner, Janzen broke an Olympic custom for the
Open. He wasn't another Jack Fleck beating Ben Hogan (1955) or
Billy Casper surprising Arnold Palmer (1966) or Scott Simpson
defeating Tom Watson (1987).
</P>
<P>
   But if 1998 didn't follow the pattern of absolute
unpredictability, then that was the point. Once it had become a
pattern, the unpredictable was the expected. It had to go.
</P>
<P>
   In its place were other delights: the beaming face of amateur
Matt Kuchar, Nicklaus' breathtaking putt on 18 to make the cut
Friday, Casey Martin's cart and how it didn't ruin golf as we know
it. And then, finally, Janzen's tears.
</P>
<P>
   His co-winner didn't break down. The Olympic Club's Lake Course
can't cry. It can steal and cheat and crush, fold, spindle and
mutilate. But as an inanimate object, it can't express emotion. If
it could, though, it wouldn't have been bawling on Sunday. It would
have been gloating.
</P>
</TEXT>
