<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPER PRUNING REJUVENATES PLANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We purchased an older home, and there are two plants in the
front yard I would like to save. I believe they are called Japanese
jasmine. They produce small yellow blooms in spring and have a
fountain shape. One is pretty spindly, but it had the most blooms.
The other is quite large, but the growth is all on top, and the
center is full of bare wood. I would like to rejuvenate these, but
I am not sure how to go about it. _ R.P., Crosby, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A. You may have primrose jasmine, Jasminum mesnyi. This
evergreen shrub has arching branches and can reach 12 feet in
height and width. The yellow blooms appear around February. The
similar Florida jasmine, Jasminum floridum, flowers later and
longer and usually matures to 4 or 5 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Cut a third of the oldest wood to the ground to make way for new
shoots and encourage denser growth. It's best to prune after
flowering. New growth will then mature over summer and fall and
produce blooms next year.
</P>
<P>
   These plants prefer sun or partial sun and some moisture. Soak
the soil around the roots once each week during this hot, dry
period. It's a good idea to fertilize early in the spring, but if
your plants have not been fertilized in some time, an application
now of a balanced fertilizer, watered in well, will replenish
nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a beautiful poodle tree about 5 years old. The cats
are using it for a scratching post. I am afraid they will kill the
plant. Can you recommend anything to discourage the cats? _ O.W.,
Houston
</P>
<P>
   A. One old-time ``remedy'' is to place cotton balls saturated in
lemon oil furniture polish or dampened with ammonia at the base of
the plant you're hoping to protect. Or try mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise you may have to resort to a physical barrier _ pine
cones or some of the decorative wire edging offered at some garden
centers and through catalogs. The edging comes in varying lengths,
and you simply install it by pushing it into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a healthy hibiscus that produces approximately two
blooms each day, but for every bud that opens, about 15 fall off.
Can you tell me what causes this and what might cure it?
</P>
<P>
   I have two 5-foot oleanders planted nearly a year ago and then
moved in January. The plants have beautiful blooms and put on new
growth, but the leaves have brown spots, turn yellow and fall off.
_ T.J., Richmond, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. Bud drop is not uncommon. This physiological problem is worse
in some seasons, sometimes when it is hot, and it affects some
varieties more often and more severely than others. Too much water
and fertilizer _ or not enough of either _ can cause bud drop. So
can too much nitrogen. If you are practicing good culture, I'm
guessing the culprit is the heat. You might want to look for a
variety that better holds its blooms in summer.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if your oleanders are in an extended state of
transplant shock. The drought we're experiencing can slow oleander
growth and blooms, but since yours have been growing and flowering,
make sure the soil drains well and that you are not overwatering
them. Too much moisture can encourage fungal leaf spots and cause
yellowing and leaf drop.
</P>
<P>
   Established oleanders need 1 to 2 inches of water a week.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Could you repeat the recipe for hummingbird feeder syrup? _ A
reader
</P>
<P>
   A. Use one part sugar to four parts water.
</P>
<P>
   Do not substitute honey or artificial sweeteners. The former has
been implicated in fungal diseases; the latter has no nutritional
value.
</P>
<P>
   Boil the water first to inhibit the growth of bacteria and
fungi. Let the solution cool before filling the feeder. You can
store any excess in the refrigerator for up to a week.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to add red food coloring. Most commercial
feeders have red containers or accents.
</P>
<P>
   Hang the feeder out of the reach of cats and away from
reflective windows.
</P>
<P>
   Clean and rinse the feeder thoroughly at least twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   Once you start, do not stop feeding as long as birds are
present.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF COLUMN
</P>
