<HEADER>
A0780 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVISION-BIBLE-NYTSF &LR;      06-22 1764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVISION-BIBLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONIST SCHOLARS SEEK TO ALTER BIBLICAL TEXTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By NEIL ALTMAN  
 c.1998 NEIL ALTMAN  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   In the near future, buying a Bible as a wedding or confirmation
gift or for one's own personal study may involve more than choosing
which version or edition is the best translation of the original
Hebrew and Greek.
</P>
<P>
   If some scholars in the field of biblical criticism have their
way, the best-selling book of all time may undergo some radical
changes and additions.
</P>
<P>
   Revisionists are also toying with the idea of adding the Temple
Scroll, one of the Dead Sea Scrolls, to the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   German scholar Hartmut Stegemann, along with others, regards the
Temple Scroll as a sixth book of Moses. However, this proposed
addition to the Pentateuch -- the five books of Moses -- does not
contain, as Stegemann admits, subjects basic to the Judaism of the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Hershel Shanks, in ``Understanding the Dead Sea Scrolls,'' tells
us that the Temple Scroll ``contains many other laws as well as
descriptions of religious festivals not mentioned in the Bible or
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanks also tells us, ``The scroll contains detailed plans for
the building of the Lord's temple; hence its name, the Temple
Scroll.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can this scroll speak of elaborate plans for the
construction of the Temple, when in the time of the scrolls'
writing -- supposedly from 300 BC to 50 AD -- the temple was still
standing?
</P>
<P>
   Such anomalies raise serious questions about the dating and
purported Jewish authorship of the Temple Scroll. Yet those who
endorse the authenticity of the Temple Scroll and apocryphal texts
found among the Dead Sea Scrolls could bring unprecedented changes
to the canon of Scripture, 66 books of the Bible, traditionally
held to have been divinely inspired.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1996 book ``Secrets of the Dead Sea Scrolls,'' Randall
Price writes, ``The Scrolls ... imply that the list of books which
were accepted as part of the Bible at Qumran apparently differed
from ... the official canon of the Hebrew Bible ... It is also
possible ... that such works as the Temple Scroll were...
canonical.''
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Jewish and Christian position, however, is that the
Old Testament canon was completed by 400 BC, long before the
existence of the Dead Sea Scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. News &AMP; World Report, ``...about 70 liberal
scholars who since 1985 have been examining the historicity of the
Gospels will likely recommend that at least some of the 27 books
(of the New Testament) be jettisoned and that other ancient texts
be added... Behind the move... is the modern discovery of
...documents, such as the Dead Sea Scrolls....''
</P>
<P>
   Since that 1993 article, the pseudo-gospel of Thomas has been
added to the four Gospels in some new Biblical translations. This
fifth gospel corrupts the New Testament canon established by the
early church.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   At stake in all of this is the credibility of the Bible. There
is today a concerted effort to alter the Holy Scriptures. Yet it is
the consistency with which the Bible has been handed down to each
generation that has established its validity.
</P>
<P>
   Judaism has always regarded the Torah as inviolable.
Torah-making was not just a scribal art but a sacred profession.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``scribe'' in Hebrew means counter, for he had to count
how many words and letters there were to the center point of the
five books of Moses, and from there to the end, to ensure no
errors. He had to follow precise rituals, such as declaring that he
was writing the Torah ``in the name of its sanctity.''
</P>
<P>
   If the scribe made an error in writing the name of God, he had
to put that parchment away and start anew. And no word could be
written from memory. There were many other checks that were used in
copying the Old Testament books to insure preservation of the
sacred words of God.
</P>
<P>
   First-century Jewish historian Josephus wrote: ``We have given
practical proof of our reverence for our scriptures. For, although
such long ages have now passed, no one has ventured to add, or to
remove, or to alter a syllable; and it is an instinct with every
Jew, from the day of his birth, to regard them as decrees of God,
to abide by them, and if need be, cheerfully to die for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One can go anywhere in the world today and find the exact same
Biblical texts among all Jewish communities.
</P>
<P>
   The writers of the New Testament also were Jews. Paul, in Romans
3:1-2, wrote the following: ``What advantage then hath the Jew?...
Much every way: chiefly, because that unto them were committed the
oracles of God.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand the great effort throughout history to preserve
the original texts of the Old and New Testaments, we have only to
read what gentile translators of the King James version of the
Bible wrote to the English monarch in 1611.
</P>
<P>
   They note it was the great labor ``out of the Original Sacred
Tongues... [that] there should be one more exact Translation of the
Holy Scriptures into the English Tongue... ``
</P>
<P>
   The King James version is considered by scholars to be the most
accurate and theologically correct translation of the New Testament
written in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts now to change not only the canon of the traditional
Bible, but existing passages in the Bible as well, are already
under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Revised Standard Version adds a significant passage to
1 Samuel 10:27 from the text of the Qumran Samuel scroll,''
according to Dr. David Scholer, division chairman of Biblical
studies at Fuller Theological Seminary in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a paragraph from the book of Judges, Chapter
6, may be deleted because of the Qumran text.
</P>
<P>
   And in the New Testament, Luke's recording of the annunciation
-- the words spoken by the angel to the shepherds regarding the
birth of the Messiah -- is now being changed in texts coming from
the Jesus Seminar Group.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve of 1996 and Easter 1997, two of the most sacred
days on the Christian calendar, ``The News Hour with Jim Lehrer''
on PBS presented, in a positive light, the Jesus Seminar's
debunking of the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   During Easter week this year, PBS (America's Public Broadcasting
System) presented revisionists scoffing at the New Testament in a
four-day Frontline series, ``From Jesus to Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By presenting only modern critical scholars whose reductionist
ways are as spiritually arid as the hills of Judea, the producers
have given traditional believers a rather discombobulating picture
(of the New Testament),'' said Jim Remsen, the Philadelphia
Inquirer's religion editor.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard professor Allan D. Callahan, one of Frontline's
on-camera sources, said the series gave the false impression that
there is a scholarly consensus on the slant the program took on the
New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   Remsen said the absence of evangelical Christians and their line
of scholarship was glaring.
</P>
<P>
   In the chaos of scholarly errors, such as the assertion that
Jesus was born in Galilee, not Bethlehem, the positive aspect of
the series is that it presented a Jewish Jesus who ``was born,
lived, died, taught as a Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   And His teachings were represented as a Jewish movement with a
universal message of salvation through ``a Jewish Messiah come to
save all mankind -- Jew and Gentile alike....''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Engle, editor of religious books at Baker Book House,
distributor of the Cambridge Bible, states, ``If you don't accept
the Bible as the inspired, inerrant Word of God, it can easily
color how you look at the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning the canon, Engle asks, ``Do you throw out all that
ancient rabbis, the church fathers, the Reformers (Calvin, Luther,
Zwingli, etc.) have established?
</P>
<P>
   ``The book of Revelation warns against such a thing and
establishes the principle of not adding to or subtracting from the
Word of God. Therefore, the canon is not something one adds to or
subtracts from in each generation.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring in Philadelphia, The Jewish Exponent's Inside
Magazine carried an article entitled ``Debunking 'Ancient Israel'''
that was originally published in the Chronicle of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the biblical revisionists, writer Christopher Shea
stated that ``... for the past half-century, scholars have steadily
chipped away at the Old Testament's credibility as a historical
document.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea's article exposes the fact that the revisionists would
undermine the very basis of Judaism, the nation of Israel and
Christianity by denying that David and Solomon ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, the scholars add two of ancient Israel's most
important kings to a roster of biblical figures they say never
lived that includes Abraham, Isaac and Jacob, the fathers of Jewry,
nation of Israel, and those of the Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The figure of King David is about as historical as King
Arthur,'' says Phillip R. Davies, a professor of religious studies
at Britain's University of Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and his allies in the revisionist camp seem to be winning
the war.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Shea writes, ``The fight has ramifications far beyond
the ranks of biblical scholars. David sits atop the genealogy of
Jesus in the Gospel of Matthew, so he is vital to Christian
theology.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's very existence is based upon the covenant that God made
with the three patriarchs and the promises to kings David and
Solomon, and without them there is no historical justification for
the state of Israel, Jewry or Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   William G. Devor, professor at the University of Arizona,
considered by some to be the dean of American archaeologists
working in the Middle East, is quoted in Shea's article as saying,
``I think it's important to unmask (the revisionists).
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not biblical scholars. They are certainly not
archaeologists .... They are ideological: They are social engineers
manipulating the biblical texts for their own goals.''
</P>
<P>
   (Neil Altman is a Philadelphia-based writer who specializes in
the Dead Sea Scrolls.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
