<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-X-FILES-HNS &LR;      06-22 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-X-FILES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `X-FILES' THE MOVIE, NO GREAT ANSWERS TO GNAWING QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movies _ particularly summer blockbusters _ come and go. But
good television shows hang around for years.
</P>
<P>
   What has gone unreported in the hype for ``The X-Files'' feature
film is that a great television show is now forever altered.
</P>
<P>
   Can fans of the television show live with the fact that basic
tenets will change when ``The X-Files'' returns in the fall? If so,
by all means cough up the eight dollars, because there's no way you
can start watching the new season without having seen the movie.
Call it the pay-off for years of patience seeking the truth that's
out there _ or call it a devious marketing ploy.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of ``The X-Files'' movie is to show where an
investigation into a massive bombing at a Dallas office building
truly leads. Hint: Out there.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's weird web will split the audience into two
distinct categories _ fans of the show and people with little or no
knowledge of the characters and what they've been up to for five
years. Although Chris Carter, who created the series and the film,
says that non-fans will have no problem finding an entree, it's
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   What about the show's metaphorically rich Cigarette Smoking Man,
who appears unexplained in the movie, lingering around all the
chaos, puffing longingly and saying almost nothing? If you've never
seen the show, you'll think you're watching a pretentious French
art film.
</P>
<P>
   And the other ambiguous characters _ like The Lone Gunmen, The
Syndicate, etc. _ will stand out as odd narrative additions to the
uninitiated. If you're a non-fan, then, here's a movie with a
wonderfully confusing plot, a little bit of action and two
mismatched, stone-faced stars (David Duchovny as Mulder, Gillian
Anderson as Scully) whose emotional relationship seems
unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   If you walk in cold to ``The X-Files,'' you'll see a classic
example of an anti-blockbuster. Most ``Godzilla'' types have zero
plot, lame dialogue and special effects that scare God. In this
movie, the special effects are nice but not eye-popping and the
plot is a Byzantine conspiracy that leaves your imagination with
painful stretch marks.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't ``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, ``The X-Files'' movie is geared to fans of the
show. It has a built-in audience of more than 20 million who should
give it a healthy box-office boost. But the danger in a television
show leaping onto the big screen is that viewers now have
heightened expectations. In this case, they'll expect answers to
questions that have been raised and allowed to fester for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, in the film, Carter delivers the goods to diehard
fans. The ``mythology'' episodes, as Carter and fans call them _
with all the obligatory red-herrings and blarney _ for the most
part bear fruit in the movie. But many of the most pertinent
questions _ what happened to Mulder's abducted sister, is the
Cigarette Smoking Man really Mulder's dad, are Mulder and Scully
actually in love with each other _ are given Carter's patented
sleight-of-hand treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' movie does answer one question raised in the
show for an hour a week, five years running: Is the government
conspiring to keep the truth about extraterrestrials from the
public? You bet. That's certainly been the implication from the
start, and since paranoia fuels the show, it's no great leap on the
big screen.
</P>
<P>
   But the ramifications are immense. Because ``The X-Files'' as a
television show succeeded mainly because of the juxtaposition of
Mulder's little-green-men beliefs and Scully's stick-to-science
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Now she knows.
</P>
<P>
   But the ambiguity of Mulder's visions and encounters week to
week was the great sustaining factor of the television show. Did he
really see what he thinks he saw? Was that a monster, an alien, a
freak of nature _ or just his imagination and a trick of light?
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Mulder and Scully have seen the future and it's a
giant leap for each of them to comprehend. Now, when ``The
X-Files'' returns _ probably in November after Fox airs the World
Series _ their relationship will have completely changed.
</P>
<P>
   Scully, the scientist, can't use a microscope and an autopsy to
prop up her stoicism. Also, Mulder may have to face his true
feelings about Scully. And the two have learned enough about the
darker forces _ particularly The Syndicate and alien colonization _
that they can't simply go back to the everyday minutia without
losing credibility with viewers. Perhaps a little truth is a good
thing and whatever direction it leads the characters in will be
fresh and appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   But how does it stack up as a movie? ``X-Files'' fans will love
it but are unlikely to do cartwheels in the lobby, and non-fans may
be left wondering what the fuss was all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
