<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT SO FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans were shamelessly and
irresponsibly grandstanding last week when they voted to eliminate
the federal income tax system in one fell swoop, without so much as
suggesting how to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Do they really believe the government can function, armies can
be fed, highways can be paved, borders can be patrolled and their
own salaries provided if nobody pays any federal taxes?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. The country does not run on fumes. It runs on
money, which must be raised somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Do they really believe voters will take such political fakery
seriously? Only if their heads are in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans once thought voters would cheer if the
government shut down, but when they actually tried that, it turned
out people missed their familiar public services and wanted those
``horrible'' bureaucrats back. Now the same legislative loonies
think voters so loathe the Internal Revenue Service that they want
it abolished altogether, regardless of the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are out on this limb virtually alone. Passage
was largely along party lines, with only 15 Democrats supporting
it. The GOP intends to take the campaign credit for it and, by
golly, it ought to be made to take the blame for such silliness,
too.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans made only a minor gesture toward sanity,
directing Congress to come up with an alternative system before
their edict to wipe out the 350 million words of the present tax
code goes into effect on New Year's Day 2003. That instruction has
no enforcement provision and includes no specific recommendations
for reaching its goal.
</P>
<P>
   Our thoughtful GOP legislators offered not a clue as to how the
tax code is to be boiled down to practically nothing. These are the
same people, remember, who have been ignoring the dream of
simplifying things for years by merrily offering up new tax breaks
that further complicate the code, from ending the so-called
marriage penalty to offering vouchers for private schools.
</P>
<P>
   It is politically easy to denounce federal taxes, particularly
after the tales of IRS abuse brought out by congressional hearings
last fall and this spring. But it is almost impossible to reach a
consensus on the way to simplify, reduce or rearrange those taxes
in ways that are fair and realistic and that still raise enough
revenue to run the government.
</P>
<P>
   If it were easy, Congress would have done it by now. Even
Democrats can figure out the political charm of bashing the IRS. No
politician wants to be condemned as defending the dreaded tax
collector.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax code has become complicated in part because members
of Congress themselves have insisted on inserting an ever-expanding
array of loopholes for favored causes. A lot of those causes are
socially worthwhile and beloved by the middle class, such as the
deductions for home mortgage interest and charitable donations.
Other tax breaks reflect the eternal political payback system,
doing favors for constituents and rewarding industries and special
interests that are big campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden agenda of conservative House Republicans may be to
force Congress to act under deadline to shift to a flat-tax system,
under which rich and poor alike would pay at the same rate and all
special deductions would die. Many experts point out that this
would mostly benefit the wealthy, disproportionately cutting their
overall taxes compared with those of folks with lesser incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The flat-tax idea is popular with conservatives, who would just
as soon cut off resources in order to starve federal services and
shrink the size of government anyway. But it is a radical, risky
departure from our traditional graduated-tax system and a flyer
into the unknown that could destabilize the economy and ruin the
present national prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   If the flat-tax base is set too low, the federal treasury will
dry up. If it is set too high, the middle class will find itself
with increased taxes and no deductions as an offset.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Congress is likely to agree on a way to simplify
the tax code within the five-year deadline is a pipe dream. In the
meantime, as President Clinton and other opponents point out,
neither individuals nor corporations will have a stable tax
framework on which to base investments and other economic
decisions. Nobody will know what to expect or what to do.
</P>
<P>
   House GOP leaders know perfectly well that the Senate is thus
far cool to the IRS-elimination idea, preferring more temperate and
reasoned reforms. The Senate, as is often the case, is likely to
sit on this particular folly and rescue the House from itself.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the House cynically left a loophole through which
it could delay the close-down of the system if indeed Congress
doesn't come up with an alternative in time. That concession in
itself is an acknowledgement that the lawmakers are aware that this
whole exercise is a phony meant for campaign talk, not the
legislative walk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
