<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JACKSON-MCRAE-2ND     06-22 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-MCRAE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Attn.: Fla.)  
 BOSTON: ... that consistency.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of when or if he is drafted, Jackson can rest assured
that he is a known talent throughout the NBA. McRae is working on
becoming the same. Enrolling at UTEP (which will leave the Western
Athletic Conference after next season), McRae will get an
opportunity to play twice against heralded point guard Andre Miller
of perennial WAC power Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention matchups against league foe Fresno State and
guard Chris Herren of Fall River, who was a teammate of McRae's on
the BABC squads. ``Going against two of the best guards in college
basketball, that gives me a chance to show the world I can play,''
McRae said, ``and if I can play well maybe that will open a few
scouts' eyes and maybe they will come look at me.''
</P>
<P>
   That could help distance him from allegations in Utah that
almost cost him any chance at fulfilling his dream.
</P>
<P>
   McRae was arrested April 19, 1996, on two charges of forcible
sexual abuse, one charge of burglary (both second-degree felonies)
and one charge of aggravated kidnapping (a first-degree felony).
</P>
<P>
   In the attempted burglary/forcible sexual abuse charge, a
19-year-old student at Dixie accused McRae of entering her room
uninvited, climbing into her bed, and fondling her before being
asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In the aggravated kidnapping/forcible sexual abuse charge, a
17-year-old high school student accused McRae of pulling her into a
room, detaining her, and fondling her before she demanded to be let
out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   McRae was held on $75,000 bail; bail was placed so high because
he once failed to appear in a Boston court on a cocaine possession
charge. He spent 13 days in a Utah jail and was able to post bail
after it was reduced to $10,000. McRae said his aunt put her home
up as collateral to bail him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really difficult, being so far from home, not close to
family and friends. That was the toughest thing about it,'' said
McRae. ``All along I knew one day, even if it wasn't the next day,
that the problem would resolve itself. I just prayed to God every
night one day it would work out and it did.''
</P>
<P>
   When the case against McRae went to trial Sept. 26, 1996, it
took several unusual twists. Defense attorney Mitchell Barker
requested to have Deputy Washington County Attorney Marlynn B.
Lema, the prosecutor, disqualified after he discovered he needed to
call her as a witness for the defense. Lema was asked to testify
about an April 19 taped interview she conducted with McRae during
his time in jail.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Lema said she told McRae she would
do everything possible to investigate the incident. The assertion
was not recorded on the interview tapes. Barker also asserted that
witnesses McRae said could clear him were not interviewed by the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Judge James Shumate to declare a mistrial and
disqualify prosecution from the case. The case was set for trial
twice afterward and canceled both times, then turned over to the
Attorney General's office.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that McRae plea-bargained to two counts of gross
lewdness (a first-degree misdemeanor). He was given 18 months
probation and sentenced to time served, and required to undergo
psycho-sexual counseling, to write a letter of apology to the
plaintiffs, and to send monthly letters to the court. Assistant
Utah Attorney General Paul Graf said both sides were satisfied with
the outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McRae still insists the incidents in question never took
place, and added he only pleaded to misdemeanor charges because he
was no longer able to afford legal counsel (transcripts show
Mitchell had withdrawn from representing him for that reason).
</P>
<P>
   McRae asserts the charges were levied after he overheard his
accusers use racial slurs in conversations about athletes at the
school they were secretly having relations with.
</P>
<P>
   He said he informed the players about what was said, the players
confronted the women, and the women concocted the allegations
against McRae to get back at him. ``When they were in court, they
acted as if they never met each other, and they were best
friends,'' McRae said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened my eyes up as far as the friends I choose to keep my
company in. And it helped me grow up a lot and see the world for
what it is. It taught me that one minute everything can be going
nice and fine and rosy, and the next minute the whole world can be
caving in.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae said he hasn't undergone a court-ordered psychological
evaluation because he is still awaiting paperwork from the courts,
but he said he doesn't think it is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing me stupid for counseling. Counseling for
what?'' he said. ``I don't even need any counseling. If this had
been anywhere else, it wouldn't have even gone to court. People
think I don't want to talk about it. But I'm willing to go on the
radio, or TV, because nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   When told about McRae's assertion that his accusers fabricated
both incidents looking for revenge, Graf said, ``This is new
information to me. The factual basis, as I understood it to be, was
him being in the bedroom and on the bed of one of the girls and
taking the other girl in the apartment and barring the door, not
letting her out. I have not heard the allegation you have made to
me, that this is a racially motivated type of situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had excellent legal counsel, and I think he would have
brought it to me. That was not mentioned.'' Graf said he would
investigate whether legal paperwork has been sent to McRae so he
could comply with the terms of the plea agreement. ``It's his
responsibility, but I will see if there is something I need to do
and take care of it,'' Graf said.
</P>
<P>
   According to McRae, the cocaine charge is behind him. ``That was
a case of being at the wrong place at the wrong time,'' he said,
adding that police broke up a party he was at and when one of those
present dropped some cocaine, everyone was taken in and charged.
</P>
<P>
   Tallahassee College coach Mike Gillespie said there were some
concerns about McRae's troubles at Dixie College and that the
school, which began its basketball program seven years ago,
conducted its own investigation before admitting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to a lot of people, and everyone said Eggie probably
had not been guilty and a lot of the things that were being said
about him had not been done,'' Gillespie said. ``I think he was
ready to get back into school. He had been treated unfairly at
Dixie. He's a young man who needed an opportunity to prove he's a
good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, McRae averaged 13 points and 9 assists a game, and
guided a 25-6 team that was ranked No. 1 among junior colleges for
most of the season before being upset in the state tournament.
``He's still a tremendous penetrator with the ball, he has great
upper body strength, and is a great leader,'' said Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, McRae said had it not been for his legal troubles,
he probably would not have taken his college studies as seriously.
He says he now is on track to receive an associate's degree from
Tallahassee College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I have any regrets, although I wish that in high
school maybe I could have studied a little harder,'' said McRae.
``Maybe then I would have passed the SAT. But maybe this is a
blessing in disguise. My mom always told me if you take the harder
route good things happen. This is not the path I would have took
earlier, but I'm making the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and McRae spent Memorial Day weekend in sultry South
Florida, visiting friends who had moved there from the Boston area.
They have spent much of the offseason in summer school while
preparing to venture along The Path alone again. Jackson said the
pair's friendship will help them both along the way, no matter how
far they drift apart.
</P>
<P>
   McRae doesn't sound so certain. ``It's going to be hard,'' he
said. ``If I ever needed anything here, I could call on Ran and he
could call on me. I'm backing his decision, and I know we can talk
on the phone, but it's not the same as face to face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
