<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-MCRAE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON, MCRAE STILL DREAMING OF NBA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ At this point, there is no getting off The Path. They
dreamed of becoming NBA superstars, and the visions were replayed
over and over, each time becoming more colorful and captivating and
seemingly closer to reality.
</P>
<P>
   They now venture toward the dream the way small boats in choppy
waters sail toward a distant glimmer at shore, braving obstacles,
not knowing if they will ever make it, too determined to see a
positive result to cease trying.
</P>
<P>
   Randell Jackson didn't embark on The Path in earnest until his
talents had developed to the point where Basketball America rated
him the 25th-best player in the country as he entered his senior
year at Boston's Madison Park High School, and scholarship offers
came by the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, he didn't even like basketball, and the only
reason he began playing was that he was a flagpole, who would grow
to 6 feet 11 inches, when most other kids in his Mission Hill
neighborhood were yardsticks, and folks steered him toward the
court. But before that senior year he left Madison Park and
followed The Path to the Winchendon School in western
Massachusetts, in part because it had a core curriculum that would
virtually ensure his reaching NCAA eligibility requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to Florida State, where he often struggled on the
court, and was much maligned by the local media. The criticism
continued this spring following his junior season at Tallahassee,
when he placed his name in the NBA Draft pool but vowed to return
to school if he wasn't projected as one of the first 15 picks.
</P>
<P>
   Winford ``Eggie'' McRae came aboard The Path when he was 6,
shortly after his first Shoot-Straight camp at the Shelburne Center
in Roxbury. The gritty kid from Roxbury was so enamored with the
sport that he proclaimed himself willing to play in the CBA or
overseas if he didn't reach the ultimate goal of the NBA _ as long
as he was playing professionally some day.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of determination comes in handy when you are the
Globe's 1992 Division 3 Player of the Year as a junior point guard,
then your school, Mission High, closes. Or when your career has a
brief hiatus because of academic troubles, then resumes at East
Boston but never reaches those heights.
</P>
<P>
   Or when you follow The Path to Redemption Christian Academy in
upstate New York to work on your grades before heading to Dixie
(Junior) College in St. George, Utah, with hopes of transferring to
Nevada-Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Or when you find yourself behind bars in St. George, facing two
counts of forcible sexual abuse and other charges from two separate
incidents he says never took place. At one point, McRae thought he
had been derailed from The Path for good.
</P>
<P>
   But the case against him was declared a mistrial, and McRae
searched high and low for a reputable, winning program to which to
transfer. Tallahassee College sparked his curiosity, and he called
Jackson, who told him there was an opening on the team since
Tallahassee's point guard was transferring to Florida State. So
McRae transferred to Tallahassee College, and he and Jackson became
roommates who have helped each other along the journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever one of us needs help on our game, we take our bags,
go over to the gym, and shoot,'' said Jackson, who first played
with McRae in a 13-and-under all-star game at the Mission Hill
Recreation Center. The two won several national AAU titles together
while playing for Leo Papile's Boston Amateur Basketball Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living with Eggie has been encouraging because we're from the
same area,'' said Jackson. ``You don't have to worry about somebody
stabbing you in the back. I have friends there, but I have one
friend I know I can depend on. And vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, the two will go their separate ways. McRae is
enrolling at the University of Texas-El Paso in August with two
years of playing eligibility remaining. Jackson signed with an
agent following the NBA predraft camp in Chicago, voiding his
option to return to Florida State for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me while at the predraft camp and told me he was
coming out regardless,'' said McRae. ``I told him that he knows
it's up to him. Nobody can live his life for him, and that I was
behind him no matter what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I feel more and more if he makes it maybe I can go
and play with those guys. Randell's a person I grew up playing
with. Someone I know making it gives me incentive to push harder.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was no real reason to limit his options, but after the
predraft camp, Randell Jackson decided he was finished with college
basketball, and while he said he will obtain his degree someday,
right now he says he wants only one egg in his basket. He signed
with No Limit Sports Management, the athletics arm of a group whose
clients include rap artist Snoop Doggy Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said to myself, `Whatever happens happens.' I've been
hearing that I will go in either the late first round or early
second round,'' said Jackson, who said he had a lot of ups and
downs at Florida State and felt stagnated while playing under
first-year coach Steve Robinson this past season. ``Whatever the
situation will be, I'm hoping for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jackson posted his best collegiate campaign last season,
averaging 12.7 points and 5.5 rebounds, shooting 49 percent from
the floor, with 37 blocked shots and 26 steals, in leading the
Seminoles to the second round of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore, Jackson showed some promise before suffering a
hip injury against Georgia Tech Feb. 9. He missed the following
game against Maryland and played sparingly against Duke the next
game. By the season finale against Wake Forest, he had scored just
35 points on 13-for-32 shooting in six games after the injury.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Demon Deacons and their senior center Tim
Duncan, he scored 16 points and grabbed 12 rebounds. He went on to
lead the Seminoles to four National Invitation Tournament wins,
averaging 11 points and 11 boards a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For his size, he's a most intriguing player,'' said former
Florida State coach Pat Kennedy, who is now at DePaul. ``He's very
good in transition and he became a much better shooter. He has
worked on his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it appears Jackson will likely be chosen in the second
round of Wednesday's NBA draft. ``I think that he is a talent, he's
long and very athletic,'' said Celtics general manager Chris
Wallace. ``The question with Randell is what position does he play?
Who is he in terms of the NBA game?''
</P>
<P>
   There are some Florida State followers who felt Jackson could
have done much to answer those questions had he come back for a
senior season, that he would have been a dominant player in the
Atlantic Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Local columnists have taken it a step further. Tallahassee
Democrat writer John Nogowski referred to Jackson as a
``now-you-see-me, now-you-don't forward'' and added that Jackson is
no more ready for the NBA ``than Michael Jordan is to quit the NBA
and become president of the Hair Club For Men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how they are at Florida State. When I say the ups and
downs I've had, that's what I mean, the media,'' said Jackson.
``For me I'm always going to be focused and do what I have to do. I
have no trouble keeping my head on straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, the critics down there badmouth you. I don't
get to the point where I blow up and get down on myself, but I know
I have a family to support, and that's my ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing for a better life for his family is one of the reasons
Jackson is on The Path. He said he had planned to forgo his senior
season before enrolling at Florida State. ``It wasn't something
written in stone. I just said that I would try to leave in three
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first two seasons weren't as good. I could have gotten more
out of them. My junior year I was more consistent. Now it's about
keeping that consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
