<HEADER>
A0845 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-BOOKS-HNS &LR;      06-22 3182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL BOOKS FOR A HOT SUMMER DAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's getting hotter outside. Forget mowing the lawn. Forget
softball. Confine your exertions to the imagination: What could be
cooler than a hot book on a summer day?
</P>
<P>
   Whether you go in for thrillers, romances, literary fare,
biographies, current events or good mysteries, you can't walk
through a bookstore without tripping over something of interest.
It's a good summer for books.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainments abound. Among the proven practitioners of
commercial fiction with new releases are Anne Rivers Siddons, who
journeys to the ``Low Country'' (HarperCollins, $24); and Nora
Roberts, who tells ``Genuine Lies'' (Bantam, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Olivia Goldsmith (``The First Wives Club'') works the
``Switcheroo'' (HarperCollins, $24), in which a look-alike wife and
mistress change places. With ``Caprice and Rondo'' (Knopf, $27.50),
historical novelist Dorothy Dunnett continues her ``House of
Niccolo'' sequence about the life and times of 15th-century
merchant-adventurer Nicholas de Fleury.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, publishers of thrillers and crime novels have loaded
up the shelves with these summer favorites. Tom Clancy fans will
have to wait until early August for his latest novel (Putnam,
$27.95), in which ex-Navy SEAL John Clark of ``Without Remorse''
reprises his role as savior of all things decent and right.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving earlier are Jeffrey Archer's ``Eleventh Commandment''
(HarperCollins, $26), in which CIA operative Connor Fitzgerald
discovers his boss is very bad news.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most eagerly awaited mysteries of the season has been
James Lee Burke's just-released ``Sunset Limited'' (Hyperion, $24).
This is the 17th book for the Louisiana novelist, who won the Edgar
for best novel for last year's ``Cimarron Rose.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Sunset Limited,'' Burke brings back Cajun detective Dave
Robicheaux in a tale that involves a 40-year-old murder by
crucifixion and the dead man's photojournalist daughter, who won't
leave the past alone.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the most popular and prolific female mystery writers
have new books. Sue Grafton has made it to the downhill side of the
alphabet with ``N'' Is for Noose`` (Henry Holt, $25). Patricia
Cornwell has chief medical examiner Kay Scarpetta battling a baddie
who uses fire to mask his misdeeds in ``Point of Origin'' (Putnam,
$25.95).
</P>
<P>
   And August will bring Faye Kellerman's ``Moon Music'' (Morrow,
$25.50). Not one of her Peter Decker/Rina Lazarus mysteries, this
one features a team of Las Vegas police detectives trying to solve
the mutilation murder of a Vegas showgirl.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1979 best seller ``Dress Gray,'' Lucian K. Truscott IV
had West Point cadet Ry Slaight investigating the murder of a gay
fellow student. Now a middle-aged lieutenant general, Slaight is
superintendent of his alma mater when a female cadet drops dead on
the parade ground. Adultery, sexual harassment and right-wing
conspiracies contribute to the murk in ``Full Dress Gray'' (Morrow,
$25).
</P>
<P>
   Two debuts deserve special mention. In Jonathan Robb's ``The
Overseer'' (Crown, $25), a 16th-century Swiss monk's master plan
for world domination survives but falls into the wrong hands.
Suddenly air-traffic control screens go blank, bombs explode in the
National Gallery, the grain market teeters on the verge of
collapse. Will the cabal's mastermind, known as the Overseer,
destroy society as we know it and forge a new world order?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother addressing fan mail to ``Jane Harvard,'' the name
on the spine of the second debut, ``The Student Body'' (Villard,
$23). JH is the nom de plume of four Harvard University friends who
cooked up this mystery, inspired by the 1986 Brown University
prostitution scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard Crimson's brightest reporter, Toni Isaacs, gets a
tip: Harvard students are turning tricks for money. She digs for
the dirt, aided by her Latina roommate, Chelo; Van, who is
Vietnamese and bisexual; and the monied Cabot Winthrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this multicultural Mod Squad for the '90s discovers will
jeopardize much more than their academic futures,'' blurbles the
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Philip Kerr (Esau) has a new thriller, ``A Five Year
Plan'' (Henry Holt, $23), which his publisher touts as more
mainstream than his previous books; Brad Meltzer, whose debut,
``The Tenth Justice,'' was a best-selling legal thriller, returns
with ``Dead Even'' (Weisbach/Morrow, $25); and in ``L.A. Noir''
($25), Mysterious Press has reissued in one volume three of James
Ellroy's early novels featuring hard-boiled police detective Lloyd
Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lit lite'' is the dismissive term sometimes applied to summer
fiction. Publishers, the idea goes, save their literary offerings
for the fall and load the warm-weather lists with bonbons.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, as every year, readers wanting more than pure
escapism have plenty of choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cities of the Plain'' (Knopf, $24) is the final volume of
Cormac McCarthy's Border Trilogy. John Grady Cole and Billy Parham,
familiar from ``All the Pretty Horses'' and ``The Crossing''
respectively, are the young cowboy-heroes of this tale. It's set in
the West Texas-Mexico border country and involves Cole's falling in
love with a Mexican prostitute, with predictably tragic results.
</P>
<P>
   The critical consensus seems to be that ``All the Pretty
Horses'' is the best of the three books. But here as elsewhere,
McCarthy fashions compelling characters and hypnotic prose.
</P>
<P>
   John Irving (``The World According to Garp,'' ``The Hotel New
Hampshire'') has roared to the top of best-seller lists with ``A
Widow for One Year'' (Random House, $26.95), a sprawling 542-page
novel full of sex, humor and violence. We meet the central
character, Ruth Cole, in 1958, when she is 4 years old. The
narrative picks her up again in 1990, when she is a novelist of
``international stature.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Price (``Clockers'') writes crime novels that manage to
be both harrowing and elegantly crafted, bearing a greater moral
and psychological weight than you find in typical specimens of the
genre. ``Freedomland'' (Broadway, $25), like ``Clockers,'' is set
in gritty urban New Jersey but hearkens to real-life events farther
south _ the notorious Susan Smith case in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The novel begins with a white woman bursting into a hospital
emergency room claiming that she's just been carjacked by a black
man and that her 4-year-old son was asleep in the back seat. Police
detective Lorenzo Council has his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Another stylish contribution to crime fiction is ``The Seville
Communion'' (Harcourt Brace, $24), the third novel by Spain's
Arturo Prez-Reverte. A computer hacker breaks through Vatican
security and messages the pope about plans to demolish an old
Seville church and about the suspicious deaths of two of the
church's defenders. The Vatican dispatches Father Lorenzo Quart to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Lamb and Jacquelyn Mitchard, whose first novels earned the
imprimatur of talk-show host Oprah Winfrey _ and thus sold millions
_ have new books.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's ``I Know This Much Is True'' (ReganBooks, $27.50) is an
897-page epic about identical twin brothers, one a paranoid
schizophrenic, the other torn between resentment and love for his
sibling. One early review praised it, saying ``thanks to
well-sustained dramatic tension, funky gallows humor and some
shocking surprises, this sinuous story of one family's dark secrets
and recurring patterns of behavior largely succeeds in its
ambitious reach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Midwesterner Mitchard turns to Texas for the setting of
``The Most Wanted'' (Viking, $24.95), which centers on a
14-year-old girl who corresponds with and then marries a prison
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Onetime Texan Rick Bass has been remarkably prolific in his
short writing career, producing a dozen well-received books of
fiction and nonfiction, but ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' (Houghton
Mifflin, $25) is his first full-length novel. Set in Montana, where
Bass makes his home, the story follows the lives of Old Dudley, an
aging Texas wildcatter who is drilling dry holes in Big Sky
country; his daughter; and two geologists who are employees of the
former and lovers of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Another first novel worth noting is ``Bombay Ice'' by Leslie
Forbes (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $23), in which a radio journalist
returns to her native India to investigate her sister's fear that
her husband, a famous Bombay film director, murdered his first
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the South's most engaging writers, Kaye Gibbons and
Bailey White, have novels this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a Year for Plums'' (Knopf, $22) is the first novel for
White, who is best-known for her National Public Radio commentaries
on the eccentricities of small-town Georgians. Darkly droll, the
novel plows similar ground.
</P>
<P>
   The life of a plantation owner's daughter is the stuff of ``On
the Occasion of My Last Afternoon'' (Putnam, $22.95) by Gibbons
(``Ellen Foster,'' ``Sights Unseen''). Born in 1842, Emma Garnet
has a pampered childhood. Although she gradually comes to
understand the brutality of slavery, she loyally serves the South
in a military hospital during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   One early review said Gibbons ``has gone back to that
still-smoldering conflict and imagined it from a wholly personal
and feminine perspective, concerned not with politics but with
blood and suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the blood and suffering of the Civil War seem
everywhere in fiction. While ``Cold Mountain'' continues to hang on
to a slot on the best-seller list, ``Jacob's Ladder'' by Donald
McCaig (Norton, $25.95) resembles ``a collaboration between Shelby
Foote and Margaret Mitchell,'' according to Publishers Weekly. The
novel follows the scion of a white slaveholding family and two of
its slaves through the course of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other literary offerings this summer: Joanna Trollope
(``The Rector's Wife,'' ``The Choir'') has another domestic novel,
``The Best of Friends'' (Viking, $23.95); Gloria Naylor, whose
``Women of Brewster Place'' was a big best seller in 1982, returns
with ``The Men of Brewster Place'' (Hyperion, $22.95); and Alison
Lurie (``The War Between the Tates, Foreign Affairs'') chooses a
Key West setting for her latest, ``The Last Resort'' (Henry Holt,
$22).
</P>
<P>
   Last month saw the publication of Robert Stone's ``Damascus
Gate'' (Houghton Mifflin, $26), which combines political intrigue,
religious fanaticism and the hallucinatory appeal of Jerusalem.
``Erudite eschatological noir'' is how one admiring fellow writer
described it.
</P>
<P>
   And weighing in at 1,281 pages is Norman Mailer's ``The Time of
Our Time'' (Random House, $39.50), which brings together essays,
journalism and fiction produced over the past half century.
</P>
<P>
   In compiling this book, Mailer didn't necessarily intend a
``best of'' volume. Rather, he says, ``I would like the book to
offer some hint at a social and cultural history.'' Thus he chooses
to organize the anthology by date of setting rather than date of
composition _ it opens with a 1966 essay about an Ernest Hemingway
boxing match in 1929. A few pages later comes a long excerpt from
``The Naked and the Dead,'' the 1948 World War II novel that put
Mailer on the literary map.
</P>
<P>
   All the classic Mailer is here, in excerpts: ``Armies of the
Night,'' `` Of a Fire on the Moon,'' ``The Executioner's Song,''
``Harlot's Ghost.'' Self-indulgent he can be, but Mailer writes
prose that bristles with intelligence and energy. ``The Time of Our
Time'' should serve to introduce this great American writer to a
new generation of readers.
</P>
<P>
   Turn from fiction to nonfiction, and you'll find equally varied
fare this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Biographies and memoirs are always popular. In ``A Pirate Looks
at Fifty'' (Random House, $24.95), the man from Margaritaville _
Jimmy Buffett _ chronicles a trip he took through the Caribbean and
South America to celebrate his 50th birthday. Along the way he
talks about how he got his start in music and his passion for
flying airplanes, a love that survived a crash near Nantucket
Island, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Equally fun and accessible is Malachy McCourt's ``A Monk
Swimming'' (Hyperion, $23.95), memoirs of the Irish-born
actor/reconteur whose older brother is Frank McCourt (``Angela's
Ashes'').
</P>
<P>
   The younger McCourt, who arrived in the United States in 1952
after an impoverished childhood, tells raucous tales of acting
gigs, parties and smuggling gold into India. Liberal doses of drink
seem to have accompanied every adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining but with somewhat more heft is humorist Roy Blount
Jr.'s ``Be Sweet: A Conditional Love Story'' (Knopf, $24). Known
for his 14 books and his comedy routines on Garrison Keillor's ``A
Prairie Home Companion,'' Blount here offers a sportive take on his
upbringing in Georgia and his relationship with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Light My Fire: My Life With the Doors'' (Putnam, $26.95),
keyboardist and band co-founder Ray Manzarek gives a close-up look
at the brilliant but self-destructive Jim Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Lorian Hemingway, Ernest's granddaughter, weaves together her
love of fishing and her battle against alcoholism in ``Walk on
Water: A Memoir'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23).
</P>
<P>
   But certainly the most notable memoir by an entertainment figure
this season remains Christopher Reeve's ``Still Me'' (Random House,
$25), the actor's candid, gutsy account of his life since a
horse-riding accident left him a quadriplegic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Cooper: American Hero'' by Jeffrey Meyers (Morrow, $26)
is a detailed and straightforward rendering of the actor's public
and private life. Meyers is a respected biographer whose subjects
have included Humphrey Bogart, Joseph Conrad and Robert Frost.
</P>
<P>
   An even more distinguished biographer turns her hand to a much
more eccentric subject in ``Suits Me: The Double Life of Billy
Tipton'' (Houghton Mifflin, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Diane Wood Middlebrook, whose books include the award-winning
``Anne Sexton: A Biography,'' tells the life story of the female
jazz musician who, from age 19 until she died at 74, lived as a man
(and ``married'' five women).
</P>
<P>
   Another gender-bending eccentric, Marion ``Joe'' Carstairs, is
the subject of ``The Queen of Whale Cay'' by Kate Summerscale
(Viking, $21.95). Carstairs, who died in 1993 at age 93, held the
record as the fastest woman speedboat racer in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Having inherited a Standard Oil fortune, the cross-dressing
Carstairs spent her money on female lovers, fast boats and cars,
and the Bahamian island that she ruled like a queen. She had an
affair with Marlene Dietrich, numbered the Duke and Duchess of
Windsor among her friends, and was obsessively devoted to a leather
doll she named Lord Tod Wadley.
</P>
<P>
   Carstairs' grandfather amassed his fortune as treasurer to one
of John D. Rockefeller's companies in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller's life is put under intense but fair-minded scrutiny
in Ron Chernow's superb ``Titan: The Life of John D. Rockefeller
Sr.'' (Random House, $30).
</P>
<P>
   Chernow, whose previous books include the National Book
Award-winning ``House of Morgan,'' delves into Rockefeller's
private life and personality as well as his business dealings to
produce a nuanced, multifaceted portrait.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a best seller, ``Titan'' should earn
major-award attention and is certainly the most important biography
of the spring-summer season.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the socioeconomic scale is Cedric Jennings.
Considered a ``nerd'' at his Washington, D.C., ghetto high school,
Jennings eschewed drugs and gangs and gained a place at Brown
University, where he has faced both opportunities and challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street Journal reporter Ron Suskind, who won a Pulitzer
Prize for a newspaper series on Jennings' high school years,
followed the young black man to college and produced ``A Hope in
the Unseen: An American Odyssey From the Inner City to the Ivy
League'' (Broadway Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker writer Lillian Ross has had the Big Apple atwitter
with the memoir of her decades-long affair with longtime New Yorker
editor William Shawn. The book is ``Here But Not Here'' (Random
House, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Other major titles in the biography/memoir category include
``Helen Keller: A Life'' by Dorothy Herrmann (Knopf, $30), an
early-August release; ``Badge of Courage: The Life of Stephen
Crane'' by Linda H. Davis (Houghton Mifflin, $35); and Ian Gibson's
``Shameful Life of Salvador Dali'' (Norton, $45), billed as ``the
most thorough and ambitious biography'' yet of the surrealist
artist.
</P>
<P>
   For Texas-history buffs, the biggest book of this season and
several past is ``Three Roads to the Alamo'' by William C. Davis
(HarperCollins, $35). This exhaustively researched joint biography
of David Crockett, James Bowie and William Barrett Travis will
appeal to readers who prefer complicated truths to simplistic
myths.
</P>
<P>
   European-history buffs should seek out Alexandra Ritchie's
``Faust's Metropolis: A History of Berlin'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf, $35).
Mammoth (976 pages) but eminently readable, the book chronicles the
city from its pre-Roman roots but concentrates on its tumultuous
20th-century history. (The author, a fellow of Wolfson College at
Oxford University, is a member of the von Moltkes, a famous German
military family.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greatest Benefit to Mankind: A Medical History of
Humanity'' (Norton, $35) sounds forbidding, but historian Roy
Porter blends erudition and anecdote to produce an engaging volume.
</P>
<P>
   Political junkies have ``Nixon in Winter'' (Random House, $30),
the second volume in Monica Crowley's Boswell-like renderings of
the ex-president's views. From 1990 to 1994, Crowley served as
Nixon's foreign-policy assistant and sounding board. She published
``Nixon Off the Record'' in 1996. In this second volume, Nixon
delivers himself on subjects ranging from the breakup of the Soviet
Union to President Clinton to the death of his wife, Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Kinder tells the story of the sinking of the gold-laden
sidewheel steamer Central America off the Carolina coast in 1857
and the recovery of the ship's treasure by inventor Tommy Thompson
in 1989. The book is ``Ship of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea''
(Atlantic Monthly Press, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ellis examines the origins and evolution of the Atlantis
myth in ``Imagining Atlantis'' (Knopf, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Bill Bryson, an Iowa-born journalist who spent 20 years
in England, has written perhaps the most delightful book of the
season, ``A Walk in the Woods'' (Broadway Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Having been out of the country for so long, Bryson decides to
reconnect with his American roots by walking the 2,100-mile
Appalachian Trail from north Georgia to Maine. Together with an
equally out-of-shape buddy, Stephen Katz, he takes to the woods,
fending off bears, yuppies and a preternaturally annoying hiker
named Mary Ellen.
</P>
<P>
   Funny and enlightening about the people and places of the trail,
``A Walk in the Woods'' might inspire you to poke your nose out the
door despite the heat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxxxxxx End of Story
</P>
</TEXT>
