<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANIES-TOYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAY HELLO TO THE MEANIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEESUN WEE 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; From her first stuffed animals as a child to
Beanie Babies as an adult, Anne Sidell has been hoarding stuff as
long as she can remember. But after years of collecting saccharine
cute and retro cool items, Sidell has discovered gross.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about Meanies, a collection of small, stuffed
critters that are crude and hilarious, or offensive _ depending on
your sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're gross and they're a riot,'' said Sidell, who owns the
entire first, 12-character series and is anxious to get her hands
on the second dozen, which went on sale earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanies' fans don't rival the masses of Beanie Babies
collectors. Local buyers and sellers of Meanies say they know of no
trading groups. But nearly a year after their debut, Meanies are
attracting followers. Proof of their growing popularity: In May,
the New York City-based idea factory, the manufacturer of Meanies,
also released teeny weenie meanies attached to key chains at
7-Eleven stores nationwide. And there will be more.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the month, the manufacturer is scheduled to unveil
a special collection parodying celebrities. The aptly titled group
of four Infamous Meanies will feature Bull Clinton, who sports
patriotic underwear _ below his knees; Buddy, Clinton's dog, its
mouth around pink panties monogrammed with the initials ML; Mike
Bison, who has an ear stuffed in his mouth; and Donkeying, a
combination of boxing promoter Don King and a donkey. So far, fans
only have been able to preview the celebrity collection on the
Internet at www.meanies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Each Meanie critter sells for about $5 and some eventually
disappear from the retail market, as has been the successful
marketing tactic for other collectible toys. But unlike a Beanie
Baby that retires, a Meanie's retail end appropriately is more
gruesome and violent. They're ``terminated.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Collectors and merchandisers say Meanies appeal to an audience
seeking something distinctly un-Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the boy's answer to the Beanie Babies,'' said Don
Aquilino of Acta Game Guys in Van Nuys, one of many Valley novelty
and toy shops selling Meanies.
</P>
<P>
   While some Meanies buyers collect all kinds of toys, Meanies
also attract boys and men who are tired of cuddly Beanie Babies and
want revenge, Valley toy store owners say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are saying, `I now have something to put on my desk,' ''
said Allen LeWinter, the originator of Meanies and president of
TOPKAT entertainment marketing company New Jersey. LeWinter has
been in the toy business for more than a decade and helped push
purple Barney into our lives through licensing agreements.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, LeWinter created Meanies with males in mind. In
contrast, Beanie Babies seem to have an especially loyal fan base
among girls and women, he said. ``I kept thinking, `Where are the
boys'?''
</P>
<P>
   Once the concept of Meanies was established, LeWinter and 10
staff members developed the characters. For ideas, they keep
abreast of news events and trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see who's on top, throw out ideas and see what's funny,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   LeWinter admits the Series II plush toys are more in-your-face
than their initial counterparts. The dirtier dozen includes Peeping
Tom Cat, with eyes that bulge out like binoculars; Donnie Didn't
Duck, a blue-and-white bird with no head _ just what looks like
blood; and the Velocicrapper, grimacing and trying to, uh ... you
know.
</P>
<P>
   LeWinter said Meanies are selling because Americans' tolerance
for foulness seems to have shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten into a period where gross is acceptable. Who
would have thought (the cartoon series) `South Park' would be
acceptable?'' he said. ``There's a trend toward the grosser. If
it's gross or yucky, it sells.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holly Carson of Sylmar, who owns about a dozen characters
and sells collectibles at Holly's Hobbies inside the Country
Antique Fair Mall in Saugus, stressed she wouldn't buy a Meanie for
a child. ``They're not for everybody,'' Carson said.
</P>
<P>
   And Sidell admits she keeps her Meanies collection in her
bedroom because not all her guests would appreciate them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, executives at Ty, manufacturers of Beanie Babies,
don't seem to be getting the joke. The publicity department did not
return telephone requests for comments about Meanies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
