<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MEASURE-H     06-22 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MEASURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE LAST YEARS OF THE CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While he was writing ``Gods and Generals,'' Jeff Shaara stayed
away from his father's novel, ``The Killer Angels,'' so he wouldn't
be tempted to steal the rhythms of that book. ``Still, my sister
said `Gods and Generals' was being written by the ghost of our
father,'' Shaara said.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Shaara's latest book, ``The Last Full
Measure'' (Ballantine Books. New York. 560 pages. $25.95.) While
``Gods and Generals'' describes the years leading up to Gettysburg
and ``Killer Angels'' deals with the three days of the battle,
``The Last Full Measure'' takes the war across its last two years,
to the surrender at Appomattox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Full Measure'' offers two of the same voices heard in
``Gods and Generals'' and ``The Killer Angels'' _ Joshua
Chamberlain of the 20th Maine and Confederate commander Robert E.
Lee. It adds the voice of Ulysses S. Grant, taking the place of
Southern generals Stonewall Jackson, who died after
Chancellorsville, and James Longstreet, wounded in the Wilderness.
But the most important voice in the book is Shaara's, brought from
father to son.
</P>
<P>
   Lee sounds the same as he did under the pen of Michael Shaara
(``There is no time''), trusting to the Lord and the rightness of a
cause gone wrong. There's also a straight line through Chamberlain,
from ``Gods and Generals'' to ``The Last Full Measure,'' as he
grows with each passing battle to the final surrender of arms at
Appomattox.
</P>
<P>
   But the voice of Grant is not as certain. Jeff Shaara can't
quite deal with all the layers of the man _ a butcher who sends
7,000 men to be cut down at Cold Harbor, whose muddled plan for the
Crater leads to more wasted lives, who loses almost half his army
on the killing floor before finally cornering Lee across the James
River. Grant comes through most forcefully in his defense of
all-out war _ ``There is only one way to make war, Colonel. You
have to hurt somebody. Maybe you have to hurt everybody ... If we
fight, men will die. If more of them die, then we will win. It has
nothing to do with cities, or government, or what is barbaric and
what is civilized.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy would find its way to Verdun, to Stalingrad, to
the massed attacks below the Yalu, putting the lie to Shaara's
argument that something was learned from the wholesale slaughter of
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Killer Angels'' was able to do justice to Gettysburg's
three days. But ``The Last Full Measure'' is crippled by the width
and breadth of a war winding down. Jeff Shaara can spend time in
the Wilderness, at the Crater and a few battles around Petersburg,
but he has to pass over the storied assault on Missionary Ridge,
the Battle of Franklin, Sherman's march and a dozen other landmarks
of the last months of the war.
</P>
<P>
   He does more than justice to the final scenes, though, as Grant
and Lee meet at Appomattox to call an end to their war. Shaara
packs emotion into Grant's exchange with Lee, into his order to
silence Union celebrations _ ``They do not need to be told they are
beaten, they do not need us to tell them we have won. He began to
move, and the men were quiet now. There were still a few cheers, a
few hats waving, but around him men were watching Grant move past,
and they began to absorb what was in his face, began to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the best compliment to his writing, Shaara pointed
to a review from the Nashville Banner (which recently ceased
publication) that called ``Gods and Generals'' ... ``a work of
which Jeff's father would have been proud. It did something `The
Killer Angels' did not; it made me cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of ``The Last Full Measure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
