<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0892 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV28-     06-22 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 28)  
 Tours to Indonesia Postponed for Many  
 Bag-Tracking by Phone or Web  
 Ruminate on Tomorrow at Disneyland  
 An Alternative to Leaping Tall Buildings  
 Rail Passes for Greece and Eastern Europe  
 Titanic: the Ship, the Movie, the Phenomenon  
 (JT)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the violence has subsided in Indonesia, the political
and economic situation remains unsettled, and the State Department,
in a June 11 public announcement, advises Americans to avoid crowds
and areas where violence has been reported. The announcement
replaced a June 3 travel warning urging Americans to defer
non-essential travel to the country.
</P>
<P>
   While Jakarta, Indonesia's capital and the site of most
demonstrations against former President Suharto _ who resigned May
21 _ is not included on most group-tour itineraries, many tour
companies are rescheduling or canceling their tours to other
sections of the country. For example, Volcano Tours canceled its
Indonesian trips scheduled for June and August, with full refunds.
Overseas Adventure Travel also canceled its trips to Indonesia for
the rest of the year, with a full refund plus $200 toward any other
trip during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bali has not experienced violence, although there have been some
demonstrations on the island. Spice Island Cruises, which offers
trips that originate in Bali and then travel to remote islands, has
not had any cancellations or drop in bookings, according to Jill
Potash, a spokeswoman, and sees no reason not to conduct business
as usual, far removed from the disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   Journeys Off the Tourist Track in Fairfax, Calif., canceled one
trip to Bali for June, but still plans to take two groups there in
August. Travelers booked on a trip to Indonesia through Asia
Transpacific Journeys in Boulder, Colo., have been given the option
to reschedule. One tour set to depart the weekend after the
disturbances in Jakarta was canceled, and refunds were offered.
Since then, the company reports almost no cancellations, but its
bookings to Indonesia have been lower than usual this year, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   Updated information on Indonesia is available from the U.S.
Embassy in Jakarta, www.usembassyjakarta.org. Call (202) 647-5225
for recorded travel information on any country. Consular
Information Sheets for all countries can be accessed through the
State Department's Internet site, travel.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   If your luggage was lost on a Delta Air Lines flight _
``delayed'' is Delta's euphemism _ there is now something to do
other than call an 800 number and listen to recorded messages. The
airline has added a feature to its Web site that allows a traveler
to learn the status of the bag search. But it can be tracked on the
Web only after a passenger arriving at an airport reports the bag
missing, describes it and its contents and receives an
identification code for what Delta calls a property-irregularity
report.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web site, www.delta-air.com/baggage, passengers enter
their names and the report identification code. The site might then
respond that the bag is being delivered to a particular address at
a specified time. Or it might report that the bag is still being
sought. For those without access to the Web, the number to call is
(800) 325-8224.
</P>
<P>
   The designers at Disneyland have seen the future, and it is
digestible. After a year of work, renovations to Tomorrowland _ one
of eight themed areas at the Anaheim, Calif., park _ were completed
last month. It now has new rides, attractions, decor _ even new
edible landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can ride rockets that orbit spinning brass planets,
watch a special-effects film called ``Honey, I Shrunk the
Audience'' in a theater featuring a floor that moves, and take part
in technology demonstrations. There is also a new maze of water
jets shooting from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The building facades have been updated with paint schemes
designed to evoke the ``futuristic'' visions of H.G. Wells.
Landscaping now consists of only edible vegetation, from orange
trees to herbs, as part of an effort throughout Tomorrowland to
make the future seem inviting rather than, in the words of
designers, alien and hostile as portrayed in movies.
</P>
<P>
   How inviting? When asked if park visitors could snack on the
landscaping, Bob Deuel, a Disneyland spokesman, said: ``We wouldn't
encourage it, but it would be safe to do. We don't use
pesticides.''
</P>
<P>
   Deuel pointed out, in fact, that some lettuce plants are
temptingly close to hamburger stands.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (714) 781-4565.
</P>
<P>
   Bungee jumping, hang gliding or tightrope walking from the top
of the 1,815-foot-high CN Tower to neighboring downtown Toronto
office buildings has become possible _ in visitor's minds, that is.
The aptly named Thrill Zone digital-animation attraction, at the
observation level near the top of the CN Tower, is part of an $18.4
million expansion and revitalization of the 22-year-old landmark.
For $12 visitors will also be able to have themselves digitally
photographed in such simulated daredevil poses as hanging by their
fingertips off the tower, with a 10-minute wait for the print. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the tower, other diversions include two new
five-minute rides in a flight simulator, a 144-seat theater showing
a new movie about Canada co-produced by IMAX and the National Film
Board of Canada, and arcade games, some of them of the virtual
reality variety.
</P>
<P>
   A package including the two rides, the movie and admission to
various observation levels costs $20, $17.50 for children
(admission to the Thrill Zone is free). New retail space with a
300-seat cafe, a duty-free shop (for international air passengers)
and a shop featuring Inuit art opened this month. Information:
(416) 868-6937.
</P>
<P>
   New this year among the crop of rail passes in Europe is the
Balkan Flexipass, offering unlimited first-class train travel in
Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia, Montenegro, Romania, Serbia and
Turkey. Three durations are available: 5, 10 or 15 days within a
single month at fares ranging from $152 to $317. For people younger
than 26, the range is $90 to $190. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also available to travelers headed for Greece are two packages
that combine either rail and air travel or rail, rental car and air
travel within the country. Greek Flexipass Rail and Fly provides
first-class train travel on any three days plus two air journeys in
Greece in a single month at a cost of $202. Holders of that pass
can fly to any Greek island served by Olympic Airways. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Greek Flexipass Fly Rail and Drive, the visitor gets three
days of first-class rail, two air trips in Greece and two days in a
minimum-category rental car starting at $278. The travel must be
used within a month. Larger cars and additional days are available
at extra cost.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Rail Europe, (888) 382-7245 or www.raileurope.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fascination with things Titanic continues this summer and
fall with two exhibits, one devoted to the movie and the other to
the ship itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic, the Movie on Tour,'' a 15,000-square-foot show of
film memorabilia, will travel to several Paramount theme parks in
North America. It features the 44-foot model of the ship used in
filming, sets such as Rose's stateroom, and behind-the-scenes
footage documenting the making of the movie. More than 150 props
and costumes include the ``Heart of the Ocean'' necklace.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will go to Kings Island in Cincinnati, July 3 to
19; Canada's Wonderland in Toronto, July 29 to Aug. 12; Kings
Dominion in Richmond, Aug. 22 to Sept. 7; and Carowinds in
Charlotte, N.C., Sept. 19 to Oct. 31 (weekends only). The exhibit
is free with admission to the theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, ``Titanic _ the Artifact Exhibition'' will present
more than 300 artifacts recovered from the vessel between 1987 and
1994, including the bronze cherub from the ship's grand staircase,
a gilt chandelier, an unopened bottle of Champagne and delicate
paper items such as a stock certificate and personal letters (found
in a passenger's luggage). Displays will illustrate the stories
behind the artifacts and the technology used to explore the ship's
resting place at the bottom of the North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The show runs from July 1 to Nov. 1 in a 30,000-square-foot
temporary structure at 164 Northern Avenue, adjacent to the World
Trade Center Boston, which organized the show. Tickets are $13.95,
$12.95 seniors, $6.95 ages 5 to 12, free under 5. Information:
(888) 744-7998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
