<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PROFILE-SHAARA-H     06-22 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PROFILE-SHAARA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CIVIL WAR BOOK SPROUTS FROM A FAMILY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This would've been in 1964, when Jeff Shaara was 12 years old,
his father, 35.
</P>
<P>
   They stood on Cemetery Ridge, at the spot where General Lew
Armistead collapsed after leading his men over the low wall, life
leaving him as he watched the last of his soldiers stop and scatter
and fall back down the hill _ as good a parable for the death of
the Confederacy as there would ever be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a kid, you know, I had my rubber sword and musket from
the gift shop, I wasn't even sure where I was,'' Shaara said. ``But
my father ... he was absolutely consumed by it. He had no idea,
when he was walking through the battlefield, that it would change
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I can tell you the moment, the exact moment. We were
standing at the high-water mark, next to the Armistead monument, me
with my little musket, and he started to tell me what happened.
He's looking back, at the ground they came over, at the place where
they died, and while he's talking he starts getting emotional. His
voice ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara stopped, looked up, and said, ``I'd never seen my father
emotional. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara's father, Michael, would go on to write what is
considered the best novel about the Civil War, ``The Killer
Angels,'' which won the Pulitzer Prize after its publication in
1974. Michael Shaara, who died of heart disease in 1988 at the age
of 59, never saw his novel become a popular success. But his son
has seen ``The Killer Angels'' reach its 79th printing and has
followed in the wake of his father's words, writing the
best-selling Civil War novel ``Gods and Generals'' and ``The Last
Full Measure,'' just out from Ballantine Books (512 pages, $25.95
hardcover).
</P>
<P>
   During a recent reading of ``The Last Full Measure'' in San
Francisco, Shaara told the audience, ``I have no illusions. If not
for heart disease, if not for my father's untimely death, he would
have written these books. I would not be standing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his death, Michael Shaara was able to hand down his
passion for the Civil War to his son, who graduated from Florida
State with a degree in criminology and went on to deal in rare
coins before writing ``Gods and Generals.'' The novel follows
officers and men through the battles before the three days of
Gettysburg _ the storm at the heart of ``The Killer Angels,'' and
the beginning of the end of war ``by the rules'' of standing
stock-straight through a hail of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the war they called Robert E. Lee `Granny' Lee,
because he wanted to put fortifications in front of Richmond,
because he wanted to dig in for defense,'' Shaara said. ``After
Gettysburg, you couldn't get enough shovels.''
</P>
<P>
   To Shaara, ``The Killer Angels'' is part of a trilogy, started
by ``Gods and Generals,'' completed by ``The Last Full Measure'' _
a novel of the war after Gettysburg, seen through the eyes of Lee,
Joshua Chamberlain and Ulysses S. Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a history book. I am not a historian,'' Shaara
said. ``This is the story of people, real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara smiled a little, saying, ``My father used to say that
during the writing of `The Killer Angels,' he was visited by every
character in the book. Not `ghost' visits, just ... a sense of
being with them.'' He's felt the same thing, said Shaara, standing
inside the house in which Stonewall Jackson died.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Fredericksburg, Va., for the writing of ``Gods and
Generals,'' Shaara found that the town has overgrown the
battlefield. ``If you want to stand where Lee stood at the top of
the hill,'' he said, ``you're in somebody's back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few miles south, Shaara spotted a sign reading,
``Stonewall Jackson Shrine,'' which led to a small, two-story house
watched over by a single park ranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me what happened there and then let me be,'' Shaara
said. ``The bed was the same, the blanket on the bed, the clock in
the room was the same, as the day Jackson died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't hard to imagine that when the rasping of his breath
stopped _ he died of pneumonia, not from the wound _ every head
turned toward the ticking of that clock. Without trying to make it
sound too melodramatic, I stood there, listening to the ticking of
the clock, the same clock that had been in the room with Jackson,
and it changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara plunged into writing ``Gods and Generals,'' which hit the
best-seller charts within weeks of being published. ``The Killer
Angels,'' despite its critical success, despite the Pulitzer Prize,
did not make it to the best-seller list until the first week of
October 1993 _ the week the film based on the novel,
``Gettysburg,'' made its debut.
</P>
<P>
   His father had written four novels and more than 70 short
stories, Shaara said, ``but he was not, in his mind, a success.
`The Killer Angels' was turned down by 15 publishers before it was
finally printed ... when I was growing up, my memories are of all
the rejection letters, my mother trying to hide them so he didn't
see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote other pieces, magazine pieces, at a penny a word,''
Shaara said with a quick smile. ``I know, because as a boy I had to
count them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally when you win a Pulitzer Prize, the doors open up. Not
for him. In 1975, the end of the Vietnam War, absolutely nobody
wanted to read a book about war. The critics were like, `How can
this man dare write a book glorifying generals?' They called it a
`cult' book.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after ``Killer Angels,'' started to sell, Shaara's father
had to run the historical gauntlet. ``He'd catch hell in the North
for being sympathetic to Lee, catch hell in the South for his
positive portrayal of Longstreet, which you just did not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've also had people get in my face, saying, `That war was
about slavery.' And I say, `You're telling me a lumberjack from
Vermont is fighting the war because of slavery? What does he know
or care about slavery?' ... It was never that simplistic, but it's
one of those things they teach kids in the fifth grade, so they can
pass a test.''
</P>
<P>
   There had to be more to it, to explain the slaughter on both
sides, Shaara said. ``Why would these guys keep marching into the
guns, year after year, when their wives are writing to them,
saying, `Enough already. The farm needs you. The kids need you.'
These men, most of them, wrote back to say, `This is for honor, for
my honor.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reason the Civil War still holds its spell half a dozen
generations later, Shaara said, is ``because they are us. Some of
us have ancestors from the war, but that's the easy answer. It's
because we can relate to these people as humans. They are us. This
is who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Northerners and Southerners fought for ``the power of an idea,''
he said _ fought to protect the same Constitution handed down from
generation to generation, war to war, through the worst and best of
this country's history.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who won't accept that, Shaara said, or accept
the concept of a historical novel. ``I've had people say, `How dare
you put words in the mouth of Robert E. Lee?' So I said to myself,
`OK, the only way you can do that is if you get to know the
characters.'''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara did, and he liked what he saw, with some exceptions. ``My
father liked Longstreet ... he saw a lot of himself in Longstreet.
They were both brooding men, bothered by depression. I had a
problem _ I didn't find the same man my father did. He saw Lee
through the eyes of Longstreet. I saw it the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Phil Sheridan? Phil Sheridan was a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara didn't see any of that when he was playing with inch-high
soldiers as a kid. ``I used to put the blue troops in the folds of
a blanket, call it the mountains, put the Confederates on the
floor, then roll marbles at 'em. Whoever was left standing, won.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Shaara grew to learn the complexities of the war and
the everyday demands of staying alive. He remembered his father
working on a definitive volume of Shakespeare as his life wore down
_ ``He would sit at the typewriter, 10 minutes would go by, and
he'd be done. He had his first heart attack at 36. I'm 46. I take
this seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
