<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HEALTHY TOURIST THINKS AHEAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever the destination, a prime requisite for maximum
enjoyment of travel is good health. And our precautions should
begin before leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because travel is so much a part of my life _ or maybe
through pure luck _ I rarely become ill on the road. And yet I
routinely pack a portable medicine chest crammed with Immodium,
Pepto-Bismol, Tylenol and Advil, insect repellent, sunscreen, cough
syrup, NyQuil, DayQuil and all sorts of other remedies that usually
go unopened.
</P>
<P>
   I take all the appropriate inoculations, too. (Ouch!)
</P>
<P>
   But during a travel editors' workshop this spring in San Diego,
I attended a seminar at which a past president of the International
Society of Travel Medicine made a recommendation I had never
considered:
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone traveling outside the United States should take along a
prescription antibiotic,'' said Dr. Jay Keystone of Toronto, a
specialist in tropical medicine and a consultant to several major
travel health organizations in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A CURE FOR MANY ILLS
</P>
<P>
   Keystone suggested that a physician familiar with an
individual's overall health history should be consulted to
prescribe an antibiotic for potential bowel, bladder, respiratory
or skin ailments.
</P>
<P>
   And the antibiotic should be used only if the traveler becomes
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to a recent European vacation, I asked my doctor about
Keystone's recommendation. He seconded the notion and prescribed an
antibiotic to take if the co-pilot or I developed a respiratory
infection. As fate held, the co-pilot got sick and the antibiotic
likely helped avert a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   Health concerns, much like safety, are topics many who make
their living in the travel industry prefer unaddressed. The
Caribbean beach resort wants us to imagine soft, white-powder sand,
not painful, beet-red sunburn. The company promoting tours of a
rain forest emphasizes lush, green foliage and romantic adventure,
not infectious mosquitoes feasting on our arms and legs. The
airline touts gourmet meals and service with a smile _ oops, that
was another era, wasn't it? _ not air recycling again and again in
crowded cabins.
</P>
<P>
   Keystone says some never learn an important lesson:
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy traveler will travel again,'' he says. ``An
unhealthy traveler won't travel again. Neither will his family, his
neighbors or his friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAKING PRECAUTIONS
</P>
<P>
   A main concern is travel to what Keystone terms ``the developing
world.'' Of 100,000 visitors to these areas, he says, ``50,000 will
develop a health problem; 8,000 will see a doctor; 1,100 will be
incapacitated in their work during or after their trip; 300 will be
hospitalized during or after the trip; 50 will be evacuated by air;
and one will die.''
</P>
<P>
   But without proper precautions, we court trouble even on a Texas
beach. ``By the year 2,000, one in 75 Americans will have malignant
melanoma, and that's a scary figure,'' says Keystone.
</P>
<P>
   Keystone has compiled what he labels ``Ten Commandments for
Tropical Travel,'' and most apply for any journey:
</P>
<P>
   1) Thou shalt consult with thy physician. Inquire about required
and recommended inoculations and other appropriate medications.
Immunize, Keystone suggests, ``according to risk, not according to
the country visited. Two people may go to Thailand; one may need
half-a-dozen immunizations and another hardly any. Joining the
Peace Corps creates a different set of circumstances than staying
in luxury hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   2) Thou shalt acclimate thyself. Get adequate rest before
departure. To guard against jet lag, go to bed later and awaken
later in advance of a trip if traveling westbound; go to bed
earlier and awaken earlier if traveling eastbound. Ask a doctor
about light-exposure alteration procedures and about medications to
help combat jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   3) Thou shalt protect thyself against insects. Malaria has long
been a major concern, and dengue fever is an emerging problem.
Keystone says DEET is the most effective repellent. ``But there is
90 percent DEET and 20 percent DEET. What's the difference? The 20
percent DEET lasts about half the time (offering 4-6 hours
protection).''
</P>
<P>
   4) Thou shalt purify the water that thou drinkest including thy
cubes of ice. Remember that even in first-class hotels, no
guarantee of adequate water purification exists, says Keystone.
</P>
<P>
   5) Thou shalt cook well thy food and peel thine own fruit and
vegetables. ``Studies show that 98 percent of travelers make a
`faux pas' involving food within 48 hours of leaving home,'' says
Keystone. Avoid leftovers, raw shellfish, unpasteurized milk, food
from street vendors and cold meats in restaurants. ``Boil it, peel
it, cook it or forget it,'' says Keystone.
</P>
<P>
   6) Thou shalt carry self-treatment for travelers' diarrhea.
``Don't leave home without Immodium and an antibiotic,'' says
Keystone.
</P>
<P>
   7) Thou shalt take and wear thy prophylactics.
</P>
<P>
   8) Thou shalt swim not in fresh water nor walk in thy bare feet.
</P>
<P>
   9) Thou shalt be concerned about thy security.
</P>
<P>
   10) Thou shalt be wary of thy conveyance.
</P>
<P>
   Keystone emphasizes that ongoing research is producing new
medications to help combat each form of hepatitis, malaria and
other illnesses. Several Internet sites provide up-to-date
information. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   1) Centers for Disease Control and Prevention:
http://www.cdc.gov/travel/travel.html.
</P>
<P>
   2) International Society of Travel Medicine:
http://www.istm.org.
</P>
<P>
   3) Travel Health Online: http://www.tripprep.com.
</P>
<P>
   4) Health Canada: http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/hpb/lcdc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxxxxxxx END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
