<HEADLINE>
WHY JOHNNIE CAN'T BASEBRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, June 24)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychologists say that violence in professional sports is worse
than ever and that some of it may be rubbing off on impressionable
youngsters who try to emulate their athletic heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The bad role models include a basketball player who choked his
coach, a major league pitcher who intentionally drilled a batter in
the back and Olympic hockey players who trashed their hotel room
after a loss.
</P>
<P>
   As another Little League season draws to a close, my impression
is that many of youngsters still don't ``have what it takes'' to
make it in professional sports, at least in terms of acting like
raging, out-of-control, homicidal maniacs.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the parents if you will, but far too many youngsters
today treat sports as ``just a game'' rather than the life and
death struggle in which winning is everything, no matter what the
cost.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each game, players on both sides form a line and
shake hands, and then dash off in search of the mom who brought
soft drinks and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the kids sit around afterward and swap baseball cards,
much like kids did when I was growing up, except that a pack of
baseball cards costs $5 today compared to a nickel back then.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of behavior that gets one promoted to the
professional ranks or gets one's name mentioned in the police
briefs of the local newspaper. If our children are going to achieve
the low standards of professional athletes, they need to start
working on their bad attitudes now.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it would be nice if the pitcher did not cry when
he accidentally hits a batter in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   Major league pitchers do not cry when they hit someone, though
they may whimper a little bit if the batter comes after them with a
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the subject of the baseball brawl, something
we've seen quite a bit of on TV lately, but which you seldom if
ever see in Little League.
</P>
<P>
   Few sights in professional sports are more inspiring than a
benches-clearing baseball melee where 50 grown men rush onto the
field in order to hug each other in as aggressive a manner as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   I have been watching Little League games for four years now and
I have yet to see a coach teach his players the subtle nuances of
the classic baseball brawl, which is a lot like ballroom dancing,
only with more spitting.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of spitting, I have also never seen a Little Leaguer
spit in the face of an umpire, even though such things happen from
time to time in the major leagues. One can only assume that we're
going to experience a severe shortage of accomplished
umpire-spitters in the near future if Little League coaches do not
stop wasting so much time on the hit-and-run, proper bunting
techniques and other silly stuff and devote more attention to this
valuable skill.
</P>
<P>
   Little Leaguers can also prepare themselves for the Big Time by
forgetting about all this ``team'' nonsense and concentrating on
themselves instead. For example, there is no need to show up for
practice if you've been out partying late the night before or get a
sudden urge to jet off to Las Vegas for a little gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson to be learned here is that if you have some talent,
just about any form of boorish, selfish, antisocial behavior is not
only acceptable, but will be richly rewarded with fat contracts,
product endorsements and maybe even a movie deal.
</P>
<P>
   America is a land of great opportunity for young athletes if
they just open their eyes and get with the program.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
