r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-WAR-1STLD     06-22 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-WAR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REQUIEM' FOR A WAR, AN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: REPLACES previous with correct story)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man walked over to Horst Faas, leaned across the table,
excused himself for interrupting, and started talking about an
argument between members of his fraternity over the Vietnam War.
``This was 1962,'' he said. ``Laguna Beach, California. I was a
hawk.''
</P>
<P>
   It was important to the man to convince Faas that he had changed
his mind, that he had come to see the human loss of the war. He
switched his wine glass from one hand to the other, blinking,
waiting for an acknowledgment of that change. Faas nodded, saying,
``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Faas, the scene has been repeated time and again over the
past few months _ with veterans, with former refugees, with sons
and daughters of those who fought, with hundreds of people who have
brushed up against the Vietnam War in one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   Faas, who edited _ along with Tim Page _ the recently published
``Requiem,'' a book of photographs from Vietnam and Indochina taken
by men and women killed in action, shakes his head over the
response to ``Requiem,'' from city to city.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx chapter of veterans from the 173rd Airborne, coming up
to him to relive the war. A crewman in one of the Marine tanks
pictured in during Tet. People who knew the photographer or someone
in a photograph, or knew the countryside or the battle. People who
were there, just out of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I did this I got questions like, `Why? Why stir up old
memories?''' Faas said. ``Then they see the book and say, `Oh. OK.
I understand.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiem'' features dozens of photos taken by French,
Vietnamese and American photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Faas, former head photographer for the Associated Press in
Vietnam, said ``Requiem'' came about when Page tried to find out
what happened to fellow photographers Sean Flynn and Dana Stone,
who disappeared while covering the spread of the Vietnam War to
Laos and Cambodia. That led to talks with the North Vietnamese, who
pointed Page to pictures taken by their own photographers during
the war, and Page carried the photos to Faas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was seeing something nobody had seen before,''
Faas said. ``Some of these pictures had never been printed. Slowly,
photo by photo, we were digging material out of Vietnam that had
been forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Faas, 65, expanded the project to include the French defeat in
Indochina and the satellite wars in countries bordering Vietnam,
then took the package to Harry Evans of Random House. ``The
accountants told him, `Nobody wants to buy a Vietnam book.' ...
Their tastes are more for artsy-fartsy things, um? ... but he said,
`We're going to do this, and we're going to do it big.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since its publication, Faas has seen his book reviewed favorably
across the country, including two takes in the New York Times.
Photo exhibits have brought written responses that include ``I was
there; the photos depict the horror,'' ``This is the true Vietnam
memorial,'' and ``These pictures stand in stark contrast to the
absence of pictures from the Gulf war. The new media in that
conflict abdicated its responsibility to tell the harsh truth.''
</P>
<P>
   And at each exhibit, Faas has been approached by people with
their own memories, people wanting to talk. In San Francisco, he
was surprised by Jimmy Lo Hung, who took pictures for AP as a
12-year-old during the Tet offensive and now runs his own photo
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Hung had brought a picture of himself in a helmet with PRESS
across the front, and a laminated story headlined ``Boy, 12, in
Dangerous Jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid me $10 a picture,'' he said, ``and that was big
money in Vietnam. It could support my whole family for one month.''
</P>
<P>
   Hung lost all his pictures and negatives when the North
Vietnamese invaded the South. ``I only had a few minutes to
escape,'' he said, remembering that ``I was pulled aboard a
helicopter filled with soldiers. They held my leg while it took
off. So many soldiers trying to get on ... some didn't, some
dropped down.''
</P>
<P>
   Faas, sitting beside Hung, said, ``This kid, I didn't even know
he was alive. I'm happy, really happy, to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the book and the exhibits of ``Requiem'' seem to lead to
these kinds of reunions, Faas said, to a sharing of memories buried
for years. But that's what photojournalism can do, he said _ ``Give
you that one, uncompromising moment, that image that cannot change,
no matter what side you are on, win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   History will make its own judgments on events like the Vietnam
War, Faas said. There will be other wars, just as cruel, despite
the stark cruelty shown in ``Requiem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A picture is taken not to change anything. It is taken to show
what is happening,'' Faas said. ``We are not there to change the
world. We are there to report the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
