<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 28)  
 (JT)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barcelona Festival
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have information on a cultural festival to be held in
Barcelona this summer? _ Sam Betelio, Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The city's summer arts festival, called the ``Grec,'' after
the Greek-style, 2,000-seat outdoor amphitheater on Montjuic
mountain, started in 1976. The initial season featured a few dozen
shows at the Grec Theater; this year's edition, Grec '98, offers
138 theatrical, dance and musical shows from June 25 to Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights are these: the National Ballet of Cuba will
perform ``Swan Lake'' from July 29 to Aug. 8 and ``Cinderella''
from Aug. 11 to 15 at the Tivoli Theater, 8 Caspe, at 10 p.m.
Tuesday to Friday and 6:30 and 10:30 p.m. on Saturday. Tickets are
$13 to $26. The Argentine dance company called the New Tango
Passion will present a revue featuring tango styles from the past
100 years, from Aug. 11 to 19 at the Grec Theater, 36 Paseo Santa
Madrona, at 10:30 p.m. Tickets cost $13 to $26. B.B. King will
perform on July 21 at 10 p.m. in the outdoor plaza of Pueblo
Espanol, 25 Avenida Marques de Comillas. Tickets cost $23. The
festival's most expensive ticket costs $40, for a concert by the
pianist Friedrich Gulda on July 11 at 10:30 p.m. at the Grec
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available at www.grecbcn.com. The festival
office, at Palacio de la Virreina, 99 La Rambla, is open weekdays
from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. and 4 to 8 p.m. through June 24 and during
August, but from June 25 to July 31 the hours are 10 a.m. to 8 p.m.
weekdays. If calling, (34) 93-301-7775, ask for the Office of
Information and you should be transferred to an English-speaking
attendant who can assist with ticket sales by phone, charged to a
major credit card Fax (34) 93-301-6100.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Harbor Tours
</P>
<P>
   Q. My father-in-law was a Navy officer serving at Pearl Harbor
when it was bombed in 1941. My husband and I are planning a trip to
Hawaii in December and look forward to visiting the Arizona
Memorial. Are there any tours that would take us onto the naval
base at Pearl Harbor and Ford Island? We also understand the
Missouri will soon be on display at Pearl Harbor. _ Carroll Guitar,
Milton, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. Pearl Harbor Naval Base, the scene of the Japanese attack on
Dec. 7, 1941, that caused heavy losses to the United States fleet,
including the sinking of the battleship Arizona, is still an active
military installation. As a result, tours are limited and often
require reservations or special arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The only formal program for individual visitors is a free tour
of a Navy surface ship (the type of ship varies depending on what
is in dock). It is held the first Saturday of each month between
noon and 4 p.m. Visitors must go to the main gate for directions to
the designated ship (for safety reasons, children must be at least
8 years old).
</P>
<P>
   There is also a similar weekly program, typically held on
Wednesdays. Though this program is primarily for organized groups,
exceptions are sometimes made for individuals who have been given
advance notice.
</P>
<P>
   With your family ties to Pearl Harbor you have a chance of
getting a more extensive tour of the base, including Ford Island
and the Utah Memorial, which is dedicated to the training ship that
sank just offshore with 50 people aboard during the 1941 attack.
Permission to take such tours is granted by the Navy on a
case-by-case basis, with preference given to veterans. Information:
(808) 471-0281.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri, the battleship on which Japan formally surrendered
in 1945, will indeed be docked in Pearl Harbor as a memorial, and
is scheduled to enter the harbor this month. The ship will be
moored near the Arizona Memorial for at least three years until a
permanent location is prepared at Ford Island.
</P>
<P>
   Tours of the Missouri, (admission $12), are not scheduled to
begin until sometime in January. Information: (808) 545-2263.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tuscany Cooking Schools &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you know of any fall cooking classes in Tuscany that
involve spending a week or two in a villa or a small hotel? _
Shirley Lowell, Westbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cooking tours are popular throughout Italy, especially in the
spring and fall, and especially in Tuscany. ``Your Guide to 82
Decadent Cooking Holidays in Italy,'' a selective listing by
Margaret Cowan, a travel consultant, lists some 30 tours in the
region. The 1998 guide, published in Vancouver, British Columbia,
by Margaret Cowan, is among the most comprehensive available and
can be ordered by calling (604) 878-0318 or (800) 557-0370. It
costs $42.77, including shipping.
</P>
<P>
   A series of weeklong cooking classes focusing on traditional
Tuscan cuisine will be held at Villa Michaela in Vorno, just south
of Lucca. Dishes you might prepare include melanzane (eggplant)
alla parmigiana, risotto and grilled vegetables with gorgonzola.
The instructor and chef, Valter Roman, has been associated with
restaurants in Italy and Britain. Participants dine in a frescoed
dining room or in the garden. There will also be opportunities to
tour Lucca, Florence, the Etruscan town of Volterra and Vorno. The
19th-century Villa Michaela, surrounded by 50 acres of olive trees,
gardens and pine forests, has nine guest rooms in the main house
and three in the coach house. All have private bathrooms. There are
tennis courts and a swimming pool on the property. This fall's
classes are scheduled to begin Oct. 10, 17, 24 and 31 and Nov. 7.
Prices begin at $2,295, double occupancy, excluding air fare. For
information, contact Cuisine International in Dallas: (214)
373-1161, fax (214) 373-1162.
</P>
<P>
   The medieval hamlet of Villa a Sesta, about 20 miles east of
Siena, is the site of another series of weeklong classes and
excursions, offered by the husband and wife team of Helene
Stoquelet and Franco Camelia, owners of Bottega del 30, one of two
restaurants in the village. Dishes you might prepare include
ravioli with pigeon filling and pine nut sauce, rabbit stuffed with
bread and prunes and timbale of grilled eggplant. Accommodations
are in private apartments with separate sitting rooms. Classes are
held in a separate building, which also houses Camelia's wine
cellar and gastronomic library. Excursions to wine cellars and
castles in the surrounding area will also be offered. The classes
begin on Sept. 26, Oct. 3, 17 and 24, and the cost is $2,575 a
person, double occupancy. Information: The International Kitchen in
Chicago, (800) 945-8606, fax (312) 654-8446.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
