<HEADLINE>
WALKING TOURS RUN OUT FAST  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If here at the brink of July you are still only dreaming about a
bracing stroll in Tuscany, Ireland or perhaps Provence, it is time
and possibly past time to act. Some companies report a doubling of
demand for walking tours, both circular walks going out from one
inn, and from inn to inn. The popularity of walking as a way to see
the countryside is linked to the rise of ``soft adventure,''
walking's health benefit and the attraction of making friends on
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   A few openings still exist on various companies' walking tours
for summer and fall, and if you are lucky, you may find just what
you want. Here is a glimpse at some offerings from established
companies whose officials say there are still spaces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Smithsonian Study Tours &LR;  has a  &UR;  &LR; new catalog with three walking
tours with openings this fall: the Cotswolds, Provence and Tuscany.
Tuscan Countryside, with 10 nights in a Siena pension and generally
rugged city walks in daytime, is scheduled for Oct. 1 to 12. The
catalog says the program involves a great amount of walking, often
up fairly steep hills. The cost, with air fare from New York and
departure taxes, is $3,959 for one of two people in a room. All
breakfasts, two lunches and eight dinners are included.
</P>
<P>
   The Walks in the Autumn Sun tour in Provence involves pretty
rugged country walks, up to eight miles a day, sometimes with
elevation gains of 800 feet. The departure date is Oct. 1, with
nine nights in a hotel in St.-Remy-de-Provence near Avignon.
``Associates will need to be in good health and able to walk five
to eight miles a day over undulating, rocky terrain, frequently
with steep inclines and descents,'' the catalog says. The cost,
with air fare from Washington, is $4,595 for one of two people in a
room. Continental breakfasts, four lunches and five dinners are
included.
</P>
<P>
   The longest walk on the Cotswolds trip, Sept. 3 to 12, is 7.5
miles. The eight nights are spent in Chipping Camden, and this is
easier over all than the two on the Continent. The cost for one of
two in a room, air fare from New York included, is $4,115.
Smithsonian Study Tours, 1100 Jefferson Drive, S.W., Washington,
D.C. 20560; (202) 357-4700; on the Web: www.si.edu/tsa/sst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; British Coastal Trails,  &LR; a walking-tour company in Carlsbad,
Calif., warns that it is hard to book any trip closer than 30 days
off, but it has space on several later trips (the company's usual
limit is 18 participants). A Week in Provence, actually six nights
starting Sept. 26, is listed as a moderate level of walking, with
undulating terrain, some steep ascents and dirt paths. The first
night is spent in a hotel in Aix-en-Provence, with three nights at
a farmhouse hotel near Lourmarin and two nights in
Vaison-la-Romaine. Prices do not include air travel, although the
company can arrange it. The Provence price is $1,895 for one of two
people in a room, with breakfast and dinner daily.
</P>
<P>
   A slightly tougher walk _ 4 on the company's 1-to-5 scale of
difficulty _ follows the Amalfi Coast, where winding footpaths
along craggy trails connect seaport towns. This seven-night trip
has openings on Sept. 5 and Oct. 10 departures. Three nights are
spent in Sorrento, two on the Isle of Capri and two in Ravello. A
walk up Vesuvius and in the up-and-down town of Positano are
included. The price is $2,185 for one of two people in a room, with
two meals daily; air fare is not included.
</P>
<P>
   This company also has openings for western Ireland walks, 11
nights, with departures Aug. 1 and Sept. 5; without air fare, it's
$2,795 for one of two people in a room. British Coastal Trails
Scenic Walking, 703 Palomar Airport Road, Suite 200, Carlsbad,
Calif. 92009; (800) 473-1210; on the Web: www.bctwalk.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Wayfarers,  &LR; a British company with offices in Newport,
R.I., has openings on its Dordogne six-night walking trip leaving
Sept. 27. This company, founded in 1984, does only walking trips
(limited to 16 participants), and these are generally more focused
and demanding than those provided by general tour companies. The
village-to-village walks average 10 to 12 miles a day, with mostly
family inns and hotels used. The towns visited are
Sarlat-la-Caneda, Vitrac, Belves, St.-Cyprien and Bordeaux. The
cost, with all meals but no air fare, is $1,880 for one of two
people in a room. There are also openings for Provence, the Loire
Valley and Burgundy; 12 departures on two Italian walks have sold
out. The Wayfarers, 172 Bellevue Avenue, Newport, R.I. 02840; (800)
249-4620; www.thewayfarers.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alternative Travel Group &LR; , an organization in Oxford, England,
has openings this fall. It offers walking trips for groups of 16 in
Italy, Spain, France, Portugal, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   These are not cream-puff trips: the most vigorous, Path to Rome,
covers 175 miles; the shortest is Renaissance Tuscany, 45 miles in
seven days, with days of varying difficulty. This Tuscany trip has
openings Oct. 24 to 31. The price of $2,730 includes all meals,
wine and accommodations, but not air fare. This trip is also
offered Dec. 20 to 27.
</P>
<P>
   A Sicily walk, from Enna in the mountains to Cefalu on the
coast, has openings for Sept. 12 to 19. This cost is $1,890, again
with meals, wine and accommodations, but no air fare. Alternative
Travel Group, 69-71 Banbury Road, Oxford, England OX2 6PE. The
company has a United States toll-free number, (800) 527-5997, in
addition to its British number, (44-1865) 315665. It closes at 5
p.m., and the time is five hours ahead of Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Overseas Adventure Travel,  &LR; a division of Grand Circle in
Boston, serves travelers over 50. It began walking tours only last
year, and is moving into the field cautiously. It has just added to
this year's schedule a pretty easy 12-night walking trip in the
west and south of Ireland. Three departures are available: Aug. 20,
Sept. 3 and Sept. 24. The limit is 16 participants. This trip is
listed as moderate, the middle of the company's three levels. There
is walking on eight days, and the longest walk is seven miles. The
nights are spent in small hotels or guesthouses with private baths:
four nights in Cork, four in Killarney and four in Limerick. The
prices, with air fare from New York or Boston, are $3,190 for Aug.
20, $3,090 for Sept. 3 and $2,990 for Sept. 24; these are for
anyone willing to share a room with another partipant. Twenty-eight
meals are included. Overseas Adventure Travel, 625 Mount Auburn
St., Cambridge, Mass. 02138; (800) 955-1925.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Country Walkers  &LR; in Waterbury, Vt., was created in 1990 by Bob
and Cindy Maynard, who earlier operated Vermont Country Cyclers and
sold it. The company's Valleys of Central Vermont, six days of
walking and a half-day of horseback riding, has openings through
September and October; five nights in inns in Stowe and Waitsfield
and all meals, but not air fare, will cost $1,425 for one of two
people in a room.
</P>
<P>
   King Arthur's Cornwall, a six-night coastal walking tour in
Penzance, Land's End, Mousehole and St. Ives, has openings on July
19 and Aug. 16 departures. The average walk, Maynard says, is six
to eight miles a day, but there are shorter options. The cost,
without air fare, is $2,050 for one of two in a room; it includes
all breakfasts and all but one dinner. Country Walkers, Post Office
Box 180, Waterbury, Vt. 05676; (800) 464-9255; Web site:
www.countrywalkers.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
