<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS SHOW THEIR LONG-TERM STAMINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: It's impossible to say where the stock market is going
in its currently pixilated state, but investors can at least take
heart from the long view.
</P>
<P>
   As a study updated recently for Market Logic shows, stocks
outperformed other investments spectacularly from 1871 through the
end of last year. According to the investment newsletter, stocks
provided a 33,770-fold total return. Put another way, $1 invested
in broadly diversified portfolio of U.S. stocks 127 years ago would
have increased in real value to $33,770 by the end of 1997. More
impressively, this is after adjustment for the loss of purchasing
power because of inflation, which caused the general price level to
increase 13 times during the 1871-1997 period.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a dollar invested in Treasury bills would have grown
to only $9.88, and a dollar invested in gold would have declined in
value to only 57 cents after adjusting for storage costs and
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers chose 1871 as the benchmark year because that
was the first year for which a reliable method was available to
measure the total return of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the performance of this theoretical investment in
stocks all the more noteworthy is the dramatic rebounds from
crashes that were required for it to happen. From 1929 to 1932, for
instance, stocks lost 81 percent of their value using the Market
Logic calculation.
</P>
<P>
   While the newsletter doesn't get into the 1930-54 period of
stagnation by the Dow Jones industrial average, the Money Logic
measure does show a remarkable difference in performance between
the small number of Dow Jones industrial average stocks and the
broad universe used for its study. While the Dow Jones industrial
average went nowhere during the quarter century after the Great
Crash, the Market Logic table shows its measure of stock prices
swelling by a 16-fold total return during that period.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, on the other hand, peaked at
381 in September 1929, and didn't return to that level until late
1954. It closed that year at 404, which was only about half that in
terms of real value after adjusting for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stock market reversals during the 1969-74 period,
for which Market Logic shows a 71 percent decline after adjusting
for inflation, the market began its most spectacular sustained
ascent in history. When the Dow Jones industrial average hit its
all-time high last month, it was up 22-fold from the 1974 low,
without any inflation adjustment. Meanwhile, the Market Logic
measure was 15-fold higher after adjusting for purchasing power
lost to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   While the study confirms the perception that T-bills are an
ultra-safe but minimally rewarding haven for investors, the shocker
is how it debunks gold as a refuge for those concerned about
inflation. Conventional wisdom has always assigned gold the role as
a store of value that would protect consumers and investors against
the ravages of rising price levels. Even at gold's peak price of
nearly two decades ago, it only outperformed stocks momentarily on
the long continuum of 127 years. Then it fell back to Earth with a
resounding thud.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market continues to slide, this discussion probably
isn't much solace for those whose paper profits are shrinking.
Looking on the bright side, however, keep in mind that if you live
long enough, your fortunes are likely to turn out even better than
you ever imagined in your wildest dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
