<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEATHS OF THE CASINOS' NEON FLAMINGOS WILL USHER IN BLEAK
TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Fast-forward, now, into the imaginary future.
</P>
<P>
   The state's high court has long ago ruled that boats in puddles
are not to be confused with boats upon rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The voters, contrary creatures, have refused to rewrite the law
to suit the gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   And the casino operators _ with appeals exhausted and no
politicians left to buy _ have packed up and traveled on to mulct
the populace of some other municipality.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind are several grotesque edifices which, like the
Hoover Dam or the pyramids of Giza, are visible from space. By any
reasonable standard, they are among the most unsightly
constructions ever erected by the hand of man.
</P>
<P>
   Now a mournful wind keens through the spokes of the false paddle
wheels and eddies around the flaking pink heads of the gigantic
flamingos that tower over the valley of the river.
</P>
<P>
   The asphalt acreages of the parking lots have been turned into
vast open-air flea markets like those seen on the outskirts of
cities in Russia, where commerce in counterfeit icons and antique
samovars has replaced the real economy.
</P>
<P>
   The abandoned structures themselves are occupied by the
homeless, who break up the furnishings for sticks to fuel their
fires and defend themselves from the creeping things that inhabit
any neglected place.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the city, weaned from the teat of the gaming industry,
has sunk into a lamentable state. The treasury is empty. Public
services are a memory.
</P>
<P>
   There no longer is any hope of patching potholes, collecting
trash, putting down insurrections, holding parades or treating the
water supply. Angry gangs prowl the street, demanding to know why
we have sunk to 227th place in the ranking of most-livable cities.
</P>
<P>
   In this hour of distress, a little clutch of community leaders
has assembled on the bluff above the river.
</P>
<P>
   Spread below them is a dreadful panorama _ those enormous
cartoon boat-buildings, unsuitable for any known use, each one
surrounded by its murky pond.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders stare down sadly at the ruin of their hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to be done?'' groans one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tear them down,'' says another.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're huge, and there's no money for it. We'd have to
close the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Close them then! Life is choices.''
</P>
<P>
   They are agreed. Whatever the cost, every reminder of the bad
dream must somehow be erased.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the moats?'' someone else asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fill them in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How? Our machines are all broken. The city workers haven't
been paid in weeks. We're insoluble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Insolvent,'' someone corrects him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   A profound silence comes over the group _ the silence of
bottomless, soul-searing despair. The light of civilization, at
this bend of the river, is about to flicker out.
</P>
<P>
   The late sun reflects from the moats strung out one after
another along the valley, and turns their surfaces to copper.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at those pools, one of the city fathers experiences a
sudden epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have it!'' he cries out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catfish! We'll start a catfish farm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catfish!'' shout the others. ``Merciful providence, YES!
Catfish!''
</P>
<P>
   From the whoop of joy they send up, you'd almost think they've
drawn a fourth ace.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard work, raising catfish, and not nearly as glamorous as
gambling parlors. But it's a way back, and a more dependable
enterprise than blackjack or roulette.
</P>
<P>
   So, almost by a whisker you might say, the city is delivered
from ruin after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
