<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-SCHOOL-SEX-COX &UR;      06-22 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SCHOOL-SEX-COX </SLUG>
   940&AMP;ADD  UNINFORMED SCHOOLS NOT LIABLE
FOR TEACHER SEX HARASSMENT, COURT SAYS
 &HT;     Not for Austin.
 &HT;     By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former Texas high school student, whose teacher
drew her into a sexual affair, cannot collect damages from the
school district because none of the teacher's supervisors knew
about the sexual harassment, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 ruling gives all school districts new protection from
harassment claims by students. Harassment victims will now have to
show that they complained to a supervisor with authority to punish
the harasser and that the supervisor refused to take action after
receiving the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   School officials hailed the decision as insurance against the
actions of renegade teachers whose conduct cannot be predicted or
controlled by officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court properly refused to hold school districts
liable for the concealed criminal conduct of abusive employees,''
said Wallace B. Jefferson, a San Antonio lawyer who represented the
Lago Vista school district near Austin, Texas, which was sued in
this case. ``Most school districts would be financially devastated
by jury verdicts holding them liable for sexual harassment which
they could not have prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was denounced by women's groups and the ex-student's
lawyer as a setback for the most vulnerable of harassment victims _
underage students for whom teachers are among the most trusted
authority figures.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ``will allow school districts to cultivate
ignorance of their teachers' wrongdoing and then to assert that
ignorance as a complete defense to any litigation,'' said the
ex-student's lawyer, Terry Weldon of Austin.``This unfairly places
all the burden on students who are, in most cases, immature and
emotionally vulnerable to teachers who exploit their position of
trust and power.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing the majority opinion,
acknowledged that ``harassment unfortunately is an all-too-common
aspect of the educational experience. No one questions that a
student suffers extraordinary harm when subjected to sexual
harassment and abuse by a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue in this case, however, is whether the independent
misconduct of a teacher is attributable to the school district that
employs him,'' O'Connor wrote. The majority ruled that the district
is not liable unless a district official refused to act on a
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Four justices, led by Justice John Paul Stevens, said the
majority decision ``ranks protection of the school district's purse
above the protection of immature high school students.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority, Stevens said, ignored the intent of federal
anti-discrimination law ``to induce school boards to adopt and
enforce practices that will minimize the danger that vulnerable
students will be exposed to such odious behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule that the Court has crafted (with Monday's decision)
creates the opposite incentive,'' Stevens wrote. ``Indeed, the rule
that the Court adopts would preclude a damages remedy even if every
teacher at the school knew about the harassment but did not have
`authority to institute corrective measures on the district's
behalf.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Weldon said the Supreme Court's ruling ``amounts to the
closing of the courthouse door'' for a case that began in 1992,
when Lago Vista high-school teacher Frank Waldrop initiated an
affair with student Alida Star Gebser, who was then 14. (The Cox
News Service does not typically name victims of sexual crimes, but
Gebser's attorney said she gave permission to have her name used in
the Supreme Court case and in news reports.) Gebser, now a student
at the University of Texas, was not granting interviews on Weldon's
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had prepared her for bad news,'' he said. ``She was
disappointed but not embittered. She's a survivor kind of kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebser told no one of her affair with Waldrop until after the
two were caught by Lago Vista police in a park in January 1993.
Waldrop was arrested, quit his teaching job and later pleaded
guilty to sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   Gebser later filed suit against the school district, seeking
damages for Waldrop's sexual harassment under Title IX of the
federal education code, which prohibits sexual discrimination by
schools that receive federal money. Courts have long considered
sexual harassment as a form of sexual discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Lago Vista school district, with about 800 students in all
grades, receives federal money totaling less than $20,000 a year.
Part of the student's lawsuit alleged that the district had failed
to follow a section of Title IX that requires schools to establish
and distribute policies for complaints about sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The student's effort to hold the district liable for Waldrop's
conduct was rejected first by U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks of
Austin, then by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans. In an earlier case involving a teacher's molestation of a
second-grade student during class, the appeals court set the
standard for schools' liability for sexual harassment. In that
case, the student's parents had complained to another teacher, not
a supervisor, which was deemed insufficient by the appeals court.
The court threw out a $1.4 million damage award to the parents,
saying they should have told a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court adopted the 5th Circuit's reasoning in the
Lago Vista case, saying that school officials with power to act on
a sexual-harassment complaint must know of _ and reject _ the
complaint before a victim can pursue damages.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said Congress created a similar standard to
govern the cutoff of federal aid when a school is suspected of
practicing discrimination covered by Title IX. Officials must be
notified and given a chance to correct the conduct before aid is
ended, O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a general matter, it does not appear that Congress
contemplated unlimited recovery in damages against a funding
recipient where the recipient is unaware of discrimination in its
programs,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Lago Vista and other school districts had raised the possibility
of crippling damage awards _ which would have to be paid by
taxpayers _ in urging the court to rule as it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is a common-sense decision,'' said Gwendolyn
Gregory, counsel to the National Association of School Boards. The
teacher's affair was ``a terrible thing to have happened, but to
have to pay out of the public coffers is not what Title IX was
designed for,'' Gregory said. ``Title IX was designed to stop
discrimination, not bankrupt school districts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court said harassment victims could continue to use
state laws to pursue claims against school, but Texas ``doesn't
have any protection on the state level for girls and young women
who are sexually harassed in their schools,'' said Jeanne
Sommerfeld, president of the Texas chapter of the National
Organization for Women.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas NOW chapter plans to seek legislation that would
create a statute similar to Title IX in Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking Gov. (George W.) Bush and all candidates to
reject this ill-conceived policy and ensure that rights of students
in Texas rank higher than the purses of school districts,''
Sommerfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
