<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICA-CONVENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOCATIONAL INDUSTRIAL CLUBS OF AMERICA MEETING IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Who will build the house your children will
someday buy? And who will fix the plumbing when it springs a leak?
</P>
<P>
   Those 21st century workers could very well be alumni of the
Vocational Industrial Clubs of America.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12,000 members and associates of the quarter-million
strong job training and leadership organization convene in Kansas
City this week for its 34th annual conference and Skills USA
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   This is the event's fifth consecutive year at Bartle Hall.
National champions will be selected in 66 competitions, in skills
such as auto collision repair, carpentry, cosmetology, public
speaking, dental assisting, commercial photography and computer
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the olympics of everyday life. The public is invited to
watch the contests all day Thursday at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   Forty high school and post-secondary students from Missouri and
Kansas are among this year's national finalists, up from 23 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters and electricians union members are donating hundreds
of hours to help set up Bartle Hall. The city slashed Bartle's
rental rates by 30 percent, and most hotels offered discounts.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual who's who among Kansas City's top corporations makes
up a VICA advisory panel to help fund the games each year to the
tune of around $200,000 in grants.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sound investment. The VICA event draws a greater
percentage of adults than the FFA does, including 1,000 contest
judges, and those attending are projected to spend around $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Kansas City's convention industry attracts 14 million
visitors a year with a combined pocketbook effect of $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One of this year's local VICA contestants is Yesenia Felix, a
graduating senior this year from Kansas City's Metro Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old is also VICA's 1998 Missouri champion in the
commercial sewing division. After college she hopes for a career in
the fashion design industry.
</P>
<P>
   Felix made her own prom dress this year _ and her younger
sister's. Her specialty, she said, is ``nice dresses, sun
dresses...girl stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into it when I was little,'' she said. ``My mom always
made my clothes and my sister's clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   VICA has encouraged that childhood interest. ``Winning awards,''
she said, ``is good for my self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   A positive attitude and a solid work ethic are what VICA
emphasizes to its 239,000 members, said Thomas H. Holdsworth,
director of VICA's post-secondary programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to an American businessman, they will tell you
that is a significant concern,'' especially in today's tight labor
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses these days also are hiring more skilled workers than
ever before. Holdsworth cited a recent study by the U.S. Department
of Labor that found the number of professionals in the U.S. labor
force had remained unchanged since the 1950s, around 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But skilled and unskilled workers have changed demographic
places in those four decades. Skilled workers now fill more than 60
percent of all American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has not changed, however, is Americans'
unrelenting ``second-class citizen'' perception of those who work
mainly with their hands, Holdsworth said. And VICA is working hard
to change that perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earning power (of skilled jobs) is definitely there,'' he
said, and many trades pay $50,000 a year and more to experienced
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's lathe worker, for instance, must be computer-literate.
The same is true for auto mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   College graduates now make up the fastest-growing group of
junior college and trade-school enrollees, Holdsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are returning home to live with their parents and
getting the same jobs in the retail industry that they could have
had right out of high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor market is crying for young, skilled workers, said Gary
Kemp, executive secretary and business manager for the Greater
Kansas City Building and Construction Trade Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We push our children to go to college and come away with more
professional skills,'' Kemp said. ``But sometimes we forget about
the skills that are necessary for everyday life. It would be hard
to imagine life without plumbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, also a member of a VICA advisory committee of local
corporations and support groups, said: ``The exciting thing about
this (Skills USA) is that you'll see young people who are the very
best in the country at what they've been learning.''
</P>
<P>
   The championship rounds Thursday will be from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
on the exhibit floor at Bartle Hall. Contestants, who are state
high school and college champions, will compete against each other
and the clock in skills contests _ such as cooking a gourmet meal,
building sections of homes according to blueprints and manicuring
nails.
</P>
<P>
   Winners will receive gold, silver and bronze medals _ plus
scholarships, textbooks, cash prizes and ``tools of the trade''
merchandise. Companies at the conference will recruit the winners
as if they were top athletes.
</P>
<P>
   VICA convention participants will attend seminars and specialty
meetings, take field trips to businesses and hear from keynote
speakers such as U.S. astronaut Jerry Linenger, 1996 Miss America
Shawntel Smith and Joseph Galli, president of DeWalt Industrial
Power Tool Co., a main corporate sponsor of VICA.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's school-to-work program, a joint effort
of the U.S. Labor and Education departments, will have its annual
meeting here this week for 400 participants at Harrah's North
Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 U.S. companies support VICA with year-round
assistance, including training and equipment. The list of sponsors
reads like a page from the Fortune 500 _ General Motors Corp., E.I.
DuPont Co., Sprint Corp., John Deere Co., Aluminum Company of
America and J.C. Penney Co. Inc. among them.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have lent or donated more than $15 million worth
of equipment and materials for this year's competition. That tally
includes 654 computers, 10,000 bricks, 25,000 pounds of mortar, 100
stoves and 50 trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing companies at the local level include Gateway, US
Rentals, Rich Mix Products Inc., Miller Material Co., and Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Pinnell, sales representative for US Rentals, called the
company's contribution a logical investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the long-term good of the industry you need to keep these
kids in the business and give them opportunities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
