<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERICHO-CASINO-HNS &LR;      06-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERICHO-CASINO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
WORLD'S OLDEST CITY WILL BECOME NEWEST GAMBLING MECCA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By DEBORAH HORAN &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JERICHO, West Bank _ The card tables are set, the slot machines
ready and dozens of young men and women are learning how to play
poker, roulette and blackjack in snappy Las Vegas style.
</P>
<P>
   With cash from private international investors, Palestinians are
about to turn the world's oldest city into the Middle East's newest
gambling destination, say representatives of an Austrian-based
casino company that has set up shop in Jericho to train croupiers,
bouncers and security guards.
</P>
<P>
   By fall, the luxury Oasis Casino, now a four-story unfinished
colossus at the edge of this sleepy West Bank town, will be
operational.
</P>
<P>
   Planners hope it will attract high rollers from Israel, Egypt,
Jordan and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, the casino will be flanked by two or three five-star
hotels and surrounded by a three-square mile compound complete with
swimming pools, an entertainment center, tennis courts and golf
course. Just in time, the promoters note, for the millennium
celebrations when more than 2 million tourists are expected to
descend on the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   The $150 million project likely will bring in millions of
dollars in tourism and gambling revenues to the Palestinian
Authority's cash-strapped government. That should help to free it
from dependence on foreign donors, who have pitched in more than $1
billion since it was established in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of tourists would be a boon to the Palestinians'
sagging economy, which has been hit hard by repeated
Israeli-imposed security closures that severely hamper the movement
of Palestinian goods and people.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea has struck a nerve with many in this conservative
biblical town. Islamic leaders condemn the casino as ``haram,''
forbidden by Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling is against God and against our religion,'' said
Sheikh Ismail Jamal, the mufti, or high religious leader, of
Jericho.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want hotels and gardens and tourists,'' he said. ``We want
people to come to Jericho to visit. But we don't want gambling. It
leads to other crimes _ to corruption and adultery and drinking
alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Casino planners seem to be considering that sentiment. No signs
have been posted at the site to announce the coming attraction,
gruff foremen try to keep Palestinian workers from talking to
passers-by and croupiers-in-training are taught how to deal cards
and spin roulette wheels at a local restaurant with the curtains
tightly drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Palestinian Authority officials are keeping tight
control over information about the project by refusing to name
investors or to estimate the amount of gambling revenues they
expect to receive. Nor will they say whether the authority will put
up any of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Local religious leaders have not been accurately informed.
Palestinian officials have told Sheikh Jamal that the site would
house only a hotel and golf course. There was no mention of the
casino.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal says he will preach against the casino _ but nothing else,
a stance echoed by leaders of the militant Muslim Hamas
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Started at the end of last year, the casino is by far the most
ambitious attempt by Palestinians to woo tourists _ and Israelis _
to areas under their control without bringing them too deeply into
Palestinian-held territory, where many Israelis are afraid to go.
The site is only 200 yards from the nearest Israeli checkpoint and
will extend south to the Dead Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no problem going into the area because the whole
resort is right at the entrance to Jericho,'' said Dana Tadmor, a
spokeswoman for Gitam Porter Novelli, a public relations firm hired
by Casinos Austria International, Ltd., the company managing the
casino and training its staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no access problem, nobody should hesitate in getting
there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis are likely to form the base of the casino's clientele.
Until Turkey banned gambling in February, about 250,000 Israelis
visited annually, spending $200 million each year. Many traveled on
four-day tours set up for casino visits.
</P>
<P>
   The work on the casino already has boosted the Palestinian
economy. Every day workers from the Akabat Jaber refugee camp, a
crumbling and half-abandoned group of rose-colored mud houses,
traipse across the main street to the casino site. Planners say the
casino, hotels and manicured grounds eventually will employ 1,200
Palestinians and 400 international workers.
</P>
<P>
   The job creation is crucial to an economy in which one-fifth of
the population lives on less than $2.50 a day and unemployment has
hovered around 30 percent for years, according to U.S.
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat, who spoke here last week
about what he termed the Palestinians' ``dire'' economic situation.
</P>
<P>
   The hardship has put the preachers in difficult straits. Most
say Palestinians can work to build the casino but not enter it to
gamble.
</P>
<P>
   And, as a gesture to Hamas and other conservative elements,
Palestinian officials may prevent their countrymen from entering
the casino, as is the practice at gambling sites in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   At the casino site, young Palestinian workers draped in the
black-and-white checkered ``kefiya'' worn by Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, say they do not like the idea of bringing gambling
so close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for Jericho,'' said Samir Hussein, a 20-year-old from
the Akabat Jaber camp. ``It will bring bad things, like drinking
alcohol. It's forbidden for us. It's for foreigners only.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one said he would role the dice if he could. ``If I had the
money I would play,'' Khalil Muhammad, 19, said with a grin.
``Naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxxxxxxx END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
