<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-RIGHTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUE OF TRIBAL FISHING RIGHTS DIVIDES WHITE COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEABECK, Wash. _ Among white fisherman and waterfront landowners
in Washington, grumbling about the special perks of American Indian
heritage comes as regularly as the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Why, goes the usual beef, should a tribal identification card
give one American the first shot at harvesting salmon? Why should
Indians have the right to pick the oysters and dig the clams from
somebody else's beach?
</P>
<P>
   Because, say Bill and Judy Matchett, a deal is a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Matchetts don't have an ounce of Indian blood. They do own
about 400 feet of waterfront on Hood Canal.
</P>
<P>
   But they accept that the rocky beach is not entirely theirs.
</P>
<P>
   They refer to an 1855 treaty that handed over great areas of
Indian land in western Washington to incoming white settlers. In
return, the treaty said, ``the right of taking fish at usual and
accustomed grounds and stations is further secured to said Indians,
in common with all citizens of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In common'' has been interpreted to mean half for Indians,
half for everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   That includes half the salmon in Puget Sound, half the crabs and
shrimp on the bottom of Hood Canal, half the oysters and clams on
the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court early this year clarified that the
treaty applied to Washington tidelands, the part of a beach between
high and low tides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not special rights; it's treaty rights,'' said Bill
Matchett. ``We've considered ourselves friends of the tribes and
sympathetic to them for years. We couldn't feel that way and then
deny them what was legally theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   They went to the Point No Point Treaty Council, a coalition of
four tribes, and worked out a contract that left it to the tribes
to determine how many shellfish could be plucked from the Matchett
tideland.
</P>
<P>
   It requires tribal members to notify the Matchetts a month in
advance of their harvest and to arrive by water and by daylight.
The Matchetts, in turn, are to log how many clams or oysters they
take.
</P>
<P>
   In practice the beach is too small for commercial harvesting,
and the Matchetts take too few shellfish to bother keeping track.
So far, three tribal members have made a single, 90-minute visit to
take clams for a ceremonial dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to set an example,'' Matchett said.
</P>
<P>
   So far they are alone among Washington's 60,000 shoreline
property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our beach is our front yard. We pay taxes on the beach. We
have deed to them, you know, the rights to them,'' said Art Price,
a retired civil engineer on Marrowstone Island. ``Having people
wandering on your beach and taking your clams is like having people
take half of your vegetable garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Lindsay, executive director of United Property Owners of
Washington, said the treaties were made by the federal government
but affected only a small minority of Americans, those with
shoreline tracts in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``All U.S. citizens ought to bear whatever treaty burdens there
are,'' Lindsay said. ``All the rest of you in Oregon and California
and Montana and Kansas don't bear this burden.''
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety builds as area catches of all seafood have dropped
significantly from overfishing and growing pollution _ making
fishing rights ever more precious.
</P>
<P>
   Across Hood Canal from the Matchetts' place, hard at the edge of
Dabob Bay, 40-year-old Victor Tuson of the Jamestown S'Klallam
tribe was poking holes in cans of Puss 'n Boots Supreme cat food in
a tiny boat overflowing with wire baskets. The punctured cans go
into the baskets as bait for spotted shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Tuson is new to shrimping. He and his half brother, Butch
Williams, bought two old and small boats after recent court rulings
made clear that members of certain tribes enjoyed rights to the
waterway's bounty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It beats punching a time clock, and it's one of those rare
things these days where the harder you work, the more money you can
make,'' said Williams. ``And it's something I can take from my
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   State fisheries officials designate certain days for Indian
fishing, and Hood Canal is dotted with a few dozen boats. Anybody
dropping shrimp pots or crab pots must be ready to flash tribal ID
cards when tribal ``fish cop'' Doug Lux floats by.
</P>
<P>
   Other days are open to anyone, but with thousands of sportsmen,
too few shellfish are left to support non-Indian commercial
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore and unable to join in the weekend's Indian-only
shrimping, 67-year-old Ken Harris is one angry white man. He
suspects that the tribes take more than their half and suggests
that something is wrong with the treaties and their two-tier
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given the Indians super rights,'' Harris said. ``To do
that, they've taken away from all us natives who have lived here
our entire lives.''
</P>
<P>
   His white neighbors tend to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's people who have been around here all these years who
you never knew were Indians until the court made these decisions,''
said Julie McClanahan, who has lived on the waterfront near
Quilcene since 1952. ``It really put a strain on old friendships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
