<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUMP-DISPUTE-KAN &LR;      06-22 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUMP-DISPUTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMP DISPUTE POINTS TO CONFUSION OVER LAND OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE ANDES, S.D. _ It might smell like a Dumpster and look like
your teen-ager's room on steroids, but to the people who fought the
Yankton Sioux to heap garbage here, this trash pit is a thing of
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're mighty proud of this landfill,'' said Jack Soulek,
Charles Mix County commissioner. ``It was a long time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the Lake Andes landfill solve the trash-disposal
problems of four counties, but for its champions, the dump also
represents a limit to American Indian authority.
</P>
<P>
   The landfill spat began as another not-in-my-back-yard argument.
But the court rulings it generated held much wider ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, in fact, the case allowed the Sioux to seize domain
over thousands of acres the tribe had sold to the federal
government more than a century before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly a landfill case blew up into this huge issue of who
had jurisdiction in all these places, the tribe or the county,''
said Ken Cotton, the lawyer who represented the trash district.
``It was a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process the authority of police departments was thrown
into question, and minor crimes such as burglary became the
business of the FBI. The dispute stirred up new resentment between
the Sioux and their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe says its intentions were misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want direct control over tribal members,'' said Robert
Cournoyer, vice chairman of the tribe. ``We don't want anything
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Identifying Indian land here is not as simple as it may sound.
The reservation's crazy-quilt boundaries come from an 1858 treaty,
a federal law passed in 1894, and thousands of subsequent and small
private transactions.
</P>
<P>
   There is land held in trust for Indians by the federal
government, land ceded by the tribes through treaties, land
allotted to individual Indian families and allotted land that ended
up being sold to white people.
</P>
<P>
   And marking where Indian country starts and stops is vitally
important, because tribal self-rule is tied inexorably to the land.
</P>
<P>
   The definition of Indian land became critical in fall 1992, when
a new trash district chose for its dump a few agricultural acres
about a mile and a half west of Lake Andes.
</P>
<P>
   Sioux leaders began objecting the following summer, saying the
landfill design needed to add a plastic liner. That would boost the
cost almost $2 million, and the trash district balked.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the tribe sued in federal court, contending that the
landfill site was under control of the tribe and, as such, subject
to federal environmental regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe noted its 1858 treaty with the U.S. government that
exchanged 11 million acres for domain over the 430,000-acre
reservation. But a deal clinched with the 1894 law paid the tribe
$600,000 for almost half the reservation _ land including the
landfill site that was ceded to the government and, in turn, sold
to white settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remaining 230,000 acres of Indian land allotted to
members of the tribe also was, over time, sold to non-Indians.
</P>
<P>
   A federal district judge ruled in favor of the tribe in 1995,
saying that although the Sioux ceded the land in 1894, they did not
surrender authority over it, because of the expansive language of
the treaties. The appeals court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight the issue became more than a dump liner.
Generations-old patterns of law enforcement across the checkerboard
of the reservation were upset.
</P>
<P>
   Whites complained that between the tribal police and a few FBI
agents stationed in Sioux Falls, many crimes like burglary and
vandalism passed without serious investigation. The tribe, in turn,
responded that it was more a perception than a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fear factor here,'' Cournoyer said. ``People don't
understand the tribe, and they tend to fear Native Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion followed. In one case two men murdered a 16-year-old
on a road that marked a border between land that was once in the
reservation and land that never was. Because one killer claimed
Indian heritage, he went through the federal judicial system and,
partly because he cooperated with prosecutors, received a 10-year
sentence. The other went through state courts and received a
40-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you'll have the lines of jurisdiction running right
through someone's home,'' said Matthew Gaffey, the Charles Mix
County state's attorney. ``It gets complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   In January the U.S. Supreme Court reversed the lower court
rulings, clearing the way for the landfill to open on the land the
tribe ceded in 1894. That put the Charles Mix Sheriff's Department
back in charge of its old territory.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' 9-0 ruling, however, did not address the question
of the allotted land sold to whites by individual Sioux families
years after the last treaty. The tribe filed another lawsuit in
March, leaving the issue of jurisdiction over that territory still
contested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stake the ground that's ours,'' said Cournoyer.
``We have to make a stand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
