<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Arm your imagination
 &HT;    for trek to Risk Level 3
 &HT;    By MIchael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shots in the arm were no problem. I'm a big boy. And the
only thing that troubled me about the malaria pill was the thought
of ravenous mosquitos and tsetse flies buzzing around the netting
at night. I'm a light sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   Then I got to reading a little booklet called Travel Health
Planner. ``In a perfect world,'' it said, ``travelers wouldn't need
to worry about becoming targets of crime.'' Whenever I read the
words ``in a perfect world,'' I prepare for its imperfections.
</P>
<P>
   My concentration clicked on and I started reading more
selectively, my eyes fastening on the ominous. There were
advisories about hepatitis and lockjaw _ that's what the shots were
for. It advised taking an insect repellent containing something
called DEET.
</P>
<P>
   I went to the pharmacy and bought the strongest stuff it had, a
cream used by the Special Forces. It's the closest I've ever been
to the military.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Travel Health Planner, I was given a printout of
information from the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent crime as well as petty crime is prevalent,'' it said.
``Armed assaults and carjackings take place. ... Criminals often
become violent quickly. ... Frequently, victims who argue with
assailants or refuse to give up their valuables are shot.''
</P>
<P>
   I go where they tell me to go, so I'm packing for a trip to
Central America, although it rather sounds like metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference between a tourist and a real traveler, and
I know which one I am. Show me your ruins. Where's your best
restaurant?
</P>
<P>
   There's also a difference between a routine and a rut. A routine
is not always a bad thing. It lets you know where you'll be from
day to day. When I wake up I want to know the paper will be on the
drive and the coffee will be in the cup.
</P>
<P>
   I should be embarrassed, but am not. One of my heroes, the late
V.S. Pritchett, would have disowned me, but the British are a
different breed. Post a Brit to a remote fastness in the Khyber
Pass, and he'll be rattling around on the edge of cliffs in a car
with bad tires. Within a fortnight he's sending home dispatches on
the cuisine and the local women, rifle shots ricocheting in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not refuse to drink the water,'' Pritchett once wrote.
``I do not see bacteria everywhere. I do not suspect everyone who
speaks a foreign language of being a thief. I do not scream that I
cannot get a good steak in Morocco ... a decent haggis in Naples or
an edible chop suey on Ascension Island.''
</P>
<P>
   That may have been fine for Pritchett, who traipsed all over the
globe and somehow lived to be 96. But I've got it here in black and
white from the U.S. government: Don't drink the water. Don't rinse
your toothbrush in tap water. Don't open your mouth in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know that I'm going to shower at all.
</P>
<P>
   For three days somebody might just have to live with me the way
I am. Or I'll sponge off, like my kids want to do when they're told
to get in the bath.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, don't use scented soap _ the insects will find you
like a heat-seeking missile. Maybe they need a taste of Tilex.
</P>
<P>
   I lived in Miami for eight years and spent a little time in the
Caribbean. But I'm not a tropical kind of guy. If I'm going
anywhere remote, I'm comforted by the sight of snow.
</P>
<P>
   In my Travel Health Planner, a map divides the world into shades
of white, gray and black. The white areas are Risk Level 1, meaning
``low risk from food, water and insects.'' The gray areas are Risk
Level 2 and the black areas, Risk Level 3.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't surprise me that the white areas are all of North
America, Australia and New Zealand and most of Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Where I'm going is one of the black areas.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the natives ``are armed,'' the State Department's
printout frankly tells me, ``and shootouts are not uncommon.''
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not even allowed to pack a firearm for self-defense. A
lot of good the Second Amendment is going to do me there.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
