<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are Women looking up to ``Ally McBeal'' or ``Xena: Warrior
Princess''
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women have come a long way, baby, but have they come far enough?
Time ($2.95) reporter Ginia Bellafante writes that the 1970s
feminism of Gloria Steinem and Betty Friedan has been supplanted by
the feminism of ``Ally McBeal''. Instead of crusading for social
change, equal pay and better day care, Bellafante says, today's
young feminists are more concerned with their bodies and their sex
lives. According to a Time/CNN poll, women are split on whether
feminism is relevant still. Some say feminism is dead because the
battle has been won.
</P>
<P>
   So what does this mean for the next generation of young women?
In a companion story, Time's Nadya Labi looks at girl power and the
marketing of feminism to teens and preteens. The Spice Girls may be
fading, but they are being replaced as role models by empowered
``grrrls'' such as ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'', ``Xena: Warrior
Princess'', and Disney's Chinese heroine Mulan. And, on a promising
note, a record 2.5 million girls are competing on high school
sports teams, compared with 300,000 in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO BEIJING: As President Clinton heads for China and a
summit with President Jiang Zemin, Newsweek ($2.95) explores the
changes that have taken place since the Tiananmen massacre. In an
essay, Clinton explains why he's going to China _ ``America's
future will not be secure if Asia's is in doubt'' _ and what he
hopes to accomplish. One of the more interesting articles in the
package is Jonathan Alter's report on the Chinese society.
Communism is dead, he writes, and crony capitalism lives. China is
now a country of cell phones and pagers, McDonald's and bowling
alleys.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.95) also looks at the China summit
with a feature on Shanghai. White House officials hope to showcase
the Westernization of Shanghai as a way of de-demonizing China in
the minds of Americans. But, says magazine correspondent Steven
Butler, in the midst of an economic boom millions are unemployed
and destitute.
</P>
<P>
   SANDERS ON SHANDLING: ``Narcissism was our first bond,''
comedian Garry Shandling says in an Esquire ($3) essay about alter
ego Larry Sanders. Elsewhere in the issue, Ron Suskind interviews
Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas about obstacles that face
minority youths today and how they can be overcome. Also of note:
Restaurant critic John Mariani rates the nation's best cities for
dining out, eliminating New York for being too obvious. The best?
San Francisco. Runners-up are Atlanta, Chicago, New Orleans, Los
Angeles, Washington, Miami, Seattle, Philadelphia, Dallas, Boston
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S ENTERTAINMENT: People ($2.79) focuses on Christina
Onassis' 13-year-old daughter, Athina, and the battle for the
family fortune. Athina's father, Thierry Roussel, has accused his
fellow trustees of plotting to kidnap his daughter. The Greeks
claim that the Israeli commandos they hired to watch Roussel were
simply checking on Athina's safety. Meanwhile, the teenager will
inherit $600 million when she turns 18. ... In an article that
makes us wonder if some magazines have full-time ``list'' editors,
Entertainment Weekly ($3.50) lists the 100 Most Creative People in
Entertainment. On the ``It List'' are Mike Myers, Cameron Diaz,
Christina Ricci, Madonna, Julie Taymor and CD-ROM's ``Tomb Raider''
heroine Lara Croft. Oh, and Taco Bell's talking Chihuahua, Gidget.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK AND WHITE ISSUE: There are more than 300,000 interracial
married couples in the United States today, according to Essence
($2.75), but there are still problems when a black man marries a
white woman. ``We're treated as if we're traitors in somebody's
grand scheme of things,'' writes New York Times reporter Garry
Pierre-Pierre, who is married to a white woman. ``I'm nobody's
traitor. I simply followed my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
