<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Record company hoping that Cameroonian artist will be big in
U.S.
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   World Cup soccer and European hits are factors Epic Records
hopes will help make the voice of Cameroonian artist Wes Madiko and
his album familiar in North America.
</P>
<P>
   His soccer-related single ``Midiwa Bol'' (``I Love Football'')
has received exposure because of the current fascination with the
sport, while another single, the dance-pop tune``Alane,'' has
European sales of 3 million. Both will appear on Madiko's album,
``Walenga,'' a 10-track release that combines traditional Bantu
stories with high-tech music and has sales of about 300,000 copies
in France alone. It also contains the radio-friendly tune ``We
Don't Need No War,'' a duet with American singer Laurnea.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Hav Plenty'' soundtrack (Sony). Grade: B+.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``La Femme Nikita: Music From the Television Series''
(Elektra). Morphine, DJ Krush, Depeche Mode among contributors.
</P>
<P>
   -- Queen Latifah, ``Order in the Court'' (Motown). Grade: B-.
</P>
<P>
   -- Van Morrison, ``The Philosopher's Stone'' (Polydor). Grade:
A.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mulan'' soundtrack. Features ``True to Your Heart'' by
98(degrees) and Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   -- Brian Wilson, ``Imagination'' (Giant). Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The X-Files: The Album'' compilation. Includes cuts by
Sarah McLachlan, Noel Gallagher, Sting with Aswad. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
