u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENJOBS-COX     06-22 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENJOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take this job and love it
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Sandi Turner dreams about working at Six Flags Over
Georgia. ``You have to be 16 to work the rides,'' says the
14-year-old. ``But I could walk around and sell cotton candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another teen, Jon Elder, wants a job at HiFi Buys because, he
grins, ``You get discounts on stereo equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Falk thinks he already has the world's best summer job.
``I'm getting $12.50 an hour working construction for my father's
friend,'' he boasts.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of summer jobs. Many industrious teenagers
have already found employment; others are still checking out the
scene. This year they can afford to be a little picky. Because of
the booming economy, jobs are so plentiful that some employers are
even offering small ``signing bonuses'' to join their work force,
and teen job seekers don't have to settle for minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   But the extra money doesn't make the jobs any more glamorous.
For the most part, they still involve repetitive tasks such as
waiting on fast-food customers, cleaning cages at an animal
hospital or giving safety instructions to thrill-ride patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Sisters Maryann and Melissa Calhoun discuss the summer jobs
they'd never take and the ones they'd love to have.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa: I'd never do fast food.
</P>
<P>
   Maryann: I agree. They make you wear those dorky outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa: They don't treat you that good at theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   Maryann: Plus you lose your hearing working the roller coaster.
(Note to Six Flags lawyers: Don't take this literally. We checked
with an audiologist, who said roller coasters pose no threat to
hearing.)
</P>
<P>
   Melissa: Baby-sitting?
</P>
<P>
   Maryann: Baby-sitting would stink. I'd take them to a neighbor's
house and plop them down.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa: I'd like a desk job.
</P>
<P>
   Maryann: I think they pay you $9.60 an hour to work in the
collection department at Car Max. You read from a script.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa: That sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Johnston and her best friend, Ashley Odom are sitting in
the food court at Town Center mall.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda: She busted her mother's Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley: So I need a job. I gotta make money. I'd work for $6 an
hour. That's decent. But I won't work fast food, and no grocery
stores, either. I'd like to work in an office at Circuit City. A
lot of kids like working at Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, but you have to
wear their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda: Yeah, that sucks.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley: It does. It does.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda: Also, I don't think it's fair that some places say you
have to be 18 to work. I don't see the difference between someone
who's 16 and someone's who's 18 _ I mean, working.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley: I should look in the newspaper for a job. My mom said as
soon as I get a job she'll get me a car. I need that car 'cause we
want to go to Panama City (Fla.) in July to celebrate my birthday.
On July 17th I'll be 17. So I gotta get a job. I just gotta.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Burns, boyfriend Steven Tipton and Steven's brother, Matt,
discuss their summer employment plans.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah: Right now I'm working for Subway for $6 an hour, but I'm
looking for a job at a day care center. I love working with kids.
That's what I want to do as a career, work with children.
</P>
<P>
   Matt: I just quit Wendy's. I was making $6.15 an hour, but
starting Monday I'm working for Mrs. Winner's at $6.60 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Steven (cracking up) : $6.60 at Mrs. Winner's? Way to go, bro'!
</P>
<P>
   At a Dunkin Donuts in Fayetteville, Ga., Abby Snauwaertdrinks a
cappuccino cooler and tells friend Lauren Walker about her summer
job.
</P>
<P>
   Abby: I work at Dixieland Fun Park.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren: I'm going to apply there for a job, too.
</P>
<P>
   Abby: Well, it's great there. My friends come to visit me. I
work there for the money, for when I start driving and I need gas
and stuff, and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   I'm the boat girl for the bumper boats.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, they give you a nickel raise. Hey, I'm
getting there. A nickel is a nickel. I make $5.30 an hour now.
Every three or four weeks I'll cash one of my paychecks. I put the
rest in the bank. I like knowing it's there, you know, my money.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Dodson, 17, just graduated from Riverwood High School and
plans to attend Morehouse College.(Ga.) In past summers, he worked
for several athletic-shoe stores and, during the Olympics, for
Anheuser-Busch. This summer he got a job selling audio equipment at
a Best Buy . With manager Mike Dircks looking on, he talks about
his new job.
</P>
<P>
   Milton: I just couldn't see myself flipping burgers somewhere.
The best summer jobs for kids are usually at music and clothing
stores. You always get a great discount on the merchandise, and
they're fun to work at.
</P>
<P>
   Mike: That's the thing. This is a fun place to work because of
the music and the friendships they make here. I like bringing in
young people because they're not set in their ways. They're willing
to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Milton: And there's the cash. This job is an opportunity to gain
extra funds for college. That's why a lot of kids work, because
once you're out of high school, Mom and Dad say, ``Hey, you're on
your own.''
</P>
<P>
   I like the challenge of it. Every day of my life I get up in the
morning and think, ``What's the best way I can earn money today?''
My mom taught me that. And with the promotions and raises I get
here _ I make $12 an hour now _ I just feel there isn't anything I
can't do here. It's a great summer job.
</P>
<P>
   Mike: I think the best summer job is being a lifeguard at a nude
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Milton: Aha.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Di's right hand
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Hall began working at Lady Di's, a hair, nail and tanning
salon owned by Diane Burdett, shortly after her family moved to
Stockbridge, Ga. in January.
</P>
<P>
   Cox: What do you do at Lady Di's?
</P>
<P>
   Alicia: I help with anything that needs to be done. I run the
tanning beds, help with Diane's chemicals. I'm just like a second
hand for her when I'm here.
</P>
<P>
   Cox: Why do you like it there so much?
</P>
<P>
   Alicia: I've always wanted to work in a beauty salon. But I
don't want to do this forever. I really want to make something out
of my life. I plan on going to college.
</P>
<P>
   Cox: What's the best summer job a teenager can have?
</P>
<P>
   Alicia: Everybody wants to work at the mall. If they're guys,
they want to work at a sports-shoe store. They get discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to work fast food, though. Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise engaged
</P>
<P>
   Kayla Strother, Mary Dawkins, Stephanie Schmit and Jill Giles
talk summer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Kayla: I think I want to be a vet's assistant because I'd love
working with animals. But truthfully, I want the money, not the
job. I think the best summer job would be to work as a professional
gum taster.
</P>
<P>
   Mary: I think the best summer job is being a lifeguard. You sit
there all summer and get a tan. My sister's a lifeguard and she has
the perfect tan. But I work in the nursery at my church, and
everyone says I'm really good with kids, so I get a lot of
baby-sitting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie: I'd baby-sit. Everyone likes being around little
kids. But I don't want anything to interfere with my summer plans.
</P>
<P>
   Jill: Me either. I do color guard in the summer and then spend
two weeks in California with my whole family. I don't have time for
a summer job.
</P>
<P>
   Cat boy
</P>
<P>
   Nick Roeker spent the last two summers working at the Cat Clinic
of Roswell (Ga.) as a volunteer. This summer, he's getting paid,
cleaning cages, sweeping floors, mowing the lawn and doing whatever
else needs to be done. With supervision, he'll even perform minor
medical procedures, such as ear cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Cox: Why do you like working here?
</P>
<P>
   Nick: Some of my friends are working at McDonald's, but I
couldn't do it. I'd rather work with the cats.
</P>
<P>
   (To a black and white kitten playing with his shoe: ``What are
you doing down there?'' He picks her up. ``You're so adorable.'')
</P>
<P>
   The first summer I worked here I was walking by a cage and a
gray calico swatted me. I had to get seven stiches in my ear.
</P>
<P>
   Cox: So it's dangerous working here?
</P>
<P>
   Nick, laughing: No, it's fun. There's always something going on
and it's always interesting. I think I may want to become a vet
some day, so this is great.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
