<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER23-COX     06-22 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Split personality accused of murder: Is the body held
accountable?
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Dateline'' (10 p.m. EDT on NBC) departs from its
usual format to focus on one story _ and it's a strange one.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Dennis Murphy's watchably Springer-esque ``Alter Ego''
tries to explore the deepest recesses of one criminal's mind. And,
in a mindboggling twist, one of the sexual assault victims of that
criminal is also his staunchest defender.
</P>
<P>
   In spring 1994, Bill Greene attacked Maryalyce Stamatiou in his
Everett, Wa., apartment. She immediately reported the crime, but
now says Greene, who's appealing a life term without parole, wasn't
the one responsible. She says the real culprit was Tyrone.
</P>
<P>
   Stamatiou is Greene's therapist. Who's Tyrone? One of Greene's
alleged 23 personalities.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Since Greene's assault of Stamatiou, the prisoner
has married a woman whom he told he has been diagnosed with
multiple personalities _ including trash-talking protector William,
shy little-boy Willy and take-charge Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's wife seems to accept her husband's condition _ even
embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't introduce them,'' she says of meeting several of his
alleged personalities during their courtship. ``They just came when
they were ready.''
</P>
<P>
   It was alter ego Frank who first told her he loved her. And the
Romeo character Anthony who gave her an engagement ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my life so I guess it isn't odd to me at all,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Twilight Zone'' are the words ``Dateline's'' Murphy uses
to describe all this. It's as bizzare as ``Springer,'' but more
honestly intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   In a testy prison interview with Greene (who morphs in and out
of personalities), Murphy wonders whether Greene is scamming him.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's responses, like his alleged personalities, are varied:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your call,'' Sam challenges. ``I think you're blowing
it, that's what I think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like you,'' little Willy pouts.
</P>
<P>
   And Bill Greene, the personality who stands convicted? He says,
``We're not trying to get away with nothing. People with an
insanity defense spend an average of six, nine years in a mental
institution. What are we getting away with?''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Shakur through the years
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so confident and so sure about the man that I am that
you can watch me,'' the late rapper/actor Tupac Shakur says at the
opening of MTV's ``BIOrhythm'' (10:30 EDT tonight). ``You can watch
me when I fall, when I cry, when I get shot, when I go to jail,
when I die. You can watch it. And that's what you're gonna do.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch this show and you'll basically hear the same story MTV and
countless others have told about Shakur's short, intriguing life.
</P>
<P>
   What really works are the images. You get to see Shakur through
the years: in grainy still pictures with his godfather, former
Black Panther Geronimo Pratt; in a home video at 17 two weeks
before he was homeless in Oakland; and at 11:30 p.m. that night in
Las Vegas he was shot. (On the way to an anti-violence event, no
less).
</P>
<P>
   The images are powerful to viewers already familiar with the
story behind them. But if you're only first learning of Shakur
here, consider ``BIOrhythm'' just a starting point.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
