<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-HARASSMENT-1STL     06-22 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASSMENT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS NOT LIABLE FOR TEACHER MISDEEDS THEY DON'T KNOW ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: ADDS grafs 6-10 with reaction to the ruling. Minor edits
throughout)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ School districts cannot be held responsible when a
teacher sexually harasses or abuses a student if the school
authorities were not informed of the misconduct, the Supreme Court
ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision in a Texas case means that in order to collect
monetary damages, a student must prove that school officials knew
of the teacher's misconduct and chose to ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Congress speaks directly on the subject, we will not
hold a school district liable in damages ... for a teacher's sexual
harassment of a student absent actual notice and deliberate
indifference,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   She noted, however, that the ruling will not affect any right
that a harassed student has to recover monetary damages from a
guilty teacher, or against a school district under some state laws.
But such state cases have proved virtually futile.
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to hold school districts liable, O'Connor
acknowledged that ``harassment unfortunately is an all too common
aspect of the educational experience ... and that a student suffers
extraordinary harm when subjected to sexual harassment and abuse by
a teacher, and that the teacher's conduct is reprehensible and
undermines the basic purposes of the educational system.''
</P>
<P>
   A women's legal organization decried the decision, saying that
unless school districts are held financially responsible, they will
have no reason to enforce sexual harassment policies strictly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the court is saying to schools is, `Stick your head in
the sand and ignore these problems,''' said Jocelyn Frey, legal
director of the Washington-based National Partnership for Women and
Families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that when a person is allowed to collect damages,
that really gets the school going to correct the probelm. If
schools don't have to worry about being liable, they have no reason
to push strong enforcemnt of sexual harassment policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Shapiro of the American Civil Liberties Union called the
decision ``unfortunate and wrong.'' He said it left ``no effective
remedy for students who are sexually victimized by their
teachers.'' He called on Congress to provide such a remedy.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia Collier, who was superintendent of the Lago Vista,
Texas, school district when it was sued in the case, said officials
there ``had absolutely zero reason to know what was going on.
Schools can't protect students from everything,'' she added. ``We
love and care for the children in our schools and we are doing our
best to protect them, but we are only human. We can't be all
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling rejected a harassment claim against the
public school district near Austin over a teacher's sexual
relationship with a ninth-grade student.
</P>
<P>
   Because the decision focused exclusively on a school setting
involving teachers and students, it does not apply to on-the-job
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices are expected to say more on that subject in a
pair of decisions to be announced before the court ends its 1997-98
term this week or next.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the justices are considering whether employers
should be held financially responsible for a supervisor's sexual
misconduct when the victim complained to another supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, the question is whether a company is
responsible if one of its supervisors harassed a woman and
threatened to make her job difficult unless she succumbed to his
sexual advances but never carried out the threat. She alleged that
even though she received a promotion, she felt compelled to resign
because of a hostile work environment.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's case, police found Frank Waldrop, then 52, a social
studies teacher at Lago Vista High School, nude in the woods with a
15-year-old student, Alida Star Gebser, in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit that Gebser and her mother later filed
against the Lago Vista school district, the sexual relationship had
lasted for about six months. Gebser, now a college student, had
apparently told no one about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in October 1992, parents or guardians of at least two
other girls had complained about what they called inappropriate
comments Waldrop made to their daughters. He met with the adults
and said he had meant no offense. The school principal admonished
Waldrop and considered the matter resolved, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   After the police discovered Waldrop and Gebser having sex,
Waldrop was fired and stripped of his teaching certificate. He
eventually pleaded no contest to a charge of attempted sexual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge threw out Gebser's suit against the school
district, however, after noting a lack of evidence that any
administrative official knew about the sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the
dismissal of the suit, rejecting arguments that school districts
should be held responsible whenever a teacher sexually harasses a
student.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Supreme Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor's majority opinion were Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the four, Stevens attacked the majority decision,
saying: ``As a matter of policy, the court ranks protection of the
school's district's purse above the protection of immature high
school students that those rules would provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens also said the decision ``thwarts the purposes of Title
IX'' of a 1972 law denying federal aid to schools that allow
discrimination against girls in sports and other school activities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Supreme Court ruled that under the 1972 law,
sexually harassed students may collect monetary damages from their
schools and school officials. But it did not say what standard
should be used for imposing liability on a school district for the
intentional acts of one of its teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In their arguments before the court, lawyers for the Lago Vista
school district said it would be unfair to make employers legally
responsible when they don't know that the harassment is takin
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
