<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0623 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, June 23,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, June
23, 1998, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SCHOOL-SEX _ WASHINGTON _ School districts are not legally
liable when teachers sexually harass or abuse students if
administrators did not know about the misconduct, the Supreme Court
ruled Monday in a Texas case. (Harlan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-FIRES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The firefighting
continues in north Florida with 90 wildfires started today, mostly
by lightning. One possible benefit: With the hay crop burned, some
ranchers are taking their cattle to market early, which could lower
beef prices. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   LAMBORGHINI-LEMON _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A
quarter-million-dollar Lamborghini Diablo Roadster is a lemon, its
disgruntled owner says in a lawsuit that he hopes to make a class
action on behalf of other Roadster owners. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   KILLERS-REJECTED _ AUSTIN _ A San Marcos, Texas, center for
troubled youths has decided it will not accept two Arkansas boys
accused of killing five people in a school shooting, even if an
Arkansas judge recommends they be placed there. (Rodriguez, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI _ Follow on the Atlanta children who were hospitalized
after E. coli sickness. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   with FOOD-SAFETY _ How safe/unsafe is our food? How accurate are
media reports/public perceptions? What is the federal government
doing now? Should there be one federal agency governing all food
regulation to track and prevent cases like the current E. coli
outbreak in metro Atlanta? We talk with experts at a meeting of the
Institute of Food Technologists in Atlanta to look at the topic of
food safety. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCEONE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The former Air Force One goes on
public display today at the U.S. Air Force Museum. (Huffman, Dayton
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BURIAL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's a matter of faith that
Jewish people can't be buried in Catholic cemeteries. But that
didn't matter to the state six years ago when it denied
Levitt-Weinstein Memorial Chapels &AMP; Cemeteries a license to open
the third Jewish cemetery in Palm Beach County. (Freeman, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FIRE _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Farm crop losses from the drought top
$100 million and might signal a drop in beef prices. Most of the
hay crop, along with corn and tobacco, has burned up in the
wildfires and rancers are taking their cattle to market early.
Elsewhere, desert-like dryness and heat have led to one of the
worst outbreaks of wildfires in Florida since 1985. (Date/Utley,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   GMSTRIKE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Follow on strike. No progress reported
and more workers are laid off. (Dillon, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
