<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAID-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      06-22 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT SAYS TEXAS LOST $1 BILLION IN MEDICAID REIMBURSEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Stands for MEDICAID-FRAUD)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Texas and the company that administers Medicaid in
the state have failed to collect $1 billion over the past decade,
according to a lawsuit filed by a former lawyer for the Texas
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, brought by James M. Churchill of Austin, alleges
that state health officials and the National Heritage Insurance Co.
resisted his repeated efforts to compel private insurance companies
to reimburse Medicaid for their share of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 2 1/2 years, I tried to get people to do what they were
obligated to do. It's a shame it has to get down to this sort of
thing, but I was just totally frustrated,'' Churchill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 10 years, an extremely conservative estimate
would be a billion dollars not collected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill, 57, retired a year ago and filed the lawsuit in
federal court in Pecos. Because it was filed on behalf of the
federal government, the lawsuit was sealed until late this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, senior U.S. District Judge Lucius D. Bunton
III rejected arguments by the defendants that the lawsuit should be
dismissed. The case is set now for trial in October in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Attorney General Dan Morales, who is defending
the state and the various state agencies involved, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to appeal Judge Bunton's ruling regarding the
state's immunity, but we're not going to get into a discussion of
the state's defense,'' Morales spokesman Ron Dusek said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for National Heritage Insurance also would not
discuss the allegations in detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe the claim is legitimate, and we certainly
plan to vigorously defend ourselves,'' said Delbra Bristol of
Electronic Data Systems, parent company of National Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   EDS was founded by Ross Perot, the Dallas tycoon and former
presidential candidate. Perot sold the company to General Motors
more than a dozen years ago. EDS since has been spun off from GM.
</P>
<P>
   National Heritage has administered Medicaid in Texas since 1977.
Its current contract dates from 1988.
</P>
<P>
   About 2.8 million people in Texas are eligible for Medicaid,
which is a state and federal health program for the poor and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1997, the most recent for which statistics are
available, Medicaid paid $10.7 billion in Texas. About two-thirds
of it came from the federal government and the rest from the state.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, National Heritage received $91.4 million from
the state to administer the program.
</P>
<P>
   According to Churchill's lawsuit, the state and the federal
governments would have paid out far less if efforts had been made,
as required by federal law, to collect from commercial insurance
companies when they were responsible for medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if a passenger in an automobile was injured in a
collision and the driver of either vehicle was found at fault, that
driver's liability insurance should pay for the treatment of the
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in numerous cases, Medicaid paid for the passenger's
treatment, and neither National Heritage nor the state sought
reimbursement, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply a matter of contacting the appropriate insurance
company and making a claim, but that has never been done,''
Churchill said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Churchill said the problem first came to his attention in late
1994 when a Health Department supervisor asked him to examine
collection guidelines as outlined in the contract the state had
with the insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill said he found very little money was being collected.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, he said, numerous meetings were held with
National Heritage and Health Department officials to try and figure
out ways to increase collections from third parties.
</P>
<P>
   One idea was to have an outside law firm collect the money for a
percentage of the collections, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there were lots of law firms willing to do it,''
Churchill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then in late fall of 1995, we were told it wasn't going to
happen. I was real concerned. I thought the problem had been
solved. They had given us promises that by the first of January
1996 they would have a contract law firm in place doing this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill said his own collection efforts proved his point.
According to the lawsuit, he negotiated $13.5 million in
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the lawsuit claims, senior Health Department
officials told him to stop discussing the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such action constituted an active attempt by the Texas
Department of Health Health Care Financing to conceal and cover up
(National Heritage Insurance's) and the other defendants' failure
to comply with the requirements of federal law,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
