<SLUG> BC-JBAKER-CHAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J. BAKER THINKS BIG WITH PLANS FOR NEW CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Grande Central Big and Tall Clothing Co. is cq; budgeted as
JBaker-Acquire)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once known as a retailer that sold shoes, J. Baker Inc. took
another step Monday toward transforming itself into a merchant that
may someday be more famous for selling clothing to big men.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker currently operates Casual Male Big &AMP; Tall, a chain of
459 stores that outfits outsized chaps in low-cost apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Next summer, the Canton, Mass. retailer plans to open a second
chain, to be known as Grande Central Big and Tall Clothing Co.,
that will aim at big guys who are willing to spend more money on
their wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for Grande Central to open about 40 stores in August
1999 and feature brand-name casual attire, in contrast to the
greater emphasis on house brands at Casual Male Big &AMP; Tall, said
Alan I. Weinstein, J. Baker's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the company's plans forced the timing of the
Grande Central announcement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Weinstein said he was unprepared Monday to disclose
more information about Grande Central's store format and what brand
names it is likely to stock.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the decade, J. Baker sold shoes in such company-run
chains as Fayva and Parade of Shoes. These chains have since been
sold off, but the company continues to run licensed footwear
departments for such retailers as Bradlees Inc. and Ames Department
Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As competition intensified and the likes of Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
started selling more shoes, J. Baker has sold some of its shoe
business and looked to emphasize big-and-tall clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Casual Male accounted for about 40 percent of J.
Baker sales, Weinstein said. J. Baker also operates the Work 'n
Gear chain of stores that sell work clothes and uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   For its last fiscal year, J. Baker reported a profit of $3.8
million on sales of $592 million. In the previous year, it reported
a loss of $111 million on sales of $897 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Nasdaq, J. Baker shares were unchanged at 12 7/8. In January,
shares were trading below 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
