<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dry vegetation will continue to fuel brush fires over portions
of Florida Tuesday. The droughty conditions will abate in a few
spots as towering cumulus clouds yield potent afternoon
thunderstorms. The strongest storms will erupt near the east
Florida coast where a developing sea breeze front lifts the very
sultry air. Large hail and frequent lightning are possible.
Meanwhile, ample sun will cover the interior Southeast with some
isolated thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds and fog will plague eastern New England Tuesday as
moist onshore breezes persist. Clouds will yield to hazy sun over
the interior where isolated afternoon thundershowers are possible.
Overcast conditions will hug the southeast New England coast much
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of showers and strong thunderstorms will accompany a
jet stream disturbance crossing the upper Ohio Valley and central
Appalachians. Very heavy rain will occur in a few of the
thunderstorms. Farther west, plenty of sunshine and slightly less
humid air will spread into the northern Great Lakes as high
pressure arrives from Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk winds from the south will transport hot and increasingly
humid into the central and northern Plains Tuesday. As the muggy
air intercepts a slow-moving front, severe thunderstorms capable of
spawning tornadoes will develop over the Dakotas and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms will form in parts of the northern
Rockies as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead. The remainder
of the West will be dry and mainly sunny though low clouds will
cover sections of the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Pennsylvania Deluge
</P>
<P>
   A thunderstorm stalled over the southern Poconos on Sunday
afternoon and deposited 5.5 inches of rain in three hours on
Lehighton. There were estimates of as much as 7 inches in parts of
Carbon County in northeastern Pennsylvania with serious flooding.
The storm formed along the boundary between marine air covering
much of southern New England and a steamy air mass over the Middle
Atlantic states. A weather balloon launched from New York City at
daybreak on Sunday indicated winds were less than 15 miles an hour
from the ground to 30,000 feet, and this was the prime ingredient
for sluggish storms. Only minor changes in the weather pattern
Tuesday could raise the risk of more slow-moving storms near the
East Coast. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
