<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREATINE23-COX     06-22 1968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creatine just part of daily diet for many athletes
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Creatine has become the food of the gods. The
nutritional supplement, little-known or used before this decade,
has become almost standard issue for our athletic heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine is helping to fuel Mark McGwire's home-run binge. John
Elway and the Denver Broncos gulped it down on the way to their
first-ever Super Bowl win. Sprinter Michael Johnson used it on his
way to running a stunning world record in the 200 meters in the
1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Texas, while some coaches remain leery of
it, creatine is being counted on to help a 4-7 team return to
football glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creatine is the hottest thing on the market,'' said Jeff
Madden, UT's new assistant athletic director for strength and
conditioning. ``It works extremely well. I've been using it for
years. I've had guys put on 20 or 30 pounds and they're gaining
lean muscle mass ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to name the football programs that aren't using
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Texas, as with other college and professional programs,
players can choose whether or not to use creatine.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine, an amino acid compound, has been touted as a safe and
legal alternative to steroids and can easily be purchased as a
powder, tablet or in a drink at health food stores. It's estimated
that 50 percent of NFL players and 25 percent of pro baseball,
basketball and hockey players use it. Proponents of the supplement
say that it might be helpful in just about every sport except
bowling and billiards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no one really knows what its long-term effects on the body
are, particularly as its use filters down to younger and younger
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say 80 to 85 percent of the athletes at our high school
camps have used creatine or some other supplement,'' Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Salesmen now call local high schools about buying creatine in
bulk, and one company even has a product, Crea-TEEN, aimed at
athletes from 19 years on down to 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine was first identified in 1832 by a French scientist who
found it to be a naturally occurring organic compound in meat. Its
name is derived from the Greek word for flesh.
</P>
<P>
   It is produced naturally by the liver and kidneys, about two
grams a day in humans. Another gram or so can can be obtained by
eating meat and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine is stored in muscles and allows muscles to regenerate
adenosine triphosphate, the major fuel used in explosive movements.
It is also thought to inhibit the buildup of lactic acid, which
contributes to muscle fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some steroids, creatine does not make a person faster or
stronger almost automatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a magic bullet,'' said Dan Pfaff, a UT assistant
track coach who has worked with Olympic 100-meter champion Donovan
Bailey and other world-class athletes. ``But there's no doubt it
works. There are weight gains and strength gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have claimed performance strength and speed gains as
great as 5 and 10 percent and there are anecdotal reports of
strength gains of 20 percent and more. At the elite level of
competition, a 3-percent edge is huge. It's the difference between
running a 10.1-second 100 meters and maybe missing the Olympic
final, or running a 9.8 and getting the gold medal and the lion's
share of the lucrative endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Although synthetic creatine was manufactured as early as the
late 1950s, it was decades before it came into vogue. More powerful
performance enhancers, anabolic steroids, became the rage, starting
in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 the International Olympic Committee began testing for
anabolic steroids and in Seoul in 1988, the drug problems came to a
head. Among the 10 athletes who tested positive at the Games was
Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson, a hunk of bulging muscle who
exploded to a 9.79 100 meters. Just as disturbing as Johnson's
disgrace were rumors that other gold-medal winners had escaped
detection. With the reputation of the Olympics, and ultimately its
mega-million TV contracts at stake, a crackdown was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992 in Barcelona, performances by both the West and the
former Eastern Bloc athletes were something less than eye popping.
In the showcase event, the men's 100 meters, only one competitor
was able to break 10.0 seconds and that was 32-year-old Linford
Christie, who became by far the oldest 100-meter winner in Olympic
history. Christie had been using creatine, as had another British
athlete who had good results that year, hurdler Colin Jackson.
Jackson would go on to set a world record in the 110-meter hurdles
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   British researchers had been working with creatine, as had Dr.
Eric Hultman at Sweden's prestigious Karolinska Institute. The
Karolinska Institute awards the Nobel Prize for physiology or
medicine. Hultman has studied how muscles work for more than 30
years and was a pioneer of carbohydrate loading, which became a
tactic for elite athletes and even recreational 10-kilometer
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Hultman was working on creatine loading in the late 1980s,
although results were not published until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, 1992, the year began in the worst way imaginable for
the Nebraska football team. In the Orange Bowl the University of
Miami football team, aiming for yet another national championship,
was trying to name its own score against the Huskers. The
Hurricanes handed Nebraska its first shutout in 221 games and held
the vaunted Nebraska running game to a puny 82 yards. The nation
saw Husker strength mocked by Hurricane speed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, 1991 and 1992 the Cornhuskers were stuck on nine wins,
a good season for most teams, but the fewest games Coach Tom
Osborne had won in Lincoln and hardly an acceptable number for a
program that considered itself on the cutting edge of athletic
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Also stuck at a plateau was the strongest guy in Nebraska's
weight room, shot putter Kevin Coleman. In 1990 he was throwing
just less than 60 feet, but couldn't improve on that in 1991.
Coleman, now the strength coach at Kansas, began using creatine. In
1992 he bettered 65 feet, and won the NCAA indoor championships in
both 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, half a dozen Nebraska football players were trying
creatine. Then dozens were downing it. Then, most of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's getting overblown,'' said Boyd Epley,
Nebraska's assistant athletic director of athletic performance.
``It's a food, not a drug. It's not a steroid. Your body produces
it naturallly. It's just one of five supplements we use.''
</P>
<P>
   Epley said the Cornhuskers recently made a change in the way
they did sets and repetitions that produced more strength gains
than creatine did. Still, the Huskers, who were unable to win a
national championship in Osborne's first two decades as Nebraska
coach, have won three in the last five years, during which time
they are 60-3.
</P>
<P>
   Madden said some of his athletes first began using creatine when
he was at Colorado in the early 1990s. In 1993 a Golden, Colo.,
company, Experimental and Applied Sciences, began marketing
creatine. A year later the Dietary Supplement Health and Education
Act was passed. The result of it was that supplements, including
creatine, no longer had to prove they were safe and effective. The
burden of proof shifted to the Food and Drug Administration to
prove they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   As for the athletic arena, Pfaff said, ``I think the governing
bodies of some sports were glad it came out. It got a lot of
athletes away from steroids. They finally had a legal substance
they could use for an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995 creatine was a $30 million-a-year business and EAS had
90 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 at the Olympic Games the use of creatine was widespread
among male and female athletes from a variety of countries. After
the Olympics creatine demand started swelling in local health food
store and even more college football teams began using it. Some
encountered problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of two-a-days, cramping became almost epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Ellis, coordinator of performance nutrition for Nebraska,
blamed much of that cramping on a 1995 NCAA rule that allowed
players to practice in half pads, rather than beginning two-a-days
in shorts and shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis explained, ``Luckily we had a head coach who saw that
cramping was not unique to athletes who used creatine and so we
turned our focus to hydration feeding protocols. Unfortunately, at
a few schools creatine didn't survive the transition and I have
witnessed them literally throw the baby out with the bath water.''
</P>
<P>
   Epley said, ``We've never had cramping problems. It's like a
salt. It soaks up water. You just need to drink more water.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other side effects can include diarrhea and bloating. Dana
LeDuc, a former strength coach at Texas who is now with the NFL's
Seattle Seahawks, said that concerns about possible cramping and
even muscle tears are why some Seahawks, epecially those in the
speed positions, have not used creatine. LeDuc estimates that about
50 percent of the Seahawks use creatine.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine use is heavier on the Broncos. After the Broncos became
a rare AFC Super Bowl champion with a powerful NFC-style ground
game, the Broncos were shown on national TV wearing EAS caps.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, McGwire is just one of several weightlifting
aficionados using creatine. Superstar catcher Mark Piazza is
another and Baltimore's Brady Anderson was one of the sport's
earliest converts. In seven years bouncing between Baltimore and
the minors Anderson had hit only 41 career home runs. Then he
discovered creatine in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Anderson hit 21 homers with Baltimore and slugged 50 in
1996. While expansion and diluted pitching have contributed to the
home run binges changing baseball, some experts feel weightlifting
and creatine also have altered the game. At the College World
Series, where the championship game was won by Southern California
with a football-sized score of 21-14, all eight coaches said there
were players on their teams who had used creatine.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine has now seeped down to the high schools, and not
everyone is pleased. Ron Schroeder, Westlake football coach, said
he gets calls from salesmen who want to market it through his
program. If it is not bought in bulk by a school, creatine can
typically cost an athlete from $30 to $60 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said that there might be some individuals on the team
who use creatine or other supplements, but, ``What we push is three
square meals a day. You want your kids to be dedicated, but you
don't want them to sell their souls.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said: ``I'm against giving it to high school athletes.
They use it like it's a magic tablet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pfaff said: ``The inherent danger is that kids get into a
psychological state that if a little is good, more is better.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, no one seems to know how much creatine is too
little or too much. Jackson reportedly uses 20 grams a day, an
amount recommended only in the early loading stage. Nebraska,
however, doesn't believe in loading and bases its doses on weight.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the success linked to creatine there are still some
skeptics. Texas women's swim coach Jill Sterkel said, ``I've been
around long enough to know there's usually a side effect to
something ... I don't think there's anything that replaces hard
work. I don't feel it's appropriate for me to tell them what to
take when I don't know what the long-term effects are.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas women's track coach Bev Kearney added, ``I get notes on it
all the time. People say ``You've got to do it. You've got to do
it.' I would prefer our athletes depend on what's in their
hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
