<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERWATCH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ConsumerWatch: Texas at odds with self-help publisher
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Another showdown is building in Texas, but this time
it's not between the sheriff and the outlaw. Rather, it's between
Nolo Press Inc. and the state legal establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo Press, a major publisher of self-help law books and
software, has been summoned to a hearing in August with the Texas
Unauthorized Practice of Law Committee to determine if Nolo Press
is violating its rules.
</P>
<P>
   All states have laws or court rulings that prohibit
non-attorneys from engaging in the practice of law, including
personally representing or advising others on legal matters. Nolo
Press contends it is not practicing law.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, several states have acted against firms or
individuals that describe themselves as paralegals and that sell
legal services to individuals -- services such as the completion of
divorce or bankruptcy papers.
</P>
<P>
   The California-based publisher, which has sold more than 7
million copies of its books and software, contends its materials
are written to help individuals handle their own legal affairs --
which is generally legal, especially in civil matters -- and such
publications are protected under the free press provisions of the
First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolo Press is a publisher of basic legal tools and information
designed to allow Americans -- many of whom cannot afford to pay
lawyers upward of $175 an hour -- to gain the information necessary
to cope with their everyday legal problems,'' said Ralph Warner,
publisher of Nolo Press, which was founded in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Warner cites a ruling by a New York court to support his
contention that Nolo Press' activities are protected by the First
Amendment. A lower court had ruled previously that a do-it-yourself
legal book on avoiding probate constituted the unauthorized
practice of law. But the decision was overruled in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we are to extend a rule of suppression beyond the
obscene, the libelous (or) utterances tending to incitement, there
is no warrant (to ban the book),'' the high court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no federal court decision on the issue. Self-help
law books and software, published by Nolo Press or other firms, are
sold in all states.
</P>
<P>
   John T. Adams, clerk of the Texas Supreme Court, said the
Unauthorized Practice of Law Committee is not an arm of the court,
and the court does not direct its activities, although it appoints
the committee's members.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the committee believes it has found an instance of
unauthorized practices, its remedy, if the unauthorized
practitioner does not agree to cease the activity, is to seek an
injunction in court,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas does enjoin the sale of Nolo Press materials in the
state, it would be a difficult ruling to enforce. Texas retailers
could be stopped, but the state would also have to try to enjoin
Internet sales by several online book and software sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
