<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1027 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN23-COX     06-22 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shoulder yet to slow down Norman's fast lane
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He flew across the country and back.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at a boat he's thinking about buying.
</P>
<P>
   He posed, with his dogs, for a calendar shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman, in other words, has spent U.S. Open week being Greg
Norman, with one notable exception. He's not golfing.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who underwent surgery on his left shoulder in April to
clean out stuff the guys with the scalpels say they usually see in
quarterbacks or tennis players, doesn't expect to start hitting
balls until August. And even then, he'll only chip them.
</P>
<P>
   Norman is aiming at his own Shark Shootout in November as the
time he'll return to competition, but the 1998 PGA Tour season is
long lost.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the forced hiatus, Norman said he would use
the time away from golf as a gauge to see how much he might miss
the game when he gives it up (of his own accord) for good. Though
he'll be only 44 years old next February, Norman has spoken of
getting out of the game by the turn of the millennium or soon
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   So?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't missed it,'' Norman said. ``I've turned my mind off
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means is Norman has had to work at missing golf, which
probably means he misses it more than he cares to let on.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Norman seldom strays into his golf room on the
family's Hobe Sound estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, I don't look at my clubs and don't touch them,''
Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   But when he happened to visit San Francisco this week _ site of
Olympic Club and the U.S. Open, which began Thursday _ Norman's
interest was piqued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in my hotel room watching interviews from the
course, and I thought, `I should be there. I wish I could be
playing,''' said Norman, who was in the area in conjunction with
his design work at The Course at Wente Vineyards in suburban
Livermore. ``I missed it there. I did. I'll admit that.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was something Norman noticed while watching those
television interviews that reminded him of part of the game he has
grown to despise. It didn't seem to him that many guys were having
much fun getting ready to deal with Olympic Club and the annual
U.S. Open test featuring deep rough, fast greens and frayed nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was on Tuesday,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that major championships, save for two British Open titles,
have been a laughfest for Norman through the years. He's endured
his share of trauma, some of it self-inflicted and some of it
heaped upon him in unbelievable fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But all those experiences, plus the extended period of
recuperation in which he now finds himself, have brought Norman to
the edge of the final stages of his playing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so different on the outside looking in,'' Norman said.
``When you're inside, you're so busy trying to build to an edge
that you don't always see what's happening. You just know you feel
tired. Well, it's because things get stale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll go back re-invigorated, but I hope I can keep the
perspective I have now.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll watch some golf this weekend _ ``I'd be a liar if I said I
wouldn't,'' Norman said _ but won't plop himself in front of the
set for hours on end. Later this summer, he'll work for CBS during
the network's PGA Championship coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's the new-fangled jet he's going to test.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman being Greg Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Golf or no golf.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
