<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech Tools: Page design program hidden behind layouts
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- I haven't looked at Microsoft Publisher in several
years, and my first glimpse of Publisher 98 was something of a
shock; it appeared to have been dumbed down rather severely.
</P>
<P>
   It has more wizards than the last five Tolkien rip-offs put
together. You want to do a nice newsletter? Fine. Here are two
dozen possibilities, each just a little different from the other,
and none anything like what you have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   It resembles, in fact, programs from what Microsoft apparently
views as its chief rivals, PrintMaster and Print Shop. Both of
those programs are intended to help people put together simple
broadsheets, greeting cards and the like.
</P>
<P>
   I had always thought of Publisher as standing between those very
simple and relatively inflexible layout programs and the high-end,
highly complicated productions like PageMaker.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays it does not come with a manual; rather, there is a thin
booklet called a Companion. It seems more oriented toward design
philosophy than program instruction, although the latter can be
found there.
</P>
<P>
   I had just about decided Microsoft had thrown Publisher to the
dogs when things began to fall together and I discovered the old,
relatively muscular page design program lurking under all the
layers of generic, pre-masticated layouts.
</P>
<P>
   You can still set up your own text and picture frames quite
easily, and build a newsletter your own way, if you have a good
idea of how you want it to look. This seems a lot easier than
taking one of the pre-formatted designs and trying to hammer it
into your own concept, unless your concept is pretty similar to the
set piece.
</P>
<P>
   If you select Blank Publications, you can then pick from a full
page, a postcard, a business card, a book fold, side fold or top
fold card, a tent card, a poster, a banner or an index card, which
should cover everything you might need. You can also do a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Web page creation, though, appears to be the most important new
thing about Publisher 98. It does Web pages easier, if not as
elaborately, as Microsoft's Front Page.
</P>
<P>
   You can build a Web page the same way you make a newsletter --
using frames for text, objects and graphics. Any of these frames
can be made into links to other pages or other sites or to large
blocks of text. It seems the only significant things missing are
the Web-bot features of Front Page.
</P>
<P>
   Unification is also emphasized in Publisher. If, for instance,
you have set up a standard newsletter format in Publisher, you can
translate that directly into a Web page design. The program will
examine the newsletter for elements that won't work properly on the
Internet, point them out and suggest what you can do about them.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been unified, itself, to look like the core
Microsoft Office programs. Creating text works the way it does in
Word, with background spell-checking and auto-correction. Of
course, it brings in text from Word readily.
</P>
<P>
   The program assumes the output is going to be sent to a color
inkjet printer. Most folks using a program like this don't expect
to be sending their output off on disk for high-end offset
printing. Nonetheless, if that's what you have in mind, it includes
an Imagesetter print driver, with the option of installing a print
driver from your printer.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher 98 is a really slick piece of work, especially for
people who want to set up a Web site and then have some paper goods
-- the ever-present newsletter or even a restaurant menu -- that
follows the same style.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
