<HEADLINE>
WEBER TRULY WORLDWIDE WITH GERMAN ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: pr bonn Public Relations GmbH is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the acquisition of a German public relations firm Monday,
Weber Public Relations Worldwide seems within striking distance of
its stated goal to become one of the world's five largest PR firms.
</P>
<P>
   Weber acquired pr bonn Public Relations GmbH, a firm with
revenues of $2.4 million. Terms of the acquisition were not
disclosed. Weber said the deal will increase its ability to provide
a wide range of PR services to global clients.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if Weber can make a few more acquisitions, it's possible
a guy who once served a brief stint as a bodyguard for the Rolling
Stones two decades ago could be running the world's largest PR firm
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll almost certainly be in the top five by the end of the
year,'' said Larry Weber, the former bodyguard who is now the
chairman of Weber Public Relations Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1996 the Cambridge, Mass. PR firm that Weber founded was
bought by a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos., the New York
holding company that recently agreed to buy Hill Holliday Connors
Cosmopulos, Boston's second largest advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   When his firm was bought, Weber's new bosses issued him a
mandate: Through acquisitions, he was to transform a regional shop
into a global firm that could provide multinational giants with
one-stop shopping for a full range of PR services.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months, Weber has made eight acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   For a firm that once specialized in helping high-tech companies,
acquisitions have given Weber expertise in such fields as health
care, investor relations, and government affairs. Acquisitions have
also given Weber entry into new geographical markets such as Latin
America and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months trade publications and British
newspapers have reported that London-based Shandwick International,
the world's second-largest PR firm, may be an acquisition target,
along with its US sister company, Golin/Harris Communications of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   News reports have identified Weber as one of several likely
Shandwick suitors. Weber declined to comment on Shandwick.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming conflict-of-interest issues could be resolved, an
acquisition of Shandwick and Golin/Harris could give Weber nearly
$300 million in annual revenues; in 1997, the tracking firm J.R.
O'Dwyer Co. ranked Burson-Marsteller as the world's largest PR firm
with 1997 revenues of $265 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Weber reported revenues of $61 million, good for 10th
place on O'Dwyer's list. Weber is now on pace to project 1998
revenues of about $90 million, an amount that would have landed
Weber in 7th place on last year's list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
