A1037 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAURO-CLINTONS-TEX     06-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAURO-CLINTONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC OPPONENT OF TEXAS GOVERNOR IN WASHINGTON FOR
FUND-RAISERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Democrats haven't exactly flocked to Garry
Mauro's campaign for governor, but the Clinton White House is
rallying to Mauro's defense in a big way this week.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and first lady Hillary Clinton will join Mauro
Tuesday night at back-to-back Washington fund-raisers that are
expected to raise about $250,000 for Mauro's uphill battle against
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is scheduled to join Mauro in El Paso on
Thursday for a dinner that is expected to generate about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's foray to the nation's capital comes less than a week
after Bush raised more than $1 million at similar Washington
events. The dueling fund-raisers reflect the extent to which the
Texas contest has become a proxy war for the next presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By helping Mauro, the Clintons and Gore can reward a loyal
Democrat while sparring with a Republican governor who is
considered one of the top GOP prospects for the year 2000. Bush,
who leads the Republican pack in early presidential polls, has said
he will not make up his mind about a possible White House run until
well after the Texas re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   James Riddlesperger, a political science professor at Texas
Christian University, said the Clinton White House has a strong
self-interest in helping Mauro dent Bush's commanding lead. A Bush
rout could carry dozens of other Texas Republicans to victory and
boost Bush's national standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're trying to do is damage control. It's bad news all
the way down the ballot if your gubernatorial candidate is a
no-show,'' Riddlesperger said. ``In terms of national politics, you
don't want Bush to walk in uncontested to the governorship and be
able to use that as a springboard for a possible presidential
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to join Mauro and his donors at
dinner Tuesday night at the Sheraton Carlton Hotel, a few blocks
from the White House. The first lady will greet the guests at a
pre-dinner reception. Tickets are $1,000 for the reception and
$5,000 for the reception, the dinner and ``briefing sessions'' on
the Texas campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who met with Washington reporters Monday, said his
high-placed Washington allies are motivated by ``old-fashioned
friendship.'' Mauro has known the Clintons since 1972, when the
three of them worked on the Texas campaign of presidential
candidate George McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who has served as Texas land commissioner since 1983,
headed the state Clinton-Gore campaigns in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think I've earned the right to run for governor, and
they're going to help, just like I helped them,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House aide agreed with Mauro's assessment but conceded
that the chance to tweak Bush ``makes it more fun'' to aid the
Texas Democrat. Tuesday night's fund-raiser will be the eighth time
that Hillary Clinton has attended a reception or dinner for Mauro.
President Clinton and Gore joined him at a Washington reception
last year, and Clinton recently signed a fund-raising letter on
Mauro's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mauro's fellow Texas Democrats have not been nearly as
loyal. Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who is godfather to one of Mauro's
children, has endorsed Bush. More than 100 Democratic officeholders
in the state's 254 counties have also abandoned the Democratic
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the Washington Democrats _ specifically, President
Clinton, Hillary Clinton and Al Gore _ are propping up Garry
Mauro's campaign,'' said Mindy Tucker, a Bush campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro will get a chance to energize Texas Democrats this weekend
when the party holds its state convention in San Antonio. Mauro
will speak to the delegates Saturday after introducing Gore on
Friday. The Democratic candidate shrugged off recent polls showing
Bush with a commanding lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one thing folks in Texas are talking about right
now, and that's 100-degree temperatures,'' Mauro said. ``When the
people of Texas stop talking about the weather and start talking
about the governor's race, they're going to look at the issues and
I'm going to do just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hutcheson, (202) 383-6101
</P>
<P>
   rhutcheson &LR; krwashington.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
