<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUEEN IS BACK AT CENTRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Duchess of Kent didn't show up, and the Princess of
Tabloids called in sick. But the Queen of Forehands, who had felt
``seven or eight weeks ago that I couldn't make it, that it was all
over for me,'' returned to her grass-paved throne room, and
everything seemed right and proper on Wimbledon's sun-splotched
opening day after all.
</P>
<P>
   As the Garden of Eden of the game, where tournament tennis began
121 years ago, the Big W has been the apple of the eyes of numerous
queens, but none has seemed so snakebit as Steffi Graf. Yet here
she was, at a decrepit 29, seeking the social security of a tennis
court again _ the tennis court, Centre Court _ starting another
trek upward toward a Saturday 11 days distant where the
championship lies. It would be her eighth, one short of Empress
Martina Navratilova's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can win,'' said Graf. ``I don't have any
feel, I'm nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   She never talked like that before. But then, she'd never been
away from her passion, her greatest love _ this game _ for so long,
and had her body and psyche so badly battered.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's score Monday _ 6-4, 6-1, over a lefthanded Spaniard, Gala
Leon Garcia _ would normally be a so-what? However, two years had
passed since she last gamboled on Centre, beating another Spaniard,
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, for another title in a run that began in
her Grand Slam year, 1988. So when Graf reappeared and made the
customary curtsy toward the Royal Box, the full house of 13,800
raised voices loud and warmly clapped for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen was unexpectedly back, and it was good to see her. Her
heart as big as the arena pumped grandly and the huge forehands
zinged damagingly. Abruptly her presence in the afternoon's second
engagement on Centre made Pete Sampras seem the warmup act as he
dusted Dominik Hrbaty, 6-3, 6-3, 6-2, with 17 aces in 83 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the radiant Duchess of Kent, she couldn't make
it. The Duchess, who usually graces the royal roost and has
presented the seven championship platters to Graf, sent her
roommate, the Duke, to do the family clapping. He has bad, if
earnest, hands, but gets them together somehow.
</P>
<P>
   The Princess of Tabloids _ 16-year-old Anna Kournikova _ was
another matter. When she was thumbed out Monday before striking a
ball, most of the scores of photographers on hand wept and wanted
to walk out with her.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was during Kournikova's career highlight victory
over Graf at Eastbourne last week that she took herself out of
Wimbledon by tumbling in the third set. That spill, as it turned
out, tore a ligament in her right thumb, and No. 10 Kournikova, a
semifinalist last year, withdrew at the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   The misfortunes of that defeat five days ago had Graf
uncharacteristically raging at line calls that went against her and
cursing herself audibly in German.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so uncertain, slow to react, didn't play my game,'' said
Graf, who typically was demanding much more of herself than
reasonable. It was only her fifth match since breaking down for a
second time within 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   But the insistence that her body support her for possibly one
last charge at Wimbledon got her here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it, but I'm 100 percent physically,'' said
Graf. ``Nothing hurts.'' But she wouldn't tell you if it did. No
tennis champion has played (and won) hurt more than she.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Gunthardt, her coach, glowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes she can play again,'' said Gunthardt. ``She
wasn't sure it would happen, but now she believes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago I was in a clinic in Austria after surgery,'' said
Graf, who came apart in losing at the French to Amanda Coetzer and
had to have her left knee rebuilt. ``I was rehabbing for hours,
early morning to night. Treatments, treatments _ lasers,
acupuncture, magnetic fields, all kinds of stuff I never heard
of.''
</P>
<P>
   She was on court again in February. Two tournaments, then
another TKO. More leg problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would recover, try to practice and something else went
wrong,'' she said. ``I thought then I couldn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse than her body's disobedience was the emotional hammering
of her father's misdeeds: philandering, alcoholism, tax evasion,
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's home now, it's fine,'' she said. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much hurt and anger within Steffi,'' said a
colleague, ``but she goes on. Tennis is her escape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stay healthy I'd like to play at least three more
years,'' said Graf. ``The records? I don't think about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 21 majors are three behind Margaret Court's all-time pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the playing, the being on court _ being here _ that
keeps me going,'' she said. ``That's what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Duchess and the Princess were missing, the Queen
was in her counting house, counting one more victory than most of
us would have bet on. You can't count her out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
