<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENT-COAL-BOS &LR;      06-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-COAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS SPAR OVER COAL EMISSIONS RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A leaked computer message outlining how coal-burning utilities
should pretend to be upset over an air pollution plan that they
actually support has set off a nasty dispute between Northeastern
governors and their counterparts in the Midwest and South.
</P>
<P>
   The fight, part of a larger war over chemicals that travel on
the wind to New England from coal plants, centers on a US
Environmental Protection Agency plan to clamp down on emissions of
nitrogen oxide that contribute to summertime smog and acid rain.
States where the coal industry has long provided abundant, cheap
power say the EPA plan will cost thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The computer message, written by an executive at the biggest US
coal-burning utility, describes West Virginia Governor Cecil
Underwood's strategy to substitute a much less strict nitrogen
oxide plan. To make the plan seem tougher, Underwood ``believes it
would be most helpful if ... utility groups could audibly grumble
about the stringency of the proposal,'' according to the memo, sent
to members of a utility lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   The memo assures readers that Underwood's substitute plan, to be
unveiled this week by Underwood and other governors, would have
only ``minor alterations'' from the position of the
utility-controlled Alliance for Constructive Air Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern officials said the memo revealed what they
suspected: that Midwestern and Southern politicians and power
companies are working in concert to defeat clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned by the appearance ... of some kind of behind
the scenes conspiracy to both weaken EPA's program, but also to
present a potentially misleading appearance of the impact of the
(Underwood) plan,'' said Maine Department of Environmental
Protection Commissioner Ned Sullivan, who supports the EPA plan.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Underwood denied that the governor is doing
anything improper, but he made no secret of his scorn for the EPA
plan, accusing Northeastern and EPA officials of waging economic
war against coal states.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA and the Northeastern states seem to be pretty much intent
on putting the screws to industry in the Midwest and South,'' said
Underwood spokesman Rod Blackstone, estimating that his state would
lose 11,000 jobs under the EPA proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern environmentalists are also crying foul over the
strategy memo, noting that any weakening of nitrogen oxide
standards means more smog for the Southeast and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole story is pitched as a Northeast versus Midwest
battle and the reality is we have serious'' smog problems in the
South, said Jeff Gleason of the Southern Environmental Law Center
in Virginia. He said Virginia had violated standards for ozone, the
key ingredient in smog, 25 times so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nitrogen oxide, a chemical by-product of combustion, forms ozone
when exposed to hot sun, and can increase water's acidity. Though
the EPA nitrogen oxide curbs would apply to 22 states, impact would
be heaviest on states that burn or produce coal.
</P>
<P>
   The June 18 message, written by Dale Heydlauff of American
Electric Power in Columbus, Ohio, and based on a talk with a top
West Virginia state official, lays out Gov. Underwood's ``strategy
to sell their package to other states and in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Underwood's alternate proposal would allow
substantially more nitrogen oxide emissions than the EPA plan,
Heydlauff wrote that Underwood's chief of operations Corky DeMarco
called for utilities to publicly gripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities should be prepared to complain about the costs and
the difficulty of complying with the established deadlines (in the
Underwood plan),'' writes Heydlauff, on the steering committee of
the Alliance for Constructive Air Policy, ``but (Underwood)
obviously does not want us to oppose the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   American Electric Power spokesman Pat Hemlepp said Heydlauff had
done nothing wrong. ``It's no different than any other lobbying
activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts Department of Environmental Protection
Commissioner David Struhs said the computer message is an
embarrassment to foes of the EPA plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This illustrates the sophistication of the people with whom
we're dealing. They think they can send an e-mail to 118 people and
keep it confidential,'' Struhs said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
