u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      06-22 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI SUPERVISOR DENIES PROTECTING MOB FIGURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As he ended two weeks of testimony Monday, the former
head of the FBI's organized crime squad in Boston reiterated that
he had no reservations about prosecuting his squad's top informants
_ James ``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   But he also admitted that neither he nor his agents went out of
their way to quiz the criminal partners about their activities.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping up his testimony before US District Judge Mark L. Wolf
in federal court, former FBI supervisor James A. Ring denied that
he kept the FBI out of an investigation of alleged drug dealing and
illegal gambling by Bulger and Flemmi in late 1984 so their roles
as informants would not be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thought didn't cross my mind,'' Ring replied when asked
by Wolf if the FBI declined to take part in the Quincy-based probe
to avoid telling the judge considering a wiretap application that
Bulger and Flemmi were informants. ``I considered them to be fair
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, in the final series of questions put to Ring, wanted to
know how deeply the FBI delved into the ongoing criminal activity
of top-level informants like Bulger and Flemmi _ leaders of the
so-called Irish mob _ and whether informants believed the
information they gave their FBI handlers could be used against
them.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the FBI and the criminals it relied on
for information is at the heart of hearings before Wolf, who must
weigh Flemmi's claim that he and Bulger were given immunity from
prosecution in exchange for information they provided the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, indicted along with Bulger and other reputed Mafia
figures in 1995, is asking that charges against him be dismissed
because any criminal activity he engaged in was authorized by the
FBI. Since the January 1995 indictment alleges a decades-long
conspiracy between the region's Irish and Italian mobs, dismissing
the charges against Flemmi would derail the case against his
alleged co-conspirators as well.
</P>
<P>
   A string of FBI employees, past and present, including Ring,
have testified that Bulger and Flemmi were never given immunity in
exchange for information.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf asked Ring to elaborate on earlier testimony in which he'd
said that he would never ask informants about crimes they were
committing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to investigate that informant, it should be
outside of that relationship,'' said Ring, who headed the organized
crime squad from 1983 until 1990. If he were to ask an informant
directly about his crimes, ``he'd think you're being really
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ring said he was unaware that agents on other squads had dropped
investigations after speaking to Bulger and Flemmi's handler, agent
John Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the hearings, FBI agent James Blackburn testified
that he never pursued allegations that Bulger was shaking down drug
dealers after Connolly told him the ``street talk'' wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   And agent James J. Lavin III testified last month that he
dropped an investigation into a guardrail being installed in front
of Bulger's South Boston liquor store _ allegedly by city workers _
after speaking to Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Wolf, Ring said he never received any information
that agents had tipped off informants to investigations, wiretaps,
or upcoming indictments. Flemmi says he was tipped off to the
January 1995 indictment, but has not said by whom. Bulger fled
before he was indicted and remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you expect that if anything like that happened, efforts
would have been made to keep you from finding out?'' Wolf asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a premise I hadn't considered in 25 years (with the
FBI),'' Ring replied. ``But yes, (I suppose) they would have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
