<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ: AN INDIVIDUAL AMONG INDIVIDUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe the real question is this: Just how much of a team game is
baseball, really?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is not football, where the running back cannot function
without appropriate line play. It's not hockey, where one person
cannot ordinarily skate through the entire opposing team (I know
Bobby Orr did just that on more than one occasion, but show me
another Bobby Orr). It's not basketball, where even Michael Jordan
would still be ringless were it not for the ongoing contributions
of Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is the sum accumulation of many individual occurrences.
Sure, you've got double plays and relay throws and outfielders
backing each other up and pitchers standing behind third base just
in case the throw gets away, but baseball is all about such things
as individual confrontation of pitcher vs. batter and the reality
that if a ball is hit or thrown at someone it is in his best
interest to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers pitch for themselves. Batters hit for themselves.
Fielders catch the ball for themselves. The culture of baseball
acknowledges statistical accomplishment as an end in itself, far
more so than in almost any other sport. You may argue that it
(itals)shouldn't(unitals) be that way, but it most certainly is.
</P>
<P>
   Fractious baseball teams have been successful. If I'm not
mistaken, Tris Speaker and either Duffy Lewis or Harry Hooper were
at such odds one season that the sum total of their dialogue
consisted of, ``I got it,'' followed by, ``You take it.'' Tinker
and Evers didn't share morning coffee, either. The Charley Finley
A's were united solely by their intense hatred of the owner
himself. There were many cabs for many players on those squads.
</P>
<P>
   So how much did it matter, really, whether Jim Leyritz was a
pain-in-the-buttsky? How much did it matter that Leyritz was far
more interested in securing enough at-bats to build up enough
statistics to get himself a very good contract than he was in
whether the Red Sox made the playoffs? Leyritz was a major
contributor to the cause in April, and there is no indication that
he was any more of a ``team'' guy then than he is today in his San
Diego uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball being baseball, we can be sure that Jim Leyritz
wouldn't ever give away an at-bat. He may have whined and moaned
and made a fool out of himself of late, but baseball is a sport in
which his inherent selfishness is actually an asset. By trying to
help himself, he would also help the team. A successful Leyritz
at-bat was a successful Boston Red Sox at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that baseball is the only true everyday sport
among our Big 4. People are thrown together from the middle of
February until the end of September, or longer if they are lucky.
Players spend far more time with their teammates and coaches than
they do with their families, and it could, in theory, become a
problem if it became obvious that 24 people were pulling in one
spiritual direction and one was pulling in another. That, we are
led to believe, is what was going on in the case of Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   So it was left to Dan Duquette to weigh the evidence. His
decision was that Leyritz was an expendable obstructionist. So
determined was the general manager to expunge his organization of
this unhappy employee that he traded him away for players of
dubious value. If any of the players Mr. Duquette has obtained from
San Diego help the Red Sox win so much as one game in 1998, it will
be an upset. Leyritz would have to be an extremely divisive
individual _ and I mean (itals)extremely(unitals) _ to warrant a
trade as apparently one-sided as this in the context of the pennant
race.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox shouldn't be surprised at this turn of events.
Leyritz isn't doing anything he hasn't done before. He is a
professional Me First guy who has always been his own biggest fan.
He was never satisfied during his 5 1/2-year tenure in New York,
where the most games he ever played was 95. The Yankees finally
traded him to the Angels for two minor leaguers following the '96
season. He wasn't happy in Anaheim, either, and he went to Texas in
the Ken Hill deal last July 29.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that Leyritz is a catcher who can't catch, or, at
least, not very well. I don't know or care who promised him what
when he came to Boston. Jimy Williams looked at him behind the
plate long enough to arrive at the same conclusion as Buck
Showalter, Joe Torre, Terry Collins, and Johnny Oates; namely, that
as a catcher, Jim Leyritz is a good meat carver. Nor have I heard
any Red Sox pitchers rushing to the Leyritz defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz is what Jim Leyritz is, that being a fairly
dangerous righthanded hitter who has the requisite intestinal
fortitude in the clutch. His resume includes a game-winning
15th-inning home run in Game 2 of the 1995 playoff series with
Seattle and the dramatic Game 4 home run off Mark Wohlers that
turned out to be the single biggest hit of the 1996 World Series.
There are a whole lot of famous baseball names that have never had
a postseason moment half as meaningful as either one of these.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator with the two big home runs is that
Leyritz wasn't happy when he hit either one. He had been in classic
Leyritz squeaky-wheel form when he hit the home run against
Seattle, so much so that it wouldn't surprise me to learn that some
Yankee players were privately saying, ``Oh, God, anybody but
(itals)him(unitals).'' And he had entered the World Series game
against Atlanta in progress, so you know he was steaming.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, so what? He's always unhappy. We know who he is. The
man looks in the mirror and he sees Johnny Bench, and never mind
that he is 34 years old with the following up-to-the-minute
695-game big league career totals: .270, 76 homers, 331 runs batted
in. When you're 34, and no manager has ever seen fit to play you in
more than 59 percent of your team's games, you ought to get the
message.
</P>
<P>
   But he has value, and he could have been very useful to the Red
Sox when the important games come. Being a first-class pain didn't
prevent him from turning on that Wohlers fastball.
</P>
<P>
   I would have kept him hostage until October. Then, and only
then, would I allow him to go somewhere else to prove for the fifth
time that he is Johnny Blanchard, and not Johnny Bench.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
