<SLUG> BC-TV-COLUMN-LEVESQUE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICK SCHRODER TO REPLACE JIMMY SMITS ON `NYPD BLUE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Schroder may have found the perfect way to dispel any
lingering notion that he is still a child star.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old actor will join the cast of the gritty,
adult-themed ``NYPD Blue'' next season, filling the vacancy Jimmy
Smits will create when he leaves the acclaimed police drama after
appearing in a handful of episodes this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder, best known to TV audiences for the teen roles of Ricky
Stratton in the 1980s sitcom ``Silver Spoons'' and Newt Dobbs in
the 1989 miniseries ``Lonesome Dove,'' will join the 15th Precinct
in a role that is still being fleshed out.
</P>
<P>
   But producer Steven Bochco says there is no doubt Schroder is
the right person to be joining the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a wonderful actor with a kind of physical
and emotional intensity,'' Bochco said Monday, ``because if you
can't stand in against the awesomeness of a Dennis Franz, you're
just going to be floating down the river belly up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochco said Schroder displayed more than enough moxie in a
reading with Franz, who plays Andy Sipowicz, the veteran detective
with the hard shell outside and soft center.
</P>
<P>
   Since the show's second season, Smits has played Bobby Simone,
Sipowicz's parter in crime-fighting. He stepped into the breach
when David Caruso left the show after the first season. Along with
Franz's stellar acting and some dynamite writing, Smits has helped
build ``NYPD Blue'' into one of the most consistently compelling
dramas on network TV.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco himself admitted to having a fairly typical reaction when
the show's casting director suggested Schroder for the new part. He
was among 30 or 40 actors considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us had some sort of old image of Rick Schroder,''
Bochco said, ``but within a minute of his coming into the room it
began to dissipate.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder was on a short list of roughly half a dozen hopefuls
who read for the role opposite Franz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick just knocked us all out,'' Bochco said. ``He knocked
Dennis out. . . . I think that, whatever surprise or doubt anybody
has about Rick's ability to credibly fit into that envirnoment,
those will be dispelled in 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the addition of Schroder may be a cheeky move on Bochco's
part. Smits and Caruso both tended to get women's hearts racing,
especially when they exposed a little skin. Schroder, who hadn't
yet reached 10 when he made his film debut in ``The Champ'' in
1989, doesn't usually fall into the same heartthrob category.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'' will get a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame
next year. So will Dennis Franz, Bob Newhart, Jane Seymour, Buffalo
Bob Smith and Alex Trebek, according to the Hollywood Chamber of
Commerce. . . . When George Clooney leaves NBC's ``ER'' at the end
of next season, he will rejoin Les Moonves, who as president of
Warner Bros. TV signed Clooney to the ``ER'' cast. Moonves is now
president of CBS Entertainment, which will be Clooney's new home
under a two-year development deal. It calls for him to appear in
two TV movies and to serve as executive producer of a new series.
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
