<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNING-BRODERBUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING CO. BUYS RIVAL BRODERBUND IN $417 MILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Learning Co., looking to become a billion-dollar player in the
home software market, said Monday it will buy Broderbund Software
Inc., one of the oldest and best-known names in consumer software.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. software firm is acquiring Novato,
Calif.-based Broderbund _ marketer of the popular Carmen Sandiego
line of educational software _ in a stock swap valued at $417
million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Broderbund shareholders will receive 0.8 share of Learning Co.
stock for each Broderbund share.  &UR;  &LR; That would value Broderbund at
$19.91 a share, based on Monday's closing prices. &UR;  &LR;  Pending
approval by shareholders and regulators, the deal should close by
September.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. was created through a series of acquisitions in the
home and entertainment software arena. It was formerly known as
Softkey International Inc., which bought Learning Co. in 1995 and
adopted its name.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Broderbund also tried to buy Learning Co. that year.
But the company was outbid by Softkey, which acquired Learning Co.
in a $606 million hostile takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1980, Broderbund established itself as a leading
maker of practical, easy-to-use software for home users. Among its
biggest hits are the Carmen Sandiego line of educational programs
for children and Family Tree Maker, a popular genealogy program.
Perhaps Broderbund's most famous product is Myst, a computer puzzle
game that has become one of the most popular home entertainment
programs of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund has recently stumbled, largely due to competition
from the Learning Co. and other makers of home software. In its
fiscal year ending last &UR;  &LR;  August , Broderbund posted a $13.5
million loss on sales of $191 million. Over the past year, the firm
has launched a restructuring that cost the job of its president and
about 150 workers. Broderbund has generated $14 million in profits
in the past two quarters &UR;  &LR; due to increased sales of its educational
software as well as last year's introduction of Riven, the sequel
to Myst.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stephen Dube of Wasserstein Perella Securities in New
York said that Broderbund was simply too small to force its
products onto the shelves of retail software stores. ``They have a
lot of titles. They are basically good titles. But it's basically
like a chicken and egg,'' Dube said. Without the size to win shelf
space from retailers, Broderbund couldn't sell enough software to
increase in size, no matter how good its products might be.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Tanny, Broderbund's vice president of marketing, said
that the acquisition by Learning Co. should finally break the
vicious cycle. ``We matter to a retailer a lot more than we used to
as a result of this merger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. President Kevin O'Leary indicated that the popular
Myst line won't be at the center of his firm's marketing efforts.
``I think the focus has been so intense on Riven and Myst in the
last year that people have forgotten what's under the hood'' at
Broderbund, said O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It was Broderbund's educational and home productivity software
that attracted the Learning Co., according to O'Leary. &UR;  &LR;  ``These
are brands that are right into our sweet spot. &UR;  &LR; You want to get a
product like Carmen Sandiego and make sure that every child who's
eight years old gets to see that product.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Myst and Riven, he said that the Learning Co. would
continue to support the products, but hadn't yet decided whether to
expand the product line. O'Leary left open the possibility that the
company might sell the Myst line to some other software company.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary also cited Broderbund's ownership of Parsons Technology
Inc. a leading mail-order marketer of home software. He said that
Parsons's expertise in direct marketing to consumers would help
expand the Learning Co.'s outreach to home users. He predicted that
by 1999 the Learning Co.'s annual sales, including the addition of
Broderbund, would approach $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Learning Co. posted a $475 million loss on $392.4
million in sales. The loss was due to amortization and merger costs
of $501 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co. stock closed at $27 57/64, down $ 7/64, on the
New York Stock Exchange. Broderbund gained $2 1/4 to $18 3/4 on the
Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
