<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD EASES TEACHER CERTIFICATION STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After deadlocking twice on the issue, the Massachusetts
Board of Education voted Monday to allow a lower passing score for
would-be teachers who took the state's first teacher certification
test.
</P>
<P>
   The lower score means only 44 percent of the 1800 candidates who
took the exam in April flunked it, rather than 59 percent under the
higher standard recommended by a panel of 300 educators. As a
result, 260 candidates who would have been barred from seeking jobs
as teachers will now be certified to instruct children.
</P>
<P>
   In move that surprised many at the contentious meeting, board
chairman John R. Silber cast the deciding vote to lower the
standard. Silber had been a vociferous supporter of the tougher
certification standard, but ultimately changed his vote in order to
break a 4-4 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Silber said the board should give deference to acting Education
Commissioner Frank W. Haydu III's arguments that many of the
candidates were unaware of the stringency of the exam and that the
state could better defend itself against lawsuits if it gave
initial testtakers more leeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the commissioner has recommended is simply to increase
the chances of making this reform stick,'' Silber said.
</P>
<P>
   Silber said it was ``regrettable'' that the lower standard would
mean 260 candidates who would have failed could be certified, but
with a large percentage still not passing the exam it nonetheless
represented ``a very big step toward improving the quality of
education in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every board member agreed. Student representative Micah
Silva, who voted against the lower standard, said it would not only
affect the 260 teaching candidates, but their students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes one incompetent teacher teaching biology to
affect an entire class,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silva disputed the idea that the exam was unusually tough,
pointing out that the questions to evaluate candidates' literacy
skills are similar to those asked of tenth-graders under the new
student testing standards.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haydu had the power under the state's education reform
law to set the passing score himself, he asked the board to endorse
his position that a lower threshhold be adopted for the short-term.
Since this is the first year the test is being given, Haydu said,
``We are giving the benefit of the doubt to the test-taker.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers, including the attorney general's office, also advised
it would be ``safer'' to adopt the lower standard in the event
lawsuits are brought, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates have complained that they were given little
notice that the April test would actually count. And with some
minority groups scoring substantially lower than whites on the
test, there also is concern that a discrimination lawsuit could be
brought, even though the test was reviewed to eliminate any
cultural or ethnic biases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Abigail Thernstrom, another board member who voted against the
lower standard, said, however, the panel's decision should not be
driven by the fear of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is questionable that we should be making policy on a legal
challenge that has yet to occur,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The board was under pressure to make a decision Monday because
candidates who failed the April test can retake it for free, and
the next test will be administered on July 11. It will be the last
one with the reduced standard: Higher scores will begin taking
effect with the following test, scheduled for Oct. 3, according to
the board's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schaeffer of FairTest, a Cambridge, Mass. monitoring
group that opposes teacher certification tests, contended that the
fact the state set the passing score after _ and not before _
candidates took the exam demonstrates that it was arbitrary, based
on politics rather than merit.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer said a certification test in Alabama was struck down
by the courts in the 1980s because the cutoff scores were set in a
similar fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
