u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-CHELSEA-BOS &LR;      06-22 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CHELSEA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SAYS ANTI-TOBACCO FIGHT WILL CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It's been a tough week for Senator John
McCain, former Vietnam prisoner of war and possible Republican
presidential candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile, anti-smoking legislation that he sponsored
died in Congress, and, ``I did something else last week I regret
terribly.'' He told a ``stupid, offensive, cruel joke'' that made
fun of, among others, President Clinton's daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to you today a bit depressed,'' McCain said Monday at a
luncheon attended by several journalists at the Inn at Harvard
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, who is running for reelection to the Senate from
Arizona this year and says he won't decide until after the election
whether to seek the White House, swore off insulting jokes in the
future and vowed to continue pushing for restrictions on tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   By spending $40 million on advertising, McCain said, the tobacco
companies ``were able to change the frame of the debate'' with the
public, emphasizing the bill's ``big tax'' aspect rather than its
anti-smoking objective.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the anti-tobacco legislation, which would have
increased taxes on cigarettes and raised $516 billion over 25
years, ``renewed my zeal for ... campaign finance reform,'' McCain
said. He said ``huge amounts of soft money'' _ dollars that are
given to political parties in unregulated quantities _ were
critical in defeating the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be more and more scandals, because there's
just too much money there,'' McCain said. But he conceded that
Republicans who vote in primaries may not be as enamored of
restrictions on campaign contributions as some other voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some conservatives have been uneasy with me for a long time,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute discussion of various topics, McCain criticized
President Clinton for ``kind of a rudderless foreign policy,''
which McCain said he fears may have more serious and widespread
consequences in the conflict in the Kosovo province of Serbia even
than it did in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my major problem with the president, who has the
greatest communicative skills of any president I've seen in my
adult life,'' McCain said. The United States has ``a posture ...
not a position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to send young people there,'' McCain said, but
Clinton has neither laid out a plan for intervention in that
explosive part of the world, nor outlined the reasons for becoming
involved to keep the local conflict from spreading to such
countries as Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration has not had a conceptual framework as to
where the threats to our national security lie, and where the
United States' national interests lie.''
</P>
<P>
   With McCain weighing a presidential run in 2000, he was asked
about the prospect of having his personal life in the media.
McCain's problems in his first marriage, and a more recent
drug-dependency issue in his family, have been documented, though
not widely publicized.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as those personal issues are concerned,'' he said, ``I
will continue to maintain it's a personal issue'' and refuse to
discuss them, even if he seeks the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar continues to change as far as the amount of disclosure
that candidates have to make about their personal lives, and I
think we all know that,'' he said. ``I believe that people have the
right to privacy, and ... I will continue to maintain that it's
nobody's business. And if that is something that hurts me, then
that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ``My life is very well-known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
