<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT STRIKES DOWN FINE, CALLING IT EXCESSIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court told the U.S.
government Monday to return most of the $357,000 in cash it seized
from an international traveler who failed to report all the money
he was carrying.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision, the court struck down as unconstitutionally
excessive the U.S. government's seizure of $357,144 from Hosep
Bajakajian, who willfully violated a federal law that requires
overseas travelers to tell federal authorities when they are
transporting more than $10,000 in currency.
</P>
<P>
   The law, designed to trap drug dealers, requires that people
found to have violated the reporting requirement surrender any
property ``involved in such offense'' to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that united its most conservative and liberal
members, the court said the amount of the forfeiture violated the
Eighth Amendment's prohibition on excessive fines because the total
seized was ``grossly disproportionate'' to the offense of not
reporting it.
</P>
<P>
   The case arose on June 9, 1994, when Bajakajian, his wife and
two daughters were waiting at Los Angeles International Airport to
board a flight to Italy. Customs inspectors, using
currency-sniffing dogs, discovered about $230,000 in the family's
checked baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Customs inspectors then approached Bajakajian and his wife,
informed them of the reporting requirement and asked them if they
had any more money. Bajakajian said he had $8,000 and his wife
another $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, a search of their carry-on bags, wallet and purse
brought the total yield to $357,144. The inspectors seized the
money and arrested Bajakajian.
</P>
<P>
   Bajakajian, who admitted a ``distrust for the government'' after
growing up as an Armenian minority in Syria, pleaded guilty to
failing to report the currency, but the government was never able
to connect the cash to any illegal enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   A federal district court ruled forfeiture of all the money would
violate the Eighth Amendment and ordered the government to return
all but $15,000 of the seized currency.
</P>
<P>
   The court also fined Bajakajian $5,000 and placed him on
probation for three years. Customs officials appealed the decision
to try to keep all the seized cash.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas, among the high court's most
conservative members, was joined in his majority decision by
liberal Justice John Paul Stevens and three other colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said Bajakajian's offense was ``minimal;'' hurt no one
and, if undetected, would have deprived the government only of the
information that $357,144 had left the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no inherent proportionality in such a forfeiture,''
Thomas wrote. ``It is impossible to conclude for example that the
harm respondent caused is anywhere near 30 times greater than that
caused by a hypothetical drug dealer who willfully fails to report
taking $12,000 out of the country in order to purchase drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer also concurred with Thomas' opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said the court
failed to recognize the government's legitimate need to seize money
in its fight against smugglers and illegal drug traffickers.
Kennedy also mocked the majority in noting that Bajakajian admitted
to lying to customs officials and would lose only $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money launderers will rejoice to know they face forfeitures of
less than 5 percent of the money transported, provided they hire
accomplished liars to carry their money for them,'' Kennedy wrote.
He was joined in dissent by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxx End of Story
</P>
</TEXT>
