<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1080 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NUKE-575&AMP;ADD-N     06-22 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NUKE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TO SELL 2 NUCLEAR POWER STATIONS TO INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia has agreed to sell two nuclear power stations to
India, defying calls to punish New Delhi because of its nuclear
testing.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Russia's Atomic Energy Ministry concluded the deal,
which is worth $3 billion or more to Russia's cash-starved nuclear
energy industry, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale has became an important test of Washington's ability to
marshal world opinion against India.
</P>
<P>
   Following unsuccessful U.S. efforts to persuade Russia not to
sell reactors to Iran or advanced anti-aircraft systems to Cyprus,
the Indian sale has become another indication of America's limited
influence with the Yeltsin government.
</P>
<P>
   The United States tried to head off the sale even before India
stunned the world by exploding nuclear devices in May. After
India's nuclear tests, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright again
urged Moscow to abandon the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the civilian plants themselves will have
little military significance. But U.S. officials say they violate
an important principle: that the world community should not engage
in nuclear cooperation with aspiring nuclear-weapon states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends the wrong the wrong message to the world and to
India and Pakistan,'' said James Rubin, the State Department
spokesman. ``Instead of pursuing business as usual, we should be
scaling back this cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials, for their part, hailed the sale, saying it
will help thwart the U.S.-led effort to impose economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has long enjoyed close ties to India. During Soviet days,
Russia saw India as a counterweight to China, as well as a customer
for weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   India's rivalry with Pakistan was not a major worry for Moscow.
Moscow had little love for Pakistan, which cooperated with U.S.
efforts to funnel assistance to Afghan rebels following the Soviet
invasion of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tutelage of Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov, Russia
has maintained close ties with New Delhi for foreign policy as well
as commercial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian officials, India is now the second-largest
purchaser of Russian arms. Just last week India's deputy defense
minister, Adjit Kumar, visited Moscow to discuss the purchase of
additional Sukoi-30 fighter bombers, another multi-billion dollar
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar visited the Zhukovsky airfield outside Moscow to observe
the latest model of the warplane, which can be equipped with bombs,
cluster munitions, air-to-air and air-to-surface missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has also promised to sell attack submarines and is
discussing the sale of anti-ship and other weapons.
</P>
<P>
   While the disagreement over the nuclear power plant erupted into
the open Monday, Russia and the United States have been at odds
over the nuclear deal for years.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the dispute go back to 1992, when nuclear
suppliers agreed to a broadened system of export controls.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea behind the 1992 ``suppliers' agreement'' was that
countries that do not have nuclear weapons should not get the
benefit of nuclear energy without committing themselves to use it
only for peaceful purposes.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, the ``suppliers' agreement'' forbade
suppliers from exporting nuclear technology to aspiring nuclear
powers that do not subject all their nuclear sites to international
monitoring. The effect was to preclude nuclear sales to India since
it will not agree to such far-reaching safeguards.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russia joined the 1992 ``suppliers' agreement.'' But economic
pressure on its nuclear industry prompted Russian officials to look
for a way to sell two 1,000-megawatt reactors to India.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials argued that Moscow had a right to proceed with
the India deal on the grounds that the sale was contemplated by a
1988 Soviet-Indian agreement, an argument Washington flatly
rejects.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiations between Russia and India dragged on, India's
nuclear tests raised the stakes. At first, Russian officials said
the Indian reactor deal was under review.
</P>
<P>
   Washington urged Moscow to drop the deal, but never sought to
link U.S. support for Western financial aid to Russia with Russian
cooperation on security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's new atomic energy minister, Yevgeny Adamov, pressed
hard for the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Atomic Energy Ministry has become increasingly
dependent on exports to pay its workers and proceed with its heady
plans to build more nuclear plants in Russia. Yevgeny Reshnetnikov,
a senior atomic energy official, said last year that the value of
the sale was $1.5 billion to $2 billion for each of the reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Adamov flew to India last weekend to cement the deal with the
chief of India's Atomic Energy Commission, R. Chidambaram.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear plants, which are to be located at Kudankulam, will
be light water reactors, meaning that ordinary water is used to
moderate the nuclear reaction. A byproduct is spent fuel with
plutonium and other highly radioactive products, which can be
processed to make bomb ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Russia argues that the two plants would be for civilian use and
would be subject to international monitoring to prevent them from
contributing to India's nuclear potential. The Russian reactors
will take eight years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials say they hope the deal will encourage nations
to engage in nuclear cooperation. India has 10 nuclear plants, but
they are much smaller, often unreliable and meet only a tiny
fraction of the nation's energy needs.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to blunt Western criticism, Valery Nesterushkin, a
spokesman for Russia's Foreign Ministry, said the deal ``will not
create a precedent for future agreements on nuclear cooperation
with India'' because India has refused to subject all of its
nuclear plants to monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Bunn, a former Energy Department official and a
specialist at Harvard University, said the sale would not be
militarily significant because the Indians already had nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But he said it was still an important setback. ``Nuclear
cooperation with countries that are flouting nuclear rules
undermines global efforts to stem the spread of nuclear weapons,''
Bunn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
