</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCESSIVE-FINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES $357,000 FINE ``EXCESSIVE'' AND UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in its 208-year history, the
Supreme Court on Monday rejected a government fine as excessive and
therefore a violation of the Eighth Amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   It ruled that federal officials must return the bulk of a
$357,144 penalty against a Los Angeles man.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision, the court said that the government cannot
necessarily keep all of the money seized from people trying to take
large amounts of unreported cash out of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires that anyone who transports more than
$10,000 in cash or other ``monetary instruments'' out of the
country must report the amount to the Treasury Department. People
who fail to report it can be sentenced to up to five years in
prison and fined up to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires the people to forfeit the unreported money
to the government.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Clarence Thomas, writing for the court, said the
forfeiture rule amounts to a fine and that in some cases the fine
can be disproportionate to the offense, violating the Eighth
Amendment's ban on excessive fines.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time that the high court, since it began meeting
in 1790, has ruled that a fine violated the amendment, which says,
``Excessive bail shall not be required, nor excessive fines
imposed, nor cruel and unusual punishment inflicted.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision means that the government must return most of the
$357,144 seized in June 1994 from Hosep Krikor Bajakajian when he
tried to leave the country with the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great victory for the defense,'' said James E. Blatt,
the lawyer representing Bajakajian, who owns two gas stations in
Los Angeles. ``This case will benefit other defendants who have had
their money taken from them,'' Blatt said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he and other legal observers said they did not expect
the ruling to significantly affect the government's ability to
seize money or property in cases involving illegal drug activity.
Many of those forfeitures are not considered punishment and
therefore are not treated as fines.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell said officials were
disappointed by the ruling. But the chief counsel for the Office of
National Drug Control Policy, Chuck Blanchard, said, ``I see it
having very little or no effect on drug cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Bajakajian, 41, was detained by U.S. Customs agents in Los
Angeles as he, his wife and two daughters waited to board an
airplane to Italy. Their final destination was Syria, Bajakajian's
native land.
</P>
<P>
   Using dogs trained to sniff and detect currency, customs
inspectors discovered the cash that Bajakajian had not reported in
his luggage. The inspectors seized the money and arrested him for
trying to leave the country with unreported cash.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers explained later that Bajakajian failed to report the
money because he did not trust customs agents, especially those in
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the incident, U.S. District Judge John Davies in
Los Angeles concluded that the money lawfully belonged to
Bajakajian. He had earned or borrowed it from friends and was
carrying it to Syria to repay relatives who had helped him get
started in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't drug money. This wasn't gambling money. This
wasn't stolen money. This wasn't money being laundered for any
reason,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Bajakajian pleaded guilty to failing to report his money to the
Treasury Department and was sentenced to three year's probation. He
was also fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davies, refusing to uphold a total forfeiture of Bajakajian's
money, ordered that $15,000 of the unreported cash be turned over
to the government.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed, upholding the
$15,000 forfeiture.
</P>
<P>
   During his appeals, Bajakajian's money remained in government
hands.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Supreme Court said the lower courts were right
and that he should get his money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever his other vices, (Bajakajian) does not fit into the
class of persons for whom the statute was principally designed: He
is not a money launderer, a drug trafficker, or a tax evader,''
Thomas wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The justice added that forcing Bajakajian to turn over the full
$357,144 would be ``grossly disproportional to the gravity of his
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was joined Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' split with the four dissenters was unusual, since he
rarely votes against the conservative Rehnquist and Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the dissenting justices, Kennedy said that opening
the door to fights over whether a fine is excessive ``is disturbing
both for its specific holding and for the broader upheaval it
foreshadows.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that ``By invoking the excessive fines clause with
excessive zeal, the majority may in the long run encourage Congress
to circumvent it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
