<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JOHN HARKES STILL ROOTS FOR HIS PALS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It was not easy to be John Harkes on Sunday. Some of his
best friends were in Lyons, mostly sitting on the U.S. bench. He
was even farther away, celebrating Father's Day in Virginia, eating
his heart out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have contributed,'' Harkes said Monday by telephone.
``I'm a player that can go forward, make a tackle, make a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tackling or running, Harkes was watching television
as his former teammates _ and maybe his future teammates _ lost to
Iran, 2-1, and were eliminated from advancing in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through so much hard work, and now the World Cup is
over so fast,'' Harkes said. ``I feel for the players. I'm part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Harkes has taken the high road, but he also knows
that Coach Steve Sampson is gone as soon as the U.S. plane lands on
home soil after the Yugoslavia game on Thursday in Nantes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I should be there,'' Harkes said. ``I thought I could
contribute something with leadership. We had such good chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Until May, John Harkes was the feisty midfielder with the yellow
captain's armband. The man had stuck out his chin and his elbows
during the qualifying games, the hard duty in El Salvador and Costa
Rica and Mexico. If an opponent needed a little manners or posture
correction, Harkes would do the job. Sometimes he even tried to
straighten out the officials.
</P>
<P>
   He was the captain, a trifle testy, maybe a step slower than he
used to be, but a veteran of the British leagues, a hard-boot
professional. Then in one unexplained action, Sampson ripped away
the armband and the team jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hugged me after the Portland game and said, `You're going
to your third World Cup,''' Harkes said. ``Then he cut me. The way
it was handled was so unprofessional.''
</P>
<P>
   Word has come down that Sampson felt that Harkes would not move
back on defense, to which Harkes replied, ``I've been known to play
more than one position.'' It was also fairly clear that Sampson
felt Harkes was smirking and shuffling during practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that body-language stuff,'' Harkes said Monday.
``I was the captain. I was leading in my way, keeping the team
together. We beat Brazil. We had some great games. Steve is the
only one who ever questioned my leadership. I think it was evident
they lacked leadership. Where was the fighting spirit?''
</P>
<P>
   He has nothing bad to say about anybody who wore the U.S.
uniform in the losses to Germany and Iran, but he does question the
lineups and the formations chosen by a coach who never played or
coached at an exalted level until the American federation put him
in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The former captain will say he did not understand sticking Eric
Wynalda, his best buddy, up front all by himself against Germany:
``He didn't have a chance. He was out there playing against four
backs, like he was a defender.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Iran, Sampson pasted together a lineup that looked like
a mixer on the first night of a cruise. The Americans might as well
have worn stickers that said, ``Hi, My Name Is ...''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Sampson was questioned closely about not using
Wynalda, and he said he would not change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange when you don't see Eric Wynalda out on the
field,'' Harkes said. ``He's our all-time leading scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Harkes said, the Yanks didn't play badly for the first
34 or 40 minutes, hitting the goal posts or crossbar three times.
``We were unlucky, you can say that, but you have to finish it,''
Harkes said.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes keeps in touch. Another of his best friends, Tab Ramos,
called him from a mobile phone on the field a couple of hours
before the Germany game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tab told me, `We miss you, you should be here,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Harkes plays for DC United in Major League Soccer, has
time for his family and comments on the World Cup for the Voice of
America.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the team, he sometimes says: ``I have my
theories. I'm saving some of it for my book, which will be out in
November.''
</P>
<P>
   He burns no bridges, because John Harkes, still only 29, sees
himself back on the U.S. team, as soon as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, Steve made the decision, which was a bad
one,'' Harkes said. ``I look forward to playing again.'' He can
even see himself wearing the captain's armband again: ``That's up
to the new coach. I have a lot of good years left.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, 1998 may be the year that John Harkes stayed
home and felt terrible for his national team, watching games he
thought he could have affected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
