<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-JASPER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE AND FEDERAL PROSECUTORS TRY TO DECIDE HOW TO HANDLE SUSPECTS
IN DRAGGING DEATH OF BLACK MAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
BEAUMONT _ Jasper County authorities will ask a grand jury July 6
to return capital murder indictments against two or possibly all
three white men accused of dragging a black man behind a pickup for
almost three miles along a winding rural highway.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investigators found James Byrd Jr.'s head and right arm more
than a mile from where his torso was dumped in front of a country
church.
</P>
<P>
   If indicted and convicted on capital murder charges, Shawn Berry
and Bill King, both 23 and from Jasper, and Russell Brewer Jr., 31,
of Sulphur Springs, would face a possible death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The three remain in the Jasper County Jail. They were arrested
about 12 hours after residents of the Huff Creek area reported
finding Byrd's mangled remains on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents have formed a special task force to investigate the
crime, but no federal charges have been filed thus far.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Michael Bradford in Beaumont said Monday that
federal prosecutors may await the outcome of state prosecution
before deciding whether to file federal hate crime charges.
Bradford said that if one of the defendants does not get the death
penalty from state charges, he could later be tried in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   Local Jasper County officials have said they hoped federal
prosecutors would take the lead in the prosecution because a trio
of capital-murder trials could cost the cash-strapped county
government up to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said his office expects to make a decision about
federal prosecution ``within the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the task force's investigation is drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Pat Hardy in Jasper County said
Monday that his office has not yet decided if it will seek capital
charges against all three of the defendants or just two of them.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, the first arrested and the owner of the pickup allegedly
used in the crime, gave investigators a detailed confession that
implicated the other two suspects. According to this account, Berry
offered Byrd a ride and that the other two defendants took Byrd to
a rural location, beat him until he was unconscious and used a
towing chain wrapped around his ankles to drag him along Huff Creek
Road.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Monday that Berry remains the only one of the
defendants to cooperate with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray said earlier that his office
may offer reduced charges to one of the defendants in exchange for
testimony against the other two. He would not say which defendant
might be offered that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, capital murder is defined as a murder committed
during the commission of a select few crimes. Assault does not fit
that category.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy would not specify what might make the Byrd murder a
capital offense, but from early on officials have mentioned
kidnapping as a possibility. Hardy noted that forensic evidence
shows Byrd fought to keep his attackers from removing him from the
back of the pickup before he was beaten and dragged. A number of
items linked to the defendants _ including tools, a compact disc
and a lighter _ were found at the scene and appeared to have been
thrown from the truck during a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local law enforcement officials are gearing up for
the next chapter of what has become an ongoing saga in Jasper _ a
Ku Klux Klan rally scheduled for Saturday in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Officers would not divulge their plans. But up to 200 city,
county, state and federal lawmen are expected to be in town
Saturday to make sure no trouble breaks out during a rally by
Klansmen from Vidor, Waco and northern Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
