A1092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NYT &LR;      06-22 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANIA MOVES INTO SECOND ROUND WITH 2-1 WIN OVER ENGLAND  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOULOUSE, France _ Britannia, the crowd insisted, rules the
waves, but England looked a mess on plain old grass Monday,
crashing to a 2-1 defeat against a slick Romanian side that took
its chances with aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, clinched by a late goal from right back Dan
Petrescu, assured Romania of advancement to the round of sixteen in
the World Cup and left England facing a tough contest against
Colombia on Friday. A defeat in that match would send England and
its large following home.
</P>
<P>
   Police deployed massive reinforcements ahead of the game after
English hooligans went on the rampage in Marseilles last week and
German thugs beat a French policeman into unconsciousness in the
northern town of Lens on Sunday. But there were no immediate
reports of serious incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Sepp Blatter, the president of the international soccer
federation, FIFA, said before the match that European governments
should do more to stop thugs traveling to games. ``They must be
aware that football is more than kicking a ball around,'' Blatter
said. ``It's the social and cultural aspects. It is up to national
authorities to make laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But the European Union allows free movement of people among its
15 member states and it was not clear how governments could clamp
down. The violence in Lens appeared to be linked to German rightist
groups and Chancellor Helmut Kohl said the incidents were ``a
scandal for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   English fans packed the stadium in this southern city Monday
night, vastly outnumbering the Romanian supporters, but they could
do little to raise their side from mediocrity. Romania, whose team
reached the quarterfinals of the last World Cup in the United
States, was faster, more assured, and razor-sharp in front of goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gheorghe Hagi, no longer the fleet-footed player who made
such an impression in America but still a considerable force, who
opened the way to victory early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing off a challenge from England's Graeme Le Saux, he cut
into the penalty box before lobbing a perfect pass to Viorel
Moldovan. The center-forward brought the ball down with his chest
and blasted the ball past David Seaman, whose main activity Monday
was fishing the ball out the net.
</P>
<P>
   Poor England. Manager Glenn Hoddle had taken off midfielder Paul
Ince midway through the first half, and Ince's guts and strength
were sorely missed as the English side looked for an equalizer.
Star striker Alan Shearer was often isolated up front, and the
English midfield looked about as capable of inspiration as a brick
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owen, Owen,'' the crowd chanted, calling for 18-year-old
Liverpool striker Michael Owen to be brought on. With 20 minutes to
go, Hoddle finally ceded to the pressure, and there Owen was in the
79th minute to sweep home a low cross from Shearer as if it was the
most natural thing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   England, one of the tournament's fancied teams, seemed to have
saved the day and even looked briefly capable of a late victory.
But with minutes left, a long pass found Petrescu bustling into the
left side of penalty box with English left half Le Saux at his
side.
</P>
<P>
   Flailing haplessly like a fish out of water, Le Saux allowed
Petrescu _ a teammate on England's Chelsea club team _ to move past
him, steady himself, and slip the ball between Seaman's legs with a
left-footed shot that had all the power of water dripping from a
tap.
</P>
<P>
   Owen, a diminutive figure but a bundle of energy, came roaring
back, and a late shot from him hit the post. But it was not
England's night, and in the end it was two Romanians who play in
England _ Moldovan of Coventry and Petrescu of Chelsea _ who sank
the English team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are bitterly disappointed,'' said Hoddle. ``I thought we
could go and win the game after we scored, not lose it.'' The coach
went on to defend his team, saying ``we will win more games than we
lose if we play like that,'' but his words lacked conviction. As
Hoddle knows, the task against an improving Colombian team will be
anything but easy.
</P>
</TEXT>
