<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAURO-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT TRYING TO UNSEAT TEXAS GOV. BUSH LASHES SON'S ROLE IN
PRESIDENT BUSH'S CAMPAIGNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
WASHINGTON _ Texas Democratic gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro
arrived in the nation's capital Monday to scoop up some much needed
cash and dish out criticism of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, linking
him to the infamous ``Willy Horton'' ads and his father's ``no new
taxes'' pledge.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mauro, who will appear at fund-raisers with the Clintons on
Tuesday, appeared as eager to discuss his Republican opponent's
vulnerabilities as a presidential candidate as he was to criticize
Bush's performance as governor.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington last week, Bush was treated as a potential
presidential candidate by lobbyists and GOP party loyalists who
crowded into his fund-raiser, which raised over a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who is trailing Bush by 53 percentage points in the
latest public opinion poll, attributed the governor's strong
showing to the healthy economy under President Clinton and the
popularity of Bush's parents in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is riding the wings of popularity of two popular
presidents. But if he ever jumps into the race for president those
wings of popularity will fall off and he will have to construct his
own wings on the way down,'' Mauro told a National Press Club
audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauro suggested that as a presidential candidate the
governor would be saddled with baggage from the presidential
campaigns of his father, George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro revisited the controversial 1988 Willy Horton commercial,
which Republicans used against Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis,
the Massachusetts governor, about a black murderer who brutalized a
couple while on furlough from a Massachusetts prison.
</P>
<P>
   While the commercial was not made by the Bush campaign, the
president was linked to the spot that critics said played on
whites' fear of black men.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said that in 1988, George W. Bush was ``in the
decision-making seat (as a campaign aide) when President Bush's
campaign refused to repudiate the now infamous Willy Horton ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Bush had broken his pledge to halt prisoners' early
release. As a result, Lawrence Russell Brewer, one of three white
men accused of killing a black man in Jasper recently, was let out
of prison early, Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush had kept his promise Brewer would have been in prison
instead of making mischief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker dismissed Mauro's attacks
as `` the same old distortions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Garry Mauro's abysmally low showing in the polls show that
people of Texas know better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Bush ended early release for anyone sentenced since he
became governor. But she said the Legislature worried it would be
unconstitutional to approve a law retroactively.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer was sentenced before Bush was elected.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Bush should have tried harder to prod the Legislature
into passing a law that would have withstood a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also suggested Bush's opponents would link him to his
father's fateful reversal of his ``no new taxes'' pledge because he
had refused to endorse the Democrat's proposal to eliminate a sales
tax on vehicles in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read my lips, George Bush called a major tax cut for average
Texans reckless,'' Mauro said. ``I wouldn't want to depend on those
wings to fly the Bush plane on the way to the New Hampshire primary
if Steve Forbes is anywhere near.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 primaries, Forbes, the wealthy magazine mogul,
caused GOP frontrunner Bob Dole to slide in the polls by attacking
him for voting for tax increases in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   While Mauro attacked Bush for accepting money from those tied to
the managed care industry, he indicated that he would not reject
such contributions to his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he saw nothing wrong with leaving Texas to look for
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any place, anytime anywhere people will get together in groups
of two and three and give me financial support I will be there,''
said Mauro, who is trailing Bush in fund-raising as well as poll
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro will attend a $1,000 a person fund-raising reception with
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton followed by a $5,000-a-person
dinner with President Clinton. The campaign hopes those two events
will raise $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mauro will attend a $1,000-a-couple fund-raiser in
El Paso with Vice President Al Gore that officials hope will raise
another $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has known the Clintons since they worked together on the
1972 McGovern campaign in Texas. Mauro has headed Clinton's Texas
presidential efforts in both campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has to do with old-fashioned friendship,'' said
Mauro of the Clintons' efforts on his behalf. &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxxxxxxxxx End of Story
</P>
</TEXT>
