   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS (Washington) _ A sharply divided Supreme Court set
a highly restrictive standard for determining when school districts
can be found liable under Federal law for a teacher's sexual
harassment of a student. A harassment victim can recover damages
from the school district only if a school official with the
authority to intervene actually knew of the teacher's misconduct
and, acting with ``deliberate indifference,'' failed to stop it,
the Court said in an opinion by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor. The
vote was 5 to 4. The decision came in a case from a school district
near Austin, Texas. By Linda Greenhouse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FISH-LOGO (Republic, Mo.) _ Eight years ago, on a whim, Marilyn
Shexsnayder entered the contest to design a logo for her hometown.
She was a stockbroker, not an artist. But using her colored pencils
and her computer she drew an oustretched hand, a family of four in
silhouette, and, to portray the centrality of religion in this old
railroad town with more than 25 churches and about 8,000 people,
she sketched the simple fish that she had regarded from childhood
as a universal symbol of faith. She won the logo contest and $100
prize. Now, suddenly, the little fish is causing an awfully big
splash. Someone complained about the fish to the American Civil
Liberties Union, and in February the organization sent a letter
asking the mayor to delete the fish from the logo because the fish
was ``unmistakably identified with Christianity.'' By Laurie
Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
