   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHUMER-FUNDS (New York) _ In his race for the U.S. Senate,
Rep. Charles E. Schumer has raised more in donations than any other
challenger in congressional history, collecting well over $10
million. His treasury not only dwarfs those of the other Democrats
in the race, Geraldine Ferraro and Mark Green; Schumer is also the
second highest fundraiser among all Senate candidates nationwide.
By Clifford Levy.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BORDER-TOWNS (El Paso, Texas) _ Four years after the North
American Free Trade Agreement lowered trade barriers, the cities
along Texas's long border with Mexico that had hoped to benefit are
instead struggling to become more than glorified truck stops as
they watch their manufacturing jobs go south by the thousands.
Almost everywhere else in the United States, the economy is booming
and the national unemployment rate is the lowest in nearly 30
years. But along the border unemployment persists at two and three
times the national rate, and incomes remain far below state and
national averages. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUIT-FLA (Undated) _ A Florida appeals court on Monday
struck down a $750,000 jury verdict against the Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp. in a landmark cigarette case that had marked one of
the few victories ever by an individual smoker in a tobacco
company. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUKE (Moscow) _ Ignoring American protests, Russia has
sold two nuclear power stations to India, Russian and India
officials said on Monday. The nuclear deal, which is worth more
than $2 billion to Russia's cash-strapped nuclear energy ministry,
is part of an broad array of civilian and military technology
Moscow is planning to sell despite India's decision to conduct five
nuclear tests, a decision that will almost certainly help India
break out of its diplomatic isolation. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   LOTT-BUDGET (Washington) _ Tucked away in spending bill under
consideration in the Senate is a $50-million expenditure that would
benefit not only Mississippi, the home state of the Senate's
majority leader, Trent Lott, but would almost surely go to an
industry with long ties to Lott's family. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8:30 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-REVENUE (London) _ The recent drop in oil prices, which
began in October and accelerated recently, has prompted several
oil-producing countries to trim spending in anticipation of less
revenue. In the last month, Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil
producer, has quietly borrowed some $2 billion from its banks to
help pay for public spending program as it prepares to reduce its
budget by at least 10 percent and raise fees on government services
_ all to offset the most serious fall in oil revenues in a decade.
By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court struck for the first
time against the federal government's aggressive use of forfeiture,
ruling that a forfeiture intended as punishment is unconstitutional
if the amount seized is ``grossly disproportional'' to the gravity
of the offense. Applying that test in a sharply contested 5-4
ruling, the court went on to declare that the government could not
constitutionally seize $357,144 in undeclared cash that a Los
Angeles man and his family had attempted to bring in their luggage
on a flight to Cyprus to repay a family debt. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
