   &UR; ENGAGING CHINA IS NOT ENDORSING CHINA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Madeleine K. Albright &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright sets out the
Clinton administration policy on a new relationship with China.
(slugged: BC-CHINA-ALBRIGHT-OPED-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY AMERICA and CHINA MUST BE FRIENDS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Li Zhaoxing &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   China's ambassador to the United States outlines Beijing's
policy on a new working friendship with the United States.
(slugged: BC-CHINA-US-FRIENDSHIP-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON SHOULD MEET WITH TIANANMEN VICTIMS' FAMILIES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Michael Jendrzejczyk &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Washington director of Human Rights Watch, Asia Division,
writes that despite China's token gestures on ``improving'' human
rights, torture and ill-treatment in prisons and labor camps is
actually widespread. President Clinton ought to meet with family
members of the victims of the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, he
writes, as well as convince the Chinese government to grant
unrestricted access to Tibet and Xinjiang by foreign journalists
and aid monitors. (slugged: BC-CHINA-HUMAN-RIGHTS-CLINTON-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOWARD A U.S.-CHINA BALANCE OF POWER FOR THE 21ST CENTURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Robert Scalapino &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here the distinguished Robson research professor of government
emeritus at the University of California, Berkeley, writes of a
complex array of competing interests in the U.S.-China
rapprochement, which must be dealt with if we are to relegate to
history the global wars of the past 100 years. (slugged:
BC-CHINA-COMPLEX-CHANGING-NYTSF)
</P>
