<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLDCUP-US-475&AMP;ADD-N     06-22 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCUP-US-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DOES U.S. SOCCER GO FROM HERE?  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORNIC, France _ The U.S. soccer team washed ashore on the
Atlantic Coast Monday, its World Cup hopes shipwrecked by Sunday's
2-1 loss to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the defeat was a chance to advance to the second round,
to grab the interest of average sports fans and to give any kind of
boost to attendance in the second half of the Major League Soccer
season.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game that was penciled in as a win. Instead the
Americans lost one of the most significant matches in the history
of U.S. soccer. As the team heads home after Thursday's meaningless
game against Yugoslavia in Nantes, the immediate future is
uncertain for the U.S. soccer federation, Coach Steve Sampson and
many of his players.
</P>
<P>
   The federation's stated hope of winning a World Cup in 2010 now
seems hopelessly premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's going to be a tremendous amount of
disappointment from the fans and the general public,'' defender
Alexi Lalas said Monday after the team had a light workout on the
Brittany coast. ``In the past four years there has been an increase
in awareness of the team, and with that comes expectations to
succeed at a high level.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is undeniably a more talented team, and a more
assertively attacking team, than it was under Coach Bora
Milutinovic's conservative, defensive approach. Sampson's team has
previously defeated Brazil, Argentina, Nigeria and Mexico. But this
team did not demonstrate that it had improved in the World Cup.
Milutinovic's 1994 team advanced to the second round, and this one
did not.
</P>
<P>
   Such disastrous defeats are seldom tolerated in the most fervid
soccer countries. Carlos Alberto Parreira, who produced a champion
with Brazil in 1994, did not even survive the first round in 1998
before he was dumped by Saudi Arabia. And Cha Bum Kun got his
walking papers after South Korea was embarrassed 5-0 by the
Netherlands. But this being the United States, where soccer moms
are a more valued constituency than soccer coaches, Sampson is
still a member in good standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me what Steve did wrong,'' Alan Rothenberg, president of
the United States soccer federation, said after the Iran game on
Sunday. ``I don't think Steve should be blamed. I don't think the
players should be blamed. They played their hearts out; they just
couldn't put the ball in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Sampson's future, Rothenberg said, ``After the World
Cup, we'll start assessing the future. I'm not going to do it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson said that he wants to return. He said that he felt
``confident and proud'' about what he had accomplished in becoming
the first American coach to qualify the United States for a World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the federation doesn't want me, I'm sure some other
organization will want me,'' Sampson said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He could join MLS, where Rothenberg is seeking to buy the San
Jose Clash. And, fluent in Spanish, he has also expressed interest
in coaching in Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm open to all offers,'' Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   If Sampson is fired, Parreira is again available. It was
Parreira who Rothenberg attempted to hire after Milutinovic was
fired in 1995. Carlos Queiroz of Portugal, whom Rothenberg also
previously sought, has just left the U.S. federation as head of
player development to coach the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant departure from the federation will be
Rothenberg's, when he steps down as a two-term president in August.
He organized what is considered the most successful World Cup in
1994, started a professional league and took soccer from
mom-and-pop amateurism to ambitious professionalism. The two
candidates to replace him, Dr. Robert Contiguglia and Lawrence
Monaco Jr., do not possess Rothenberg's international connections
or audacious showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg believes the financial side of the federation is
solid with about $500 million set to come in from deals signed with
Nike and the International Management Group, and from television
rights, between now and 2010. On the player side, the federation
still has much work to do in aggressively recruiting Hispanic and
black athletes. Rothenberg said the federation intended to hire
scouts to roam the country spotting talent. But he acknowledged
that outside of places like the Houston Parks Department, the game
is not being played and organized as the federation would like in
the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a better job attracting the best athletes the
United States has to offer into the sport of soccer,'' said
Sampson, who has built significant bridges into the Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the United States needs players who can put the
ball into the net. In 14 games this year, the Americans have scored
an anemic 15 goals. Eric Wynalda is the country's all-time leading
scorer, but he has scored only twice in his last 15 games. At some
point, the Americans must realize that hitting the post or crossbar
four times against Iran was not bad luck but an obvious lack of
finishing skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``One area is key to our success _ precision in front of the
goal,'' Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he wanted players with ``personality,'' by which he
meant players who are not made timid by the opposition. This
hesitancy, or even fear, was obvious in a 2-0 loss to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also need leadership. All of the current players
have professional experience, but they sometimes seem like a team
of fraternity boys _ nice guys, but without any fearsome presence.
No one stepped in when Claudio Reyna took a shot to the kidneys in
the first minute of the Germany game. In replacing John Harkes,
Sampson did not replace his gritty personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team was capable of doing better than 1994,'' said
defender Jeff Agoos. ``It just didn't come through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
