<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THACHER-INDICT-BOS &LR;      06-22 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THACHER-INDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY CARE CHIEF INDICTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The US Department of Labor has filed a lawsuit against
Frederick Thacher alleging that the chief executive of Community
Care Systems Inc. in Wellesley illegaly diverted the retirement
funds of about 400 of his employees.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in US District Court in Boston, alleges that
Thacher and his financially troubled company withheld approximately
$150,800 in 401(k) contributions from employee checks but did not
forward the money to their retirement plan. The suit seeks to hold
both CCSI and Thacher responsible for paying the retirement funds
into the plan, with interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are alleging that Thacher and his companies illegally
retained and used employee witholding amounts for their own
purposes because CCSI and some of its subsidiaries have been having
financial difficulty,'' said James Benages, Regional Director for
the Labor department's Pension &AMP; Welfare Benefits Administration,
which oversees employee retirement programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thacher did not return phone calls placed to his Boston home.
Jay Fialkow, the attorney who has been dealing with the Labor
department on Thacher's behalf, was out of town and unavailable for
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   CCSI owns two psychiatric hospitals, Charles River Hospital in
Wellesley, and Jackson Brook Institute in Portland, Maine. Earlier
this year, CCSI closed another psychiatric hospital in Chicopee,
citing financial difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
in Maine after state authorities alleged CCSI had diverted $15.5
million to its Massachusetts subsidiaries. The company later
relinquished control of Jackson Brook to state regulators, leaving
behind an estimated $4.3 million in unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Brook is up for sale and has ``several interested
buyers,'' according to David Hillman, an attorney representing the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, financial problems continue to plague CCSI. Employees
at Charles River Hospital in Wellesley, who asked not to be named,
said in recent interviews that some of their paychecks have
bounced. They also said that the retirement contributions from
their checks have not been deposited in their 401(K) plan.
</P>
<P>
   One nurse at the hospital, who requested anonymity, said she
watched as the hospital's dumpster was repossessed last month. The
nurse said employees have been forced to haul hospital trash to the
local dump.
</P>
<P>
   CCSI is privately held. Thacher is the company's sole board
member and majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Departent's lawsuit alleges that since November 1997,
CSSI and its subsidiaries have failed to forward employee
reitrement assets to their 401(k) plan as required by the federal
Employee Retirement Income Security Act, known as ERISA.
</P>
<P>
   ``These withheld monies have been and continue to be comingled
with the general assets of CCSI...,'' the suit alleges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
