<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY, OTHERS, CHEER ON HIKE IN MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After nearly two hours of testimony, Senator Edward M.
Kennedy looked out at the crowd and pronounced his verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a case against increasing the minimum wage, but
we sure haven't heard it today,'' the state's senior senator told
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   No, they hadn't. The State House's Gardner Auditorium, after
all, has its acoustical advantages. And Monday's was a rhetorical
echo between the panel of politicians and the public-policy
presenters before them.
</P>
<P>
   From Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, a recent convert to the idea
of raising the wage floor, to former Labor Secretary Robert Reich
and Paula Rayman, director of the Radcliffe Public Policy
Institute, to a grocery-store worker and a laundry employee
struggling along on the minimum wage, their views were unanimous:
Only good come could of hiking the minimum wage, whether at the
state level or federally, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Past predictions of adverse economic impacts hadn't come true,
said Cellucci, explaining why he now backs an idea he opposed only
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps that consensus shouldn't have come as a complete
surprise to the senator. According to press aide Darcy Lee, it was
his office, that picked the guests to speak at the informal
``minimum wage forum.'' Those they chose made it obvious what
Kennedy sought was not a debate, but a cheerleading squad. Asked
afterward why he hadn't also invited foes of a minimum-wage
increase, Kennedy said he had heard their arguments before and
didn't find them ``terribly convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal arguments are, one, unemployment and two,
inflation,'' Kennedy said. ``I thought Bob Reich, who is the
secretary of labor and the economist, addressed both of those
issues very well.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, who hails from less
contentious St. Louis, apparently left the forum thinking
Massachusetts was all of one mind about hiking the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no argument against it anymore,'' Gephardt declared.
``I don't know what they would argue. What would they argue?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, had Kennedy and company really wanted a debate, they
wouldn't have had to look awfully far.
</P>
<P>
   No further, say, than Copley Square, where the 5,000-member
Associated Industries of Massachusetts is located. The state's
largest employer group, AIM worries that hiking the state's minimum
wage will put Massachusetts at a competitive disadvantage with
neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Coalition for a Competitive Massachusetts --
with seven chambers of commerce and eight business associations
among its members -- which sent a June 15 letter to state
legislators highlighting their concerns about job loss if the
minimum wage goes up.
</P>
<P>
   There's even market-oriented economist David Tuerck, executive
director of Suffolk University's Beacon Hill Institute, a
conservative thinktank. Tuerck says he would have happy to walk
across the street to argue the real effect of a minimum wage hike
is not so much job loss as jobs uncreated.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Brian Gilmore, AIM's executive vice-president, said he
would have liked to offer his views -- but wasn't surprised not to
have been asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the list of speakers that were invited, it didn't seem to
me that it was going to be an open hearing,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a conclusion that really is hard to argue with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
