<SLUG> BC-MA-GUN-BILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREARMS LICENSING FEE HALVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The gun lobby has been busy on Beacon Hill. It has also
been effective.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a move to ban assault weapons was expected to pass the
House but the industry won a key amendment slicing in half the
proposed $50 firearms licensing fee. The move so stunned House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran that he postponed further debate on the
issue until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It may have marked the first time so many of Finneran's
committee chairs have voted out of line with his wishes and he
promptly called the team into a meeting in an attempt to reverse
the amendment, approved 79-73.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven members of Finneran's leadership voted for the amendment,
which would require those with firearm identification cards to pay
$25 _ rather than $50 _ every three years to renew their license.
The amendment also exempts those over 65, as well as those who
currently have hunting or sporting licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it costs just $2 for a lifetime permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of sportsmen out there saying you should go
after the criminals and leave us alone,'' said Representative David
Peters, a Charlton Republican, who offered the amendment. ``The
speaker has grossly overestimated the members' appetite for this
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Yacino, executive director of the Gun Owner's Action
League, said the group has for years been pushing for a bill that
would track all gun-related crimes, including whether the
perpetrator had a license.
</P>
<P>
   The current assault weapons ban, he said, would restrict those
with a license, while not truly preventing criminals from obtaining
high-powered guns illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts is not going to be able to stop crime by making
life more difficult for the licensed gun owner,'' Yacino said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Yacino for further comment Monday were
unsuccessful because, according to one GOAL worker, he was out
lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Such arm twisting of the legislators may not defeat the assault
weapons ban altogether, but it has put it in jeopardy, while
fighting for second amendment rights continues on other fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing the industry are scheduled to be in Suffolk
Superior Court Wednesday seeking an injunction against Attorney
General Scott Harshbarger's handgun safety regulations, some of
which took effect Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations effectively ban Saturday Night Specials in the
state and require all handguns sold in Massachusetts to be child
proof, with tamper proof serial numbers and safety warnings.
</P>
<P>
   However, the American Sports Shooting Council Inc., along with
manufacturers Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., Glock Inc. and Taurus Firearms
Co. Inc. have filed suit, charging Harhsbarger is overstepping his
authority. About 30 types of handguns, most of them .22- or
.25-caliber weapons are likely to be barred from sale here for
failing to meet the new standards.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger believes he has the right to implement such
regulations under the state's consumer protection laws. But the
industry says he is skirting the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Monday assailing the gun lobby for
attacking his regulations, Harshbarger said he hoped the House
would pass the assault weapons ban.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adrian Walker of the Globe Staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
