<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TARGETS TOBACCO COMPANIES THAT TARGET CHILDREN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
WASHINGTON _ Giving no ground in his fight with tobacco companies
and their congressional allies, President Clinton called Monday for
annual government surveys to determine which tobacco brands are
favored by underage smokers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The information will help identify ``which companies are most
responsible for the problem'' of teen smoking, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents, quite simply, have a right to know'' which companies
are ``targeting children,'' the president said as he left for an
annual forum on family issues in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief session with reporters, Clinton fired another
verbal volley at Senate Republicans who last week blocked
comprehensive anti-smoking legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressional leadership seems willing to walk away from
its obligation to our children,'' the president said. ``The
Republican leadership placed partisan politics and tobacco
companies above our families. Their vote was not just pro-tobacco
lobby, it was anti-family.''
</P>
<P>
   Killed in a series of procedural votes, the anti-smoking
legislation hammered out over several months would have raised the
price of a pack of cigarettes by $1.10 over five years. The measure
would have expanded Food and Drug Administration regulation of
nicotine and subjected the industry to new restrictions on
marketing, advertising and labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, a spokesman for the tobacco industry, said
cigarette companies have agreed to help with research into why
teens use tobacco products. He said the survey ordered by Clinton
will not help in that research and amounts to ``a continuation of
his attack rhetoric while giving the impression to the public that
he is doing something substantive.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the president's remarks are viewed by the tobacco
companies ``as a political gesture designed to divert attention
from the fact that (the White House) failed to offer any
substantive leadership on the tobacco debate'' since an agreement
was reached a year ago between cigarette makers and several state
attorneys general with input from the administration.
</P>
<P>
   In that compromise, tobacco companies agreed that the industry
as a whole would pay up to $2 billion annually if youth smoking did
not decline. As the agreement was drafted in bill form, the White
House insisted that the annual maximum penalty be increased to $3.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a provision was inserted that would have
levied additional penalties against individual companies for
failing to meet their targets for weaning teen-agers from tobacco
products. To help determine which companies fell short of their
targets, the legislation called for an annual survey much like what
Clinton directed the Department of Health and Human Services to
produce.
</P>
<P>
   The government reports that about 3,000 young people start
smoking every day and 1,000 of them will die of smoking-related
causes. The average age for starting to smoke is 14 1/2, and seven
of every 10 smokers are hooked by their 18th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A Health and Human Services study in 1994 found that when
advertising budgets were increased for Camel and Newport cigarettes
in the early 1990s, the number of teens buying Camels went up by 64
percent and by 55 percent for Newports. The study estimated that 3
million teens smoke cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president's announcement is a signal
he intends to ``push forward on all fronts'' and not wait idly for
Congress to act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that once survey information reaches the public,
tobacco companies ``will then no longer be able to evade
accountability and neither will Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats say they will make the tobacco vote an issue in
the November elections, Republicans have expressed doubts that the
issue will resonate with voters. A recent poll by the independent
Pew Research Center found that by a 2-1 margin the public wants the
government to take some sort of action against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxxxx END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
