<HEADLINE>
MENINO LEANS HEAVILY ON HISTORICAL HERITAGE IN WOOING DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Menino administration Monday ushered the Democratic
party elite into town on a carpet of history to hawk Boston as the
natural milieu for the millenium convention.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting 50 Democrats may be teachers or union leaders in
everyday life, but Monday they were whisked by Lincoln Continental
from the fog-shrouded Logan International Airport to start a
privately-funded tour with lunch at the tres chic Maison Robert in
Old City Hall, featuring a surviving link to the golden days of
Camelot _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Images from yesteryear that swathed the site committee Monday
were part of a strategy to stress the city's strength _sterling
Democratic roots, and downplay the mere 35 electoral votes that all
six New England states could, collectively, hope to offer to any
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But, think history, say Boston officials. Paul Revere and John
Singleton Copley.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Los Angeles _ lead contender to host the August
2000 Democratic National Convention _ is set in vote-heavy
California and can offer a post-convention bounce as wide as the
west. Forget about Philadelphia as another cradle of liberty
situated in a key electoral state next door to heartland swing
states of the midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Boston history is the mantra percolating through the halls of
the all-Americana JFK Library, where Boston's pitch for the
convention started Monday evening. It is the third of seven stops
for the delegates, who will chose the host city sometime later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   After the library, the delegates moved on to the splendid Copley
Square and the grand entrance to the McKim building, circa 1895.
There, assembled party chairs from five states and a host of
panelists followed a hall of fame _ photographs of historic figures
with strong local ties from Leonard Bernstein (a Boston Latin
School graduate) to Henry David Thoreau (born in Concord and a
Harvard University graduate) to Harriet Tubman (active in the
women's movement in New England).
</P>
<P>
   ``What better place can you be for the millenium but where the
origins of our nation took place?'' said Howard Leibowitz, the
city's director of intergovernmental relations.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia could strike the same theme, but Boston hopes to
come out ahead of Philly, home to the Liberty Bell, by highlighting
its futuristic achievements in biotech and software fields, not to
mention the city's poster child status for the Clinton
administration's crime fighting successes.
</P>
<P>
   The attending Democrats, whose turnout is stronger here than in
most of the other seven cities the panel is visiting, were bestowed
with souvenirs at every turn. First, a pair of Rockports for each,
they were polled for shoe size in advance, to highlight the walking
city theme; then, a hand-held computer from 3Com corp., containing
the tour itinerary and important phone and pager numbers.
</P>
<P>
   As nice as the tchotchkes are, though, the Menino administration
has not lost sight of its audience of visiting party stalwarts who
love to revel in political lore.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the step through the looking glass of Camelot, and on to a
political memorabilia exhibit at the Boston Public Library, where
party diehards had an entire brass showcase devoted to pictures of
James Michael Curley, the infamous, bad boy Boston mayor (four
times between 1914 and 1950) and governor (1935-1937) who served
the voters while doing time in 1947.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      06-22 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWD FILLS COURTROOM AS COSBY TRIAL OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ The victim's friends and family filled
two rows. The other seats were taken too, everyone crowded into the
courtroom Monday to see the teenager accused of killing Bill
Cosby's only son.
</P>
<P>
   But the entertainer whose celebrity was the draw during opening
statements made no appearance himself. He has said he wants a
dignified proceeding, and so Cosby and his wife stayed away from
the same courthouse where the O.J. Simpson civil trial was held two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, interest was intense, competition for seats stiff. Los
Angeles Superior Court Judge David D. Perez, who normally rules
from a temporary trailer behind the building, was relocated to a
second-floor courtroom for the Cosby case. Spectators had to pass
through a metal detector set up at the door, where extra security
personnel were also stationed.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the victim's last name, however, and the $130,000
Mercedez-Benz whose tire Cosby was changing on a dark freeway exit
road, little about the case sets it apart from any other street
robbery gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of all the attention was 19-year-old Mikail
Markhasev, charged with gunning down Ennis Cosby, 27, in the early
hours of Jan. 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In her opening statement, Deputy District Attorney Anne Ingalls
reconstructed the crime scene and police investigation for jurors,
then set out to prove that Markhasev's own jailhouse letters to
friends amount to a confession. The prosecution also contends that
Markhasev, a Ukranian immigrant who spent time in juvenile
detention, is a member of the notorious prison gang called the
Mexican Mafia. The letters introduced in court Monday were filled
with Spanish words and idiomatic expressions.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Hall, the defendant's lawyer, told the racially mixed
jury that police have the wrong man, that the killer was in fact a
friend of Markhasev's who is now a star prosecution witness. Both
men resemble the composite picture that was based on a description
given by one of Ennis Cosby's friends, who was shining her car's
lights on his tire as he changed it.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the trial, Hall said, ``We will know who the
killer is, and it's not him.'' He added, ``This case is about a
chance meeting. It's also a case full of mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   The murder and attempted robbery charges could put Markhasev,
who wore a gray suit with a fine pinstripe to court, in prison for
the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis Cosby, a graduate student at Columbia University, was
visiting his parents during Christmas break when he was shot and
left to die on the side of the road at 1:45 a.m. Two months later,
police arrested Markhasev, and prosecutors intend to call 25
witnesses who they say will bolster DNA analysis and other physical
evidence that places him on the darkened stretch of road.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall, a public defender, noted that Stephanie Crane, Cosby's
friend, failed to identify Markhasev in a police lineup and
stressed that two friends who say they were with Markhasev that
night lied, in part to receive lenient treatment in an unrelated
case. One, Eli Zakaria, 24, is the real killer, Hall insisted again
and again.
</P>
<P>
   Police recovered the murder weapon, a .38-caliber pistol, and a
knit cap that Crane said the killer was wearing, with the help of
two of the defendant's other friends. One, Michael Chang, is
expected to testify that Markhasev called him for help finding the
murder weapon, which he had thrown away. Markhasev also allegedly
admitted killing Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, however, said the stories were motivated by a $100,000
reward offered by a supermarket tabloid. To underscore his point
that the prosecution's witnesses are not credible, he displayed
posters featuring their pictures and criminal records. He also said
the letters his client allegedly wrote were forgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about people covering up for Eli Zakaria, and
that's fine and dandy for all of the witnesses to do. . .,'' Hall
told jurors. ``But your job is to see through that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
