<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     THE POETRY OF MONICA LEWINSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years before &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  was a friendly White House intern,
she was a schoolgirl poet, reports the New York Post. The latest
issue of the literary quarterly Open City reprints a poem she wrote
at the age of 10 or 11, published in the yearbook of the  &UR; John
Thomas Dye &LR;  School:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a pizza/ I can be a delicious lunch, dinner/ or
breakfast, if you're weird/ I have a great deal of toppings on me/
I am a round and flat piece of dough/ with lots of toppings/ I make
your mouth water/ I'm very good to eat, but I'm/ Fattening!/ I am a
mouth's best friend/ I make you say, `Yum, Yum'/ I am a pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   Deconstructionists will note the author's identification of
herself within the pizza structure as a piece of dough that serves
as a support for repeatedly mentioned ``toppings,'' obviously
indicative of the young Lewinsky's ambition to serve as a
functionary for a top executive, to wit, the nation's
executive-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Internet rumor has it that  &UR; Winona Ryder &LR;  and  &UR; Matt Damon &LR;  are
about to announce their engagement.
</P>
<P>
   - The Telegraph of London reports that the Chinese government
has ordered stores in Beijing to remove from their shelves a book
about  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; ,  &UR; Paula Jones &LR;  and  &UR; Monica &LR; 
 &UR; Lewinsky &LR; . A bookstore employee told the Telegraph that the
government said that displaying the book while the president is
visiting would be ``potentially damaging to Sino-U.S. relations.''
</P>
<P>
   - In an interview on the occasion of his 16th birthday,
 &UR; Prince William &LR;  told the British Press Association that he likes
computers but does not own one of his own.
</P>
<P>
   - Artist  &UR; Karla Roberts &LR; ' recent installation on one New York
City street corner involves the hanging of 1,250 pine-scented
car-freshener trees on a chain-link fence. Metropolis magazine
described the work as evoking ``the value of a real forest by
offering an intrusive, synthetic alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   - Motoring through Colma (as picturesque as driving through the
Alps, but without yodelers)  &UR; Ted Loewenberg &LR;  saw a casket truck
with ``We Deliver'' painted on its fender.
</P>
<P>
   - Athlete's feats: &UR; Danny Brauer &LR;  of Camdenton, Mo., winner of
the Wal-Mart FLW Tour's Angler of the Year award, will be the first
fishing champion in history to be pictured on a Wheaties box.
</P>
<P>
   - The San Francisco Visitors and Convention Bureau and MBNA
American Bank is offering an ``Official San Francisco'' Visa card,
decorated with the image of a cable car, the Golden Gate Bridge or
the Conservatory of Flowers. A portion of the card's receipts will
be donated to Golden Gate Park restoration.
</P>
<P>
   - Founded on the proposition that certain smells bring a ``swarm
of emotion and memories ... so powerful that you are practically
transported to a different place or time,'' smell THIS scents,
available at Nordstrom, come in the following options: Baby Powder,
Beach Smells, Cake Batter, Canned Peaches, Chocolate Bar, Cinnamon
Buns, Clean Wet Laundry, Cream Soda, Cut Grass, Fluffy Pillow,
Fresh Squeezed, Grandma, Grapefruit, Head Shop, Iced Tea, Melon,
Rain Forest, Salon Shampoo, Soda Pop Fizz, Sucker Candy, Tropical
Fern and Vanilla Shake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Constance Stellas &LR;  describes her work as a professional
psychic shopper, in the latest issue of Working Woman: ``I use
astrological charts to counsel clients on the most appropriate
gifts. ... Aquarius rules all electrical gadgets and Leo likes
everything gold.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``On those magical summer evenings in San Francisco when the &LR; 
 &UR; fog rolls in from the Pacific Ocean and people emerge from the &LR; 
 &UR; hotels on Nob Hill and go for brave walks down the staggeringly &LR; 
 &UR; steep slopes of Powell Street and shiver deliciously in the &LR; 
 &UR; chilly air and listen to the happy clapper clangor of the cable &LR; 
 &UR; cars and the mournful foghorns of the freights heading out to &LR; 
 &UR; sea, and all at once life is a lovely little operetta from the &LR; 
 &UR; year 1910 _ at that moment, likely as not, barely five miles to &LR; 
 &UR; the east, a brutal sun has been roasting Contra Costa County for &LR; 
 &UR; 13 or 14 hours.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - From  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; 's forthcoming novel, ``A Man in Full,''
excerpted in the latest Rolling Stone. Five miles? Perhaps measured
by Tom's thumb.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News &LR; 
 &UR; Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
