<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-DEATHS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 10 ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS DIE FROM HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Torrid heat has killed at least 10 people who
have walked into the United States illegally, U.S. Border Patrol in
southern Texas said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As another body was found on Monday, the Border Patrol launched
Operation Lifesaver to find and rescue others who have crossed the
border in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are walking in conditions where we wouldn't last a
day,'' said Patty Mancha, a spokeswoman for the patrol in the
border city of Del Rio. ``From now through the end of August, we'll
be on alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Drought and extreme heat have gripped the region in recent
weeks. Walking in the sun and temperatures hovering around 100 can
cause dehydration and weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they found more than two dozen illegal
immigrants jammed into the back of an unventilated moving van
outside San Marcos, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 28 men were sick from heat and dehydration when they were
found late Sunday morning, said Ray Dudley, spokesman for the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temperature inside the van was estimated at 125 degrees or
higher,'' Dudley said. ``We had to have medical personnel look the
men over, and they were taken back to our offices where they were
given water and fluids all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, bodies have been discovered in remote
stretches along the Rio Grande. On Monday, a group of men from
Mexico led agents to a body south of Kingsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several isolated stretches where there's no water,
and a person can walk for days and not see a soul,'' Mancha said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't have a compass or any sense of
direction,'' she said. ``There's a tendency to get delirious.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of Operation Lifesaver, INS, which oversees the Border
Patrol, has provided public service announcements for Mexican radio
and television stations to warn potential immigrants about the
dangers of extreme heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not worth your life!'' warns one radio message.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Mexican officials last week announced a joint plan
aimed at keeping illegal immigrants out of dangerous areas, at
rescuing them if they get in trouble, and identifying those who
die.
</P>
<P>
   Agents who roam in vehicles as well as those deployed in
helicopters and aircraft have received emergency medical training
and are carrying extra jugs of water.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission is not only to hunt for people entering the United
States illegally, but try to save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're geared up if anything happens,'' said Fred Borrego, head
of a patrol checkpoint near Kingsville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PHILADELPHIA-$     06-22 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PHILADELPHIA-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE LIBERTY BELL, A MOVE WITH A VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 28)  
 (JT)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ No tourist attraction in Philadelphia draws more
people than the Liberty Bell. Last year, the National Park Service
recorded 1.6 million visitors at the modest pavilion where it sits,
helping make Independence National Historical Park one of the
busiest park service sites.
</P>
<P>
   Just stand there, and ponder its wonder, the inscrutable crack
and words that speak to the freedoms of a nation: ``Proclaim
Liberty throughout all the Land unto all the Inhabitants Thereof,''
a passage from Leviticus.
</P>
<P>
   And now, gaze beyond the bell. Just off in the distance is
glorious Independence Hall, a spired structure of red brick where
the Declaration of Independence was adopted, the United States
Constitution was drafted and the 2,080-pound bell once hung. And
just beyond Independence Hall, towering high above it _ indeed,
dominating the view _ are the Penn Mutual office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The what? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is now painfully apparent that the esthetics of Independence
Mall, created in 1976 as part of a national park with its symbols
of liberty and justice for all, did not take into account two
insurance-company buildings that possess little in the way of
architectural or historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller of the Penn Mutual buildings dates from the 1920s,
the larger from about 50 years later, when the general area was
still densely populated with offices, businesses and center-city
residents, and Independence Hall was just another old building in
the oldest section of one of America's oldest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pavilion housing the bell, which opened on Jan. 1, 1976,
to celebrate the Bicentennial, was placed smack in front of
Independence Hall, with a view that leaves it dwarfed by the
mercantile backdrop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the park service's most ambitious effort to beautify the mall
and dramatize its two greatest treasures, plans are underway to
move the bell from its location near Market Street, between 5th and
6th Streets, into a larger new pavilion 200 yards away just off the
corner of 6th and Chestnut, a shift toward the southwest that will
allow visitors at the bell to view Independence Hall at a sharp
angle, with open sky as the background, not buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Independence Hall is an international icon,'' said
David Hollenberg, assistant regional director for the National Park
Service, ``and many people have a strong desire to see the hall and
the bell against its spire simultaneously. But in the current
setting, it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a new site for the bell, the redesign efforts
will include a Liberty Bell interpretive center near the bell
pavilion, a visitor center and a new National Constitution Center,
a project endorsed by Congress to focus attention on the
Constitution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Park officials say the plans for the pavilion will not be
finalized for several months. The entire project will take at least
two years and cost $215 million, only $65 million of which has been
raised from public and private sources.
</P>
<P>
   When the Park Service embarked several years ago on its latest
long-range study to consider how to make the park more
accommodating to the growing number of annual visitors, officials
did not immediately contemplate such a radical change as moving the
Liberty Bell. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more than 200 years, it has largely resided in Philadelphia,
leaving for occasional exhibits outside the city around the turn of
the century. After two parades in Philadelphia during World War I,
it was moved only once more, from inside Independence Hall to its
current pavilion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service's interest in changing the design of
Independence Park drew an assortment of suggestions _ some modest
in scope _ that recommended leaving the Liberty Bell where it is,
and some controversial. One group proposed building a high-tech
underground $170 million Constitution Center, with the Liberty Bell
at its ground-level exit point.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials unveiled their general ideas for redevelopment
last year, but it was not until they retained a nearby local
architectural firm to conceive a plan did the idea of moving the
bell come to light. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The head of the firm, Laurie Olin, was a frequent visitor to the
mall and, as Hollenberg said, was the first person to propose
moving the bell to enhance the view of the hall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the first to note that from the Liberty Bell was the
only place to view the spire,'' Hollenberg said. Once officials
agreed (and they agreed quickly) that the shift made sense, the
rest of the plan fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   An important part is the new pavilion, which will be designed to
give bell viewers longer and quieter visits. In its current
pavilion, the bell can be viewed by up to 150 people at a time,
with rangers offering historical perspective. With the new plans
that include a separate interpretive center and more expansive
surroundings at the bell, visitors will be allowed to spend more
reflective moments, without rangers whisking them out for the next
group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; ttj-z
