<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History revisited: Jones remembers homers of '96 Series
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Andruw Jones sat Monday afternoon behind the batting
cage at Yankee Stadium, stretching the legs that make him such a
dangerous outfielder. To his left, about 320 feet away, is where he
made history almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He was 19 then, blasting two home runs in Game 1 of the World
Series, the youngest player ever to go deep in the Fall Classic.
</P>
<P>
   They landed in the seats in left field, and the next morning
Jones landed across the back pages of the New York tabloids. They
called him The Kid, baseball's newest phenom, playing a starring
role in a town and a stadium that such greats as Babe Ruth, Joe
DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle called home.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Jones is 21, and on Monday he was barely noticed as he
trotted on to the field for batting practice. No mobs of reporters
approaching him. No one yelling his name.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he won't be a star some day. But those two Series
homers still stand above everything else. Baseball still is waiting
for Jones to blossom offensively, but there are signs he is about
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think about those homers,'' he said. ``I'm just
concentrating on baseball right now. Maybe when I retire I will
look back and really think about them. But it's not 1996 anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones comes to New York hitting .261 with 12 home runs and 42
RBIs. At his current pace, he would finish with 26 homers and 91
RBIs, power numbers that are nothing to be ashamed. Then again,
it's easy to expect a lot from a player who hit homers on his first
two Series at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I will never forget those homers,'' manager Bobby Cox
said. ``It was huge, it was very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has learned quite a lot since that Fall Classic. He has
learned that baseball can be a very humbling game, after struggling
for most of last season and getting off to a terrible start this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves remained patient. They could afford to; one thing
that never suffers is Jones' defense. It is always very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard all the people saying I should be in the minors,''
Jones said. ``But they had seen me play, they knew what I could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball people think that his development might have been
retarded by the two homers he hit here. In other words, it gave him
a false sense of security or perhaps even a big head. It also put
all kinds of pressure on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Andruw feels pressure,'' Cox said. ``He sure
didn't feel any pressure when he was struggling earlier this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said ``I don't read things (about me), but people come up
and tell me things. I have learned a lot over the last two years, I
have learned what it is like to play under pressure. But I am still
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Like teammates Javier Lopez and Eddie Perez, Jones has been
helped by the presence of Andres Galarraga, both on and off the
field. Galarraga, able to communicate with the team's Latin players
in their own language, has been a settling influence for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andres has helped me, (and) so has C.J.,'' Jones said,
referring to batting coach Clarence Jones, ``but they cannot go up
to the plate and hit for me. I have to do that. I have to be the
one that takes the advice and makes it work at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   And right now it's working.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
