<SLUG> BC-NBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harpring awaiting NBA's verdict
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Matt Harpring stands on the threshold of a pro
career, it's important to remember that he has been fooling
basketball scouts for years.
</P>
<P>
   Harpring was a solid football prospect in high school at the
Marist School, a quarterback who had Wake Forest and Northwestern
to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   But Harpring grew three inches between his junior and senior
years at Marist and became a hot basketball property. Georgia
wanted him. Georgia Tech got him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a chance Harpring can become an Atlanta Hawk during
the NBA draft Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Although he hopes he'll be taken higher _ the Hawks pick 20th _
Harpring says he wouldn't mind a chance to play his entire career
in his home town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done what I can,'' he said. ``If I go in the teens,
that's great. If I end up in Atlanta, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpring figures that would make him one half of a very exotic
bet. ``Keith Brooking went to my school, then to Tech and was
drafted by the Falcons. If I go from Marist to Tech to the Hawks,
how often does something like that happen?''
</P>
<P>
   How often does an athlete come home a winner as a longshot?
</P>
<P>
   Harpring wasn't a gleam in Bobby Cremins' eye until his senior
year in high school, yet he joined Mark Price, as the only two
Georgia Tech players ever named first-team All-ACC three seasons in
a row. He averaged 21.6 points as a senior and 17.9 ppg. as a
four-year starter.
</P>
<P>
   But problems for the 6-6 1/2 forward grew out of his inability
to work out for a number of teams this spring. Limited by an ankle
injury, he dropped from the upper third of the first round and now
faces an uncertain landing.
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors, of course.
</P>
<P>
   First, the influx of young, athletic players has obscured a less
flashy senior who now may find himself slipping into the 20s
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Houston and Orlando dominate the middle of the draft,
holding all but one selection from 12 through 18. If they don't
take Harpring and Minnesota passes at 17, then the solidly built
22-year-old is looking at Milwaukee (19), Atlanta (20), Charlotte
(21) or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Harpring's ailment is a bone bruise in his left ankle, similar
to a stress reaction. ``I hurt my ankle with three or four games
left in the season,'' he said Monday. ``It was stiff and sore. I
took two weeks off from running and lifting, and I guess I should
have taken more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Richard Howell knew the clock was ticking and that
Harpring would have plenty of time to rest this summer. ``He said,
`You need to work out,''' Harpring said. ``I did and it got sore
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpring visited the Magic and the Rockets last week and worked
out for Minnesota on Monday. He believes teams understand his
predicament. And if he slips, he slips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I could. I really wanted to let these teams get to
meet me and get to know me. After four years at Georgia Tech, they
should know my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Hawks know Harpring. They watched through four
years of college competition. They saw him scrimmage with NBA
players in September. So, when Harpring met recently with the
Hawks' basketball staff and took their psychological tests, there
was no pressure to see him on the floor again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've watched throughout his career,'' Hawks general manager
Pete Babcock said Monday, offering this evaluation: ``The plus side
of his game is that he plays with great intensity, great effort. He
is unrelenting in his work. The downside is that he's an undersized
small forward by NBA standards, but he remains a great
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell said he believes Harpring's value has held, but in a
draft this unpredictable, everyone's hedging bets.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts know Harpring can shoot, and there is the suggestion his
game will improve in the NBA, where a player who did everything in
college fulfills a role much more narrowly defined.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a matter of waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
