<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY READY TO UNLEASH `ALE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Powerful strikers such as Argentina's
Gabriel Batistuta and Brazil's Ronaldo have been drawing most of
the attention at France '98. Their teams, along with Croatia,
France, and Nigeria, clinched second-round berths after two games
and will be coasting in preparation.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a feeling that a more subtle force could soon
explode. Call it coincidence or call it destiny. The young Italian
forward they call ``Ale'' will make his France '98 starting debut
against Austria at Stade de France tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The shouts should be louder than during Monday's training
session at the massive Stade, when Alessandro Del Piero's teammates
constantly called out the diminutive of his name, sounding much
like, ``Allez, allez, allez,'' the French for, ``Go, go, go!''
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero is expected to become the center of attention for
Italy, a player with grace and style plus the innate ability to
produce goals in the most difficult circumstances. He is the
logical successor to Roberto Baggio.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this can be a mixed blessing. Baggio was the Italian savior
at USA '94, but the tournament ended sourly as he missed a penalty
kick against Brazil and then was consigned to many months of
purgatory fighting for recognition in Italy's Serie A. National
team coach Cesare Maldini, a pragmatist from the conservative
school, deemed creators such as Baggio and Del Piero out of
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero was left out of qualifying games, despite a prolific
goal-scoring record for Juventus, and Baggio was resurrected only
the week before Maldini had to submit a roster for this event.
Baggio pulled off another magic trick to salvage a draw against
Chile in the opener but against Cameroon, he declined and was
replaced by Del Piero.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero has recovered from a thigh injury and gets his turn
now. Monday's practice concluded after Del Piero slipped a
brilliant backheel to Paolo Maldini for a goal _ just the type of
play Baggio used to make regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Maldini would not confirm the starting lineup for tonight,
saying that the shirts the players were wearing would be a good
clue.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Del Piero and his Juventus teammate, Filippo
Inzaghi, would be paired in attack. But it is unlikely that former
Juventus striker Christian Vieri is being excluded, since he is
tied for second with Chile's Marcelo Salas in scoring in this
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Italy could go with a three-pronged attack. The only other
change could be Luigi Di Biagio, possibly displacing Demetrio
Albertini as the midfield generator.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero, 23, is from San Vendemiano, near the Piave River and
less than 50 miles from Baggio's hometown of Caldogno. Del Piero
has a high profile in most of the world but he has not been
promoted like Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero has a long-term contract with Juventus and the club
considers him the heir to Michel Platini, the stylish Frenchman who
led Juve to European success in the '80s. Again, Del Piero is
associated with coincidence or destiny; Platini is president of the
France '98 Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Del Piero's World Cup is just getting started, so too are the
traditional World Cup powers. A closer look at where things stand:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP A &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brazil can guarantee Norway's elimination with a two-goal
victory tonight. The Brazilians' primary objective is to prepare
for their second-round match at Parc des Princes Saturday. But they
could be motivated by Norwegian coach Egil Olsen, who has been
critical since his team defeated Brazil, 4-2, in Oslo last year.
This could open the way for Scotland, which has never advanced past
the first round of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP B &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chile is the favorite to follow Italy. The Chileans have
performed well, taking the initiative with strikers Ivan ``El
Terrible'' Zamorano and El Matador Salas, only to surrender late
goals in ties against Italy and Austria. Chile was eliminated from
the 1990 and '94 World Cups after a scandalous faked injury
incident during a qualifier against Brazil. Coincidentally, Brazil
is the second-round foe for Group B's second-place team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP C &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   France requires at least a draw against Denmark in Lyon tomorrow
to win the group. This would allow Les Bleus to avoid Nigeria in
Sunday's second-round match. Both France and Denmark are missing
key players after Red Thursday, when referees expelled five players
in two games. Zinedine Zidane of France and Tibor Molnar of Denmark
are suspended for two games, and Denmark's Mogen Weighorst is out
for one match.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP D &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria has a chance to try a different defensive scheme with
captain Uche Ukechukwu suspended against Paraguay in Toulouse
tomorrow. Goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert has promised to score the
most memorable goal of the World Cup, and has come close on two
free kicks for the Paraguayans. Both Bulgaria and Spain, among the
most impressive teams at USA '94, could be out of the tournament
after this game. The Spaniards lost only one game since falling to
Italy in Foxborough four years ago before falling to Nigeria last
week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP E &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico carries CONCACAF's hopes after Jamaica and the US were
quickly eliminated. Tomorrow in St. Etienne, the Mexicans will meet
the Netherlands, which showed its potential in a 5-0 crushing of
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP F &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Germany and Yugoslavia are contending for the top spot, which
likely means avoiding the Netherlands in the second round.
Yugoslavia is regretting surrendering a late goal to Oliver
Bierhoff in a 2-2 tie with the Germans in Lens Sunday. The
Yugoslavs will need a big win over the US in Nantes Thursday to
overtake the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP G &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Romania gave England a reality check with a 2-1 win in Toulouse
last night. Gheorge Hagi's team remains among the most dynamic in
this tournament. The second spot will be determined by the
Colombia-England matchup in Lens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUP H &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Argentina and Croatia, as expected, dominated the group and will
meet for first place in Bordeaux Friday. The Argentines have the
World Cup's leading scorer, Batistuta, plus Ariel ``El Burrito''
Ortega, and have a team capable of progressing beyond the Diego
Maradona era. Japan has been the best of the newcomers so far, a
good sign for the 2002 World Cup, which it will host with South
Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
