<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1151 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISH-LOGO-ART-2TAKES-     06-22 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-LOGO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE FISH MAKES BIG SPLASH IN BIBLE-BELT TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REPUBLIC, Mo. _ Eight years ago, on a whim, Marilyn Shexsnayder
entered the contest to design a logo for her hometown. She was a
stockbroker, not an artist. But using her colored pencils and her
computer she drew an oustretched hand, a family of four in
silhouette and, to portray the centrality of religion in this old
railroad town with more than 25 churches and about 8,000 people,
she sketched the simple fish that she had regarded from childhood
as a universal symbol of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish is better than a cross, because if you use a cross,
the Jewish people are mad because it's not a star of David,'' Mrs.
Shexsnayder says. ``I wanted a symbol that would represent religion
totally, all religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shexsnayder won the logo contest and $100 prize, and for
eight years the logo with the fish has adorned the town's trucks,
flags, street signs, stationery, business cards and chamber of
commerce brochures.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, the little fish is causing an awfully big splash.
Someone complained about the fish to the American Civil Liberties
Union, and in February the organization sent a letter asking the
mayor to delete the fish from the logo because the fish was
``unmistakably identified with Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish symbol, also known as an ichthus, first appeared in
the second century and was used as a secret sign of Christianity,''
said the letter from Doug Bonney, a volunteer ACLU lawyer, quoting
from a Bible dictionary, two Christian encyclopedias and a
theological review. The first Greek letters of the phrase ``Jesus
Christ, Son of God, Savior'' spell out ``fish'' in Greek, and often
appear with the fish symbol. ``Thus we believe the City's seal
violates the First Amendment's prohibition against the
establishment of religion,'' Bonney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of changing its logo, like another nearby town recently
faced with a similar warning from the ACLU, Republic has vowed to
fight. Many Republic residents are gearing up for the battle,
saying they must take a stand for local autonomy against meddling
outsiders like the ACLU, and for the Christian faith of the town's
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logo represents the town overall,'' said Paula Howell, an
office manager at an accounting firm and a third-generation
Republic native, ``and I don't see anything wrong with that because
the majority of our community are actually Christians. The majority
of our community are very religious. This is the Bible Belt and the
number of churches we have per person is pretty high. It ranks
right up there with fast-food restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy also reveals what happens when a religiously and
ethnically homogeneous town begins to feel the first cracks in its
communal identity. This is a place so steeped in an evangelical
Protestant sensibility that residents talk about ``non-Christians,
such as Catholics.'' A handful of Jewish and Asian families live
here, but nobody seems to know of any black or Hispanic residents.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a sign of the town's emerging diversity, a Jewish man
was elected to the board of aldermen, and some people have friends
married to Muslims. One resident Wiccan, a practicing witch, says
that until the fish dispute arose, she had felt comfortable rearing
her family in Republic. And one evening in April when the board of
aldermen was taking up the fish issue at city hall, dozens of high
school and college students turned out to protest, carrying signs
saying, ``Small Towns, NOT Small Minds'' and ``Diversity Is
Divine.''
</P>
<P>
   Debates like this one in Republic over the separation of church
and state are coming up with increasing regularity around the
country. Sometimes the issue is a town's or state's logo or slogan
with an explicitly religious reference; sometimes a creche placed
on civic property; and sometimes a teacher or coach leading
students in prayer. Often, the conflicts must be resolved in court.
</P>
<P>
   In Republic, the warning letter from the Civil Liberties Union
stung like a poison arrow from a hostile tribe. In March, more than
60 people packed a meeting of the board of aldermen, where many
residents, including ministers, spoke passionately in defense of
the fish. Mayor Douglas Boatwright, who was then running for
re-election, scuffed his foot across the floor and announced, ``I,
for one, would like to draw a line in the sand and say this is it.
I will not change the logo!''
</P>
<P>
   Boatwright's challenger in the race for mayor, James Huntsinger,
a retired Army warrant officer who moved to Republic three years
ago, said the city's time and money would be better spent on less
``trivial'' matters like weather-proofing houses and the
environmental impact of the local building boom. He soon found
himself making house calls to voters who telephoned him questioning
whether he was truly a Christian. Huntsinger says he tried to
explain that he was indeed a Christian who favors prayer in the
schools, but found the fish on the logo ``constitutionally
indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish became the big issue in the election,'' Huntsinger
said in an interview. ``Everything else kind of took a back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   The fish began appearing all over town _ on a banner on the side
of Calvary Baptist Church, drawn on sidewalks saying, ``Save Me,''
as a sculpture on busy U.S. Highway 60, the main road through town.
</P>
<P>
   At the local nail salon, manicurists began painting fish on
customers' fingernails. A few weeks before the election, on April
7, Debbie Boatright, the mayor's wife, appeared in a photograph on
the front page of The Republic Monitor displaying her fish
manicure. Boatright, who declined to be interviewed, won the
election against Huntsinger, 716-587.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Howell, the third-generation Republic native, and 10 other
residents answered the board of aldermen's call for the formation
of a citizens' committee to raise money to defend the fish. The
board estimated that the city would need at least $100,000 to cover
legal fees to finance the fish fight.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Mrs. Howell insisted that her ``Support
Republic Committee'' did not want to be seen as a ``bunch of Bible
thumpers.'' She is a member of the state PTA board, and has run for
local office as a Democrat. At the committee's first meeting, Mrs.
Howell said, they prayed to ask God for direction. Then they
decided not to pray in their meetings again ``so the ACLU doesn't
use anything against us.'' So far the committee had raised $10,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Howell said the city's volunteer lawyers are exploring a
legal strategy that will draw on research showing that the fish
predates Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that if we can prove it's not just a Christian
symbol,'' Mrs. Howell said, ``we stand a very good chance of not
having it removed, because it's showing faith in general and not a
specific religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Kurtenbach, executive director of the Civil Liberties Union
of Kansas and Western Missouri, the regional office handling the
lawsuit, said in a telephone interview, ``This is precisely the
harm that comes to religion in these battles. What's sad is,
Republic is now scrambling to try to circumvent the First
Amendment's establishment clause by saying, `This symbol doesn't
mean much.'''
</P>
<P>
   After all this time, the person who started the controversy by
complaining about the logo has never identified himself or herself
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their own little paranoid theories,'' Mrs.
Howell said. ``Mine is that the ACLU moves people into the
community just to do this.'' She said she believed that when a
black father and his family once moved into a trailer park in
Republic and then accused the town of racial discrimination and
suddenly moved out, the ACLU had planted them there.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the ACLU are talking with several potential
plaintiffs about whose name should go on the lawsuit. One possible
plaintiff withdrew, Kurtenbach said, out of fear of losing a job.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Revi, a volunteer with the Civil Liberties Union in
Springfield, said, ``There's a real climate of fear down in
Republic right now and some of these people who initially spoke up
do not want to be named publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper editor, Larry Rottmann, insisted he was not the
person who complained, and the witch, Jean Webb, said she had not
complained either, but was considering signing on to the lawsuit
for the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not Christian. We are Wicca,'' Mrs. Webb said, talking
at a table at the Taco Bell with Jessica, her teen-age daughter.
Mrs. Webb said she had moved her family to Republic three years ago
after her daughter was harassed for her religion at the elementary
school in nearby Aurora. They moved to Republic for the good
school, the warm people, and to stay near the doctors who are
treating her husband, who has emphysema. Republic had been
``everything we wanted, until the ichthus thing came up,'' Mrs.
Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Mrs. Webb had worked at the newspaper as a
typesetter and writer. After the aldermen's meeting in March, she
says the publisher asked her to write a counterpoint editorial
opposing the fish. Mrs. Webb's editorial criticized the ``righteous
anger'' and ``gang mentality'' she said she saw at the meeting. She
says the fervor frightened her.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Webb left her job at the newspaper, she says, under
pressure from the new publisher, the father of the former
publisher. Neighborhood children have taunted Jessica, she said.
``It's gotten ugly,'' she said. ``As soon as my husband passes on,
we're moving.''
</P>
<P>
   No one involved in the fish controversy has driven the five
miles from town to Marilyn Shexsnayder's farm to ask her what she
thinks should become of the logo she designed, says Mrs.
Shexsnayder, who is mostly housebound, recovering from a car
accident two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say my eyes have been opened,'' Mrs. Shexsnayder said
softly. Until the furor over the fish, she said, ``I didn't know it
was just for Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside his wife, Del Shexsnayder, who runs a dry-ice
business and sits on the board of the local Lions Club, said that
no one he knew was in favor of keeping the fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some people within the political network of
Republic, strong Christians, that are taking this just too far,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Shexsnayder had to do it all over again, she said she
would try to find a symbol that was truly universal. ``Maybe,'' she
offered, ``a halo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
