<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEC-REVENUE-ART-NYT &LR;      06-22 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-REVENUE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PRODUCERS COPE WITH STEEP DROP IN REVENUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling 212
556-4204.) 
(JT)  
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The recent drop in oil prices, which began in October
and accelerated recently, has prompted several oil-producing
countries to take some of the medicine that high oil prices once
imposed on oil-guzzling countries like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, Saudi Arabia, the world's largest and richest
oil producer, has quietly borrowed some $2 billion from its banks
to help pay for public spending programs as it prepares to reduce
its budget by at least 10 percent and raise fees on government
services _ all to offset the most serious fall in oil revenues in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago the oil minister of Kuwait, another huge oil
producer, warned of ``a looming economic catastrophe,'' akin to the
economic and political collapse of Indonesia, for his country and
some other oil producers. The minister, Sheik Saud Nasser al-Sabah,
said that unless world oil producers made drastic cuts in oil
production, the free fall in oil prices. could bring down some
governments. Prices have plunged recently by more than 48 percent
to an average of less than $12 a barrel, from $23 last year,
</P>
<P>
   A hint of things to come may have already begun in tiny Yemen,
one of the world's smallest oil producers. Beginning on Saturday,
several cities exploded in riots as thousands of people protested a
new round of cuts in subsidies for bread and fuel imposed by the
International Monetary Fund and the government as it struggles to
make up lost income from oil exports.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in oil prices prompted the 11 members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries plus Mexico to reduce
production this year by 1 million barrels a day to help lift
prices. But the cutbacks halted the slide in prices only briefly,
and when some countries started pumping more petroleum than they
had agreed to and consumption starting declining again, prices
plunged anew. Now prices are lower than they were three months ago
when OPEC called its last emergency meeting. Another session begins
in Vienna on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the meeting will including several large
oil-producing countries that are not members of the cartel.
including Russia, Norway, Mexico and Oman.
</P>
<P>
   For the OPEC members the dimension of the crisis can be summed
up in one simple statistic: Their annual oil revenues have fallen
so far this year by almost a third, or nearly $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The recent turmoil in Asia has diminished demand for oil in what
used to be the fastest growing energy-consuming market in the
world. ``The need is for a large cut in oil production,'' said
Peter Gignoux, managing director of energy futures at Smith Barney
in London.
</P>
<P>
   He echoed a widespread view among experts that OPEC members as
well as those like Norway, Russia and Mexico, must decide to remove
far more oil from the market. perhaps as much as 2.5 million
barrels a day. That would amount to a 3.4 percent cut in total
world oil production, or twice the level of cuts OPEC and Mexico
announced in March.
</P>
<P>
   With most analysts skeptical that OPEC will agree on a such a
huge cut, oil prices are likely to fall with unpredictable
consequences of social unrest, rising unemployment and economic
instability in countries including Algeria, Russia, Nigeria,
Bahrain and Indonesia, which is already suffering an economic
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   For oil-consuming nations like the United States and Europe, the
news is just the reverse. As it stands today, these consumers are
enjoying strong economic growth and the cheapest oil in a quarter
century. Pierre Terzian, editor of the Paris-based Petrostrategies,
noted in an interview Monday that when compared with the dollar's
strength in 1973 _ the year OPEC began its ascent as a cartel _
today's oil prices are lower.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment virtually all producers to which oil represents
the lion's share of revenues are experiencing serious pain. The
full impact of the falling prices is just emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has had to stop pumping some 350,000 barrels of its daily
output of 5.9 million barrels because the cost to extract and
transport the oil exceeded market prices. In mid-May Russia also
failed to sell Rosneft, the last large state-owned oil company,
which it wants to privatize as means to raise money to reduce its
budget deficit. Russia's initial price tag of $ 2.1 billion drew no
bidders because of falling oil prices. The company is now on the
market for about $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has watched its income from oil exports, which are its
key source of hard currency, decline by a third. If prices continue
to fall, they will seriously discourage foreign oil companies from
investing further in Russian oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not by chance the Russians are going to attend this OPEC
meeting as observers,'' says Roger Diwan, director for global oil
markets for the Petroleum Finance Company, a Washington consultant.
``They are hurting as much as everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kuwait, even before the most recent price collapse began, the
government had anticipated a deficit in this year's budget of $5.73
billion, assuming an average oil price $12 a barrel. With oil
prices now likely to go lower, the deficit in the $16 billion
budget may be far higher.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia's situation is more pressing. Unlike Kuwait, it
largely spent its vast reserves during the Persian Gulf war, which
cost the country some $75 billion, and it has not been able to
replenish them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tremendous awakening to a new situation,'' said a
senior Saudi official who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``We
will have indirect taxation,'' he added, referring to tariffs and
fees for services and transactions. ``government spending will be
squeezed. This time around we don't have financial reserves to fall
back on.''
</P>
<P>
   The government of Venezuela, the leading source of oil for the
United States, so far this year has trimmed spending by $4 billion.
The Finance Ministry has announced that economic growth will fall
drastically from a very healthy 5.1 percent last year to an anemic
0.8 percent this year. The national currency, the bolivar, is
expected to lose value against the dollar resulting in higher
unemployment and rising higher prices for imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria, with oil representing 95 percent of its exports, stands
to loose at least 13 percent of its revenues this year. The loss is
certain to worsen a political and economic crisis that has already
fueled a six-year-long undeclared war that has taken 60,000 lives
between government forces and Islamic militants recruited among the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extent to which the country can withstand the present
crisis depends very much on how long oil prices remain depressed,''
said Ali A. Efssaoui, an Algerian senior research fellow at the
Oxford Institute for Energy Studies.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that a quick fix will arrest the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
