u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT &LR;      06-22 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ CRITICIZES U.N. REPORT ABOUT ITS WEAPONS PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq has criticized a U.N. report that said it
is still hiding details about its program to develop weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Security Council made public on Monday, the
deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz, complained that the report
misrepresented Iraq's willingness to make a full disclosure, which
would permit lifting the embargo on oil sales.
</P>
<P>
   The letter offered the latest counterpoint to a running dispute
that began with the imposition of sanctions after Iraqi troops
occupied Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Since it lost the Persian Gulf war in 1991, Baghdad has insisted
that it has disclosed the extent of its biological and chemical
weapons and ballistic missiles and the means to make them, but U.N.
inspectors have ferreted out evidence to the contrary. The ensuing
game of hide-and-seek has brought the United States and its allies
nearly to the point of military confrontation with Iraq twice in
the last eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz, in a letter dated Saturday, accused the chief arms
inspector, Richard Butler, who sent the report to the president of
the council last week, of ``concentrating on controversial points
in a manner that fails to give a balanced and objective picture of
what occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, the executive chairman of the U.N. Special Commission,
which is charged with ridding Iraq of its weapons of mass
destruction, visited Baghdad from June 11 to 15 to work out a
disarmament schedule that could open the way for the removal of the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   He initially expressed optimism about his progress. But his
report to the Security Council last Thursday said, ``Iraq stated
that it has already presented all the evidence available to it, and
that no additional information or documentation would be provided
to the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular Butler said Iraq refused to respond to further
questions about its production of deadly VX nerve gas. He also said
Aziz declined to provide more information about biological weapons
and missile fuel. Withholding such evidence would make it
impossible to verify that Iraq had eliminated its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The letter from Aziz appeared to have been timed to provide
Iraq's position before Wednesday, when Butler is to brief the
council.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz wrote that Baghdad had given the Special Commission ``the
relevant clarifications, explanations and documents pertaining to
VX nerve gas'' and had demonstrated that ``Iraq did not have any
other documents on the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz also argued that ``since the accounting for missile
engines, missile launchers and the warheads was completed, the
question of missile propellants loses importance and becomes a
secondary issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is in Iraq's interest to provide documents, Aziz
said, ``the Special Commission should not insist and request
something that does not exist.'' In the past, inspectors repeatedly
found documents with details of biological and chemical weapons
production that Iraqi officials had insisted did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Under Security Council Resolution 687, whose terms Iraq accepted
in 1991, the U.N. inspectors must verify that Iraq is free of
weapons of mass destruction before the oil embargo can be lifted.
The next major review by the Security Council is scheduled for
October.
</P>
<P>
   If destruction of the weapons is confirmed, active inspections
are to be replaced by long-term monitoring by a surveillance system
of video cameras and other electronic devices to prevent Iraq from
rebuilding its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad has regularly insisted that it has been unfailingly
forthcoming, while repeatedly testing the council's resolve about
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   In the last confrontation, in January and February, three of the
council's five permanent members, China, France and Russia, opposed
military strikes proposed by the United States and Britain to force
Iraq to open up fully to U.N. inspectors. This has reportedly
fueled hope in Baghdad _ and concern in Washington and London _
that support for the tough line represented by sanctions is
eroding.
</P>
</TEXT>
