<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-22 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAS LASORDA BEHIND CLAIRE, RUSSELL FIRINGS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Before a recent game against the Cincinnati Reds,
Bill Russell sat gloomily in his clubhouse office at Dodger Stadium
venting his frustrations about Tom Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy's just killing me and Fred (Claire) with the Fox
people,'' said Russell. ``Fred knows it. I know it. And there's
nothing we can do about it. It's just tough to work under these
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy's just vicious when he wants something. He did the same
sort of thing when he was a coach under Walter Alston, and wanted
Alston's job. Tommy's been second-guessing me ever since I took
over for him. Why? I don't know. All I know is that we haven't
spoken for months. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Tom Lasorda denied Russell's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Russell is like a son to me and Fred Claire has been a
friend of mine for more than 30 years,'' Lasorda told Los Angeles
sports talk show host Joe McDonnell. ``I would never politic for
either guy's job. I would never do something like that. I didn't
want anyone to get fired. But it happened, and we have to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tom Lasorda indeed had been putting the knock on Russell, he
only would have joined a lengthening list of Russell detractors
that included many Dodger fans, many media types and, ultimately,
too many members of Rupert Murdoch's impatient new management team
who questioned Russell's leadership abilities and tactical skills.
</P>
<P>
   And, if Lasorda were laying deadly minefields of criticism about
Fred Claire around town, it would have been treated with a
cautionary wink by the new Fox brass that understood that Lasorda's
motives just might be tainted by the well-known fact that he was
fanatically determined to assume Claire's job and run the team
himself.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the aftermath of the Great Dodger Sunday Night Massacre
in which both Bill Russell and Fred Claire were savagely cashiered,
there are those observers inclined to believe that Tom Lasorda
played a prominent role in it.
</P>
<P>
   And they are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Lasorda for sure hasn't been reciting epic poetry about
Russell and Claire that would inspire comparisons to T.S. Eliot, or
Ezra Pound. And it's also known he's schmoozed for long hours with
Michael Milken, a top adviser to Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm sure that the two Fox executives, Peter Chernin and
Chase Carey, who manipulate the puppet strings attached to the
so-called Dodger president, Bob Graziano, would have coolly ignored
Lasorda's alleged remonstrances and not made such a stunning
decision had the team not fallen haplessly on its cleats.
</P>
<P>
   The cruel bottom line is that Bill Russell and Fred Claire are
among the dearly departed because of where the Dodgers now find
themselves in the N.L. West Division standings.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday evening's debate with the Anaheim Angels, the
Dodgers were 36-38 and 12{ games behind the San Diego Padres, not
exactly where the Los Angeles team expected to be at this juncture
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the giddy optimism of March and April, the Dodgers
were actually the consensus favorite to win their division for
reasons I never quite understood.
</P>
<P>
   You knew the team simply wasn't that good when it arrived here
for its opener without a legitimate center fielder and with a bunch
of guys on its roster (Matt Luke, Trenidad Hubbard, Thomas Howard,
ad nauseam) that nobody else desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough players,'' Bill Russell stated to me
privately.
</P>
<P>
   And what compounded the Dodgers' miseries is that they didn't
have any pitchers, either, as all except Ramon Martinez and Darren
Dreifort turned out to be disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo was such a bust that the Dodgers traded him to the
New York Mets, which might turn out to be a deft move in light of
Nomo's failings.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Fred Claire, responsible for putting this Dodger team
together, must be held at least partly accountable for its
pratfall, although Claire was kept under a severe monetary
restraint in recent years by the notoriously thrifty former Dodger
owner, Peter O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   While a division rival like the Padres was going out and
spending money to get players like Kevin Brown, Ken Caminiti and
Greg Vaughn, Claire has had to operate under the handicap of being
forced to go after second-tier guys like Todd Zeile, Jose Vizcaino,
Eric Young, etc.
</P>
<P>
   And, in what was particularly humiliating to him, Claire wasn't
even consulted last month in perhaps the biggest transaction in
Dodger history.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it turns out Claire was vehemently opposed to that
staggering miscalculation pulled off by the neophyte Fox management
team when it put its baseball ignorance on public display for all
to ridicule by trading away the team's only marquee performer, Mike
Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   It has been one of the hoariest maxims of professional athletics
since the Boston Red Sox got rid of Babe Ruth almost 80 years ago
that a team should never divest itself of a superstar who's in his
prime, but Messrs. Chernin and Carey were going to show the
baseball establishment how the big boys do it in the movie
business.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. They sure showed everybody!
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were struggling before they dispatched Piazza and
Zeile to the Florida Marlins for Gary Sheffield, Charles Johnson,
Bobby Bonilla and Jim Eisnreich, none of whom has exactly stirred
Dodger fans to storm the turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Dodgers are struggling even more without at least
the presence of the slugging Piazza to boost home attendance during
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Fox worsened a bad situation with a trade it probably already is
embarrassed about---Piazza has been treated like a conquering hero
in New York---and now has detached Russell and Claire for I guess
therapeutic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt if Russell's successor, Glen Hoffman, can do much to
reverse the fortunes of a team that simply doesn't possess enough
talented players to exceed the .500 caliber baseball it's played
throughout this erratic Dodger season.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if Fox wanted to do something dramatic, it should have
stuck Tom Lasorda back into the dugout, where his charismatic
presence would have at least enlivened a moribund team and where he
has longed to be ever since he retired as manager in the middle of
the 1996 summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda also longed for Fred Claire's job, and it's the irony of
all ironies that he landed it on the day Claire's successor, Al
Campanis, a close friend of Lasorda, died.
</P>
<P>
   Claire took over for Campanis in April of 1987 after Peter
O'Malley fired Campanis for his racially insensitive remarks on
ABC's ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire's greatest legacy will be the Dodgers' storybook 1988
season in which they shocked the New York Mets to win the National
League pennant and then did the same to the Oakland A's to win the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It was Claire who brought in a fellow who would goad that team
to its destiny, Kirk Gibson, and Claire would win Executive of the
Year honors for his work.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers never again would reach such heights during
Claire's long incumbency, and it seemed in recent years Claire
never was able to get over that disastrous trade he made earlier
this decade with the Montreal Expos when he parted with a young
righthander named Pedro Martinez for Delino DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not all Fred Claire's fault, or Bill Russell's, that
the Dodgers have deteriorated into mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plight became inevitable a few years back when Peter
O'Malley, unable or unwilling to battle teams like the Atlanta
Braves in pursuit of high-priced free agents, forced Claire to
conduct his business with one arm tied behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   The neophyte Fox team tried to undo the mess that O'Malley's
tight-fisted policies created, but only exacerbated the chaos with
the ouster of Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tom Lasorda is back in power, trying to bring light into a
Dodger scene that has fallen into darkness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
