u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-HARASS-BOS &LR;      06-22 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING PROTECTS SCHOOLS IN SEX HARASSMENT CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in the first of three decisions
this term to define liability for sexual harassment, ruled Monday
that school districts do not have to pay damages to students
harassed by teachers if officials didn't know about the misconduct
or tried to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision will make it much harder for victims of school
harassment to win monetary awards. It also signaled that a majority
of the justices would like to start changing the punitive climate
that pervades sexual-harassment law.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the majority,
acknowledged that while ``harassment unfortunately is an all-too
common aspect of educational experience,'' a Texas middle-school
student was not entitled to collect punitive damages from the Lago
Vista public school district that employed a high-school teacher
who sexually harassed her for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damages may not be recovered ... unless an official of the
school district who at mimimum has authority to institute
corrective measures has actual notice of, and is deliberately
indifferent to, the teacher's misconduct,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who said she based her opinion on interpretation of
Title IX, the federal statute that prohibits sex discrimination in
education, upheld an appeals court ruling and was joined by Chief
Justice William Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony
Kennedy, and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In a toughly worded dissent, Justice John Paul Stevens said the
court ruling ``thwarts the purposes of Title IX'' _ which is to
``minimize the danger that vulnerable students will be exposed to
such odious behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as school boards can insulate themselves from
knowledge about this sort of conduct, they can claim immunity from
damages liability,'' wrote Stevens, who was joined in his dissent
by Justices David Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision was closely analyzed by civil rights and
business groups that are awaiting two other Supreme Court rulings
in the next week considered crucial in setting the extent of an
employer's liability when a supervisor sexually harasses a worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ... ruling is promising,'' said Robin Conrad, a senior
vice president at the National Chamber Litigation Center, an arm of
the US Chamber of Commerce and an advocate for limiting liability
on employers for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to hold employers liable for wrongdoing
they didn't notice and corrective actions they didn't know to
take,'' Conrad said. ``The court is showing a certain pragmatism
here that makes us hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the one of the pending cases, the court has been asked to
find the city of Boca Raton financially liable for the sexual
harassment of lifeguard Beth Ann Faragher by her supervisor, a city
employee. Faragher sued the city in 1992 for failing to police
obscene talk and obnoxious touching by her boss at the beach. A
federal appeals court sided with the city, saying it should not be
held responsible for misconduct that was not reported to city hall.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, the court must decide if an employer,
Burlington Industries, must be liable when a supervisor engages in
sexual misconduct but the employee, Kimberly Ellerth, rebuffed the
advances and suffered no adverse job consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of so-called quid pro quo harm was central to US
District Judge Susan Webber Wright's dismissal of Paula Jones's
sexual harassment lawsuit against President Clinton. Jones's
lawyers say they are waiting for the Supreme Court to rule in the
Burlington case before filing papers in their appeal of Wright's
April 1 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said it is risky to predict how the court will
come down in the two employment cases, based on Monday's decision
in the student-harassment case. O'Conner made it clear in her
opinion that the liability standards under Title VII, the law
barring sex discrimination in the workplace, are stricter than
those in Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't make Monday's decision insignificant, according
to Victoria Alzapiedi, executive director of the Title IX Advocacy
Project in Boston. She said the ruling will have a chilling effect
on the reporting and follow-up of sexual harassment incidents in
middle schools and high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If students have to let school administrators, as opposed to
teachers or counselors, know about harassment, they will fear the
implications for themselves and the stigma among their peers,''
said Alzapiedi, whose nonprofit group works with adolescents on
Title IX issues. ``The backlash _ subtle or blatant _ will be a
major disincentive to report a hostile sexual environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's case, a middle school student met social studies
teacher Frank Waldrop in 1991 when she was placed in a program for
the gifted at Lago Vista High School near Austin. Waldrop's
sexually suggestive remarks to her grew into a sexual relationship
in 1992. In 1993, the pair was caught by a police officer, who
arrested Waldrop. The school district fired Waldrop, who later
pleaded guilty to statutory rape.
</P>
<P>
   At no time did the student complain to school officials, though
the high school principal was told by other parents about Waldrop's
lewd comments in class. In 1993, the student and her mother filed a
sexual-harassment suit against the school district and Waldrop,
seeking punitive damages from both. Two lower federal courts
rejected the claims against the school district. The federal court
sent the suit against Waldrop to a state court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court properly refused to hold school districts
liable for the concealed criminal conduct of abusive employes,''
said Wallace Jefferson, the San Antonio lawyer who represented the
school district. ``Most school districts would be financially
devastated by jury verdicts holding them liable for sexual
harassment, which they could not have prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of School Boards, which filed a
friend-of-the-court brief on behalf of the school district, praised
Monday's decision and said it would make schools more, not less
vigilant in exposing sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reinforces the importance of preventive action, and in no
way lets any school administrator off the hook,'' said Anne Bryant,
executive director of the school boards association, a private
group.
</P>
<P>
   But Marcia Greenberger, co-president of the National Women's Law
Center, called it ``a very disappointing decision'' and said
Congress will have to legislate remedies for students that the
court would not prescribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially painful to see students having less access
than adult employees have under Title VII, when harassment in
schools can be just as severe with even greater lifelong
consequences,'' Greenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The case is Gebser vs. Lago Vista Independent School District,
96-1866.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
