<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STINSON-ECOLI-COX     06-22 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STINSON-ECOLI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves shortstop Weiss takes leave to be with E. coli-infected
son
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (S) sports and (A) general news categories.)
 &HT;    By Tom Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brody Weiss is two months shy of his fourth birthday,
with blond hair and a sharp angle on life that makes you wonder how
something that small lives that large.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's our high-maintenance kid, bouncing off the wall, he's got
so much energy,'' said his father, Walt Weiss, a reserved and
reflective man. ''Everybody who knows him always jokes about it.
The first thing people who haven't seen us for a while is, 'How's
Brody?' Everybody loves him because he's so active.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss is leaning against a wall down the hall from the
Intensive Care Unit at Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center,
which is all wrong. The past week has been all wrong, not just for
Walt and wife Terri Weiss, but for a small but heavy handful of
families in the metro Atlanta. Their kids have been diagnosed with
E. coli 0157:H7, a deadly strain of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Brody Weiss' kidneys have already shut down and all anyone can
do is watch over the coming weeks for what else the bacteria might
do before it recedes. Walt has just gotten off the phone, where
he'd been trying in vain to reach his boss, Bobby Cox, who is with
the rest of the Atlanta Braves in New York City, which must be a
million miles away from this place. Maybe Walt will be at shortstop
Wednesday night at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no antibiotics that can treat this,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you develop toxins in your blood and obviously once
it's your blood, it passes through your whole body... and your
kidneys ultimately shut down. When (wife Terri) brought him in
Saturday evening, he had 50 percent kidney failure. Now he's at 100
percent (failure). He just came out of surgery to get a catheter
put into his stomach for his bowels and _ just now as we speak _
he's getting hooked up to a dialysis machine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically now, they're trying to get his kidneys working on
their own and then sit back. I mean, you hope that . . . the thing
you want to stay away from is neurological damage. When it's in you
blood, it's everywhere. It has the potential to affect other
organs.''
</P>
<P>
   So insidious is this strain of E. coli that somehow, the Weisses
feel blessed that Brody is in serious condition. Two other children
at Scottish Rite are listed as critical. The families share the
common nightmare _ a healthy child struck down in a mysterious
instant. The wait is 24 hours at a time, the stashed pillows and
blankets in the corners now all their transmuted homes. A World Cup
soccer match on a corner TV plays for no one.
</P>
<P>
   The blinking red light on the phone at the Sheraton Centre in
Montreal late Saturday night hinted at nothing like this. Weiss had
just gone 3-for-4 against the Expos and, though he'd helped bring
Brody in to the hospital three times last week, a dose of
antibiotics hinted he'd turn the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good thing my wife has been persistent through this
whole thing,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She took him back to ER a fourth time. We were aware that he
had E. coli. It came back in his stool sample. But there are
different strains of E. coli and once she brought him back in
Saturday evening, that's the first time he was diagnosed as having
the deadly strain. He was probably admitted about game time in
Montreal (7 p.m.) that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss left the Braves the next morning and hasn't even had time
to clear the family's message machine at their Marietta, Ga. home.
The source of the infection and whether it could be linked with
other cases is something he's put aside for now, the better to turn
his full energies to maintaining all of the Weisses. Besides Terri,
there is a son Blake, 11, and an infant, Bo.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll be 11 months,'' Weiss said, checking the date on his
watch, ''in two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, on this day, on this hall, in this place is only an
eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson is a sports writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
