<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VIAGRA-WOMEN-625(     06-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VIAGRA-WOMEN-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIAGRA'S OTHER SIDE EFFECT: UPSETS IN MANY A MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(EDS: This replaces story with the same slug but different
description listed on noon sked.) (lh) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the surface, the couple from Queens seemed like
perfect candidates for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   They have been married for 30 years, and he began having trouble
achieving an erection a few years ago. While unhappy about it, the
husband, 59, had learned to see some good in it. ``My eye doesn't
wander anymore,'' he said, ``because I can't do anything about it''
</P>
<P>
   And though the woman, 53, said she ``could not imagine staying
in a relationship without sex,'' she, too, had reconciled herself
to having other kinds of intimacy and other forms of sex.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra, the popular new drug for impotence, would appear to be
their ticket back to a more conventional sex life. But like many
couples contemplating Viagra, the two are starkly divided about
whether to try it: While he is looking for a medical panacea for a
physical problem that often comes with age, she has long wondered
whether the problem might be better addressed on a therapist's
couch than in a doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Viagra was being promoted by everyone from
urologists to drug company analysts as destined to help solve
millions of Americans' sexual problems. The drug flew off pharmacy
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   But therapists and experts on sexuality are finding that Viagra
and other impotence aids may actually throw into chaos
relationships that have fallen into their own routine, sexual
dysfunction and all.
</P>
<P>
   The most common problem, they say, is that men hope to treat
their impotence as a simple mechanical issue, while women tend to
want to address the emotions related to impotence. In other cases,
a man and woman are forced to confront their divergent views about
what it means to have sex and how often they want to have it _
issues that impotence had rendered moot.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that many couples are finding that a solution to
what they thought was a medical problem may uncover myriad other
issues in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very high-tech society, and people are used to
having things done very quickly,'' said Eileen Palace, director of
the Center for Sexual Health at Tulane University Hospital in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw in the 1960s how the pill could control biology. Later,
we saw how to control infertility. People want a simple, easy, fast
solution. And many physicians assume that just because there is a
physical problem means there is no psychological cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Urologists interviewed for this article said they had been
writing Viagra prescriptions by the dozens, many for patients who
had never before said they were impotent. Some had not even
confided in their partners. Instead, they simply avoided sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy sees himself having trouble, and he, out of
embarrassment and lack of communicativity, he says, `I am going to
sleep in the other room,''' said Dr. Walter Bortz, a geriatrics
specialist at the Palo Alto Medical Foundation, in California.
``The wife thinks he has a girlfriend. And it becomes a gulf that
enters a well-cemented relationship, because egos get in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   When the possibility of sex resurfaces, a couple is often at a
loss. They never talked much about their problems before, and now
they have no idea how to approach the change. In the meantime, all
the issues that contributed to the impotence or resulted from it
have been long swept under the rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone hears about Viagra, they are expecting to get
better on their sexual problems,'' said E. Douglas Whitehead,
director of the Association for Male Sexual Dysfunction in New
York. ``But there are many issues that affect desire: life
stresses, the stock market, other issues. But most of the time,
people don't talk about those problems. ... They think Viagra will
address them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The woman from Queens who, like her husband, agreed to be
interviewed if they were not identified, said she was frustrated
and had given up trying to persuade her husband to address the
emotional aspects of their sexual problems in therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``His doctor suggested he go into therapy because he couldn't
find any medical reason for his borderline erections,'' she said.
``I thought therapy was a great opportunity, but he didn't want to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Therapy is where many couples dealing with impotence belong,
even if they use Viagra, many doctors say. The couple may never
have discussed the inevitable resentment and pain that resulted
from their damaged sex lives, feelings that will not disappear with
medication. Once Viagra allows a couple to have sex again, their
relationship can change.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Viagra, which must be taken an hour before
intercourse, and other drugs for impotence leave little room for
spontaneous romantic encounters. What is more, a couple used to not
having sex may be out of practice in the language and gestures of
sexual intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Palace recalled a man with diabetes, which often contributes to
impotence, who would inject drugs that help impotent men achieve
erections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in in tears, because his wife's romantic gesture was
to lay the syringe on the pillow,'' she said. ``You have to be able
to talk about the role of the treatment in the relationship. And
I've learned to trust penises, because they are good indicators of
what is going on in a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven and Katherine, who spoke on the condition that their last
name not be used, had married shortly after testicular cancer left
him impotent in 1990. They then found their relationship in trouble
when Steven began using penile injections.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we would go to the urologist,'' Katherine said, ``they
would come up with this or that and address really only my husband
and his physical problems.'' This or that turned out to be
injections that produced erections but terrible sex. The injections
themselves were disturbing enough, she said, but the underlying
problem was her unacknowledged feelings about having married a man
who was impotent. Ultimately, she said, she worked through the
problem in sex therapy at Tulane. ``Part of what therapy did was
help me face the grief that I had never faced being married to a
man who was impotent.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven agreed that he had not thought through the emotional
issues related to their sexual problems. ``I thought my primary
problem was plumbing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that amazed me when we finally opened the lines of
communication was that my sexual performance was not satisfactory
for her. I thought things were fine. But because she loved me
anyway, she made a conscious decision to forgo a good sexual life
to have a good marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they have decided to forgo Viagra and explore other
avenues of sexual intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   While many therapists and urologists say that most men are loath
to discuss their sexual problems with anyone, especially a
therapist, the men themselves see Viagra as an easy way out.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper Schwartz, a professor of sociology at the University of
Washington in Seattle and author of several books about American
sexual habits, cited two things about Viagra that appeal to men:
``They don't have to talk about impotence, and they have a high
assurance of potential good in using it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``the issues that have been shrugged off are the
psychological and social aspects of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I do believe that any drug that alters the core way a
couple relates to each other requires discussions of expectations
and pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Most men, however, seem reluctant to talk even to their
partners, let alone an outsider, about their sexual problems. A
74-year-old man from Long Island who has had erectile dysfunction
since his 20s could never quite talk to his wife of 25 years about
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tend to kind of brush the problem under the rug,'' he
said. ``It isn't an easy topic to deal with. It goes to the heart
of your masculinity.''
</P>
<P>
   After a divorce, his problem recurred during a 20-year
relationship with a much younger woman. He now admits that a more
active sex life might have saved both relationships.
</P>
<P>
   He is convinced that Viagra is the answer to his lifelong sexual
problem and that no amount of therapy would help.
</P>
<P>
   The woman from Queens went into therapy alone and kept her
emotional journey to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therapy was helpful to me,'' she said. ``I felt like it made
me understand that this was just one more thing to deal with, not
the end of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-HARASS-BOS &LR;      06-22 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING PROTECTS SCHOOLS IN SEX HARASSMENT CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in the first of three decisions
this term to define liability for sexual harassment, ruled Monday
that school districts do not have to pay damages to students
harassed by teachers if officials didn't know about the misconduct
or tried to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision will make it much harder for victims of school
harassment to win monetary awards. It also signaled that a majority
of the justices would like to start changing the punitive climate
that pervades sexual-harassment law.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the majority,
acknowledged that while ``harassment unfortunately is an all-too
common aspect of educational experience,'' a Texas middle-school
student was not entitled to collect punitive damages from the Lago
Vista public school district that employed a high-school teacher
who sexually harassed her for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damages may not be recovered ... unless an official of the
school district who at mimimum has authority to institute
corrective measures has actual notice of, and is deliberately
indifferent to, the teacher's misconduct,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who said she based her opinion on interpretation of
Title IX, the federal statute that prohibits sex discrimination in
education, upheld an appeals court ruling and was joined by Chief
Justice William Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony
Kennedy, and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In a toughly worded dissent, Justice John Paul Stevens said the
court ruling ``thwarts the purposes of Title IX'' _ which is to
``minimize the danger that vulnerable students will be exposed to
such odious behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as school boards can insulate themselves from
knowledge about this sort of conduct, they can claim immunity from
damages liability,'' wrote Stevens, who was joined in his dissent
by Justices David Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision was closely analyzed by civil rights and
business groups that are awaiting two other Supreme Court rulings
in the next week considered crucial in setting the extent of an
employer's liability when a supervisor sexually harasses a worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ... ruling is promising,'' said Robin Conrad, a senior
vice president at the National Chamber Litigation Center, an arm of
the US Chamber of Commerce and an advocate for limiting liability
on employers for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to hold employers liable for wrongdoing
they didn't notice and corrective actions they didn't know to
take,'' Conrad said. ``The court is showing a certain pragmatism
here that makes us hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the one of the pending cases, the court has been asked to
find the city of Boca Raton financially liable for the sexual
harassment of lifeguard Beth Ann Faragher by her supervisor, a city
employee. Faragher sued the city in 1992 for failing to police
obscene talk and obnoxious touching by her boss at the beach. A
federal appeals court sided with the city, saying it should not be
held responsible for misconduct that was not reported to city hall.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, the court must decide if an employer,
Burlington Industries, must be liable when a supervisor engages in
sexual misconduct but the employee, Kimberly Ellerth, rebuffed the
advances and suffered no adverse job consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of so-called quid pro quo harm was central to US
District Judge Susan Webber Wright's dismissal of Paula Jones's
sexual harassment lawsuit against President Clinton. Jones's
lawyers say they are waiting for the Supreme Court to rule in the
Burlington case before filing papers in their appeal of Wright's
April 1 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said it is risky to predict how the court will
come down in the two employment cases, based on Monday's decision
in the student-harassment case. O'Conner made it clear in her
opinion that the liability standards under Title VII, the law
barring sex discrimination in the workplace, are stricter than
those in Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't make Monday's decision insignificant, according
to Victoria Alzapiedi, executive director of the Title IX Advocacy
Project in Boston. She said the ruling will have a chilling effect
on the reporting and follow-up of sexual harassment incidents in
middle schools and high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If students have to let school administrators, as opposed to
teachers or counselors, know about harassment, they will fear the
implications for themselves and the stigma among their peers,''
said Alzapiedi, whose nonprofit group works with adolescents on
Title IX issues. ``The backlash _ subtle or blatant _ will be a
major disincentive to report a hostile sexual environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's case, a middle school student met social studies
teacher Frank Waldrop in 1991 when she was placed in a program for
the gifted at Lago Vista High School near Austin. Waldrop's
sexually suggestive remarks to her grew into a sexual relationship
in 1992. In 1993, the pair was caught by a police officer, who
arrested Waldrop. The school district fired Waldrop, who later
pleaded guilty to statutory rape.
</P>
<P>
   At no time did the student complain to school officials, though
the high school principal was told by other parents about Waldrop's
lewd comments in class. In 1993, the student and her mother filed a
sexual-harassment suit against the school district and Waldrop,
seeking punitive damages from both. Two lower federal courts
rejected the claims against the school district. The federal court
sent the suit against Waldrop to a state court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court properly refused to hold school districts
liable for the concealed criminal conduct of abusive employes,''
said Wallace Jefferson, the San Antonio lawyer who represented the
school district. ``Most school districts would be financially
devastated by jury verdicts holding them liable for sexual
harassment, which they could not have prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of School Boards, which filed a
friend-of-the-court brief on behalf of the school district, praised
Monday's decision and said it would make schools more, not less
vigilant in exposing sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reinforces the importance of preventive action, and in no
way lets any school administrator off the hook,'' said Anne Bryant,
executive director of the school boards association, a private
group.
</P>
<P>
   But Marcia Greenberger, co-president of the National Women's Law
Center, called it ``a very disappointing decision'' and said
Congress will have to legislate remedies for students that the
court would not prescribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially painful to see students having less access
than adult employees have under Title VII, when harassment in
schools can be just as severe with even greater lifelong
consequences,'' Greenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The case is Gebser vs. Lago Vista Independent School District,
96-1866.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
