<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD REGULATE AU PAIRS IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An au pair licensing bill originally designed to
prevent a repeat of a Louise Woodward case cleared a major
legislative hurdle Monday, but its sponsor charged that lawmakers
had bowed to pressure from au pair agencies and that the rewritten
version has lost its teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature's Committee on Human Services, after seven
months of debate and negotiations, approved the bill, which creates
state regulations and licensing guidelines for au pair agencies. It
also would require au pairs to take certified training in various
child-care skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can only improve child care for Massachusetts families,''
said Susan Gross, director of program development at the EF Au Pair
agency of Cambridge, which placed Woodward in the Eappen family.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward this year was found guilty of manslaughter in the death
of Matthew Eappen, who prosecutors said died after being violently
shook.
</P>
<P>
   But Representative Marie J. Parente, a Milford Democrat who
offered the original bill in the days following Woodward's
conviction in October, scoffed at the rewritten version, saying the
committee has done little to change the way the au pair agencies
are doing business. She removed her name as a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must be celebrating,'' said Parente, who said the panel
had come under intense lobbying from EF Au Pair. ``The committee is
asking them to do what they already do, for the most part. They've
only added a few things.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill goes to the House Ways and Means Committee before it
can reach the full House for a vote. If approved, it would then go
to the Senate. Because the legislative session is winding down, it
is not clear whether the bill can be enacted before the lawmakers
end their session next month.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Michael P. Cahill, the Beverly Democrat who
chairs the committee, said he would not speculate on whether the
legislation could prevent another case in which a child under an au
pair's care dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't hazard a guess on that,'' Cahill said. ``But in
looking into this issue, we could see the potential dangers have
been there all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Parente, however, said some of her bill's provisions, such as
clearly defining an au pair's role and requiring au pairs to have
previous professional child care experience, would have made a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Louise had been properly trained, she might never have
faced what it appears she did in the Eappen home,'' Parente said.
``These unresolved stories between the family and Louise would not
have been there if there were clear and defined objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Parente was particularly critical of the committee decision to
delete her proposal that would limit 18- and 19-year-olds to caring
for only two children under 5 years of age. She also wants to
require that the au pair have professional child care experience,
something the committee rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bill says they have to come properly trained,'' Parente
said. ``I don't see that with this bill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
