<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-U.S.-450-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BELARUS, ENVOYS' HOUSES ARE NO LONGER THEIR HOMES
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president of Belarus, Alexander Lukashenko,
insists that he cannot understand what all the fuss is about. ``A
simple housing problem is being turned into an affair of state,''
he complained Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But for the ambassadors from the United States, Japan and
several European countries, the efforts of the Belarus government
to oust them from their homes in Minsk, the capital, is an affair
of state and a clear violation of diplomatic convention.
</P>
<P>
   The United States recalled Ambassador Daniel Speckhard and made
clear that the Belarus ambassador would not be welcome back in
Washington anytime soon. ``In English, it would be a real bad idea
for him to come to the United States right now,'' said James Rubin,
the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Belarus officials have told the diplomats that the authoritarian
president wants to force the ambassadors out of their apartments in
a diplomatic compound in Minsk so he can expand his official
residence, which adjoins the compound. Officially, the government
has said the diplomats must move because of a need for extensive
renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to evict the diplomats has not been subtle.
Electricity, water and phone service have been cut off without
warning. Some diplomats returned to their homes last week to find
workmen trying to weld the gates shut. Rubin described the actions
as ``unprecedentedly uncivilized behavior for a member of the
international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain, France, Germany, Greece, Italy and Japan also withdrew
diplomats from Minsk on Monday to protest what seemed to be a
blatant violation of the Vienna Convention, under which embassies
and residences are supposed to be inviolable.
</P>
<P>
   As she prepared to leave Minsk on Monday, British Ambassador
Jessica Pearse said the exodus was meant to send a message to
Lukashenko, a former director of a collective farm who rules
Belarus virtually as a dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of us leaving is to show that he cannot treat us in
the way that he expects to be able to treat anyone in his
country,'' she said on the BBC. ``Ambassadors are expected to be
treated with a certain status, a certain respect and a certain
common courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the protests, the State Department was careful to point
out that the United States was not breaking diplomatic ties with
Belarus, a former Soviet republic of 10 million people that won
praise several years ago when it chose to give up the nuclear
warheads that the Soviet Union had left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our embassy remains open,'' Rubin said. ``But so long as
they're going to violate one of the first premises of diplomatic
relations _ that is, the inviolability of an ambassador's residence
_ it's very hard to have a serious diplomatic discussion with
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
