<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SAFETY-COX     06-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAFETY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expert advice: Wash food, cook meat and be a smart consumer
 &HT;    (EDS: Can also run with ECOLI and STINSON-ECOLI)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dangers of E. coli can be serious, but consumers can often
combat them by thoroughly washing and cooking food, according to a
leading expert on the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Doyle, director of the Center for Food Safety and
Quality Enhancement at the University of Georgia, is involved in
testing and studying the dangerous strain E. coli O157:H7. He
tested meat in the 1993 widely publicized Jack in the Box case in
the Seattle area, an outbreak that sickened hundreds and killed
four.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle is a member of a panel assembled by the National Academy
of Science to recommend improvements to government food safety
efforts. He spoke Monday at a national meeting in Atlanta of the
Institute of Food Technologists, a gathering of food scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is E. coli and are all strains alike and bad for us?
</P>
<P>
   A: E. coli is a bacteria and some of them are good. They live in
our intestinal tract and do no harm whatsoever. It's the particular
strain O157:H7 that can kill.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long has this deadly strain been evident and what foods
are most likely to carry it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was first recognized as a pathogen in 1982, though it's
probably been around for 30 to 50 years. The No. 1 source of E.
coli O157:H7 illness is ground beef. The second most common way is
by coming in direct contact with animal feces on a farm. Beyond
that, foods such as apple juice, lettuce and sprouts have all been
sources of outbreaks. And this organism has an unusual resistance
to acid, including stomach acid, which we usually count on to kill
harmful bacteria. That's why it can survive in juices.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the symptoms of the illness and who does it threaten
most?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not everyone who comes in contact with it develops an
illness. Those most severely affected are the young and the
elderly. It starts out with watery diarrhea and severe abdominal
cramping. Then you will see bloody stools. From there about 10
percent of children and the elderly will develop hemolytic uremic
syndrome, or HUS. That can lead to kidney failure and, in the most
severe cases, death.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can be done to prevent it, starting with the source?
</P>
<P>
   A: At the processing plants, there are steps, such as steam
pasteurization, to try to clean the surface of the meat and to
avoid cross contamination. But it's next to impossible to remove it
all. You may kill a hundred-fold or a thousand-fold of the
bacteria. But it takes a very low dosage of E. coli O157:H7 to make
you sick. Irradiation of meat, which has now been approved by the
FDA, can help. But there aren't enough facilities for irradiation
and it does effect the flavor of meats with high fat content, like
ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what's the option for the consumer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The consumer has to take this very seriously. Do not eat
ground beef that is pink in the middle. Many people still do that.
Cook ground beef until there's no pink and the juices run clear. To
be extra sure, use a meat thermometer and cook to 160 degrees.
Beyond that, wash fresh foods that aren't cooked, like lettuce,
very, very well. Peel off the outside layers. For juices and cider,
pasteurization will take care of it. And wash your hands before
handling food.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you think the food industry is handling this
challenge?
</P>
<P>
   A: Food processers have responded very positively, putting into
place processes that help ensure safety. That's in their best
interest. But the producers are where the problem lies. If there is
no way to convince the producers that they've got to help produce
safe food, then they will continue to hand the problem over to the
processors. Too many farmers think of food as a commodity and not
as something we eat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about government agencies? Are they doing enough in
terms of food safety?
</P>
<P>
   A: Considering the resources available, they are doing a
remarkable job. But things can be done better. Sometimes hands are
tied by statutes and by producers. And some problems emerge, like
new pathogens, that we can't predict.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
