</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-PROVOST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U of F scientist is named provost at UGA
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ University of Georgia President Michael Adams on
Monday named Karen Holbrook, a scientist and administrator from the
University of Florida, as the university's new provost and chief
academic officer, saying she was both committed to undergraduate
teaching and experienced with research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any one of the three finalists could have done the job, but
the chemistry between us was the best,'' Adams said as he
introduced Holbrook, the highest ranking woman ever at UGA, to
about 40 employees from across campus. ``I like to like the people
with whom I spend this much time.''
</P>
<P>
   In her new job, Holbrook, 55, will be responsible for all core
academic functions, including public service and outreach,
instruction, student affairs and research. She will be one of three
vice presidents reporting directly to Adams, who began touting this
new administrative structure when he arrived on campus last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being personable, Holbrook is viewed by her fellow
faculty members as collegial, Adams said. Her scientific background
complements his background in the social sciences professionally,
as does her productive work pace.
</P>
<P>
   According to UGA, Holbrook will be paid $210,000 yearly. In
addition, she will receive a car allowance and half membership in
the Athens Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook holds a bachelor's degree and a master's degree in
zoology from the University of Wisconsin and a Ph.D. in biological
structure from the University of Washington School of Medicine. She
joined the faculty there in 1972, eventually becoming the associate
dean for scientific affairs by 1993, when she moved to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida, she was dean of the Graduate School Office of
Research, Technology and Graduate Education and a professor of
anatomy and cell biology and medicine. Her area of interest in
research is dermatology. She has worked on various levels with the
National Institutes of Health for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook said that she had ``heard really positive things''
about UGA and Georgia Gov. Zell Miller's commitment to higher
education. She wants the university to continue as one of the
nation's finest research institutions ``that still cares about its
undergraduate education program.''
</P>
<P>
   She is married to James R. Holbrook, an oceanographer retired
from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, and they
have a grown son.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
