<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH--DISNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR MAY TAKE HEAT FROM G.O.P. CONSERVATIVES FOR TIES TO
DISNEY, R-RATED FILMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's first chore if he runs for
president in 2000 may be to convince Republican social
conservatives to accept his little-known role in helping finance
more than a dozen R-rated movies for the Walt Disney Co.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boycotts of Disney by the Southern Baptist Convention and
American Family Association over its adult movies appear to have
had little financial effect on Disney, but the influence of social
and religious conservatives in the Republican presidential
nominating process could cause trouble for Bush because of his
personal ties to financing Disney movies.
</P>
<P>
   Social conservatives in Texas already are pushing state
government under Bush to sell off more than $416 million in Disney
stock owned by Texas trust and pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a paid director of Silver Screen Management Services
Inc. from 1983 until he resigned from its board two months before
announcing for governor in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Screen, through limited partnerships, raised more than $1
billion to finance Disney movies ranging from The Little Mermaid to
Stakeout, a comedy about undercover police spying on suspected
criminals in a fancy mountain home. Silver Screen financed 21
R-rated movies; 32 PG and PG-13 movies; and nine G movies.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Screen was founded and run by Bush's Yale fraternity
brother Roland Betts. Betts also was the largest single shareholder
in the Texas Rangers baseball team while Bush was the team's
managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Betts recently sold their interests in the Texas
Rangers, and last week Bush received $14.9 million for his original
$600,000 investment in the team.
</P>
<P>
   None of the R-rated movies financed by Silver Screen are among
the more controversial films that have led to boycotts of Disney by
social conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   The movies most often cited as offensive _ ``Priest,'' ``Pulp
Fiction'' or ``Chasing Amy'' _ were produced under the Miramax
label. Silver Screen partners financed more than 50 Walt Disney and
Touchstone label movies.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the Silver Screen-financed movies _ ``Down and Out in
Beverly Hills'' _ was the first R-rated movie ever produced by
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   American Family Association of Texas President Wyatt Roberts
said the Touchstone movies ``are not the really raunchy stuff.
Those are more adult oriented, more mature.'' But Roberts said
Touchstone paved the way for the more ``sexually graphic and
gratuitously violent'' Miramax movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touchstone opened the door,'' Roberts said. ``It signaled to
people that Disney was ready to broaden its appeal beyond family
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there is no reason why his party's social
conservatives should hold his work with Silver Screen against him.
He said he was never an investor in either Silver Screen or Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only interest was for the company itself,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said as an outside director his role was not to make movies
but to make sure the business itself was properly run. Bush said
Betts asked him to be on the board as part of several business
deals they were doing together, such as the Texas Rangers. But
State Board of Education member Bob Offutt of San Antonio, who is
pushing the state to sell its Disney stock, said he was
``disappointed'' to learn of Bush's connection to the financing of
R-rated Disney movies.
</P>
<P>
   Offutt said that connection could make Bush a tough sell to
social conservatives nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you add those things together there will be many of the
social conservatives in the Republican Party who will be seeking an
alternative to him in the year 2000,'' Offutt said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, however, said the effect on Bush will be ``negligible''
for anyone except those who already oppose Bush for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Those conservatives, he said, ``will hold it up and say, `He's
bankrolling the Disney empire,''' Roberts said. ``But given the
minimal involvement he had, I can't see this having an impact on
his political aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   When social conservative voters turned against U.S. Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, in Louisiana and Iowa in 1996, it ended his quest
for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   One of the controversies surrounding Gramm was his 1974
investment of $7,500 in an R-rated movie called ``Beauty Queens''
being produced by his former brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty Queens'' was never made. The money instead was spent on
an R-rated satire of former President Nixon. Gramm said he never
saw the script of either movie and was just trying to help a family
member.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as governor, has had an uneasy relationship with his
party's social conservatives, especially on education issues. Some
of those issues include school textbook adoption, school-to-work
programs and a curriculum standard that social conservatives called
``faddish and experimental.''
</P>
<P>
   During this month's Republican State Convention, Bush appealed
to social conservatives with promises to support the teaching of
sexual abstinence to teen-agers and to pass a law requiring
parental notification before a minor can get an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Social conservatives next month plan to ask the State Board of
Education to sell the Permanent School Fund's $47 million share of
Disney stock.
</P>
<P>
   Offutt said such a vote would send a message to Disney
executives, even though selling the stock is unlikely to affect
Disney profits or stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they (Disney executives) have completely
abandoned the family, but we want them to know if they continue to
produce objectionable stuff, there could be negative consequences
for their corporation,'' Offutt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is sort of the corporate equivalent of Dr. Jekyll and
Mr. Hyde,'' Roberts said. ``They do some very good things, and they
do some very, very bad things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he opposes the state selling the Disney stock because
he believes investment trust managers should not be politically
motivated in making their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, the investment decisions ought to be made
on a return on investment basis,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Betts-Bush connection to the film industry began in 1983,
when Betts formed Silver Screen and made Bush a director.
</P>
<P>
   An entertainment lawyer, Betts had previously been brought in to
save a company that had financed ``Gandhi'' and ``The Killing
Fields.'' Silver Screen gave Betts the opportunity to become a film
financier himself.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1985, Betts signed a deal to finance movies for Disney
through limited partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The movies were produced under either the Walt Disney or
Touchstone labels and distributed through Buena Vista Distributing
Co., a Disney subsidiary. Disney chose the movies to produce, and
Silver Screen provided the financing.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship ended in 1990 when Disney replaced Silver
Screen with a group of Japanese investors to give Disney additional
financial clout. But Silver Screen has continued to exist to manage
its investors' residuals and ownership rights in the Disney
movies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
xxxxxxxxx END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
