</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brill's content is called into question
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brill's Content, the new monthly media-watchdog publication
founded by Steven Brill of Court TV and The American Lawyer
magazine fame, has been born into a climate increasingly critical
of journalism standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything selling itself to you as nonfiction should be true,''
Brill tells readers in the premiere issue of the magazine, which
bills itself as ``The Independent Voice of the Information Age.''
Now Brill's own fact-gathering methods and political allegiance are
in the eye of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressgate,'' a bombshell article in the 152-page issue, which
should be on most newsstands by week's end, quotes independent
counsel Kenneth Starr admitting to press leaks about the Bill
Clinton-Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers called for an investigation of Starr's
office. Starr disputed Brill in a 19-page letter about the
24,000-word article, saying it bordered on libel. Howard Kurtz of
The Washington Post reported that five other sources have disputed
information attributed to them. In the June 29 issue of The Weekly
Standard, opinion editor David Tell accuses Brill of using the
expose to ``recycle the White House party line in the guise of
press criticism'' and calls it ``fundamentally dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   The brouhaha has succeeded in putting Brill, TV's latest talking
head, ``out there,'' in press speak. The magazine is not aimed at
journalists, but at the mass market of media users. Brill's wants
to pry into the methods of the pryers, showing an initial 225,000
readers how the media products they read or watch are made.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue also features stories on television (how CNN and
other news outlets have special ``bookers'' who arrange live
interviews during breaking news), books (the power of Barnes &AMP;
Noble's chief buyer to make or break a book), newspapers (how The
New York Times investigated the growth of Columbia/HCA Healthcare
Corp.), magazines (the suit against YM magazine over photos used
with an advice column) and the Internet (a profile of David Talbot,
creator of Salon).
</P>
<P>
   Columns include ``The Ticker,'' offering media and cultural
factoids; ``Unhyped Books,'' featuring U.S. Rep. John Lewis'
memoir, ``Walking With the Wind''; and ``Credentials,'' listing the
educational degrees of medical and science reporters, including the
Atlanta Journal Constitution's Mike Toner.
</P>
<P>
   An explicit policy promises to publish corrections ``at least as
prominently as the original mistake.'' And Brill recruited Bill
Kovach, curator of the Nieman Foundation for Journalism at Harvard
University and a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-
</P>
<P>
   Constitution, as ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   Kovach writes that he is there ``to receive and investigate
specific complaints about the work of Brill's Content, and to make
a judgment about how such complaints should be handled.'' The storm
around ``Pressgate'' should give him plenty to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
