<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-LOTT-BUDGET     06-22 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-LOTT-BUDGET-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DESIGNATES MONEY FOR HELICOPTER CARRIER THE NAVY DIDN'T ASK
FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Miss., Maine, Va.)  
 (JT ) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy is not asking for a new helicopter
carrier, but Trent Lott wants it to have one.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the military budget bill that the Senate debated
Monday is $50 million to buy parts for a $1.5 billion helicopter
carrier that the Navy did not request. The money is also included
in a companion appropriations bill awaiting Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   Senators, aides and lobbyists say the idea of putting a down
payment on the new ship in the $270 billion Pentagon budget bill
came largely from Lott, the Senate majority leader. He represents
Mississippi, where the new vessel would almost certainly be built.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has seven of the helicopter carriers in service or
under construction. Five older ships of a similar design are also
in the fleet, and the Navy seemed to be leaning in its long-range
plan toward overhauling them, at a cost of $950 million each,
rather than buying a new one.
</P>
<P>
   All the ships were built at Ingalls Shipbuilding in Pascagoula,
Miss., the state's largest private employer with nearly 11,000
workers at its 800-acre shipyard on the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls a unit of Litton Industries, would almost certainly
build any new helicopter carriers, if Congress approved them. But a
contract to refurbish an older vessel could go to other shipyards
around the country. Knowing the stakes, Ingalls turned to its chief
patron on Capitol Hill, Lott, as well as to other Mississippi
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other lawmakers who lobby long and loud to champion their
cause, Lott, by dint of his lofty position, can often accomplish as
much or more through simple indirection.
</P>
<P>
   An utterance here, a suggestion there goes a long way when it
comes from the Senate majority leader. Lott's top aides, for
instance, hardly need to be told to pay attention when Ingalls
executives come calling with a favor to ask. And when those aides
talk, other senators' staff know they speak for Lott.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being Mississippi's leading employer, Ingalls has
ties to Lott's family that date to the senator's father, Chester,
working at the shipyard as a pipe fitter.
</P>
<P>
   Lott insists he never directly intervened in this case, saying
that the Senate Armed Services Committee ``saw the wisdom'' of
financing parts for the new ship on its own. ``It came out of the
blue,'' Lott said in a brief interview outside his Capitol office.
``But I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services seapower
subcommittee, said he did not confer with Lott before including the
$50 million in the bill. The message came through top aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff worked with his staff,'' said Warner, who was
secretary of the Navy when the first of the older helicopter
carriers was ordered in the early 1970s. ``It was the right idea,
so I put it in.''
</P>
<P>
   An industry official familiar with Ingalls' lobbying effort on
Capitol Hill, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said of
Lott's assistance: ``Certainly his work and the work of his staff
was very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lobbyist on Capitol Hill familiar with the issue
underscored the senator's influence: ``This is all Lott. This is
the type of thing that majority leaders do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Back home in Mississippi, Lott is not taking any public credit
for his role in inserting the money. People who know him say that's
not unusual. ``He doesn't grandstand,'' said Jim Young,
Pascagoula's city manager. ``He works behind the scenes on these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott is not always so quiet when it comes to protecting Ingalls'
interests.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, the shipyard suffered a damaging blow when it
lost out on a Navy contract to build the first three of a class of
12 new amphibious assault ships, the LPD-17, worth about $750
million each. The contract was awarded to a competing consortium
from Maine and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Upset but undaunted, Lott and Ingalls then lobbied to gain an
advantage on an existing contract to build 12 DDG-51 destroyers
from 1998 to 2001, with the ships evenly split between Ingalls and
Bath Iron Works Corp. in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Lott and Ingalls succeeded in coaxing the Navy, and
Congress, to speed up the construction of two additional
destroyers, which would not have been contracted until after 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In the fight for the new helicopter carrier, Lott and his top
aides had a formidable ally, Gen. Charles Krulak, the outspoken,
four-star commandant of the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   The marines are a part of the Department of the Navy and report
to the secretary of the Navy, but they sometimes represent views
independent from the Navy's on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the $50 million being included in the
Senate's version of the military budget bill, Krulak urged
lawmakers to invest in a new helicopter carrier rather than sink
money into upgrading one of the older vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Marine generals voice concern that future U.S. military
operations will resemble the Somalia mission in 1992, in which
troops must be flown or ferried into trouble spots from larger
ships off shore.
</P>
<P>
   Krulak said it would be more cost-effective to spend more money
now on a more capable ship that will last 40 years, than extend an
older, less capable ship's service life by 15 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Krulak repeated his arguments in a letter to Lott that same
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
