<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CONTEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potential new food products get taste test
 &HT;    By Marques G. Harper
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's midnight and you're hungry, so you head to the
kitchen for a late-night snack.
</P>
<P>
   Pretzels or chips? Boring. Left-over chicken? Too messy for this
time of night.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some S'morsels, Banana-Custard Delights or Dinodrops.
Dinodrops?
</P>
<P>
   A student contest that concluded Monday at the Georgia World
Congress Center showcased prospective new food products. Cornell
University's Wrapidos was the winning product. Twenty schools
entered, and six made it to the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Three products are designed to satisfy a sweet tooth:
</P>
<P>
   _ Banana-Custard Delights, created by the Rutgers University
team, are frozen chocolate-covered banana slices filled with
vanilla custard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dinodrops, developed by the University of British Columbia,
are chocolate-coated sour cherries imprinted with a dinosaur's
foot.
</P>
<P>
   _ And an old campfire favorite _ s'mores _ returns new and
improved. S'morels, created by Iowa State University, combine
graham crackers, marshmallows and chocolate in a roll shape.
</P>
<P>
   Another entry reflects a trend toward adding nutritional
supplements to food.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the additive is bacteria. Pro-Crunch, created by
the University of Wisconsin at Madison, is toasted cookie bits
coated with Bifidobacterium longum and Lactobacillus acidophilus.
The designers say these bacteria are good for the human
gastrointestinal system.
</P>
<P>
   The other two entries take advantage of the growing popularity
of tortillas:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wrapidos _ flour tortillas sealed on three sides with one side
open for stuffing, pita-style _ were developed by Cornell. You
might call them ``tidy tortillas.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicotillas, developed by Kansas State University, are
bite-size, rolled tortillas with raisin filling, flavored with
herbs and spices.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams have received inquiries from manufacturers and have
taken steps to get patents. But there's no guarantee that any of
the six products will make it to the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Prizes, including $1,000 to the winner from sponsor Mars, were
awarded during a meeting of the Institute of Food Technologists,
which conducted the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
