<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Slumping Graffanino gets call to lead off
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one was more surprised by the Braves' lineup
Monday night than the man atop it. Leading off ... Tony Graffanino?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not swinging like a leadoff man right now,'' said
Graffanino, who started at second base against Yankee left-hander
Andy Pettitte and led off for just the second time in his brief
big-league career. ``I'm not sure I want the five at-bats right
now. I've been hitting the ball OK but right at people. But I've
got to try to get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino began the night batting just .208. He was hitless in
seven at-bats over the weekend in Montreal, extending his hitless
streak to 0-for-13. Graffanino was 2-for-his-last 34, .059. That's
far worse than his 5-for-31 slump (.161) to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   With Walt Weiss back in Atlanta with his seriously ill and
hospitalized son, Brody, 3, Bobby Cox needed another leadoff man.
Cox said Weiss might rejoin the team Wednesday, when this series
shifts to Atlanta. Ozzie Guillen started again at shortstop, but
despite his .364 lifetime average against Pettitte, Cox chose to
bat Graffanino first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else is gonna lead off?'' Cox asked. ``He's right-handed
and he's leading off. (Guillen) hits Pettitte, but I thought I'd
just give Graf a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other time Graffanino led off was July 22 last year, in
the second game of a doubleheader in Chicago. He was 0-for-3 with
two walks and a strikeout that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel all right,'' Graffanino said. ``I'm seeing the ball
well, and I don't feel I'm having bad at-bats. But my confidence is
not where it should be. I just hope I don't owe (pitchers). I hope
I'm working on credit right now, where they owe me. All I can do is
keep swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino was rewarded immediately Monday. In his first at-bat,
he singled up the middle. But two batters later, leaning and
running with a full count to Chipper Jones, Graffanino was picked
off by Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Graffanino drilled a shot in the hole on the left
side. But Derek Jeter fielded it and threw out Eddie Perez at
third. Graffanino and Guillen then scored when Gerald Williams'
drive to deep left glanced off Tim Raines' glove for a double.
</P>
<P>
   Lining up
</P>
<P>
   With Perez catching Greg Maddux Monday, Cox used Javy Lopez as
his designated hitter. The manager also used the right-handed
lineup he has employed regularly lately. That meant Williams in
right field and Danny Bautista, not Ryan Klesko, in left. And that
left Klesko's bat, the club's hottest, on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko doubled Sunday in Montreal to extend his career-high
hitting streak to 13 games. During that stretch, he's 21-for-51
(.412) with four homers and 13 RBIs. In last year's interleague
series in Yankee Stadium, Klesko homered in each of the two games
he played.
</P>
<P>
   But Klesko never has faced Pettitte and is batting just .192
(5-for-26) against left-handers. All 12 of his homers have come
against right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Williams watch
</P>
<P>
   Williams continues to make the most of his starting chances. He
began Monday with a .528 average against left-handers, .417 with
runners in scoring position and a .474 average (9-for-19) over his
last 10 games. After striking out in the first inning, Williams
ripped Pettitte for a two-run double in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be a professional for all the situations I'm put
in,'' Williams said. ``That nothing affects my willingness and
drive when I'm called on. Going into the game, I understand I'm not
as sharp as if I'm playing day in, day out. I've got to understand
I can't try to do too much. I do what I can. Everything else is a
bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
