<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTRANA PLEDGES PEACE, BETTER TIES TO WASHINGTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
BOGOTA, Colombia _ Just one day after winning the presidency,
Andres Pastrana vowed Monday to end a civil war that has vexed nine
presidents before him and has bled Colombia for 34 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pastrana, who defeated Horacio Serpa of the ruling Liberal Party
in a run-off election Sunday, pledged to personally sit down for
talks with leaders of the nation's left-wing guerrilla groups. He
said the first meeting could come within the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we will begin to make all the contacts necessary to
meet with the (guerrilla leadership),'' Pastrana said at a news
conference. ``The top priority of this government is peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, who will be sworn in Aug. 7 to lead Colombia's first
Conservative Party government in 12 years, also promised to improve
relations with the United States, which hit bottom under outgoing
President Ernesto Samper.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Pastrana envoy met in the Andean foothills with top
leaders of Colombia's largest guerrilla organization _ the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. A FARC communique
that ridiculed Serpa's claims to be the ``peace candidate'' may
have persuaded some voters to support Pastrana in Sunday's
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door has been opened. We have to take advantage of it,''
Pastrana said. ``Four years ago, the FARC would not meet with any
member of the Samper government. But they have shown a clear
willingness to begin a peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   During Samper's term in office, the guerrillas have dealt the
army a series of humiliating defeats and have grown in terms of
troop strength as well as territorial control. Numbering between
12,000 and 15,000, the rebels are now present in about half of
Colombia's 1,071 municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Their military prowess and involvement in the drug trade has
alarmed Washington, which has increased military assistance to
Colombia in the past three years. The guerrillas finance their war
by demanding ransom for kidnapping victims and by providing
protection to drug traffickers and farmers who grow coca, the raw
material for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have refused to negotiate with Samper during his
entire term. They insist that Samper, who was elected in 1994 with
the help of $6.1 million from the Cali drug cartel, lacks
legitimacy and moral authority.
</P>
<P>
   During this year's recent presidential campaign, however, both
the FARC and the smaller National Liberation Army have appeared
willing to open talks with the incoming administration.
</P>
<P>
   To help persuade the guerrillas to disarm, Pastrana vowed to
seek state and private-sector investments in impoverished,
rebel-dominated areas in order to help fighters make the transition
to civilian life.
</P>
<P>
   He also said his government would guarantee the safety of
disarmed rebels, a sensitive issue to guerrillas. When supporters
of the FARC formed a political party in the 1980s, right-wing
paramilitary squads killed more than 1,000 of its members.
</P>
<P>
   Marcos Calarca, a FARC spokesman in Mexico City, said the rebels
are taking a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must have the political will and capacity to achieve
peace, and that can't be demonstrated through declarations alone.
This is demonstrated through deeds,'' Calarca told Bogota's NTC
television.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana also invited the United States to play a greater role
in the peace process. He vowed to improve Colombia's relations with
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Due to the Samper campaign-finance scandal, the Clinton
administration has treated Colombia as a pariah nation over much of
the past four years. The United States revoked Samper's visa and
sanctioned his administration for being uncooperative in the fight
against drugs in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana said Colombia, the world's No. 1 supplier of cocaine,
needs a ``Marshall Plan'' of international aid to pay for the
eradication of coca crops.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that Washington's agenda in Colombia should
include peace, human rights and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Washington on Monday, State Department spokesman
James Rubin offered Pastrana ``warm congratulations'' and said the
U.S. government ``looks forward to working with him and his new
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pastrana's post-election enthusiasm on the prospects for
peace, it may prove difficult for him to keep his promises.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Torres, a security consultant for oil companies in
Colombia, said it's unclear whether the rebels, who have scored
some of their biggest victories in the past three years, are
serious about disarming. He also said that Pastrana lacks a
comprehensive peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants negotiations, but no one really knows what to
say,'' Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   But others say Pastrana should seize the moment. As a member of
the upper class, Pastrana may be able to persuade Colombia's elite
to consider guerrilla demands for agrarian reform, social spending
and a reduction in the size of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Jesus Bejarano noted that lengthy civil wars
in El Salvador and Guatemala were brought to an end by conservative
presidents during their first years in office.
</P>
<P>
   John Otis, a free-lance journalist based in Bogota, wrote this
story for the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
