<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT SHARPLY LIMITS HARASSMENT SUITS AGAINST SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING for all needing to correct slug; skedded SCOTUS, to be
filed, is a different story)   (fb)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court set a highly
restrictive standard Monday for determining when school districts
can be found liable under federal law for a teacher's sexual
harassment of a student.
</P>
<P>
   A harassment victim can recover damages from the school district
only if a school official with the authority to intervene actually
knew of the teacher's misconduct and, acting with ``deliberate
indifference,'' failed to stop it, the court said in an opinion by
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor. The vote was 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in a case from a school district near Austin,
Texas, where a high school teacher seduced a ninth-grader and
engaged in a yearlong affair with her. The girl never told school
officials about the affair, which ended when a police officer
discovered the two. The teacher was dismissed and criminally
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The girl and her mother sued the Lago Vista Independent School
District for damages under a federal law, Title IX of the Education
Amendments of 1972, which prohibits sex discrimination by
educational institutions that receive federal money, a definition
that applies to all public school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Supreme Court decisions established that the law's
reference to sex discrimination covers a wide range of misconduct
involving sexual harassment, and also provided for suits for
damages by individual victims. But the court had not addressed the
standard for establishing liability.
</P>
<P>
   Over the four dissenters' vigorous protest that the court was
enacting into law a judicial ``policy judgment'' that would have
the effect of insulating school districts from nearly all such
lawsuits, the majority chose the most restrictive of several
alternative standards.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the court rejected the Department of Education's
interpretation of Title IX, under which a school district could be
found liable, regardless of whether officials knew of the
misconduct, if a teacher had misused his position of authority in
carrying out the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   That was a misunderstanding of Title IX, O'Connor said in her
majority opinion. ``It does not appear that Congress contemplated
unlimited recovery in damages against a funding recipient where the
recipient is unaware of discrimination in its programs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist joined the majority opinion
along with Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, and
Clarence Thomas. The dissenters were Justices John Paul Stevens,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg, David H. Souter, and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, O'Connor noted that Title IX ``amounts
essentially to a contract between the government and the recipient
of funds,'' under which schools agree to accept certain conditions,
such as preventing discrimination, in exchange for their federal
money.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said it did not make sense that Congress would have
expected school districts to subject themselves to open-ended
liability for misconduct of which no one in a position of authority
might even be aware.
</P>
<P>
   She said that while ``no one questions that a student suffers
extraordinary harm'' from harassment and abuse by teachers, the
court could not impose broad liability on school districts ``until
Congress speaks directly on the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   The National School Boards Association had warned the court, in
a brief filed on the Lago Vista district's behalf, that any
standard other than the ``actual knowledge'' test the court adopted
on Monday would have a ``devastating financial impact on the
nation's public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   While many school districts receive relatively small amounts of
federal money _ $126,000 a year in the case of Lago Vista _ jury
verdicts in harassment cases can exceed $1 million, the school
board association's brief said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a group of civil rights organizations _ led
by the National Women's Law Center _ here said in their brief that
because many victims of sexual harassment by teachers feel isolated
and afraid to report the situation, a liability standard that
depends on official knowledge would effectively immunize school
districts much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the plaintiff, Alida Star Gebser, testified that
she was afraid to tell anyone about her relationship with the
teacher, Frank Waldrop.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia D. Greenberger, co-president of the National Women's Law
Center, said Monday that the decision would ``make the job of
eliminating sexual harassment in schools far more difficult.''
Greenberger is currently seeking Supreme Court review in a case
that raises the separate but related question of whether schools
can be held liable for the harassment of one student by another.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The decision on Monday, Gebser vs. Lago Vista Independent School
District, No. 96-1866, upheld a ruling last year by the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in New Orleans. That court, affirming an
initial ruling by the U.S. District Court in Austin dismissing
Gebser's suit, held that the school district could be liable only
if a supervisory employee ``actually knew of the abuse, had the
power to end the abuse, and failed to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Decisions by other federal courts, including a 1997 ruling by
the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in New York, had taken a
different approach under which a district could be found liable if
a teacher had abused his authority over a student.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the court Monday went even further in
protecting school districts than the 5th Circuit opinion it
affirmed. O'Connor said that to establish liability, the school
district failure to respond must have amounted to ``deliberate
indifference to discrimination,'' which she defined as an
``official decision'' not to act on its knowledge. The 5th Circuit
had left open the question whether a district could be liable if
its failure to respond was simply negligent, rather than
deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, in a dissenting opinion that the other dissenters also
signed, said the court had given school districts an incentive not
to take steps to protect vulnerable students. ``As long as school
boards can insulate themselves from knowledge about this sort of
conduct, they can claim immunity from damages liability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters said that the court had in effect overruled a
1992 decision that made damages available to individual plaintiffs
in Title IX cases. The majority's reasoning suggested ``that no
damages should ever be awarded in a Title IX case,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate dissenting opinion, Ginsburg said that if a school
district had an effective policy in place for reporting and
redressing sexual harassment, such a policy could be an
``affirmative defense'' against a lawsuit by a plaintiff who had
not taken proper advantage of the policy. Souter and Breyer also
joined this opinion, which may have represented an abortive effort
to marshal a majority by allaying fears about unlimited liability
for school districts.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, the court is scheduled to decide two other
sexual harassment cases. Both deal with employer liability for
harassment in the workplace, which is addressed by a different
federal law, Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. For that
reason, the ruling Monday does not necessarily forecast the outcome
of the other cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
