<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1313 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-soccer-HNS &LR;      06-22 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-soccer-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Beaten like a steel drum
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jamaica's Reggae Boyz gain experience in 5-0 loss to Argentina
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ When the Argentine and Jamaican national soccer teams
lined up for the playing of their national anthems before Sunday
afternoon's World Cup meeting, the picture could not have looked
more bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Argentines, in their famed blue-and-white-striped
jerseys, the consummate professionals, heroes to a nation, winners
of three World Cup championships and representing one of the most
storied soccer histories in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Reggae Boyz.
</P>
<P>
   The guys who call the soccer ball their girlfriend _ and,
``nobody dances with my girl,'' as they are wont to say.
</P>
<P>
   The guys who wear Bob Marley T-shirts under their jerseys,
compose the youngest team in the World Cup, have thousands of
partying fans looking more for fun than for soccer victories _ good
thing _ and come from a nation that only recently picked up the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The final score proved to be Argentina 5, Jamaica 0, a romp. But
please understand: While the Argentines didn't need any help
whipping Jamaica, they got it when a Jamaican player was red-carded
in the first half, meaning Argentina played the rest of the way
with a one-man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Which is like starting a game of H-O-R-S-E against Michael
Jordan at ``S.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reggae Boyz have come a long way, regardless of the score.
And they still have big plans, regardless of the score.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to the fans at the Gare De Lyon train station, who
were kicking around a soccer ball while waiting for their next
train on this unlikely World Cup ride and listening to reggae
music.
</P>
<P>
   They were asked about Jamaica's chances in its next game, which
comes Friday against Japan and on the heels of a 3-1 loss to
Croatia and the 5-0 loss to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will win 10-0,'' said Edward Powell, a travel agent who led
a group of fans to France for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Have we mentioned that the Reggae Boyz and their throng of fans
always are confident? Have we mentioned that Jamaica already has
been eliminated from the tournament and will play its first-round
finale, appropriately, for fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an identity, and we like it,'' said midfielder Robbie
Earle. ``But this is a real soccer team. You don't make it to the
World Cup unless you earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's the name. Reggae Boyz is what they call
themselves. It is not some tag laid on these fellows by a group of
fans or someone in the media.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday's game notwithstanding, being a Reggae Boyz player is
not a bad thing at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here for experience, and we're getting it,'' Jamaica
coach Rene Simoes said. ``When you play with 10 men against a team
the caliber of Argentina, you are likely to allow a lot of goals.
We don't have the proper experience to play that game. It was not a
reflection of our best game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica's best game is free-lancing, shoot-first, worry about
offsides and defense later. It is exactly what these talented
players want to be known for _ fun in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, these guys really are talented, although the attacking
style backfired Sunday at Parc des Princes against an Argentine
team that also likes to attack and is much better at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come here to advertise tourism,'' Simoes said. ``We
came here to play.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, as much as the Reggae Boyz are soccer's version of
the Jamaican bobsled team, a novelty act of sorts that entered the
1988 Winter Olympic Games as a sideshow, by 1998 the bobsled team
had become a legitimate squad.
</P>
<P>
   So has Jamaican soccer, and it didn't take nearly as long for it
to reach a high level.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a healthy if small national amateur soccer association
and a big boost from Simoes, a proven Brazilian coach who took over
Jamaica's national team in 1994, Jamaica this year became only the
third Caribbean nation to qualify for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean nation to make it to the Cup finals was Haiti in
1974. Before that, Cuba qualified in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players are enthusiastic about soccer, and they are
talented athletes,'' Simoes said. ``This is a serious effort.
Jamaica wanted to reach the top level of the game, and today it has
nothing to be ashamed about. It is getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a team that will go home after Friday's game against
Japan. But the potential is clear.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cup qualifying process, which ended with the Reggae
Boyz tying powerful Mexico 0-0 last November to earn the third and
last qualifying berth out of its region, which also includes the
United States, Jamaica surprised many experts by earning the bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are better teams than us playing today,'' Earle
said. ``But we have come a long way in a very short time.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 when Simoes took over the Jamaican team, it was
considered a joke in international circles, losing by such scores
as 9-2 and 6-0 in the months before Simoes' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   But Simoes, a tough tactician who had coached Brazil's national
Under-20 and Under-23 teams, gathered a group of 40-plus Jamaican
players together and began training them hard.
</P>
<P>
   Some players dropped out of the tough training program,
including Walter Boyd, who was one of Jamaica's most popular
players but did not embrace the training.
</P>
<P>
   Simoes also took various Jamaican teams to Brazil over a
two-year period, training the teams with Brazilian professionals
and scheduling games against top Brazilian teams.
</P>
<P>
   The initiation into elite soccer was tough. Simoes went through
more than 50 lineups, and the record in those exhibition games was
abysmal.
</P>
<P>
   But three years later, Jamaica was putting scares into the
United States and Mexico. Then, the Reggae Boyz squeezed into the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, they stood shoulder to shoulder with Argentina, if
not eye-to-eye in terms of soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team will be back,'' Simoes said.
</P>
<P>
   Their fans, no doubt, will come along too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-COX     06-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mysterious 'cluster' of dangerous E. coli strikes Atlanta
children
 &HT;    (Eds: Can run with STINSON-ECOLI and FOOD-SAFETY.)
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ State health officials are investigating a ``cluster''
of E. coli infections that have stricken six Atlanta children,
including the son of Atlanta Braves shortstop Walt Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the children, girls ages 2 and 4, were in critical
condition on Monday at Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center,
diagnosed with a highly infectious and sometimes lethal strain of
the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' 3-year-old son, Brody, was in serious condition at
Scottish Rite. All three children are suffering from kidney failure
and are being treated with dialysis, respirators and blood
transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth child, a 3-year-old boy, was in stable condition at
Egleston Children's Hospital near Emory University. Two others,
ages 12 and 8, have been treated and released at area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   At least five of the six are from the north metro area. Although
authorities have declined to identify any of the youngsters, Weiss
confirmed his child was among them.
</P>
<P>
   So far, officials have not found a common denominator among the
six cases for E. coli O157:H7. And they warned that it may be a
week before results from sophisticated DNA tests determine whether
the illnesses have a common point of origin.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the children began showing symptoms more than a
week ago, on June 14. ``It's above and beyond what you'd expect to
see in this short of time,'' said Dr. Larry Slutsker, an
epidemiologist with the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. The federal agency has not been asked by the state to
join the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The six children live in Cobb, Cherokee, Bartow and Fulton
counties in the metro Atlanta area. Local jurisdictions have handed
the investigation over to the state Department of Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials are searching for clues in food, fruit juices
and a popular metro Atlanta water park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very preliminary right now,'' said Dr. Jim Buehler,
epidemiologist with the state Division of Public Health. ``We're
talking to families about what they've done, where they've been and
trying to interview the children who are sick about what they've
eaten and who they've been in contact with.''
</P>
<P>
   E. coli is a bacteria that lives in the digestive tracts of
cattle and other animals. It is found most often in ground beef.
The ``0157:H7'' strain of the bacteria was discovered in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, only 15 cases were reported in Georgia. In 1996, the
last year for which data exist, 39 cases were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The worst known outbreak of E. coli infection was the 1993 Jack
in the Box case in the Seattle area, in which contaminated
hamburgers from the West Coast chain sickened hundreds and killed
four people.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say E. coli cases are not uncommon during the
summer, a season for hot weather, outdoor cooking, picnics and
swimming in potentially contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
   But six cases at once is unusual, state officials admit. ``We're
calling this a cluster because of the short time period,'' said
spokeswoman Joyce Goldberg. ``We are not calling it an outbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   That would imply that a single source of the disease has been
found, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, health workers tested the water and inspected
the food services at White Water park in Marietta, Ga., which
officials said some of the families had visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a clean bill of health in three separate tests,'' said
Deedie Dowdle, marketing director for the park.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors checked the water and the park's restaurants, she
said, adding ``they gave our restaurant a 97 out of 100.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cobb County health department spokeswoman Hamilton said it
is too early to draw conclusions. ``We are looking at all
possibilities right now,'' Hamilton said, ``and we've got a number
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of those still hospitalized, according to the state Board
of Health, are suffering from hemolytic uremic syndrome _ a
shutdown of the kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   There is no specific treatment for E. coli, other than to treat
the symptoms. The mortality rate from HUS is is 3 to 5 percent .
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the cluster of six children, Egleston Children's
Hospital in Atlanta is treating two sisters, ages 2 and 6, who were
admitted for E. coli infection on June 6 and are in stable
condition. They are not considered part of the cluster.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County epidemiologist Bob Finton said the six cases at
once in a single area is unusual, ``but it may be hard to link
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In this country, E. coli cases arise most commonly from
insufficiently-cooked or contaminated food, unpasteurized milk or
juices, or inadequate handwashing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Waterborne contamination from E. coli is most common in
third-world countries. The bacteria can't spread in chlorinated
water.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said his son appeared to be recovering when he suddenly
took a turn for the worse while the Braves were opening their road
trip in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started getting severe diarrhea a week from yesterday,''
Weiss said Monday. ``We ended up taking him to ER three times. We
just thought he had a bug but blood started showing up in his bowel
movements and by Thursday (June 18), he was just passing pure blood
from his bowels.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Torpy and Thomas Stinson are staff writers for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
