<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHUMER-FUNDS-ART-     06-22 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-FUNDS-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER LEAVES FELLOW DEMOCRATS BEHIND AND RIVALS D'AMATO IN
RAISING MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: Photo of Charles Schumer is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic tracking his campaign donations is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During his nearly two decades in Washington, Rep.
Charles Schumer has become one of the most unblushingly tenacious
fund-raisers in politics. He has built a roster of wealthy Wall
Streeters, courted and cajoled the faithful in Brooklyn, N.Y., and
beyond, and spent hours on the phone seeking donors with a
well-buffed sales pitch. Now his investment is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   In his race for the Senate, Schumer has raised more from
contributors than has any other challenger in the history of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He has collected well over $10 million, accumulating a treasury
that not only dwarfs those of the other candidates in New York's
Democratic primary, Geraldine Ferraro and Mark Green, but also is
the second largest among all Senate candidates nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The only candidate who has taken in more is the man Schumer
wants to challenge, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a virtuoso fund-raiser
who has collected more than $17 million for what is likely to be
one of the most expensive Senate contests ever.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for all their political disagreements, the two men
share a dogged style of fund raising and some of the same big
donors, particularly Wall Street executives. It is a similarity
that Schumer's primary opponents have tried to use against him.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has prospered even though he is less well-known, has
never before run a statewide race and occupies the kind of middling
position in Congress that has traditionally not commanded much
respect from moneyed interests. He has compensated by being
persistent and by relying on a network of supporters that he has
nurtured in his nearly two decades in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Since April alone, he has held about 20 fund-raisers, while
continuing his regular barrage of cold calls to potential
contributors, a regimen that many politicians would bemoan but he
doesn't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very clear about what he is asking you to do and why he
is asking you to do it,'' said Robert E. Denham, whose steadfast
support for Schumer _ he and his wife, Carolyn, have given a total
of $7,000 since 1995 _ grew out of an unsolicited call from Schumer
a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Denham was the chairman of Salomon Inc. when the first call
came. He didn't know Schumer at the time but he agreed to meet him
for breakfast, and by the time they had finished, Schumer had not
only netted himself a wealthy supporter but also won a willing
guide to other deep pockets on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``You fund-raise by convincing people to believe in you and to
believe that you are going to make a difference,'' said Denham, who
stepped down as chairman of Salomon Inc. last year. ``He
communicates that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although campaign finance controversies roil Washington and
Schumer says he favors reducing the role of donations in campaigns,
the congressman is not shy about his bankroll, saying he must
stockpile money if he is to oust a well-financed incumbent like
D'Amato. He often asserts that nominating Ms. Ferraro or Green
would be disastrous for Democrats because neither would have the
money to compete with D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd call that a formula to lose,'' Schumer said in a telephone
interview last week from Texas, where he was on a fund-raising
trip. ``I believe that the day after the primary, D'Amato will do
what he has done in the past, which is unload, sort of launch a
blitzkrieg of ads, and I think that you have to be able to defend
yourself. And to point out D'Amato's foibles.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone appreciates Schumer's approach. He sometimes is not
deterred when people say they are supporting another candidate
after he asks them for a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, some of those people said Schumer's response was
not gracious. ``He began sort of challenging me,'' said one Ferraro
supporter, who spoke on condition that he not be identified.
``There was no threat or anything like that, but I thought it was a
little unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For all his money, Schumer has yet to shake up the Democratic
primary. In polls, he still trails Ms. Ferraro, who has raised far
less but may need to spend less because she has the more recognized
name.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other nonincumbents in the history of Congress have
rivaled Schumer in the financing of their campaigns, both of them
Senate candidates in California: Michael Huffington, who lost the
general election in 1994, and Darrell Issa, who lost the primary
this month. Huffington spent more than $28 million and Issa spent
$10 million, but most of their money came from personal funds, not
from contributors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1316 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHUMER-FUNDS-ART-     06-22 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-FUNDS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: from contributors.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As of March 31 of this year, Schumer had $8.2 million in the
bank after expenditures, Ms. Ferraro had $1.1 million and Green had
$800,000, according to disclosure records. D'Amato had $10.6
million after expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer attributed his fund-raising success to his record on
issues like gun control, abortion rights and Israel. He noted that
when he first met Denham, they strongly disagreed on free trade, a
demonstration, he said, that he was not pandering to Wall Street
executives to get their support. He pointed out that contributions
to his campaign since November 1996 have averaged only about $110.
He said he liked his fund-raisers to be small gatherings of 20 or
30 people, not the banquet-style events that many politicians
sponsor, because he enjoyed talking to everyone who showed up.
Schumer's aides would not allow a reporter to attend one of his
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who give to me, clearly not all, regard it
as a charitable act,'' Schumer said, ``as something they should do
for the good of their country.''
</P>
<P>
   His partisans are eager to rebut the idea that his candidacy
revolves around a hunt for money. They say his fund-raising success
stems from more than just his toiling on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   While Schumer's treasury will ensure that he can buy an arsenal
of television commercials, it may hinder him in attacking D'Amato's
fund-raising and ethics, should he win the nomination. D'Amato, the
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, has raised millions of
dollars for his Senate campaign and for the New York Republican
State Committee from donors with interests that bring the donors
before his panel.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has a far less important position as a senior member of
the Democratic minority on the House Banking Committee. Still, just
as D'Amato has backed proposals being pushed by some of his biggest
contributors, so too has Schumer, especially on issues involving
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the longstanding battle over legislation that would loosen
rules for mergers between banks, securities firms and insurance
companies, Schumer has usually sided with securities firms. Last
year, he was a sponsor of an amendment to the legislation that
would insure that a certain type of thrift institution that is
owned by several securities firms would not be subject to rigorous
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's donors include many prominent Wall Street executives.
Since 1993, Schumer has collected more than $1.4 million from
donors who also gave to D'Amato, including many Wall Street
executives, lawyers and real estate developers, according to
analysis of disclosure records.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 18 executives at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. contributed to
both candidates, giving a total of $19,250 to Schumer and $16,250
to D'Amato. But now, Schumer may find it harder to raise money from
strongholds like Wall Street because some donors are increasingly
worried about offending D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendously difficult situation,'' said a lobbyist
on securities issues, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified. The lobbyist has contributed to both candidates but is
now shunning Schumer. ``Chuck has been there on every single issue
for the securities industry,'' he said. ``But you have to go with
D'Amato. You don't have any choice about that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One key to Schumer's success has been his ability to stash away
contributions from his House campaigns. In 1996, he raised roughly
$3 million in his successful race against an unknown Republican who
collected less than $40,000. Schumer then transferred most of that
money to his Senate account.
</P>
<P>
   The transferred House money is not counted against the
contribution limits for this race, which are $2,000 for individuals
and $10,000 for political action committees. The move has
essentially allowed Schumer to raise far more than $2,000 from some
individuals for his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, since 1993, D'Amato has been able to raise a
maximum of $2,000 from each individual donor because as a Senator,
the limit applied for his entire six-year term. But until recently,
Schumer was raising funds as a House member, whose terms are two
years. So every two years, a new $2,000 limit applied, and many
donors gave $2,000 to Schumer in 1995-1996 and then another $2,000
in 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
   This maneuver is legal, but Green, New York City's Public
Advocate, has contended that it violates the spirit of the campaign
laws. Green has also questioned how Schumer can back legislation _
including the campaign finance overhaul now under consideration in
the House _ intended to reduce the role of money in campaigns even
as he is so busy passing the hat. The criticism is part of an
effort by Green to portray Schumer's fund-raising as no different
than D'Amato's.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer brushed aside Green's charges. ``Mark Green is working
every bit as hard as I am to raise money from the same people I
am,'' Schumer said. ``I will make campaign finance reform one of my
major issues in the Senate. I have always believed in it strongly.
Until the system changes, you can't unilaterally disarm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
