</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW FALLS, NASDAQ CLIMBS AS INVESTORS STILL SEE VALUE
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which was up by about 50
points during the day, fell 1.74 points, or 0.2 percent, to
8,711.13. The technology-heavy Nasdaq jumped 24.52 points, or 1.4
percent, to 1,805.82, with shares of Intel, Microsoft, Dell
Computer, and Cisco Systems climbing.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow had been up as much as 50 points, before retreating
sharply in the last half-hour of trading. Analysts largely
attributed the late turnaround to a computer-generated sell
program.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury rose. Its yield was unchanged
at 5.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GM STRIKE COULD LAST UNTIL AUGUST With few signs of progress
being made toward settling strikes against General Motors, the
United Automobile Workers union has raised the prospect that the
walkout could last into mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   PAINKILLER PULLED FROM MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has halted sales of the drug
Duract, a painkiller manufactured by the Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories
unit of the American Home Products Corporation, because the drug
has caused a dozen cases of serious liver failure in patients who
took it for longer than the recommended 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   A SOFTWARE MAKER IS ACQUIRED
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co.agreed to acquire Broderbund, maker of the Myst
and Carmen Sandiego software series, in a $420 million stock swap,
the largest in a wave of deals consolidating the educational and
consumer software market. Shares in Broderbund rose nearly 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUSA TO BUY RIVAL FROM TANDY
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA agreed to purchase Computer City from Tandy in a
$275-million deal that will combine the nation's two biggest
retailers of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   DROP IN OIL PRICES FORCES CUTBACKS
</P>
<P>
   The recent drop in oil prices has prompted several oil-producing
countries to borrow money and reduce social spending to make up for
lost income from oil exports.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries will meet in Vienna on Wednesday to talk about oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   GM EXPANDS CHINA INVESTMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Despite Asia's economic problems, General Motors said it would
invest $100 million in a joint venture with a Chinese company to
make pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles in China's northeast
city of Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL LYNCH BUYING CANADIAN FIRM
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has agreed to buy Canada's last major independent
brokerage firm, Midland Walwyn, for $855 million.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA WANTS TO TALK ABOUT TRADE
</P>
<P>
   Shi Guangsheng, China's minister for foreign trade and economic
cooperation, said that China hopes to make progress toward joining
the World Trade Organization during this week's visit to that
country by President Clinton. The organization sets global trade
rules, and its 132 member nations must meet requirements for
reducing barriers to trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE CLEARS WORLDCOM-MCI DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The European Union approved Worldcom's proposed $43.7-billion
purchase of MCI, and American regulators are expected to give their
approval soon. MCI agreed to sell its Internet business as a
condition for European approval, and analysts said Britain's Cable
and Wireless was the likely buyer.
</P>
<P>
   POLYGRAM EXECUTIVE LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   Polygram announced the resignation of its president and chief
executive, Alain Levy. His departure marks the first major
executive shift at the pop music powerhouse since its agreement to
be purchased by Seagram was announced last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
