<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-U.S.-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING U.S. AIDE PLEDGES HELP FOR JAKARTA'S ECONOMIC REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The United States pledged on Monday to
support Indonesia's economic reform efforts and said it was
prepared to provide economic and technological assistance to help
rescue the country's stalled economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The restoration of economic stability is an absolute top
priority,'' Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said after a
90-minute meeting with the Indonesian president, B.J. Habibie. He
did not elaborate on the amount or form of the economic and
technological assistance he mentioned on his one-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said he was ``encouraged'' by the reforms undertaken by
Habibie since he became head of state on May 21, after President
Suharto resigned under public pressure after 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We explained that what is most important is the action that
Indonesia takes,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie has promised to follow through with the measures
prescribed by the International Monetary Fund for its bailout
package.
</P>
<P>
   Summers' visit, his second this year, comes as the IMF is
reportedly nearing the end of its latest round of negotiations with
top government officials to resume aid payments from the rescue
package, which were halted after riots that left nearly 1,200
people dead in May. A second installment of $1 billion is expected
to be released in early July.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who was responsible for the delay in aid from the
IMF, to which the United States is a major contributor, Summers
said, ``The IMF makes its own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's top economic official, Ginandjar Kartasasmita, has
acknowledged that the country's efforts to slow inflation,
stabilize food supplies and curb rising unemployment would fail
without foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stabilizing the economy is our responsibility, but we are
aware that without international help, our stabilization program
will not succeed,'' Ginandjar, coordinating minister for economics
and finance, told reporters after meeting with Summers later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia saw its economy shrink more than 6 percent in the
first quarter of this year, and the country's worst recession in
three decades has left almost one-sixth of the country's work force
of 90 million people unemployed. Annual inflation was officially
recorded at 52 percent in March, with some private analysts
predicting triple-digit inflation by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank said in a statement on Monday that it would
allocate funds to help the hungry and the sick and contribute to a
national education campaign to help keep children in school.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Threats of further social unrest have led the government to
place heavily armed troops around shopping malls, hotels and other
strategic locations in the capital, where more than 4,000 shops and
buildings were looted or destroyed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations, mostly peaceful, continue in the capital. More
than 500 Muslim students demonstrated outside Parliament on Monday
to demand a reduction in basic commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   The country's powerful military has said it will uphold the
spirit of reform that has swept through campuses and resulted in
the removal of many restrictions on the press and labor unions, but
has warned that it will not tolerate any ``unconstitutional acts.''
Military officials did not elaborate.
</P>
</TEXT>
