<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-FLA-600&AMP;     06-22 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-FLA-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDICT AGAINST TOBACCO COMPANY IS VOIDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Florida appeals court on Monday struck down a $750,000 jury
verdict against the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., ruling that
the lawsuit, one of the few a cigarette maker has ever lost to a
smoker, was filed six days too late.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 verdict was only one of two verdicts outstanding
against cigarette makers. Earlier this month, a Florida jury
ordered Brown &AMP; Williamson to pay $1 million, including $500,000 in
punitive damages, to the family of a deceased smoker.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, a three-judge panel of the state Court of Appeals
for the 1st Circuit found that the statute of limitations in the
1996 case had expired because the smoker, Grady Carter, had waited
too long to file his lawsuit in 1995, after discovering he had lung
disease in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Carter expressed disappointment over the ruling but said he was
not surprised. ``It is hard to beat the tobacco companies,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on tobacco litigation said that while they had not
reviewed the decision, it appeared largely limited to the specifics
of Carter's case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mary Aronson, the president of Aronson Washington
Research, which advises institutional investors on legal trends,
said the ruling was an emotional setback for plantiffs' lawyers in
smoking cases, after the optimism following last week's $1 million
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this throws a damp rag on the euphoria some
plaintiffs' lawyers were feeling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rabin, a law professor at Stanford University said that
Monday's decision demonstrated that while the public perceives that
tobacco cases are decided on issues like possible corporate
misrepresentation they often are won by tobacco companies that hire
top defense lawyers who exploit legal issues like statutes of
limitations on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin said that Carter's lawyer could appeal the decision to the
Florida Supreme Court, but, failing that, his case was dead.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, officials of Brown &AMP; Williamson, based in
Louisville, Ky., said they were pleased with court's ruling. ``We
are gratified that the court of appeals has applied the law in this
case,'' said Tom Bezanson, company lawyer who argued its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood Wilner, a lawyer in Tallahassee, who handled Carter's
claim, did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wilner also represented the family of Roland Maddox, who won the
lawsuit earlier this month against Brown &AMP; Williamson, and has
filed about 200 lawsuits on behalf of individual smokers against
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The jury verdict in the lawsuit brought by Maddox's family
marked the first time that a jury had award punitive damages in a
tobacco case. Brown &AMP; Williamson has said that it will appeal the
award and that Monday's ruling could aid them.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Carter, who had smoked Lucky Strikes and other
cigarettes for 44 years, said he became concerned about his health
when he began coughing and spitting up blood in late January 1991.
He consulted his doctor, who took X-rays on Feb. 4, 1991, and told
Carter that he had a spot on his lung that indicated several
diseases, including cancer. The next day, Carter saw a chest
specialist who performed a number of tests. On Feb. 14, Carter was
told he had lung cancer and underwent surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Williamson, a subsidiary of BAT Industries, asserted
that the statue of limitations in Carter's case began on Feb. 5,
when he was told that he had a disease that might be the result of
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court agreed and held that because Carter had waited
until Feb. 10, 1995, to file his claim Florida's four-year statute
of limitations had expired.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The panel also held that the trial judge had erred by allowing
an expert witness to testify that Brown &AMP; Williamson could have
inserted additional warnings about the risks of smoking inside
cigarette packages. But courts have typically found that a 1969
Federal law requiring a warning on the outside of cigarette
packages pre-empted any state statutes requiring more health
information.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also held that the trial judge should not have allowed
Wilner, the lawyer for Carter, to use a 1963 internal Brown &AMP;
Williamson memo that reflected communications between two company
lawyers, a category of documents normally protected from disclosure
by attorney-client privilege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
