<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CHAMPIONS FIND REASSURANCE AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Champions are nothing if not greedy. Just
ask Monica Seles, who has won nine Grand Slam events, but will not
retire a happy woman unless she manages to win Wimbledon once.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, and several other players lately fallen on troubled times
_ four-time and defending Wimbledon champion Pete Sampras,
seven-time champion Steffi Graf and Andre Agassi, who won his first
Slam title here in 1992 _ all ventured to this venerable tournament
like pilgrims to Lourdes, seeking restoration, reaffirmation,
regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   And all found at least a short-term cure Monday in the form of
straight-set victories that left them feeling a little more secure
about their long-term recoveries from what ails them.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, who has said that she is ``out to win the most Grand
Slams that I can,'' barged her way into this one with a 6-3, 6-4
subjugation of Maria Sanchez Lorenzo on an unsettled but rainless
opening day. And Graf actually burst into tears after coolly
blasting Gala Leon Garcia off Center Court, 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Graf said a performance like Monday's, in a place that moves her
like no other, gave her cause to hope that, at 29, she could still
make a difference in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is a long way away, but it is my favorite tournament,
and I do feel it is my place, and experience does help,'' she said.
``A year ago I was basically lying in bed not able to do anything.
I don't take anything for granted anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi and Sampras shared Graf's brand of humility _ the kind
that comes with maturity born of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can just get into the tournament, I'll start playing my
best tennis,'' vowed the 13th-seeded Agassi. ``I need to take it up
to a new level.'' He got to the second level of the seven-round
event by trouncing 83rd-ranked Alex Calatrava of Spain, 6-2, 6-4,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who fired 17 aces at Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia in his
methodical 6-3, 6-3, 6-3 victory, said: ``I don't know if it's
mental or what it is, but over the years, this place has just
brought out the best in me. Wimbledon is kind of a new start.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And they can all use one.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has not won a major title since collecting his 10th
career Grand Slam championship here a year ago, and he cannot help
overhearing the whispers about his missing motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Graf sat out last year's tournament because of knee surgery, and
seven weeks ago she was considering quitting because she was fed up
with her nagging leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi had not won a Wimbledon match since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Seles emerged from two years of emotional limbo just last month
in Paris, where she put on the emotional blinders and reached the
French Open final just two weeks after losing her father, Karolj,
to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While those favorites advanced, the seventh-seeded Russian
Yevgeny Kafelnikov, whose title on grass at Halle, Germany, two
weeks ago seemed to bode well for a credible campaign here, tumbled
back into what he termed his ``crisis'' mode. Kafelnikov committed
22 double faults and tumbled out of contention with a 6-7 (5-7),
7-6 (7-1), 6-4, 6-2 loss to Mark Philippoussis and his 21 aces.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pierce, who has yet to develop a fondness for Wimbledon or
its slippery lawns, became the first seeded player to depart. The
11th-seeded Pierce performed with increasing indifference once she
dropped the first set's tie breaker to 87th-ranked Elena Tatarkova
of the Ukraine, and the ensuing 7-6 (7-4), 6-3 defeat marked her
earliest Wimbledon exit.
</P>
<P>
   But Pierce was not the most celebrated player to vanish from the
women's side of the draw: that distinction went to 12th-seeded Anna
Kournikova, the 17-year-old Russian, whose tanned midriff was
featured on the front pages of several London newspapers Monday
morning but whose sore right thumb prompted her reluctant
withdrawal from her favorite Grand Slam event. It was here on
Center Court last year that she made the run to the semifinals that
proved she was a player, and not just a poser. ``I was for a whole
year thinking about coming back here again,'' she said. ``It's a
tough decision to make, to withdraw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
