<P>
   (NYT16) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- June 22, 1998 -- COSBY-TRIAL,
6-22 -- A local FOX television reporter waits to tape his report as
a gardener cuts the grass outside the Santa Monica courthouse,
where the opening statements for the Ennis Cosby murder trial began
Monday morning. Cameras are barred from the courtroom. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- June 22, 1998 -- NY-SCHUMER-FUNDS, 6-22 --
In planning a run against Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, Rep. Charles
Schumer has raised more from contributors than has any other
challenger in the history of Congress, collecting well over $10
million. ``I believe that the day after the primary, D'Amato will
do what he has done in the past, which is unload, sort of launch a
blitzkrieg of ads, and I think that you have to be able to defend
yourself,'' says Schumer. ``And to point out D'Amato's foibles.''
(Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) EL PASO, Texas -- June 22, 1998 -- TEXAS-BORDER-TOWNS,
6-22 -- At night, downtown El Paso, where 70 businesses closed in
1994, is deserted. The Department of Labor says 10,000 workers in
the Texas border city lost jobs because of the North American Free
Trade Agreement. (Bruce Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KHIRBET KILKES, West Bank -- June 22, 1998 --
JERUSALEM-HOUSING, 6-22 -- On a sunbaked hill outside Hebron, a
Palestinian family lives in a tent beside the rubble of its house,
which has been demolished for the third time, after Israeli
authorities denied the family a building permit. Zuhur and Youssef
al-Atrash and their 10 children live without running water or a
toilet and drink water from a tanker truck. ``This is what
Netanyahu has left us,'' Mrs. Atrash says. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOUAFLE, Ivory Coast -- June 22, 1998 --
IVORYCOAST-LABOR, 6-22 -- A youth from Mali stands in the village
near Bouafle, where he has been forced to work as a slave on a corn
plantation since he was tricked into going there by promises of
work, housing and pay. His story is emblematic of thousands of
coerced migrant laborers, many of them children, in this
overwhelmingly agricultural country. (Robert Grossman/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1998 -- RESORT-FASHION-3, 6-22 --
Cashmere sweater and organdy apron skirt, right, and laser cut
jacket and capri pants both by Donna Karan. ``Everything is cotton,
cashmere or charmeuse,'' says Ms. Karan. ``It's all about how
clothes feel.'' (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1998 -- RESORT-FASHION-2, 6-22 --
At right, Ralph Lauren's featherweight cashmere T-shirt and organza
skirt. At left from Isaac Mizrahi is this gray easy jacket and
beige wrap pants. Right now, designers are showing retailers the
resort lines that customers will find at the end of this year. So,
the best time to find summer wares is in October, November and
December, when resort clothes are in the stores. (Lauren:James
Estrin/New York Times Photo; Mizrahi G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
