<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1340 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-22 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING FISHY ABOUT TOP FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's even worse than we had imagined. Like most serious
aficionados of cinematic art, I was shocked and appalled that the
American Film Institute's list of the Top 100 films did not include
that sweeping saga of love, war and a man who turns into a fish,
``The Incredible Mr. Limpet.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture stars Don Knotts, the slightest heavyweight ever to
grace the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   Our family saw it at the Green Garden Drive-In, an expansive
``V'' carved into the low woods of western Pennsylvania and shared
most summer evenings by unequal numbers of moviegoers and
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   I was 9 when ``Limpet'' came out. Like most boys my age, I
pictured myself as Kirk Douglas in ``Spartacus.'' Until I looked in
a mirror, and saw Don Knotts.
</P>
<P>
   Limpet was a dreamer.
</P>
<P>
   By determination alone he was able to transform himself into
something bigger, better and more glorious than anyone expected.
The movie's enlightened themes, its unrestrained enthusiasm, its
sense of hope and grandeur set my young mind soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Either that, or it was the entire can of insect repellent I'd
sprayed on myself at the drive-in.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I never forgot the film.
</P>
<P>
   I figured if Don Knotts could be metamorphosed into a big
cartoon carp, then I could become something just as good.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday I will. &QL; 
A gross injustice &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I can point out the gross injustice done to
``Limpet'' by the American Film Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the movie not included in the Top 100, it wasn't
included in the Top 400 from which the best were chosen.
</P>
<P>
   And neither were any of the Tarzan movies, among them ``Tarzan
and his Mate,'' which in its fully restored video version has a
fully naked Jane stand-in swimming in a
fish-tank-supposed-to-be-a-lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Tarzan's New York Adventure,'' in which Cheetah rides on
top of a cab while Tarzan dives off the Brooklyn Bridge, then gets
a herd of circus elephants to rescue Boy by saying ``Timba, timba,
magoolie, umgawa!'' over and over.
</P>
<P>
   (Tarzan began using this phrase as a child, while living with
apes. By repeating the words he found he could get the apes _ or
any other creature _ to do whatever he wanted, provided he promised
to stop saying it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 1,500 leaders from the American film community''
picked the films, according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
   I find this difficult to believe. If that were so, the
``leaders'' would have ditched ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance
Kid'' (No. 50) and replaced it with the greatest buddy film of all
time _ ``The Man Who Would Be King.''
</P>
<P>
   They would have moved No. 85, ``Duck Soup,'' way up, and
included ``A Day at the Circus,'' in which Groucho sings ``Lydia,
the Tattooed Lady'':
</P>
<P>
   ``When her muscles start relaxin'/ Up the hill comes Andrew
Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Freshman'' belongs on the list as the only American film
to feature an enormous Marlon Brando ice skating to Tony Bennett.
``The Black Stallion'' should be included for having the best end
credits of all time. ``Captain Blood'' _ Errol Flynn, Basil
Rathbone. Enough said. And something, anything, with Liv Ullmann. &QL; 
LIST IS PERSONAL
</P>
<P>
   We see movies in crowded theaters but it's an individual
experience.
</P>
<P>
   When we see them, and where, and with whom, determine _ as much
as what's on the screen _ if a film makes our personal Top 100
list.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, I believe the selections of the 1,500 film community
experts need to be re-evaluated. I recognize that, to the American
film industry, I'm more a fish out of water than a Limpet. But I
believe in this instance the thoughtful suggestions of a
knowledgeable man can and will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to put it another way:
</P>
<P>
   Timba, timba, magoolie, umgawa! Timba, timba, magoolie, umgawa!
Timba, timba, magoolie . . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
