<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Free-Speech Victory in Internet Case   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Online free-speech advocates scored a major legal victory yesterday
when the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that Internet service providers
are not liable for defamatory material that appears on their
systems.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without comment, the nation's high court let stand a federal
appeals court decision which determined that the Telecommunications
Act of 1996 shields providers against legal attack for libelous or
obscene material they distribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision encourages full and robust speech on the
Internet,'' a relieved AOL general counsel George Vradenburg told
The Chronicle. ``If the phone company were responsible for
filtering the content of every call that contained comments that
were libelous, pornographic or hate-filled, voice traffic would
grind to a halt. And so would correspondence on the Internet _ if
we had lost this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The court justices denied an appeal by Kenneth Zeran, a Seattle
artist and filmmaker, who sued AOL in 1996 for defamation after
being the victim of a wide-scale cyberhoax.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after the bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City in 1995, an unknown user posted a message on an AOL
message board that advertised ``Naughty Oklahoma T-Shirts.''
Prospective customers were instructed to call ``Ken'' at Zeran's
home phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several days, similar messages were posted on AOL
message boards, prompting a tidal wave of abusive phone calls and
eventually the wrath of an Oklahoma City radio station announcer,
who encouraged listeners to call Zeran's home.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail was exposed as a ruse a few weeks later. The
perpetrator is still unknown. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Zeran sued AOL in 1996, insisting the company had a duty to
remove the defamatory posting immediately, tell its members that
the message was untrue and screen future defamatory material. He
said AOL removed the fake ad, but refused to post a retraction as a
matter of company policy.
</P>
<P>
   After a federal judge in Virginia and then a federal appeals
court ruled in favor of AOL, Zeran appealed to the U.S. Supreme
Court. He said his case presented the court ``with the first
opportunity to interpret the limits of immunity granted online
service providers'' by the 2-year-old Telecom Act.
</P>
<P>
   Internet service providers have keenly followed the Zeran case
as a signpost of their responsibility for material posted on their
services.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been a spate of libel cases ensnaring
Internet companies as third parties, &UR;  &LR; this is the first to involve
the country's high court.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge Incident
</P>
<P>
   In April, U.S. District Judge Paul L. Friedman dismissed AOL as
a defendant in a White House adviser's $30 million defamation suit.
Sidney Blumenthal and his wife, Jacqueline, sued AOL and
self-styled ``Internet informer'' Matt Drudge over an inaccurate
online report in August that said Blumenthal had a ``spousal abuse
past.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL pays Drudge, who unearthed the Monica Lewisky scandal,
$3,000 a month to distribute his column.
</P>
<P>
   However, Friedman ruled that Drudge himself is still potentially
liable and must defend the lawsuit in Washington, D.C., rather than
in California where he is based. Blumenthal sued the columnist even
though Drudge retracted the story and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's Supreme Court ruling, however, erases any doubts
about an Internet service provider's culpability and treats them
more like phone companies than the Fourth Estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is better off if we don't treat ISPs as publishers.
They are common carriers,'' said Tom Leonard, a University of
California at Berkeley journalism professor. ``Once you try to
regulate content online, you're heading down a dangerous road.''
</P>
<P>
   Providers are ``thrilled with the ruling,'' said Deb Howard,
president of ISP Consortium, a Minneapolis organization that
represents 220 small- to mid-sized providers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that ISPs should not be held responsible
for their customers' posting,'' Howard said. ``Don't shoot the
medium, go after the person with the message. We can't be the
thought police and we certainly aren't the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Russo, a computer law attorney in Palo Alto, said the
decision ``gives the Internet freer rein in what people can say
than the traditional media. It doesn't put any control on what
people say online.
</P>
<P>
   ``ISPs are passive carriers,'' Russo said. ``It is very hard for
them to police their environments.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you're AOL.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, a Mammoth Operation
</P>
<P>
   The world's most popular online service has little control over
what its 12 million subscribers say online: It processes 30 million
pieces of e-mail a day and oversees 19,000 chat rooms. AOL's
Instant Messenger Service, which lets Web users chat and send
instant messages to one another, &UR;  &LR; is available to more than 80
million Web users.
</P>
<P>
   AOL monitors language on its chat rooms under a terms of service
agreement that prohibits vulgarity, obscenity and threatening
messages from its users. The policy, like Netcom's and others, is
intended to maintain a community standard. Violators of the
so-called TOS face expulsion from the online service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to set a standard somewhere between a phone company
and the press: We're not AT&AMP;T and we're not ABC,'' AOL's Vradenburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Netcom spokeswoman said the San Jose ISP does not believe in
monitoring its customers' online conversations, but it will not
hesitate to eject subscribers who frequently use offensive language
under its terms of service agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't sacrifice the rights of the many for the stupidity of
the few,'' said ISP Consortium's Howard.
</P>
<P>
   She empathizes with Zeran, she said, but believes he chose the
wrong party to sue. ``Hash out your problems with the other person
and, if you have to, contact the local authorities. To implicate
the carrier is not the point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
