<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-624&AMP;ADD     06-22 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-624&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY'S LAWYERS TO TURN OVER RECORDS OF BOOK PURCHASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: in 4th graf, name ``Kramerbooks &AMP; afterwords'' is cq with a
lower case word.) 
 (fb) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Monica Lewinsky have reached an
agreement with prosecutors to provide records from a bookstore of
several of Lewinsky's purchases, lawyers and a co-owner of the
bookstore said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was a small step in the larger and more significant
negotiations between Lewinsky's lawyers and the prosecutors over
whether the former White House intern should be granted immunity
from prosecution in exchange for her cooperation in the
investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides remain far apart in those discussions, although
lawyers in both camps said Monday that the talks were still in the
preliminary stages.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the bookstore deal, the bookstore _ Kramerbooks &AMP;
afterwords _ agreed to turn over to Lewinsky records of her book
purchases, and she will then turn them over to the independent
counsel. Prosecutors have long been interested in those purchases
because Lewinsky's lawyers have acknowledged that she and Clinton
exchanged books as gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But the bookstore, with the support of the industry and the
American Civil Liberties Union, had fought the subpoena, contending
that it violated Lewinsky's First Amendment rights and right of
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a federal judge ordered Kramerbooks to turn over
business records describing some of Lewinsky's book purchases. The
judge also ruled that another bookstore, Barnes &AMP; Noble, did not
have to turn over any material because it did not have any relevant
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the arrangement that we helped to broker, she can now
voluntarily provide what information she wants to the independent
counsel,'' said Bill Kramer, a co-owner of the bookstore, obviously
happy to have sidestepped a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement was the first sign that Lewinsky's new lawyers
and prosecutors in the office of Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, are capable of reaching agreements, although their broader
talks involving immunity remained far from resolution, lawyers
involved in the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The immunity negotiations were rekindled this month when
Lewinsky changed lawyers, dropping the flamboyant California
counsel, William H. Ginsburg, for two experienced Washington
criminal lawyers, Plato Cacheris and Jacob A. Stein.
</P>
<P>
   But in the opening round of discussions with the independent
prosecutor, Cacheris and Stein were said to have provided fewer
details about the roles played by Clinton and his close friend,
Vernon E. Jordan Jr., than Ginsburg had offered.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Jordan and Lewinsky are the focus of an investigation
that is examining whether anyone lied, obstructed justice or
tampered with witnesses in the sexual harassment lawsuit brought by
Paula Jones against Clinton. Lewinsky and Clinton have both denied
under oath in that case that they had a sexual relationship. But
from the outset of the investigation, Lewinsky has offered to
testify, in exchange for immunity, that she did have such a
relationship, lawyers involved in the inquiry have said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lawyers in both camps disputed the account of several
published reports last weekend that the independent counsel had
been insisting on an agreement that included a confession by
Lewinsky that she had committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers said the two sides were still far apart on
several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's lawyers have not provided details about a three-page
``talking points'' memo that Lewinsky handed Linda Tripp, a former
colleague at the Pentagon, that coached Tripp about what to say in
the Jones lawsuit. The memo is one of the most important pieces of
evidence to emerge in the inquiry, although investigators remain
puzzled about its origins.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides also appear to be at some distance over Starr's
demand that Lewinsky be interviewed by investigators prior to any
deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This week promises to be a busy one on several fronts for the
independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the negotiations with Lewinsky's lawyers,
prosecutors have signaled their intention to call two White House
aides, John Podesta and Sidney Blumenthal, back to the grand jury.
Podesta helped arrange for a job interview for Lewinsky with
Ambassador Bill Richardson, the representative to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   And Blumenthal had previously refused to answer some questions
posed by the prosecutors on the ground that they were protected by
executive privilege. Clinton recently dropped that claim during an
appeal of a judge's ruling that the privilege was outweighed by the
needs of the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing the Clinton administration and the
independent counsel's office are also set to argue soon in two
federal appeals court cases, on Friday and Monday, over the issue
of whether the administration can limit the testimony of Bruce
Lindsey, a top White House lawyer, and Secret Service officials, on
the ground that they are protected by privileges.
</P>
</TEXT>
