Stephen DeRosa, left, Erika Rolfsrud and Hamish Linklater in a
one-act playlet by Tony Kushner called ``Terminating, or Lass Meine
Schmerzen Nicht Verloren Sein, or Ambivalence.'' The production is
just one of seven brisk theatrical odes being performed by the
Acting Company at the Joseph Papp Public Theater under the title
``Love's Fire.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1998 -- SHAW-THEATER-REVIEW, 6-22 --
Robert Sean Leonard as Valentine and Katie Finneran as Gloria in
George Bernard Shaw's ``You Never Can Tell.'' Shaw's demands on the
audience's suspension of disbelief begin as soon as the curtain
rises. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHICAGO -- June 22, 1998 -- MARIO-LANZA, 6-22 -- A
tribute to Mario Lanza on Saturday night in Grant Park in Chicago.
``The name Mario Lanza brings a smile to just about every music
lover's face,'' says tenor Richard Leech, who narrated and sang the
orchestral program, which included such Lanza standards as ``Be My
Love'' and ``Because You're Mine.'' (Steve Kagan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- June 22, 1998 -- BRODY-HEALTH, 6-22 -- A kiss
from Splash the stingray is incentive enough for Noah Howard, who
has cerebral palsy, to leave his wheelchair and walk up stairs.
Assistance animals, as they are called, are participating in the
treatment, care and emotional nourishment of seriously ill or
injured individuals, and are the stars of a documentary, ``Mary
Tyler Moore in Three Cats From Miami,'' to be broadcast Sunday on
HBO. (Courtesy of HBO/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1998 -- FITNESS-HEALTH, 6-22 --
Deborah Gregory of Manhattan exercises often and considers herself
healthy. Stylish and attractive, Ms. Gregory is noticed when she
walks into a room. She tries to eats a balanced diet, sleeps well
and works an hour of exercise into her busy schedule almost every
day. But at 5 feet 11 and 227 pounds, she is also obese, as defined
under new federal guidelines. The question for Ms. Gregory and
others like her: Can a person be both fit and fat? (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CARVILLE, La. -- June 22, 1998 -- SCI-LEPER-COLONY-3,
6-22 --. The few lepers who still live and receive treatment in
Carville, which will soon become a center for troubled young
people, can accept a $33,000 annual stipend to leave Carville for
good and move to a long-term nursing home in nearby Baton Rouge.
``My folks thought I was crazy for marrying a girl with leprosy.
'Well,' I told him, 'I have leprosy, too,' `` says Johnny Harmon,
86, displaying a book he wrote. (John H. Williams/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CARVILLE, La. -- June 22, 1998 -- SCI-LEPER-COLONY-2,
6-22 -- In the early days of the leprosy center in Carville, some
people were forcibly taken there in handcuffs to live behind a
barbed-wire fence. Displays along a wall show the various names
that Carville has had since it was established in 1894. (John H.
Williams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CARVILLE, La. -- June 22, 1998 -- SCI-LEPER-COLONY-1,
6-22 -- Carville's quiet setting off a country road in Louisiana
seems far removed from the emotional dramas that have been played
out there for more than a century. In the early days of the leprosy
center, some people were forcibly taken there in handcuffs to live
behind a barbed-wire fence. (John H. Williams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
