<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Windows 98 Upgrade Just Windows Dressing   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Windows 98 proves a main contention of Microsoft's most vocal
critics: Take away competition, and innovation also disappears.
<TEXT>
<P>
   How else can you explain this uninspiring ``upgrade'' to Windows
95, which goes on sale Thursday?
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 contains few improvements over Windows 95, the
operating system that runs most of the personal computers in the
universe. And none of the improvements are earthshaking enough to
make anyone run out and pay $89 for it.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is not as bad as Apple, whose wheezing Macintosh
operating system is looking for a major overhaul 14 years after its
introduction. But you'd think the world's largest software company
could come up with something exciting in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has made no secret of its plan to combine Windows with
Windows NT, the version of the operating system used in corporate
networks. That will take place sometime next year. So Windows 98 is
really just a placeholder, something Microsoft hopes will keep
sales up in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   As of this week, most new PCs will come with Windows 98. The
real question is whether individuals who already own PCs should buy
the upgrade, which includes the latest version of Microsoft's
Internet Explorer Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   The answer: If your Windows 95 system is doing the job for you,
if your printer and modem and other peripherals work properly and
if your Internet setup is satisfactory, don't bother with Windows
98.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you already may have some of the advantages claimed by
Windows 98, and you can get others for free:
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft's free Web browser, Internet Explorer 4.0, includes
the Active Desktop that comes with Windows 98. This feature lets
you single-click your way around and makes folders look like Web
pages.
</P>
<P>
   _Windows 98 comes with DirectX technology that improves the
performance of 3-D video games. But most high-performance games
also come with DirectX, which you can install at the same time you
install the game.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 does have a few genuine goodies. It launches
applications a little faster than its predecessor. And it's also
faster at shutting down your system.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it has built-in support for DVD drives and USB ports,
which let you plug in printers, scanners and such and use them
without first having to configure them.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 is easier than Windows 95 to set up the first time
you use it. The program automatically configures printers, monitors
and other peripherals. On the down side, it can take up to an hour
to install the program.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 also makes it easier to get on the Web, with an
Internet Connection Wizard that recommends an Internet service
provider in your area and guides you through the process of signing
up.
</P>
<P>
   Other small benefits: There's a ``Maintenance Wizard'' for
keeping your PC fine-tuned, trouble-shooting wizards for when
things go wrong, and a feature for automatically going online and
updating Windows when Microsoft comes up with improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, however, is that Windows 98 looks almost
identical to Windows 95, and the average person might not be able
to tell the difference at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
