<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 A Low-Key Launch for Windows 98   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Microsoft officially will introduce Windows 98 in San Francisco on
Thursday, but the event will be a watered-down version of the
flamboyant launch of Windows 95.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that Microsoft will spend only $10 million to
promote Windows 98, a pittance compared to the $100 million-plus it
spent on the Windows 95 debut.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows 95 launch was a day-long event emceed by Jay Leno
from Microsoft's headquarters in Redmond, Wash and broadcast all
over the world. Microsoft projected the Windows 95 logo onto the
Empire State Building and persuaded computer stores across the
country to open at midnight. It sold a million copies the first
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows 98 launch _ which has the theme ``Route 98: Another
Milestone on the computing highway'' _ will be held Thursday
afternoon at Fort Mason Center in San Francisco. Microsoft CEO Bill
Gates will speak to between 500 and 1,000 journalists, analysts and
technology executives before they adjourn for some computer
demonstrations and a buffet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows 95 was a unique experience,'' said Kim Akers, Windows
98 project manager at Microsoft. ``Windows 98 is very different and
the timing is very different.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for Microsoft's low-key approach to
Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   _ Windows 98 is an upgrade rather than a revolutionary new
operating system like Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft is pitching Windows 98 to a smaller audience than
Windows 95, which was aimed at consumers and businesses. Microsoft
is only pursuing home and small business users with Windows 98. It
is encouraging corporate clients to switch from Windows 95 to
Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   _ Windows 98 is the subject of a lawsuit by the Justice
Department and 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the suit, Microsoft doesn't want to call excessive
attention to Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the suit, it doesn't need to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research showed that awareness of Windows 98 is very high
_ after all, it's definitely been in the news a lot,'' said Akers,
the Windows 98 product manager.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's ads will tout specific features of Windows 98 _ such
as better game graphics or fewer computer crashes _ along with the
tagline ``Works better. Plays better.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads will appear in mainstream magazines like The New Yorker,
Bon Appetit and Time, but will not show up in computer trade
magazines as Windows 95 ads did.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is also skipping television advertisements this time
around _ but it does plan to blanket the Web with online ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not going to be anywhere near as major,'' a media
splash as Windows 95, said Rob Enderle, analyst at Giga Information
Group in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   In the week following the Windows 95 launch, one survey showed
that the new software was featured in nearly as many TV news
stories as the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as many stories have been written about Microsoft's
battle with the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors contend that Microsoft is illegally using
its monopoly in operating systems to muscle its way into the
Internet market. Windows 98 is a central piece of the case because
it integrates Microsoft's Web browser software into the operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust enforcers are demanding that Microsoft remove its
Internet software from Windows 98 or add a competing program from
Netscape Communications. Microsoft argues that the Internet browser
is an integral part of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is set to begin September 8 in District Court in
Washington D.C. Until the judge rules on the case, Windows 98 will
be available in stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
