A1348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAW-THEATER-REVIEW-A     06-22 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAW-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOU NEVER CAN TELL': SHAW, IN GENTLE MOOD, RELAXES AT THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (JT)  
 By WILBORN HAMPTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeing Shaw's ``You Never Can Tell'' is a little like
sitting on a beach watching a skywriter, wondering what fanciful
and amusing things the pilot might spell out. You won't take them
all that seriously, but it's fun to watch and try to guess what he
will say next.
</P>
<P>
   The play belongs to a group of early Shaw efforts known as
``plays pleasant,'' and the Roundabout Theater's new revival is
just that: as pleasant as a light, breezy summer's day at the
seashore, which is also where the comedy is conveniently set.
</P>
<P>
   Written 100 years ago, ``You Never Can Tell'' is primarily a
spoof of the prevalent notions of love and marriage as the world
approached the 20th century, with some side sallies against
Victorian social mores and a gentle deflating of the New Woman of
the incipient feminist movement. But the humor is more of the
joshing elbow-in-the-ribs variety than the rapier wit of Shaw's
more crusading works.
</P>
<P>
   The action, all of which takes place on one day, centers around
the wooing by a young dentist named Valentine of Gloria, the
headstrong elder daughter of a single mother who 18 years earlier
left her husband, changed her name and took her three children to
Madeira to raise them. The mother, who is also the author of a
series of books on what to expect in the 20th century, has now
returned to England with the grown children _ Gloria, Dolly and
Philip _ and winds up in the seaside resort in Devon where her
husband just happens to reside. The husband also just happens to be
the dentist's landlord.
</P>
<P>
   If those coincidences seem a bit much to swallow, there are even
more to come. Shaw's demands on the audience's suspension of
disbelief begin as soon as the curtain rises to find Dolly having a
tooth pulled by the handsome dentist. Why a healthy teen-age girl
would need a tooth extracted during a day at the beach is not a
question to trouble us. It is done painlessly and bloodlessly, for
which the audience may be grateful, and it provides as good an
occasion as any for Valentine to be invited to lunch, a meal to
which he will of course bring his landlord, the same long-lost
husband and father.
</P>
<P>
   As the inevitable complications arise from the sudden reunion of
a broken household after an 18-year separation, not to mention the
courtship of a young 20th-century feminist by a 19th-century
Lothario, the services of a lawyer are suddenly required. In one
last test of the audience's tolerance, the barrister who arrives
just happens to be the son of the headwaiter at the hotel where the
family is staying.
</P>
<P>
   The waiter, who put his son through Cambridge and law school
because the boy ``never had a hand for real work,'' is Shaw's
stroke of brilliance in ``You Never Can Tell.'' Like Shakespeare's
fools, the waiter is the one calm voice of reason amid the wounded
familial pride, hurt feelings and jealous lovers jilted by their
own pasts and future expectations, a sage who can dispense advice
while taking drink orders and serving the soup at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Although the role would seem a supporting one by mere line
count, Philip Bosco turned it into a star turn in a 1986 revival of
the play at the old Circle in the Square, and Charles Keating does
no less in this Roundabout production.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw once boasted that ``You Never Can Tell'' was a play that
was ``actor proof.'' Fortunately that premise is not severely
tested in the Roundabout production. The main roles are ably
filled, starting with Keating, who is a walking definition of
unflappability and understatement. ``You can't learn being a
waiter, sir,'' he confides at one point. ``You have to be born to
it.'' He might have added that it's not unlike acting in that
regard, and Keating is as natural a Shavian as he proved to be an
Ortonian in revivals of ``Loot'' and ``What the Butler Saw'' a few
seasons back.
</P>
<P>
   The lovers are in the capable hands of Robert Sean Leonard as
Valentine, the five-shilling dentist who manages to stay one step
ahead of the latest feminist thinking on matters of the heart until
he puts his foot in his mouth, and Katie Finneran as Gloria, the
modern young woman who hates pretty speeches until she hears one.
Leonard, nervous and clumsy one moment, dropping napkins and
spilling drinks, then ardent in his declarations of love the next,
is a dashing figure who commands one's attention on the stage (much
as Victor Garber did in the same role in the 1986 revival). Ms.
Finneran is amusing in her haughty disdain for such old-fashioned
sentiments as love and shattered with self-loathing once she
succumbs to them.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Kellner is a delight as Dolly, the impertinent younger
daughter who asks more questions than Kenneth Starr, and Simon
Jones is convincing as the long-lost husband and father, an almost
Dickensian reading of a man who has found that ``most things that
are good for me are nasty.'' Jere Shea adds a nice turn as Bohun,
the brash young lawyer who has made a ``specialty of being right
when others are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Carey never quite finds the feminist zeal of the mother,
and some of the supporting performances are uneven. But Nicholas
Martin's direction mostly maintains a pace that moves quickly over
the rough edges (except in one Jack Benny-like pause that fails to
get the laugh it seeks and nearly brings the play to a standstill).
Allen Moyer's set is full of light and almost smells of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `YOU NEVER CAN TELL'
</P>
<P>
   By George Bernard Shaw; directed by Nicholas Martin; sets by
Allen Moyer; costumes by Michael Krass; lighting by Frances
Aronson; sound and original music by Mark Bennett; dialect coach,
Tim Monich; production stage manager, Robert I. Cohen. Presented by
the Roundabout Theater, Todd Haimes, artistic director; Ellen
Richard, general manager. At Criterion Center, Laura Pels Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Catherine Kellner (Dolly), Robert Sean Leonard
(Valentine), Sarah Rafferty (Parlor Maid), Saxon Palmer (Philip),
Helen Carey (Mrs. Clandon), Katie Finneran (Gloria), Simon Jones
(Crampton), Nicholas Kepros (M'Comas), Charles Keating (Waiter),
Jere Shea (Bohun), Greg Keller (Jo) and Phil Tabor (Louis).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
