<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LEAVE ELLETT, BAUMGARTNER UNPROTECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veteran defenseman Dave Ellett and winger/enforcer Ken
Baumgartner, both of whom joined the Bruins as free agents last
summer, are among the veterans Boston has left exposed for Friday's
expansion draft that will stock the NHL's Nashville Predators.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely Bruin to be sent South, however, is Mike
Sullivan, the 30-year-old center who proved to be a valuable
faceoff man and defensive specialist last season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Predators find themselves in need of an enforcer, then
Baumgartner could be the the one picked in the expansion draft,
which will be held at 2 p.m. in Buffalo, one day before the annual
amateur entry draft at Marine Midland Arena. But it's far more
likely that Nashville will look to build around speed and
dependability, a scenario that points to Sullivan, the former
high-scoring Boston University pivot.
</P>
<P>
   The league released the protected lists of all 26 teams Monday,
and the Bruins, as expected, opted to protect two goalies, four
defenseman, and seven forwards. Their keepers included a couple of
mild surprises, right wing Landon Wilson and defenseman Darren Van
Impe.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, a Group 2 free agent, has done little since his arrival
here from Colorado in December '96 in the deal that cost the
Bruins' their first-round pick Saturday. Van Impe showed himself to
be a valuable point man on the power play but also porous on
defense, leading coach Pat Burns to keep him on the bench much of
the time when play was at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wilson and Van Impe were retained at the risk of either
Ellett or Baumgartner, two of Burns's favorites. No club can lose
more than one player in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Grant Ledyard, acquired in a late-season swap with
Vancouver, also was left unprotected by the Bruins. Not
surprisingly, Byron Dafoe and Rob Tallas were the two goalies
retained, leaving former Vezina Trophy winner Jim Carey out there
for his former general manager in Washington, David Poile, to
select. At a cost of $5 million over the next two years, and coming
off a 1997-98 season that was curtailed by shoulder surgery, Carey
isn't likely to be picked up by Poile.
</P>
<P>
   The Predators, if they feel emboldened, can select some of the
priciest talent in the league, including St. Louis's Brett Hull.
Hull is free to sign with any team as of July 1, with the Blues
owed nothing in return. The Blues recently offered the former
high-scoring winger a three-year, $15 million pact, but wouldn't
yield to the Golden Brett's demand to write a no-trade clause into
year No. 3 of the deal. He is expected to sign with Chicago early
next month. It's highly doubtful that the Predators would waste the
pick, but Hull's high name recognition could lead Poile &AMP; Co. to
consider signing him for Team Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton's Curtis Joseph, Florida's John Vanbiesbrouck, and the
Rangers' Mike Richter, all free agent goalies who likely will be
offered $5 million a year or better on long-term deals, were left
unprotected. The Predators can draft up to five goalies, but again
it's doubtful that they'd bite on any of the high-priced
unrestricted free agents. A promising young netminder such as Mike
Dunham, left unprotected by the Devils, probably will be more
tantalizing, or perhaps the Senators' Ron Tugnutt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
