<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ranchers in Florida 'desperate' due to heat wave
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida's cattle ranchers will likely become
the latest victims of the state's continuing heat wave, adding to
the $80 million in crops already lost this summer, Agriculture
Commissioner Bob Crawford said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been this desperate in Florida in 50 years,''
Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months of record-breaking heat, North Florida
farmers have lost $20 million worth of sweet corn, $20 million of
hay, $15 million in peanuts, $12 million in cotton and $10 million
in soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   It's that loss of hay _ about 95 percent of the expected crop
this year _ that in turn is cutting into the $150 million-a-year
cattle industry, Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Large ranchers might be able to cope by purchasing hay from
other states, but smaller ranchers are more likely to ship their
calves to market early, depressing further an already low market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of pasture. We're out of hay,'' said Lawrence
Heitmeyer, director of Leon County's Agricultural Extension. ``We
just don't have anything to feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ranchers' losses won't translate into cheaper steaks at
the supermarket, cattle experts said. Rather than raising cattle to
the size necessary for slaughter, Florida cattlemen produce calves
that are then shipped to feed lots in the West and Midwest. Two
years later, the animals are sent to large slaughterhouses and then
to meat wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Don't look for cut-rate rib-eyes this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a couple of years to affect that price,'' said Mark
Kistler, head of the Okeechobee County Extension, adding that the
business has ``too many middlemen'' for consumers to see any
benefit at the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for other foods, like corn or peanuts, may rise slightly,
depending on what happens to crops in other states, Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
