<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fires continue to burn with no relief in sight
 &HT;    (EDS: All mentioned locations are in Florida, unless otherwise
noted.)
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida is so crackling dry and hot that
even prayed-for thunderstorms brought lightning that fueled the
worst outbreak of wildfires in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke from burning timber land blacked out the Daytona Beach
area on the east coast and 10,000 acres of pine forests burned
Monday near Perry, 50 miles southeast of Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Power &AMP; Light turned off the electricity for up to three
hours to pool filters, water heaters and air conditioners of
hundreds of thousands of customers in a voluntary program across
the state to keep the use of power under control.
</P>
<P>
   Power use reached 17,774 megawatts, not far from the record
summer peak of 18,004 megawatts, said FPL spokesman George Molina.
set when?
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters in Palm Beach County scrambled to control eight
brush fires from Jupiter Farms to south Boca Raton, yet all but one
was less than 4 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Relief for South Florida may be less than a week away. The wet
season weather pattern has returned, proven by rain around Lake
Okeechobee Sunday, including nearly 2 inches south of Clewiston.
</P>
<P>
   East and southeast winds push afternoon thunderstorms inland. A
westerly wind allows storms to build over the east coast.
``Eventually it will come,'' said Eric Swartz, a meterologist with
the South Florida Water Management District.
</P>
<P>
   Since Memorial Day, fires have burned more than 80,000 acres in
40 counties stretching from Lake Okeechobee to the Panhandle. The
state is seeing an average of 80 new fire starts a day, 90 percent
of them started by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide fires have destroyed 114 buildings and 74 vehicles
and have cost $4 million to fight so far, said Palm Beach County
Rescue Chief Raymond Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen firefighters from Palm Beach County headed Monday to
Volusia County, to relieve some of the about 30 local firefighters
already there. The county and Boca Raton each sent five, Delray
Beach four and Boynton Beach three.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sheppard said Palm Beach County, where 18 brush fires
cropped up this weekend, isn't placing itself at risk by helping
others. The point of the region-wide response ``is that no one
(department) becomes overwhelmed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford, whose office runs
the forestry division, has asked counties and municipalities to
cancel their Fourth of July fireworks displays, and several north
and central Florida counties have agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted that banning private celebrations would be a
legal problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``One sparkler, one small firecracker can cause tremendous
damage,'' he said. ``We're going to have a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters in Martin and Palm Beach counties haven't pushed
for a ban on either public fireworks displays or private
celebrations despite the fact that two of Monday's brush fires
likely were started by firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the rights of the people of this county to
celebrate the Fourth of July in the way they see fit,'' said Palm
Beach County Fire Rescue spokesman Nigel Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach (Fla.) Post staff writers Cara Anna, Douglas Belkin,
Joe Brogan, Shirish Date, Eliot Kleinberg and Jennifer Peltz and
Post wire services contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
