<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lamborghini lawsuit claims costly cars 'defective'
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ He thought he'd be James Bond-cool in
his new purple Lamborghini, which came complete with a hydraulic
lift to get the low frame over the speed bumps.
</P>
<P>
   But once the car's battery died, and the roof started leaking,
and the doors stuck shut, and the steering wheel rapped his knees,
and the sunroof latches thwacked him in the head, John Martin's new
car seemed more like something from the garage of Inspector
Clouseau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted a quality vehicle,'' he said. ``With all the
money you're paying, you expect the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 31, of Fort Lauderdale, Fla. filed a lawsuit in federal
court last week charging the Automobili Lamborghini company, maker
of his 1997 Diablo Roadster model, with knowingly selling him a
defective car. Martin's lawyer, Saul Smolar, said he has sworn
statements from four former employees of the Italian automaker who
said the company has concealed a litany of faults with the
Roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Few Lamborghinis are on the road, probably because of their
prohibitive cost (including the Ferrari he traded in, Martin and
his parents paid about $240,000 for his). But Smolar and two other
law firms want to make Martin's suit a class-action on behalf of
the 50 to 60 other people in the United States who bought Diablos.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's suit seeks repayment for the car, repair costs,
insurance costs and interest.
</P>
<P>
   The Diablo went on the market in 1996 as Lamborghini's first car
intended for typical driving conditions. Until then, Lamborghinis _
which can reach speeds exceeding 200 mph _ primarily were racing
cars, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem with the Diablos, Smolar says, are their
distinctive vertical doors. The windows are supposed to retract
slightly to let the door rise, but often the windows get stuck,
preventing passengers inside from getting out. The doors also are
part of the leaking problem, in which the car fills with water
every time it rains, Smolar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a Diablo that does not leak,'' Smolar said. ``You
need an umbrella in the car if you are going to drive in the
rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his car was in the shop more than 10 times for
repairs, the last time for nearly three weeks. He said the
dealership that sold him the car, Prestige Imports in North Miami
Beach, Fla., refused at first to take the car back.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the car's makers sent Martin a recall notice, offering
to fix a switch in the door and recommending that Martin drive with
the windows slightly open at all times.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Lamborghini was out of town Monday and couldn't be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's lawsuit lists still more complaints about his car: It
stalls, it's rusting, the horn doesn't work, and lights on the
dashboard sometimes flicker inexplicably. Not even that nifty
hydraulic lift is working; he says he's still bouncing off the
speed bumps.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a pharmacy student at Broward Community College, has
placed his Lamborghini in the garage. Now he's driving a sports
utility vehicle made by Mercedes Benz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just gave up on anything Italian except pasta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach (Fla.) Post researcher Barbara Gellis Shapiro
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
