<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online Privacy Alliance introduced as Commerce Department opens
summit
 &HT;    By Mike Drummond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lexis-Nexis and NCR Corp. were among some 50 major American
companies that formed a new trade group Monday to protect consumer
privacy on the Internet and thwart government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The Online Privacy Alliance and a separate initiative by the
Better Business Bureau were unveiled before the Department of
Commerce opened its two-day summit on Internet privacy today, as
debate rages over how to deal with commercial Web sites that siphon
information from unsuspecting Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a similar initiative led by Lexis-Nexis last year, the
self-regulating Alliance lacks ways to punish member companies for
violating terms of the group's privacy policies
(www.privacyalliance.org), despite its requirement that members
post privacy policies and prohibit children's sites from collecting
information without parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their motivation is they don't want legislation, but
unfortunately legislation is needed to have privacy protected,''
said Evan Hendricks, editor of the Washington, D.C. newsletter
Privacy Times . ``Self-regulation is a king without clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's other mission is to cultivate electronic
commerce. Framingham, Mass.-based International Data Corp.
estimates that global Internet commerce revenue will grow to $223
billion in 2001 from $10.6 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox is that while e-commerce mushrooms, government and
industry officials say its full potential is hobbled by fears of
lack of privacy, even among experienced computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Lexis-Nexis triggered debate over online privacy two years ago
when inaccurate rumors circulated on the Web about its P-Trak
people-finder service. Last year, Lexis-Nexis helped form the
Individual Reference Services Group, a coalition of 14 companies
that pledged to limit who can access personal information and allow
people to ``opt out'' of certain databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is self-regulation can work,'' said Lexis-Nexis
spokeswoman Judith Schultz, noting that IRSG members will be
independently audited and face federal penalties for violating
privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Clinton administration said it would give
Internet businesses more time to develop their own privacy rules to
protect information they collect from customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRSG and the Alliance may not be enough to satisfy a
more aggressive Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the FTC recommended government legislation to
protect children from Web sites that collect personally
identifiable information.
</P>
<P>
   The commission conducted a survey of commercial Web sites this
year and found few provide any privacy notices. The FTC also found
almost 90 percent of 212 children's sites surveyed collected
personally identifiable information directly from children.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, Ohio-based NCR markets automatic teller machines and
other products that gather consumer information and feeds it into
NCR data warehouses. Yet the company also tries to balance its
data-gathering mission with protecting privacy, in part because not
doing so may invite the heavy hand of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global e-commerce will not fulfill its promise without privacy
and data protection,'' said Chris Hankin, director of governmental
affairs for NCR. ``But bureaucracy is inherently slow, and the
Internet is very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
