 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sampson's changes questioned after U.S. defeat
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France _ Losing to Germany in the World Cup opener was
neither a shock nor cause for a fire alarm at Camp USA.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Soccer coach Steve Sampson even said as much after that
game, when he promised to only tinker with the things that went
wrong in the Americans' World Cup-opening loss, but concluded that
it was no time to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be fine,'' Sampson said. ``We're confident with
the things we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words have come back to haunt Sampson, whose tinkering for
Sunday's crucial and ill-fated game against Iran was like Tim ``The
Toolman'' Taylor deciding to add on a room.
</P>
<P>
   There were wholesale changes not just in the USA's lineup but in
the entire offensive and defensive schemes, which only days before
Sampson had described as giving the U.S. its best chance of
winning. Also, U.S. players were wondering about one of the most
critical decisions of all.
</P>
<P>
   Why bench Eric Wynalda, the creative goal-scorer with more
international experience than any forward on the team?
</P>
<P>
   It was but one of several questions facing the coach and the
team Monday in the wake of a 2-1 loss that some called the worst in
U.S. Soccer history and ended all U.S. hopes of advancing past the
first round of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Should the U.S. team lose to Yugoslavia on Thursday in Lens, the
best it could finish in the Cup is 27th place. It will have gone
through the entire tournament winless. It will have seen a
disturbing goal-scoring drought linger on.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the U.S. finished 14th overall, in a group that
was considered equally as tough as this year's. Among the teams the
U.S. faced four years ago were Colombia and Romania. That U.S. team
advanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to others to decide how much progress we've made,''
Sampson said. ``I think we are a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the Americans seemed to outplay the Iranians in
most parts of Sunday's game, taking more shots, getting more shots
on goal and possessing the ball significantly longer.
</P>
<P>
   But Iran won 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's critical go-ahead goal came when there was a significant
breakdown in the new defensive set that Sampson put together
specifically for the Iran game. Iran counterattacked, which long
has been its best asset.
</P>
<P>
   Tab Ramos and Claudio Reyna _ natural midfielders _ were the two
players involved in the mix-up in the U.S. box on the huge Iranian
goal, as Iran's Hamid Estili got a clear shot on a header shortly
before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (Ramos) had him, and he thought I had him,'' Reyna
said. ``It was a breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the game. And it exposed the strange nature of Sampson's
sudden and drastic change in tactics.
</P>
<P>
   For months prior to the World Cup, Sampson professed a
commitment to playing six midfielders against opponents in order to
utilize the U.S. team speed. In lead-up matches to the tournament,
the 3-6-1 worked amazingly well, forging victories over Austria and
even Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Against Germany in the opener, it's likely no scheme or tactic
would have mattered. The Germans were miles better.
</P>
<P>
   But against Iran, a team that usually does not build offensive
attacks, instead relying on counterattacks for its goals, Sampson
ditched the six midfielders and went to a more conventional four
midfielders.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Ramos and Joe-Max Moore for the middle-back of the
defense, playing them out of position in defensive roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't change a thing,'' Sampson said when asked why Ramos
and Moore played when some of the most decorated and taller
players, Jeff Agoos, Marcelo Balboa and Alexi Lalas, were on the
bench. ``I'm very happy with the effort of the players I chose.
It's up to other people to decide what they think.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the other people questioning Sampson's shift in
strategies, which seemed to play into Iran's strength of
counterattacking, were his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're the kind of team that can change
strategies just like that,'' Reyna said.
</P>
<P>
   Said forward Cobi Jones: ``The coach puts up the lineup, and we
play. That's all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players still refused Monday to speak publicly regarding
the crash in U.S. Soccer fortunes and the strange and sudden change
in strategies against Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas and Agoos only shook their heads when asked to comment
about the game and the plan.
</P>
<P>
   And at the center of it all was Wynalda, who is regarded among
the most dangerous scorers in U.S. history but never saw the field
even after the Americans fell behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't start, and you just say OK, and we'll go out and
play without him,'' Reyna said. ``Everyone here has not started
games. But I was surprised that Eric didn't get in at some point.
When we made changes, I thought it would be Eric coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't. The normally accommodating Wynalda also refused
to discuss the issue. Sampson said it was not a matter of condition
or injuries, just his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Said goalkeeper Kasey Keller: ``You go down, and you need to
score some goals. I wondered why Eric wasn't there. He's one player
who can score goals for you. We're going to be asking ourselves a
lot of questions about this (World Cup), I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll have time. It's a long flight home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2156EDT &QL; 
