 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Year 2000 Problem Worries Americans   By Amy Doan  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Nearly one in four Americans thinks that Year 2000 computer
glitches will affect their daily life, according to a survey
released yesterday by the Information Technology Association of
America.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ITAA said its poll of 1,000 people nationwide is the first
one to gauge the views of ordinary Americans on the Year 2000 bug.
Jon Englund, vice president of the ITAA in Arlington, Va., called
the one-in-four number ``significant.''
</P>
<P>
   A May 1998 Gallup poll found that only 6 percent of small
business owners considered the millennium problem ``very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those individuals in the ITAA poll who expect to be stricken
by the Year 2000 bug, 80 percent worry that their financial records
will be distorted and 72 percent fear business losses.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those surveyed said that government and business leaders
aren't doing enough to remedy the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a clear message to President Clinton to get serious
about the bug and what it's going to cost taxpayers,` said Englund.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also criticized the Clinton Administration last week
for doing too little to make government computer systems Year 2000
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   At his birthday party on Saturday, House Speaker Newt Gingrich
said Clinton is presiding over a ``large wreck'' waiting to happen
on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, House Republicans voted to earmark $4 billion in
emergency spending for fixing Year 2000 glitches.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium bug results from a 1960s programming convention
restricting the year to two digits of code.
</P>
<P>
   Come Jan. 1, 2000, some systems might interpret the date as Jan.
1, 1900, resulting in delays, errors or shutdowns.
</P>
<P>
   While the millennium glitch may make some people wary of
computers, a large segment of the U.S. population is comfortable
sending credit card numbers over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen percent of Americans have made at least one online
purchase, according to another ITAA survey.
</P>
<P>
   That figure should encourage online marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Christmas selling season should be the first one that
e-commerce really makes a dent in sales at traditional
brick-and-mortar stores,` said Vernon Keenan, senior analyst with
Zona Research Inc. in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   Age and income are tightly correlated with electronic commerce
experience, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   People over 55 are three times less likely to have made an
online purchase than younger Americans, and those making more than
$60,000 per year are over three times more likely to have bought
something online than those earning between $15,000 and $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among those reluctant to buy products over the Web, 10 percent
cited a desire to ``touch and feel'' the merchandise. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
