 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Former Sybase Workers' Startup Gets $10 Million in Cash   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
A gang of refugees from Sybase have  spawned a new genre of
databases, and today their startup will be blessed with $10 million
in venture cash.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in these inflated times, that's a big bet on Cloudscape
Inc., which is trying to popularize a program that ships data to
handheld devices.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudscape of Oakland was born two years ago when ex-Sybase
engineers Nat Wyatt and Howard Torf saw opportunity in two trends.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the rise of Java, a programming language that
creates portable programs which can travel easily over the
Internet. The second was the popularity of Palm Pilots and now
Windows CE devices, handhelds too small to run conventional
databases.
</P>
<P>
   For their first $500,000 in seed funding, Wyatt and Torf lined
up impressive backers like Informix co-founder Roger Sippl and
longtime Sybase marketing whiz Stewart Shuster.
</P>
<P>
   Today's financing round is led by Mohr, Davidow Ventures, which
hopes the $10 million cash inflow will send Cloudscape aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Merv Adrian, an industry analyst with Giga Information Systems,
said Cloudscape will need that cash to compete with the current
market leader in mobile databases _ a prize if you guessed that
it's Sybase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real trick ... is to line up software partners to create
niche applications, and that costs money,'' Adrian said.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate objective is to create programs that insurance
brokers might use on Windows CE handhelds, or that car salesmen
might whip out on a Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sybase and Oracle both have databases that send info to
mobile gadgets, IDC analyst Evan Quinn said Cloudscape's database
is written in Java, which has the technical advantage of being
easier to ship over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudscape won't have the Java-database space to itself for
long. DataBean in San Mateo is working on a competing Java-based
package. DataBean was founded by Bruce Scott, formerly one of the
top database programmers at Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Zooming in: &LR;  San Francisco-based Xoom will announce today that
it has acquired SiteMail, a vendor of free Web-based e-mail for an
unspecified sum. Xoom will soon add free e-mail to the list of
services it offers members.
</P>
<P>
   What is Xoom? If you have to ask, then you're not one of the 1.7
million people who've created personal Web pages in Xoom's
fast-growing electronic community.
</P>
<P>
   Xoomers pay no fees for their plots in cyberspace. Instead,
users fill out personal profiles and agree to accept e-mail sales
pitches that, in another context, would be called spam. Xoom gets
paid for being the middleman in these direct marketing pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in September 1996 by veteran entrepreneurs Chris Kitze
of Lycos and Laurent Massa of the Learning Company, Xoom's
35-person staff is adding new members at the rate of 22,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The company is currently in a quiet period prior to the filing
of an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Car talk? &LR;  With four venture capitalists on stage, the
Churchill Club had a sellout crowd at last week's dinner speech in
Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   With the Valley awash in cash, and everybody carrying around a
business plan, dinner-goers hoped to grab a card from such venture
veterans as Sam Colella, Irwin Federman and Michael Child.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Jim Breyer of Accel Partners who stole the show by
treating the crowd to a translation of venture capital euphemisms.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when VCs say their startup is pursuing ``an
acquisition strategy,'' what they really mean is their current
products have no market. ``Limited downside'' is just another way
to say things can't get much worse.
</P>
<P>
   But Breyer waxed serious long enough to say that when evaluating
startups, he looks for Hondas in their parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a profit mentality and expense controls from
Day One,'' said Breyer, who steers clear of firms with Porches and
Beemers out front.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Digital Bay now appears in this space every Tuesday, Thursday and
Saturday. Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear
it by phone (650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
