 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Layoffs Likely In Broderbund Acquisition   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Learning Company's acquisition of Broderbund is likely to
result in some job cuts and product realignments because both
companies employ significant workforces in the Bay Area and make
many competing software programs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Layoffs probably won't be announced until after the $420 million
deal _ confirmed yesterday _ closes in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their jobs for the next 60 to 90 days'' until
the merger closes, said Lauren Tanny, Broderbund's vice president
of marketing. Although she said she doesn't expect major layoffs,
The Learning Co. has approved a severance package.
</P>
<P>
   One of Broderbund's core products, The Print Shop suite of home
publishing software, competes directly with Printmaster, which is
made by The Learning Co.'s Mindscape division.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund's best-selling Family Tree Maker and clip art and
encyclopedia products also compete with Learning Co. offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The companies will spend the summer figuring out ways to
integrate those product lines. One print program, for instance,
might be sold at a higher price, or one might move into an office
market.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Michael Perik
said he will ``de-emphasize'' Broderbund's entertainment line,
which includes Warlords, The Journeyman Project, and Last Express.
But he said he will keep the smash hit Myst and its sequel, Riven,
which was released late last year.
</P>
<P>
   In educational software, Broderbund's well-known titles _
including Where in the World is Carmen Sandiego?, Arthur, and Dr.
Seuss _ can be sold right alongside The Learning Co.'s Reader
Rabbit, Oregon Trail and Cluefinder software.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Perik _ who kept pronouncing
the name of his newly acquired company ``Borderbund'' _ said the
deal should result in ``the first pure $1 billion revenue line from
a consumer software company.''
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal 1997, Broderbund had sales of $192 million and The
Learning Co. had $392.4 million in sales. But this year, The
Learning Co. has acquired several companies, including Novato-based
Mindscape, and Broderbund is expected to do $300 million in
revenues, including sales from Riven.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Broderbund employs 1,100 people, with 600 at its headquarters
in Novato and 100 in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co., based in Cambridge, Mass., employs 2,000
people, including 300 in Novato and 300 in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Broderbund stock closed yesterday up $2.25, or 12 percent, at
$18.75 on the news. The Learning Co. closed down 11 cents at
$24.89.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broderbund has been struggling for a few years. In the hands
of a company like The Learning Co., shareholders will see a better
return,'' said Andrea Williams, an analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan
and Co.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Learning Co. will swap eight-tenths of a share for each
share of Broderbund stock. The Learning Co. expects its earnings
per share to rise about 10 cents this year due to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been reached yet on the board of directors or on
the fate of Broderbund CEO Joe Durrett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
