<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-THEATER-REVIEW-A     06-22 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE'S FIRE': HOW AGED THOSE SONNETS, BUT THEY DOTH SPEAK FRESH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (JT)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The squiggly little things keep multiplying like
amoebas. They grow, they shrink, they change forms, they disappear,
they come back, they attack their creators.
</P>
<P>
   Words, words, words! You can't say one without meaning an
infinity of others. And if you're one inordinately well-read,
hopelessly conflicted analysand named Hendryk, who could only be
the product of the inordinately well-read playwright named Tony
Kushner, you can't open your mouth without a swarm of the little
varmints filling the room, endlessly trailing paradoxes and
associations. Why, just consider the title of the brief,
deliciously convoluted play in which this victim of logorrhea
appears: ``Terminating, or Lass Meine Schmerzen Nicht Verloren
Sein, or Ambivalence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Terminating,'' as it will henceforth considerately be called,
is one of seven brisk theatrical odes being performed by the Acting
Company at the Joseph Papp Public Theater under the title ``Love's
Fire.'' Kushner is in august company: the evening's other
contributors are Eric Bogosian, Ntozake Shange, Marsha Norman,
William Finn, Wendy Wasserstein and John Guare, each of whom was
commissioned by the Acting Company to write a playlet inspired by a
different Shakespearean sonnet.
</P>
<P>
   Hold on, now. What exactly do Hendryk's babblings about sex and
smells and curtain fabrics and tattoos and existential despair have
to do with Shakespeare's Sonnet 75, the one that begins, ``So are
you to my thoughts as food to life''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the poem is definitely, on one level, about ambivalence,
and Hendryk, played with megawatt electricity by Stephen DeRosa,
has enough of that trait to take Hamlet through another five acts
of vacillation. So, for that matter, does his shrink, Esther (the
winning Erika Rolfsrud), who would rather be pondering her own
problems than listening to this cosmic kvetcher.
</P>
<P>
   But even more resonantly, ``Terminating'' has everything to do
with the limits and limitlessness of language. Which is also, of
course, the essence of Shakespeare, in whose world a rose is seldom
only just a rose. (Roses, by the way, figure in Hendryk's
discussion of his distaste for a certain sex act, but don't ask
how.) Kushner's spirited dialogue between doctor and patient, with
the voices of their lovers thrown in as condiments, turns
psychiatric free association into a floating metaphor for the
transforming perspective every reader brings to every piece of
literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Fire,'' which has been directed with ingenuity and
great good humor by Mark Lamos, lets you crawl into seven very
different minds dealing with similar material. The resulting
production, which has already toured the United States and been
seen at the Barbican Center in London, is a testament to the
inexhaustibility of these poems _ a reminder that while the
Shakespearean sonnet may be a tight and disciplined form, its life
doesn't stop with its concluding couplet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words of a dead man are modified in the guts of the
living,'' W.H. Auden wrote in his elegy for W.B. Yeats. Few words
have been so rigorously subjected to so much analysis over the
centuries as those of Shakespeare's sonnets, which have been
presented as everything from a narrative of homosexual love to the
ultimate semiotic game. ``Love's Fire,'' in addition to using the
poems as a sort of Rorschach test for its different playwrights,
acknowledges the interpretive Tower of Babel that the works have
given rise to.
</P>
<P>
   Lamos appropriately begins the evening with the nine members of
the ensemble uttering fragments from the sonnets under
consideration, in a manner that starts slowly and seductively and
then builds into a cacophony of clashing voices. The idea of a
multiplicity of points of view is underscored throughout the
evening in having each sonnet recited by two different actors, and
in the designer Michael Yeargan's use of a wall of television
screens to echo and fragment the faces of the actors and the words
they speak.
</P>
<P>
   The evening concludes with Guare's ``General of Hot Desire''
(spun off from the last of the sonnets, 153 and 154), which
presents the entire ensemble as a group of college students, armed
with essays and reference books, who have been assigned the task of
creating a play from those same poems. What they come up with is
nothing less than a history of the world, starting with the Garden
of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot Desire'' is a doggedly whimsical work, sometimes
irritating in its cuteness but often truly affecting, too. In its
scope and story-theater symbolism, it is reminiscent of Thornton
Wilder's ``Skin of Our Teeth'' (this summer's first offering, by
the way, from the New York Shakespeare Festival in Central Park).
</P>
<P>
   Like that play, it sees something admirable and pathetic in
humankind's attempts to reconnect, through art and religions, with
paradise lost and an indifferent God, and it sums up the generosity
of spirit of the whole evening. Its climactic, festive song, with
music by the gifted Adam Guettel, is filled with an intense love of
performing that lingers long after the students have lapsed back
into academic quibbling over their project.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other plays, Kushner's combustible rant of a work aside, are
most interesting as exercises in individual styles, reflecting the
distinctive mind-sets of their creators. Ms. Norman, the author of
the harrowing `` 'Night, Mother,'' creates a dark daisy chain of
erotic desire in her ``La Ronde''-ish ``Sonnet 140.'' Ms.
Wasserstein, the master of the urbane comedy of manners, uses
Sonnet 94 as a springboard for a look at worldly dissatisfaction
among the rich and name-dropping in ``Waiting for Philip Glass,''
which brings to mind her screenplay for ``The Object of My
Affection.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lovely, palate-cleansing musical vignette, Finn, the
composer of ``Falsettos'' and the current ``New Brain,'' has a
painter ( DeRosa) consider the impossibility of capturing his
beloved (Jason Alan Carvell) in art. Bogosian, best known for his
funny, splenetic performance pieces, turns a confrontation between
a couple (Heather Robison and Daniel Pearce) on the eve of their
wedding into a robust comic look at the sexually divided self.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Shange, the author of the poetic portrait of black
womanhood ``For Colored Girls Who Have Considered Suicide/ When the
Rainbow Is Enuf,'' takes off from the musical tropes of Sonnet 128
into a conflicted mating dance to Chico Freeman's music, performed
by Carvell and the incandescent Lisa Tharps and choreographed by
Dyane Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   The actors _ who also include Hamish Linklater, James Farmer and
Jennifer Rohn _ aren't all equally comfortable with the extremely
varied demands of the material, and there are occasionally feelings
of the pained self-consciousness of an acting class. But they all
have shining moments. Ms. Rohn, for example, is hilarious as a
woebegone Eve looking for words for depression in Guare's piece.
And DeRosa, in particular, has the bright presence and dexterous
shading of which stars are made.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's writers are, to some degree, stars already.
``Love's Fire'' isn't going to make or break them. But how
wonderful to have them assembled, in all their differences, as they
are here. The sheer exhilaration of Kushner's emotionally weighted
wordplay is alone enough to make the production worthwhile. But
it's the contrasts within ``Love's Fire'' that give it such a
hopeful glow. They demonstrate that poems spun four centuries ago
continue to evolve and mutate in ``the guts of the living'' and may
well do so forever. That is something to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE'S FIRE'
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Numbers by Seven American Playwrights.
</P>
<P>
   One-act plays inspired by Shakespeare's sonnets, by Eric
Bogosian, William Finn, John Guare, Tony Kushner, Marsha Norman,
Ntozake Shange and Wendy Wasserstein; directed by Mark Lamos;
original music by Finn, Chico Freeman and Adam Guettel; sets by
Michael Yeargan; costumes by Candice Donnelly; lighting by Robert
Wierzel; sound by John Gromada; choreography by Dyane Harvey;
dramaturge, Anne Cattaneo; voice and speech consultant, Elizabeth
Smith; production supervisor, Maureen Gibson; production stage
manager, Jennifer Rae Moore. Produced in association with Ira
Pittelman and Jonathan C. Herzog. Presented by the Acting Company,
Margot Harley, producing director. At the Joseph Papp Public
Theater, Newman Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jason Alan Carvell, Stephen DeRosa, James Farmer, Hamish
Linklater, Daniel Pearce, Heather Robison, Jennifer Rohn, Erika
Rolfsrud and Lisa Tharps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
