<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-HARASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HARASSMENT IN THE SCHOOLS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 23:
</P>
<P>
   A sharply divided Supreme Court on Monday emphasized the
``extraordinary harm'' suffered by student victims of sexual
harassment or abuse by teachers, but then perversely deprived them
and their families of an effective legal remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-to-4 ruling, shattering the court's usual unanimity on
sexual-harassment issues, was the product of a conservative bloc of
justices who sought to substitute their own views for those of
Congress in interpreting Title IX, the federal law that bars sex
discrimination in schools receiving federal funds. The majority
ruled that victims of harassment could recover damages from a
school district only if officials knew of the misconduct and
deliberately failed to act. In thus greatly narrowing the ability
of victims to hold school districts liable for the abusive behavior
of teachers, the Court granted schools an immunity they do not
deserve as a matter of law or public policy.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the court also rejected the Department of
Education's reasonable interpretation of Title IX, under which a
school district could be found liable, regardless of whether
officials knew of the misconduct, if a teacher had misused his
position of authority in imposing the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new ruling, a harassment victim may not recover
damages from a school district absent a showing that a school
official with power to intervene had ``actual notice'' of the abuse
and, acting with ``deliberate indifference,'' failed to stop it.
The majority opinion, by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, with
concurrence from Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justices
Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and Anthony Kennedy, held that
lack of a formal school policy against harassment or any system for
reporting complaints should not be deemed evidence of ``deliberate
indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   The four dissenters _ Justices John Paul Stevens, David Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer _ rightly scored the
majority's disingenuous reading of Title IX's legislative history
and the harmful impact their stringent liability standard will have
in insulating school districts from nearly all harassment suits. As
Stevens said in his minority opinion, the court put ``protection of
the school district's purse above the protection of immature high
school students.''
</P>
<P>
   It is little solace that the victim is still free to sue the
district for damages under state laws and the individual teacher
for damages under Federal and state laws. Many states lack a remedy
for this kind of serious sexual harassment, and going after a
teacher with little ability to pay ignores the responsibility of
schools for preventing abuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
