<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST ON FAA WATCH LIST OVER SAFETY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Federal regulators have stepped up scrutiny of America
West Airlines in the wake of safety concerns raised by the
carrier's mechanics and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 9 memo to Federal Aviation Administration inspectors
in cities served by America West, an FAA supervisor in Phoenix said
the Tempe carrier had been placed on ``Troubled Air Carrier''
status.
</P>
<P>
   America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack described the FAA's action
as routine for carriers in protracted labor negotiations, and said
America West is cooperating. She added that ``no significant
maintenance or operating problems have been discovered as a result
of these additional inspections.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA memo suggested six areas for increased surveillance,
from in-flight procedures to compliance with critical maintenance
regulations. It was written by Ronald Rosenhahn, supervisor for the
America West Certificate Management Unit of the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The memo didn't cite the reasons for the FAA's increased
vigilance, but an FAA spokesman said it stemmed from complaints
called into the FAA's aviation safety hotline by America West
flight attendants and mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   He said the calls suggested labor unrest, which, along with
airline financial troubles, always trigger increased FAA scrutiny.
America West's flight attendants and mechanics are both in union
contract negotiations that have dragged on and now involve a
mediator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that we do when we get an indication that a
carrier is under strain, and because of the strain there might be
some temptation to skip some of things they're supposed to do,''
said Mitch Barker, public affairs specialist in the FAA's Seattle
office.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said Northwest Airlines, which also is involved in union
negotiations, is also on the FAA's watch list, the new name for
Troubled Air Carrier status. He said the latter term was used in
error on the memo about America West.
</P>
<P>
   The specific areas on the suggested surveillance list include:
</P>
<P>
   Minimum equipment list program compliance. The list includes
critical instruments that must be operating correctly or the plane
can't leave the gate, such as the radio used to communicate with
air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   _Ramp inspections, with emphasis on indications of airplane
corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   _Performance of scheduled and unscheduled maintenance done by
the company and outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
   _Dispatch paperwork, emphasizing appropriate weather
information.
</P>
<P>
   _En route flight procedures, emphasizing checklist procedures.
</P>
<P>
   _In-flight/flight attendant training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said America West's watch list status is open ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surveillance will continue at an increased level until we
don't feel it needs to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the inspectors find problems, fines could be levied. The
worst-case scenario is that major problems are uncovered and the
airline's certificate, or operating permit, would be suspended.
Last year, Iowa-based Great Lakes Aviation, a commuter airline, was
ordered to suspend service and agreed to pay $1 million in
penalties for sloppy maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   While not familiar with the details, one aviation expert is
unfazed by America West's watch list status. Arnold Barnett, a
professor of statistics at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology who specializes in safety issues, said ``there's no end
to (such) lists, in a certain way.'' He said he flies America West
often from Boston to the West Coast and wouldn't hesitate ``for a
moment'' to do so today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an airline that has done a lot of things very well,''
he said, citing its accident-free record and rapid expansion after
the industry deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   While this is the first time America West has been on the FAA's
troubled carrier/watch list, regulators have criticized the company
in the past for lax maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   During a major inspection two years ago, the FAA found serious
maintenance errors which it blamed on the company's decision, in
late 1995, to lay off 500 mechanics and transfer its heavy aircraft
maintenance to Tramco, a contractor in Everett, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA found, among other things, that more and more repairs
were being deferred to keep planes flying. An FAA official said the
airline's cost-cutting efforts had gone too far. Overall, however,
it said the carrier was safe.
</P>
<P>
   America West responded by saying it would hire dozens of
mechanics and increase the number of internal auditors who make
sure that paperwork is completed properly and that outside vendors
are properly qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Since then America West mechanics and their union, the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, have criticized the work
done by outside mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, on the eve of America West's annual shareholders
meeting, the union raised concerns about flight safety and said
mechanics were going to follow the maintenance book to the letter
even if it meant flight delays. America West officials dismissed
the move as a negotiating tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very concerned about the maintenance and the
outsourcing at America West ever since December of 1996,'' said
Patrick Lacefield, a Teamsters spokesman in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our folks have seen a lot of the effects of the outsourcing in
terms of planes that come in and are supposed to be fixed and
aren't fixed and have to be fixed again.''
</P>
<P>
   The 350 remaining mechanics want America West to rehire the
mechanics it fired, he said.
</P>
<P>
   America West quietly terminated its maintenance contract with
Tramco in March. The work is now being done in Indianapolis by
United Airlines. The airline also uses other contractors, including
Air Canada, to service its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Association of Flight Attendants, which
represents America West's 2,100 flight attendants, could not be
reached for comment. The negotiating committee is meeting in
Atlanta this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at 444-8617 or
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
