</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CONSTRUCT-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLEANING UP CONSTRUCTION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 23:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has moved with impressive success against
organized crime in industries that few experts thought could be
cleaned up. He now wants to eliminate bribery, shakedowns, and
bid-rigging in New York City's construction industry by setting up
a powerful new commission to deny licenses to unworthy companies.
This is a noble objective, but his task may be much more difficult
than his earlier challenges to the Fulton Fish Market and the
commercial garbage haulers.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is going after a politically well-connected industry.
Hardly any elected official in the city has not received some form
of campaign contribution from builders, developers and contractors.
It does not help his prospects that he is currently engaged in a
political war with the City Council Speaker, Peter Vallone. Vallone
has helped the mayor in earlier anti-corruption efforts, and the
mayor needs to enlist his leadership in this new effort.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's proposal deserves a careful, nonpartisan hearing.
Recent investigations by the Manhattan district attorney, Robert
Morgenthau, have turned up mob involvement in office building
management and resulted in successful prosecutions. Mob involvement
should of course be the primary target, but the commission would
also perform a valuable service by reshaping the culture of an
industry in which bribes and payoffs are accepted business
practices. These practices have helped drive New York City
construction costs to a level far higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The trick will be to carry out both tasks without a cumbersome
and expensive new bureaucracy. The mayor proposes to start with
only the biggest 400 to 500 companies, but much of the problem lies
with myriad subcontractors less easy to investigate. The council
should certainly feel free to recommend improvements to minimize
the burdens on the industry and avoid damage to legitimate
contractors. It may also wish to look at the government's role, in
part because bribery of city inspectors is thought to be a major
part of the problem, and in part because the city's building codes
are so complicated. But in broad terms, Giuliani's proposal makes
very good sense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980622.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-TRIAL-ART-624&AMP;A     06-22 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-TRIAL-ART-624&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR POINTS TO WORDS BY ACCUSED IN KILLING OF COSBY'S SON 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 (fb) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ Mikail Markhasev's own words prove he
shot and killed Ennis Cosby as Cosby fixed a flat tire in the inky
January night, just off a Los Angeles freeway, a prosecutor said
Monday in the opening statements of Markhasev's murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, deputy district attorney Anne Ingalls, said
Markhasev described the Cosby killing as a ``robbery gone bad'' in
letters from jail to another imprisoned friend, mixing English and
Spanish slang. Ingalls said that Markhasev also told a friend while
he was trying to recover a gun from the woods that he had shot a
black man: ``It's all over the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Those statements will be buttressed by the testimony of two
friends who were with Markhasev around the time of the killing,
friends who saw him looking for news of the crime on television
later that day and another friend who said Markhasev asked him for
help in recovering the gun, Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   But in his own statement, Henry J. Hall, a defense lawyer, said
his client was not even at the scene of the crime when Cosby was
killed and that the murder was instead committed by one of the
prosecution's chief witnesses, Eli Zakaria. Hall, a public
defender, said the letters implicating Markhasev had been
fabricated, and he attacked the credibility of witnesses who would
testify against his client.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of six men and six women were given two portraits of
Markhasev: a man who shot Cosby during a robbery and left him lying
on the road, or an innocent Ukrainian immigrant, then 18, offered
up by questionable witnesses seeking financial gain or to conceal
their own involvement in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev faces a possible life sentence without parole if he is
found guilty of killing Cosby on Jan. 16, 1997, not far from the
courtroom. A weathered white cross and shaded flowers still mark
the site where Cosby, the son of the entertainer Bill Cosby, was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby's name was mentioned once Monday morning, when Hall
asked the jury not to let the case ``be infected by the celebrity
of the victim's father.''
</P>
<P>
   Two rows of friends and family members of the victim sat in
court, but Bill Cosby was not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis Cosby, a 27-year-old graduate student at Columbia
University Teachers College in New York, was visiting Los Angeles
on a break, the prosecution said. He was on his way to meet a woman
around 1:15 a.m. in his mother's Mercedes-Benz, when he pulled over
because of a flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev had been partying at a Bel Air home with his friends,
Eli Zakaria and Sara Peters, Ingalls said, before they passed
Cosby. Zakaria asked him: ``Hey are you OK?'' and Cosby replied:
``Yeah. Everything's cool,'' Ms. Ingalls said, and then the three
went to a nearby pay telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby had called his friend, Stephanie Crane, on a cellular
telephone, and asked her to come and shine her headlights on his
car while he changed the tire, Ingalls said. As Crane sat in her
Jaguar, the defendant appeared at her window and said: ``Open the
door or I'll shoot,'' Ingalls said. Crane drove away quickly, then
turned around because she had left Cosby behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that time, the defendant went over to Ennis, demanded his
money, and when Ennis wasn't quick enough, shot him once at close
range in the temple, killing him instantly,'' Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the prosecution said, two associates, Chris So
and Michael Chang, went with Markhasev to a wooded area to try to
recover the gun and it was then that he implied he had killed
Cosby. So called The National Enquirer to claim a $1,000 reward for
information about the slaying. When the police came to his home, he
took them to the same wooded area, where they found the gun. The
prosecution said that tests showed the gun was the murder weapon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perhaps to counter defense attacks, Ingalls acknowledged that
the prosecution witnesses, Zakaria and Chang, are convicted felons
currently serving prison sentences. She acknowledged that So was
motivated by a financial reward. Also, the prosecution
acknowledged, Crane failed to pick out Markhasev in a police lineup
after his arrest nearly two months after Cosby's death.
</P>
<P>
   Hall referred to So as just one of the ``bottom-dwelling
witnesses in this case.'' So told two different stories when he
called the Enquirer, Hall said. He said the jailhouse letters that
were turned over by an informant now serving time for bank robbery
in a federal prison in Texas, were in two different types of
handwriting and contained inaccuracies that someone who knew the
case would not mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Hall showed the jury a composite sketch drawn from Ms. Crane's
description of the killer, along with a photograph of Zakaria,
saying the long nose and rounded chin looked more like the
government witness than the defendant. And he said that there was a
45-minute gap between the departure of Markhasev from the Bel Air
home with Zakaria and Peters and the killing. He said that
Markhasev was being dropped off at home during the slaying. Zakaria
and Peters returned to the Bel Air home for drugs, he said, and
they are the only ones who know who killed Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen of the jury when you get to the end of
this case, the evidence will show you beyond any doubt that the
real person who did this killing was Eli Zakaria,'' Hall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
