<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH STOCKS RISE WHILE DOW RALLY FIZZLES  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 50-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average
evaporated in the last 30 minutes of trading Monday, pushing the
gauge lower and extending its losses for a third consecutive
session.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares, however, ignored the Dow's decline and
continued to rise. The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index,
which advanced 0.5 percent on Friday, rose 1.4 percent Monday.
Intel, Microsoft, Dell and Cisco led the advance.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts largely attributed the Dow's reversal Monday to a
computer-generated sell program that stripped 44.09 points off the
Dow late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the effects of computer-generated programs was
positive Monday, as such programs added 6.73 points to the Dow and
2.25 points to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, said Jim Bohart, an
official with Birinyi Associates, a stock market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's 100-point selloff of the Dow, stocks traded
higher throughout much of the day Monday, with prices buoyed by a
temporary abatement of concern about Asia's economic crisis and new
round of merger news.
</P>
<P>
   Some buyers viewed Berkshire Hathway's planned $21.7 billion
purchase of General Re Corp. and the educational software maker
Learning Co.'s offer of $420 million in stock for Broderbund
Software as signs that some investors still see value in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Both offers valued the stocks at prices higher than their recent
closing price before the announcement of the deals.
</P>
<P>
   In taking stocks higher during the day, investors were scooping
up shares that had fallen sharply recently, such as International
Business Machines. The computer maker, which fell 10 points last
week, was the leading gainer among Dow stocks Monday. It closed at
108[, up 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow ended down 1.74 points at 8,711.13. Procter &AMP; Gamble,
American Express and Merck were the leading decliners.
</P>
<P>
   Moves last week by the United States and Japan to sell dollars
to lift the sagging yen stemmed further declines in stocks, said
Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at Cowen &AMP; Co. The
sales were viewed as an effort to curb further erosion in the
Japanese currency. If the yen continued to fall, many investors
feared its weakness could amplify the Asian economic crisis and its
impact on American companies which do business in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market feels it's bought some time,'' Pradilla said.
``Ultimately it may not change things, but it takes the idea that
there is a financial crisis off the front burner and puts it on to
the back burner'' for a while, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index inched up 2.59 points, to
1,103.24. The Nasdaq composite index rose 24.53 points, after a
36.24-point gain last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a feeling that maybe some of them were oversold,''
Robert Basel, a trader at Salomon Smith Barney, said of the buying
rage for technology shares. ``There was really no fundamental
news.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the bellwether technology shares,
Internet-related companies were beneficiaries of Monday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   The bookseller Amazon.com rose 5 9/16 points, to 81], amid news
that Bertelsmann AG had purchased a stake in Nuvomedia. The
fledgling company, founded last year, is developing technology that
allows people to download books over the Internet. Barnes &AMP; Noble,
an Amazon.com competitor, also owns a stake in the company. Some
analysts are skeptical that reading books on an electronic device,
like the one being developed by Nuvomedia, will become popular.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet-related shares also rose. Yahoo rose 10 5/16
points, to 139 9/16, and Earthlink Network rose 6 points, to 72.
America Online and Lycos also closed higher.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts warned that investors might be too
enthusiastic about the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon.com is not going to make money for another couple of
years,'' said Warren Epstein, head trader at Richard Rosenblatt &AMP;
Co. in New York. ``But the company is valued at more than $4
billion and Barnes &AMP; Noble is valued at $2 billion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrationality sometimes goes a little farther than anybody
thinks it will. I'd be surprised if all of the companies were
thriving in five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein pointed to Spyglass, which traded as high as 55 in
January 1996. The stock closed Monday at 10 15/16, up 1/16 point.
The company, which went public in June 1995, is an Internet
software manufacturer that created one of the first World Wide Web
browsers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
