<HEADER>
A1399 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JESSICA-LANGE-IN-COUS     06-22 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSICA-LANGE-IN-COUSIN-BETTE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSICA LANGE GOES PERIOD WITH A VENGEANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jessica Lange with Elisabeth Shue in a
scene from ``Cousin Bette.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Jessica Lange's laugh is a throaty, sexy chuckle, informal,
inviting _ and exactly what you won't catch her doing in ``Cousin
Bette,'' her latest film, based on Honore Balzac's classic novel.
 &HT;    ``I've always liked to play characters that can let their
emotions explode on screen,'' she says, ``but Cousin Bette is the
kind of woman who, although full of tremendous passion, doesn't
show it.
 &HT;    ``She's also living in 19th-century France, where women weren't
encouraged to be demonstrative,'' Lange adds, ``so I had to be very
careful not to use my hands too much, which is a very natural thing
for me to do.''
 &HT;    The 49-year-old actress still radiates the sensual beauty that
made her a star as a model and a sex symbol in such early films as
``King Kong'' (1976) and ``The Postman Always Rings Twice'' (1981).
But, again, you'll see little of that sexiness in ``Cousin Bette,''
where her character is a bitter, vindictive woman seeking revenge
on her own family and friends.
 &HT;    ``I got this very dark wig that fit like a helmet,'' she says,
``because Balzac had referred to Bette as a `black crow.' I skipped
makeup, except something they put on to make my skin look sallow,
and I let my eyebrows grow in. Everything we did was designed to
make me look worse.''
 &HT;    Laughing, Lange admits that watching the film wasn't easy.
 &HT;    ``As an actress, I still have tremendous vanity,'' she says.
``If my face is going to be up there 40 feet wide or whatever, I
would love it to look good. Sometimes I would close my eyes when we
were watching the dailies. But I knew that we shouldn't compromise
and do some glamorous Hollywood version of `Cousin Bette.'
 &HT;    ``There was something about changing my appearance that appealed
to me more and more,'' she continues. ``It's the idea of wearing a
disguise, and getting further and further away from the person you
really are and how you really look. I even considered wearing a
prosthetic nose for the role, but it would have taken too much time
in makeup to put it on.''
 &HT;    Many actresses, particularly those who have reached an age at
which Hollywood traditionally views actresses as ``too old,'' might
have hesitated to take so unglamorous a role. Not Lange, she says.
 &HT;    ``I wanted the challenge of playing Cousin Bette,'' she says.
``I really wanted to step outside of the work that's easy for me to
do, these kind of big, emotional women who go on big emotional
journeys. Bette was the antithesis of that. It was interesting to
repress so much and still be able to show what was going on inside
her.
 &HT;    ``I first read the novel when I was 21,'' she recalls. ``I loved
it, and I really can't tell you why, but it stuck in my mind. At
the time, I hadn't even considered acting a career. So all these
years later, when they came to me and asked to me play Cousin
Bette, it seemed like a very natural thing to do.''
 &HT;    ``Cousin Bette,'' in which Tony Award winner Des McAnuff _ who
staged ``The Who's Tommy'' and ``Big River'' _ makes his big-screen
directing debut, also stars Elisabeth Shue as a courtesan who sings
and dances at the Folies Bergere and Australian hunk Aden Young as
the lusty artist who melts Bette's heart.
 &HT;    ``If I could put a neon sign above the title of this film,''
Lange says, ``It would be, `This is not another Jane Austen clone!'
 &HT;    ```Cousin Bette' is a little dirty and a little naughty,'' she
says. ``It's what Balzac did best _ lampooning all the human
foibles, all of our worst qualities. It's not a 19th-century
costume drama, it's a deliciously farcical black comedy.''
 &HT;    As she faces the half-century mark, Lange is still challenging
herself. She is considering a part in the upcoming film version of
Shakespeare's ``Titus Andronicus,'' with Anthony Hopkins in the
title role, and early next year will star in a London stage revival
of Eugene O'Neill's ``Long Day's Journey Into Night.''
 &HT;    Prestigious roles in Shakespeare and O'Neill reflect a long
life's journey from Lange's critically trashed debut in Dino Di
Laurentiis' much-maligned remake of ``King Kong.'' The film almost
ended her career before it had begun, but Lange insists that she
has no regrets.
 &HT;    ``It was really a lark for me at the time,'' she recalls. ``I
was studying acting and living in the Village, working part-time as
a waitress. When they asked me to audition I thought, `Great.' When
I got the part I didn't think of it as a momentous career move, I
just took it as a kind of a goof.
 &HT;    ``It turned out to be sort of an initiation by fire to the
business of filmmaking,'' she admits, ``but I never felt it was the
wrong thing to do.''
 &HT;    Looking ahead, Lange faces new obstacles, particularly as an
``aging'' leading lady.
 &HT;    ``Certainly, the powers that be seem to think that sexuality has
something to do with age or lack of it,'' she concedes. ``It's not
a problem for older actors _ you get Jack Nicholson with Helen Hunt
or Nick Nolte with Julia Roberts. The guys don't seem to be
embarrassed by playing love scenes with women who are 20 years
younger than they are. I find all of it rather funny.''
 &HT;    Lange has participated in some of Hollywood's hottest sex
scenes, including a controversially explicit kitchen-table bout
with Jack Nicholson in ``The Postman Always Rings Twice.''
 &HT;    ``You hear actors complaining a lot,'' she says with a smile.
``They're always saying, `Ohhh, love scenes, I hate them.' I've
never felt that way.
 &HT;    ``I suppose they could be hateful if you hated the person you
were doing them with,'' she admits. ``But I must say, in `Rob Roy'
(1995), for instance, it wasn't hard to imagine being in love with
Liam Neeson. It's not like you have to push yourself to the limits
of your craft to make it believable.''
 &HT;    Offscreen, Lange has lived with playwright Sam Shepard for many
years. They have two children, 12-year-old Hannah and 10-year-old
Walker, plus Alexandra, Lange's teen-age daughter from an earlier
relationship with dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov. Home is a farm in
Stillwater, Minn., the state where Lange grew up.
 &HT;    Combining her acting career with her desire to be a strong,
supportive mother had been difficult, Lange says.
 &HT;    ``My own mother was a model parent,'' she says. ``She had
incredible patience and sweetness. I fall short in those areas
because I have a temper. I really have to work at not letting it
flare up.''
 &HT;    That's not hard to believe for anyone who's seen any of Lange's
signature roles as troubled, emotionally volatile women _ as a
misunderstood and psychologically troubled actress in ``Frances''
(1982), for which she received an Academy Award, for example, or
her second Oscar-winner as an unstable military wife in ``Blue
Sky'' (1994). On stage, she scored a hit as Tennessee Williams'
deranged Blanche Dubois in ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' on Broadway
in 1995.
 &HT;    Lange cheerfully acknowledges that unsettled characters are her
specialty.
 &HT;    ``My daughter Hannah said to me, `Mom, do you think playing all
those crazy women is going to make you crazy?''' Lange recalls,
laughing.
 &HT;    ``I said, `I think it's just the opposite. Playing all those
crazy women lets me get it all out, so I don't end up being crazy
myself.'
 &HT;    ``I think it's true,'' she says. ``If I weren't an actress, I
think I'd be quite mad.''
 c.1998 Pentacom Productions  
