<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVEN-SODERBERGH-DIRECTS-OUT-OF-SIGHT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVEN SODERBERGH: AN INDIE SUPERSTAR VISITS THE MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Steven Soderbergh directing a scene from
``Out of Sight.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Even by independent-filmmaker standards, Steven Soderbergh's
career output is eclectic in the extreme.
 &HT;    It started with ``Sex, Lies and Videotape'' (1989), the
surprise-hit drama/comedy/whatever that took the Sundance Film
Festival by storm and changed the independent-film world forever.
 &HT;    He followed that with ``Kafka'' (1991), a shadowy semibiography
starring Jeremy Irons as the tormented Czech writer.
 &HT;    Then came the critically praised ``King of the Hill'' (1993), an
offbeat, Depression-era family drama.
 &HT;    Then ``The Underneath'' (1994), a film-noir-inspired thriller.
Then ``Schizopolis'' (1997), a black comedy in which Soderbergh and
his ex-wife, actress Betsy Brantley, starred as a couple in a
crumbling marriage. And ``Gray's Anatomy'' (1997), a filmed version
of a Spalding Gray monologue.
 &HT;    All of them weird, many of them wonderful and none of them
obvious precursors of ``Out of Sight,'' opening June 26. With a
comparatively gargantuan budget of $49 million and a cast of big
names _ George Clooney, Jennifer Lopez, Ving Rhames, Dennis Farina,
Don Cheadle, Steve Zahn, Albert Brooks _ this adaptation of Elmore
Leonard's novel is unapologetically mainstream.
 &HT;    ``It was emotional, but not externally emotional, which is
territory I feel comfortable with,'' the straight-talking
Soderbergh says during a telephone conversation from a Los Angeles
hotel. ``At the same time, it was very clearly a character-driven
piece that required a little bit of gimmickry to keep it
interesting.
 &HT;    ``I thought I knew what the gimmickry should be,'' he says.
``When I read it, I saw the movie in my head and felt like I knew
what to do with it. I felt that, for better or worse, I had a take
on the material. I'm seldom right, but I'm rarely in doubt.
 &HT;    ``Also, even though I grew up in a suburban subdivision and
Leonard's world is definitely not a world in which I traveled,
there's a certain ironic tone that I understood and could
recognize,'' the director adds. ``That was enough to carry me
through the rest of it.''
 &HT;    Soderbergh professes disinterest in questions of commercial vs.
art-house films, mainstream vs. independent or even accessible vs.
personal.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what all of those terms mean, and I never have,''
Soderbergh says. ``Everyone applies them to me, but I don't know
what relevance they have anymore.
 &HT;    ``Every movie I've made I made because it interested me at the
time,'' he says. ``In terms of being commercial, I don't know how
to make a movie more accessible, more palatable than `King of the
Hill.'
 &HT;    ``That film has a classic American narrative,'' the director
says. ``Nobody went to see it, and there was nothing arty or
esoteric about it.
 &HT;    ``It's not like I'm off in some weird limbo saying commercial
films are for boobs,'' he adds with a laugh. ``I will say that,
coming off `Schizopolis' and `Gray's Anatomy,' two ultra-low-budget
movies, `Out of Sight' seemed pretty appealing.''
 &HT;    Clooney and Lopez are probably the highest-profile stars he's
worked with, but Soderbergh has nothing but praise for the two.
They came in prepared and energetic, he says, an attitude that made
his task easier.
 &HT;    ``I got the film I wanted,'' Soderbergh says. ``Whether or not
that translates into people liking it or commercial success, I have
no idea.
 &HT;    ``I hope it does well, but I would always rather be happy with a
movie than just have it perform at the box office,'' he says. ``The
movie itself is the thing that sits there and is a constant.
 &HT;    ``The rest of it _ critical and commercial response _ is always
shifting one way or another,'' the director adds. ``I can't control
what movies open the same weekend that mine do.
 &HT;    ``All I can do is try is make my films as good as they can be.''
 &HT;    It's been nearly a decade since Soderbergh arrived on the scene
from Baton Rouge, La., with ``Sex, Lies and Videotape,'' a timely,
erotic drama widely credited for launching the indie-film craze.
Much has been written about Soderbergh's output since then, as
observers wondered aloud if the director, now 35, lived up to
expectations.
 &HT;    ``I didn't have any expectations,'' Soderbergh says dryly.
``It's astonishing to me that this would be a topic of conversation
with anyone other than my parents.
 &HT;    ``I like the range of movies I've done,'' he says. ``I think
it's an eclectic group. Some of them work, some of them don't, but
they're all attempts at something.
 &HT;    ``They all feel like they were made by an individual and not by
a committee. There's nothing embarrassing about that.''
 &HT;    In looking back at his own films, Soderbergh is frank in
assessing his own successes and failures.
 &HT;    ```Sex, Lies' works on its own term,'' he says. ``People seem to
like `King of the Hill,' and it works pretty well, as does `Gray's
Anatomy.'
 &HT;    ```Kafka' is a bit of a mess, but an interesting mess,'' he
admits. ```The Underneath' was tough. I felt I blew it _ at its
heart, it's flawed in a way that I was never going to fix.''
 &HT;    Most of the few people who saw it felt the same way about
``Schizopolis,'' a black comedy which many found self-indulgent,
with its parallels to the real-life breakup of Soderbergh and
Brantley.
 &HT;    It was, Soderbergh explains, the work of a filmmaker in personal
and professional turmoil.
 &HT;    ``I look back on it fondly because it meant a lot to me
creatively,'' he says. ``It was the shedding of a skin that I think
was beginning to suffocate me.
 &HT;    ``If the movie is out of control and incoherent, that's because
I felt that I was in danger of being too controlled, too coherent
and becoming too much of a formalist,'' he adds. ```Schizopolis'
was, to me, a necessary step I had to take to get to `Gray's
Anatomy' and `Out of Sight.'
 &HT;    ``Hollywood is a hard place in which to play it out,''
Soderbergh says, ``but a filmmaker has to have these mistakes. You
have to go down some blind alleys.
 &HT;    ``Some people don't understand that, and the business just
doesn't support it,'' Soderbergh says glumly. ``But it's necessary
if a filmmaker is going to move and not stagnate.''
 &HT;    By his own admission not the ``vacationing type,'' Soderbergh is
actively seeking his next project. It may be something he scripts
himself, he adds, or it may not.
 &HT;    ``I've got to find something before June 26, when `Out of Sight'
opens,'' he says with an easy laugh. ``I've got to build the bridge
in front of me before they burn the one behind me.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
