<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      06-22 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the week. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parole Rights
</P>
<P>
   In another 5-4 decision, the court ruled that illegally seized
evidence, which would be barred by the exclusionary rule from use
by the prosecution at a criminal trial, can be used in parole
revocation hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, in an opinion by Thomas, overturned a ruling by
the Supreme Court of Pennsylvania. The case involved a search by
parole officers of the home of a paroled murderer, who was barred
from owning any weapons. The officers found guns and other weapons,
and they began parole revocation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion in the case, Pennsylvania Board of Probation vs.
Scott, No. 97-581, Thomas said that the costs of the exclusionary
rule were always high, unjustifiably so in the parole context.
``The costs of allowing a parolee to avoid the consequences of his
violation are compounded by the fact that parolees (particularly
those who have already committed parole violations) are more likely
to commit future criminal offenses than are average citizens,''
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist and O'Connor, Scalia and Kennedy joined the opinion.
Stevens, Souter, Ginsburg and Breyer dissented. ``If the police
need the deterrence of an exclusionary rule to offset the
temptations to forget the Fourth Amendment, parole officers need it
quite as much,'' Souter said, referring to the constitutional
prohibition against unreasonable searches.
</P>
<P>
   Class-Action Settlements
</P>
<P>
   Accepting a case for its next term, the court agreed to revisit
an issue it last dealt with a year ago when it rejected a huge
class-action settlement that had purported to resolve the liability
of 20 former asbestos manufacturers to workers who had been exposed
to the deadly substance but who had not yet become ill. In last
year's case, Amchem Products vs. Windsor, the justices said the
settlement unfairly limited the ability of future victims to get
redress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time it decided that case, which was from the
federal appeals court in Philadelphia, the court summarily vacated
another appeals court's decision that had upheld a similar
settlement between a different asbestos maker, Fibreboard Corp.,
now a subsidiary of Owens Corning Fibreglass, and a different group
of plaintiffs. The justices told the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in New Orleans, to study the Fibreboard case again in
light of the principles established in the Supreme Court's Amchem
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In a cursory five-paragraph opinion, adopted by a 2-1 vote, the
5th Circuit reinstated its earlier opinion, finding that
differences in the way the Fibreboard settlement was structured
made the Supreme Court's ruling disapproving the other settlement
irrelevant. The appeal the Supreme Court accepted Monday, Ortiz vs.
Fibreboard Corp., No. 97-1704, argued that the earlier ruling was
directly relevant and made the Fibreboard settlement insupportable.
``Some people just can't take a hint,'' Laurence Tribe of Harvard
Law School, the lawyer representing the challengers, said in an
unusually breezy introduction to his successful petition seeking
court review.
</P>
<P>
   Disabled Prisoners
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the court turned down an appeal by California
that challenged Congress' constitutional authority to bring
disabled state prison inmates within the protection of the
Americans With Disabilities Act. Last week, the Supreme Court ruled
that the act did apply to state prisoners as a matter of statutory
interpretation, but did not address the constitutional issue raised
by this case, Wilson vs. Armstrong, No. 97-686.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
