<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1401 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-A-BOOMING-BIOGRAPHY-S     06-22 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A-BOOMING-BIOGRAPHY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING LIFE STORIES: THE BOOM IN `BIOGRAPHY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a black-and-white slide of Harry Houdini in a scene from
``Biography.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who tune in A&AMP;E's popular program ``Biography'' each
night may not know who they're getting, but they know what to
expect: a nonjudgmental, hour-long portrait of a prominent person.
</P>
<P>
   There is no protocol to the selection _ with more than 500
episodes of ``Biography'' aired thus far, the subject range has
veered from figures legendary _ such as Jesus, Attila the Hun and
Nostradamus _ to offbeat _ Houdini, Santa Claus and Benedict
Arnold. The famous _ Amelia Earhart, W.C. Fields, Bing Crosby _
have mingled with the notorious _ Adolf Hitler, Howard Stern, John
Gotti. Each night, a new life unfurls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biography's'' succinct formula has also made it a phenomenon
in television-industry circles. In the United States, it's far and
away A&AMP;E's top-rated show. In the past few years, it's even
outranked CNN's ``Larry King Live'' in the ratings, a feat all the
more impressive when you realize that ``Biography'' only went from
once-a-week to nightly format in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It took time for ``Biography'' to grow in the United States.
However, according to its executive producer, Michael Cascio, the
show became an immediate hit in an unlikely market: Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians just got the show faster,'' Cascio says. ``We were
embraced more quickly by the Canadian audience, because I think
they know documentaries better than the U.S. audience. And we hear
disproportionately from our Canadian viewers, because they're also
pretty knowledgeable about what works and what doesn't. They love
the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the television program itself, which now airs seven days
a week, the franchise also includes a glossy monthly magazine with
a circulation of 350,000 and a best-selling video series.
</P>
<P>
   The show's popularity has also resulted in a `Saturday Night
Live' skit in which affable host Jack Perkins, who shares
weeknight-host duties with Peter Graves, was portrayed as a
scotch-tippling blowhard. Maybe not the best advertisement _
Perkins himself was reportedly not amused _ but it demonstrates
that the show is now part of popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night,'' Cascio says, ```Biography' was the answer
in final `Jeopardy.' A couple of years ago, we were happy if
somebody just mentioned to us they'd seen the show. Now we're a
parody on `Saturday Night Live.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In the most recent U.S. TV Guide,'' he adds, ``Julia Roberts
said her favorite show is `Biography.' And we're still, like,
`Somebody noticed!'''
</P>
<P>
   As with most quality television series, a lot of hard work goes
on behind the scenes on ``Biography.'' With the addition of the
weekend versions, ``Biography This Week'' and ``Biography for
Kids,'' the series demands a hefty 130 episodes a year.
</P>
<P>
   To feed the beast, A&AMP;E employs a network of nearly 500
producers, writers, researchers, editors and various technical
staff to assemble the shows. At any given time, there are more than
100 in production, and that means various stages of research,
preproduction or postproduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much that goes into these things,'' Cascio says.
``Much of the time is spent assembling the visuals, but research
takes equal status: We're very rigorous and we source everything.
We're not going to say J. Edgar Hoover wore a dress unless we're
really convinced that is a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, it takes a few months to properly construct a
``Biography,'' but there are also those occasions when Cascio and
his staff have to move fast, particularly when it comes to
``Biography This Week,'' which profiles that week's biggest
newsmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come in Monday and it's like: Who is it this week?,''
Cascio says. ``And it's not just when someone dies. We did Kenneth
Starr, the Unabomber ... Every week we have to move fast. It gives
us what we feel like is a bit of an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Another clever ``Biography'' innovation has been the
well-promoted Theme Weeks, in which five personalities are linked
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps reinforce the idea we're on five days a week,'' says
Cascio, who created the concept. ``Now it's a game with us to come
up with new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Theme Weeks in recent memory have included ``Great Monsters'' _
Boris Karloff, Bela Lugosi, Lon Chaney Jr. _ ``Poor Little Rich
Girls'' _ Christina Onassis, Camilla Parker Bowles, Doris Duke _
and ``Addicted to Fame'' _ Andy Warhol, Tennessee Williams, Truman
Capote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our highest-rated week was `Attention, Shoppers,' which was
about the Woolworths, Marshall Fields and J.C. Penney,'' Cascio
says. ``We ran it during the holiday season, so it tied into what
most viewers were probably doing at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``Biography'' is like public television, except
that there are no pledge-drive breaks. Cascio takes obvious pride
in the fact that he's developed a television series which, while
adhering to a rigid 44-minute format, nevertheless manages to both
enlighten and entertain.
</P>
<P>
   The tough part, of course, is deciding who gets the
``Biography'' treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, some subjects appeal to some people more than
others,'' he says. ``The most satisfying thing for me is when we do
someone like Oscar Levant. He was this neurotic, piano-playing side
character in movies, and he was a favorite of mine, but I thought,
`Who's going to know who he is?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we took a chance, and it did a wonderful rating _ a
terrific rating. Now a lot more people know about Oscar Levant.''
</P>
<P>
   Cascio also takes a measure of pride in the fact that
``Biography for Kids'' is part of the curriculum in school systems
across the United States. And the franchise keeps growing, with
plans for an all-``Biography'' cable channel in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, ``Biography'' has plenty of material.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in no danger of running out of people any time soon,''
Cascio says confidently. ``Look at the people in recent history,
and then of course there's traditional biographies from history.
And then there's revisionist versions of the same people, so ... As
long as there are people, there'll be `Biography.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor of Canadian TV Guide, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
