<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-BLIND-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGHT UNSEEN: SHOPPING BLIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of author Carol Fleischman and her guide
dog, Misty. 
 By CAROL FLEISCHMAN  
 c.1998 The Buffalo News  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever tried to buy a dress you couldn't see?
</P>
<P>
   I have, because I'm blind.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, I used to shop with friends. I stopped doing so
after an incident which showed me that I needed to be more
discriminating about their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Happily bringing home a dress which a friend had helped me
choose, I modeled it for my husband, Don.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fit is great,'' he said, ``but do you like all those huge
fish?''
</P>
<P>
   The dress went back.
</P>
<P>
   Now I rely on Don and my guide dog Misty as my shopping
partners. On a recent visit, we entered the store and made a
beeline for the dress department.
</P>
<P>
   Don saw two or three salespeople scatter, and the aisles
emptied, as if a bomb threat had just come in.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment we were puzzled _ and then I realized that the
threat was about a foot in front of me. I don't blame them,
actually: Once I too was uneasy around large dogs. Although she is
better behaved than most children, I know a 65-pound German
shepherd is imposing.
</P>
<P>
   A brave saleswoman approached us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I help you?'' she said to my husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm looking for a dress,'' I replied _ since I would be
wearing it, not him. ``Maybe something in red or white.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Red or white,'' she said, very slowly and loudly _ though my
hearing is fine. I managed not to fall as Misty jumped back onto my
feet, frightened by the woman's booming voice.
</P>
<P>
   Don was distracted, too. I heard him rustling through hangers on
a nearby rack. I called his name softly to get his attention, but
another man answered my call. What were the chances of two Dons
being in earshot?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great!'' my Don said, holding up a treasure.
</P>
<P>
   I swept my hand over the dress to examine it. It had a neckline
that plunged to the hemline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in good shape _ I walk three miles daily with Misty _ and I
stay current with fashion, but I'm positive this costume would have
looked best on one of the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I chose three dresses to try on. Before I could start
for a dressing room, however, another shopper distracted Misty,
even though the harness sign reads: ``Please do not pet. I'm
working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your dog reminds me of my Max, whom I recently put to sleep,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help being sympathetic. We discussed her loss for 15
minutes, until Don came back. He told me the route to travel to the
dressing room. I commanded Misty: right, left, right and straight
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   We wove our way past several small voices: ``Mom, why is that
dog in the store?'' ``Mom, is that a dog or a wolf?'' And, my
personal favorite, ``But that lady's eyes are open.''
</P>
<P>
   I trust such parents to explain: ``The lady is giving her guide
dog commands. Her dog is a helping dog. They're partners.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder whether this positive message is being communicated,
however _ I once heard an adult say, ``Oh, there's one of those
blind dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other people, though well-intentioned, can interfere with my
effective use of Misty.
</P>
<P>
   Guide dogs are highly trained and very dependable, but
occasionally make potentially dangerous mistakes. On my way through
the aisles, Misty bumped me into a pointed rack, requiring my quick
action. I used a firm tone to correct her, and she flopped to the
ground like a dying actress.
</P>
<P>
   Witnessing this performance, another shopper chastised me for
being cruel. I was shocked. Misty's pride was hurt, but I needed to
point out the error in order to avoid future mistakes. If I did not
discipline her, what would prevent Misty from walking me off a curb
into traffic?
</P>
<P>
   Composing myself, I was delighted by the saleswoman's
suggestion: ``Can I take you to your dressing room?''
</P>
<P>
   I was less delighted when she grabbed me and pushed me ahead
while Misty trailed us on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   I wriggled out of the woman's wrestling hold. Gently pushing her
ahead, I lightly held her elbow in sighted-guide technique _ so
called because the person who sees goes first.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better,'' I said. ``Please put my hand on the door
knob. I'll take it from here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the room, Misty plopped down and sighed with boredom. I
sighed with relief that she was still with me. Once, I was so
preoccupied with trying on clothes that Misty sneaked out beneath
the dressing-room doors. I heard her tags jingling as she left, but
was half-dressed and couldn't retrieve her. Fortunately, Don was
outside the door and snagged her leash.
</P>
<P>
   I modeled the dresses for Don and, feeling numb, bought all
three.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the store, Misty's magnetism, like the Pied Piper,
attracted a toddler who draped himself over her. She remained calm
as he tried to ride her, until his fun was halted by his frantic
mother.
</P>
<P>
   When we returned to our car, I give Misty a treat and lots of
praise. A good day's work deserves a good day's pay _ for both of
us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Carol Fleischman is a Niagara Falls, N.Y.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
