<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYME-DISEASE-SAGA-LIF     06-22 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYME-DISEASE-SAGA-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYME DISEASE: ONE FAMILY'S SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes a 300-word sidebar 
 By ROUL TUNLEY  
 c.1998 Family Circle  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started as an innocent walk in the countryside. It ended as a
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Parrish and her children, 9-year-old Blake, 6-year-old
Chase and 2-year-old Skye, had taken many walks in the rolling
hills around their hometown, Waukesha, Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   But that day in 1992 was especially inviting. It was the first
warm day of spring, and there wasn't a trace of snow. They knew
they might find wild asparagus, so they headed for the tall grass.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in shorts, they pushed their way through the hip-high
sea of green, marveling that they had the place to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to us that people might have been staying
away for a reason,'' Parrish says.
</P>
<P>
   That night Parrish picked a tick from Blake's ear.
</P>
<P>
   A week later the whole family came down with flulike symptoms _
the whole family, that is, except for Parrish's husband Wayne, who
hadn't gone on the walk.
</P>
<P>
   Nagging ill health plagued Parrish and her children all summer.
Then, in September, Chase had a stroke. This was followed by a
second a month later, and then a third.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors were at a loss, and could only suggest that the family
seek a milder climate. And so the Parrishes moved to Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's strokes stopped, but the children continued to have
health problems. Skye would fall down for no apparent reason, and
the boys continued to have flulike symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   One day Parrish found a strange rash on her calf, but by the
time she got to her doctor's office, it had disappeared. She asked
the doctor to test her for Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just laughed at me, saying that everybody thought they had
Lyme disease,'' she recalls. ``If he had only tested me for Lyme
disease, it might have saved us years of agony, to say nothing of
thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But that visit did accomplish something: It convinced Parrish
not to rely on doctors alone. She began spending hours at the
library, poring over medical texts and journals for symptoms that
matched her family's.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day in 1995, Chase had another stroke. Panicked,
Parrish insisted that doctors test him for Lyme disease, refusing
to sign any release forms until the test was done. The results
revealed that Chase did indeed have the disease _ as did the whole
family, according to subsequent testing, except for Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   From her studies Parrish knew that Lyme disease is an infection
caused by a spirochete _ a type of bacteria _ called Borellia
burgdorferi, which is carried by some deer ticks. If diagnosed
early, it is easy to cure with antibiotics. But, left untreated, it
can cause arthritis, eye complications and neurological and
cardiovascular problems.
</P>
<P>
   After AIDS, Lyme disease is the fastest-growing disease in the
United States. In 1995 there were 11,700 reported cases, while in
1996 there were 16,455 _ an increase of 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While her family underwent an ongoing regimen of intravenous
antibiotics, Parrish continued her research. She learned that Dr.
Charles Ray Jones, a noted Connecticut-based pediatrician, was
perhaps the nation's leading authority on the disease. She called,
and he agreed to see her children.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the support of her church _ the congregation raised
$4,000 to pay for the trip _ the Parrishes traveled to Connecticut.
Jones confirmed the diagnosis, and told Parrish about a new
experimental treatment conducted by William Fife, a professor at
Texas A. &AMP; M. Health Science Center in College Station. He
suggested the Parrishes try it.
</P>
<P>
   The month-long treatment requires patients to sit in a
hyperbaric chamber wearing helmets flooded with pure oxygen in an
attempt to destroy the bacteria. Because the procedure is
experimental, there would be no charge, but the plane fare and the
cost of a month's lodging and food would come to $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Help came from an unexpected source: New York Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner, a Tampa native, who saw a television program
on the Parrishes' plight and immediately sent them a check to cover
all costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Parrishes' situation improved somewhat after the
hyperbaric-chamber treatment, but Jones is doubtful that they can
be cured by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symptoms can be alleviated so they can live more normally,''
he says, ``but because the disease got such a big head start,
they'll probably always have some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In the year since the chamber treatment, the children have
continued to rack up a number of hospitalizations. And last winter,
Parrish herself was diagnosed with an inoperable brain aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   For the Parrishes, every new day can usher in a new worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the sun's out one minute, and the rain comes rolling
in the next,'' Wayne Parrish says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parrish fights to maintain a normal family life and tries
to keep everyone's spirits up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we've been able to cope because we don't let things
get us down,'' she says. ``I now have a routine. Whenever we have
to go to the hospital, I call one of the pastors and ask him to
pray. Somehow we get through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people say they live from day to day,'' Parrish
says. ``In our case, we live from hour to hour, never knowing what
might happen next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I'm sure of is that I will rely on prayer and
love and support from friends and family _ for everything,'' she
says. ``Believe me, it works!''
 &UR; SIDEBAR: LYME DISEASE: THE FACTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much remains unknown about Lyme disease, but some facts have
been determined:
</P>
<P>
   + It's a relatively new disease.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme disease was first discovered in the United States in the
1970s, when an unusually high number of children in Lyme, Conn.,
developed rheumatoid arthritis. A mother suspected the outbreak was
not a fluke, and persisted in her campaign until medical experts
confirmed her hunch.
</P>
<P>
   + It's a bacterial infection.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme is an infection caused by a spiral-shaped bacteria called
Borellia burgdorferi, named after the doctor who identified it.
</P>
<P>
   + It's transmitted by ticks.
</P>
<P>
   A bite from a tick that carries the bacteria can pass the
disease on to humans. Dogs, cats and other animals can carry the
tick.
</P>
<P>
   + It's widespread.
</P>
<P>
   All 48 mainland states have reported cases, but Lyme is most
prevalent in the Northeast. The largest number of cases, in
descending order, are found in New York, Connecticut, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   + It's been spreading until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996 the number of cases soared each year. But in 1997
cases were down, perhaps because of drier weather or because people
were learning how to protect themselves from Lyme.
</P>
<P>
   + Stop ticks, stop Lyme.
</P>
<P>
   Ticks prefer wooded or grassland habitats. Shaded lawns can
harbor ticks, although most lawns are too short and dry to support
them.
</P>
<P>
   + It's a summer disease.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-risk months are from May through August.
</P>
<P>
   + It can be hard to spot.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosis is tricky _ early blood tests of Lyme patients often
show up negative. Symptoms are so similar to those of other
ailments, such as flu or arthritis, that anything except a clinical
diagnosis is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The recent discovery of an antibody in the spinal fluid of Lyme
patients, however, may make it easier to detect the disease in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   + It is often curable.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme is treatable and is not contagious. If it is detected
early, antibiotics can practically ensure a cure. When it goes
undetected for months or years, as with the Parrishes, it can be
serious.
</P>
<P>
   + Help is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Two different vaccines for Lyme are currently being tested.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the disease, its diagnosis or its
treatment, call the American Lyme Disease Foundation at (800)
876-LYME.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roul Tunley is a Stockton, N.J.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
