<HEADLINE>
WHEN CHILDREN NEED TO BE ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By AVA L. SIEGLER  
 c.1998 Child magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How come you're sitting alone in your room?'' asks 5-year-old
Rosalie's mom. ``Why don't you go outside and play with your
friends next door?''
</P>
<P>
   As parents, we worry when we see a child by herself. Is she sad?
Is she feeling left out? Does she have trouble making friends? Is
she getting sick?
</P>
<P>
   But being alone from time to time is essential to every child's
well-being. It's only in solitude that a child gets a chance to
think, reflect and discover, to renew and replenish her energies,
and to have time and space for creative work.
</P>
<P>
   Here are ways to think about your child and solitude.
 &UR; BIRTH TO AGE 1 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's so exciting to have a newborn that it's hard to keep your
hands off him. And certainly babies flourish with lots of love and
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But even the tiniest infant needs some time to himself _ time to
watch his mobile move in the sunlight or listen to the sounds in
the street _ so that his growing brain can learn to make sense of
what he sees and hears.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving your little one to his own devices for a few minutes at
a time encourages him to become more curious about the world and
helps build his self-reliance. After all, a baby who can amuse
himself is a baby who is learning to build and rely on his own
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Take your cues from your child. Some babies have an independent
temperament and are happy to watch the world from their infant
seat. Other babies need your constant presence to feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a youngster who can't be without you, try to balance
care and comfort with some moments alone. Even a 3-month-old can
spend five minutes lying on a blanket on the floor while playing
with a squeaky toy or rattle.
</P>
<P>
   And be sure to take advantage of any such time. Use those few
free moments to put your feet up and enjoy some well-earned
solitude of your own.
 &UR; 1 TO 3 YEARS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once your child begins to walk and talk, all kinds of
possibilities open up. Mobility means that she can literally walk
away from you if she wishes, separating herself from your authority
and scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The development of language contributes to this independence: A
toddler's adorable chattering _ ``Where's Bunny? Bunny loves Katie.
Katie is a good girl'' _ helps to fill the space left by these new,
self-initiated separations.
</P>
<P>
   She may express a desire for privacy for the first time, and
start to recognize some of the positive meanings of being alone _
feeling like a big girl, being able to do things by herself _ as
well as the negative connotations, such as feeling left out or
anxious without a grown-up around.
</P>
<P>
   At this age, parents often begin to use time-outs as punishment.
Make sure your child understands that a time-out is not about being
left alone, but rather about taking time to consider what she's
done wrong or to calm down after a tantrum.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a child this age still needs adult supervision.
Create a space near you where your little one can play while you
watch from a distance. Learning to enjoy this kind of semisolitude
will help your child feel comfortable with being completely alone
when she gets older.
</P>
<P>
   Remember also that putting a child in front of a television is
not the same as helping her to play on her own. Television shapes
and directs your youngster's thoughts and feelings, while solitary
play enables her to think and feel whatever she wants.
 &UR; AGES 3 TO 7 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time your child reaches this age, his growing
intellectual awareness, physical competence and maturing judgment
make it possible for him to spend some real time alone _ digging in
the back yard, playing with dinosaurs in his room, building a
hospital with Legos on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   While you still need to keep watch, a young child can generally
be left alone for 10 minutes to 20 minutes before being checked on
by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   At this age, kids experience a lot of intellectual and emotional
growth that is nurtured by solitude. Your child is using his alone
time to figure out how to make decisions without you, how to
exercise his judgment and how to develop his fantasy life.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, your youngster's need for privacy is expanding.
Kids this age want to have their own thoughts and ideas, their own
secrets and their own surprises. Solitude gives your child the
opportunity to shape a separate, independent personality and also
to strengthen his ability to think about and manage the increasing
challenges in his young life.
</P>
<P>
   Try to have your child spend at least 15 minutes a day on his
own in a safe environment, occupying himself without the
participation of his parents or playmates.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the significance of solitude to your child, make an
effort to respect his time alone: ``Dinner's ready, but we can wait
until you finish your puzzle, since you're almost done.''
Similarly, encourage him to respect your solitude: ``Mommy needs to
finish reading this chapter right now _ I'll come and tell you a
story in a few minutes.''
 &UR; AGES 7 TO 10 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time your child is 7 or 8, she's become a thinking
person. Now she can read, write, figure things out and come up with
ideas of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Solitude provides her with further opportunities to learn,
letting her focus on and pursue her own interests and hobbies
without distraction. She can also use time to herself to develop
habits of concentration and study that will serve her well in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But many kids this age have difficulty being alone. With their
developing social skills, making, keeping and spending time with
friends is extremely important. That's one reason why doing
homework alone in one's room can feel like such a tremendous
struggle. In fact, many kids have trouble distinguishing between
being alone and being lonely.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty or 30 minutes of alone time every day provides your
grade-schooler the important opportunity to develop a rich inner
world of thoughts and feelings that will help her be alone, not
lonely.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is such a thing as too much solitude. A child
who retreats to her room for hours at a time, who has difficulty
joining family or friends, or who consistently turns down chances
to be with others may be anxious, depressed or experiencing
academic or social problems.
</P>
<P>
   If you think this might be the case, it's more important than
ever to keep the lines of communication open. Encourage your child
to talk about her feelings and share what's happening at school.
</P>
<P>
   Your youngster's teacher or doctor can provide additional ideas
on how to help, as well as referrals to a specialist if necessary.
 &UR; AGES 10 TO 12 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As your child approaches the teen years, his need for solitude
will increase: He's likely to come home from school and spend most
of his time locked in his room.
</P>
<P>
   This is because the preteen push for independence causes a shift
from the need for attachment to a need for separation. Privacy
takes on important new meanings, including the opportunity to
explore one's thoughts and one's body without the scrutiny or
supervision of others.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, being alone gives your preteen a chance to
explore brand-new sexual feelings without exposure to humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, your preteen will begin to spend time alone
daydreaming and fantasizing about the future. While daydreaming may
seem like a waste of time, it actually helps your youngster
anticipate events and prepare for the complexities of adolescent
life.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, daydreaming _ like so many solitary activities your
child will engage in as he grows _ will help him to meet the
challenges of adult life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ava L. Siegler is a New York-based child psychologist and
free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
