<HEADLINE>
`LICENSED TO KILL': THE UGLINESS AT WORK IN ATTACKS ON
HOMOSEXUALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1977 Arthur Dong, a young San Francisco documentary maker,
narrowly escaped from four teen-agers on a gay-bashing spree. The
boys then got hold of a priest, who they thought was homosexual,
and inflicted severe head injuries. It's not the sort of experience
that is easily forgotten, and 20 years later the memory impelled
Dong, who had since won awards for ``Coming Out Under Fire,'' a
history of homosexuals in the military, to turn his camera on seven
men who have been convicted of assaulting and in some cases killing
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The answers to his question ``Why did you do it?,'' drawn from
police interrogations as well as his own interviews, are not easily
categorized. But in these disjointed and possibly dishonest
responses you can find plenty of ugliness at work.
</P>
<P>
   There are simple predatory attacks on people who are seen as
effeminate, vulnerable and sometimes engaged in risky cruising;
there are murderous outbursts justified by biblical injunctions or
by claims of past abuse by pedophiles; there is an ideological stew
that lumps together homosexuals, flag burners and people who are
against school prayer as fit targets of attack, and there are
intimations that anxiety about sex feeds the impulse toward
violence.
</P>
<P>
   One murderer says that his ``rage came from nowhere.'' A young
man says that being touched by an older man ``made me furious.'' A
fan of Pat Robertson, the television evangelist seen here
denouncing homosexuality, says, ``I was disgusted with these
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   There are expressions of remorse, whether at their crimes or
their long sentences you can decide. Dong uses newsreels and police
videos effectively to document the brutality behind the words.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to sort out candor from make-believe, dissimulation
from rationalization, manipulation from confusion in these
confessions. What are we to make of the super-articulate Minnesota
man, now serving two concurrent life sentences for murder and
attempted murder?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gay preferences,'' he says, ``but I don't really
embrace the gay community, and I'm religiously hostile to them. I
mean, there's a lot of contradictions there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no criticism of ``Licensed to Kill'' to observe that it
offers no certain or novel answers to ``Why did you do it?'' What
the program does reveal is a free-floating hatred that finds its
victims in a group already subject to discrimination. Nothing,
alas, new in that.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `P.O.V.'
</P>
<P>
   Licensed to Kill
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Dong, producer, director, writer and editor; Robert
Shepard, director of photography; Miriam Cutler, original music;
Anjie Rosga, research consultant; Allan Berube, story consultant;
Marc N. Weiss, creator of P.O.V.; Lisa Heller, executive producer
of P.O.V., which is produced by American Documentary Inc.; Ellen
Schneider, executive director; Ward Chamberlin, chief executive
officer. ``Licensed to Kill'' is a co-presentation of the National
Asian-American Telecommunications Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
