<BODY>
 GM TO EXPAND INVESTMENT IN BUILDING TRUCKS IN CHINA 
 (fb) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ General Motors announced on Monday that it
would invest $100 million in a joint venture with a Chinese company
to make pickup trucks and sport-utility vehicles in northeastern
China.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on top of GM's $1.5 billion project to assemble a
Buick-style passenger car in Shanghai, the new plan reflects
optimism about the car market in China.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the current economic crisis in Asia, international
carmakers were expressing doubts about the buying potential in
China and complaining about the bureaucracy, bad distribution and
ever-shifting policies that made the car business here unusually
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   GM has already had a bad experience in Shenyang, the
northeastern Chinese city where a plan to spend $132 million to
make light trucks never really got off the ground. Production
started in 1992 but was suspended in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of abandoning that project GM executives said Monday
that they would increase their investment to $230 million and try
another tack. They have a new partner, First Auto Works, which took
over GM's previous partner, Jinbei Automotive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the market is better, and the automobile agreement is
better,'' Stan Clemens, GM's executive director for truck
development in China, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   According to the terms of the agreement, the new venture will
produce a Chevrolet Blazer sport utility vehicle and a revamped
Chevrolet S-10 crew-cab pickup. Production will start in the year
2000, with 4,000 vehicles assembled in the first year, increasing
to an eventual rate of 50,000 vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
   GM's new partner, First Auto Works, a large state-owned
automaker with 47,000 employees, can produce about 700,000 light
trucks a year. First Auto Works has 19 manufacturing subsidiaries
and operates 10 other businesses as well.
</P>
<P>
   The car market in China looks gloomier now than it did in 1995,
when GM was one of the car companies competing to win the right to
form a partnership with the Shanghai Automotive Industrial Corp.,
one of China's most profitable state-run industries.
</P>
<P>
   A finalist against the Ford Motor Co. and the Toyota Motor
Corp., GM apparently won the deal by offering Chinese car industry
officials what they most wanted: a top-of-the-line model. GM also
promised to manufacture engines and automatic transmissions, to
invest in parts making and to build a design and testing plant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as GM completes its $1.5 billion plant in Shanghai, the
first Buick is expected to roll off the assembly line at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how long it will take for that investment to
pay off. In a country where per capita income is $350 a year, the
Shanghai-made Buick is expected to cost more than $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   GM did not disclose the price for the sport utility vehicle and
pickup trucks to be made in Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
   The sport utility vehicle will likely compete with the Chrysler
Corp.'s Cherokee, made by Beijing Jeep, which was the first
American car-making project in China when it was opened by American
Motors in 1984. A Cherokee now sells for about $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing Jeep sold 26,000 Cherokees in 1996. Chrysler executives
have said they expect to sell only about 13,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales have dropped in part because government ministries have
abandoned a previous practice of routinely ordering Cherokees for
their various ministries and offices. The army and public security
services used to buy 70 percent of the production each year.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign car makers have had it even worse. PSA Peugeot
Citroen abandoned a car-assembly plant in the southern city of
Guangzhou last year, citing irreconcilable differences with its
local partner. Daimler-Benz has gotten bogged down in negotiations
over a plant to build mini-vans in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
   The only foreign car maker that has done well in China is
Volkswagen, which makes a simple, no-frills sedan called the
Santana, adopted as the standard taxi cab in many Chinese cities.
It has captured almost half the sedan market in China, which still
totals fewer than 500,000 vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives have said that they aim to become one of the top
three auto makers in China in the coming years by taking 15 percent
the market. The company now operates 18 ventures in China, counting
its Delphi Automotive Systems and Delco Electronics component
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
