u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-GAYS-475&AMP;ADD-     06-22 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-GAYS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN LOWERS GAY CONSENT AGE, CREATING A SINGLE STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British House of Commons voted overwhelmingly
Monday night to lower the age of consent for homosexuals to 16,
easily overcoming objections from leaders of the Church of England.
</P>
<P>
   The action, much less contentious than a similar move four years
ago reducing the age from 21 to 18, brings the law into line with
that for heterosexuals and brings Britain into conformity with laws
elsewhere in Europe and with a recent decision by the European
Human Rights Commission. The Finnish parliament passed the same
measure last Monday, and Austria, the one remaining country with 18
as the legal age, is scheduled to follow suit next month. In the
United States the age of consent is set by individual states and is
normally 16 or 17.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers and applause rang out from the packed public galleries
when the huge margin of 207 votes _ 336-129 _ was read out.
</P>
<P>
   The motion, an amendment to a law-enforcement bill, was
supported by Prime Minister Tony Blair and William Hague, the
leader of the opposition Conservatives, and Paddy Ashdown, the head
of Britain's third major party, the Liberal Democrats. The decision
was on a so-called ``free vote'' in which legislators are not bound
by their party's position and can follow their ``consciences.''
</P>
<P>
   The Church of England opposed the change, saying it ``may give
wrong messages both to young people and to our society as a
whole.'' The Anglican bishops said the church and state had a duty
``to protect young people from harm and exploitation and to offer
them a vision of what is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Their statement continued, ``Pressures are at work to legitimize
any and every lifestyle, irrespective of any difference of value
and quality between them. These pressures should be resisted.''
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop of Canterbury, George Carey, felt so strongly
about the reform that he personally appealed to the prime minister
to oppose it even though Blair had voted for the first reduction
four years ago and had spoken out forcefully in favor of the new
one.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign four years ago witnessed one of the biggest lobbies
ever organized in the history of the British Parliament, provoking
thousands of letters to lawmakers, public discussions of the
position of lesbian and gay people in British society and a vigil
outside the House of Commons on the night of the vote. A motion
then to lower the age to 16 failed by 27 votes.
</P>
<P>
   The only serious dispute this year centered on an amendment
offered on the floor to make it an offense for adults in charge of
youngsters under 18 to have sex with them. It was voted down
234-194 after the Home Office spokesman, Alun Michael, expressed
sympathy for the notion of protecting youngsters from predatory
adults but said the amendment was a ``technically'' flawed way to
deal with it. He said a government working group would take up the
issue and make a recommendation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the debate, a Conservative legislator, Sir Patrick Cormack
brought jeers and cries of, ``For shame!'' from Labor benches when
he recalled the old saying about the Navy's being ``rum, sodomy and
the lash'' and said, ``I do not believe that every single young man
who followed that way of life was born into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Winterton, another Conservative, also provoked hoots of
derision when he said, ``If the Lord Almighty had meant men to
commit sodomy with other men, their bodies would have been built
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's vote and the days leading up to it passed
quietly, a reflection of rapidly changing attitudes in a
legislature where at least six members are openly homosexual or
lesbian and a government where one avowedly gay cabinet member,
Culture Secretary Chris Smith, attends formal functions with his
longtime male partner.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the motion swarmed into committee rooms to watch
the debate on television while others milled about the entrances to
the Parliament. Among those in the press gallery was British actor
and director Sir Ian McKellen, who in recent years has become an
activist for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Keen, the Labor legislator who introduced the bill, has a
gay son, and she said that there is enough pressure on a teen-age
boy discovering he is gay without the worry that he might be
breaking the law if he had sex. ``Many of these young people and in
particular their parents want a responsible but an equal law,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action, Keen said, concerned ``discrimination'' rather
than sex at 18 or 16. ``Our laws at the moment discriminate against
many of our young people who are gay young men,'' she said, ``who
start their adult life as a criminal, which has got to be
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
