<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES FACE 9 MORE CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also SCOTUS and SCOTUS-HARASS) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After issuing decisions in five cases Monday, the
Supreme Court has nine cases left to decide before it completes its
1997-98 term. The court has scheduled additional decision days on
Thursday and Friday, but whether the justices will meet Chief
Justice William Rehnquist's goal of concluding the term on Friday
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Following are brief summaries of the remaining cases; as usually
happens at this time of year, they include a number of the term's
most important cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual harassment: Two cases, Faragher vs. City of Boca Raton,
No. 97-282, and Burlington Industries Inc. vs. Ellerth, No. 97-569,
could define the liability of employers for sexual harassment under
Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. The basic question in
the Boca Raton case, a suit by a former city lifeguard who was
harassed by her supervisor, is whether the city can be held
accountable for misconduct of which it had no direct knowledge. The
Burlington Industries case raises the question of whether an
employee who refused to submit to a supervisor's sexual advances,
and who suffered no adverse consequences on the job, can still
bring a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Line Item Veto: Whether Congress violated the constitutional
separation of powers by giving the president the authority to
cancel portions of appropriations bills he has signed into law is
the question in Clinton vs. City of New York City, No. 97-1374.
</P>
<P>
   HIV discrimination: In Bragdon vs. Abbott, No. 97-156, the court
will decide whether the Americans with Disabilities Act protects
people who have the virus that causes AIDS; the ruling may also
define the scope of legal protection for other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Privilege: The question in Swidler &AMP; Berlin vs. United States,
No. 97-1192, is whether the attorney-client privilege always
survives the death of the client _ in this case, the death of
Vincent Foster Jr., the deputy White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Decency test: In National Endowment for the Arts vs. Finley, No.
97-371, the Clinton administration is defending a decency test for
the awarding of federal arts grants.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth Amendment: The court will decide in United States vs.
Balsys, No. 97-873, whether a person who faces deportation can
claim the Fifth Amendment's protection against compelled
self-incrimination on the basis of likely prosecution overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Liability: The question in Eastern Enterprises vs. Apfel, No.
97-42, is whether the government can constitutionally impose
retroactive liability on the coal industry for health benefits for
retired miners.
</P>
<P>
   Double Jeopardy: In Monge vs. California, No. 97-6146, the court
will examine the relationship between ``three-strikes'' laws that
impose added penalties on repeat offenders and the constitutional
protection on double jeopardy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
