</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-540-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROVIDES DETAILS OF EFFORTS TO INSURE MORE CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ President Clinton announced a series of
low-cost federal initiatives Monday intended to encourage hundreds
of thousands of poor families who lack health insurance to enroll
their children in state and federal health care programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding many of the health-care themes that Democrats have put
near the center of their domestic agenda this year, Clinton said at
a conference on health and families at Vanderbilt University that
schools, health clinics and a variety of federal government offices
should be used more aggressively to educate low-income parents
about government health care programs such as Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the finest health care in the world, but we still
can't figure out how to give everybody access to it in a quality,
affordable way,'' Clinton said at the conference, which was
organized by the family of Vice President Al Gore, a Tennessean.
``We have to do a better job of turning laws into reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that the number of uninsured people in
America is increasing, despite the healthy economy. Health care
experts have said that the reasons include the growth of low-paying
jobs that do not provide health benefits and changes to welfare
laws that have ended cash benefits for many families. In those
cases, experts say, many parents do not realize that their children
remain eligible for Medicaid even after they leave the welfare
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 12 million uninsured children in the country,
government and private studies show. About two in five of those
children, or 4.7 million, are eligible for Medicaid, the
state-federal program that serves the poor. More than 18 million
children are served by Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policies the president outlined Monday, which do not
require congressional approval, the leaders of eight federal
agencies will be required to send letters to 350,000 government
employees urging them to help enroll uninsured children in Medicaid
or state health programs. Information on government health care
programs will also be distributed at thousands of health centers,
schools, welfare offices, tax offices, housing projects and other
agencies that serve low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced Monday that the federal government would
begin a study into which brands of cigarettes are most poplar with
teen-agers. The president said the survey, which was also called
for in comprehensive tobacco legislation that died in the Senate
last week, would help focus public pressure on tobacco companies
that tailor their marketing to adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will clearly demonstrate that there is something in the
nature of the advertising that has something to do with this,''
Clinton told reporters outside the White House Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill that was killed in the Senate, tobacco companies
could have been fined if they did not reduce the number of
teen-agers who smoked their brands. Clinton said the federal survey
could be used to target companies for such fines if a tobacco bill
was enacted later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey will be made part of a study of drug abuse conducted
by the Department of Health and Human Services each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
