<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING A COOL HEAD  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For summer, hairstyles should be no fuss, easy and
casual, to withstand heat and humidity, especially if you spend a
lot of time outdoors. Hair that's long, and of one length, can be
pulled back into a pony tail or pinned into a French twist. Short
hair dries quickly and bares the neck to breezes, winning it fans
this summer like Marla Maples of the formerly long blond tresses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maples' cut is boyish, but short hair needn't be. Jennifer
Lawrence, the head stylist at the Louis Licari Color Group, has
been cutting two variations of short hair into layers that are just
long enough to be worn in slightly different styles.
</P>
<P>
   Both are close to the neck in back but thick, not shorn-looking,
so the effect is feminine. The front may have short chunky layers
around the face or longer layers, perhaps three inches, on top and
in front, which can be worn as bangs, combed to the side or even
slicked back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
