<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-AUPAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AU PAIR TELLS BBC SHE WAS U.S. SCAPEGOAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Louise Woodward, the British au pair convicted of
killing the 8-month-old Massachusetts boy she had been paid to care
for, declared on Monday night in a BBC television interview that
she was innocent and that the American criminal justice system had
prevented her from getting a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything wrong,'' said Ms. Woodward, 20, who left
Boston last week after the state's highest court upheld a judge's
decision to reduce her murder conviction to manslaughter in the
1996 death of Matthew Eappen. ``If anything, I tried to help him as
best I could and didn't do anything to hurt him or harm him in any
way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 45-minute interview, on BBC's ``Panorama'' program, Ms.
Woodward said she had been made a scapegoat, particularly by
Matthew's parents, Deborah and Sunil Eappen of Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel it right that the mentality is that somebody has
to pay,'' she said. ``That, well, if the parents didn't do it, who
did; there is only you left. And there was the whole feeling that
somebody has to pay and that somebody had to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward expanded on remarks she made last week in which she
accused the Boston district attorney's office of being ``purely
political'' and called the jury pool ``tainted.'' On Monday night
she said she had been used by the system, comparing it unfavorably
with the one in Britain, where the news media are forbidden to
report anything but the barest details about criminal proceedings
outside of trials, which are not televised.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston, the prosecutors use the media to pretty much
convict you before you even set foot in the courtroom,'' Ms.
Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   John Mirick, a lawyer for the Eappens in a civil lawsuit against
Ms. Woodward, said they would watch the interview but not comment
until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward's decision to argue her case on television was met
with criticism. The Daily Mirror branded the interview ``An Insult
to Diana,'' saying that Ms. Woodward ``seems to model herself'' on
the Princess of Wales, who spoke to the same interviewer, Martin
Bashir, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BBC is now in the gutter,'' the paper quoted Denis
MacShane, a member of Parliament, as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
