<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      06-22 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ads, Again, From Anne Klein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Anne Klein is gambling its reputation on 30 accomplished women,
who will appear in 32 pages of advertising in the August issue of
Elle magazine. It's an understandable yet necessary roll of the
dice for the company: five years ago, it was one of the premier
names in American sportswear, and now it is battling for position.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign will unveil the first bridge collection bearing
the Anne Klein name. The Anne Klein II signature, once on more than
a dozen products including bridge sportswear, has been dropped
except for watches and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is in a turnaround, and an ordinary effort of a
model looking into a camera with a logo underneath was not going to
do the trick,'' said Laura Wenke, the company's senior vice
president for marketing. ``We wanted to get the industry behind us
as well as consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 32-page spread will run in Vogue, Harper's Bazaar and
Mirabella this fall, and smaller selections of the group portraits
will be seen in seven other publications. Anne Klein, which has not
advertised for almost two years, is spending $5 million to $6
million on the ads, Ms. Wenke said.
</P>
<P>
   The photos were taken by Annie Leibovitz and bear more than a
trace of the look she developed for Vanity Fair's fold-out
Hollywood covers.
</P>
<P>
   Marrying the style and substance of real women and men to sell
fashion is not new _ the Gap, Macy's, Donna Karan and Coach have
used the combination effectively. But the wide swath of Anne
Klein's push is remarkable. Among the women featured are Ann
Richards, the former governor of Texas; Anna Deavere Smith, the
actress and playwright; Denyce Graves, the mezzo-soprano; Jenny
Thompson, the Olympic swimmer; Esther Dyson, author and publisher;
Bebe Neuwirth, star of ``Chicago'' and ``Cheers''; Julie Taymor,
the ``Lion King'' director and Sylvia Rhone, the chairwoman of
Electra Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The women each received $1,000 a day, which many donated to
charity, and a $2,000 certificate that can be redeemed at Anne
Klein's employee store, Ms. Wenke said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Back in New York &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The thinning ranks of prominent American designers presenting
collections at the New York shows, to be held July 27-30, will be
bolstered by the return of Donna Karan and John Bartlett. Last
season, Karan, Bartlett and Calvin Klein defected to Milan, where a
growing cadre of designers with global expansion in mind now
introduce their collections, aiming to meet earlier sales and
delivery deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, who will present his first collection for Byblos on
July 1 during the Italian men's shows, thought it better to keep
his own line in New York this season. The signature collection is
to close the New York shows on July 30 at 7 p.m. His move back to
the United States is not necessarily permanent, Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   The same holds for Karan, who plans to return to Milan in 1999.
She is showing in New York this year for a practical reason: to
stay close to home as she oversees the introduction of tailored
suits, jackets and trousers in an offshoot of her secondary line,
DKNY. Licensed to Peerless Clothing Inc., a Canadian company, the
line will be shown with the rest of DKNY sportswear on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's DKNY, and DKNY is so much about New York, we
wanted to show it here,'' said Patti Cohen, a senior vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2228EDT &QL; 
