<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESORT-FASHION-ART-NY     06-22 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESORT-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONG SEASON CALLED RESORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (JT)  
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that summer is here, it's too late to buy summer clothes.
Anyone with a yen for a pair of white pants had to shop for them
while the weather was cold. Tough luck if you've waited until now.
Go into just about any fashion store in June, and you'll find the
remnants of warm-weather clothes that have already been marked down
to make room for the first wave of fall styles.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this situation, designers don't even do summer
collections anymore, but instead include summery clothes in their
late spring deliveries, affording them a short shelf life. So, the
best time to find summer wares is, paradoxically, in October,
November and December, when resort clothes are in the stores. Right
now, designers are showing retailers the resort lines that
customers will find at the end of this year. And designers are very
aware that not all the resort clothes will be heading for holidays
in Miami Beach or the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done an extensive collection,'' Calvin Klein said,
``because it's an important season. Those three months are the one
time women get an opportunity to buy clothes after fall. They know
that the clothes they buy for resort are the clothes they'll wear
in the summer. And from our point of view, it's a long selling
season.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is more to the resort collections than summery
clothes. There are also citified styles a woman could wear in her
hometown and evening clothes she could wear just about anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell these clothes around the world,'' Klein said, ``but
they're based on how Americans live and travel.''
</P>
<P>
   He has concentrated on natural fibers. There are crisp cotton
shirts, often cropped above the waist, to go with drop-waist skirts
that graze the ankle; unlined linen jackets and elastic-waist
pants; sweaters of cotton or lacy cashmere; a fitted silk shirt
jacket with stretch cotton pants; stretch slot-cotton dresses, and
stretch silk balmacaans.
</P>
<P>
   Military colors like khaki and olive drab raise the clothes to a
high level of sophistication. And Klein believes they look fresher
than the usual navy or black.
</P>
<P>
   Evening is important because of end-of-the-year parties. Klein
has used textured and crinkled silks in the palest blue or ivory in
simple loose shapes or with draping in back, but his favorite
outfit is a low-neck black sweater over a full skirt of dark gray
satin with a slight shimmer. ``It's quintessentially us,'' he said,
``just a sweater and skirt but really strong.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The sweater and skirt for evening were a recurring
theme in many fall collections and, sure enough, can be found in
most of the resort lines being shown now.
</P>
<P>
   In an all white and neutral collection, Donna Karan teamed
hand-knit cashmere sweaters with skirts of layered organdy or
satin. She also experimented with new ways of incorporating burnout
techniques and devised one-piece dresses with panels of fabric that
wrap and tie to look like a T-shirt and skirt. ``Everything is
cotton, cashmere or charmeuse,'' Karan said. ``It's all about how
clothes feel. I don't think it's a question of take away or not
take away.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to all the soft, airy pieces, she showed jackets
with laser-cut edges that look raw and unfinished and eliminate the
need for linings or facings. They look crisp and clean, a very
modern alternative to tailoring and one that will potentially have
a tremendous influence on fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren has also turned away from strict tailoring in favor
of shirtlike unlined jackets, featherweight cashmere sweaters,
dirndl skirts, apron-wrap jumpers, and dresses. ``Everything is
lightweight, easy and very feminine,'' said Buffy Birrittella, the
company's design director for women's wear. ``We're getting rid of
inner facing and everything that adds weight or structure to
jackets.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the fabrics and colors are light enough to head
south, it is more urban than past Lauren resort collections. He's
used neutrals like taupe and cream rather than true colors, and
instead of swimsuits there are suedes, though the suedes are so
thin and silky they are actually seasonless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with our retail stores,'' Ms. Birrittella said, ``we
feel the customer at that time of year is looking for new spring
clothes. She's tired of her winter clothes and is looking for
things that give a lightness to her wardrobe and will carry her
into spring.''
</P>
<P>
   For pure resort wear, there are the Michael Kors, Isaac Mizrahi
and John Bartlett collections.
</P>
<P>
   Kors used mainly aqua, cantaloupe and black for silk tank tops
and cashmere sweaters, knee-length wrap skirts that close with
hidden magnets, shantung clam-diggers and long silk faille skirts.
The collection was a dressy take on sportswear and obviously aimed
more at the woman headed for Palm Beach, Fla., than the one going
to St. Bart's. (His first resort line for Celine spotlights intense
colors like buttercup yellow and robin's-egg blue for separates
that he describes as ``American sportswear meets Riviera chic.'')
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi's approach to resort, which he terms spa, is: ``What,
besides khakis, is worth buying to take away?''
</P>
<P>
   His solution was unexpected takes on blue denim, including silk
denim, linen denim and, for swimsuits, knitted denim. He also used
violet cotton satin for apron-wrapped culottes, red jersey for a
floor-length sweatshirt dress, gray tropical-weight wool for a
hoodless anorak and natural straw cloth for hot pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to be dressy,'' Mizrahi said. ``The American look
is to be casual. Spa has less to do with fashion than with life
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he managed to infuse plenty of fashion into the collection,
but the kind of fashion many women would feel comfortable in.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's influence was nautical. He used dark navy and white
for sailor pants and skirts of stretch canvas; sailcloth anoraks
and drawstring-waist skirts; leather A-line skirts and sailor
pants, and sweaters of cashmere and silk. He was the rare designer
who used pattern, showing horizontal and geometric stripes for
sweaters, swimsuits and cover-ups. It was sporty without losing the
sexy edge he is known for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
