<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTNEY-PHOTOS-NYT &LR;      06-22 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTNEY-PHOTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: LINDA MCCARTNEY NEVER LET FAME OBSTRUCT HER
VIEW  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGARETT LOKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To be claimed by fame is to be pigeonholed. But Linda
McCartney, who died of breast cancer in April at 56, never seemed
to feel fame's constraining effects on her life or her photography.
</P>
<P>
   She was best known for the unvarnished black-and-white portraits
of rock stars that she took in the mid-1960s to support herself and
her young daughter. After she married Paul McCartney in 1969, she
was invariably identified as his wife (and as a committed
vegetarian and animal-rights activist), but she had the luxury of
broadening and deepening her work throughout the next decades.
</P>
<P>
   A self-taught photographer, Ms. McCartney brought an engaged,
intuitive and minimalist eye to her black-and-white landscapes and
still lifes of the 1980s and '90s. Two dozen or so of these images,
none of which have previously been shown in New York, are on view
at the Bonni Benrubi Gallery, at 52 E. 76th St. in Manhattan,
through July 2. (A memorial service for Ms. McCartney was scheduled
Monday night at Riverside Church.)
</P>
<P>
   These photographs are worlds apart from the rock star pictures
of the '60s and from the 1996 exhibition ``Roadworks'' at the
International Center for Photography Midtown. Those pictures,
mainly street and road scenes, were also published by Bulfinch in a
book of the same title.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCartney's portraits of rock-and-roll stars, which were
compiled in a 1992 book ``Linda McCartney's '60s: Portrait of an
Era'' (Bulfinch), reflect her love for the music. But they also
reflect her untutored eye at a time when the rock scene still had a
brash innocence.
</P>
<P>
   She was the only person with a camera allowed to join
journalists at a high-profile 1966 press reception for the Rolling
Stones aboard a luxury yacht cruising the Hudson, perhaps because
she was young, good-looking and blond. Nonetheless, seizing the
opportunity, she quickly showed that she could take pictures that
caught the freewheeling spirit of her subjects.
</P>
<P>
   She was at the time an occasional photographer and a full-time
receptionist at Town and Country magazine, which had received the
invitation. But her nonchalant pictures, especially a Lisette
Model-like frontal image of Brian Jones slouched back in his seat,
seemingly in mid-yawn and with his legs wide apart, put her on the
rock 'n' roll photographic map.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the pictures in ``Roadworks,'' on the other hand, show
an oddly disengaged and aimless photographer. Although a few of the
enigmatic images taken from cars have a Robert Frank feel to them,
far too many of them have nothing much to say, and many of the
blurred pictures are meaninglessly blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Among the handful of exceptional photographs in ``Roadworks'' is
``Boys on the Beach, Barbados'' (1969), which could be the obverse
of Martin Munkacsi's exuberant picture of three black boys running
into the sea. In Ms. McCartney's photograph, a half-dozen figures,
almost equidistant from one another, look at the gentle waves
rolling out, their still silhouettes beautifully contrasted with
the delicate, silvery marks left on the sand by the waves.
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning image in ``Roadworks'' is ``Out Here,
California'' (1975). As a pickup truck is about to whiz past, a
burly passenger sitting in the flatbed staring right at her, Ms.
McCartney takes the picture. With a surrealistic bluish cast, this
image balances a crisply, almost lovingly detailed truck, from its
pristine exterior to its immaculate hubcaps. It shows the fragile
lines of a bicycle in the back of the truck, the man beside it
looking straight at the camera, his long hair flying, his
sunglasses not hiding his grim eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The body of work currently on exhibit at the Bonni Benrubi
Gallery _ selected by Ms. Benrubi and approved by Ms. McCartney a
few days before she died at her Arizona home _ is titled ``Wide
Open.'' But a large part of the show is, paradoxically, intensely
private. You wouldn't think so from the subject, landscapes, but
the pictures of sea and sky, of trees and of clouds share a
profound aloneness. Grainy and confined to broad strokes of black,
gray and white, and in some instances resembling charcoal drawings,
these platinum prints say less about the human capacity to turn
natural vistas into asphalt and concrete and much more about the
kind of thoughts on Thomas Gray's mind when he wrote, in ``Elegy
Written in a Country Churchyard'':
</P>
<P>
   Far from the madding crowd's ignoble strife,
</P>
<P>
   Their sober wishes never learn'd to stray;
</P>
<P>
   Along the cool sequester'd vale of life
</P>
<P>
   They kept the noiseless tenor of their way.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the quietly elegiac landscapes were taken in the
mid-1980s in Sussex, England, where the McCartneys had a home. One,
titled ``Lone Horse Rider'' (1985), shows the small figure of a
horse and rider on the slight incline of a dark horizon. Beyond it
are low smudges of gray, and above it a huge expanse of white sky.
A decade later, in ``Sand Sea Sky'' _ taken in East Hampton, N.Y.,
the year Ms. McCartney's breast cancer was diagnosed _ a tiny lone
figure sits on a beach, seemingly contemplating the waves washing
up to shore. The sky above, which takes up about four-fifths of the
frame, is a wash of gray and white that turns into roiling black.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the platinum prints, ``Wide Open'' includes
photogravures and silver-bromide prints. ``Wooden Bowl Indian Wood
Cuts'' (1994), a photogravure, has the graceful, minimalist vigor
of a Paul Strand still life and ``Ap and Shadow Painting'' (1996),
also a photogravure, is a dreamily mysterious study of a plastic
horse whose form is echoed in a nearby painting. (``Wide Open''
could have done without the greeting-card-pretty Polaroid
transfers.)
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Ms. McCartney's crisply sharp
silver-bromides, all made in the 1990s, would seem to be another
radical departure from her other work. But they, too, are spare and
the subject quite ordinary, shadows: the shadow of a bent figure on
a hard piece of land, wild mushrooms casting their shadows on the
lawn, the shadow of a beat-up old trumpet hanging on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in The New York Times on the vegetarian meal Ms.
McCartney cooked at the East Hampton home of the chef Pierre Franey
in 1994, Bryan Miller noted that Ms. McCartney was ``disarmingly
earthy and outgoing,'' and that she cooked without regard to
precise measurements. ``Everything is added in handfuls, pinches,
smidgens,'' he wrote. ``Her favorite measurement is `lots of.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her photography, too, could be disarmingly earthy. But her eye
was definitely precise. In a 1996 silver-bromide print of a glass
teapot, partly filled with hot water and placed majestically
outdoors, its clear lines are offset by the blurred dark background
and tall trees. Reflected in the water are the trees (upside down,
of course). And Ms. McCartney titled the image ``Through a Glass
Teapot,'' perhaps leaving the viewer to add the word ``darkly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
