<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY SECURITIES PRICES HELPED BY INCREASE IN DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities were mixed Monday,
supported by a rising dollar.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting of the seven industrial nations over the weekend
failed to produce any new measures to bolster Japan's ailing
economy, thus strengthening the dollar Monday against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   A strong dollar makes investments like U.S. Treasury securities
more attractive to foreign investors, not only for the yield, but
also for the potential of additional gains through currency
translation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gamba, senior vice president and manager of bond trading at
Cowen &AMP; Co., said Monday's trading session was mostly dollar
driven, but with a little undertone of cautiousness. ``I think the
market was expecting more out of the G-7 meeting, and really there
wasn't anything new or concrete to come out of it that would
stimulate the Japanese economy and reform its ailing banking
system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond rose 2/32, to 106 20/32. The bond's yield was
unchanged at 5.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gamba believes the market will focus Tuesday on the two-year
note auction. ``The two-year notes will have little problem being
absorbed by the market,'' he said. ``The key here is what is
happening overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that the lack of economic reports this week will
mean that bond market participants will focus on overseas events,
the dollar and stock market activity.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries traded well Monday because Asian stock markets had
slumped and investors sought the relative safety of U.S.
investments.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury will sell $23 billion in two-year and five-year
notes this week, with the two-year issue to be sold Tuesday and the
five-year note on Wednesday. In when-issued trading, the two-year
maturity was being offered late Monday at a price to yield 5.47
percent and the five-year note at a price to yield 5.46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Early talk in the market is that yields may need to increase on
the two-year issue to attract investor interest. After this sale,
the Treasury will offer five-year notes on a quarterly basis
instead of monthly. Monday's auctions of the three-month bill came
in at an average rate of 4.99 percent, down from 5.01 percent a
week ago, while the rate for a six-month maturity was 5.12 percent,
up from 5.065 percent. About $4.5 billion in corporate bonds are
expected to be issued this week, but demand has eased somewhat
because of the concern that the Asian economic turmoil could hurt
the U.S. economy and corporate earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
