<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIEF ITEMS FROM THE WORLD OF SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Eyes See, but the Brain Decides
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to think of one's eyes as cameras that feed real-time
images into the mind.
</P>
<P>
   But nature doesn't work that way. Those incoming images are
deconstructed at the retina, extensively processed and then
reconstituted somewhere in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists at the Institute of Neurology in London have
explored one of the higher-level stages of processing by sitting
subjects in a brain-scanning machine and showing different images
to the left and right eye in such a way that neither eye could see
the image shown to the other.
</P>
<P>
   When the brain is faced with conflicts of this kind, it tries to
spare the conscious mind the embarrassment of seeing two
contradictory versions of reality by presenting the two images in
alternation. Erik D. Lumer and his colleagues report in the current
issue of Science that this gatekeeping role is performed by a site
in the side and frontal lobes of the brain, far removed from the
optic cortex at the back of the head, where visual input from the
eyes is first routed. This is apparently the first time, Lumer
said, that the frontal lobes have been so clearly implicated in
influencing the content of visual awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Show Greater Tolerance for Contradictions  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contradictions, at least of the intellectual kind, are better
tolerated by Chinese than by Americans, according to a study by
Kaiping Peng, a former Beijing scholar who is now a psychologist at
the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   In a family conflict, Chinese are more likely to urge disputing
parties to agree, without apportionment of blame, whereas Americans
tend first to decide which party is right and then insist the other
capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the American way of dealing with contradiction may be
optimal for scientific exploration and the search for facts because
of its aggressive, linear and argumentative style,'' Peng
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Clues to the Past Suggest Aggressive Dining by T. Rex
</P>
<P>
   Some of those aggressive, linear American scientists, along with
Canadian colleagues, report in the current issue of Nature their
discovery of the largest known dinosaur coprolite, probably from a
Tyrannosaurus rex that once roamed southwestern Saskatchewan where
the fossil was found.
</P>
<P>
   Coprolite is the paleontological term for fossilized excrement.
</P>
<P>
   Of what possible use is a large slab of lithified feces? The
ordure speaks to T. rex's table manners: the creature chewed its
meals (other dinosaurs) thoroughly, but apparently digested them
less well, the bone fragments being relatively pristine despite
their passage through the T. rexian gut.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfly Wings and the Evolutionary Scale
</P>
<P>
   Those scales on the dinosaur's hide may have metamorphosed into
feathers, as evolution, with its customary economy in making old
structures serve new ends, crafted the bird. But from what existing
structures did evolution create something so special as the scales
on a butterfly's wing?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is the bristle. The sensory bristles that stud a
fly's body have a pattern of development in the embryo similar to
that of the butterfly's scales. Sean B. Carroll and colleagues at
the University of Wisconsin at Madison now report in Current
Biology that the butterfly's scale control gene is related in its
DNA sequence to the fruit fly's bristle control gene.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll suggests that the wings of the first winged insects were
covered with sensory bristles. As butterflies evolved, the bristles
flattened into scales and acquired a palette of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Another clever transformation, but one achieved in minutes, not
the eons of evolutionary time, is the quick costume change
performed by the spirochete that causes relapsing fever. This
bacterium alternates between infecting a tick and the human or
other mammal that the tick may feed on.
</P>
<P>
   A principal difficulty of this mode of existence is that
different defenses are required against the immune systems of each
host. The bacterium can quickly change the proteins that make up
its outer coat.
</P>
<P>
   How does the microbe know when to do this, considering that it
is mindless? Its cue is the rise in temperature as it passes from
the coolness of the tick's salivary glands to a person's warm blood
stream, Tom G. Schwan and B. Joseph Hinnebusch report in the
current issue of Science.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
