<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE EYES BOTTLING AND SELLING ITS TAP WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHY GEORGE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle gave the world Starbucks, Pearl Jam and Bill
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   How about tap water, too?
</P>
<P>
   The City Council thinks the stuff dripping from our household
faucets is so superior that it should be bottled and sold, just
like Evian or Perrier.
</P>
<P>
   And now the city is about to spend up to $50,000 to study
whether its public water utility should dive into the bottled water
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our drinking water is pure enough to bottle,'' Councilwoman
Margaret Pageler said Monday, moments before the council
unanimously approved the study.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Seattle's Cedar River water is so clean that
Congress exempted it from filtration requirements, council members
said a bottled version should be just as appealing as expensive
``designer'' water.
</P>
<P>
   And Seattleites might want bottles of their tap water if their
plumbing is bad, or just for convenience, Pageler said.
</P>
<P>
   The council already has a name for its potential product:
Seattle Rain.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea might turn out to be all wet.
</P>
<P>
   The city will hire a consultant to determine by September
whether a water-bottling venture is even legal, not to mention
practical.
</P>
<P>
   Questions to be answered include whether the law allows this
kind of commercial venture, whether the city can find a private
bottling partner and whether Seattle's neighboring cities will
tolerate any additional drain on limited regional water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's the bottom line. If the city can't net at least a
$500,000 a year, it's probably not worth the effort, Pageler said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her main goal in sponsoring the proposal is to raise
money for environmental projects, such as protecting salmon habitat
in the city's Cedar River watershed.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an opportunity to tell the world how clean Seattle's
water is, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any place known for great water, it's Seattle,''
said Lisa Fitzhugh, special assistant to Mayor Paul Schell.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, public utilities resisted the idea of bottling
water because it might imply that plain old tap water is somehow
inferior, Pageler said. But public officials are beginning to
realize that bottling can be used to promote tap water, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City already is bottling its municipal water, and San
Francisco is considering it.
</P>
<P>
   The trail blazed by other cities suggests that any legal
barriers can be overcome, she said, adding that the mayor's office
hopes to start bottling and selling tap water next year, ``as
quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The city already is talking to private local companies
interested in marketing Seattle's tap water, she said. She declined
to identify the firms.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers now spend up to 1,000 times more for imported bottle
water than for tap water in their own homes, according to a book
co-authored by several Seattle water managers.
</P>
<P>
   At current Seattle water rates, ``one penny will buy you 80 cups
of (tap) water,'' said D'Anne Mount, spokeswoman for Seattle Public
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The study will look at how much to charge for bottles of Seattle
tap water, and what kind of containers to use. Pageler wants
lightweight recycled materials.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainties surrounding the city's splashy idea,
one councilman already is sounding like a salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that our water is among the best-tasting, purest and
finest that you can find,'' Peter Steinbrueck said. ``I hope to see
it available all over the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Kathy George
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8390
</P>
<P>
   or kathygeorge &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
