<HEADLINE>
CHINA VOICES HOPE ON JOINING WORLD TRADE GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A senior Chinese trade official said Monday that China
hoped to make progress toward joining the World Trade Organization
during President Clinton's visit this week.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast with earlier hopes that China's entry could be
clinched soon, the official, Shi Guangsheng, minister for foreign
trade and economic cooperation, said there was no timetable. He
also reacted mildly to American statements that China was far from
satisfying requirements for opening its markets to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``we will continue to hope for positive and
substantive progress'' toward agreement on entry into the trading
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``China wants to join the WTO because this is necessary for our
own economic reform and opening up,'' Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization sets global trade rules. Its 132 member nations
must meet requirements for reducing barriers to trade and
investment, and in turn give each other better trading conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday in Beijing the chief American trade negotiator,
Charlene Barshefsky, said it had become clear that Chinese leaders,
preoccupied with domestic economic dangers, were not ready to make
the major changes needed to qualify for entry. Besides general
tariff levels, American officials are especially concerned about
barriers to agricultural imports and to foreign involvement in
financial, accounting, tourism and other service industries.
</P>
<P>
   China has portrayed entry into the trade body as a political as
well as an economic goal, and has sometimes lambasted the West for
imposing what China considers unfair requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But Shi made only a muted complaint Monday, consistent with a
general effort by officials to minimize conflict with the United
States before the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current difficulties are because the requirements set by
the United States and some European countries are too high, and
have exceeded the limits of the Chinese economy,'' Shi said. But he
added: ``We have no timetable, and we hope negotiations can
continue and we can continue to make progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
