<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NEWS AND NOTES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   In the Flow
</P>
<P>
   Song and show business celebrate the mighty Mississippi, the
Shenandoah and even the Wabash, but what about the Hudson River?
Well, to hear the organizers of a new festival tell it, the Hudson
_ the economic lifeblood of New York City since the Dutch settlers
_ has been unjustly neglected. So, as the sun sets Tuesday night,
the curtain (figuratively speaking) goes up on the summerlong
Hudson River Festival. Produced by the World Financial Center and
Battery Park City, and running through Sept. 1, the festival will
consist of dance, music, theater and film, among other arts, in the
public spaces of Battery Park City. Most events are scheduled for 7
p.m. to show off the sunset over the river. Included are
performances by the Paul Taylor Dance Company and Eliot Feld's
Ballet Tech; dance parties to the music of Tommy Dorsey and Duke
Ellington; screenings of ``Singin' in the Rain,'' ``Top Hat'' and
``An American in Paris,'' and more. Tuesday night King Sunny Ade
and his African Beats perform at the World Financial Center Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Another Beginning
</P>
<P>
   The five-story house where Pablo Picasso was born in 1881 was
dedicated as a museum Monday by King Juan Carlos of Spain. After a
$1.6 million conversion, the museum in Malaga, Spain, will soon
open with exhibitions of paintings, ceramics and engravings.
</P>
<P>
   A Second Baton
</P>
<P>
   Claus Peter Flor has been named principal guest conductor of the
Dallas Symphony Orchestra, beginning with the 1999-2000 season,
when the ensemble will celebrate its centennial. In announcing the
appointment, Andrew Litton, music director of the orchestra, said
Flor ``is one of the leading European conductors of his generation,
and he brings to Dallas a unique perspective on the great German
classical tradition.'' Flor, who was born in Leipzig, Germany, in
1953, becomes the orchestra's third principal guest conductor. He
follows Guenther Herbig, who served from 1979 to 1981, and Pinchas
Zukerman, who served from 1993 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
