<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-ROW-OVERTURN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITAL MURDER CONVICTION OF WOMAN ON TEXAS' DEATH ROW OVERTURNED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge has overturned the capital murder conviction of
one of seven women on Texas' death row, paving the way for her
possible third trial in the 18-year old case.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein said Pam Perillo's right to a
fair trial was compromised because her attorney had a close
personal and professional relationship with the prosecution's chief
witness.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent hearing ordered by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, Werlein said, he discovered that Houston attorney Jim
Skelton failed to discredit Linda Fletcher's testimony on crucial
points during Perillo's 1984 trial.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Skelton failed to tell Perillo of his personal
relationship with the witness _ a relationship that began in 1980
when Skelton represented Fletcher on murder charges in the same
case, Werlein said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted Skelton admitted during the hearing he sometimes
lies to his clients. ``Skelton's credibility is questionable,''
Werlein's opinion stated.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton represented Fletcher when she, her then-husband Mike
Briddle and Perillo were charged with the February 1980 killings of
Robert Banks and Bob Skeens.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton later represented Fletcher on aggravated robbery charges
after negotiating a plea bargain for her testimony against Briddle.
</P>
<P>
   Months after convincing a Harris County jury to sentence the
battered wife to five-months probation, Skelton traveled to
California to give Fletcher away at her 1981 wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher stayed at Skelton's condominium when she came to
Houston to testify against Perillo two years later and also was
Skelton's guest when she testified against Briddle during his 1982
capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . this fact, as the court of appeals has held, tends to
confirm the reality of the conflict of interest position in which
Skelton placed himself,'' Werlein noted.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher's testimony that she was not present during the 1980
strangulation killings of Banks and Skeens went unchallenged,
despite statements that implicated Perillo, Werlein said.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton also failed to tell the jury that Fletcher had blood on
her jeans when arrested, nor did he reveal that only Fletcher's
fingerprints were identified at the crime scene, Werlein said.
</P>
<P>
   But Werlein stopped short of questioning Skelton's ethics.
Instead, he said Skelton shortsightedly put himself into a
situation where he had few options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Skelton successfully impeached Fletcher, he might have
been the instrument of subjecting her to perjury charges and, at
this point, the interests of Perillo and Fletcher diverged,''
Werlein wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dusek, spokesman for Texas Attorney General Dan Morales,
said a motion has been filed asking Werlein to reconsider. If he
does not, the matter will be appealed to the 5th Circuit, Dusek
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County District Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. expressed
confidence that Werlein's ruling, issued Thursday, will be
overturned, but that he will retry the case if it is not.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Los Angeles, Perillo turned to burglary and robbery
as a teen-ager to support a heroin habit. While on a drug-induced
high, she, Briddle and Fletcher stole $800 from Skeens and Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Perillo later confessed to the killings and all three were
charged with capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Perillo did not implicate Fletcher in her statement to police,
but she told defense attorney Robert Scott during her 1981 trial
that she and Fletcher wrapped a rope around Banks' neck. Perillo
and Fletcher each took an end and pulled it taut, court documents
quote Perillo as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Perillo said she and Briddle then did the same to Skeens. All
three were initially charged with capital murder, but Skelton
convinced prosecutors that Fletcher played no part in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Perillo's capital murder conviction in the men's deaths
was overturned because of an error during jury selection.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, she was convicted of Skeens' murder and again sentenced
to death, but she appealed because of Skelton's involvement with
Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   Briddle was convicted in 1982 and executed in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Werlein noted disciplinary proceedings are pending against
Skelton by the State Bar of Texas in another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Heasty, spokeswoman for the State Bar, said the Supreme
Court of Texas Board of Disciplinary Appeals reversed a disbarment
judgment against Skelton on Feb. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The matter was sent back to the State Bar's grievance committee
for a new hearing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
