<HEADLINE>
WALLY GOLD, 70, SONGWRITER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walter Gold, a songwriter and music producer, died on
June 7 at Holy Name Hospital in Teaneck, N.J. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was colitis, his wife, Fredda, said.
</P>
<P>
   Gold, who wrote songs as Wally Gold, was born in Brooklyn. After
Navy service in World War II, he sang in a quartet, the Four
Esquires, before becoming a songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, he and his partner, Aaron Schroeder, wrote ``It's Now
or Never,'' which was recorded by Elvis Presley and became a No. 1
hit. In 1963, Gold wrote ``It's My Party'' with John Gluck Jr. and
Herb Wienner, and it became a best seller for Lesley Gore. Later,
Gold worked as a record producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
