A1485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WALLACH-NYT &LR;      06-22 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WALLACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES G. WALLACH, 55, CHAIRMAN OF PULP AND PAPER CONCERN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James G. Wallach, the chairman and chief executive of
Central National-Gottesman Inc., a pulp, paper, and newsprint
marketing concern, died on Friday at his home in Scarsdale, N.Y. He
was 55.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a cerebral aneurysm, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallach became president and chief executive of Central
National-Gottesman in 1979 and chairman and chief executive in
1997. The privately owned company is based in Purchase, N.Y., and
has sales of more than $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   It was after receiving a master's degree in business
administration in 1966 from the University of California at
Berkeley that he joined the Central National-Gottesman
organization. He foresaw the growing significance of Asia for the
pulp and paper business and directed a swift expansion in the
company's Asian operations in the early 1980s. It now has 22
offices in foreign countries, including 10 in Pacific Rim nations.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s he supervised the company's expansion into
sales of paper used in business forms and stationery. The company
also sells paper for use in book publishing, magazines and
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Wallach was a trustee of Bates College in Maine and a vice
president and a director of the University of Maine Pulp and Paper
Foundation. He was also on the boards of several Wallach family
charitable foundations. Beneficiaries of the family's philanthropic
largess have included the New York Public Library, the Metropolitan
Museum, the Central Park Conservancy and the American Museum of
Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Manhattan and raised in Scarsdale and went on to
graduate from Deerfield Academy in Deerfield, Mass., and in 1964
from Bates College.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 27 years, Mary Kerr Wallach; two
sons, Andrew and Scott, both of Scarsdale; his parents, Ira Wallach
and Miriam Gottesman Wallach, of Scarsdale; a brother, Kenneth, of
Manhattan; and two sisters, Sue Wachenheim, of Rye, N.Y., and Kate
Cassidy, of East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
