<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-nbadraft-centers-HNS &LR;      06-22 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nba </SLUG>
 draft-centers-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Olowokandi ends up 
big man off campus
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nigerian undisputed cream of center crop
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Five years ago, not only could no one spell Michael Olowokandi's
name, but no one in the NBA _ or most anywhere else in this country
_ had ever heard of the native of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone wants him now.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as if everyone in the league is lining up to try to get
one of the first two picks in Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because if you're third, you probably won't get the ``Kandi
Man,'' the 7-1 shot-blocker from Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, Denver, Philadelphia, Milwaukee, Boston and Golden
State are all making pitches to Vancouver, which possesses the No.
2 pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   There is even talk that the Los Angeles Clippers, who were
expected to take Arizona point guard Michael Bibby with the first
pick, have been talking about perhaps taking Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy whose stock is skyrocketing is Olowokandi,'' said
Nuggets general manager Dan Issel. ``In fact, there's a lot of
people talking that the Clippers could be moving away from Bibby
and thinking about taking Olowokandi first. But I think the
Clippers will take Bibby. That makes sense for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibby is probably a legitimate No. 1 pick, he's big in Los
Angeles, and (agent David) Falk's got him, and David seems to
always be able to have it turn out the way David wants it to. So I
think Bibby will be No. 1, and I think there's a ton of teams that
would like to get to No. 2 to take Olowokandi.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi, who spent high school and his first year of college
in England, doesn't feel his lack of experience is a handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I am somewhat inexperienced compared to the rest of
the guys, some might take that to be a disadvantage,'' Olowokandi
said. ``At the same time, I don't have a style of play which I am
accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm more like a sponge, so that is an advantage in
itself. You are presented with a lot of different opportunities in
life. It's about making the most of the chance that you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi's story should be familiar to Houstonians since it is
almost a carbon copy of Hakeem Olajuwon's.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi was born and raised in Nigeria and moved to England
when his father, Ezikiel, was assigned a diplomatic post there.
Olowokandi played cricket, rugby and ran track and field at Brunel
University, which did not offer athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   After picking up a basketball for the first time at age 17,
Olowokandi fell in love with the game and decided to come to
America to hone his skills. Olowokandi picked up a guide to
American colleges, randomly chose a spot and opened the book up. He
called the college on that page, the University of the Pacific, and
asked if he could transfer his college credits from England.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Yes, why?''' Olowokandi said. ``I explained the
whole thing, how I wanted to go to school and play basketball, and
they asked me how big I was, and I said that I was 7-feet tall and
265 (pounds) and they said, `We'll have you.' That's basically
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as the clich goes, is history.
</P>
<P>
   While Olowokandi, who averaged 22 points, 11 rebounds and three
blocks for Pacific last season, is often likened to Olajuwon, there
are those who fear he might turn out more like Yinka Dare, the
former bust with the New Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Olowokandi will turn out be like) neither, and I'm not
straddling the fence here,'' said Boston general manager Chris
Wallace. ``Down the line, in three to four years, he'll be a top-10
center, if not a top-five center. With experience, that will
happen. He came to the U.S. without significant experience, and he
played (fewer than) 80 games in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not consider him a project since he has offensive
ability, he has an NBA body and athleticism. When you get from him
(now) is more down the road than let's say Tim Duncan in San
Antonio or Shaq (O'Neal) in Orlando (where he was drafted).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the top center prospect in the draft, and I expect him to
go within the first two picks. He also has a tremendous work ethic
and is a bright and determined young man. He has all the bases
covered in terms of intangibles.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Blake, who evaluates talent for the NBA, is blunt about
the fuss over Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only center prospect out there,'' Blake said. ``But
he's a couple of years away. He hasn't played that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could go No. 1. You need a center (to win), and he has
potential. He has improved tremendously, and there are no other
centers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
