<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APARTHEID INQUIRY WILL HEAR WIDOW OF MOZAMBIQUE'S PRESIDENT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Graca Machel, the widow of
President Samora Machel of Mozambique and now President Nelson
Mandela's companion, is to testify on Tuesday about the
circumstances surrounding her husband's death in 1986, officials of
South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission said on Monday.
She is to testify behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has been looking into the events leading to the
crash of Machel's plane. Earlier this month, it heard evidence from
witnesses including a Mozambican official, members of the former
South African Defense Force, and Craig Williamson, a notorious
former spy, who has admitted helping the apartheid-era government
plot assassinations of political activists.
</P>
<P>
   The crash, which killed most of Machel's top advisers, has
always been been deemed suspicious by Mozambicans. Mozambique had
regularly vexed the former South African government by giving
refuge to its political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the crash, the South African government ruled it
an accident due to pilot error. But Russian investigators, called
in because it was a Russian-built plane, said they believed a decoy
beacon pulled the plane off course. They concluded that it emitted
a signal on the same frequency as that of the airport at Maputo,
the Mozambican capital.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, on a flight from Zambia, crashed into mountains in
South Africa near Mozambique's border. Of the 45 people aboard, 35
died.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials said that Mrs. Machel had wanted to
testify. She made her own inquiries about the crash and wished to
share her information with the panel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
