u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-ECON-475&AMP;ADD     06-22 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ECON-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PRICES SINK, HONG KONG CURBS LAND SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Seeking to stop a frightening downward spiral in the
property market, Hong Kong's government Monday announced it was
halting the sale of land until next March. The action, which was
made public after the stock market closed, was the starkest sign
yet of how deeply the Asian crisis is hurting Hong Kong's normally
resilient economy.
</P>
<P>
   Property prices drive the broader stock market here, and the
government is the biggest single land owner, selling about half of
Hong Kong's new residential property at public auctions. By halting
land sales, officials will effectively try to freeze real estate
prices at current levels. It amounts to government intervention on
a huge scale in Hong Kong's most important business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian crisis has brought a lot of suffering and pain to
Hong Kong people,'' said Tung Chee-hwa, the territory's chief
executive. ``We believe we are in a critical phase and, therefore,
we have to be pragmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Tung announced a series of measures to restore consumer
confidence and ease the deepening credit shortage. These include
the lowering of import and export duties, a tax rebate and a freeze
in government salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tung acknowledged that no degree of stimulus would pull
Hong Kong out of what is fast becoming its worst downturn since
World War II. Property prices have plunged 40 percent in the last
six months, unemployment is at a 15-year high, and output declined
by 2 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In a further setback, the Standard &AMP; Poor's ratings agency
warned Monday that it might lower the credit rating of the
territory's short-term and long-term debt, which would increase
government borrowing costs. Standard &AMP; Poor's said it had placed
Hong Kong on a credit watch list for review because of a ``growing
likelihood of a protracted economic downturn that could challenge
the ability of Kong Kong's government to maintain its prudent
fiscal policies and traditional noninterventionist stance toward
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tung said the economy would shrink again in the second quarter _
the first official confirmation of recession. Unless the government
acted to stabilize property prices, he said, the financial
condition of Hong Kong's banks would deteriorate and a crisis of
confidence would overwhelm local financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Influential business executives in the territory applauded the
halting of public property sales, but the government's aggressive
intervention may frighten overseas investors, who value Hong Kong
for its untrammeled markets. Late Monday, some analysts were
already questioning whether Hong Kong would continue linking its
currency to the U.S. dollar at a fixed exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks, which had rebounded the previous four sessions, fell
sharply, with the benchmark Hang Seng index losing 4.5 percent on
Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Making matters worse, the Japanese yen declined. Its fall had
been broken by joint intervention in the currency markets last week
from the U.S. and Japanese central banks to prop up the yen's
value. But after Japan announced no persuasive details in its
latest plan to invigorate the economy, the yen weakened again and
Hong Kong's market followed.
</P>
<P>
   The action taken here on property sales is a sign that Hong Kong
officials see little hope of a rebound in the yen any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be a rare animal if I said the situation in Japan were
stable,'' said Donald Tsang, the territory's financial secretary,
who devised the new measures in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Without any boost to the economy from outside, Tsang said Hong
Kong felt compelled to take the extraordinary action of halting
land sales. In the heyday of growth here, property auctions used to
draw scores of developers, who bid up the price of land to levels
some deemed absurd _ feeling sure that they could build towering
apartment complexes and sell the units for millions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the auctions have become dismal affairs. As for the two
million Hong Kong people who already own apartments, Tsang said
that the 40 percent decline in property prices was ``traumatic''
and that the government needed to reassure them that their
investments were not worthless.
</P>
<P>
   By foregoing auctions for nearly a year, he estimated that the
government would lose more than $30 billion (roughly $3.8 billion
U.S.) _ resulting in a rare budget deficit of $21.4 billion (nearly
$2.8 billion U.S.).
</P>
<P>
   Tsang and Tung reaffirmed Hong Kong's determination to continue
linking the currency to the U.S. dollar. But analysts said Monday's
action raised questions about how much economic hardship Hong Kong
was willing to endure before it devalued its currency.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, in an economy with a fixed exchange rate, the
government would allow external market forces to depress the price
of assets such as property. That is what Hong Kong did over the
last six months. Unlike Asian countries that devalued their
currencies, Hong Kong defended the dollar by increasing interest
rates, even though that devastated the property market by making
loans prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems to be bowing to political pressure to ease the
pain. The free fall in property prices hammered both powerful
developers and individual homeowners. Hong Kong's newly elected
legislators accused the territory's administration of insensitivity
toward the plight of ordinary citizens, while the tycoons pressed
top officials at private meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives said the decision would restore
confidence. ``It's the signal that the market has been waiting
for,'' said Nicholas Brooke, chairman of Brooke Hillier Parker, a
real estate brokerage firm here.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts said the government was engaged in an
increasingly desperate struggle to ease the consequences of a burst
bubble economy. ``Either land prices would have had to give or the
peg would have had to go,'' said Jan Lee, chief economist here of
the Hongkong and Shanghai Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
