<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1602 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPECIAL-DEVICES-LADN     06-22 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIAL-DEVICES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN BUYING SPECIAL DEVICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Special Devices Inc., a maker of explosive
devices used to inflate automobile air bags, has agreed to be
acquired by a New York investment fund for nearly $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   A unit of J.F. Lehman &AMP; Co. will pay $37 a share, or $296
million, for the business, Special Devices spokesman John Vinke
said Monday. The price is 4.2 percent above the issue's Monday
closing price of $35.50.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which must be approved by shareholders, comes six
months after Special Devices hired Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
Securities Corp. to help consider strategic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Vinke said the deal will not affect the company's day-to-day
operations and nearly all management will remain in place. ``It'll
continue operating just as it has. It'll just be privately held,''
Vinke said.
</P>
<P>
   Special Devices and the slightly larger OEA Inc., based in
Denver, are the top suppliers of automobile air bag initiators,
small explosive devices that rapidly inflate the safety bags in
crashes. The company also produces explosives used in military crew
escape systems.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Special Devices have gained 139 percent in the last
year, and the firm's earnings have risen 42.7 percent over the same
period. The company had 1997 sales of $140.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Special Devices is in the process of moving its manufacturing
plant and corporate headquarters to a facility under construction
in Moorpark. Venke said the proposed sale will not affect that
move.
</P>
<P>
   John Lehman, a general partner in J.F. Lehman, told Bloomberg
News that his firm likes companies with both commercial and defense
products. The fund has purchased five companies and has sold all
but two, he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
