<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-MILITARY-2TA     06-22 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-MILITARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN'S ARMY FADES, EVEN IN NUCLEAR CHOICE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ For nearly 24 years of its half-century
existence, Pakistan has been ruled by military dictators, but its
most important military decision _ to explode nuclear test devices
_ was made by a newly established civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   The army remains the country's strongest and most cohesive
institution _ indeed, perhaps its only cohesive institution _ but
for the past decade it has been steadily backing away from
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The change began with death of Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq in a
mysterious plane crash in 1988, after ten years in power. Zia's
mustache and impeccable uniforms gave him the air of a military
ruler straight from central casting.
</P>
<P>
   But today the army chief-of-staff, traditionally one of the
three most powerful officials in the country, is an unassuming
former tank commander, Gen. Jehangir Karamat. He is widely regarded
as a professional soldier who has resisted any temptation to wield
power.
</P>
<P>
   It was Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, elected in February 1997, in
the biggest landslide in the country's history, who made the
decision to match the nuclear tests of rival India. A main plank in
the platform that brought him his victory was a call for a
rapprochement with New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a land still largely feudal and tribal, riven with
religious, linguistic and ethnic tensions, and where the legacy of
elected government is corruption and incompetence. Indeed, Sharif
faces more problems at home than he does in his confrontation with
India.
</P>
<P>
   While spending untold millions in its search for nuclear arms,
Pakistan, like India, cannot provide basic services for vast
numbers of its citizens. Its economy is a shambles, defense
spending and servicing the foreign debt consumes most of the
federal budget, and the taxes that do exist are almost universally
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of the war in the 1980s in neighboring Afghanistan
has left the country awash in guns and drugs, as well as
fundamentalist Islamic preachers. Armed clashes, kidnappings, and
murders among rival groups occur daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army would like to get out of politics, but if the country
enters into chaos, the generals may again be forced to play a
role,'' said Stephen P. Cohen, a leading authority on the country
and its military, who is joining the Brookings Institution. ``This
could be a watershed, the best hope for Pakistan _ a government
with such a large majority _ but only if the civilians demonstrate
a degree of competence in running the country.''
</P>
<P>
   There was widespread agreement within the Cabinet that Pakistan
had to respond to India's nuclear tests with tests of it own. But
even though Sharif's decision to carry out tests was hugely popular
here _ political sniping has already begun over the austerity plans
needed to deal with Western sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made four phone calls to Sharif urging
Pakistan not to set off a nuclear explosion. His last offer,
officials here said, was this: from $3 billion to $5 billion in
World Bank and International Monetary Fund aid over the next five
years; a visit to Washington by Sharif; repeal of the Pressler
Amendment, which bans exports of weapons and military technology to
Pakistan because it was a developing a nuclear program; the release
of 28 jet fighter jets that the Pakistanis had bought and paid for
during the time of the Afghanistan war.
</P>
<P>
   The offer, Pakistani officials said, was judged not to amount to
much.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Nishat Ahmad, now retired, said: ``Pakistan wanted to
bargain, but this was, really, an issue affecting our national
existence. If the U.S. had come up with some kind of guarantee
against nuclear use by India, perhaps it could have been different.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharif would have been lynched if he traded national security
for a trip to Washington,'' he added. Before the Indian tests, the
Pakistani military had favored a kind of nuclear ambiguity, Cohen
noted in a forward to the forthcoming update of his book ``The
Pakistan Army'' (Oxford University Press).
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, military officers felt it was vital to show that
they could match their rivals, government officials here said. The
nuclear scientists were particularly eager to prove that their
device would work. However, an army staff college study also
suggested that there might be alternatives, like security
guarantees by outside powers or a conventional weapons buildup,
which would also have to be supported from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was primarily a political choice,'' said Ahmad. ``The army
had input because it is a security issue, but the military has no
control over decision making.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the days when generals ran the country.
</P>
<P>
   Field Marshal Mohammad Ayub Khan took power in 1958, ousting
discredited politicians, but after ten years another military coup
installed Gen. Agha Mohammad Yahya Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the military fell into disgrace as the distant eastern
half of Pakistan revolted, becoming Bangladesh, and a war with
India was swiftly lost. The civilian government of Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto came to power then, but in 1977 as political strife and
widespread violence mounted, Zia seized power, put the squabbling
party leaders in ``protective custody,'' and declared martial law.
Bhutto, father of the current opposition leader, Benazir Bhutto,
was hanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the perception was our politicians didn't
manage well,'' said retired Ahmad. ``The unfortunate conclusion of
the military was that we can put it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Zia took over, the Soviet Union entered the fighting
in Afghanistan, in 1979. Pakistan soon became a proxy base as
American aid was resumed and money and arms, channeled through
Pakistani intelligence, flowed to Islamic fighters battling the
Soviet side.
</P>
<P>
   After Zia died, the new army chief, Gen. Aslam Beg, presided
over what were regarded as unusually free elections in 1988, with
Ms. Bhutto becoming prime minister. As she and Sharif rotated in
power, the army remained in the background but was sometimes a
mediator.
</P>
<P>
   When a political impasse loomed in 1993, for example, Gen. Abdul
Waheed, described by Cohen as ``hitherto politically invisible,''
persuaded both Prime Minister Sharif and President Gulam Ishaq to
resign and hold new elections, bringing Ms. Bhutto back. When
Waheed retired, resisting entreaties to stay on, he was replaced as
chief of staff by Karamat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a thorough professional with a good education,'' said
Ahmad, who taught Karamat at the army staff college here and saw
him go on to the U.S. army's Command and General Staff College at
Fort Leavenworth. ``He is not overly ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Cohen wrote in the updating of his book on the
army, for the military leadership ``the Zia years are now regarded
with a degree of embarrassment.'' But, he added, the army's own
mistakes _ as seen by the officer corps itself _ pale in comparison
with those of the politicians, who are seen as responsible for
economic ruin and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Krepon, an authority on Pakistan who is president of the
Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington, said it is worrisome that,
unlike General Karamat, future generations of commanding officers
will not have been exposed to American training and values, because
schooling at elite staff colleges has been cut off under the
Pressler amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, what's happening inside the army,'' Krepon
said. ``The next generation of corps commanders, and, more
importantly, the generation after that. Where are the
fundamentalists in the army? How are the junior officers relating
to the senior officers?''
</P>
<P>
   Beg, the officer who had started the about-face from politics,
said that when Zia's plane exploded, ``it was expected of me as the
most senior army commander to step into Zia's boots as chief
martial law administrator. But I preferred not to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a great respecter of the constitution,'' he said. Then he
paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of my mind was the performance of the three
martial law regimes,'' he went on sadly. ``Ayub Khan, Yahya Khan,
Zia, I mean they made a mess of everything. It was a
disappointment, a complete disillusionment with the performance of
the military regimes. I knew it would have been a very clumsy
effort, something worse than the earlier efforts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
