u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-TV-SPORTS-NYT &LR;      06-22 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: 90 MINUTES HELD HOSTAGE BY SOMNOLENT ANNOUNCERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S.-Iran match should have animated the dead. It held
political import, for the animosity between the countries since
Iranian militants held Americans hostage for 444 days between 1979
and 1981. It held soccer import, for the U.S. team had to at least
tie to entertain a chance of playing in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Even a soccer dolt like me knew enough to be pumped. Brent
Musburger, ABC's studio host, was primed. He was wired! He was
loopy! ``In other words, this match against the United States is
Iran's World Cup,'' he stated, with an air of confident
obviousness. Then, the soccer authority boldly predicted the final
score: ``Three-nil, U.S., baby!'' Sure, he was wrong, but he was
Musburgerian: exciting fans, even hyperbolically.
</P>
<P>
   But would somebody awaken the game announcers Bob Ley and Seamus
Malin? Maybe they need honey to loosen their vocal cords. Malin,
the analyst, could make a whispering greenside golf announcer sound
like Michael Buffer.
</P>
<P>
   I roared when Malin, deadpanning like the comedian Steven
Wright, said during the second half: ``This is a tremendously
gripping game.'' Yes it is, I thought. Tell me!
</P>
<P>
   I've watched a few of Ley and Malin's games during this
tournament. But Sunday's was the nadir of their emotion-free
approach. Ley, one of television's best sports reporters and a top
``Sportscenter'' anchor, was hardly ever roused to a consistent
level of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   No, Ley need not sing a 90-minute aria like Univision's Andres
Cantor. But not to be jazzed by a goal? (Even an Iranian's?) Call
it as if it were no more of an event than a corner kick? The best
sportscasters raise their voices, step by step, as they describe
critical action or anticipate a score. Cantor is glorious fun not
only for his ``Gooooaaaalllll!'' call but for his touch-by-touch
narrative, which grows more invigorated with each pass.
</P>
<P>
   Try to imagine Mike Emrick or Gary Thorne, the pre-eminent
voices of hockey, calling soccer. They have the vocal juice to stay
excited for 90 minutes. Ley may yet show it, but hasn't so far.
Instead of raising his game at the end, he lowered it. ``This is
the final minute,'' he said at the 89th minute, as if he were
describing a funeral cortege.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Ley lacked vocal oomph, Malin lacked analytical brio.
He often leaned on the Americans' hitting the crossbar or the goal
post _ their inability to finish _ as reasons for their failure
Sunday. But those were symptoms of a teamwide problem Malin never
adequately analyzed. What were they doing wrong? What must they do
to correct their faltering offense? Whom should Coach Steve Sampson
send in to right the listing ship? How did the Iranian Mehdi
Mahdavikia get loose for a breakaway to make the score 2-0?
</P>
<P>
   Malin is not taking advantage of better production afforded by
ABC and ESPN and the French world feed. With better visuals, a good
analyst can provide the fruits of a full-field vision a view that
illuminates broad strategies. That didn't happen Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Of even greater concern than their verbal style were Ley and
Malin's apparent leanings. Sure, it's easy to root against Iran,
but that's not for announcers. No, they didn't outwardly cheer.
Maybe they didn't know when they sounded like homers.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ley showed emotion, it appeared more for the United
States. A shot on goal by Claudio Reyna pushed Ley to shout,
``Rey-na!'' He shouted ``Save!'' when Brian McBride almost scored.
When McBride scored, Ley said: ``Is that in? Yes. Is that a goal?
Yes!''
</P>
<P>
   Both announcers seemed a tad too hopeful that Coach Steve
Sampson's underachieving team would not only break their goal-less
string, but turn back the Iranians. They harped on the near goals
as signs that the Americans were playing great, save for the
trajectory of their kicks. But even a casual observer could sense a
great deal of confusion on the United States team. Yet Ley and
Malin seemed to hope more than explicate. When four minutes of
stoppage time were posted after the 90 minutes of regulation ended,
Ley said: ``So there is time? There is time.'' He sounded a little
too relieved.
</P>
<P>
   In a game when well-balanced emotion was absent, ABC offered an
emotional report by Gillian Findlay during the pre-game show on
Iranian star Khodadad Azizi. Her halftime report, on fan reaction
in a Tehran bar to Iran's first goal, was temporarily delayed by
Iranian censors. Eventually, before the second half, it went
through.
</P>
<P>
   AIRWAVES: The U.S.-Iran World Cup game generated an overnight
4.8 Nielsen rating for ABC, down from a 7.8 for the U.S.-Romania
game four years ago in a similar Sunday time slot. ... Lee Janzen's
comeback victory over Payne Stewart in the U.S. Open on NBC
captured a 6.7 overnight rating on Sunday, down 14 percent from a
year ago; Saturday's 5.0 rating fell 23 percent from 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
