u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKERS-TRUST-650&AMP;ADD     06-22 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKERS-TRUST-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKERS TRUST OVERCOMES SCANDALS
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Variety headline might offer this take on the
Bankers Trust Corp.: Banking's Bad Boys Bounce Back.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived a series of financial scandals that tarnished
the vaunted trading house's reputation and tore into its bottom
line in recent years, Bankers Trust is refashioning itself as
investment banker to the nation's _ indeed, the world's _ smaller,
fast-growth companies.
</P>
<P>
   Already, earnings have rebounded. But it remains to be seen
whether this strategy will give the New York bank the heft it needs
to go it alone on Wall Street and avoid becoming takeover bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proponents of the idea that bigger is not necessarily
better,'' said Frank N. Newman, who became the bank's chief
executive nearly three years ago as the company began recovering
from the trading scandals. ``We're trying to find markets where we
can add value.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman said Bankers Trust, currently the country's
seventh-largest bank, had no intention of trying to compete with
larger rivals like Goldman, Sachs, Merrill Lynch, or Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter for the juiciest spoils of Wall Street: stock and bond
underwritings and fees gleaned from mergers-and-acquisition advice
for the biggest corporations in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the bank is focusing its efforts on providing these
services to smaller companies in fields like high technology,
health care, the media and telecommunications, building on its
solid franchise as a junk-bond underwriter. And Bankers Trust also
sees itself as an aggressive competitor in emerging markets like
Asia and in an economically consolidating Europe, where it believes
its expertise in local markets gives it an edge.
</P>
<P>
   To these ends, Newman has led Bankers Trust on an acquisition
spree, scooping up the mergers boutique Wolfensohn in 1996 and the
brokerage firm BT Alex. Brown Inc. last year, to give the bank the
firepower it needs to provide financial advice and stock
underwriting for up-and-coming companies. The bank proudly points
to a $1.3 billion equity offering it co-led in March for Chancellor
Media, a radio broadcasting concern, as evidence of its new-found
underwriting muscle. It also cites recent deals it has done for
Channel Communications, a broadcasting concern, and Fred Meyer
Inc., which operates supermarkets in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts worry that all the expertise that Bankers
Trust has been buying is really just a grab bag of disparate
businesses incapable of steering it through the competitive storms
swirling around Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Alex. Brown appears to be a good fit, sharply bolstering the
bank's revenue and profits from investment banking and immediately
making it a player in the financing of high-tech companies, where
Alex. Brown had built a stellar reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But the $200 million Wolfensohn acquisition is largely viewed on
Wall Street as something of a bust. Bankers Trust was able to boast
about snagging Paul Volcker, the Wolfensohn chairman and former
Federal Reserve chairman, but the purchase has yet to substantially
advance the bank's position in the mergers-and-acquisitions game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bankers Trust still has a long way to go to realize
the value of its franchise,'' said Raphael Soifer, an analyst with
Brown Brothers Harriman. ``If the markets cooperate, we should see
more benefits from their recent acquisitions. If the markets sour,
they could have fairly tough sledding.''
</P>
<P>
   Other problems loom that could weaken Bankers Trust's bottom
line and make it a more tempting takeover target. Relative to its
size, it is among the most exposed of American banks in Asia _ and,
as Asia's economic crisis has deepened recently, the specter of
escalating losses there could become a reality when Bankers Trust
reports second-quarter earnings next month.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust's stock closed Monday at $112.125, well below its
52-week high of $136.3125.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Bankers Trust may be shrewd in trying to position itself
as the premier financier to growth companies, it will ultimately
have to contend with bigger investment banks that will move in for
a piece of the action if it proves to be profitable enough. The big
houses have already started to threaten Bankers Trust in junk
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never immune to competition,'' said Yves C. de Balmann,
Bankers Trust co-head of investment banking. ``In the target
markets in which we have decided to play we are all things to those
people because we are not trying to be all things to all people.
And in our target markets I will compete head-on with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Bankers Trust's future, it is clearly a different
company than it was just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust has always been one of the most innovative banks
in the country, and by the early 1990s, it had earned a reputation
as one of the ablest purveyors of complex financial products known
as derivatives. The bulk of the company's profits came from
derivatives trading, but unseemly sales tactics and the widespread
perception that the bank was ruthless and predatory caused Bankers
Trust to run afoul of clients, regulators and investors. That paved
the way for the arrival of Newman, a former Treasury Department
official and BankAmerica executive, whose reputation for
circumspection helped sanitize Bankers Trust's image.
</P>
<P>
   Newman has sharply curtailed the bank's trading as he has
expanded the investment-banking business. That has touched off a
certain amount of upheaval and staff departures at the bank, as
many on the trading desks have felt slighted. Newman acknowledged
the turmoil, but said the changes were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Trading ``was a terrific business, but the ratios were wrong and
we had to be a more balanced company,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, at the height of its derivatives prowess, Bankers Trust
earned $1.1 billion, about 70 percent of which came from trading
and sales. Profits plunged to $686 million in 1994 and $311 million
in 1995 as the derivatives scandals and trading losses took their
toll. But net income recovered sharply in 1996 and rose to $866
million last year, with trading and sales accounting for only 22
percent of that pile. Investment banking kicked in 70 percent of
the profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Newman, this company has done a lot to become more
focused and better managed,'' said David Berry, an analyst with
Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods. ``On the other hand, they're not earning
the kinds of returns they did before the derivatives debacle. But
analysts and investors were never really comfortable with the risks
they took in those days either.''
</P>
<P>
   But Berry, like many other Bankers Trust observers, is waiting
to pass final judgment on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Bankers Trust really have a long-term strategy?'' Berry
asked. ``Do they have something in place that will vault them into
the 21st century? I'm not sure yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
