<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-22 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING THE WILD WEST _ AS WELL AS THE NOT-SO-WILD REST OF THE
COUNTRY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When executives of a Kentucky restaurant chain wanted
desert scenery and armadillos for a commercial, they knew where to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, said Lynn Birdwell, co-founder of Rio Bravo
Pictures, the Houston production company that filmed the spot for
the chain, Texas Roadhouse of Louisville, Texas doesn't have any
trained armadillos. State law forbids selling the critters or
keeping them for sale except for limited purposes. So two had to be
flown in from Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sometimes arduous task of appearing Texan enough to
suit outsiders, the Lone Star State's commercial production
companies report a growing business. The industry was jump-started
in the 1980s by the television series ``Dallas,'' as locals gained
experience on the set and some out-of-state professionals chose to
remain in Texas, said Jeff Klein, executive director of the Texas
Association of Film/Tape Professionals, a nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   The state now ranks third _ or perhaps fourth _ in the amount of
money spent there to make TV commercials, he said. California is
first, with New York a distant second. Illinois, primarily Chicago,
would be the most likely rival of Texas for No. 3, according to
Klein.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the University of Dallas' Graduate School of
Management estimated that 678 commercials were shot in 1997 in
Dallas and Houston alone.
</P>
<P>
   While Houston and, especially, Dallas are the focal points of
the industry, production companies have also sprouted in Amarillo,
Austin, Corpus Christi, and El Paso, Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Copeland, director of the Texas Film
Commission, about $80 million a year is spent across the state
making TV spots.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is an obvious choice for beer commercials, given the
populace's drinking preferences. But commercials are produced here
for other reasons as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many varied looks in Texas,'' Copeland said, from
coastline and mountains to deserts and piney woods. Also, he said,
``the weather is probably going to be good,'' with lots of
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the mystique of the Old West, Copeland added,
despite the imported armadillos.
</P>
<P>
   Tammie Edwards, co-founder of the Dallas production company
Bednarz Film, gave another reason. ``It's easy to shoot here''
compared with cities like New York and Los Angeles, she said,
because of less ``red tape'' in obtaining permits and other such
details.
</P>
<P>
   Wages and other costs are lower, Ms. Edwards said. ``They're
looking at $200-a-day for a hotel in New York, whereas in Dallas,
it's $75 to $100,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Costs can also be kept down, Klein said, because the state has
no income tax and does not levy a sales tax on film or equipment
rental.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, said Adolfo Aguilar Jr., president of one of
the nation's top Hispanic ad agencies, there is a growing market
for commercials aimed at Spanish-speaking consumers, who have a
large presence in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar said that his San Antonio agency, Bromley, Aguilar &AMP;
Associates, part of the D'arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles unit of
MacManus Group, often uses local production companies to make their
Spanish-language spots.
</P>
<P>
   While production crews can, of course, be imported to film in
Texas, there are now enough talented locals to do the work, those
in the state's industry say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually easier to find someone who's already in Texas
rather than bringing in the whole show,'' said Rodrigo Rodriguez,
the other co-founder of Rio Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Texas production companies now compete nationally and
film spots elsewhere. Of the 26 spots Bednarz Film made last year,
Ms. Edwards said, 10 were set outside Texas. And Bednarz staff
members went to New York this year to shoot an American Airlines ad
featuring the city's bridges, part of a campaign created for the
New York market.
</P>
<P>
   Texas companies have produced commercials for Sports Illustrated
and McDonald's, Klein said. A recent Sprint commercial was also a
Texas creation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas companies sticking close to home are also doing well. Pony
Pictures of Lubbock, which produces mostly regional commercials,
saw its revenues double last year, said Dwight Harper, its owner.
</P>
<P>
   While some advertisers like the Texas look, Harper added, others
come to the state because it can look like somewhere else. He
recalled, for example, going to the mountains of West Texas
recently to shoot a commercial for a Mexican restaurant whose
owners ``wanted it to look like interior Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
