<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS, WITHOUT DRAFT PICKS, HAVE OTHER PRIORITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Amid all the projections, evaluations, misinformation,
disinformation and speculation, only one thing is sure about the
NBA draft on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It has undergone a fundamental change in the way teams use it.
</P>
<P>
   And don't use it.
</P>
<P>
   Some general managers and scouts say it is overrated. Of course,
not one of them had a chance last year to pick Tim Duncan, who
restored the San Antonio Spurs' faith in at least one draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan, last year's No. 1 pick and subsequent Rookie of the
Year, appears to be the exception in a process that has slipped
from fundamental building block to something else. Overrated might
be an overstatement. But NBA teams clearly are not in a rush to
acquire picks that were so valued a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   An example: the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns do not have a pick in either of the two rounds. They
have some interest in trading for one in the mid- to late first
round, when two European big men, 7-foot-1 Radoslav Nesterovic and
6-11 Vladimir Stepania, might be available. But nobody within the
walls of the team's executive offices will cry if they don't
acquire a pick.
</P>
<P>
   They have other priorities, free agency being the biggest. It
also could be the most immediate if stalled talks for a new
collective bargaining agreement are resolved before July 1, when
free-agent shoppers would get the green light. Trades are the other
priority. A draft pick often is the prelude to a deal that day or a
trade later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can build through free agency and/or trade, typically
it is a better route,'' said Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo,
who has to decide whether the investment in a draft pick is worth
the salary-cap money that would be subtracted from the Suns' pool
to attract free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get there quicker with a trade or free agent because
you know what you are acquiring. You're dealing with a proven
commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   With draft picks, there is the uncertainty of how a player will
fit into your system and how well he will perform in the NBA,
Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most draft picks are a product of their colleges. Those
college systems might hold back one player and, in some cases,
accentuate positives that overvalue another player. It's always
more of a sure thing to look at a proven commodity through a trade
or a free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nash is proof-positive that the Suns' philosophy is shared
leaguewide. Colangelo said he was swamped Monday by calls from
teams interested in the playmaker, the subject of widespread rumors
in February near the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Nash's two years of NBA experience and his probable role next
season as Jason Kidd's backup are a powerful lure for teams seeking
a playmaker. A team would know what kind of player it is getting in
Nash, who was picked No. 15 in 1996 and was the only Suns draft
pick still on the roster at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   The same certainty cannot be applied to 20-year-old Mike Bibby,
the possible No. 1 pick from the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Colangelo does not dismiss the draft's potential
value. Depending on each team's makeup, a pick could provide
immediate help. In fact, NBA super scout Marty Blake argues that
Duncan had an immediate impact on the Spurs because veteran center
David Robinson already was in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no impact players anymore,'' Blake said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A young team might be better served by building through the
draft, Colangelo said. He cited three-year-old Vancouver, which has
drafted Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves, Shareef Abdur-Rahim and
Antonio Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is at the other end of the spectrum. The aging Rockets
need youth, which they might try to acquire with three first-round
picks, Nos. 14, 16 and 18.
</P>
<P>
   But in each case, the key is patience, which is rare in today's
win-now-or-else NBA. Big money for young players _ some right out
of high school _ is another factor. Under the current collective
bargaining rules, a team might have a player for only two seasons
after it drafts and signs him. Then, he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   An example is Antonio McDyess, who was picked No. 2 in 1996 by
the Clippers and traded to Denver. Last, summer the Nuggets traded
McDyess to Phoenix in a three-way deal with Cleveland that included
the Suns' first-round pick (No. 23) in Wednesday's draft. The
Nuggets feared that they would lose McDyess with nothing in return
this summer in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's up to the Suns to re-sign McDyess. It's a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   But the Suns watched McDyess begin to develop. About him, they
know a lot. About the draft, they know enough to realize that they
have the same chances as a guy walking into a bingo parlor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
