<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' PRO TECTED LIST PRO DUCES FEW SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes excluded goalie Jimmy Waite and defenseman
Murray Baron from their protected list for Friday's NHL expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven players in all were left unprotected, with few
surprises other than Waite, who played well in the absence of
starting goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, and Baron, a top defenseman who
will become an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable Coyotes who were exposed, according to lists
obtained Monday, include left wing Darrin Shannon, left wing Louie
DeBrusk, acquired two weeks ago from Tampa Bay in the Craig Janney
trade, and 700-goal scorer Mike Gartner, 38, whose contract is set
to expire and who wasn't going to be invited back anyway.
</P>
<P>
   NHL rules stipulate that the Coyotes will lose only one player
to the Nashville Predators in Friday's expansion draft in Buffalo,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Also unprotected are: forwards Jocelyn Lemieux, Tavis Hansen,
Darin Kimble, Rob Murray and Scott Levins; defensemen Jim Johnson,
Norm Maciver, Michel Petit and John Slaney; and goalies Scott
Langkow and Darcy Wakaluk, who announced his retirement toward the
end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Across the NHL, several big names were left unprotected,
including goalies Mike Richter (Rangers), Curtis Joseph (Edmonton),
John Vanbiesbrouck (Florida) and Sean Burke (Philadelphia), in
addition to skaters Brett Hull (St. Louis), Ray Ferraro (Los
Angeles), Wendel Clark (Toronto), Dale Hunter (Washington) and Tony
Granato and Marty McSorley (San Jose).
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Baron unprotected by the Coyotes comes as a bit of a
surprise. He was a top-four defenseman for much of his time here
after being acquired from Montreal in the Dave Manson trade. But
Baron is asking for more money than the Coyotes are interested in
paying the veteran, and he likely will sign elsewhere, regardless
of what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville will pick one player from each of the 26 existing
clubs and can draft up to five goalies, one of whom might be Waite,
who was strong through Khabibulin's injury last season.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin was the only goalie the Coyotes protected, and most
other teams in the league also only protected one goalie. Phoenix
protected nine forwards and six defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the forwards are right wingers, three others are
centers.
</P>
<P>
   The lone left winger protected was captain Keith Tkachuk. The
rest of the protected list includes centers Bob Corkum, Jeremy
Roenick and Cliff Ronning, right wingers Rick Tocchet, Jim Cummins,
Shane Doan and Dallas Drake and J.F. Jomphe, obtained last week
from Anaheim for Jim McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   The defensemen protected are veterans Teppo Numminen, Keith
Carney, Gerald Diduck and youngsters Oleg Tverdovsky and Deron
Quint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
