<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS FROM THE WORLD OF ADVERTISING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Barnes &AMP; Noble Account in Review
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. said on Monday that it was searching for an
agency to handle the creative part of its account, which had been
handled for less than a year by Weiss, Whitten, Stagliano in New
York. Billings were estimated at $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our needs have changed,'' said Mary Ellen Keating, a
spokeswoman for Barnes &AMP; Noble in New York, confirming reports of a
review this week in Advertising Age and Adweek.
</P>
<P>
   The company has invited eight agencies in New York to compete
for the creative account, Ms. Keating said, though she declined to
identify them. Among the possible contenders listed by Adweek were
Deutsch Inc. and Margeotes/Fertitta &AMP; Partners. The review will be
narrowed in mid-July to two to three finalists, she said, with a
decision by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Stagliano, president at Weiss, Whitten, said: ``Obviously,
we're disappointed. It was a challenging account, but they seemed
pleased with the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, Whitten recently began running a multimedia campaign that
reintroduces the Barnes &AMP; Noble Web site, which competes against
Amazon.com in selling books on line.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Brewing Sues 2 Former Agencies
</P>
<P>
   The Miller Brewing Company has sued two former agencies, Bates
USA and Zenith Media Services, both of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bussen, a spokesman in Milwaukee for Miller, part of the
Philip Morris Cos., said that the lawsuit, which was filed in
federal district court in Milwaukee, accuses the agencies of
failing to seek television commercial time to compensate for spots
that ran on local stations in 1995 and 1996 and fell short of
reaching ratings goals. The lawsuit is seeking $6.9 million,
reflecting the estimated value of the free spots to make up for the
shortfalls, known as make-goods.
</P>
<P>
   The suit by Miller, the nation's second-largest brewer, is
seeking an additional $937,997 from Bates, accusing the agency of
``double billing'' Miller for services.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Torello, a spokeswoman for Bates USA, said: ``We haven't
had an opportunity to look at the complaint. But from what we
understand, we feel it is without merit.'' Rich Hamilton, chief
executive of United States operations of Zenith Media, said: ``This
action is utterly without merit. It relates to alleged guarantees
in local television, which were not made.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates is owned by Cordiant Communications Group PLC and Zenith
is a joint venture of Cordiant and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ESC Medical Systems Names 5 Finalists
</P>
<P>
   ESC Medical Systems Ltd. in Needham, Mass., has named five
finalists to compete for a new consumer account with estimated
first-year billings of $12 million, which could grow eventually to
as much as $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Krinsky, a partner at Advice and Advisors in New York,
which was hired to help manage the review, identified the finalists
as Quantum Group in Parsippany, N.J., and four agencies in New
York: Gotham Inc., part of the Interpublic Group of Companies;
Jordan, McGrath, Case &AMP; Partners; Publicis, part of Publicis SA,
and Warwick Baker O'Neill. A decision is expected in mid-July. ESC
makes and markets devices like the Epilight hair remover that use
pulsed-light technology.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   -- Mass Transit Administration, Baltimore, to the Reeves Agency,
Baltimore, to handle its account, which had been handled by Gray
Kirk/Van Sant, Baltimore. Billings were estimated at $3 million for
a four-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   People
</P>
<P>
   -- Melissa Pordy was named senior vice president and print
services director at Zenith Media Services, a joint venture of
Cordiant Communications Group PLC and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC,
succeeding Amy Andrews, who left. Ms. Pordy had been vice president
and associate media director at Hill, Holliday/Altschiller, New
York, part of the Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
