u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-ARGENTINA-DEFRAU     06-22 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-ARGENTINA-DEFRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUILTY PLEA TO DEFRAUDING ARGENTINA; BANKER'S FAKERY GOT BONUSES
FOR EXPORTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A director of an Argentine bank admitted on
Monday that he had forged financial documents to cover up a scheme
to defraud the government of Argentina of as much as $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty to a single count of conspiracy to violate
the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act, the director, Luis E. Machado, 41,
explained how he had helped inflate sales figures for copper and
other metals exported to the United States. The scheme took
advantage of an Argentine government program to promote
manufacturing exports by rewarding companies with cash bonuses and
tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The case was prosecuted in New Jersey because many of the
fraudulent sales were made to a dummy company in Holmdel, N.J.,
called Molds, Dies, and Novelties, which prosecutors said had been
set up specifically to handle shipments of relatively worthless
copper medallions and steel dies. Other fake sales were made
through Weekend Novelties, a company in Newtown, Pa., and
Intergold, a company in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the case was unusual because its strategy was
the reverse of most customs fraud schemes, in which the
conspirators seek to play down sales numbers so that they are
charged less in duty taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Machado, a Uruguayan citizen who worked for a Buenos Aires bank,
Banco Baires, testified in federal district court in Camden that he
had carried out the conspiracy with Enrique Piana, an Argentine
citizen and metals exporter. Piana pleaded guilty last August in
federal district court in Camden to bank fraud. According to their
pleas, Machado and Piana faked more than $130 million in sales of
copper and other metals.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the falsified sales figures, Piana collected as
much as $20 million in bonuses known as export rebates from the
Argentine government. The program, intended to increase
international trade, paid companies 12.5 percent rebates on metals
sales to the United States. In court on Monday, Machado admitted
faking bank documents to make Piana's sales appear legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to enriching the conspirators, the scheme also
skewed U.S. data on trade with Argentina, said Noel L. Hillman and
Colleen C. Piccone, the prosecutors who handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before Judge Joseph E. Irenas, Machado testified on
Monday that he had been assisted in falsifying bank documents by
unidentified officers of MTB Bank, a New York City bank that has
had a business relationship with Banco Baires for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Machado said that he had used MTB accounts set up under fake
names to conduct money transfers that seemed to legitimize the
sales in metals. Paperwork from the fake transactions was then used
by Piana, the president of Casa Piana, an exporting company, to
request the export rebates from the Argentine government.
</P>
<P>
   Machado also testified that the accounts, in the names of Paul
Sharpe and Tom Stewart, had been established years ago and that
prior to the export scheme they had been used to help people in
Argentina conduct clandestine overseas bank transactions. The
government of Argentina had been investigating Piana even before he
was arrested in the United States and is now seeking to have him
extradited.
</P>
<P>
   Faith S. Hochberg, the U.S. attorney for New Jersey, praised the
prosecutors, customs inspectors and Internal Revenue Service agents
who had uncovered ``a scheme as complex as this and revealed the
international intrigue and conspiracy that resulted in looting the
Argentine treasury of tens of millions of dollars.'' She added:
``It took an alert customs inspector to suspect an overvaluation of
goods to start this entire investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   When Machado is sentenced by Irenas on Sept. 18, he will face a
maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
