<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUPCOL-COLUMN-LAD     06-22 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUPCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY STEP FORWARD, GIANT LEAP BACKWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Call it a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson won't, and neither will his players, but no matter
how much they protest otherwise, the United States' failure in this
World Cup is a setback.
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with not reaching the second round; the
Americans never were expected to get that far. To be eliminated
after their second game, with a devastating loss that one U.S.
Soccer official ranked as the worst in their history, is another
matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampson, the U.S. coach, handled Sunday's 2-1 defeat to Iran
with a sense of pride. He was pleased, he repeated, with how his
team conducted itself, how it approached the match and how it
controlled play for much of the way.
</P>
<P>
   And with one Group F game to go _ here Thursday against
Yugoslavia _ he declared this World Cup a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here with the goal of demonstrating that we have grown
as a soccer-playing nation,'' Sampson said. ``I believe we have
accomplished that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some debate as to that, but other questions need to be
asked. Was that the proper goal for this cup? Was demonstrating to
the world that we can play their sport more important than
suggesting to Americans _ whose level of sophistication is such
that the many of the subtleties were bound to be lost _ that we can
win? Should a higher priority have been assigned to results?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely disappointing for the fans and the general
public,'' defender Alexi Lalas said. ``In the past four years there
has been an increased awareness of this team, and with that comes
expectations to succeed at a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   A win over Iran might have been success enough in this cup. Not
providing casual and non-fans something to grasp, like a win over
Iran, has damaged soccer's standing in the United States. That's
not good news for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, aside from those horrendous first 45 minutes
in the 2-0 loss to Germany in the opener, the Americans have not
performed that poorly. They applied a good 20 or 25 minutes of
pressure against a German team that is good enough to win this
tournament, and they were unlucky not to beat the Iranians after
hitting the posts and crossbar three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half against Germany was not a good half,'' Sampson
acknowledged. ``Three of the four halves, I believe, achieved our
goal of showing we've grown as a soccer-playing nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's true, or whether that's enough, is debatable. Not
all of Sampson's players agree with him, although few will say so
publicly. Not everybody, though, was willing to spout the company
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sad, disappointed,'' said midfielder Joe-Max Moore.
``I'm not sure what positives there are at this point. We work our
whole lives to get here ... and we just didn't do what we were
supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A good deal of the blame should go to Sampson. Regardless of how
one feels about his actions leading to the cup _ the John Harkes
decision, the change of defensive personnel, the reliance on a
formation that was adequately tested just once _ there seemed an
element of desperation in the way he dumped the 3-6-1 alignment
after the loss to Germany. And he made questionable changes in
personnel, switching five starters before the Iran game and failing
to insert Eric Wynalda, the Americans' all-time scoring leader,
when a goal was an absolute necessity.
</P>
<P>
   If Sampson's three-year tenure as head coach has been solid,
there's plenty evidence that he failed during this World Cup. It
might cost him his job _ anywhere else it would _ but U.S. soccer
isn't so predictable.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's game, Sampson was asked if, given the quick
elimination, this had been a disastrous cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, of course not,'' he replied. ``It would have been
disastrous if we didn't play well. You the media now have to decide
whether the quality of soccer that's been demonstrated the last two
games demonstrates we've improved or not. That's in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve, I don't think you want to go there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
