<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-MIDLAND-600-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH TO BUY CANADIAN BROKERAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch has agreed to buy Canada's last major
independent brokerage firm, continuing an international acquisition
spree that has given Merrill commanding positions in markets from
Thailand to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill will pay $1.26 billion (Canadian), or $855 million
(United States), in stock for Midland Walwyn. The deal marks
Merrill's return to the Canadian market, which it left in 1990
because of regulatory barriers to expanding its business there.
</P>
<P>
   The deal adds another niche in Merrill's growing worldwide
network of retail brokers and fund management firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are doing is putting themselves into very strong
market positions in a variety of promising markets,'' said Raphael
Soifer, a securities industry analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman.
``It comes at a price, but they are betting that they will earn
back that price by putting more product and services through these
new channels.''
</P>
<P>
   By leveraging its rising stock price and its sharply higher
earnings, Merrill has become the most aggressive American broker
abroad. It bought Smith New Court and Mercury Asset Management,
making it a dominant broker and fund manager in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It has hired 2,000 employees of Yamaichi Securities, the failed
Japanese broker that was once that country's fourth largest. It
also snapped up Phatra Thanakit, a leading Thai broker, at a
fraction of the price that the company would have commanded a year
ago, before Asian markets plunged. Merrill has also made
acquisitions in Australia and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition streak is not over. Merrill has its sights set
on an American financial company that specializes in advising
medium-sized American companies that are not yet ready to make
public offerings, said Jerry Kenney, Merrill's executive vice
president for corporate strategy and research. He declined to name
the target company. But he said the purchase would help Merrill
compete for initial public offerings business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be a financial provider to growing companies while
they are still private, so they might naturally turn to us when
they are ready'' to offer shares to the public, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill sold its Canadian retail unit in 1990 to CIBC Wood Gundy
Securities, a Canadian investment bank. But the rising United
States dollar _ in contrast to the Canadian dollar, which has
fallen to a historic low _ combined with Merrill's high stock price
made this a prime time to re-enter the Canadian market, Merrill
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Canada has recently relaxed rules that prohibited
links between banks and brokerage houses, leading to a scramble
among Canadian banks to buy leading brokerage companies there.
</P>
<P>
   The Canada purchase was further enhanced because government
authorities now allow Canadian pension funds to invest up to 20
percent of their assets abroad. Because the Merrill-Midland
combination is the only such foreign tie-up in Canada, officials of
both companies said the new entity, to be named Merrill Lynch
Canada, would have an upper hand in managing Canada's rapidly
growing pension fund assets.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, 0.24 Merrill share will be
exchanged for each Midland Walwyn share, valuing the Canadian firm
at $31.89 (Canadian) _ 17 percent higher than Midland's closing
price on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill told analysts that the purchase was equivalent to 21
times Midland's book value, considered an expensive price, said
Soifer of Brown Brothers Harriman. But Soifer said the new entity,
which can offer Merrill's broad financial product line in Canada's
less developed market, could expand its earnings faster than
Midland could alone, justifying the price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
