<SLUG> BC-PERU-U.S.-PRISONER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU'S PRIME MINISTER URGES PARDON FOR U.S. WOMAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ The new prime minister of Peru has startled U.S.
officials by publicly saying that Lori Helene Berenson, a New
Yorker jailed for life on charges of terrorism, should be freed
from her cell and expelled.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States said the new prime minister, Javier Valle
Riestra, might be speaking just for himself, and not for the
government. In a television interview on Sunday night, Valle
Riestra expressed disagreement with Ms. Berenson's trial in 1996 by
a secret military court that he characterized as repressive.
</P>
<P>
   His comments represented a sharp break from previous government
statements on the case. Ms. Berenson, 28, a former resident of New
York City, was found guilty of treason for helping stage an assault
on the Peruvian Congress by the Tupac Amaru revolutionary movement
in an effort to take hostages who could be exchanged for jailed
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Ms. Berenson and several rebels apparently
thwarted the planned attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite her crime,'' Valle Riestra said, ``for reasons of
state and for the sake of Peru's prestige, she should be pardoned,
because of the mistakes made in classifying the crime and because
of the repressive legislation dealing with this type of offense.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said the remarks ``came as a
considerable surprise to us.'' The official, who insisted on
anonymity, said Ambassador Dennis Jett pressed the prime minister
on Friday to look into the case and consider her release.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case remains a serious irritant in our relations with
Peru,'' said the official, because her trial did not follow the
norms of due process under international law. The cross-examination
of witnesses was not allowed, and the judges were anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berenson remains in a tiny cell high in the Andes in a
prison filled with convicted terrorists. Because of the constant
cold, U.S. officials have reported that she appears to be
developing circulatory problems. American consular officials are
allowed to visit her occasionally and take blankets and clean
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Senior consular officials on Monday pressed senior Peruvian
officials to free Ms. Berenson, but no other Peruvian official has
publicly reiterated the prime minister's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office three weeks ago, Valle Riestra, a
constitutional lawyer, has made several surprising remarks,
including one opposing President Alberto Fujimori's re-election in
2000. Valle Riestra's appointment as prime minister, effectively
coordinator of the Cabinet, was a surprise, because Valle Riestra
has long been a political opponent of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear what the prime minister's comments mean,'' the
State Department official said. ``His power remains to be tested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
