</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS STATE THEIR POINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers have decided whom to
pick, now the only question is whether they will keep the pick.
</P>
<P>
   With the No.1 selection in Wednesday's NBA draft, the Clippers
are a popular team, as clubs attempt to find out what it will take
to wrest the top pick away from L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot of calls,'' said Elgin Baylor, the Clippers
vice president of basketball operations. ``Thursday and Friday has
been the busiest time. I got a lot of calls (Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Vancouver is getting even more offers for the No.2
pick, since the Grizzlies are actively shopping their draft choice.
With the draft lacking a franchise player, the offers aren't as
attractive this year, but Baylor said he expects to hear from teams
up until the Clippers make their selection.
</P>
<P>
   There have been rumors involving Orlando's Penny Hardaway and
San Antonio's David Robinson, but Baylor denied that those players
were offered to the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, until something attractive comes out, we plan
to keep the pick,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Whom will the Clippers pick? ``We know who we're going to
pick,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though the team will select Arizona guard Mike
Bibby, given its need for a point guard and his expressed desire to
play for the Clippers, a point not to be underestimated for this
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby refused to work out for any team but the Clippers, and his
agent, David Falk, has tried to do everything possible to make sure
his client is perceived as the top player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   But late signals indicate that the Clippers may instead select
Pacific center Michael Olowokandi, and upset everybody's mock
drafts by grabbing the 7-foot-1 English import.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi was summoned to Los Angeles over the weekend for his
second workout with the Clippers, proof that he is indeed getting a
serious look. If the the Clippers listen to Vancouver general
manager Stu Jackson, they would select Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have to (take him),'' Jackson said. ``Can you let
that go by?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sorta an interesting young man,'' Baylor said. ``A
tremendous young man.''
</P>
<P>
   If you just based it on private workouts, Kansas swingman Paul
Pierce might have been the best player the Clippers saw in the past
few weeks. The reason there remains some mystery at No.1, however
slight, is because this draft lacks a Tim Duncan or even a Keith
Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can say anyone is going to be an impact
(player),'' said Ryan Blake, who scouts and identifies college
players for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bibby, who would probably start for the Clippers next
season, has some drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are asking whether he's going to be an impact
(player) in the draft,'' Blake said. ``He's been shut down a couple
of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake also worries that Bibby is more of a shooting point guard
than playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he going to be able to do that?'' Blake said. ``Will he
make L.A. or Vancouver a different team?''
</P>
<P>
   Local basketball fans will recall that Bibby was outplayed twice
this season by USC's Gary Johnson and burned repeatedly by Utah's
Andre Miller in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby has many more positives, however, and Baylor said if the
Clippers trade the pick, ``You better get an all-star player. If
it's a point guard, fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers also have to decide whom to select with the 22nd
pick, which they acquired from Miami in the Brent Barry-Isaac
Austin trade.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said nearly 20 players were brought in for workouts,
including UCLA's Jelani McCoy, Oregon State guard Corey Benjamin,
Michigan forward Robert Traylor, Ball State guard Bonzi Wells,
Cincinnati guard Ruben Patterson and Minnesota guard Sam Jacobson.
</P>
<P>
   No one would be surprised if the Clippers took somebody they
didn't work out. Baylor attended the pre-draft camp in Chicago two
weeks ago, and among those Baylor watched was Purdue center Brad
Miller (6-11, 250), who might be slow but would provide depth in
the post.
</P>
<P>
   If he's still around, the Clippers would also have to consider
Valparaiso guard Bryce Drew, who was probably the most impressive
player in Chicago. Another player worth keeping an eye on is 7-foot
center Radoslav Nesterovic of Slovenia, who has been playing in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Although they didn't work out UCLA forward J.R. Henderson, there
has also been speculation the Clippers might keep him in L.A.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
